/* Glossary tooltip descriptions, keyed by Wikipedia article slug (decoded). Add terms one at a time with
   `node .claude/add-glossary.js <entry.json>` (see CLAUDE.md). Missing terms fall back to the slug name. */
window.GLOSSARY = {
"Sima_Qian": "The Han historian (c. 145–86 BCE) regarded as the father of Chinese historiography. His Records of the Grand Historian set the form for the official histories of every later dynasty. He famously chose mutilation over death in order to finish his work.",
"Protohistory": "The transitional stage between prehistory and written history. It covers a culture that has not yet developed writing of its own, or whose own writing survives only in fragmentary or undeciphered form, but which appears in the records of contemporary literate neighbours. Because it is defined by this relationship to literacy rather than by absolute dates, protohistory falls at different times in different parts of the world.",
"Fuxi": "In Chinese mythology a legendary culture hero and primordial founder of civilization, counted among the Three Sovereigns and traditionally regarded as a divine, miraculously born first emperor. He is credited above all with devising the eight trigrams (bagua) that underlie the I Ching, and with teaching his people to fish and hunt with nets, to keep domesticated animals, and to observe the institution of marriage. He is paired with Nüwa as sister and consort, the two shown in early Chinese art as an entwined couple with human upper bodies and serpentine tails.",
"Nüwa": "In Chinese mythology, the mother goddess and creator of humankind, counted in some traditions among the Three Sovereigns. She is said to have molded the first humans from yellow clay and to have repaired the collapsed heavens by smelting five-coloured stones, propping up the fallen sky with the severed legs of a great turtle. Traditionally paired with Fuxi as his sister and consort, the two are depicted with intertwined serpent bodies.",
"Sanwu_Liji": "The Sanwu Liji (三五歷紀, \"Three Five Historic Records\") is a lost Chinese text written by Xu Zheng of the state of Eastern Wu during the Three Kingdoms period. It contains the earliest surviving written account of the Pangu creation myth, in which the cosmos begins as a cosmic egg and Pangu separates heaven from earth. The work survives only in fragments quoted by later encyclopedias such as the Taiping Yulan and Yiwen Leiju.",
"Eastern_Wu": "Eastern Wu, also called Sun Wu or simply Wu, was one of the three states of the Three Kingdoms period, founded by Sun Quan in the lower Yangtze region of the southeast. Sun Quan declared independence from Cao Wei as King of Wu in 222 and proclaimed himself emperor in 229, ruling the Sun-clan state from its principal capital at Jianye (modern Nanjing) as the rival of Cao Wei and Shu Han. It was the last of the three states to fall, conquered by the Jin dynasty in 280, which ended the Three Kingdoms period.",
"Daoist": "Daoism or <b>Taoism</b>&nbsp;is a Chinese philosophical and religious tradition centred on the Dao, the Way, understood as the spontaneous source and underlying pattern of all things. It teaches living in harmony with the Dao through wu wei (effortless, non-coercive action) and naturalness, ideals expressed in its foundational text the Daodejing, traditionally attributed to Laozi. The tradition is often distinguished into a philosophical strand (daojia) and an organized religion (daojiao) with deities, ritual, and the pursuit of immortality, though scholars increasingly question this binary.",
"Pangu": "In Chinese mythology, Pangu is a primordial being and creator figure said to have emerged from a cosmic egg of swirling chaos, the first living thing to take shape. As the myth tells it, he separated the egg into earth and heaven, the murky yin sinking below and the clear yang rising above, and held the two apart as he grew for some 18,000 years. After his death his body is said to have become the features of the world, his breath the wind and clouds, his eyes the Sun and Moon, and his blood the rivers, a transformation related in the 3rd-century Wuyun Linian Ji attributed to Xu Zheng.",
"Xu_Zheng_(Eastern_Wu)": "Xu Zheng was a 3rd-century scholar-official and writer of the state of Eastern Wu during the Three Kingdoms period, sometimes characterized as a Daoist author. His Sanwu Liji and Wuyun Linian Ji together give the earliest surviving written account of the Pangu creation myth, the former relating the cosmic egg and the parting of heaven and earth, the latter the transformation of Pangu's dying body into the features of the world. Little is reliably known of his life, and both works are lost, surviving only as fragments quoted in later encyclopedias.",
"Wuyun_Linian_Ji": "The Wuyun Linian Ji (五運歷年紀, \"Chronicle of the Five Cycles of Time\") is a lost Chinese text attributed to Xu Zheng of the state of Eastern Wu during the Three Kingdoms period. A companion to Xu Zheng's Sanwu Liji, it recounts the death of Pangu and the transformation of his body into the world, his breath becoming the wind and clouds, his eyes the Sun and Moon, and his blood the rivers. The work survives only in fragments quoted by much later compilations, above all Ma Su's seventeenth-century Yishi.",
"Three_Kingdoms": "The Three Kingdoms was the period when China was divided among three rival states — Cao Wei in the north, Shu Han in the southwest, and Eastern Wu in the southeast — following the disintegration of the Eastern Han dynasty. It is conventionally dated 220–280 CE, beginning when Cao Pi forced the abdication of the last Han emperor and ending when the Jin dynasty conquered Eastern Wu, though some scholars trace its origins to the warlord struggles of the late second century. One of the most destructive eras in Chinese history, it closed when the Sima clan's Jin dynasty, having already absorbed Wei, reunified the realm, and it was later immortalized in the fourteenth-century novel Romance of the Three Kingdoms.",
"Qilin": "An auspicious, benevolent mythical creature of Chinese mythology, sometimes loosely called the Chinese unicorn. It is a chimerical composite, variously described with a deer-, ox-, horse-, or goat-like body, scales or flame-wreathed flanks, cloven hooves, and one or two horns, and is traditionally held to be so gentle that it harms nothing and treads without crushing grass or insects. Its rare appearance is read as a good omen heralding a sage or benevolent ruler and an era of peace, and it is counted among the Four Benevolent Animals alongside the dragon, phoenix, and tortoise.",
"Sun_Quan": "Sun Quan was the founding emperor of Eastern Wu, one of the Three Kingdoms, inheriting his family's lower-Yangtze domain in 200 from his slain elder brother Sun Ce. He allied with Liu Bei to defeat Cao Cao at the Battle of Red Cliffs in 208, securing the south. He took the title King of Wu and declared independence from Wei in 222, proclaimed himself emperor in 229 with his capital at Jianye (modern Nanjing), and ruled until his death in 252, receiving the posthumous title Emperor Da (the Great) of Wu.",
"Ymir": "In Norse mythology, Ymir is the primordial being and ancestor of the giants, the jötnar, said to have formed in the void Ginnungagap where northern ice met southern fire. According to the medieval Eddas, he was nourished by the primeval cow Auðumbla, and the race of giants is said to have sprung from his body. The myth relates that the god Odin and his brothers Vili and Vé slew Ymir and fashioned the world from his remains, his flesh becoming the earth, his blood the seas, his bones the mountains, and his skull the sky.",
"Taiping_Yulan": "The Taiping Yulan (太平御覽, \"Readings of the Taiping Era\") is a vast leishu encyclopedia compiled between 977 and 983 by a team of scholars under Li Fang, on the order of Emperor Taizong of the Song dynasty. It runs to 1,000 chapters arranged in some fifty-five categories, draws on over 2,500 earlier works, and is counted among the Four Great Books of Song. Because many of the texts it quotes are now lost, it is a major source for reconstructing earlier Chinese literature.",
"Yiwen_Leiju": "The Yiwen Leiju (藝文類聚, \"Collection of Literature Arranged by Categories\") is a Tang-dynasty leishu encyclopedia completed in 624 by a team under Ouyang Xun, commissioned by Emperor Gaozu of Tang. Running to 100 chapters across 46 categories, it is distinctive among early leishu for pairing factual excerpts (shi) with literary quotations (wen). It draws on more than 1,400 earlier works, many of them now lost, making it an important source for reconstructing pre-Tang Chinese literature.",
"Dao": "The Dao (道, \"the Way\") is a foundational concept of Chinese philosophy and religion, with the core sense of a road or path and, by extension, the proper course, method, or underlying principle of things. In Daoism it is the ineffable, nameless source and natural order from which all things arise and according to which they unfold, and with which the sage seeks to live in harmony. Though most central to Daoism, the term is shared across Chinese thought, including Confucianism, where it tends to mean the right moral and social way.",
"Prehistory": "Prehistory is the long span of the human past before the invention of writing, known to us only through material remains rather than written records. It stretches from the earliest stone tools made by human ancestors, roughly 3.3 million years ago, to the appearance of the first written documents, and is studied chiefly through archaeology. Because writing emerged at different times around the world, the boundary between prehistory and recorded history falls at different dates in different regions.",
"Yin": "Yin (陰) is one of the two fundamental principles of traditional Chinese cosmology, the dark, passive, and receptive aspect of things. It is associated with the moon, shade, water, cold, earth, night, and the feminine, and takes its name from the shady, north-facing side of a hill. It was understood as a quality present in all things, continually waxing and waning through the cycles of nature.",
"Yang": "Yang (陽) is one of the two fundamental principles of traditional Chinese cosmology, the bright, active, and expansive aspect of things. It is associated with the sun, light, fire, heat, heaven, day, and the masculine, and takes its name from the sunny, south-facing side of a hill. It was understood as a quality present in all things, waxing and waning in a constant rhythm through the cycles of nature.",
"Norse": "Norse refers to the medieval North Germanic peoples of Scandinavia — chiefly of what is now Norway, Sweden, and Denmark — who spoke Old Norse during the Viking Age and early Middle Ages. The Vikings, the seafaring raiders and traders of this culture, were Norsemen, though not every Norseman was a Viking; the term also covers their Old Norse language and their pre-Christian religion and mythology. That mythology, a cosmos of gods, giants, and other beings, survives chiefly through medieval Icelandic sources, above all the Poetic Edda and Snorri Sturluson's Prose Edda.",
"Tiamat": "In Mesopotamian mythology, Tiamat is the primordial goddess of the salt sea, a personification of watery chaos who, with the freshwater Apsu, gave birth to the first generation of gods. The Babylonian epic Enuma Elish tells how she went to war against the younger gods and was slain by the storm god Marduk. Marduk is said to have split her vast body in two, raising one half as the vault of the heavens and setting the other below as the earth.",
"Vedic": "Vedic describes the culture, language, and religion of the Vedic period of ancient India, roughly 1500 to 500 BCE, spanning the late Bronze and early Iron Ages. It takes its name from the Vedas, the oldest Hindu scriptures, composed in Vedic Sanskrit by the Indo-Aryan peoples of the northern subcontinent. The Vedic religion of this era, centred on ritual sacrifice and the hymns of the Vedas, was a principal forerunner of later Hinduism.",
"Purusha": "In Vedic mythology, Purusha is the primordial cosmic being or first Man, whose sacrifice by the gods is recounted in the Purusha Sukta hymn of the Rigveda. From the parts of his dismembered body the ordered world and its creatures were formed, along with the four social classes, the priests arising from his mouth, the warriors from his arms, the commoners from his thighs, and the servants from his feet. In later Hindu philosophy, especially Samkhya, Purusha came to mean the eternal cosmic spirit or pure consciousness, set against prakriti, the realm of matter and nature.",
"Han_dynasty": "The Han dynasty was the second imperial dynasty of China, founded by Liu Bang in 202 BCE after the collapse of the Qin and lasting until 220 CE. Regarded as a formative golden age, it gave its name to the Han Chinese, China's majority ethnic group, and to the Han characters of the Chinese script. Its long rule was split into Western and Eastern Han by the brief Xin interregnum, and it ended when the throne passed to Cao Pi, opening the Three Kingdoms period.",
"Literacy": "Literacy is the ability to read and write, though modern definitions broaden it to the capacity to understand, interpret, and communicate using written materials across many contexts. By extension the word also denotes competence or knowledge in a particular field, as in computer or financial literacy. Because writing is what makes lasting records possible, the spread of literacy marks the threshold between prehistory and recorded history.",
"Mythology": "A mythology is the body of myths belonging to a particular culture, religion, or people, the traditional and often sacred narratives, frequently involving gods and the supernatural, that explain origins and uphold a society's view of the world. The term also names the scholarly study of such narratives. In that academic sense, calling a story a myth implies nothing about whether it is literally true, only that it serves this foundational cultural role.",
"Three_Sovereigns": "The Three Sovereigns are a group of legendary sage-rulers and culture heroes of earliest Chinese tradition, demigods said to have reigned in remote antiquity before the first dynasties. Credited with founding gifts of civilization such as fire, farming, and the family, they precede the Five Emperors in the traditional sequence of mythical rulers. Their membership varies between sources, commonly including Fuxi, Nüwa, and Shennong, and they are regarded today as legendary rather than historical figures.",
"Yangtze": "The Yangtze, known in Chinese as the Chang Jiang or Long River, is the longest river in China and in Asia and the third-longest in the world, running some 6,300 kilometres. It rises on the Tibetan Plateau and flows generally eastward across central and southern China to the East China Sea near Shanghai. Long the principal dividing line between northern and southern China, its valley has been a vital artery of transport, agriculture, and population for millennia.",
"Cao_Wei": "Cao Wei was the most powerful of the three states of the Three Kingdoms period, controlling northern China. It was founded in 220 CE when Cao Pi forced the last Han emperor to abdicate, building on the power amassed by his father, the warlord Cao Cao, and it ruled from the capital at Luoyang. Real authority gradually passed to the Sima clan, who deposed the last Wei ruler in 266 and replaced the state with the Jin dynasty.",
"King_of_Wu": "King of Wu was a Chinese royal title for rulers of the Wu region on the lower Yangtze, originally borne by the kings of the ancient state of Wu, which fell to the state of Yue in 473 BCE. The title was recreated in the Three Kingdoms era, when Sun Quan received it as a vassal of Cao Wei and then, in 222, used it to declare his independence. He reigned as King of Wu until 229, when he proclaimed himself emperor and founded the state of Eastern Wu.",
"Wu_wei": "Wu wei (無為) is a central concept of Daoism, literally non-action or non-doing, better understood as effortless, unforced action in spontaneous accord with the Dao. Rather than striving or interfering against the natural course of things, one accomplishes more by yielding to and flowing with it. The ideal is often applied to the sage or the ruler, who is held to govern best by not meddling in what would unfold of its own accord.",
"Daodejing": "The Daodejing (道德經), also known as the Tao Te Ching, is the foundational text of Daoism and a classic of Chinese philosophy, traditionally attributed to the sage Laozi. Though tradition places it in the 6th century BCE, most scholars date the received text to around the 4th century BCE and regard its authorship as uncertain or composite. A short work of about eighty-one terse chapters, it expounds the Dao and the ideal of wu wei, prizing simplicity, humility, and harmony with the natural order.",
"Laozi": "Laozi, meaning Old Master, is the semi-legendary ancient Chinese sage traditionally regarded as the founder of Daoism and the author of its central text, the Daodejing. Tradition makes him a 6th-century BCE figure and an older contemporary of Confucius, but many modern scholars doubt he existed as a single historical person, treating him as legendary or composite. In later religious Daoism he was venerated as a deity, a personification of the Dao itself.",
"Ma_Su_(historian)": "Ma Su (馬驌) was an early Qing-dynasty scholar and historian, best known for compiling the Yishi, a comprehensive history of Chinese antiquity. Completed in 1670, the work gathers and arranges material from the mythological age down to the fall of the Qin, preserving passages from many earlier texts that are otherwise lost. He also wrote the Zuozhuan Shiwei and is noted for innovations such as the inclusion of maps and charts in a work of history.",
"Yishi": "The Yishi (繹史) is a vast history of Chinese antiquity compiled by the early Qing-dynasty scholar Ma Su and completed in 1670. Arranged in the topical jishi benmo style and running to 160 chapters, it covers the past from the mythological age to the fall of the Qin dynasty. Drawing together quotations from a great many older works, it preserves fragments of texts now otherwise lost, and was innovative in including maps and charts.",
"Confucianism": "Confucianism is a Chinese ethical and philosophical tradition founded on the teachings of Confucius (551–479 BCE), variously regarded as a philosophy, a religion, and a code of social conduct. It stresses moral self-cultivation and virtues such as ren (benevolence) and li (ritual propriety), together with filial piety and right relationships as the basis of social harmony, and holds that rulers should lead by virtuous example. Becoming dominant under the Han dynasty, it served for two millennia as the principal ethical and political framework of imperial China.",
"Sino-Tibetan": "Sino-Tibetan is one of the world's major language families, comprising more than four hundred languages spoken across East, Southeast, and South Asia. It is the second-largest family by number of native speakers, after Indo-European, with on the order of 1.4 billion speakers. By far its largest branch is the Sinitic languages, that is Chinese, while it also includes the Tibeto-Burman languages such as Tibetan and Burmese.",
"Apsu": "In Mesopotamian mythology the personification of the primordial freshwater abyss that lay beneath the earth. He was the consort of the salt-sea goddess Tiamat, and the mingling of their waters is said to have begotten the first generation of gods. When those younger gods grew clamorous and he plotted to destroy them, he was killed in his sleep by the clever god Ea, who built his dwelling upon the slain waters.",
"Auðumbla": "Auðumbla is the primeval cow of Norse mythology, whose name is generally taken to mean hornless cow rich in milk. According to the Prose Edda she emerged in the early world and nourished the first jötunn, Ymir, with four rivers of milk that flowed from her udder. Over three days she is said to have licked the first god, Búri, ancestor of Odin, free from the salty rime of the ice.",
"Cao_Pi": "The son of the warlord Cao Cao and the first emperor of the state of Cao Wei, reigning from 220 to 226. In 220 he forced the last Han emperor, Emperor Xian, to abdicate, ending the Han dynasty and opening the Three Kingdoms period. As ruler he institutionalized the nine-rank system for selecting officials and curtailed the power of imperial princes.",
"Chinese_dragon": "The Chinese dragon, or long (龍), is a benevolent serpentine creature of Chinese mythology and a symbol of power, good fortune, and imperial authority. As a rain deity it rules over rivers, seas, and other moving waters and was traditionally invoked during droughts and floods. An auspicious figure associated with strength and blessing, it appeared in its five-clawed form as an emblem once reserved for the emperor alone.",
"Christian": "A person who follows Christianity, the monotheistic Abrahamic religion centred on the life and teachings of Jesus Christ. The faith arose in first-century Judea and grew to become the largest religious community in the world, divided across many denominations. Its spread into Scandinavia gradually displaced the old Norse pagan religion and brought the Viking Age toward its close.",
"Culture_Hero": "A mythological figure, often a god, ancestor, or animal, credited with bringing humanity the foundations of civilization. Such gifts typically include fire, farming, tools, writing, and law, and the figure is said to have transformed the world through invention or discovery. Culture heroes hold a central place in their people's traditions and frequently disappear or are transformed once their work is done.",
"Denmark": "A Scandinavian country in northern Europe occupying the Jutland Peninsula and an archipelago of more than four hundred islands. It was one of the core homelands of the Norse, and its Danes ranged west to England and south along the coasts of France and Iberia during the Viking Age. The kingdom coalesced in the tenth century under Gorm the Old, whose son Harald Bluetooth converted the Danes to Christianity around 965.",
"Eddas": "The Eddas are two medieval Icelandic works that together form the chief written sources of Norse mythology. The Poetic Edda is a collection of Old Norse poems preserved chiefly in the 13th-century manuscript known as the Codex Regius, while the Prose Edda was composed around 1220 by the Icelandic scholar Snorri Sturluson as a handbook of poetics. Both draw on older oral tradition and preserve the surviving accounts of the Norse gods, cosmology, and heroic legend.",
"Enuma_Elish": "The Babylonian epic of creation, composed in Akkadian and named for its opening words meaning when on high. It recounts how the young god Marduk defeated the primordial sea-goddess Tiamat and built the ordered world from her remains, exalting Babylon and its patron deity above the older gods. Scholars generally place its composition in the later second millennium BCE, often around the reign of Nebuchadnezzar I, though the date remains debated.",
"Four_Benevolent_Animals": "The four benevolent animals (四靈, siling) are the qilin, the dragon, the phoenix or fenghuang, and the tortoise, the four auspicious and numinous creatures of Chinese tradition. They are named together in the Book of Rites as the chiefs of all the beasts, scaled creatures, birds, and shelled creatures. Each was regarded as a bringer of good fortune and a sign of virtuous rule and cosmic harmony.",
"Germanic": "Germanic refers to the Germanic peoples and Germanic languages of northern and central Europe, a grouping first recorded in contact with the Roman world during classical antiquity. The Germanic languages form a branch of the Indo-European family, conventionally divided into North, West, and East Germanic. The Norse belong to the North Germanic branch, whose speech developed into the modern Scandinavian languages.",
"Ginnungagap": "In Norse mythology Ginnungagap, a name often rendered as the yawning void or gaping abyss, is the primordial emptiness that existed before creation. It is said to lie between the frozen realm of Niflheim to the north and the fiery realm of Muspelheim to the south, where meeting ice and heat gave rise to the first being, the jötunn Ymir. From this void the gods are described as shaping the earth, sea, and sky.",
"Hindu": "A follower of Hinduism, the major religious and cultural tradition of the Indian subcontinent, also called Sanatana Dharma. The word derives from Sindhu, the Sanskrit name for the Indus River, and began as a geographic label for peoples living beyond it before acquiring a religious sense. The tradition has no single founder or creed but is bound by shared concepts such as dharma, karma, and moksha and by sacred texts including the Vedas and Upanishads.",
"Icelandic": "Relating to Iceland, the North Atlantic island settled by Norse colonists mainly from western Norway from about the 870s, and to its people and language. The Icelandic language descends from the Old Norse the settlers brought and, through geographic isolation, has changed remarkably little since. Medieval Iceland became the great repository of Norse tradition, preserving the myths and legends in the Eddas and the sagas.",
"Jötnar": "The jötnar (singular jötunn) are a race of beings in Norse mythology, often portrayed as a threat to the gods and frequently in conflict with Thor. The first of them is said to be Ymir, who formed in the void of Ginnungagap and from whose slain body the gods are described as fashioning the world. Though commonly translated as giants, the jötnar are not always large, and the boundary between them and the gods is blurred, since several deities are themselves of jötunn descent.",
"Marduk": "The patron god of the city of Babylon, who rose to become the head of the Mesopotamian pantheon. In the Babylonian creation epic he is said to have slain the chaos-goddess Tiamat in single combat and to have fashioned the ordered cosmos from her divided body. His supremacy over the older gods was enshrined under Nebuchadnezzar I in the late second millennium BCE.",
"Middle_Ages": "The era of European history between classical antiquity and the modern period, running roughly from the fall of the Western Roman Empire to the Renaissance. Historians divide it into the Early, High, and Late Middle Ages, spanning the centuries in which the idea of Europe as a distinct cultural unit took shape. The term itself was coined by later scholars to mark the stretch of time separating their own age from the ancient world.",
"Norsemen": "The medieval North Germanic people of Scandinavia, identified by their common ancestry, culture, and use of the Old Norse language. The seafaring raiders known as Vikings were a subset of them, since most Norsemen were farmers, traders, and settlers who never went raiding. Neighbouring peoples often called them simply Northmen, the name from which the term derives.",
"Norway": "Norway is a Scandinavian country occupying the western and northernmost parts of the Scandinavian Peninsula in northern Europe. It is known for its long, deeply indented coastline of fjords and its mountainous, sparsely populated terrain, with Oslo as its capital. It formed part of the Norse homeland and was a major center of the Viking Age, from which seafarers settled Iceland and reached as far as North America.",
"Odin": "Odin is the chief god of the Norse pantheon, the foremost of the Æsir, associated with war, wisdom, poetry, and the dead. With his brothers Vili and Vé he is said to have slain the primordial being Ymir and shaped the world from his body, and to have given life to the first humans. He is commonly depicted as a one-eyed, long-bearded wanderer who sacrificed an eye for wisdom and is attended by his ravens and wolves.",
"Old_Norse": "The North Germanic language spoken by the Norse in Scandinavia and their settlements during the Viking Age and early Middle Ages. It was the tongue of the Eddas, the skaldic poems, and the Icelandic sagas, and it gave English everyday words such as egg, knife, and window. It descended from Proto-Norse and is the ancestor of the modern Scandinavian languages, of which Icelandic has stayed closest to it.",
"Phoenix": "The phoenix is a legendary bird of classical and Near Eastern mythology that lives for a great span of years and then is often consumed in fire, only to be reborn from its own ashes. Associated with the sun and appearing in ancient Greek, Roman, and Egyptian traditions, it became a widespread emblem of renewal, resurrection, and immortality. Its name derives from the Greek phoinix, a word also meaning purple-red and linked to the Phoenician people.",
"Poetic_Edda": "A collection of Old Norse mythological and heroic poems that is among the chief sources of Norse myth. It survives mainly in the Codex Regius, an Icelandic vellum manuscript written around 1270, though the poems themselves are reckoned to be considerably older than that copy. Its verses tell of the creation and foretold destruction of the world and of heroes such as Sigurd and Brynhild.",
"Prakriti": "In Samkhya and Hindu thought, the primal matter or nature that is the active material principle, set against purusha, the passive cosmic consciousness. It embraces not only physical substance but the cognitive, emotional, and psychological dimensions of existence, and it alone acts while purusha merely observes. Its workings arise from three qualities or gunas, sattva, rajas, and tamas, which rest in equilibrium until cosmic manifestation sets them in motion.",
"Prose_Edda": "An Old Norse handbook of poetics and mythology written by the Icelander Snorri Sturluson around 1220, and a key source of Norse myth. It retells the legends of the gods in order to explain the kennings and ornate diction of the old skaldic poets, and it surveys the many verse metres of the tradition. Much of what is known of the Norse mythological world survives because Snorri set it down here.",
"Rigveda": "The oldest of the four Vedas and the foundational text of Vedic religion, a collection of over a thousand Sanskrit hymns arranged in ten books. Its verses praise deities such as Indra, Agni, and Soma, and its later layers turn to cosmological and philosophical speculation. Composed in the northwestern subcontinent and preserved for millennia by exacting oral transmission, it ranks among the oldest surviving texts in any Indo-European language.",
"Samkhya": "One of the orthodox schools of Hindu philosophy, a dualist system that divides reality into purusha, pure passive consciousness, and prakriti, active material nature. It holds that suffering springs from confusing the conscious self with the workings of matter, so that liberation comes through discriminating knowledge that tells the two apart. Systematized in the classical Samkhyakarika, it supplied the metaphysical framework later adopted by the Yoga school.",
"Scandinavia": "Scandinavia is a region of northern Europe most commonly comprising Norway, Sweden, and Denmark, sometimes extended on cultural grounds to include Iceland and the Faroe Islands. The mainland occupies much of the Scandinavian Peninsula, with mountains, long coastlines, and fjords, and reaches north of the Arctic Circle. It was the homeland of the Norse, whose seafaring expansion during the Viking Age spread their language and culture across much of Europe.",
"Snorri_Sturluson": "The Icelandic historian, poet, and chieftain (1179–1241) who was among the most powerful men of his age and twice lawspeaker of the Icelandic high court. He wrote the Prose Edda, a handbook of skaldic poetics and mythology, and the Heimskringla, a history of the kings of Norway. He was assassinated at his home in Reykjaholt on the order of King Haakon of Norway.",
"Sweden": "Sweden is a Scandinavian country on the eastern side of the Scandinavian Peninsula in northern Europe, bordering Norway and Finland, with Stockholm as its capital. The largest of the Nordic countries by area, it stretches far to the north and contains extensive forests, lakes, and archipelagos. It formed part of the Norse homeland, and during the Viking Age its seafarers, known as Varangians, ranged eastward through the rivers of eastern Europe.",
"Tortoise": "A tortoise is a land-dwelling reptile of the turtle order, enclosed in a high, domed bony shell into which it can typically withdraw its head and limbs for protection. Tortoises are slow-moving, largely herbivorous, and famously long-lived, with some individuals surviving well beyond a century. They are found in habitats ranging from deserts and dry scrub to grasslands across parts of the Americas, Africa, Asia, and southern Europe.",
"Vé": "In Norse mythology Vé is one of three brother-gods, alongside Odin and Vili, the sons of Borr and the jötunn Bestla. Together the brothers are said to have slain the primordial being Ymir and shaped the world from his remains, and then to have made the first humans from two trees found at the shore. The name Vé derives from a Proto-Germanic root meaning holy, connected with sacred enclosures and sanctuaries.",
"Viking_Age": "The period of Norse expansion, raiding, trading, and settlement that ran from the late eighth century to the eleventh. It is conventionally dated from the raid on the monastery of Lindisfarne in 793 to the Norman Conquest of England in 1066. Across these centuries Norsemen reached as far as Greenland and North America to the west and the rivers of eastern Europe to the east.",
"Vikings": "Seafaring Norse raiders, traders, and explorers who sailed out from Scandinavia during the Viking Age. The name derives from the Old Norse vikingr, a pirate or raider, and to go viking meant to set off on such a venture by ship. They were a subset of the broader Norse population rather than the whole of it, for most Scandinavians never went raiding at all.",
"Vili": "In Norse mythology Vili is one of three brother-gods, alongside Odin and Vé, the sons of Borr and the jötunn Bestla. The three are said to have slain the primordial being Ymir and to have fashioned the world from his body, afterward creating the first humans, Ask and Embla. The name Vili is generally understood to mean will in Old Norse, and the figure receives little attention in the surviving sources compared with his brother Odin.",
"Zhurong": "Zhurong (祝融) is the god of fire in Chinese mythology and folk religion, also associated with the south. He is said to have served as the divine Minister of Fire and is linked in legend to the cosmic struggle involving the water god Gonggong. In myth he was regarded as a descendant of the sky god Zhuanxu and an ancestor of the ruling house of the state of Chu.",
"Assyria": "The ancient Mesopotamian kingdom and empire of the north, which grew from the city-state of Ashur on the Tigris. At its height as the Neo-Assyrian Empire it was the largest the world had yet seen, ruling from a later capital at Nineveh. It collapsed when a coalition of Babylonians and Medes destroyed Nineveh in 612 BCE and ended the last Assyrian king in 609 BCE.",
"Bagua": "The bagua (八卦), or eight trigrams, are eight three-line symbols built from combinations of broken yin lines and unbroken yang lines. Each trigram stands for a fundamental aspect of reality, and paired together the eight generate the sixty-four hexagrams of the I Ching. They are a basic framework of Chinese cosmology, traditionally attributed to the legendary Fuxi.",
"Búri": "In Norse mythology the first of the gods and an early ancestor of the Aesir. He was licked free over three days from the salty rime-stones of the primordial ice by the cow Audumbla, emerging first as hair, then a head, then a whole man. He was the father of Borr and the grandfather of Odin, Vili, and Ve.",
"Burmese": "Relating to Myanmar, formerly Burma, in Southeast Asia and to its majority people, the Bamar. The Burmese language is the country's official tongue and a member of the Tibeto-Burman branch of the Sino-Tibetan family. With tens of millions of speakers, it is the largest Tibeto-Burman language and carries a literary tradition dating from the twelfth century.",
"China": "The country and civilization of East Asia, among the world's oldest continuous civilizations, with a written record reaching back more than three thousand years. Its population is led in number by the Han, alongside dozens of other recognized ethnic groups. The Chinese language belongs to the Sino-Tibetan family.",
"Confucius": "The Chinese philosopher and teacher Kongzi, or Master Kong, who lived during the Spring and Autumn period. His teachings on personal virtue, social harmony, and righteous government were gathered by his disciples and became the foundation of Confucianism. Long after his death he was honored as the great sage and master whose thought shaped the moral and political life of East Asia for two millennia.",
"Cosmic_egg": "A widespread creation motif in which the universe or a primordial being emerges from a primal egg. Typically the egg hatches to release the cosmos itself, or a first being who then fashions the world, with its halves often becoming sky and earth. The image recurs independently across many mythologies, from the Orphic egg of the Greeks to traditions of India, Finland, and East Asia.",
"Cuneiform": "One of the earliest writing systems, a wedge-shaped script pressed into wet clay with a reed stylus. It was developed by the Sumerians in Mesopotamia in the late fourth millennium BCE and was adapted to write Akkadian and many other languages of the ancient Near East. It remained in use for roughly three thousand years before alphabetic scripts displaced it.",
"Daojia": "Daojia (道家) is the philosophical strand of Daoism, the school of thought associated with the Dao. It centers on the classic texts attributed to Laozi and Zhuangzi and their teachings on the Way, naturalness, and non-action. It is distinguished from daojiao, the organized Daoist religion, though the two traditions overlap and share roots.",
"Daojiao": "Daojiao (道教) is organized, religious Daoism, the Daoist religion with its deities, scriptures, ritual, and ordained clergy. It seeks harmony with the Dao through practices such as liturgy, alchemy, meditation, and the pursuit of longevity or immortality. It is distinguished from daojia, the philosophical Daoism of Laozi and Zhuangzi, while drawing on the same tradition.",
"Ea": "The Mesopotamian god of fresh water, wisdom, magic, and crafts, known in Sumerian as Enki and by the Akkadian name Ea. In the myth of the Enuma Elish he learns of the primordial god Apsu plotting to destroy the younger gods, lulls him asleep with a spell, and slays him, then makes his home upon Apsu and fathers Marduk. He is portrayed as a cunning and benevolent helper of humankind, a patron of craftsmen, healers, and the arts of civilization.",
"East_Asia": "The eastern subregion of Asia, centred on China and historically shaped by its civilization. It also includes Japan, North and South Korea, Mongolia, and Taiwan. Shared classical influences across the region include Chinese characters, Confucian thought, and Buddhism.",
"East_China_Sea": "The marginal sea of the western Pacific Ocean off the eastern coast of China. The Yangtze is the largest river flowing into it, emptying through its estuary near Shanghai. It is bordered by mainland China, the Korean Peninsula, the Japanese islands, and Taiwan.",
"Eastern_Han": "The second half of the Han dynasty, restored by Emperor Guangwu after the fall of Wang Mang's Xin dynasty. Its capital moved east to Luoyang, which gives the period its name. It dissolved in 220 CE when the last emperor ceded the throne to Cao Pi, opening the Three Kingdoms period.",
"Euphrates": "The western and longest of the two great rivers of Mesopotamia, the other being the Tigris. It rises in the highlands of eastern Anatolia and flows southeast through Syria and Iraq across the Mesopotamian plain. It merges with the Tigris before reaching the Persian Gulf, and the land between the two rivers gave Mesopotamia its name.",
"Filial_piety": "Filial piety (孝), or xiao, is the Confucian virtue of respect, care, and devotion toward one's parents, elders, and ancestors. It calls for supporting parents in life, honoring them through proper conduct, and venerating them after death with mourning and sacrifice. Confucius treated it as the root of virtue, and it became a cornerstone of family ethics and social order across East Asia.",
"Five_Emperors": "The legendary sage-rulers (五帝) who in Chinese tradition follow the Three Sovereigns at the dawn of civilization. The best-known list, from Sima Qian Records of the Grand Historian, names the Yellow Emperor, Zhuanxu, Ku, Yao, and Shun, though the membership varies across sources. They are regarded as legendary culture heroes and models of virtuous rule rather than historically attested kings.",
"Four_Great_Books_of_Song": "The four monumental compilations (宋四大書) sponsored by the early Song court to gather the empire knowledge. They are the leishu encyclopedia Taiping Yulan, the story collection Taiping Guangji, the literary anthology Wenyuan Yinghua, and the institutional encyclopedia Cefu Yuangui. The set took its name once the last of them, the Cefu Yuangui, was finished in the early eleventh century.",
"Gaozu_of_Tang": "Li Yuan, the founder and first emperor of the Tang dynasty, who reigned from 618 to 626 after rising in rebellion against the collapsing Sui. He commissioned the literary encyclopedia Yiwen Leiju, which was completed under Ouyang Xun in 624. He abdicated to his son Li Shimin, the future Emperor Taizong, after the Xuanwu Gate Incident.",
"Hinduism": "The major religious and cultural tradition of the Indian subcontinent and one of the largest religions in the world. It grew from many sources, chief among them the historical Vedic religion of the Indo-Aryan peoples, and is often called the oldest living major faith. It embraces a vast range of philosophies, deities, and ritual practices rather than a single creed or founder.",
"History": "The study and written record of the human past, both the academic discipline and the body of events it documents. Its central evidence is the written document, which sets it apart from prehistory, the span before writing that is left to fields such as archaeology. Historians gather, weigh, and interpret sources to reconstruct and explain what came before, increasingly drawing on neighbouring disciplines to do so.",
"I_Ching": "The I Ching (易經), or Book of Changes, is one of the oldest Chinese classics, a divination manual organized around sixty-four hexagrams of broken and unbroken lines. Its core text, the Zhouyi, took shape in the early Western Zhou and was later layered with cosmological and philosophical commentaries known as the Ten Wings. Canonized among the Five Classics, it became a foundational influence on Confucian and Daoist thought alike.",
"Indo-Aryan": "The Indo-Aryan peoples and the languages they speak, forming the easternmost reach of the Indo-European family. Descended from pastoralists who moved into the northwestern Indian subcontinent in the late Bronze Age, their early speech is preserved as Vedic Sanskrit. In that archaic form they composed the Vedas, the oldest texts of ancient India, and their modern languages are now spoken by roughly a billion people across South Asia.",
"Indo-European": "The world's largest language family by number of speakers, native to most of Europe, the Iranian plateau, and much of the northern Indian subcontinent. Its branches include Indo-Iranian, Italic, Hellenic, Germanic, Balto-Slavic, and Celtic, embracing classical tongues such as Sanskrit, Latin, and Greek alongside modern ones like English. All are held to descend from a single reconstructed ancestor, Proto-Indo-European, spoken in prehistory and never directly attested.",
"Leishu": "A leishu (類書) is a traditional Chinese reference compendium that gathers extracts from many earlier works and arranges them under systematic categories and subcategories. Often described as classified encyclopedias, these compilations preserved knowledge and quotations across history, literature, and statecraft. Famous examples include the Yiwen Leiju and the Song-era imperial reader Taiping Yulan.",
"Li_(Confucianism)": "Li (禮) is the Confucian concept of ritual propriety, the proper forms of conduct, ceremony, and decorum that govern human relationships. Originally referring to religious sacrifice, it came to embrace all the rites and norms that order family, society, and the dealings between people and the spirits. Confucius held that practicing li civilizes the individual and sustains social harmony.",
"Li_Fang_(Song_dynasty)": "The Song scholar-official who led the great compilation projects of Emperor Taizong. He directed the teams that produced the Taiping Yulan and the Taiping Guangji, and also worked on the Wenyuan Yinghua, three of the Four Great Books of Song. He had earlier served the Later Han and Later Zhou before rising to high office under the Song.",
"Liu_Bang": "The peasant-born rebel leader who founded the Han dynasty and reigned as its first emperor, Emperor Gaozu, from 202 to 195 BCE. After the collapse of the Qin he prevailed over his rival Xiang Yu in the Chu-Han Contention, winning the decisive Battle of Gaixia in 202 BCE. He was among the very few founders of Chinese dynasties to have risen from common origins.",
"Luoyang": "An ancient city in Henan province on the Luo River, one of the cradles of Chinese civilization and among the oldest of the Four Great Ancient Capitals. It served as the seat of many dynasties, including the Eastern Zhou, the Eastern Han, and Cao Wei. Under the Jin its population approached 600,000, ranking it among the largest cities in the world.",
"Mesopotamia": "The historical region between the Tigris and Euphrates rivers, largely modern Iraq, often called a cradle of civilization. It was home to a succession of peoples and powers including Sumer, Akkad, Babylonia, and Assyria. It was the birthplace of cuneiform, the wedge-shaped script that is among the earliest writing systems.",
"Ouyang_Xun": "The early Tang scholar-official and calligrapher who served as lead editor of the Yiwen Leiju, completed in 624. He was renowned as one of the Four Great Calligraphers of the Early Tang, famous for his rigorous regular script known as the Ou style. He had served under the Sui before entering the Tang court, where he taught at the Hongwen Academy.",
"Persia": "The first Persian empire, founded by Cyrus the Great and the largest the ancient world had yet seen, ruled from centres such as Persepolis and Susa. Under Cyrus the Persians conquered Babylon in 539 BCE, ending Babylonian independence and absorbing Mesopotamia into the empire. It endured until Alexander the Great overthrew it in 330 BCE.",
"Qing_dynasty": "The last imperial dynasty of China, a Manchu-led empire ruled by the Aisin Gioro clan. After proclaiming their state in 1636, the Manchus seized Beijing in 1644 and went on to assemble one of the largest empires in world history. It fell in 1912 when the last emperor abdicated following the Xinhai Revolution.",
"Ren_(Confucianism)": "Ren (仁) is the central Confucian virtue, usually rendered as benevolence, humaneness, or co-humanity. It names the ideal disposition of the fully realized person toward others, encompassing compassion, empathy, and reciprocity. For Confucius it was the supreme moral quality, cultivated through proper conduct and expressed in how one treats other people.",
"Romance_of_the_Three_Kingdoms": "The fourteenth-century historical novel (三國演義) attributed to Luo Guanzhong, dramatizing the turbulent collapse of the Han and the ensuing Three Kingdoms era. Blending history with legend, it follows the rival states of Wei, Shu, and Wu from the Yellow Turban Rebellion to reunification under the Western Jin. Drawing on Chen Shou Records of the Three Kingdoms, it is counted among the Four Great Classical Novels of Chinese literature.",
"Sage_(philosophy)": "A sage is a person of profound wisdom and moral excellence, held up as a model of how to live. In many philosophical and religious traditions the sage represents the highest human ideal, one whose insight and virtue are taken to reach into the deepest order of things. Such traditions typically honor a small number of revered figures, often founding teachers or legendary rulers, as their supreme exemplars of this ideal.",
"Sanskrit": "The ancient classical language of the Indo-Aryan branch of Indo-European, the sacred tongue of South Asia. It is the language of the Vedas and of the foundational scriptures of Hinduism, Buddhism, and Jainism. Long after it ceased to be a vernacular it remained the medium of philosophy, law, science, and poetry across the subcontinent, and it is still used in Hindu ritual today.",
"Shanghai": "The major port city and metropolis on China's east coast, sitting on the southern estuary of the Yangtze where it meets the East China Sea. It is China's largest city and a global hub of finance, trade, and industry. Its harbor, the Port of Shanghai, is among the busiest container ports in the world.",
"Sima_clan": "The scholar-official family that displaced the ruling Cao house within Cao Wei and went on to found the Jin dynasty. Sima Yi seized control as regent through the Incident at the Gaoping Tombs in 249, and his son Sima Zhao consolidated that power and conquered Shu Han. In 266 his grandson Sima Yan deposed the last Wei emperor and proclaimed himself Emperor Wu of Jin.",
"Sinitic": "The Chinese branch of the Sino-Tibetan language family, comprising the varieties usually grouped together as the Chinese languages. It includes Mandarin, Cantonese, Wu, Min, Hakka, Xiang, and Gan, and is by far the most spoken branch of the family. Scholars often treat Sinitic as forming a primary split against the rest of Sino-Tibetan, the Tibeto-Burman languages.",
"Song_dynasty": "The Chinese dynasty that ruled from 960 to 1279, divided into the Northern Song based at Kaifeng and the Southern Song based at Hangzhou after the loss of the north to the Jin in 1127. It was an era of exceptional cultural, scientific, and economic flourishing, with paper money, woodblock printing, and booming commerce. Its court sponsored vast scholarly compilations, including the Four Great Books of Song.",
"Southeast_Asia": "The region of Asia south of China and east of the Indian subcontinent, lying northwest of Australia. It divides into Mainland Southeast Asia, which includes Myanmar, Thailand, Cambodia, Laos, Vietnam, and Malaysia, and Maritime Southeast Asia, which includes Indonesia, the Philippines, Brunei, Singapore, and Timor-Leste. Its eleven states are all members of the regional bloc ASEAN.",
"Sumer": "The earliest known civilization of southern Mesopotamia, where the first cities and the cuneiform script arose. Its independent city-states, among them Uruk, Ur, and Lagash, pioneered monumental temple architecture, irrigation, and written record-keeping. Sumerian survived as a learned and liturgical language long after the region was absorbed into Akkadian and Babylonian rule.",
"Taiwan": "The island in the western Pacific Ocean off the southeastern coast of China, lying between the East and South China Seas. It is today self-governed, with its own elected government, while its political status remains internationally contested. Its population is majority Han Chinese, alongside indigenous Austronesian peoples.",
"Taizong_of_Song": "The second emperor of the Song dynasty, who reigned from 976 to 997 after succeeding his brother the founder Taizu. He commissioned the great early-Song encyclopedias, ordering scholars to compile the Taiping Yulan, the Taiping Guangji, and the Wenyuan Yinghua. He completed the reunification of China proper but failed twice to recover the northern territories from the Liao.",
"Tibetan": "Relating to Tibet, its people, and their culture. The Tibetans are an ethnic group native to the Tibetan Plateau, with communities also across neighbouring regions of China, India, Nepal, and Bhutan. The Tibetic languages they speak form a branch of Tibeto-Burman within the Sino-Tibetan family, with a literary tradition reaching back to the seventh century.",
"Tibetan_Plateau": "The vast, high plateau of Central and East Asia, the highest and largest in the world and often called the Roof of the World. It holds the headwaters of many of Asia's great rivers, including the Yangtze, the Yellow River, and the Mekong. Its glaciers and ice fields make it one of the largest stores of fresh water outside the polar regions.",
"Tibeto-Burman": "The large non-Sinitic division of the Sino-Tibetan family, taking its name from its two best-documented members, Tibetan and Burmese. Over four hundred such languages are spoken across the Himalayan region, parts of China, and the highlands of Southeast and South Asia. Beyond Tibetan and Burmese they include tongues such as Newar and Meitei, many of them spoken by small mountain communities.",
"Tigris": "The eastern of the two great rivers that define Mesopotamia, the other being the Euphrates. It rises in the Armenian highlands of eastern Anatolia and flows southeast through modern Iraq, past cities such as Mosul and Baghdad. It joins the Euphrates near the head of the Persian Gulf, into which their combined waters drain.",
"Vedas": "The oldest scriptures of Hinduism, four great collections of hymns and ritual texts composed in Vedic Sanskrit. They are the Rigveda, the Samaveda, the Yajurveda, and the Atharvaveda, and they form the oldest layer of Sanskrit literature. Transmitted orally with extraordinary precision long before they were written, they remain the foundational authority of the tradition.",
"Western_Han": "The first half of the Han dynasty, spanning from its founding by Liu Bang to the usurpation by Wang Mang. Its capital lay at Chang'an in the west, which gives the period its name. It ended in 9 CE when Wang Mang proclaimed his Xin dynasty.",
"Wu_(state)": "An ancient state of the Zhou period at the mouth of the Yangtze, with its capital near modern Suzhou. After a long rivalry with its southern neighbour Yue, it was conquered and absorbed by Yue in 473 BCE. At its height under King Helü and King Fuchai it was briefly one of the dominant powers of the late Spring and Autumn period.",
"Xin_dynasty": "The short-lived dynasty established by the usurper Wang Mang, who seized the throne from the Han after years as regent for child emperors. It interrupted the Han, dividing it into the earlier Western Han and the later Eastern Han. Famine, the Yellow River changing course, and rebellions such as the Red Eyebrows brought it down, and Wang Mang was killed when Chang'an fell in 23 CE.",
"Yue_(state)": "An ancient state of the Zhou period in southeastern China, centered on what is now Zhejiang, known for its naval power and renowned bronze swords. Under its king Goujian it conquered and absorbed the neighboring state of Wu around 473 BCE. Yue itself was later broken by Chu around 333 BCE.",
"Zuozhuan_Shiwei": "A study of the Zuo Zhuan (左傳事緯) by the early Qing scholar Ma Su, who rearranged the chronicle into thematic chapters tracing each event from start to finish. It served as a companion to his larger history of antiquity, the Yishi, sharing its source-driven, topical method. Like the Yishi, it reflects the seventeenth-century turn toward organizing early records by subject rather than year.",
"Akkadian_Empire": "The first great empire of Mesopotamia, founded by Sargon of Akkad and centred on the city of Akkad, whose site has never been located. It united the Akkadian and Sumerian speakers of the region and projected power from the Persian Gulf into the Levant and Anatolia. It gave its name to the Akkadian language, the Semitic tongue that long served as the lingua franca of the ancient Near East.",
"Abrahamic_religion": "The Abrahamic religions are the family of monotheistic faiths that trace their origin to the patriarch Abraham, principally Judaism, Christianity, and Islam. They share a belief in a single, all-powerful God who is held to have revealed himself to Abraham, and they place great weight on scripture as a guide to religious and moral life. Smaller traditions such as the Baha'i Faith, the Druze faith, and Samaritanism are also commonly counted among them.",
"Aesir": "The principal pantheon of gods in Norse mythology, including Odin, Thor, and the deities of war and sky. They are set apart from the Vanir, a second divine family associated with fertility, with whom they were said to have warred and then reconciled. The standard spelling is Æsir, the Old Norse plural of áss.",
"Akkad_(city)": "The ancient Mesopotamian city, also called Agade, that served as the seat of Sargon and his Akkadian dynasty. It was a major political and religious centre in the later third millennium BCE before fading from prominence. Despite long searching, its exact site has never been located, with proposals clustering near the Tigris around modern Baghdad.",
"Akkadian_language": "An extinct East Semitic language of ancient Mesopotamia, spoken across Akkad, Assyria, and Babylonia and written in cuneiform script borrowed from Sumerian. By the Bronze Age it had become the lingua franca of much of the ancient Near East, used even in diplomatic correspondence with Egypt. It slowly gave way to Aramaic, though scholars kept writing it until the first century CE.",
"Anatolia": "The large peninsula of Western Asia, also called Asia Minor, that makes up most of modern Turkey. It is bounded by the Black Sea to the north, the Mediterranean to the south, and the Aegean to the west, with the Sea of Marmara dividing it from Europe. A crossroads of peoples since the Neolithic, it hosted civilisations from the Hittites to the Romans and Byzantines.",
"Borr": "In Norse myth the son of Búri and the father of the three creator-brothers Odin, Vili, and Vé. His wife is said to be Bestla, daughter of a giant, and his name is usually read as meaning the borer. His own role is obscure in the sources, where he appears chiefly as the link between Búri and his world-shaping sons.",
"Burmese_language": "The Sino-Tibetan language of the Tibeto-Burman branch that serves as the official language of Myanmar. It is the most widely spoken of the Tibeto-Burman languages and, within the broader Sino-Tibetan family, the second most spoken after the Sinitic languages. It is the first language of the Bamar majority and a second language for many of the country's other peoples.",
"Cao_Cao": "The dominant warlord of the late Eastern Han, who unified northern China and laid the foundations of the state of Cao Wei. Although he held the Han court in his grip and ruled as its chancellor, he never took the imperial title in his own lifetime. After his death his son Cao Pi founded the Cao Wei dynasty in 220 and honored him posthumously as Emperor Wu of Wei.",
"Christianity": "Christianity is a monotheistic, Abrahamic religion centred on the life and teachings of Jesus of Nazareth, whom Christians regard as the Son of God and the awaited messiah. With over two billion adherents it is the world's largest and most widespread religion, and its sacred text is the Bible. Its major branches are Roman Catholicism, Eastern Orthodoxy, and Protestantism, which together profess one God understood as Father, Son, and Holy Spirit.",
"Deity": "A deity is a god or goddess, a supernatural being held to be divine and worthy of worship. Such beings are typically regarded as possessing powers and knowledge far beyond those of humanity and as holding authority over some aspect of the cosmos or human life. In English a male deity is called a god and a female deity a goddess, and traditions that worship many deities at once are described as polytheistic.",
"Gorm_the_Old": "The first widely recognized king of Denmark, who reigned from Jelling until his death around 958. He was the father of Harald Bluetooth and is traditionally counted as the founder of the Danish royal line. He remained a follower of the old Norse religion, and it was his son who later converted the kingdom to Christianity.",
"Harald_Bluetooth": "The tenth-century king of Denmark, and for a time Norway, who unified the Danish realm and converted it to Christianity. The son of Gorm the Old, he raised the great Jelling stone proclaiming the new faith before being deposed by his son Swein Forkbeard. The Bluetooth wireless standard is named after him, its logo binding the runes for H and B.",
"Jesus_Christ": "Jesus of Nazareth was a 1st-century Jewish preacher and religious leader in the Roman province of Judea and is the central figure of Christianity. Christians regard him as the incarnate Son of God and the messiah, or Christ, foretold in scripture, and believe that he was crucified and rose from the dead. Most scholars of antiquity hold that he existed historically and was crucified during the governorship of Pontius Pilate.",
"Judea": "Judea is an ancient mountainous region of the southern Levant centred on Jerusalem, its traditionally dominant city. It came under Roman control in 63 BCE and was organised as the Roman province of Judaea, the setting in which Christianity arose during the 1st century CE. In the following decades it became the epicentre of major Jewish revolts against Rome, culminating in the destruction of the Second Temple in 70 CE.",
"Jutland_Peninsula": "The peninsula that forms mainland Denmark together with the northern part of Germany in Schleswig-Holstein. It juts northward into the sea, bounded by the North Sea to the west and the Baltic Sea to the southeast. Flat and low-lying, it was a heartland of the Danes and the seat of the early kings at Jelling.",
"Levant": "The region of the eastern Mediterranean covering roughly modern Syria, Lebanon, Israel, Palestine, and Jordan, sometimes extended to Cyprus and southern Turkey. It forms a land bridge linking Africa, Asia, and the Mediterranean world. The name derives from an Italian and French word for the rising sun, marking the lands to the east.",
"Lingua_franca": "A common bridge language adopted between speakers of different native tongues to make trade, administration, or diplomacy possible. Such languages tend to arise naturally out of practical need rather than being deliberately created. The term itself means language of the Franks, after a Romance-based pidgin once spoken around the medieval Mediterranean.",
"Myanmar": "The Southeast Asian country also known as Burma, sharing borders with China, India, Bangladesh, Laos, and Thailand. It is the largest country by area in mainland Southeast Asia, with its capital at Naypyidaw and its largest city at Yangon. Its majority people are the Bamar, who give the country its dominant Burmese language and Theravada Buddhist culture.",
"Near_East": "A historical term for the lands of Western Asia and the eastern Mediterranean, especially in antiquity, taking in Mesopotamia, the Levant, Anatolia, Persia, and Egypt. Western geographers coined it in the nineteenth century to set these nearer regions apart from the Middle and Far East. In modern usage it overlaps heavily with the term Middle East, though it remains standard in the study of the ancient world.",
"Pagan": "A term, originally a Christian label, for followers of polytheistic or folk religions outside the Abrahamic faiths. It derives from the Latin paganus, meaning a rural or rustic person, and was long used disparagingly by Christians for those outside their faith. It is commonly applied to traditions such as the pre-Christian Norse religion.",
"Persian_Gulf": "An arm of the Indian Ocean lying between the Arabian Peninsula and Iran, joined to the Gulf of Oman through the Strait of Hormuz. It is shallow and warm, averaging only about fifty metres deep. The Tigris and Euphrates, joined as the Shatt al-Arab, empty into its northwestern head.",
"Semitic": "Relating to the Semitic branch of the Afroasiatic language family, which includes Akkadian, Hebrew, Aramaic, and Arabic, and to the peoples who speak them. The name comes from Shem, a son of Noah in the Book of Genesis, and was coined by German scholars in the late eighteenth century. These languages typically build words from three-consonant roots into which vowels are woven.",
"Sumerian_language": "The language of ancient Sumer in southern Mesopotamia and the first language ever committed to writing in cuneiform. It is a language isolate, with no proven relatives in any known family. Displaced as everyday speech by Akkadian around 2000 BCE, it survived as a sacred and literary language down to the first century CE.",
"Annals_of_the_Three_Sovereigns": "The Annals of the Three Sovereigns 三皇本紀 is a short supplement written by the Tang scholar Sima Zhen to the Records of the Grand Historian. Sima Qian had begun his history with the Five Emperors and omitted any dedicated treatment of the earlier Three Sovereigns. Sima Zhen composed this added chapter to furnish an account of those legendary rulers and prefix it to the existing work.",
"Aramaic": "A Northwest Semitic language that arose in ancient Syria and spread to become the common tongue of much of the ancient Near East. The Neo-Assyrian kings adopted it as a lingua franca, and under the Persian Achaemenid Empire a standardized Imperial Aramaic served as the language of administration across its vast territories. It long outlasted those empires, shaping later scripts and surviving in dialects spoken to this day.",
"Ashur": "The ancient city on the western bank of the Tigris that was the first capital and the enduring religious centre of Assyria. It took its name from Ashur, the chief national god of the Assyrians, whose temple stood there even after the royal residence moved to Nimrud and Nineveh. The Medes and Babylonians sacked it in 614 BCE during the wars that brought down the Assyrian Empire.",
"Babylonia": "The ancient civilization and state of southern Mesopotamia, centred on the city of Babylon between the Tigris and Euphrates. It rose around 1894 BCE under an Amorite dynasty and first dominated the region under Hammurabi, who gave southern Mesopotamia the name Babylonia. After many dynasties it lost its independence in 539 BCE, when Cyrus the Great conquered Babylon for Persia.",
"Baghdad": "The city on the Tigris that is the capital and largest city of modern Iraq. It was founded in 762 CE by the Abbasid caliph al-Mansur as the seat of his caliphate and quickly grew into one of the largest cities in the world. During the Islamic Golden Age it was a leading centre of learning, home to the House of Wisdom and scholars such as al-Khwarizmi.",
"Bestla": "In Norse mythology, a jötunn who is the wife of Borr and the mother of the gods Odin, Vili, and Vé. She is the daughter of the jötunn Bölþorn, and the god Odin is often called her son in skaldic verse and the Eddas. Some scholars have suggested that her unnamed brother, from whom Odin learns magic songs, may be the wise being Mímir.",
"Bronze_Age": "The middle period of the three-age archaeological system, falling between the Stone Age and the Iron Age. It is defined by the widespread use of bronze, an alloy of copper and tin, and coincided with the rise of writing, cities, and complex states in regions such as Mesopotamia and Egypt. Because it is marked by technology rather than a fixed date, its span varies by region, beginning around 3300 BCE in the Near East and arriving later elsewhere.",
"Chuci": "The Chuci 楚辭, the Songs of Chu, is an anthology of richly imaginative ancient Chinese poetry rooted in the southern state of Chu. Its earliest and most famous pieces are associated above all with Qu Yuan, with later imitations added during the Han dynasty before the collection was edited into its received form. The poems are marked by vivid imagery, shamanistic and mythological themes, and a distinctive sao verse style.",
"City-state": "A sovereign, self-governing state consisting of a single city and the surrounding territory it controls. Unlike an ordinary city subject to a larger nation, it holds its own government and is answerable to no higher power. The form flourished in antiquity, as in the city-states of Sumer and ancient Greece, and survives today in places such as Singapore and Monaco.",
"Egypt": "The country at the northeast corner of Africa, linking that continent to Asia across the Sinai Peninsula. Its civilization, one of the oldest in the world, arose along the Nile River whose annual flooding sustained farming in an otherwise arid land. Famed for its pharaohs, monumental pyramids and temples, and hieroglyphic writing, it endured for some three thousand years before falling under Roman rule.",
"Fujian": "A mountainous province on the southeastern coast of China, facing the island of Taiwan across the Taiwan Strait. Said to be eight parts mountain, one part water, and one part farmland, it has narrow coastal plains backed by rugged highlands such as the Wuyi Mountains. Its rugged terrain turned its people toward the sea, making its ports centers of trade and emigration.",
"Greece": "The country at the southern tip of the Balkan Peninsula in southeastern Europe, made up of a mainland and thousands of islands across the Aegean and Ionian seas. Its ancient civilization is regarded as the cradle of the Western world, originating democracy, formal philosophy, drama, and the Olympic Games. The achievements of city-states such as Athens and Sparta in politics, art, and thought profoundly shaped later European culture.",
"Guangdong": "A populous southern coastal province of China on the north shore of the South China Sea, with Guangzhou as its capital. Its port of Guangzhou, long known to Europeans as Canton, was a leading hub of the Maritime Silk Road and the chief gateway for South China's foreign trade. The most populous of China's provinces, it has been a center of maritime commerce for over two thousand years.",
"Guangxi": "A region of southern China bordering Vietnam and the Gulf of Tonkin, officially the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region. It is the home of the Zhuang, a Tai-speaking people who are the largest ethnic minority in China and most of whom live within the region. Formerly a province, it was reorganized as an autonomous region in 1958 in recognition of its Zhuang population.",
"Hammurabi": "The sixth Amorite king of the first dynasty of Babylon, who reigned from about 1792 to 1750 BCE. Through a series of campaigns he conquered the rival city-states of southern Mesopotamia and united almost the whole region under Babylonian rule. He is best remembered for the Code of Hammurabi, one of the earliest and most complete written law codes to survive.",
"Japan": "The East Asian island country lying in the Pacific Ocean east of the Korean Peninsula and China. Its long history runs from early clan rule through periods of imperial court, samurai shogunates, and modern industrial nationhood. From its earliest historical eras it borrowed heavily from China, including writing, Buddhism, Confucian statecraft, and art, while developing a distinct culture of its own.",
"Luo_River": "A river of central China that rises in Shaanxi and flows east through Henan to join the Yellow River. The ancient capital Luoyang, which took its name from the river, stands on its banks. In legend the Luo gave rise to the Luoshu, a magical writing or diagram said to have appeared on the shell of a turtle emerging from its waters.",
"Medes_(people)": "An ancient Iranian people of the mountainous region of northwestern Iran, centred on Ecbatana, near modern Hamadan. Under their king Cyaxares they allied with Babylon and destroyed the Neo-Assyrian Empire between 616 and 609 BCE, then built a kingdom of their own across much of western Iran. In 550 BCE Cyrus the Great defeated their last king and absorbed Media into the Persian Achaemenid Empire.",
"Neo-Assyrian_Empire": "The last and greatest stage of Assyria, lasting from about 911 to 609 BCE. At its height it dominated the entire ancient Near East and is often called the first world empire, ruling from capitals such as Nimrud and Nineveh. A coalition of Medes and Babylonians destroyed it, taking Nineveh in 612 BCE and the final stronghold of Harran in 609 BCE.",
"Neo-Babylonian_Empire": "The final flourishing of Babylon, founded when Nabopolassar revolted against Assyria and took the throne in 626 BCE. Its golden age came under Nebuchadnezzar II, who rebuilt the city with works such as the Ishtar Gate and destroyed Jerusalem in 587 BCE. The empire ended in 539 BCE when Cyrus the Great captured Babylon, the last Mesopotamian state ruled by native monarchs.",
"Nineveh": "The great capital of the Neo-Assyrian Empire, set on the eastern bank of the Tigris opposite modern Mosul. Rebuilt on a vast scale by Sennacherib around 700 BCE, it was among the largest and wealthiest cities of the ancient world, holding well over a hundred thousand inhabitants. It fell to the Medes and Babylonians in 612 BCE, marking the effective end of Assyrian power.",
"Philosophy": "The systematic, rational study of fundamental questions about existence, knowledge, values, reason, mind, and language. It proceeds through critical inquiry and reasoned argument rather than appeal to myth or authority. Its major branches include metaphysics, epistemology, ethics, and logic, and its name comes from the Greek for love of wisdom.",
"Records_of_the_Grand_Historian": "The Records of the Grand Historian, or Shiji 史記, is the monumental history of China compiled by the Western Han historian Sima Qian, building on work begun by his father Sima Tan. It narrates the past from the legendary Yellow Emperor down to Sima Qian's own time under Emperor Wu of Han, organised into basic annals, tables, treatises, hereditary houses, and biographies. Its structure became the model for the later official dynastic histories of imperial China.",
"River_Map": "The River Map, or He Tu (河圖), is a mythical diagram of paired black-and-white dots said in Chinese legend to have been revealed on the back of a dragon-horse that emerged from the Yellow River. Tradition links it to the sage Fuxi, who is said to have derived the eight trigrams of the Yijing from its patterns. It was long treated as a foundational source of Chinese cosmology, numerology, and divination.",
"Sargon_of_Akkad": "The ruler who founded the Akkadian Empire, the first great empire of Mesopotamia, reigning roughly from 2334 to 2279 BCE. Said to have risen from humble origins as a cup-bearer at Kish, he conquered the Sumerian city-states and welded them into a single realm. He is often named as the first person in recorded history to rule over an empire.",
"Shandong": "A coastal province of eastern China whose peninsula juts into the Yellow Sea toward the Korean peninsula. A heartland of early Chinese culture, it held the states of Qi and Lu and was a core area of Shang civilization. It is revered as the home of Confucius, who was born and taught in the state of Lu and is honored at Qufu.",
"Shangdi": "Shangdi (上帝) is the supreme sky deity and high god of early Chinese religion, whose name means roughly the Highest Deity. He was worshipped especially during the Shang dynasty as the greatest power presiding over other gods, royal ancestors, the weather, the harvest, and success in war. During the Zhou dynasty his prominence was gradually absorbed into the more abstract concept of Heaven, or Tian.",
"Sima_Zhen": "Sima Zhen was a Tang-dynasty scholar best known as a major commentator on the Records of the Grand Historian, the history compiled by Sima Qian. His commentary, the Shiji suoyin, sought to clarify obscure passages and names in that text. He also composed a supplementary Annals of the Three Sovereigns to provide an account of the legendary Three Sovereigns that Sima Qian had not covered.",
"Spring_and_Autumn_period": "The Spring and Autumn period is the earlier portion of the Eastern Zhou, roughly 771 to 476 BCE, during which the Zhou kings declined into figureheads and many vassal states contended for supremacy. It takes its name from the Spring and Autumn Annals, a chronicle of the state of Lu traditionally associated with Confucius, who lived in this age. The era saw the erosion of central authority and the early flowering of Chinese philosophy.",
"Taihao": "Taihao is a legendary Chinese sovereign and culture hero of high antiquity whose name is traditionally glossed as Great Brilliance. In later tradition he is frequently identified or conflated with Fuxi, the two often being merged into a single figure called Taihao Fuxi. He appears in classical historiography as one of the ancient rulers who shaped early Chinese civilization.",
"Turkey": "The transcontinental country whose territory spans the Anatolian peninsula in western Asia and a small corner of southeastern Europe across the Bosporus and Dardanelles straits. It is the principal successor state of the Ottoman Empire, which ruled much of the Middle East, North Africa, and southeastern Europe for centuries. The modern republic was founded in 1923 under Mustafa Kemal Atatürk with its capital at Ankara.",
"Vanir": "In Norse mythology, one of the two principal groups of gods, associated with fertility, prosperity, wisdom, and the forces of nature. Their best-known members are Njörðr and his children Freyr and Freyja. According to the myths they fought a war with the Aesir that ended in truce and an exchange of hostages, after which the two groups merged into a single pantheon.",
"Wu_Liang_Shrine": "The Wu Liang Shrine is an Eastern Han stone offering shrine in Jiaxiang County, Shandong, built around 151 CE for the Confucian scholar Wu Liang. It is renowned for its engraved stone reliefs, which depict a comprehensive program of mythological and historical figures, including ancient sovereigns and culture heroes of high antiquity. The carvings are among the most important surviving examples of early Chinese pictorial art and are widely known through ink rubbings.",
"Xici": "The Xici 繫辭, often rendered as the Great Treatise or Great Commentary, is one of the Ten Wings, the philosophical commentaries appended to the I Ching. It moves beyond divination to set out a cosmology in which the hexagrams model the patterns of change in nature and human affairs. Scholars generally date the Ten Wings, including the Xici, to a span running from the late Warring States into the early Han, rather than to a single author or moment.",
"Yellow_Emperor": "The Yellow Emperor, or Huangdi, is a legendary sovereign and culture hero traditionally counted as the first of the Five Emperors of high antiquity. In Chinese tradition he is credited with founding innovations of civilization and is regarded as a common ancestor of the Chinese people. Most scholars hold that he originated as a deity who was later represented as a historical ruler.",
"Yellow_River": "The second-longest river in China, known as the Huang He, rising on the Tibetan Plateau and flowing east to empty into the Bohai Sea. Its silt-laden water gives it its name and builds the broad delta in Shandong, while frequent catastrophic floods earned it the nickname the river of sorrow. Its valley is regarded as a cradle of Chinese civilization, the heartland of the early Shang and Zhou dynasties.",
"Yu_the_Great": "Yu the Great is a legendary ruler of ancient China famed for taming the great floods by dredging channels to carry the waters to the sea. Tradition credits him with founding the Xia, conventionally regarded as China's first dynasty, after the throne was ceded to him for his virtue and diligence. There is no contemporary evidence of his existence, and he is generally treated as a legendary sage-king.",
"Zhuangzi": "Zhuangzi 莊子 names both the Warring States thinker Zhuang Zhou and the foundational Daoist text traditionally attributed to him and his followers. The work is celebrated for its parables, allegories, and playful paradoxes, which it uses to question fixed distinctions and conventional values. It champions spontaneity and harmony with the Dao, and stands alongside the Daodejing as a central text of Daoist thought.",
"Nüba": "Ba 魃, also called Nüba or Hanba, is a drought goddess of Chinese myth and a daughter of the Yellow Emperor. Legend holds that at the Battle of Zhuolu she descended from heaven to aid her father, using her power of drought to dry up the wind and rain that Chiyou's wind god and rain god had unleashed. Afterward she could not return to the heavens, and wherever she dwelt no rain would fall, so she was settled north of the Red Water.",
"Canon_of_the_Yellow_Emperor": "The Inner Canon of the Yellow Emperor (黃帝內經) is the foundational classic of Chinese medicine, framing its theory as dialogues between the legendary Yellow Emperor and his ministers. It comprises two parts, the Suwen on medical theory and diagnosis and the Lingshu on acupuncture, and sets out the doctrines of qi, yin-yang, and the channels that have shaped Chinese medicine for two millennia. Its layers were composed over a long span, with much of its systematic theory dated to around the second to first centuries BCE.",
"Chinese_medicine": "The traditional system of medicine developed in China over more than two millennia, shaped largely by Daoist thought and the concepts of qi, yin and yang, and the Five Phases. It draws on a range of practices including herbal therapy, acupuncture, massage, dietary therapy, and breathing exercise. Its theoretical foundations were broadly in place by the Han dynasty.",
"Chiyou": "Chiyou (蚩尤) is a fierce war god and tribal leader of Chinese legend, remembered as chief of the Nine Li and as a maker of weapons and a bringer of war. According to myth he was defeated and slain by the Yellow Emperor at the Battle of Zhuolu, traditionally placed around the twenty-sixth century BCE. Though cast as a chaotic adversary in many texts, he is revered as a founding ancestor by the Miao and Hmong peoples.",
"Classic_of_Mountains_and_Seas": "The Classic of Mountains and Seas (山海經) is an ancient Chinese compendium of geography, mythical creatures, deities, and folklore, cataloguing the mountains, waterways, peoples, and strange beings of a mythic world. Assembled by many hands over several centuries, it is a foundational source for early Chinese mythology and cosmology. Han-dynasty scholars such as Liu Xiang and Liu Xin are credited with editing it into roughly its present form.",
"Fengsu_Tongyi": "The Comprehensive Meaning of Customs (風俗通義) is an encyclopaedic work of the late Eastern Han compiled by the scholar-official Ying Shao that records customs, folklore, popular beliefs, and the origins of institutions and surnames. Written in the aftermath of the Yellow Turban upheavals, it sought to correct errors and establish a shared standard of knowledge, and is a valued source for Han social life and religion. Of its original thirty chapters only ten survive intact, with the rest preserved as fragments quoted in later texts.",
"Five_Phases": "The Five Phases 五行, or wuxing, are the five agents of Chinese cosmology: wood, fire, earth, metal, and water. Conceived as dynamic processes rather than fixed substances, they were thought to generate and overcome one another in fixed cycles and were correlated with the directions, seasons, colors, and bodily organs. Chinese thought drew on these cycles to explain change, cosmology, and medicine, a scheme systematized in the third century BCE and dominant through the Han dynasty.",
"Flame_Emperor": "The Flame Emperor, or Yan Emperor, is a legendary ruler of prehistoric China remembered as a tribal ancestor of the Chinese people. He is frequently identified with Shennong, the Divine Farmer, and is associated in tradition with the mastery of fire, farming, and pottery. Paired with the Yellow Emperor, he is honored as a joint progenitor of the Huaxia, the ancestral stock of the Han Chinese.",
"Ao_(turtle)": "Ao (鰲) is a colossal sea turtle of Chinese mythology said to have lived in the eastern seas at the time of the world's formation. In the legend of Nüwa mending the heavens, the goddess severed the turtle's four legs and set them up as pillars to prop up the corners of the sky after Gonggong toppled the mountain that had supported it. In another tradition Ao is said to live on, bearing the three sacred isles of the immortals upon its back.",
"Gonggong": "Gonggong (共工) is a water god of Chinese mythology, often depicted with a human head and the body of a serpent and blamed for floods and cosmic disasters. After losing a struggle with the fire god Zhurong, he is said in legend to have smashed his head against Mount Buzhou, one of the pillars holding up the sky, tilting the heavens to the northwest and the earth to the southeast. The damage from this collision is the catastrophe that the goddess Nüwa is said to have repaired.",
"Hebei": "A northern Chinese province lying largely on the North China Plain and entirely surrounding the municipalities of Beijing and Tianjin. It was the territory of the states of Yan and Zhao in the Spring and Autumn and Warring States periods and was later administered as Zhili under the Ming and Qing before being renamed Hebei. Sitting on the Yellow River plain, it has been a heartland of early Chinese history.",
"Hmong_(people)": "An ethnic group of the mountainous regions of southern China and mainland Southeast Asia, counted as one of the largest subgroups within the Miao. Most still live in the southern Chinese provinces, while since the late eighteenth century many have migrated into northern Vietnam, Laos, Thailand, and Myanmar. They speak Hmong, one of the Hmong-Mien languages.",
"Huainanzi": "The Huainanzi (淮南子) is a major early Western Han philosophical compendium compiled under the patronage of Liu An, prince of Huainan, and presented to Emperor Wu around 139 BCE. Its twenty-one chapters draw together Daoist, cosmological, Confucian, and Legalist thought into a synthesis on the cosmos, governance, and the cultivation of the ruler. It is also an important repository of early myth and is generally regarded as the work of scholars at Liu An's court rather than of Liu An alone.",
"Huang-Lao_school": "An early Han school of thought (黃老) that paired the legendary Yellow Emperor with Laozi, treating the former as the ruler who first applied the principles of government and the latter as the master who set them forth. A syncretic and politically influential form of Daoism, it was the dominant current of the early Western Han. It was gradually displaced after Emperor Wu established Confucianism as the official state philosophy.",
"Huaxia": "Huaxia 華夏 is an ancient self-designation of the Chinese, denoting a shared cultural and ethnic identity among the agricultural peoples of the Central Plains along the middle and lower Yellow River. The term, attested in early texts such as the Zuo Zhuan, distinguished these states by their ritual etiquette and dress from the surrounding peoples they called the Four Barbarians. Huaxia is regarded as the forerunner of later Han Chinese identity.",
"Miao_(people)": "A group of linguistically related ethnic minorities living mainly in the mountains of southern China, including Guizhou, Yunnan, Hunan, and neighboring provinces. By legend they descend from the Nine Li tribal alliance led by Chiyou, who was defeated by the Yellow Emperor and whose followers migrated south. The official Chinese category Miao encompasses several subgroups, among them the Hmong.",
"Mount_Buzhou": "Mount Buzhou 不周山 is a mythical pillar-mountain that, in early Chinese cosmology, stood in the northwest and helped hold up the sky. According to the legend recorded in the Huainanzi and other texts, the water god Gonggong smashed his head against it in a fit of rage, breaking the pillar and tilting the heavens toward the northwest and the earth toward the southeast. The damage is said to explain why the sun, moon, and stars drift to the northwest and why China's rivers flow to the southeast, and it is the disaster the goddess Nüwa later mended.",
"Nine_Li_tribes": "The Nine Li 九黎, or Jiuli, were an ancient tribal confederation led by Chiyou and remembered in Chinese tradition as the rivals of the Yellow Emperor. Legend holds that they were defeated at the Battle of Zhuolu, after which Chiyou was killed and the confederation broke apart. Some southern peoples, including the Miao and Hmong, regard the Jiuli as an ancestral kingdom.",
"Qibo": "Qibo is a legendary physician and minister of the Yellow Emperor in Chinese tradition. He serves as the Emperor's chief interlocutor in the Huangdi Neijing, the Canon of the Yellow Emperor, answering the ruler's questions on medical theory and practice in its question-and-answer dialogues. Through this foundational classic he is traditionally honored as a founder of Chinese medical theory.",
"Qin_Shi_Huang": "The king of Qin who in 221 BCE completed the conquest of the warring states and proclaimed himself the first emperor of a unified China. With his minister Li Si he standardized the written script, weights, measures, and axle widths, imposing a single administrative order across the realm. He also linked and extended earlier frontier defenses into early sections of the Great Wall.",
"Shennong": "Shennong, the Divine Farmer, is a legendary culture hero often counted among the Three Sovereigns of prehistoric China. He is credited in tradition with inventing agriculture and the plough and with founding herbal medicine, said to have tasted hundreds of plants to discover their healing and poisonous properties. He is frequently identified with the Flame Emperor, the Yan Emperor, and is venerated as a patron of farmers and healers.",
"Tianwen": "The Heavenly Questions (天問) is a poem in the Chuci anthology that poses some 170 enigmatic riddles about cosmogony, mythology, and the deeds of gods and ancient kings, traditionally attributed to the Warring States poet Qu Yuan. Composed of roughly 370 mostly four-syllable lines, it ranges over the origin of heaven and earth, divine and legendary beings, and the rise and fall of dynasties. It survives as one of the richest single sources for the myths and legends of early China.",
"Yinglong": "Yinglong (應龍), the responsive dragon, is a winged dragon and rain deity of Chinese mythology. In legend he aided the Yellow Emperor in the war against Chiyou, attacking from the sky and gathering the waters, and he is associated with rain, rivers, and the control of floods. Later tradition tells of him helping Yu the Great tame the Great Flood by tracing the courses of drainage channels with his tail.",
"Abraham": "The patriarch revered as a founding father of Judaism, Christianity, and Islam, who in scripture enters into a covenant with the one God. In the biblical and Quranic narratives he is promised numerous descendants and is regarded by these traditions as an exemplar of faith in one God. He is a traditional and largely legendary figure, and most scholars hold that the patriarchal accounts cannot be tied to a firm historical date.",
"Baha'i": "A monotheistic religion founded by Baháʼu'lláh in 19th-century Persia, who in 1863 announced his claim to be a messenger of God. It teaches the spiritual unity of humanity and the essential oneness of the major religions, which it views as stages of a single progressive revelation. Its other central figures are the Báb, regarded as its herald, and ʻAbdu'l-Bahá, the son and appointed interpreter of Baháʼu'lláh.",
"Divination": "The practice of seeking knowledge of the future or of hidden things through the reading of omens, ritual, or supposed supernatural means. Its methods range widely across cultures, from interpreting natural signs to consulting texts such as the I Ching or inscribed oracle bones. Diviners are held to draw insight from signs, spirits, or the will of unseen powers, often to guide practical and political decisions.",
"Divine_Farmer's_Materia_Medica": "The foundational Chinese pharmacological classic 神農本草經, traditionally attributed to the legendary culture hero Shennong, the Divine Farmer, though scholars hold it was compiled from older oral traditions in the Eastern Han period. It catalogues 365 medicinal substances drawn from plants, animals, and minerals, ranked in three grades by potency and toxicity. As the earliest surviving Chinese materia medica, it became a cornerstone of traditional Chinese medicine and shaped the pharmacological texts that followed.",
"Druze": "An esoteric ethnoreligious group of the Levant whose faith grew out of Ismaili Islam in 11th-century Fatimid Egypt but incorporates other philosophical and religious traditions. Its followers, who call themselves al-Muwahhidun, form a closed and endogamous community that does not accept converts and reserves its inner teachings for an initiated class. Most Druze live in Syria, Lebanon, and Israel, with diaspora communities elsewhere.",
"Dynasty": "A sequence of rulers drawn from the same family or line, succeeding one another usually by inheritance. By extension the word also names the era during which that family held power. Historians commonly periodize the past of many states and civilizations into a framework of successive dynasties.",
"Eastern_Zhou": "The later part of the Zhou dynasty, beginning when the court fled the sacked western capital and re-established itself at Chengzhou near modern Luoyang. It was an age of steadily declining royal authority in which the Zhou kings reigned in name while powerful regional states held real power. It encompasses both the Spring and Autumn period and the Warring States period, ending when Qin extinguished the Zhou royal house in 256 BCE.",
"Great_Flood_(China)": "The great deluge of Chinese mythology, a flood said to have swept the land for generations until it was finally tamed. Gun first tried to dam the waters and failed, after which his son Yu the Great succeeded by dredging channels to drain the flood to the sea. The feat is said to have won Yu the throne and founded the Xia, traditionally counted as the first Chinese dynasty.",
"Islam": "The monotheistic, Abrahamic religion that teaches submission to the one God and the absolute oneness of God, known as tawhid. Muslims hold that it is founded on revelations received by the Prophet Muhammad in 7th-century Arabia, beginning around 610 CE and recorded in the Quran. Its core duties are framed as the Five Pillars, and its largest branches are Sunni and Shia Islam.",
"Judaism": "The monotheistic, Abrahamic religion and way of life of the Jewish people, counted among the oldest monotheistic faiths and traditionally traced back to the patriarch Abraham. In Jewish tradition it centres on a covenant between God and the Jewish people, renewed with Moses at Mount Sinai and expressed through observance of the Torah. Its teachings and law are elaborated in rabbinic works such as the Mishnah and Talmud, and practised today across movements including Orthodox, Conservative, and Reform.",
"Samaritanism": "The Abrahamic, monotheistic religion of the Samaritans, an ancient tradition closely related to Judaism that traces its roots to the Israelites of the northern Kingdom of Israel. It is centred on Mount Gerizim, which Samaritans hold to be the chosen holy place rather than Jerusalem, and it recognises only the Samaritan Pentateuch as scripture. Today it is practised by a very small community led by a high priest of the Aaronite line.",
"Shang_dynasty": "The earliest Chinese dynasty firmly confirmed by archaeology and by contemporary writing, ruling the Yellow River valley of the North China Plain. Its kings are documented by the oracle bones, inscribed turtle shells and ox bones used in divination that carry the oldest known Chinese script. Excavations at its late capital of Yinxu near Anyang have yielded royal tombs, bronzes, and the records that establish it as historical.",
"Warring_States_period": "The era of seven great rival states that contended for supremacy after the Spring and Autumn period, marked by intense warfare and shifting alliances among Qin, Chu, Qi, Yan, Zhao, Wei, and Han. It nominally fell within the late Eastern Zhou, though the Zhou kings held almost no real power, and it ended when the state of Qin conquered its rivals to unify China in 221 BCE. It was also the great age of the Hundred Schools of Thought, when Confucianism, Mohism, Legalism, and Daoism took shape.",
"Western_Zhou": "The first part of the Zhou dynasty, when royal power was at its height and the court ruled from its capital at Fenghao in the Wei River valley near modern Xi'an. Its kings governed through a network of kinsmen and allies granted regional fiefs, an order later idealized by Confucian thinkers. It ended in 771 BCE when the Quanrong sacked the capital and killed King You, forcing the surviving court to flee east and beginning the Eastern Zhou.",
"Xia_dynasty": "The first dynasty in traditional Chinese historiography, said to have been founded by Yu the Great after he tamed the floods of the Yellow River. Its historicity is debated, as it is known only from much later texts such as the Records of the Grand Historian rather than any contemporary records, and the link to the Bronze Age Erlitou culture remains unproven. Many scholars therefore treat it as semi-legendary, marking the boundary between Chinese myth and documented history.",
"Yanhuang_confederation": "The legendary tribal alliance 炎黃 said to have formed when the people of the Yellow Emperor merged with those of the Yan, or Flame, Emperor in the middle Yellow River basin. In myth their union, sealed by victory over the rival Jiuli tribes, gave rise to the Huaxia and so to the Chinese people, who still call themselves descendants of Yan and Huang. It is remembered as a foundational origin story of Chinese civilization rather than a documented historical state.",
"Zhou_dynasty": "The long-lived dynasty that followed the Shang and endured longer than any other in Chinese history, ruling much of the Yellow River region. Under it the doctrine of the Mandate of Heaven took shape to justify its overthrow of the Shang, and the classic schools of Chinese philosophy emerged in its later centuries. It is divided into the Western Zhou, when royal power was strong, and the Eastern Zhou, when authority passed to contending regional states.",
"Afghanistan": "Afghanistan is a landlocked country in South-Central Asia, bordered by Pakistan, Iran, Turkmenistan, Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, and China. Its capital and largest city is Kabul, and the rugged Hindu Kush mountain range dominates the country's center. Long a crossroads of empires along the Silk Road, it has endured prolonged conflict and came under Taliban control in 2021.",
"Albania": "Albania is a country in Southeastern Europe on the Balkan Peninsula, fronting the Adriatic and Ionian Seas. Its capital and largest city is Tirana, and much of the interior is mountainous. After decades of isolationist communist rule under Enver Hoxha, it transitioned to a multiparty democracy in the early 1990s.",
"Algeria": "Algeria is a country in North Africa along the Mediterranean coast, and is the largest country in Africa by land area. Its capital and largest city is Algiers, while the vast Sahara Desert covers most of its southern interior. A former French colony, it gained independence in 1962 after a protracted war and is a major oil and natural gas producer.",
"Andorra": "Andorra is a small landlocked microstate in the eastern Pyrenees mountains of southwestern Europe, bordered by France and Spain. Its capital, Andorra la Vella, is the highest capital city in Europe by elevation. The principality is unusual in having two co-princes as joint heads of state, the President of France and the Bishop of Urgell.",
"Angola": "Angola is a country on the Atlantic coast of southern-central Africa, bordered by Namibia, Zambia, and the Democratic Republic of the Congo. Its capital and largest city is Luanda, and the oil-rich Cabinda exclave lies separated from the rest of the country. A former Portuguese colony, it became independent in 1975 and then endured a long civil war that ended in 2002.",
"Antigua_and_Barbuda": "Antigua and Barbuda is a twin-island country in the Lesser Antilles of the eastern Caribbean Sea, at the southern end of the Leeward Islands. Its capital and largest city is Saint John's, on the island of Antigua, and tourism drives the economy. Formerly a British colony, it gained independence in 1981 and remains a Commonwealth realm.",
"Argentina": "Argentina is a country in the southern part of South America, the second-largest country on the continent after Brazil. Its capital and largest city is Buenos Aires, and its terrain ranges from the Andes Mountains in the west to the Pampas grasslands and Patagonia in the south. It gained independence from Spain in 1816 and is known for beef production, tango, and football.",
"Armenia": "Armenia is a landlocked country in the South Caucasus region of Eurasia, bordered by Turkey, Georgia, Azerbaijan, and Iran. Its capital and largest city is Yerevan, and the country is mountainous and highland in character. It was the first state to adopt Christianity as its official religion in the early fourth century.",
"Australia": "Australia is a country and continent in the Southern Hemisphere, comprising the Australian mainland, Tasmania, and numerous smaller islands. Its capital is Canberra, while Sydney and Melbourne are its largest cities, and much of the interior is arid outback. Originally inhabited by Aboriginal peoples for tens of thousands of years, it was colonized by Britain from 1788 and federated as a nation in 1901.",
"Austria": "Austria is a landlocked country in Central Europe, bordered by Germany, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Hungary, Slovenia, Italy, Switzerland, and Liechtenstein. Its capital and largest city is Vienna, and the Alps cover much of its western and southern territory. Once the heart of the Habsburg Empire, it is now a neutral federal republic and a member of the European Union.",
"Azerbaijan": "Azerbaijan is a country in the South Caucasus region at the boundary of Eastern Europe and West Asia, on the western shore of the Caspian Sea. Its capital and largest city is Baku, a major center of oil and gas production. Formerly part of the Soviet Union, it regained independence in 1991.",
"The_Bahamas": "The Bahamas is an island country in the West Indies, an archipelago of hundreds of islands and cays in the Atlantic Ocean north of Cuba and southeast of Florida. Its capital and largest city is Nassau, on the island of New Providence, and the economy relies heavily on tourism and offshore finance. Formerly a British colony, it became independent in 1973 and remains a Commonwealth realm.",
"Bahrain": "Bahrain is an island country in the Persian Gulf in West Asia, an archipelago centered on Bahrain Island and connected to Saudi Arabia by the King Fahd Causeway. Its capital and largest city is Manama, and it was among the first Gulf states to discover oil. It is ruled by the Al Khalifa dynasty as a constitutional monarchy.",
"Bangladesh": "Bangladesh is a country in South Asia, bordered by India on most sides and Myanmar to the southeast, with a coastline on the Bay of Bengal. Its capital and largest city is Dhaka, and it occupies much of the low-lying Ganges-Brahmaputra delta, making it prone to flooding. It gained independence from Pakistan in 1971 after a liberation war.",
"Barbados": "Barbados is an island country in the Lesser Antilles of the eastern Caribbean, lying outside the main island arc in the western Atlantic. Its capital and largest city is Bridgetown, and the economy is built on tourism and sugar. A former British colony, it became independent in 1966 and a republic in 2021.",
"Belarus": "Belarus is a landlocked country in Eastern Europe, bordered by Russia, Ukraine, Poland, Lithuania, and Latvia. Its capital and largest city is Minsk, and the country is characterized by extensive forests and marshland. Formerly a Soviet republic, it became independent in 1991 and maintains close ties with Russia.",
"Belgium": "Belgium is a country in Western Europe, bordered by the Netherlands, Germany, Luxembourg, and France, with a short North Sea coastline. Its capital and largest city is Brussels, which also hosts the headquarters of the European Union and NATO. The country is divided between Dutch-speaking Flanders and French-speaking Wallonia.",
"Belize": "Belize is a country on the northeastern coast of Central America, bordered by Mexico and Guatemala, with a Caribbean coastline. Its capital is Belmopan, while Belize City is the largest city, and it features the second-largest barrier reef in the world. Formerly British Honduras, it is the only Central American country with English as its official language and became independent in 1981.",
"Benin": "Benin is a country in West Africa, bordered by Togo, Nigeria, Burkina Faso, and Niger, with a short coastline on the Gulf of Guinea. Its official capital is Porto-Novo, while Cotonou is the largest city and seat of government. Formerly the French colony of Dahomey, it became independent in 1960 and was renamed Benin in 1975.",
"Bhutan": "Bhutan is a landlocked country in South Asia, situated in the eastern Himalayas between China and India. Its capital and largest city is Thimphu, and the kingdom is renowned for measuring progress by Gross National Happiness rather than GDP alone. Ruled by the Wangchuck dynasty, it remained largely isolated for much of its history.",
"Bolivia": "Bolivia is a landlocked country in west-central South America, bordered by Brazil, Paraguay, Argentina, Chile, and Peru. It has two capitals: Sucre is the constitutional and judicial seat, while La Paz holds the executive and legislative branches and is the de facto seat of government. Bolivia is home to the Salar de Uyuni, the world's largest salt flat, and to part of Lake Titicaca, the highest navigable lake on Earth.",
"Bosnia_and_Herzegovina": "Bosnia and Herzegovina is a country in the Balkan region of southeastern Europe, bordered by Croatia, Serbia, and Montenegro. Its capital and largest city is Sarajevo, and the state is divided into two main entities, the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina and Republika Srpska. The country declared independence from Yugoslavia in 1992, triggering the Bosnian War that ended with the 1995 Dayton Agreement.",
"Botswana": "Botswana is a landlocked country in Southern Africa, bordered by South Africa, Namibia, Zimbabwe, and Zambia. Its capital and largest city is Gaborone, and much of the country is dominated by the Kalahari Desert. Botswana is known for the Okavango Delta and for being one of the world's largest producers of diamonds.",
"Brazil": "Brazil is the largest country in South America and the fifth-largest in the world by area. Its capital is Brasília, a planned city inaugurated in 1960, while São Paulo is its largest city. Brazil contains most of the Amazon rainforest and is the world's largest Portuguese-speaking nation.",
"Brunei": "Brunei is a small sovereign state on the northern coast of the island of Borneo in Southeast Asia, surrounded on its land borders by Malaysia. Its capital is Bandar Seri Begawan, and the country is an absolute monarchy ruled by the Sultan of Brunei. Brunei gained full independence from the United Kingdom in 1984 and derives much of its wealth from petroleum and natural gas.",
"Bulgaria": "Bulgaria is a country in southeastern Europe on the Balkan Peninsula, bordering Romania, Serbia, North Macedonia, Greece, Turkey, and the Black Sea. Its capital and largest city is Sofia, and the country has been a member of the European Union since 2007. Bulgaria was the first state to use the Cyrillic alphabet, which was developed there in the ninth and tenth centuries.",
"Burkina_Faso": "Burkina Faso is a landlocked country in West Africa, bordered by Mali, Niger, Benin, Togo, Ghana, and Ivory Coast. Its capital and largest city is Ouagadougou, and the country was known as the Republic of Upper Volta until it was renamed in 1984 by president Thomas Sankara. The name means land of incorruptible people, combining words from the Mossi and Dyula languages.",
"Burundi": "Burundi is a landlocked country in the Great Lakes region of East-Central Africa, bordered by Rwanda, Tanzania, and the Democratic Republic of the Congo. Its political capital is Gitega, while Bujumbura, the former capital, remains the largest city and economic center. The country lies on the northeastern shore of Lake Tanganyika and gained independence from Belgium in 1962.",
"Cambodia": "Cambodia is a country in mainland Southeast Asia, bordered by Thailand, Laos, Vietnam, and the Gulf of Thailand. Its capital and largest city is Phnom Penh, and the country was the center of the medieval Khmer Empire. Cambodia is home to Angkor Wat, the largest religious monument in the world.",
"Cameroon": "Cameroon is a country in Central Africa, bordered by Nigeria, Chad, the Central African Republic, Equatorial Guinea, Gabon, the Republic of the Congo, and the Gulf of Guinea. Its political capital is Yaoundé, while Douala is the largest city and main port. Often called Africa in miniature for its geological and cultural diversity, it is officially bilingual in French and English.",
"Canada": "Canada is a country in North America spanning ten provinces and three territories, the second-largest country in the world by total area. Its capital is Ottawa, while Toronto is its largest city, and it shares the world's longest international land border with the United States. Canada is a federal parliamentary democracy and is officially bilingual in English and French.",
"Cape_Verde": "Cape Verde is an archipelago nation of ten volcanic islands in the central Atlantic Ocean, about 570 kilometers off the western coast of Africa. Its capital is Praia, located on the largest island, Santiago. A former Portuguese colony, it gained independence in 1975 and has Portuguese-based Creole as a widely spoken language.",
"Central_African_Republic": "The Central African Republic is a landlocked country in Central Africa, bordered by Chad, Sudan, South Sudan, the Democratic Republic of the Congo, the Republic of the Congo, and Cameroon. Its capital and largest city is Bangui, situated on the Ubangi River. A former French colony, it gained independence in 1960 and is rich in natural resources including diamonds, gold, and uranium.",
"Chad": "Chad is a landlocked country in north-central Africa, bordered by Libya, Sudan, the Central African Republic, Cameroon, Nigeria, and Niger. Its capital and largest city is N'Djamena, and it is the fifth-largest country in Africa by area. The country takes its name from Lake Chad, a major freshwater lake on its western border that has shrunk dramatically since the 1960s.",
"Chile": "Chile is a long, narrow country occupying a strip of land between the Andes mountains and the Pacific Ocean on the western edge of South America. Its capital and largest city is Santiago, and it borders Peru, Bolivia, and Argentina. Chile contains the Atacama Desert, the driest nonpolar desert on Earth, and is one of the world's leading copper producers.",
"Colombia": "Colombia is a country in northwestern South America, with coastlines on both the Caribbean Sea and the Pacific Ocean. Its capital and largest city is Bogotá, and it borders Venezuela, Brazil, Peru, Ecuador, and Panama. Colombia is one of the most biodiverse countries in the world and is a leading global producer of coffee and emeralds.",
"Comoros": "Comoros is an archipelago nation in the Indian Ocean, situated in the Mozambique Channel between Madagascar and the coast of southeastern Africa. Its capital is Moroni, on the largest island, Grande Comore. The country gained independence from France in 1975 and has experienced numerous coups since then.",
"Republic_of_the_Congo": "The Republic of the Congo is a country on the western coast of Central Africa, bordered by Gabon, Cameroon, the Central African Republic, the Democratic Republic of the Congo, the Angolan exclave of Cabinda, and the Atlantic Ocean. Its capital and largest city is Brazzaville, which sits on the Congo River across from Kinshasa. A former French colony, it gained independence in 1960 and relies heavily on petroleum exports.",
"Costa_Rica": "Costa Rica is a country in Central America bordered by Nicaragua to the north, Panama to the south, the Caribbean Sea to the east, and the Pacific Ocean to the west. Its capital and largest city is San Jose, located in the temperate Central Valley highlands. The country is noted for abolishing its standing army in 1948 and for its extensive system of protected national parks and biodiversity.",
"Croatia": "Croatia is a country in Central and Southeast Europe on the coast of the Adriatic Sea. Its capital and largest city is Zagreb, situated inland on the Sava River below Medvednica hill. The crescent-shaped country has a deeply indented coastline studded with over a thousand islands and joined the European Union in 2013.",
"Cuba": "Cuba is an island country in the northern Caribbean, the largest island in the region by area. Its capital and largest city is Havana, founded by Spain in the early sixteenth century and long the country's chief port. A Spanish colony until 1898, Cuba became a one-party socialist state following the 1959 revolution led by Fidel Castro.",
"Cyprus": "Cyprus is an island country in the eastern Mediterranean Sea, the third largest Mediterranean island after Sicily and Sardinia. Its capital and largest city is Nicosia, which remains divided between the Republic of Cyprus and the Turkish-occupied north. The island has been split since Turkey's 1974 invasion, and the republic joined the European Union in 2004.",
"Czech_Republic": "The Czech Republic, also called Czechia, is a landlocked country in Central Europe bordered by Germany, Austria, Poland, and Slovakia. Its capital and largest city is Prague, situated on the Vltava River and known for its Gothic and Baroque architecture. Comprising the historic lands of Bohemia, Moravia, and Czech Silesia, it emerged as an independent state when Czechoslovakia dissolved in 1993.",
"Democratic_Republic_of_the_Congo": "The Democratic Republic of the Congo is a country in Central Africa and the second-largest country in Africa by area. Its capital and largest city is Kinshasa, which lies on the Congo River opposite Brazzaville. Formerly known as Zaire, it holds vast mineral wealth, including major reserves of cobalt and copper.",
"Djibouti": "Djibouti is a small country on the northeast coast of the Horn of Africa, bordering Eritrea, Ethiopia, and Somalia. Its capital and largest city, also named Djibouti, hosts a major deepwater port at the southern entrance to the Red Sea. The country sits beside the strategic Bab-el-Mandeb strait and gained independence from France in 1977.",
"Dominica": "Dominica is an island country in the Lesser Antilles of the eastern Caribbean, lying between Guadeloupe and Martinique. Its capital and largest town is Roseau, on the southwestern coast at the mouth of the Roseau River. The mountainous, heavily forested island is known as the Nature Island of the Caribbean and gained independence from the United Kingdom in 1978.",
"Dominican_Republic": "The Dominican Republic is a country occupying the eastern five-eighths of the Caribbean island of Hispaniola, which it shares with Haiti to the west. Its capital and largest city is Santo Domingo, founded by Spain in 1496 and the oldest continuously inhabited European settlement in the Americas. It is the second-largest country in the Caribbean by area after Cuba.",
"East_Timor": "East Timor, officially Timor-Leste, is a country in Southeast Asia occupying the eastern half of the island of Timor along with the Oecusse exclave and nearby islands. Its capital and largest city is Dili, on the north coast. A Portuguese colony until 1975 and then occupied by Indonesia, it restored its independence in 2002.",
"Ecuador": "Ecuador is a country in northwestern South America bordered by Colombia, Peru, and the Pacific Ocean, and crossed by the equator from which it takes its name. Its capital is Quito, a high Andean city, while Guayaquil is the largest city. Ecuador also governs the Galapagos Islands, lying about 1,000 kilometres off its Pacific coast.",
"El_Salvador": "El Salvador is the smallest and most densely populated country in Central America, bordered by Guatemala, Honduras, and the Pacific Ocean. Its capital and largest city is San Salvador, a financial and industrial centre founded in the sixteenth century. It is the only Central American country with no Caribbean coastline and is known for its volcanoes and frequent earthquakes.",
"Equatorial_Guinea": "Equatorial Guinea is a country on the west coast of Central Africa, comprising the mainland region of Rio Muni and several islands including Bioko. Its long-established capital is Malabo, on Bioko Island, though a planned inland city, Ciudad de la Paz, has been designated to take over the role. It is the only sovereign African state where Spanish is an official language and its economy depends heavily on offshore oil.",
"Eritrea": "Eritrea is a country in the Horn of Africa with a long coastline along the Red Sea, bordered by Sudan, Ethiopia, and Djibouti. Its capital and largest city is Asmara, noted for its well-preserved Italian colonial modernist architecture and recognized as a UNESCO World Heritage Site. After a thirty-year war of independence, Eritrea separated from Ethiopia in 1993.",
"Estonia": "Estonia is a country in the Baltic region of Northern Europe, bordered by the Gulf of Finland, the Baltic Sea, Latvia, and Russia. Its capital and largest city is Tallinn, a port on the Gulf of Finland known for its well-preserved medieval old town. Independent after the collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991, Estonia joined the European Union and NATO in 2004 and is recognized as a digital and technology hub.",
"Eswatini": "Eswatini is a small landlocked country in Southern Africa, bordered by South Africa and Mozambique. Mbabane is its administrative capital, while Lobamba serves as the royal and legislative capital. Known as Swaziland until it was renamed in 2018, it is one of the world's few remaining absolute monarchies.",
"Ethiopia": "Ethiopia is a landlocked country in the Horn of Africa, the most populous landlocked nation in the world. Its capital and largest city is Addis Ababa, which also hosts the headquarters of the African Union. One of the world's oldest states, Ethiopia was never formally colonized and became landlocked after Eritrea's secession in 1993.",
"Fiji": "Fiji is an archipelagic country in Melanesia in the South Pacific Ocean, made up of more than three hundred islands of which about a hundred are inhabited. Its capital and largest city is Suva, on the island of Viti Levu, which holds most of the population. Most Fijians live on the two main islands of Viti Levu and Vanua Levu, and the country gained independence from the United Kingdom in 1970.",
"Finland": "Finland is a Nordic country in Northern Europe bordered by Sweden, Norway, and Russia, with the Gulf of Bothnia and Gulf of Finland to its west and south. Its capital and largest city is Helsinki, on the southern coast and the most northerly capital on the European mainland. Heavily forested and dotted with over 180,000 lakes, Finland is often called the land of a thousand lakes and joined NATO in 2023.",
"France": "France is a country primarily in Western Europe, the largest by area in the European Union, sharing borders with Belgium, Germany, Switzerland, Italy, Spain, and several other states. Its capital and largest city is Paris, a leading global centre of culture and commerce on the Seine. France also holds numerous overseas regions and territories worldwide, giving it one of the largest exclusive economic zones on Earth.",
"Gabon": "Gabon is a country on the Atlantic coast of Central Africa, straddling the equator. Its capital is Libreville, and the country derives most of its export revenue from petroleum. Nearly 90 percent of its territory is forested, supporting populations of forest elephants and gorillas.",
"The_Gambia": "The Gambia is a country in West Africa surrounding the lower course of the Gambia River and bordered by Senegal on all sides except its short Atlantic coast. Its capital is Banjul, situated on an island at the river mouth. It is the smallest country on the African mainland.",
"Georgia_(country)": "Georgia is a country in the Caucasus region at the junction of Eastern Europe and West Asia, on the eastern shore of the Black Sea. Its capital and largest city is Tbilisi. It is home to some of the world's earliest known sites of winemaking, dating back roughly 8,000 years.",
"Germany": "Germany is a country in Western and Central Europe lying between the Baltic and North seas to the north and the Alps to the south. Its capital and largest city is Berlin. It is the most populous member state of the European Union and has the largest national economy in Europe.",
"Ghana": "Ghana is a country in West Africa along the Gulf of Guinea, bordered by Ivory Coast, Burkina Faso, and Togo. Its capital and largest city is Accra. In 1957 it became the first sub-Saharan African colony to gain independence from European rule.",
"Grenada": "Grenada is an island country in the eastern Caribbean Sea, the southernmost of the Windward Islands, lying north of Trinidad. Its capital is St. George's. Known as the Island of Spice, it is a leading producer of nutmeg and mace.",
"Guatemala": "Guatemala is a country in northern Central America bordered by Mexico, Belize, Honduras, El Salvador, and the Pacific Ocean. Its capital and largest city is Guatemala City. It formed part of the heartland of the ancient Maya civilization and is the most populous country in Central America.",
"Guinea-Bissau": "Guinea-Bissau is a country in West Africa bordered by Senegal to the north, Guinea to the southeast, and the Atlantic Ocean to the west. Its capital is Bissau, and the offshore Bijagos Archipelago forms part of its territory. Formerly the colony of Portuguese Guinea, it relies heavily on cashew nut exports.",
"Guinea": "Guinea is a country on the Atlantic coast of West Africa, bordered by Guinea-Bissau, Senegal, Mali, Ivory Coast, Sierra Leone, and Liberia. Its capital and largest city is Conakry. It holds some of the world's largest bauxite reserves, and its highlands are the source of the Niger, Gambia, and Senegal rivers.",
"Guyana": "Guyana is a country on the northern Atlantic coast of South America, bordered by Suriname, Brazil, and Venezuela. Its capital and largest city is Georgetown, and it is the only South American country with English as its official language. Culturally tied to the Caribbean, it has seen rapid economic growth since major offshore oil discoveries in 2015.",
"Haiti": "Haiti is a Caribbean country occupying the western third of the island of Hispaniola, which it shares with the Dominican Republic. Its capital and largest city is Port-au-Prince. Established through the Haitian Revolution of 1791 to 1804, it became the first country in the Americas to abolish slavery and the only state founded by a successful slave revolt.",
"Honduras": "Honduras is a country in Central America bordered by Guatemala, El Salvador, Nicaragua, the Caribbean Sea, and the Pacific Ocean. Its capital and largest city is Tegucigalpa. The ancient Maya city of Copan, near its western border, is among the most important archaeological sites in the region.",
"Hungary": "Hungary is a landlocked country in Central Europe spanning much of the Carpathian Basin within the Danube's drainage area. Its capital and largest city is Budapest. Its population is mostly ethnic Hungarians, whose Magyar language is one of the few in Europe outside the Indo-European family.",
"Iceland": "Iceland is a Nordic island country in the North Atlantic, lying on the Mid-Atlantic Ridge between Europe and North America. Its capital and largest city is Reykjavik. It is the most sparsely populated country in Europe and is highly volcanically active, drawing most of its heat and electricity from geothermal and hydroelectric power.",
"India": "India is a country in South Asia bordered by the Indian Ocean, the Arabian Sea, and the Bay of Bengal, and is the seventh-largest country by area. Its capital is New Delhi. It is the most populous country in the world and the world's most populous democracy.",
"Indonesia": "Indonesia is a country in Southeast Asia and Oceania comprising over 17,000 islands between the Indian and Pacific oceans, making it the world's largest archipelagic state. Its capital is Jakarta, though a new capital, Nusantara, is being built on Borneo to take over the role. It is the fourth most populous country and has the largest Muslim population of any nation.",
"Iran": "Iran is a country in West Asia bordered by Iraq, Turkey, the Caspian Sea, and the Persian Gulf. Its capital and largest city is Tehran. Historically known as Persia, it is home to one of the world's oldest continuous major civilizations and holds substantial reserves of oil and natural gas.",
"Iraq": "Iraq is a country in West Asia bordered by Turkey, Iran, Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, Jordan, and Syria. Its capital and largest city is Baghdad. It encompasses ancient Mesopotamia, the land between the Tigris and Euphrates rivers often called the cradle of civilization.",
"Ireland": "Ireland is a country in northwestern Europe occupying roughly five-sixths of the island of Ireland, with the remainder forming Northern Ireland in the United Kingdom. Its capital and largest city is Dublin. Surrounded by the Atlantic Ocean and the Irish Sea, it shares its only land border with Northern Ireland.",
"Israel": "Israel is a country in West Asia, in the Southern Levant on the eastern Mediterranean coast, bordered by Lebanon, Syria, Jordan, and Egypt. Its declared seat of government is Jerusalem, though that status lacks broad international recognition, while Tel Aviv is the main economic center. Israel declared independence in 1948, an event followed by the first Arab-Israeli war.",
"Italy": "Italy is a country in Southern and Western Europe occupying a long peninsula in the central Mediterranean Sea, along with Sicily, Sardinia, and other islands. Its capital is Rome, the historic seat of the Roman Empire and the Roman Catholic Church. Italy holds more UNESCO World Heritage Sites than any other country and is among the most visited nations in the world.",
"Ivory_Coast": "Ivory Coast is a country in West Africa on the Gulf of Guinea, bordered by Guinea, Liberia, Mali, Burkina Faso, and Ghana. Its political capital is Yamoussoukro, while Abidjan is the largest city and economic hub. The country is the world's leading producer and exporter of cocoa beans.",
"Jamaica": "Jamaica is an island country in the Caribbean Sea, part of the Greater Antilles south of Cuba. Its capital and largest city is Kingston, and it gained independence from the United Kingdom in 1962. Jamaica is the birthplace of reggae music and the Rastafari movement.",
"Jordan": "Jordan is a country in West Asia, in the Southern Levant, bordered by Saudi Arabia, Iraq, Syria, Israel, and the West Bank. Its capital and largest city is Amman. Jordan contains the shore of the Dead Sea, whose surface is the lowest land point on Earth, as well as the ancient rock-cut city of Petra.",
"Kazakhstan": "Kazakhstan is a transcontinental country mostly in Central Asia, with a small portion in Eastern Europe, bordered by Russia, China, Kyrgyzstan, Uzbekistan, and Turkmenistan. Its capital is Astana, while Almaty is the largest city. Kazakhstan is the world's largest landlocked country and the ninth-largest country by area.",
"Kenya": "Kenya is a country in East Africa on the Indian Ocean, bordered by Somalia, Ethiopia, South Sudan, Uganda, and Tanzania. Its capital and largest city is Nairobi. Kenya straddles the equator and is noted for the Great Rift Valley and major fossil discoveries documenting human evolution near Lake Turkana.",
"Kiribati": "Kiribati is an island country in the central Pacific Ocean, comprising 32 atolls and the raised coral island of Banaba spread across both Micronesia and Polynesia. Its capital is South Tarawa. Kiribati's islands span all four hemispheres, the only country to do so.",
"Kosovo": "Kosovo is a landlocked territory in Southeast Europe in the central Balkans, bordered by Albania, Montenegro, Serbia, and North Macedonia. Its capital and largest city is Pristina. Kosovo declared independence from Serbia in 2008 and is recognized by many United Nations member states, though Serbia and several others do not recognize it.",
"Kuwait": "Kuwait is a country in West Asia at the northern end of the Persian Gulf, bordered by Iraq and Saudi Arabia. Its capital and largest city is Kuwait City. Kuwait holds some of the world's largest proven oil reserves, and petroleum dominates its high-income economy.",
"Kyrgyzstan": "Kyrgyzstan is a landlocked country in Central Asia, dominated by the Tian Shan mountains and bordered by Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, and China. Its capital and largest city is Bishkek. The country is highly mountainous, with most of its territory lying above one thousand meters in elevation.",
"Laos": "Laos is a landlocked country in mainland Southeast Asia, bordered by Myanmar, China, Vietnam, Cambodia, and Thailand. Its capital and largest city is Vientiane. Heavily bombed during the Vietnam War era, Laos is the only landlocked nation in Southeast Asia and is traversed by the Mekong River.",
"Latvia": "Latvia is a country in Northern Europe in the Baltic region, on the eastern shore of the Baltic Sea, bordered by Estonia, Lithuania, Russia, and Belarus. Its capital and largest city is Riga. One of the three Baltic states, Latvia is heavily forested and regained independence from the Soviet Union in 1991.",
"Lebanon": "Lebanon is a country in West Asia on the eastern Mediterranean coast in the Levant, bordered by Syria and Israel. Its capital and largest city is Beirut. The region was home to the ancient Phoenicians, a maritime people credited with spreading an early alphabet across the Mediterranean.",
"Lesotho": "Lesotho is a landlocked country in Southern Africa, an enclave entirely surrounded by South Africa. Its capital and largest city is Maseru. Lesotho is the only independent state that lies entirely above one thousand meters in elevation, earning it the nickname Kingdom in the Sky.",
"Liberia": "Liberia is a country on the West African coast, bordered by Sierra Leone, Guinea, Ivory Coast, and the Atlantic Ocean. Its capital and largest city is Monrovia, named after US President James Monroe. Founded by freed American slaves, Liberia declared independence in 1847 and is often called Africa's oldest republic.",
"Libya": "Libya is a country in North Africa in the Maghreb, bordering the Mediterranean Sea and bordered by Egypt, Sudan, Chad, Niger, Algeria, and Tunisia. Its capital and largest city is Tripoli. Much of Libya lies within the Sahara Desert, and the country holds large proven oil reserves.",
"Liechtenstein": "Liechtenstein is a landlocked microstate in Central Europe, situated in the Alps between Switzerland and Austria along the Rhine. Its capital is Vaduz, overlooked by Vaduz Castle, the residence of the reigning princely family. The principality is one of the world's smallest countries and a noted financial center with one of the highest GDP per capita.",
"Lithuania": "Lithuania is a country in the Baltic region of northeastern Europe, bordered by Latvia, Belarus, Poland, and the Russian exclave of Kaliningrad. Its capital and largest city is Vilnius, noted for one of Europe's best-preserved baroque old towns and a UNESCO World Heritage designation. The largest of the three Baltic states, it was once the center of the medieval Grand Duchy of Lithuania.",
"Luxembourg": "Luxembourg is a small landlocked country in Western Europe, bordered by Belgium, Germany, and France. Its capital, Luxembourg City, is one of the institutional seats of the European Union and hosts the Court of Justice of the European Union. The world's only remaining sovereign grand duchy, it is a developed economy with among the highest GDP per capita globally.",
"North_Macedonia": "North Macedonia is a landlocked country in the south-central Balkans, bordered by Kosovo, Serbia, Bulgaria, Greece, and Albania. Its capital and largest city is Skopje, which sits on the Vardar River and holds about a quarter of the national population. Formerly the Republic of Macedonia, it adopted its current name in 2019 under an agreement resolving a long dispute with Greece.",
"Madagascar": "Madagascar is an island country in the Indian Ocean off the southeastern coast of Africa, separated from the mainland by the Mozambique Channel. Its capital and largest city is Antananarivo, set on the central highland plateau. It is the world's fourth-largest island and is renowned for biodiversity, with most of its plant and animal species, including lemurs, found nowhere else.",
"Malawi": "Malawi is a landlocked country in southeastern Africa, bordered by Zambia, Tanzania, and Mozambique. Its capital is Lilongwe, designated in 1975, while Blantyre remains the largest commercial center. The country is dominated by Lake Malawi, one of Africa's largest lakes, which covers about a fifth of its territory and is famed for its diversity of fish.",
"Malaysia": "Malaysia is a Southeast Asian federation of thirteen states and three federal territories, split by the South China Sea into Peninsular Malaysia and East Malaysia on Borneo. Its official and royal capital is Kuala Lumpur, while Putrajaya serves as the administrative and judicial center. A constitutional monarchy, it is a multiethnic country with a diverse economy spanning manufacturing, commodities, and services.",
"Maldives": "The Maldives is an archipelagic country in the Indian Ocean, lying southwest of India and Sri Lanka and consisting of around 1,200 coral islands grouped into a chain of atolls. Its capital is Malé, a densely populated island city that is the political and commercial heart of the nation. With an average elevation of about 1.5 meters, it is the world's lowest-lying country and is acutely threatened by rising sea levels.",
"Mali": "Mali is a large landlocked country in West Africa, the eighth-largest on the continent, with more than half its territory lying within the Sahara Desert. Its capital and largest city is Bamako, located on the Niger River in the more populous south. Once the center of powerful medieval empires, it counts the historic trading city of Timbuktu among its UNESCO World Heritage Sites.",
"Malta": "Malta is an island country in the central Mediterranean Sea, an archipelago lying south of Sicily whose three largest islands are Malta, Gozo, and Comino. Its capital is Valletta, built by the Knights of St. John after the Great Siege of 1565 and the smallest capital in the European Union. Maltese and English are the official languages, and the country joined the EU in 2004.",
"Marshall_Islands": "The Marshall Islands is an archipelagic country in the central Pacific Ocean, part of the Micronesia region, made up of coral atolls and islands across the Ratak and Ralik chains. Its capital is Majuro, an atoll that holds roughly half the national population. A former U.S. trust territory, it is associated with the United States under a Compact of Free Association.",
"Mauritania": "Mauritania is a country in the Maghreb region of West Africa, bordered by Western Sahara, Algeria, Mali, and Senegal, with about 90 percent of its land in the Sahara Desert. Its capital and largest city is Nouakchott, a planned coastal city on the Atlantic that grew rapidly after independence. The Islamic Republic spans Arab-Berber and West African cultures and relies on iron ore, fishing, and pastoralism.",
"Mauritius": "Mauritius is an island country in the Indian Ocean off the southeastern coast of Africa, east of Madagascar, and part of the Mascarene Islands along with Rodrigues and Reunion. Its capital and largest city is Port Louis, a major port founded by the French in the 18th century. It was the only known home of the dodo, a flightless bird driven to extinction after the islands were settled.",
"Mexico": "Mexico is a country in southern North America, bordered by the United States to the north and Guatemala and Belize to the southeast, with coasts on the Pacific Ocean and the Gulf of Mexico. Its capital is Mexico City, built on the site of the Aztec capital Tenochtitlan and the most populous city in North America. It is the country with the largest number of native Spanish speakers and a major hub of pre-Columbian and colonial heritage.",
"Federated_States_of_Micronesia": "The Federated States of Micronesia is an island country in the western Pacific Ocean, spread across the Caroline Islands in four states: Yap, Chuuk, Pohnpei, and Kosrae. Its capital is Palikir, on the island of Pohnpei, one of the smallest national capitals in the world. A former U.S. trust territory, it is associated with the United States under a Compact of Free Association.",
"Moldova": "Moldova is a landlocked country in Eastern Europe, bordered by Romania to the west and Ukraine to the north, east, and south. Its capital and largest city is Chisinau, the main cultural and commercial center. A former Soviet republic that gained independence in 1991, it includes the breakaway region of Transnistria along its eastern border.",
"Monaco": "Monaco is a sovereign city-state and microstate on the French Riviera in Western Europe, bordered by France on three sides and the Mediterranean Sea to the south. The principality shares its name with its capital and is the world's second-smallest country and the most densely populated. A constitutional monarchy ruled by the House of Grimaldi, it is known for tourism, its casino at Monte Carlo, and the Monaco Grand Prix.",
"Mongolia": "Mongolia is a landlocked country in East Asia, bordered by Russia to the north and China to the south, and the second-largest landlocked country in the world. Its capital and largest city is Ulaanbaatar, home to about half the population and reputed to be the world's coldest capital. Dominated by steppe, mountains, and the Gobi Desert, it has a deep nomadic heritage and was the heart of the Mongol Empire founded by Genghis Khan.",
"Montenegro": "Montenegro is a country in the western Balkans on the Adriatic Sea, bordered by Croatia, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Serbia, Kosovo, and Albania. Its administrative capital is Podgorica, while Cetinje is the historic and cultural center. It became an independent state in 2006 after a referendum ended its union with Serbia.",
"Morocco": "Morocco is a country in the Maghreb region of North Africa with coastlines on both the Atlantic Ocean and the Mediterranean Sea. Its capital is Rabat, while Casablanca is the largest city and main economic hub. A kingdom shaped by Arab and Berber cultures, it administers the disputed territory of Western Sahara to its south.",
"Mozambique": "Mozambique is a country in southeastern Africa bordering the Indian Ocean, Tanzania, Malawi, Zambia, Zimbabwe, South Africa, and Eswatini. Its capital and largest city is Maputo, a port on the southern coast that anchors the national economy. A former Portuguese colony, Mozambique gained independence in 1975 and Portuguese remains its official language.",
"Namibia": "Namibia is a country in southwestern Africa bordering the Atlantic Ocean, Angola, Zambia, Botswana, and South Africa. Its capital and largest city is Windhoek, located on the central Khomas Highland plateau. Namibia gained independence from South African administration in 1990 and contains the arid Namib Desert along its coast.",
"Nauru": "Nauru is a small island country in the southwestern Pacific Ocean, a raised coral island in Micronesia north of the Solomon Islands. Government offices are located in the Yaren District, though Nauru has no official capital. One of the world's smallest states, its economy was long dominated by phosphate mining that has scarred much of the island interior.",
"Nepal": "Nepal is a landlocked country in South Asia situated mainly in the Himalayas between India and China. Its capital and largest city is Kathmandu, set in a valley near the confluence of the Bagmati and Bishnumati rivers. Nepal contains eight of the world's ten highest peaks, including Mount Everest on its border with Tibet.",
"Netherlands": "The Netherlands is a country in northwestern Europe bordering Germany, Belgium, and the North Sea. Amsterdam is its constitutional capital, while the seat of government and the royal residence are in The Hague. Much of the low-lying country lies below sea level and is protected by an extensive system of dikes and reclaimed land called polders.",
"New_Zealand": "New Zealand is an island country in the southwestern Pacific Ocean made up of two main landmasses, the North and South Islands, plus numerous smaller islands. Its capital is Wellington, at the southern end of the North Island, while Auckland is the largest city. Originally settled by Polynesian Maori, it later became a British colony and is known for its mountainous, varied terrain.",
"Nicaragua": "Nicaragua is a country in Central America bordered by Honduras, Costa Rica, the Caribbean Sea, and the Pacific Ocean. Its capital and largest city is Managua, situated on the southern shore of Lake Managua. It is the largest country in Central America by area and contains Lake Nicaragua, the region's largest lake.",
"Niger": "Niger is a landlocked country in West Africa bordered by Algeria, Libya, Chad, Nigeria, Benin, Burkina Faso, and Mali. Its capital and largest city is Niamey, in the southwest along the Niger River. More than four-fifths of its territory lies within the Sahara Desert, and it is the largest country in West Africa by area.",
"Nigeria": "Nigeria is a country in West Africa bordering Niger, Chad, Cameroon, Benin, and the Atlantic Ocean at the Gulf of Guinea. Its capital is Abuja, a planned city in the centre of the country that replaced Lagos as capital in 1991. The most populous country in Africa, Nigeria has Lagos as its largest city and main commercial centre.",
"North_Korea": "North Korea is a country in East Asia occupying the northern half of the Korean Peninsula, bordering China and Russia to the north and South Korea to the south. Its capital and largest city is Pyongyang. The peninsula was divided after World War II, and the Korean War of 1950 to 1953 ended in an armistice rather than a peace treaty.",
"Oman": "Oman is a country on the southeastern coast of the Arabian Peninsula bordering Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, and Yemen. Its capital and largest city is Muscat, a port on the Gulf of Oman backed by volcanic mountains. Ruled as a sultanate, Oman was historically renowned for its frankincense trade and maritime power across the Indian Ocean.",
"Pakistan": "Pakistan is a country in South Asia bordering India, Afghanistan, Iran, China, and the Arabian Sea. Its capital is Islamabad, a planned city built in the 1960s below the Margalla Hills, while Karachi is the largest city and main port. One of the world's most populous countries, Pakistan was created in 1947 from the partition of British India.",
"Palau": "Palau is an island country in the western Pacific Ocean in the Micronesia region of Oceania, comprising hundreds of islands in the western Caroline Islands. Its capital is Ngerulmud, a small administrative settlement on the largest island, Babeldaob. Formerly administered by the United States, Palau became fully independent in 1994 and is known for its marine biodiversity.",
"Panama": "Panama is a country on the isthmus linking Central and South America, bordered by Costa Rica, Colombia, the Caribbean Sea, and the Pacific Ocean. Its capital and largest city is Panama City, on the Pacific coast near the canal's southern entrance. The Panama Canal, opened in 1914, cuts across the country and links the Atlantic and Pacific Oceans.",
"Papua_New_Guinea": "Papua New Guinea is an island country in Oceania occupying the eastern half of the island of New Guinea and many offshore islands in Melanesia. Its capital and largest city is Port Moresby, on the southeastern coast along the Gulf of Papua. It is one of the world's most linguistically diverse nations, with hundreds of indigenous languages, and gained independence from Australia in 1975.",
"Paraguay": "Paraguay is a landlocked country in south-central South America bordered by Bolivia, Brazil, and Argentina. Its capital and largest city is Asuncion, situated on the Paraguay River near its confluence with the Pilcomayo. Spanish and the indigenous Guarani are both official languages, and the Paraguay River divides the country into eastern and Chaco regions.",
"Peru": "Peru is a country on the Pacific coast of western South America bordered by Ecuador, Colombia, Brazil, Bolivia, and Chile. Its capital and largest city is Lima, founded by Francisco Pizarro in 1535 in the desert coastal plain. The Andes mountains run the length of the country, which was the heartland of the Inca Empire and contains the ruins of Machu Picchu.",
"Philippines": "The Philippines is an archipelagic country in Southeast Asia made up of more than 7,000 islands in the western Pacific Ocean. Its capital is Manila, on the island of Luzon, within the densely populated Metro Manila region. Colonized by Spain and later administered by the United States, it is one of the most populous countries in Southeast Asia and predominantly Roman Catholic.",
"Poland": "Poland is a country in Central Europe bordered by Germany, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Ukraine, Belarus, Lithuania, Russia, and the Baltic Sea. Its capital and largest city is Warsaw, on the Vistula River in the east-central part of the country. A member of the European Union, Poland stretches from the Baltic coast in the north to the Carpathian and Sudetes mountains in the south.",
"Portugal": "Portugal is a country on the Iberian Peninsula in southwestern Europe, bordered by Spain to the north and east and the Atlantic Ocean to the west and south. Its capital and largest city is Lisbon, and the country includes the Atlantic archipelagos of the Azores and Madeira. During the Age of Discovery, Portugal built one of the earliest and longest-lived global maritime empires.",
"Qatar": "Qatar is a country occupying a peninsula on the northeastern coast of the Arabian Peninsula in the Persian Gulf, sharing its sole land border with Saudi Arabia. Its capital and largest city is Doha, and the state is governed as an absolute monarchy by the Al Thani family. Qatar holds vast natural gas reserves and is among the world's wealthiest countries by per capita income.",
"Romania": "Romania is a country in Southeastern Europe at the crossroads of Central and Eastern Europe, bordered by Ukraine, Moldova, Bulgaria, Serbia, and Hungary, with a coastline on the Black Sea. Its capital and largest city is Bucharest, and the Carpathian Mountains and the Danube River dominate its geography. Romania is a member of the European Union and NATO.",
"Russia": "Russia is a transcontinental country spanning Eastern Europe and northern Asia, making it the largest country in the world by land area. Its capital and largest city is Moscow, and it spans eleven time zones while bordering fourteen countries. Russia is a permanent member of the United Nations Security Council and possesses the world's largest stockpile of nuclear weapons.",
"Rwanda": "Rwanda is a landlocked country in the Great Rift Valley region of East-Central Africa, bordered by Uganda, Tanzania, Burundi, and the Democratic Republic of the Congo. Its capital and largest city is Kigali, and its hilly terrain gives it the nickname land of a thousand hills. In 1994 the country suffered a genocide against the Tutsi minority, after which it pursued reconciliation and rapid economic development.",
"Saint_Kitts_and_Nevis": "Saint Kitts and Nevis is an island country in the Leeward Islands of the Lesser Antilles in the Caribbean, comprising the two islands of Saint Kitts and Nevis. Its capital is Basseterre on Saint Kitts, and it is a Commonwealth realm with a constitutional monarchy. It is the smallest sovereign state in the Western Hemisphere by both area and population.",
"Saint_Lucia": "Saint Lucia is an island country in the eastern Caribbean, part of the Windward Islands in the Lesser Antilles, lying north of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines. Its capital and largest city is Castries, a port frequented by cruise ships. The island is known for its twin volcanic peaks, the Pitons, a UNESCO World Heritage Site.",
"Saint_Vincent_and_the_Grenadines": "Saint Vincent and the Grenadines is an archipelagic country in the eastern Caribbean, consisting of the main island of Saint Vincent and a chain of smaller islands in the northern Grenadines. Its capital and largest city is Kingstown, on Saint Vincent, which holds the country's main port and commercial center. The island of Saint Vincent is dominated by the active volcano La Soufrière.",
"Samoa": "Samoa is an island country in Polynesia in the South Pacific Ocean, consisting of two main islands, Savaii and Upolu, and several smaller islands. Its capital and largest city is Apia, located on Upolu. Formerly administered by New Zealand, Samoa gained independence in 1962 and remains a member of the Commonwealth.",
"San_Marino": "San Marino is a microstate in Southern Europe, a landlocked enclave completely surrounded by Italy near the Adriatic coast. Its capital is the City of San Marino, perched atop Monte Titano. It claims to be the world's oldest surviving sovereign state and constitutional republic, traditionally dated to its founding in AD 301.",
"São_Tomé_and_Príncipe": "Sao Tome and Principe is an island country in the Gulf of Guinea off the western coast of Central Africa, consisting of two main islands, Sao Tome and Principe, lying near the Equator. Its capital is Sao Tome, on the larger island. A former Portuguese colony, it is the smallest Portuguese-speaking country and one of the smallest nations in Africa.",
"Saudi_Arabia": "Saudi Arabia is a country occupying most of the Arabian Peninsula in Western Asia, the largest country in the Middle East by land area. Its capital and largest city is Riyadh, and it is an absolute monarchy ruled by the House of Saud. It contains Islam's two holiest cities, Mecca and Medina, and holds some of the world's largest petroleum reserves.",
"Senegal": "Senegal is a country in West Africa on the Atlantic coast, bordered by Mauritania, Mali, Guinea, and Guinea-Bissau, and nearly surrounding The Gambia. Its capital and largest city is Dakar, located on the Cap-Vert peninsula, the westernmost point of continental Africa. A former French colony, Senegal is known for its stable democracy and its musical and cultural heritage.",
"Serbia": "Serbia is a landlocked country in Southeastern Europe at the crossroads of the Balkan Peninsula and the Pannonian Plain, bordered by Hungary, Romania, Bulgaria, North Macedonia, Croatia, Bosnia and Herzegovina, and Montenegro. Its capital and largest city is Belgrade, situated at the confluence of the Sava and Danube rivers. Serbia was a constituent republic of the former Yugoslavia until that federation dissolved.",
"Seychelles": "Seychelles is an island country in the Indian Ocean northeast of Madagascar, an archipelago of around 115 granitic and coral islands. Its capital is Victoria, on the main island of Mahe, and is one of the world's smallest national capitals. With the smallest population of any sovereign African state, its economy relies heavily on tourism and fishing.",
"Sierra_Leone": "Sierra Leone is a country on the southwestern coast of West Africa, bordered by Guinea and Liberia, with a coastline on the Atlantic Ocean. Its capital and largest city is Freetown, founded as a settlement for freed slaves. The country endured a civil war from 1991 to 2002 and holds significant deposits of diamonds and other minerals.",
"Singapore": "Singapore is an island city-state in Southeast Asia, located at the southern tip of the Malay Peninsula off the southern edge of Malaysia. The city of Singapore is both the country and its capital, occupying one main island and numerous smaller islets. A major global financial center and one of the world's busiest ports, it transformed from a British trading colony into a high-income economy after independence in 1965.",
"Slovakia": "Slovakia is a landlocked country in Central Europe, bordered by Poland, Ukraine, Hungary, Austria, and the Czech Republic. Its capital and largest city is Bratislava, on the Danube River near the Austrian and Hungarian borders. It became an independent state in 1993 following the peaceful dissolution of Czechoslovakia and is a member of the European Union and the eurozone.",
"Slovenia": "Slovenia is a country in Central Europe at the junction of the Alps, the Mediterranean, and the Pannonian Plain, bordered by Italy, Austria, Hungary, and Croatia with a short Adriatic coastline. Its capital and largest city is Ljubljana. Formerly a constituent republic of Yugoslavia, it became independent in 1991 and joined the European Union and the eurozone.",
"Solomon_Islands": "Solomon Islands is an archipelagic country in Melanesia in the southwestern Pacific Ocean, lying to the northeast of Australia and east of Papua New Guinea. Its capital and largest city is Honiara, on the island of Guadalcanal. The islands saw major fighting during World War II, including the Guadalcanal campaign, and gained independence from Britain in 1978.",
"Somalia": "Somalia is a country in the Horn of Africa, the easternmost part of the African mainland, bordering Ethiopia, Djibouti, Kenya, the Gulf of Aden, and the Indian Ocean. Its capital and largest city is Mogadishu, an ancient Indian Ocean port and one of the earliest Arab trading settlements on the East African coast. Somalia has the longest coastline of any country on mainland Africa.",
"South_Africa": "South Africa is the southernmost country in Africa, bordering the Atlantic and Indian Oceans and surrounding the kingdom of Lesotho. It uniquely has three capitals, with Pretoria serving the executive branch, Cape Town the legislature, and Bloemfontein the judiciary. The arrangement dates to the 1910 union of former British colonies and Boer republics, and the country ended its apartheid system of racial segregation in the early 1990s.",
"South_Korea": "South Korea is a country in East Asia occupying the southern half of the Korean Peninsula, separated from North Korea by the Korean Demilitarized Zone. Its capital and largest city is Seoul. After rapid post-war industrialization often called the Miracle on the Han River, South Korea became a major developed economy.",
"South_Sudan": "South Sudan is a landlocked country in East-Central Africa, bordering Sudan, Ethiopia, Kenya, Uganda, the Democratic Republic of the Congo, and the Central African Republic. Its capital and largest city is Juba, which sits on the White Nile. It became independent from Sudan on 9 July 2011 following a referendum, making it the world's youngest widely recognized sovereign state.",
"Spain": "Spain is a country in southwestern Europe occupying most of the Iberian Peninsula, bordering Portugal, France, Andorra, and the Mediterranean Sea and Atlantic Ocean. Its capital and largest city is Madrid, located near the centre of the peninsula. Spain built a vast global empire after 1492 and remains the principal source of the Spanish language now spoken across much of the Americas.",
"Sri_Lanka": "Sri Lanka is an island country in South Asia in the Indian Ocean, southeast of India across the Palk Strait. Its official and legislative capital is Sri Jayawardenepura Kotte, while the largest city and commercial centre is the nearby port of Colombo. The island was known as Ceylon until 1972 and is a major producer of tea, cinnamon, and gemstones.",
"Sudan": "Sudan is a country in Northeast Africa bordering Egypt, the Red Sea, Eritrea, Ethiopia, South Sudan, the Central African Republic, Chad, and Libya. Its capital, Khartoum, lies at the confluence of the White Nile and the Blue Nile, which join there to form the main Nile. Once Africa's largest country by area, it lost that distinction when South Sudan seceded in 2011.",
"Suriname": "Suriname is a country on the northeastern coast of South America, bordering Guyana, French Guiana, Brazil, and the Atlantic Ocean. Its capital and largest city is Paramaribo, whose historic inner city is a UNESCO World Heritage Site of Dutch colonial wooden architecture. A former Dutch colony, it is the smallest sovereign state in South America and the only one where Dutch is the official language.",
"Switzerland": "Switzerland is a landlocked country in Central Europe, bordering Germany, France, Italy, Austria, and Liechtenstein, with much of its terrain in the Alps. Bern is its de facto capital and seat of government, though the federation of 26 cantons has no formal constitutional capital. The country is noted for its long-standing policy of armed neutrality and for hosting numerous international organizations.",
"Syria": "Syria is a country in the Levant region of Western Asia, bordering Turkey, Iraq, Jordan, Israel, Lebanon, and the Mediterranean Sea. Its capital, Damascus, is among the oldest continuously inhabited cities in the world and once served as the seat of the Umayyad Caliphate. The country endured a prolonged civil war that began in 2011.",
"Tajikistan": "Tajikistan is a landlocked, mountainous country in Central Asia, bordering Afghanistan, Uzbekistan, Kyrgyzstan, and China. Its capital and largest city is Dushanbe, whose name means Monday in Tajik, a reference to a former weekly market. Much of the country lies above 3,000 metres, dominated by the Pamir Mountains.",
"Tanzania": "Tanzania is a country in East Africa within the African Great Lakes region, bordering several countries and the Indian Ocean. Its official capital is Dodoma in the centre of the country, while Dar es Salaam remains the largest city and commercial hub. It is home to Mount Kilimanjaro, Africa's highest peak, and to Lake Tanganyika and the Serengeti.",
"Thailand": "Thailand is a country in mainland Southeast Asia, bordering Myanmar, Laos, Cambodia, and Malaysia. Its capital and largest city is Bangkok, established as the royal seat in 1782 under the Chakri dynasty. Formerly known as Siam, it was the only Southeast Asian state never colonized by a European power.",
"Togo": "Togo is a narrow country in West Africa, bordering Ghana, Benin, Burkina Faso, and the Gulf of Guinea. Its capital and largest city is Lome, a port on the coast that serves as the country's administrative and commercial centre. Once part of German Togoland, it was later divided between British and French rule before gaining independence from France in 1960.",
"Tonga": "Tonga is a Polynesian island country in the South Pacific Ocean, made up of around 170 islands of which several dozen are inhabited. Its capital, Nukualofa, sits on the main island of Tongatapu. A constitutional monarchy, it is the only Pacific island nation never formally colonized, having retained its own sovereign throughout the colonial era.",
"Trinidad_and_Tobago": "Trinidad and Tobago is a twin-island country in the southern Caribbean, lying just off the northeastern coast of Venezuela. Its capital is Port of Spain, on the northwest coast of the larger island of Trinidad. The nation has an oil- and gas-based economy and is widely regarded as the birthplace of calypso music, the steelpan, and the Carnival celebration.",
"Tunisia": "Tunisia is the northernmost country in Africa, set in the Maghreb region and bordering Algeria, Libya, and the Mediterranean Sea. Its capital and largest city is Tunis, which lies near the ruins of ancient Carthage, once a major power rivalling Rome. Its 2011 Jasmine Revolution toppled the long-ruling president and sparked the wider wave of uprisings known as the Arab Spring.",
"Turkmenistan": "Turkmenistan is a landlocked country in Central Asia, bordering the Caspian Sea to the west and dominated by the Karakum Desert. Its capital and largest city is Ashgabat, known for its dense concentration of white marble buildings. The country holds some of the world's largest natural gas reserves and gained independence from the Soviet Union in 1991.",
"Tuvalu": "Tuvalu is a small island nation in the west-central Pacific Ocean, made up of nine low-lying coral atolls and reef islands. Its capital is Funafuti, where about half of the country's roughly 10,000 people live. One of the world's smallest and least populous countries, it gained independence from the United Kingdom in 1978 and is highly vulnerable to rising sea levels.",
"Uganda": "Uganda is a landlocked country in East Africa, lying within the African Great Lakes region and the Nile basin. Its capital and largest city is Kampala, situated on hills just north of Lake Victoria. The country takes its name from the Buganda kingdom and became independent from the United Kingdom in 1962.",
"Ukraine": "Ukraine is a country in Eastern Europe, the second-largest on the continent by area after Russia. Its capital and largest city is Kyiv, which straddles the Dnieper River and was the center of the medieval state of Kyivan Rus. Ukraine gained independence from the Soviet Union in 1991.",
"United_Arab_Emirates": "The United Arab Emirates is a federation of seven emirates on the eastern Arabian Peninsula in West Asia, bordering the Persian Gulf. Its capital is Abu Dhabi, the largest emirate and center of the oil industry, while Dubai is its most populous city. The federation was formed in 1971 and has become a major hub for trade, finance, and tourism.",
"United_Kingdom": "The United Kingdom is an island country in northwestern Europe made up of four constituent nations: England, Scotland, Wales, and Northern Ireland. Its capital and largest city is London, and it is a constitutional monarchy with a parliamentary system. Once the center of a global empire, it remains a major economic, political, and cultural power.",
"United_States": "The United States is a federal republic of 50 states located primarily in central North America, bordered by Canada and Mexico. Its capital is Washington, D.C., while New York City is its most populous city. It is the world's largest economy and a leading military, scientific, and cultural power.",
"Uruguay": "Uruguay is a country in southeastern South America bordering Argentina, Brazil, and the Atlantic Ocean. Its capital and largest city is Montevideo, a major port on the Rio de la Plata and the southernmost national capital in the Americas. It is the second-smallest country in South America and is known for its rolling grasslands and stable democracy.",
"Uzbekistan": "Uzbekistan is a doubly landlocked country in Central Asia, lying mainly between the Amu Darya and Syr Darya rivers. Its capital and largest city is Tashkent, the most populous city in Central Asia. Home to historic Silk Road cities such as Samarkand and Bukhara, it gained independence from the Soviet Union in 1991.",
"Vanuatu": "Vanuatu is an archipelagic country in Melanesia in the South Pacific Ocean, made up of roughly 80 islands of mostly volcanic origin. Its capital and largest city is Port Vila, located on the island of Efate. Most inhabitants are indigenous Ni-Vanuatu, and the country gained independence from joint British and French rule in 1980.",
"Vatican_City": "Vatican City is a walled city-state enclaved within Rome, Italy, and is the smallest sovereign state in the world by both area and population. It serves as the spiritual and administrative headquarters of the Roman Catholic Church, governed by the pope through the Holy See. It became independent through the Lateran Treaty of 1929 and contains St Peter's Basilica and the Vatican Museums.",
"Venezuela": "Venezuela is a country on the northern coast of South America, bordering the Caribbean Sea and the Atlantic Ocean. Its capital and largest city is Caracas, and its landscape ranges from the Andes and the Orinoco plains to Angel Falls, the world's highest waterfall. The country holds vast proven oil reserves but has experienced severe economic and political crises.",
"Vietnam": "Vietnam is a country at the eastern edge of mainland Southeast Asia, with a long coastline along the South China Sea. Its capital is Hanoi, while Ho Chi Minh City is its largest city, and its terrain features the Red River and Mekong deltas. One of the world's most populous countries, it was reunified under communist rule in 1976 after the Vietnam War.",
"Yemen": "Yemen is a country at the southwestern corner of the Arabian Peninsula, bordering the Red Sea, the Gulf of Aden, and the Arabian Sea. Its constitutional capital is Sanaa, one of the world's oldest continuously inhabited cities, though the seat of government has shifted to Aden amid civil war. The country has been devastated by prolonged armed conflict and humanitarian crisis.",
"Zambia": "Zambia is a landlocked country in south-central Africa, lying on a high plateau and named after the Zambezi River. Its capital and largest city is Lusaka, and Victoria Falls lies on its southern border with Zimbabwe. The country is a major copper producer and gained independence from the United Kingdom in 1964.",
"Zimbabwe": "Zimbabwe is a landlocked country in southeastern Africa, lying between the Zambezi and Limpopo rivers. Its capital and largest city is Harare, formerly known as Salisbury until 1982. The country takes its name from the medieval stone city of Great Zimbabwe and became independent from the United Kingdom in 1980.",
"Alloy": "An alloy is a material made by combining a metal with one or more other elements, at least one of which is usually a metal. Alloying alters the base metal to improve properties such as strength, hardness, or corrosion resistance, as when copper and tin form bronze or iron and carbon form steel. The constituent atoms are held by metallic bonding, yielding a material whose qualities differ markedly from those of its components.",
"Archaeology": "Archaeology is the study of human history and prehistory through the excavation and analysis of material remains. It examines artifacts, architecture, and other physical evidence to understand how past peoples lived. It is especially valuable for prehistoric societies that left no written records.",
"Battle_of_Mingtiao": "The Battle of Mingtiao is the semi-legendary clash in which Tang of Shang defeated the forces of Jie, the last king of the Xia. Tradition holds that Jie's demoralized troops surrendered or fled, and that the rout drove him into exile, ending the Xia dynasty. The victory allowed Tang to take the throne and found the Shang.",
"Bible": "The Bible is the collection of sacred scriptures of Judaism and Christianity. It comprises the Hebrew Bible, known to Christians as the Old Testament, and, for Christians, the New Testament. Different traditions recognize varying numbers of canonical books.",
"Brasília": "Brasília is the planned capital of Brazil, built in the interior highlands of the Central-West region to replace coastal Rio de Janeiro. Constructed in roughly four years and inaugurated on 21 April 1960, it was laid out by urban planner Lúcio Costa with modernist buildings designed by Oscar Niemeyer. Its distinctive architecture and urban plan led UNESCO to inscribe it as a World Heritage Site in 1987.",
"Bronze": "Bronze is an alloy consisting mainly of copper with about a tenth or eighth part tin, harder and more durable than copper alone and easier to cast. Its adoption marked a major technological advance that gave its name to the Bronze Age, when it replaced stone and copper for tools and weapons. Beyond utilitarian implements it was widely worked into weapons, ornaments, and ritual or ceremonial objects, which in many early societies served as prized markers of status and authority.",
"Copper": "Copper is a soft, malleable, reddish-orange metal with very high electrical and thermal conductivity, second only to silver among pure metals. It was among the first metals worked by humans, used as native copper for ornaments and tools before smelting and casting were developed in antiquity. Alloyed with tin it forms bronze, making copper foundational to early metallurgy across many ancient civilizations.",
"Gold": "Gold is a dense, lustrous, bright-yellow precious metal, the most malleable of all metals and highly resistant to corrosion and chemical attack. Its rarity, durability, and inertness made it prized since prehistoric times for ornament, coinage, and as a store of value. It underpinned early monetary systems and remains used in jewelry, investment, and electronics.",
"Gun_(Chinese_mythology)": "Gun is a figure of Chinese legend, remembered as the father of Yu the Great and as the official tasked with controlling the Great Flood. He labored for years to dam and dike the waters, but his barriers failed and the flooding worsened, for which the sage-emperor Shun is said to have had him banished. His son Yu then succeeded him and tamed the flood by dredging channels instead.",
"Heaven": "Heaven, or Tian (天), is the supreme cosmic power of Chinese religion, at once the physical sky and an impersonal yet moral deity that guards the laws of nature and of mankind. As the source of the Mandate of Heaven, it confers and withdraws the right to rule, granting authority to virtuous sovereigns and removing it from unworthy ones. In role it succeeded the Shang high god Shangdi, whose more personal cult the Zhou gradually absorbed into the more abstract notion of Tian.",
"Ink_rubbing": "Ink rubbing is the technique of reproducing the relief of an inscribed or carved surface by laying moistened paper over it, tamping the paper into every depression, and then dabbing it with an inked pad. The carved lines come out white against a black ground, yielding a faithful copy of the original. Long practised in China to record stone inscriptions and pictorial reliefs, it preserved the texts of steles and the carvings of shrines, and many ancient monuments are now known chiefly through such rubbings.",
"Iron_Age": "The Iron Age is the final stage of the three-age system, a prehistoric and protohistoric period defined by the widespread smelting and working of iron and steel for tools and weapons. It followed the Bronze Age, as iron implements gradually replaced bronze ones once techniques for removing impurities and controlling carbon content were mastered. Its onset varies widely by region, beginning near the Bronze Age collapse in the Near East and centuries later in Europe.",
"Jade": "Jade is a hard, tough ornamental stone covering two distinct minerals, the calcium-magnesium amphibole nephrite and the sodium-aluminum pyroxene jadeite, both hard enough to carve into intricate forms. Prized for its toughness, fine polish, and translucent color, it has been carved into ornaments, ritual objects, and tools by many cultures and has at times rivalled or exceeded gold in value. Nephrite and jadeite are sourced from a limited number of deposits worldwide, and worked jade is found among societies in East Asia, Mesoamerica, and elsewhere.",
"Jiaxiang_County": "Jiaxiang County is a county in southwestern Shandong, China, administered under the city of Jining. It is best known for its Han-dynasty funerary monuments, above all the Wu Liang Shrine, whose engraved stone reliefs are a landmark of early Chinese pictorial art. The carvings there are widely studied and are familiar to scholars through ink rubbings.",
"Jie_of_Xia": "Jie is traditionally the seventeenth and last king of the Xia dynasty, remembered as a cruel and dissolute tyrant. Legend charges him with extravagance, brutality toward his ministers, and the misrule that forfeited the loyalty of his people. He was defeated by Tang of Shang and died in exile, ending the Xia and giving rise to the Shang.",
"Legend": "A legend is a traditional story popularly regarded as historical but not authenticated. It is typically set in human history and centers on a notable person or event. Legends are distinguished from myths, which more often concern gods or the supernatural.",
"Luoshu": "The Luoshu (洛書), or Luo River writing, is a mythical diagram in the form of a three-by-three magic square in which the numbers one through nine are arranged so that every row, column, and diagonal sums to fifteen. In Chinese legend it appeared as a pattern of dots on the shell of a turtle that emerged from the Luo River. It was treated as a foundational source of cosmology, numerology, and divination, its arrangement linked to the trigrams of the Yijing and the order of the universe.",
"Monotheism": "Monotheism is the belief in or worship of a single, supreme God. It characterizes the Abrahamic religions of Judaism, Christianity, and Islam. It is distinguished from polytheism, the belief in multiple deities.",
"Nine_Provinces": "The Nine Provinces (九州), or Jiuzhou, are the traditional division of ancient China into nine regions, an early conception of the Chinese realm that came to stand symbolically for the country as a whole. Their creation is attributed to Yu the Great, who is said to have laid out the provinces after taming the great floods. The scheme is recorded in classical texts such as the Tribute of Yu, though the term is absent from the oracle bones and is generally regarded as a later, legendary framework rather than a historical administrative map.",
"Nine_Tripod_Cauldrons": "The Nine Tripod Cauldrons (九鼎), or Jiuding, are nine great bronze ding said in legend to have been cast by Yu the Great from metal collected in tribute from the Nine Provinces. They became enduring symbols of sovereignty and the Mandate of Heaven, passed from the Xia to the Shang and then the Zhou as the visible token of legitimate rule. To inquire after the weight of the cauldrons became a proverbial phrase for harbouring designs on the throne, and their eventual loss is recounted in the early histories.",
"Patriarch": "A patriarch is a male head of a family or tribe who exercises authority over its members. In the Abrahamic tradition the title refers to the revered forefathers of the people of Israel, namely Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob. The term later expanded to denote senior bishops in some Christian churches.",
"Patriarchy": "Patriarchy is a social system in which men hold primary power and predominate in roles of authority, descent, and inheritance. Its name derives from the Greek for rule of the father. Sociologists generally treat it as a historically conditioned social structure rather than a biological inevitability.",
"Portuguese_language": "Portuguese is a Western Romance language of the Indo-European family that originated in the medieval kingdoms of the Iberian Peninsula and developed in Portugal. It has more than 250 million native speakers, making it one of the most widely spoken languages in the world. It is an official language in Portugal, Brazil, and several African nations including Angola, Mozambique, and Cape Verde, as well as in Timor-Leste.",
"Qi_(deity)": "In Chinese mythology Qi, also read Xie (契), is the legendary first ancestor of the Shang royal house, venerated as an ancestral spirit said to have been miraculously born when his mother Jiandi swallowed the egg of a dark bird. Tradition makes him a son of the high god Shangdi and credits him with serving Yu the Great in taming the floods and acting as Minister of Instruction under the sage-king Shun. He is generally treated as a mythic figure rather than a historical one, his cult bound up with the Shang claim to divinely granted rule.",
"Qi_(force)": "Qi (氣) is the vital energy or life-force that, in Chinese thought and medicine, animates all things and flows through them. It is conceived as the primordial breath or material energy whose gathering produces life and whose dispersal ends it, circulating through the body along channels that medicine and acupuncture seek to keep in balance. The same notion underlies cosmology, geomancy, and the cultivation practices of Daoism, in which the unobstructed flow of qi is held to sustain health and harmony.",
"Quran": "The Quran is the central religious text of Islam, believed by Muslims to be the word of God revealed to the Prophet Muhammad. It is organized into 114 chapters, called surahs, made up of individual verses. Muslims regard it as the foremost authority on faith, worship, and conduct.",
"São_Paulo": "São Paulo is the most populous city in Brazil and the largest in the Southern Hemisphere, with a metropolitan area of more than 20 million people. It is the country's financial and industrial centre, generating roughly a tenth of Brazilian GDP and hosting B3, the largest stock exchange in Latin America. The city is one of the world's major financial hubs and the headquarters of most multinational corporations operating in Brazil.",
"Shaokang": "Shaokang is a legendary king of the Xia dynasty, traditionally its sixth ruler, celebrated for the Shaokang Restoration. After the Xia throne was seized by the usurper Han Zhuo, Shaokang was born in exile and grew up in hiding, then gathered support and overthrew the usurpers to reclaim his ancestral throne. His restoration is held up in tradition as a model recovery of a fallen royal house.",
"Shun_(emperor)": "Shun is a legendary sage-emperor of ancient China, traditionally reckoned the last of the Five Emperors. He was revered as a model of filial virtue who rose from humble origins and was chosen to rule for his merit rather than his birth. By tradition he passed over his own son and ceded the throne to Yu the Great, who went on to found the Xia dynasty.",
"Silver": "Silver is a soft, lustrous, whitish-gray precious metal that has the highest electrical and thermal conductivity and reflectivity of any metal. Valued since antiquity, it served as currency across Greek, Roman, and medieval economies and remains widely used in coinage, bullion, and jewelry. Its conductivity and reflectivity also make it important in electronics, mirrors, and other industrial applications.",
"Steel": "Steel is an alloy of iron and carbon, with carbon content up to about two percent, that is far stronger and harder than pure iron. The dissolved carbon resists deformation, though higher carbon makes the metal harder but more brittle, a balance tuned for different uses. Historically reserved for cutting edges of knives, swords, and tools, it is now fundamental to construction, machinery, and weapons.",
"Stone_Age": "The Stone Age is the earliest and by far the longest prehistoric period, the first stage of the three-age system, defined by the manufacture of stone tools before the working of metals. It spans roughly the first 99 percent of human history, beginning with the oldest known stone tools and ending with the advent of metallurgy. Its boundaries vary by region, ending around 4000 to 2000 BCE in different areas as societies entered the Bronze Age or, in parts of Africa, passed directly to iron.",
"Tang_of_Shang": "Tang of Shang is traditionally the first king of the Shang dynasty, said to have overthrown the tyrant Jie, the last ruler of the Xia. By legend he defeated Jie at the Battle of Mingtiao and drove him into exile, bringing the Xia to an end. He is remembered as a benevolent founder whose rise was justified by Jie's misrule.",
"Tin": "Tin is a soft, malleable, silvery-white metal with a notably low melting point, the lowest among its group of elements. Its chief historical importance was as the minor component of bronze, where adding roughly an eighth part tin to copper lowers the melting temperature and yields a denser, more easily cast metal. Beyond bronze it is also used in solders and as a protective plating.",
"Tribute_of_Yu": "The Tribute of Yu (禹貢), or Yu Gong, is a chapter of the Book of Documents that describes Yu the Great's survey of the land after the floods, its division into the Nine Provinces, and the tribute owed by each. It systematically catalogues the soils, products, waterways, and routes of the provinces, making it one of the earliest works of Chinese geography. Though traditionally ascribed to the Xia, most scholars hold that it was compiled much later, probably during the Warring States period.",
"Yao_(emperor)": "Yao is a legendary sage-king of ancient China, counted among the Five Emperors and revered as a paragon of virtuous, selfless rule. Tradition holds that he preceded Shun, instituted a calendar to order the seasons, and confronted the onset of the Great Flood. Rather than passing the throne to his own son, he is said to have abdicated in favor of the worthy Shun.",
"Zhuanxu": "Zhuanxu is a legendary sovereign of ancient China, traditionally counted among the Five Emperors who reigned in the age before the first dynasties. He is held to be a grandson of the Yellow Emperor through his father Changyi, and is credited in tradition with calendar reforms and the suppression of shamanistic practices. Like the other Five Emperors, he belongs to legend rather than verifiable history.",
"Mandate_of_Heaven": "The Mandate of Heaven (天命) is the traditional Chinese doctrine that Heaven grants the right to rule to a just and virtuous sovereign, the Son of Heaven. A ruler who became cruel or incompetent was held to forfeit the Mandate, so that natural disasters, revolts, and a dynasty's fall were read as signs that Heaven had withdrawn its favour and bestowed it on a worthier successor. First invoked by the Zhou to justify their overthrow of the Shang, it remained a central principle of political legitimacy and the dynastic cycle throughout imperial Chinese history.",
"Central_Plains": "The Central Plains (中原), or Zhongyuan, are the lands of the lower and middle Yellow River around modern Henan, the cradle and historic heartland of Chinese civilization. The Huaxia regarded this region, roughly between Luoyang and Kaifeng, as the centre of the world, and more than twenty dynasties placed their capitals there. Control of the Central Plains was long equated with legitimate rule over China as a whole.",
"Primordial": "Primordial means existing from the very beginning, original or primeval, belonging to the earliest stage of the world. In creation myths it describes the formless original state of things and the first beings that arise before the ordered cosmos takes shape. The term is applied across many traditions, from a primordial chaos or void to the primordial beings from whom the world is fashioned.",
"Inheritance": "Inheritance is the passing of property, rights, titles, or possessions from a person to their heirs or successors, usually upon death. By extension it also names biological heredity, the transmission of traits from parents to offspring, and more broadly any legacy handed down from earlier generations. In dynastic and political life it underlies hereditary succession, by which rule passes within a family or line from one ruler to the next.",
"Buddhism": "Buddhism is a major world religion based on the teachings of Siddhartha Gautama, the Buddha, who lived in the Indian subcontinent around the 5th century BCE. It holds that suffering arises from craving and teaches a path of ethical conduct, meditation, and wisdom, set out in the Four Noble Truths and the Eightfold Path, leading toward liberation, or nirvana, from the cycle of rebirth. Spreading across Asia into the Theravada, Mahayana, and Vajrayana traditions, it reached China around the Han dynasty and became a great influence on Chinese culture alongside Confucianism and Daoism.",
"Lu_(state)": "Lu (魯) was a Zhou-era state on the Shandong peninsula, founded for the family of the Duke of Zhou and famous as the home state of Confucius. A devoted custodian of Zhou ritual and culture, it was relatively weak in war and survived among greater neighbours until it was annexed by Chu in 256 BCE. Its court chronicle, the Spring and Autumn Annals, gave its name to the whole Spring and Autumn period.",
"Jin_(state)": "Jin (晉) was a powerful northern state of the Spring and Autumn period centred on modern Shanxi, for a time the dominant power among the Zhou states. Its great noble houses grew over-mighty and carved the state apart, a partition recognized by the Zhou king in 403 BCE and completed by 376 BCE. Its three successor states, Zhao, Wei, and Han, went on to become major powers of the Warring States period.",
"Chu_(state)": "Chu (楚) was a great Zhou-era state on the middle Yangtze in the south, regarded by the northern states as half-barbarian yet immensely powerful and culturally distinctive. Its rulers were among the first to claim the title of king in defiance of the Zhou court, and the state produced the poetry anthology the Chuci. One of the last realms standing in the Warring States, it was conquered by Qin in 223 BCE.",
"Qi_(state)": "Qi (齊) was a major Zhou-era state in the east on the Shandong peninsula, founded for the strategist Jiang Ziya and made rich by salt, iron, and trade. Under Duke Huan and his minister Guan Zhong in the seventh century BCE it became the first of the hegemon states. Its ruling house was later supplanted by the Tian clan, and it endured as a great power until it was the last state to fall to Qin in 221 BCE.",
"Qin_(state)": "Qin (秦) was a Zhou-era state in the far northwest, originally a frontier fief that rose through Legalist reforms and military discipline. Hardened by war on the steppe frontier, it conquered the six rival states one by one, and in 221 BCE its king unified China as Qin Shi Huang, the first emperor. The state thereby became the Qin dynasty, the first imperial dynasty of China.",
"Zhao_(state)": "Zhao (趙) was one of the seven major Warring States, formed in the north from the partition of Jin and centred on modern Shanxi and Hebei. Known for its cavalry and its adoption of nomadic-style mounted archery, it was among Qin's most formidable rivals. After heavy defeats it fell to Qin in 228 BCE.",
"Wei_(state)": "Wei (魏) was one of the seven major Warring States, formed from the partition of Jin and holding lands across the central plains around the Yellow River. It was the earliest of the Warring States to rise to dominance through far-reaching reforms before being gradually eclipsed by the rising power of Qin. It was conquered by Qin in 225 BCE.",
"Luoyi": "Luoyi was the eastern capital of the Zhou dynasty, built near modern Luoyang on the Luo River, to which King Ping moved the court in 770 BCE. It served as the royal seat throughout the Eastern Zhou even as the kings' real power waned. The site lies in the Central Plains, a region long favoured as a Chinese capital.",
"Spring_and_Autumn_Annals": "The Spring and Autumn Annals (春秋) is the terse court chronicle of the state of Lu covering the years 722 to 481 BCE, traditionally said to have been compiled or edited by Confucius. One of the Five Classics of the Confucian canon, its laconic entries were later expanded by commentaries such as the Zuo Zhuan. It gives its name to the Spring and Autumn period of Chinese history.",
"Five_Hegemons": "The Five Hegemons were the most powerful feudal lords of the Spring and Autumn period, who in turn dominated the other states while nominally upholding the authority of the weakened Zhou king. The hegemon, or ba, led the states in war and diplomacy, the first and greatest being Duke Huan of Qi. Traditional lists of which five lords count as hegemons vary from source to source.",
"Duke_Huan_of_Qi": "Duke Huan of Qi was the ruler of the eastern state of Qi who became the first of the Five Hegemons of the Spring and Autumn period. Guided by his chief minister Guan Zhong, he strengthened Qi through administrative and economic reform and rallied the states under the banner of honouring the Zhou king and repelling the barbarians. After his death his sons fought over the succession and Qi's pre-eminence faded.",
"Guan_Zhong": "Guan Zhong was the celebrated chief minister of the state of Qi under Duke Huan, regarded as one of the foundational statesmen of Chinese history. His reforms of administration, taxation, and the salt and iron trades made Qi wealthy and powerful and raised Duke Huan to the first hegemony. The administrative classic the Guanzi was later attributed to him.",
"Hundred_Schools_of_Thought": "The Hundred Schools of Thought (諸子百家) is the name for the great flowering of Chinese philosophy during the Spring and Autumn and Warring States periods. Rival schools including Confucianism, Daoism, Mohism, and Legalism debated questions of ethics, government, and the cosmos as thinkers sought order amid political collapse. This era laid much of the intellectual foundation of later Chinese civilization.",
"Mohism": "Mohism (墨家) was a philosophical school founded by Mozi during the Warring States period, in its day a major rival of Confucianism. It taught impartial care for all people equally, condemned offensive war and wasteful ritual and music, and prized frugality, meritocracy, and practical benefit. Influential for a time, it faded after the Qin unification and was largely eclipsed by Confucianism.",
"Legalism_(Chinese_philosophy)": "Legalism (法家) was a school of Chinese political philosophy holding that social order rests on strict laws backed by clear rewards and harsh punishments rather than on moral virtue. Its thinkers, such as Shang Yang and Han Fei, exalted the power of the state and the ruler, and it became the governing ideology of the state of Qin and its short-lived empire. Discredited by the Qin's severity, it was later absorbed in part into the statecraft of the Confucian empire.",
"Historiography": "Historiography is the writing of history and, more particularly, the study of the methods, sources, and interpretive choices by which history is produced. It asks how accounts of the past are constructed, how they reflect the assumptions of their authors and eras, and how interpretations shift over time. As both a craft and a field of study, it distinguishes the disciplined writing of history from the raw events it records.",
"Covenant": "A covenant is a solemn, binding agreement between parties, carrying greater moral or sacred weight than an ordinary contract. In the Abrahamic religions it refers above all to the sacred bond between God and a chosen people, such as the covenant said to have been made with Abraham and with Israel. The idea of a binding, often sworn promise also appears widely in law and politics.",
"Asia": "Asia is the largest and most populous continent, occupying the eastern part of the combined Eurasian landmass and home to most of the world's people. It stretches from the Mediterranean and the Arctic to the Pacific and the tropics, taking in East, South, Central, Southeast, and West Asia. It was the seat of several of the earliest civilizations, including those of Mesopotamia, the Indus Valley, and China.",
"Africa": "Africa is the second-largest and second-most-populous continent, lying south of the Mediterranean and straddling the equator. It is widely regarded as the cradle of humankind, where the earliest humans evolved, and was home to ancient civilizations such as Egypt and Kush. It holds great geographic and cultural diversity, from the Sahara to tropical rainforest and savanna.",
"Europe": "Europe is a continent forming the western part of Eurasia, bounded by the Atlantic, the Arctic, the Mediterranean, and conventionally the Ural Mountains in the east. Though one of the smaller continents, it has been historically outsized in influence, the home of ancient Greece and Rome and later of seaborne empires. It comprises dozens of nations and is densely populated and highly developed.",
"North_America": "North America is the northern continent of the Western Hemisphere, reaching from the Arctic to the tropics between the Atlantic and Pacific Oceans. It includes Canada, the United States, Mexico, Central America, and the Caribbean, and was home to indigenous peoples and civilizations such as the Maya and Aztec before European colonization. Today it is among the world's wealthiest regions.",
"South_America": "South America is the southern continent of the Western Hemisphere, joined to North America at the Isthmus of Panama and bordered by the Atlantic and Pacific. It contains the Andes mountains and the Amazon rainforest and river basin, and was home to civilizations such as the Inca before European colonization. Most of its nations were later colonized by Spain and Portugal, shaping their languages and cultures.",
"Mandarin": "Mandarin is the largest group of Sinitic languages, spoken across northern and southwestern China and grounded in the northern dialects around Beijing. Its standard form, based on the Beijing dialect, is the official spoken language of China and Taiwan and is the most widely spoken native language in the world. It belongs, like all Chinese varieties, to the Sino-Tibetan family.",
"Cantonese": "Cantonese is a Sinitic language of the Yue branch, centred on Guangzhou and widely spoken in Guangdong, Hong Kong, Macau, and overseas Chinese communities. It preserves features of older Chinese lost in Mandarin, is mutually unintelligible with it, and has its own colloquial written forms. It belongs to the Sino-Tibetan family.",
"Erlitou_culture": "The Erlitou culture was a Bronze Age culture of the Yellow River valley in modern Henan, marked by early palaces, bronze casting, and signs of a centralized state. Flourishing roughly between 1900 and 1500 BCE, it is widely identified by Chinese archaeologists with the Xia dynasty, though no contemporary writing survives to confirm the link and the identification remains debated. It represents a key stage in the emergence of Chinese civilization between the Neolithic and the literate Shang.",
"Chengzhou": "Chengzhou was an eastern capital of the early Western Zhou dynasty, built around 1036 BCE by the Duke of Zhou near modern Luoyang in the Central Plains. It was established to garrison the east and to resettle the remnants of the conquered Shang nobility, securing Zhou control over the former Shang heartland. It lay close to the sister city of Wangcheng, or Luoyi, and the area remained a seat of royal power into the Eastern Zhou.",
"Chinese_mythology": "Chinese mythology is the body of myths and legends transmitted in China, encompassing creation stories, gods, culture heroes, and legendary sage-rulers. It draws on diverse sources and traditions, including folk religion, Daoism, and Confucian historiography, and was often recorded as semi-historical accounts of a remote golden age. Among its central figures are the creator Pangu, the goddess Nüwa, and the Yellow Emperor.",
"Book_of_Documents": "The Book of Documents (尚書), or Shangshu, is one of the Five Classics of the Confucian canon, a collection of speeches, proclamations, and other prose attributed to rulers and ministers of high antiquity. Its chapters purport to record the words of sage-kings such as Yao, Shun, and Yu and the founders of the Xia, Shang, and Zhou. Long revered as a foundational source on early statecraft, parts of the received text are of disputed authenticity.",
"Geography": "Geography is the study of the Earth's surface, its physical features, and the distribution of life and human activity across it. It examines landscapes, climates, oceans, and ecosystems as well as how people, settlements, and cultures relate to place and environment. As a discipline it spans the physical and the human, linking the natural sciences with the study of societies.",
"Bronze_vessel": "A bronze vessel is a container cast from bronze, an alloy of copper and tin prized in antiquity for its strength and the fine detail it could hold. In many early civilizations such vessels served for cooking, feasting, storage, and above all ritual offerings to gods and ancestors. Often bearing inscriptions or ornament, they are among the most prized artefacts archaeologists recover from early cultures.",
"Yinxu": "Yinxu is an archaeological site near modern Anyang in Henan, the ruins of the last capital of the Shang dynasty. Occupied from about 1250 to 1046 BCE through the reigns of the dynasty's final kings, it has yielded palace foundations, royal tombs, bronze vessels, and the great majority of known oracle bones. The inscriptions unearthed there confirmed the historical reality of the Shang, and the site is a UNESCO World Heritage Site.",
"Anyang": "Anyang is a city in northern Henan province, on the North China Plain near the borders with Hebei and Shanxi. It is best known as the location of Yinxu, the ruins of the last Shang dynasty capital, where the oracle bones were unearthed. As one of the cradles of Chinese civilization, it is counted among the historic ancient capitals of China.",
"Ding_(vessel)": "The ding (鼎) is an ancient Chinese cauldron, a ritual bronze vessel standing on legs, most often with three round feet and a pair of handles. Used to cook and present sacrificial meat and offerings, it became a potent emblem of political and ritual authority, possession of which signified the right to rule. The legendary Nine Tripod Cauldrons, said to symbolize sovereignty over the realm, were ding of this kind.",
"Shang_oracle_bones": "Shang oracle bones (甲骨) are the ox shoulder blades and turtle shells used for divination at the late Shang court, whose surfaces were heated until they cracked so that diviners could read the answers of ancestors and spirits. The questions, and sometimes the outcomes, were then carved into the bone, leaving the earliest substantial body of Chinese writing. Unearthed in their tens of thousands at Yinxu near Anyang, they are a primary source for Shang history, religion, and language.",
"Oracle_bone_script": "Oracle bone script (甲骨文) is the earliest known form of Chinese writing, used in the divination inscriptions carved on the bones and shells of the late Shang dynasty. Already a mature logographic system of several thousand characters, it is the direct ancestor of later Chinese script, and many of its signs can be traced into modern characters. Its decipherment opened a contemporary written window onto Shang government, ritual, and daily life.",
"Henan": "Henan is a populous province of north-central China, lying mostly south of the lower Yellow River in the heart of the North China Plain. Long regarded as a cradle of Chinese civilization, it holds many of the earliest capitals and sites, including the Erlitou culture, the Shang ruins at Yinxu, and the ancient cities of Luoyang and Kaifeng. Its name means south of the river, referring to the Yellow River.",
"Hunan": "Hunan is a province of south-central China lying south of the middle Yangtze, named for its position south of Lake Dongting. A region of rice paddies, rivers, and hills, it was historically part of the southern lands once dominated by the state of Chu. Its name means south of the lake.",
"Hubei": "Hubei is a province of central China on the middle Yangtze, named for its position north of Lake Dongting. Centred on the fertile Jianghan Plain where the Han River joins the Yangtze, it was a heartland of the ancient state of Chu. Its name means north of the lake, and its capital, Wuhan, is a major inland port.",
"Liaoning": "Liaoning is the southernmost province of Northeast China, fronting the Yellow Sea and the Bohai Gulf and bordering North Korea along the Yalu River. Centred on the Liao River valley from which it takes its name, it was a frontier between the Chinese heartland and the peoples of Manchuria. In modern times it became one of China's foremost centres of heavy industry.",
"Sichuan": "Sichuan is a large province of southwestern China, dominated by the fertile, densely populated Sichuan Basin ringed by mountains and bordering the Tibetan Plateau to the west. Watered by the Yangtze and its tributaries and shielded by its terrain, it was historically a rich and somewhat self-contained region, once home to the ancient states of Shu and Ba. It is famed for its spicy cuisine and as a habitat of the giant panda.",
"Jiangsu": "Jiangsu is a coastal province of eastern China on the Yellow Sea, occupying the flat, watery lower Yangtze delta north of Shanghai. Crossed by the Yangtze and the Grand Canal and dotted with lakes, it has long been one of China's most prosperous and densely populated regions. Its historic cities include Nanjing, several times a national capital, and Suzhou, renowned for its classical gardens.",
"Jiangxi": "Jiangxi is a province of southeastern China, a basin drained by the Gan River into Lake Poyang, the country's largest freshwater lake, and ringed by mountains. Lying inland from the southeastern coast, it was an important corridor for trade and migration between the Yangtze and the south. It is celebrated as the home of Jingdezhen, the historic centre of Chinese porcelain manufacture.",
"Zhejiang": "Zhejiang is a coastal province of eastern China south of the Yangtze delta, a region of hills, bays, and islands along the East China Sea. Long among China's wealthiest and most commercial areas, it has historic cities such as Hangzhou, a former imperial capital famed for West Lake, and the great port of Ningbo. Its name comes from the Zhe, an old name of the Qiantang River.",
"Gansu": "Gansu is a province of northwestern China, a long, narrow region stretching along the Hexi Corridor between the Tibetan Plateau and the deserts of Mongolia. This corridor was a vital section of the Silk Road, carrying trade and Buddhism between China and Central Asia, and is lined with sites such as the Mogao Caves at Dunhuang. Largely arid and mountainous, it has historically been a frontier and a meeting place of peoples.",
"Xinjiang": "Xinjiang is a vast region of far northwestern China, officially the Xinjiang Uyghur Autonomous Region and the country's largest provincial-level division. A land of deserts, oasis towns, and high mountains, it straddles the ancient Silk Road and borders several Central Asian states. Its name means new frontier, and it is home to the Uyghurs and other largely Turkic, traditionally Muslim peoples.",
"Tibet": "Tibet is a high plateau region of Inner Asia, north of the Himalayas, the homeland of the Tibetan people and the historic centre of Tibetan Buddhism. With an average elevation of over 4,000 metres, it is the highest region on Earth and the source of many of Asia's great rivers. Long governed by Buddhist rulers under the Dalai Lamas, it is today the Tibet Autonomous Region of China.",
"Rammed_earth": "Rammed earth is an ancient building technique in which damp earth, sometimes mixed with lime, gravel, or other stabilizers, is compacted in layers within a temporary frame to form hard, dense walls. Used independently by many cultures around the world, it produces durable structures from cheap and locally available material. It has served for everything from humble dwellings to city walls, fortifications, and monumental platforms.",
"Antiquity": "Antiquity is the distant past, especially the long span of early human history before the Middle Ages. The term is often used for the era of the earliest civilizations and their literate cultures, from the first cities and writing down to the close of the ancient world. As a general expression it can also mean simply great age or things surviving from remote times.",
"Euhemerism": "Euhemerism is the interpretation of myths as exaggerated or distorted accounts of real historical people and events, so that gods and heroes are understood as deified kings, ancestors, or benefactors. Named after the ancient Greek writer Euhemerus, who held that the gods had originally been mortal rulers, it treats legend as a memory of history embellished over time. As an approach to mythology it has been applied to many traditions across the world.",
"Battle_of_Zhuolu": "The Battle of Zhuolu is a legendary battle in Chinese mythology in which the Yellow Emperor defeated the war-god Chiyou and his Nine Li tribes. Said to have been fought on the plain of Zhuolu in the north, it is remembered as a decisive struggle that secured the Yellow Emperor's supremacy over the early tribes. It is cast in tradition as a founding event of the Huaxia people and of Chinese civilization.",
"Battle_of_Banquan": "The Battle of Banquan is a legendary battle in Chinese mythology in which the Yellow Emperor defeated the Flame Emperor, the leader of a rival tribe. According to tradition it ended in reconciliation, the two leaders' peoples merging to form the nucleus of the Huaxia, the ancestors of the Chinese. It is paired in legend with the later Battle of Zhuolu against Chiyou as a foundational conflict of early China.",
"Shaokang_Restoration": "The Shaokang Restoration was the legendary revival of the Xia dynasty under King Shaokang, after the royal house had lost the throne to usurpers. Following the seizure of power by Han Zhuo, the Xia heir Shaokang grew up in exile, gathered loyal supporters, and overthrew the usurpers to reclaim his family's rule. Chinese tradition holds it up as a model recovery of a fallen royal house, the archetype of a dynastic restoration.",
"Han_Zhuo": "Han Zhuo was a usurper in Chinese legend who seized control of the Xia dynasty during a long interruption of its rule. Taking power after the archer-lord Houyi, who had himself ousted the Xia king, he dominated the realm until the rightful heir Shaokang returned from exile to defeat him. His overthrow brought about the Shaokang Restoration and the return of the Xia royal line.",
"Centralization": "Centralization is the concentration of power, authority, and decision-making in a single central body or place, rather than dispersing it among local or subordinate units. In government it describes the gathering of control over administration, law, taxation, and the military under one ruler or capital. The degree to which authority is centralized is a recurring question in the organization of states and institutions.",
"Neolithic": "The Neolithic, or New Stone Age, is the final phase of the Stone Age, defined by the adoption of farming and settled village life. In this period people domesticated plants and animals, made polished stone tools and pottery, and built permanent dwellings, a shift often called the Neolithic Revolution. Its dates vary widely by region, beginning around 10,000 BCE in the Near East and giving way to the Bronze Age.",
"Mesolithic": "The Mesolithic, or Middle Stone Age, is a transitional phase of the Stone Age between the Paleolithic and the Neolithic. It covers the period after the end of the last Ice Age, when hunter-gatherers adapted to warming climates with smaller, finer stone tools known as microliths before the rise of farming. Its timing varies by region, and the term is applied chiefly where the shift to agriculture came gradually.",
"Paleolithic": "The Paleolithic, or Old Stone Age, is the earliest and by far the longest phase of the Stone Age, spanning most of human prehistory. It began with the first use of stone tools by early humans and lasted until the end of the last Ice Age, throughout which people lived as nomadic hunter-gatherers. Stretching over millions of years, it encompasses the emergence and spread of the human species.",
"Contemporary": "Contemporary describes something existing, occurring, or originating in the same period as something else; a contemporary source is one created at the same time as the events it records. By extension the word also means belonging to the present day, or modern. In both senses it stresses the sharing of a span of time, whether with a past subject or with the present.",
"Gravel": "Gravel is a loose aggregate of small rock fragments, coarser than sand but finer than boulders, formed by the natural weathering and erosion of rock. Found in riverbeds, beaches, and deposits left by ice and water, it ranges from fine pebbles to larger stones. It has been used since ancient times for construction, road-building, and as a component of concrete and other materials.",
"Lime_(material)": "Lime is a calcium-rich material produced by heating limestone or other carbonate rock, yielding quicklime, which becomes slaked lime when combined with water. Used since antiquity, it serves as a binder in mortar and plaster, a treatment for soils in agriculture, and an agent in many industrial processes. It should not be confused with the citrus fruit of the same name.",
"Archaeological_culture": "An archaeological culture is a recurring set of artefacts, building styles, and other material remains found together across a particular area and period. Archaeologists use such groupings to identify past human societies that left no written records, treating shared material traits as the signature of a community or tradition. The relationship between an archaeological culture and an actual people, language, or ethnic group is often uncertain and much debated.",
"Archaeological_excavation": "Archaeological excavation is the careful digging and recording of sites to recover the material remains of the past. Working in measured layers, archaeologists document the exact position of structures, artefacts, and deposits, since the context in which something is found is as important as the object itself. Because it destroys the layers it removes, it is the primary means of recovering buried evidence and must be recorded in meticulous detail.",
"Euhemerus": "Euhemerus was an ancient Greek writer and mythographer of the late fourth century BCE, active at the court of King Cassander of Macedon. In his work the Sacred History he argued that the gods had originally been great kings, heroes, and benefactors who came to be worshipped as divine after their deaths. His name gave rise to euhemerism, the interpretation of myth as distorted history.",
"Mercury_(planet)": "Mercury is the smallest planet in the Solar System and the closest to the Sun, which it orbits faster than any other planet. A rocky, heavily cratered world with almost no atmosphere, it swings between extreme heat and cold and is named after the swift Roman messenger god. Visible to the naked eye, it was tracked by astronomers in many ancient cultures.",
"Venus_(planet)": "Venus is the second planet from the Sun and the nearest to Earth, similar in size and rocky composition but wrapped in a thick, toxic atmosphere that traps heat and makes it the hottest planet. Brilliantly bright, it is often the first star-like point visible at dusk or dawn and is named after the Roman goddess of love. As the morning and evening star it has been observed and recorded by many ancient peoples.",
"Mars_(planet)": "Mars is the fourth planet from the Sun, a cold, rocky desert world whose reddish, iron-rich surface gives it the name the Red Planet. It has a thin atmosphere, polar ice caps, and the largest known volcano and canyon in the Solar System, and has long been a focus in the search for past life. Named after the Roman god of war, it has been tracked by astronomers since antiquity.",
"Jupiter_(planet)": "Jupiter is the largest planet in the Solar System, a giant ball of gas more massive than all the other planets combined. Banded with colourful clouds and marked by the Great Red Spot, a centuries-old storm, it has dozens of moons and a faint ring system. Named after the king of the Roman gods, it shines brightly in the night sky and has been known since ancient times.",
"Saturn_(planet)": "Saturn is the sixth planet from the Sun and the second largest in the Solar System, a gas giant famous for its broad, bright rings made of ice and rock. Like Jupiter it is composed mainly of hydrogen and helium and is circled by dozens of moons. Named after the Roman god of agriculture, it is the most distant planet readily visible to the naked eye.",
"Uranus_(planet)": "Uranus is the seventh planet from the Sun, an ice giant composed largely of water, methane, and ammonia surrounding a small rocky core. Its methane-rich atmosphere gives it a pale blue-green colour, and it rotates almost on its side, so that its poles take turns facing the Sun. Too faint to be seen easily without a telescope, it was the first planet discovered in modern times, in 1781.",
"Chong_(Zhuanxu_myth)": "Chong (重) is a figure in Chinese mythology whom the sage-sovereign Zhuanxu charged with taking command of Heaven. In the legend of the separation of Heaven and Earth, he was set to govern the heavens and the spirits while the earth and its people were placed under another, severing the free passage that had once joined the two realms. The story, preserved in early texts such as the Discourses of the States, was understood to end an age when humans and gods mingled freely.",
"Li_(Zhuanxu_myth)": "Li (黎) is a figure in Chinese mythology whom the sage-sovereign Zhuanxu charged with taking command of the earth. In the legend of the separation of Heaven and Earth, he was set to govern the earth and its people while the heavens were placed under another, cutting off the passage that had linked the mortal and divine worlds. Preserved in early texts such as the Discourses of the States, the tale was read as ending a primordial age when gods and humans freely mingled.",
"Stratification": "Stratification is the arrangement or formation of something in distinct layers, or strata. In geology and archaeology it refers to the build-up of layers of rock, soil, or deposits over time, whose ordering allows the relative dating of what they contain. The term is also used in other fields, as in the division of a society into ranked social layers.",
"Guoyu": "The Guoyu (國語), or Discourses of the States, is an ancient Chinese history that gathers speeches and conversations attributed to rulers and statesmen of the Spring and Autumn period. Arranged by state rather than strictly by chronology, it is traditionally ascribed to Zuo Qiuming and was probably compiled around the fourth century BCE. It is a major source for the thought, politics, and legends of early China, including the myth of the separation of Heaven and Earth.",
"Five_Classics": "The Five Classics (五經) are five ancient books that form the core of the Confucian canon, long revered as foundational works of Chinese civilization. They comprise the Book of Changes, the Book of Documents, the Book of Songs, the Book of Rites, and the Spring and Autumn Annals. Studied for centuries as the basis of education and the civil service examinations, they were traditionally said to have been compiled or edited by Confucius.",
"Syncretism": "Syncretism is the blending or fusion of different beliefs, traditions, or schools of thought into a new combined form. It occurs most often in religion and philosophy, when elements of separate systems are reconciled and merged, but the term applies to art, language, and culture as well. The result may harmonize once-distinct traditions or be criticized as an inconsistent mixture.",
"Ba_(daughter_of_Yellow_Emperor)": "Ba (魃), also called Nüba, is a drought goddess of Chinese mythology, said to be a daughter of the Yellow Emperor. In the great battle against Chiyou she descended to halt the wind and rain the enemy had conjured, helping to secure victory, but afterwards lost her divine power and could not return to the heavens. Wherever she wandered drought followed, and she became associated in legend with parching, rainless skies.",
"Cangjie": "Cangjie (倉頡) is a legendary figure of Chinese mythology, traditionally honoured as the inventor of Chinese writing. Said to have been a historian or minister of the Yellow Emperor, and often depicted with four eyes, he is described as devising characters after observing the tracks of birds and animals and the patterns of nature. The legend holds that at the creation of writing the heavens rained millet and the spirits wailed in the night.",
"Leizu": "Leizu (嫘祖), also known as Xilingshi, is a legendary Chinese empress, the wife of the Yellow Emperor, traditionally credited with the discovery of silk and the invention of the silk loom. According to legend she discovered sericulture when a silkworm cocoon fell into her tea and unravelled into a long thread, and she taught her people to raise silkworms and weave their silk. She has long been honoured as the goddess or patron of silk.",
"Silk": "Silk is a fine, strong, lustrous natural fibre spun by certain insect larvae, above all the silkworm, to form their cocoons, which can be unwound and woven into smooth, light cloth. Prized for its softness, sheen, and strength, it has long been among the most valued of textiles and a luxury carried over great distances by trade. It takes dye in brilliant colours and can be woven into fabrics ranging from sheer gauzes to heavy brocades.",
"South-pointing_chariot": "The south-pointing chariot (指南車) was an ancient Chinese two-wheeled vehicle bearing a pointer or figure that continuously indicated south, no matter how the chariot turned, by means of a differential gear train rather than magnetism. In legend it was devised by the Yellow Emperor to find his way through a thick fog raised by Chiyou in battle, or by the Duke of Zhou to guide envoys home. It is celebrated as one of the most ingenious mechanical inventions of early China.",
"Physician": "A physician is a medical practitioner trained to diagnose and treat illness and injury and to help maintain health. The term traditionally refers to a doctor who treats disease by means other than surgery, as distinct from a surgeon, though in common use it means any qualified medical doctor. Physicians have existed in some form in every literate civilization, developing varied traditions of medicine over thousands of years.",
"North_China_Plain": "The North China Plain is a vast, flat lowland in northern China, built up over ages by silt deposited by the Yellow River and other rivers. One of the most densely populated regions on Earth and a cradle of Chinese civilization, it has been the agricultural and political heartland of China for millennia. It spreads across much of Hebei, Henan, Shandong, and neighbouring areas around the lower Yellow River.",
"Beijing": "Beijing is the capital of China, a great city in the north of the country at the northern edge of the North China Plain. With a history stretching back about three thousand years, it served as the imperial capital under the Yuan, Ming, and Qing dynasties and holds monuments such as the Forbidden City, with the Great Wall in the surrounding hills. Today it is the political and cultural centre of China and one of the most populous cities in the world.",
"Tianjin": "Tianjin is a large port city in northern China on the Bohai Gulf, lying southeast of Beijing and serving as the capital's gateway to the sea. Long an important station on the Grand Canal and later a treaty port opened to foreign powers, it grew into a major centre of trade and industry. It is today one of China's directly administered municipalities.",
"Guangzhou": "Guangzhou, long known to the West as Canton, is a major port city in southern China and the capital of Guangdong province, set on the Pearl River near the South China Sea. For more than a thousand years it has been one of China's chief gateways for foreign trade and a southern terminus of the Maritime Silk Road. Today it is a sprawling metropolis and a leading centre of commerce and manufacturing.",
"Ming_dynasty": "The Ming dynasty was a Chinese dynasty that ruled from 1368 to 1644, founded by a former peasant rebel after the overthrow of the Mongol-led Yuan dynasty. A native Han Chinese regime, it was an age of cultural achievement, naval expeditions, and great building works, including much of the present Great Wall and the Forbidden City in Beijing. It fell to peasant rebellion and the Manchu conquest that established the Qing dynasty.",
"Yuwang_(Yan_emperor)": "Yuwang (榆罔) is, in traditional Chinese genealogy, the last of the Yan Emperors, or Flame Emperors, the line of legendary rulers said to begin with Shennong. As the reigning Flame Emperor in the time of the Yellow Emperor, he was defeated by him at the Battle of Banquan, after which their two peoples merged. His fall marks the traditional end of the Flame Emperor line and the ascendancy of the Yellow Emperor.",
"Totem": "A totem is a natural object, animal, or plant adopted as the emblem of a family, clan, or group, often regarded as a spiritual symbol or ancestor. Totems appear in the traditions of many peoples around the world, expressing a special bond between a social group and a particular species or thing. The belief system built around such emblems is known as totemism.",
"Bear": "A bear is a large, powerful mammal with shaggy fur, a heavy build, and a short tail, found across much of the Northern Hemisphere and parts of South America. Bears are mostly omnivorous and range from the great brown and polar bears to smaller species, and many sleep through the winter in a deep dormancy. Strong and imposing, they appear as symbols of strength and as totem animals in the myths of many cultures.",
"Tiger": "The tiger is the largest member of the cat family, a powerful striped predator native to Asia, from the snows of Siberia to tropical forests in the south. A solitary hunter marked by an orange coat with dark stripes, it is now endangered through habitat loss and hunting. Long admired for its strength and ferocity, it serves as a symbol of power and a guardian figure in the cultures of many Asian peoples.",
"Materia_medica": "Materia medica is a Latin term for the accumulated body of knowledge about the substances used in healing and their therapeutic properties. It refers both to the medicinal materials themselves, drawn from plants, minerals, and animals, and to the texts and traditions that catalogue how they are prepared and used. For centuries it formed the basis of pharmacy and the study of remedies before the rise of modern experimental methods.",
"Pharmacology": "Pharmacology is the branch of science concerned with drugs and how they interact with living organisms. It studies the composition, actions, mechanisms, uses, and toxic effects of substances used to treat, prevent, or diagnose disease. A modern experimental discipline, it developed from the older study of medicinal substances and their effects on the body.",
"Mineral": "A mineral is a naturally occurring inorganic solid with a definite chemical composition and an orderly internal crystal structure. Minerals are the building blocks of rocks and include such substances as quartz, salt, and the ores from which metals are won. In nutrition the word also refers to inorganic chemical elements that living things require in small amounts.",
"Pan_Geng": "Pan Geng was a king of the Shang dynasty, remembered above all for moving the royal capital to a site called Yin, near modern Anyang, around 1300 BCE. This final relocation gave the dynasty the lasting centre at which its kings would rule until the Shang fell, and from which the great archaeological remains at Yinxu derive. A speech urging his reluctant people to accept the move is preserved as a chapter of the Book of Documents.",
"Yin_(Shang_capital)": "Yin (殷) was the last capital of the Shang dynasty, established near modern Anyang when King Pan Geng moved the court there around 1300 BCE. So closely was it identified with the dynasty that the Shang are often called the Yin, or the Shang-Yin, especially in their later centuries. Its abandoned remains, the Ruins of Yin or Yinxu, have yielded the richest evidence of Shang civilization.",
"Shanxi": "Shanxi is a province of northern China, a high, mountainous plateau west of the North China Plain between the Taihang and Lüliang ranges. Bounded on its west and south by the great bend of the Yellow River, it was an early seat of Chinese civilization and the heartland of the ancient state of Jin. Rich in coal, it has long been one of China's foremost sources of that mineral.",
"Shaanxi": "Shaanxi is a province of north-central China straddling the middle Yellow River, with the Loess Plateau across its north and the Qinling Mountains through its centre. A cradle of Chinese civilization, it was the heartland of the Zhou, Qin, and Tang dynasties, and its capital Xi'an, once called Chang'an, was the seat of empire for over a thousand years. Its name is spelled with a doubled letter to distinguish it in writing from neighbouring Shanxi, which differs only in tone.",
"Di_Xin": "Di Xin, known to history by the damning name King Zhou, was the last king of the Shang dynasty, remembered in tradition as a cruel and dissolute tyrant. His reported debauchery, extravagance, and savage punishments are said to have cost the Shang the Mandate of Heaven and turned his own people against him. When his armies were crushed by the Zhou at the Battle of Muye around 1046 BCE, he took his own life, and the dynasty ended.",
"Battle_of_Muye": "The Battle of Muye was the decisive clash in which the Zhou overthrew the Shang dynasty, traditionally dated to around 1046 BCE. According to tradition the smaller Zhou army under King Wu routed the much larger Shang host, many of whose soldiers, drawn from slaves and captives, turned against their hated king. The victory ended the Shang and established the Zhou, and was long held up as a model of a just war that fulfilled the Mandate of Heaven.",
"Sacrifice": "Sacrifice is the offering of something of value to a god, spirit, or sacred power, typically as an act of worship, thanksgiving, or appeasement. Practised in religions throughout history, it has ranged from offerings of food, drink, incense, and animals to, in some societies, the killing of human beings. More broadly, the word also means the giving up of something prized for the sake of a higher claim or purpose.",
"Di_(high_god)": "Di (帝), also known as Shangdi, was the supreme god of the Shang dynasty, the highest power presiding over the cosmos in early Chinese religion. Recorded in the oracle bones, he was believed to command rain, wind, thunder, and harvest and to decide the fate of the king and the realm, yet he received no direct sacrifice and was petitioned through the royal ancestors. In later ages this high god came to be identified more and more with the abstract notion of Heaven.",
"Fu_Hao": "Fu Hao was a queen and military general of the Shang dynasty, one of the many consorts of King Wu Ding, and one of the earliest documented female commanders in Chinese history. She led armies of thousands into battle and served as a high priestess, and is well attested in the oracle bone inscriptions. Her tomb at Yinxu, discovered intact in 1976, is one of the richest and most important Shang burials ever excavated.",
"Shang_human_sacrifice": "Shang human sacrifice was the practice, widespread under the Shang dynasty, of killing people as ritual offerings to gods and royal ancestors. The victims, frequently war captives, were sacrificed in large numbers at royal funerals, the consecration of buildings, and divination ceremonies, and their remains fill the sacrificial pits and royal tombs unearthed at Yinxu. The custom declined after the Shang fell, as the Zhou came to favour more symbolic and animal offerings.",
"Wu_Ding": "Wu Ding was a king of the Shang dynasty whose long reign marked a high point of Shang power, expanding the state through wide-ranging military campaigns and a network of allies. His consort Fu Hao served as a general and high priestess, and her intact tomb is among the greatest of Shang finds. More than half of all known oracle bone inscriptions date from his reign, which yields the earliest substantial records of Chinese writing.",
"Suwen": "The Suwen (素問), or Basic Questions, is one of the two parts of the Inner Canon of the Yellow Emperor, the foundational classic of traditional Chinese medicine. Cast as a dialogue between the Yellow Emperor and his minister Qibo, it sets out the theory of medicine, including yin and yang, the five phases, qi, and the diagnosis of illness. It was compiled in the centuries around the Han dynasty and has been studied ever since as a cornerstone of Chinese medical thought.",
"Lingshu": "The Lingshu (靈樞), or Spiritual Pivot, is one of the two parts of the Inner Canon of the Yellow Emperor, the foundational classic of traditional Chinese medicine. It is devoted above all to acupuncture, describing the channels of the body, the points used in treatment, and the techniques of needling. Compiled in the centuries around the Han dynasty, it became the principal classical authority on acupuncture and the meridians.",
"Mediterranean_Sea": "The Mediterranean Sea is a large, nearly landlocked sea between Europe, Africa, and Asia, joined to the Atlantic Ocean by the narrow Strait of Gibraltar. Almost enclosed by land, it has been a great highway of trade and culture since antiquity, ringed by the civilizations of Egypt, Greece, Rome, and many others. Its name means the sea in the middle of the land.",
"Equator": "The equator is the imaginary circle around the middle of the Earth, equidistant from the North and South Poles, that divides the planet into the Northern and Southern Hemispheres. At zero degrees latitude, it is the longest circle of latitude and the line along which the Sun can pass directly overhead. Regions near it have a hot, wet tropical climate with little seasonal change in the length of the day.",
"Kush_(ancient_kingdom)": "Kush was an ancient Nubian kingdom of northeast Africa, centred on the Nile in what is now Sudan, with capitals first at Napata and later at Meroë. A wealthy power trading in gold, ivory, and iron, it was deeply influenced by and at times rival to Egypt, and its kings ruled Egypt as pharaohs of the Twenty-fifth Dynasty in the eighth and seventh centuries BCE. It endured for more than a thousand years before declining around the fourth century CE.",
"Balkan_Peninsula": "The Balkan Peninsula is a region of southeastern Europe bounded by the Adriatic, Ionian, Aegean, and Black Seas. Largely mountainous and historically divided among many peoples, languages, and faiths, it lay at the crossroads of empires from Rome and Byzantium to the Ottomans. Its patchwork of nations and long history of conflict gave rise to the term balkanization for the splintering of a region into hostile units.",
"Ionian_Sea": "The Ionian Sea is an arm of the Mediterranean Sea lying between southern Italy, Sicily, and the western coast of Greece. It contains some of the deepest waters of the Mediterranean and is dotted with Greek islands such as Corfu and Ithaca. It has been a route of seafaring and trade since the days of ancient Greece.",
"Adriatic_Sea": "The Adriatic Sea is an arm of the Mediterranean Sea separating the Italian Peninsula from the Balkan Peninsula. A long, narrow body of water reaching deep into Europe, it has linked the lands along its shores in trade since antiquity, with Venice rising as its dominant maritime power in the Middle Ages. Its eastern coast is famed for its many islands and deep natural harbours.",
"Tirana": "Tirana is the capital and largest city of Albania, set on a plain in the centre of the country between the Adriatic coast and the inland mountains. Founded in the early seventeenth century under Ottoman rule, it became the Albanian capital in 1920. It is the political, economic, and cultural heart of the nation.",
"Enver_Hoxha": "Enver Hoxha was the communist dictator who ruled Albania from 1944 until his death in 1985. A devoted Stalinist, he held power through a one-party state and a feared security service, breaking in turn with Yugoslavia, the Soviet Union, and finally China to pursue a fiercely independent and isolationist course. His regime was severely repressive, and in 1967 it declared Albania the world's first officially atheist state.",
"Democracy": "Democracy is a system of government in which political power rests with the people, who rule either directly or through representatives they elect. It is typically marked by free and fair elections, majority rule balanced by the protection of individual rights, and freedoms of speech, assembly, and the press. The word comes from Greek roots meaning rule by the people, and the idea is often traced to the city-states of ancient Greece.",
"Isaac": "Isaac is one of the three patriarchs of the Hebrew Bible, the son of Abraham and Sarah and the father of Jacob. In the biblical narrative he is the long-awaited child of God's promise to Abraham, famously bound for sacrifice by his father before God spared him. He is revered as a patriarch in Judaism, Christianity, and Islam.",
"Jacob": "Jacob is one of the three patriarchs of the Hebrew Bible, the son of Isaac and grandson of Abraham, later given the name Israel. According to the biblical account his twelve sons became the ancestors of the twelve tribes of Israel. He is honoured as a patriarch in Judaism, Christianity, and Islam.",
"Black_Sea": "The Black Sea is a large inland sea between Eastern Europe and Western Asia, joined to the Mediterranean through the narrow Bosporus and Dardanelles straits. Fed by great rivers such as the Danube, its deep lower waters are nearly without oxygen and almost lifeless. Ringed by many nations, it has been a vital artery of trade and a contested frontier between empires for thousands of years.",
"Tang_dynasty": "The Tang dynasty was a Chinese dynasty that ruled from 618 to 907, widely regarded as a golden age of Chinese civilization. An era of cosmopolitan culture, far-reaching trade along the Silk Road, and great achievements in poetry and art, it saw China powerful, prosperous, and open to the world. Founded after the collapse of the Sui, it was for a time the most populous and advanced empire on Earth.",
"Sui_dynasty": "The Sui dynasty was a short-lived Chinese dynasty that ruled from 581 to 618, reunifying China after centuries of division. Though it lasted only two reigns, it carried out vast works, including the joining of the Grand Canal, and rebuilt central institutions that its successors would inherit. Exhausted by costly campaigns and forced labour, it collapsed in rebellion and gave way to the Tang.",
"Yuan_dynasty": "The Yuan dynasty was the Mongol-led dynasty that ruled China from 1271 to 1368, established by Kublai Khan, grandson of Genghis Khan. It was the first time all of China came under foreign rule, as part of the vast Mongol Empire, and the era saw widened trade across Eurasia and famous foreign visitors such as Marco Polo. Resented by many Han Chinese and weakened by factional strife and natural disasters, it was overthrown by the rebellion that founded the Ming.",
"Lesser_Antilles": "The Lesser Antilles are a long arc of small islands in the eastern Caribbean, reaching from near Puerto Rico southward toward the coast of South America. Together with the larger Greater Antilles they form the West Indies, the island chain that encloses the Caribbean Sea. Their many islands, split into the Leeward and Windward groups, were colonized by competing European powers and are today a patchwork of nations and territories.",
"Caribbean_Sea": "The Caribbean Sea is a large tropical sea of the western Atlantic, bordered by Central and South America to the south and west and enclosed to the north and east by the islands of the West Indies. Dotted with islands, reefs, and gulfs, it was the scene of European colonization, piracy, and the plantation trade from the sixteenth century onward. Today it is renowned for its warm, clear waters and is a major destination for tourism.",
"Leeward_Islands": "The Leeward Islands are the northern group of the Lesser Antilles in the eastern Caribbean, lying where the island arc bends westward toward Puerto Rico. Their name reflects their sheltered position relative to the prevailing trade winds that blow across the region. They include such islands as Antigua, Saint Kitts, Guadeloupe, and the Virgin Islands.",
"Saint_John's": "Saint John's is the capital and largest city of Antigua and Barbuda, a port on the northwestern coast of the island of Antigua in the eastern Caribbean. Long a British colonial harbour shipping the sugar of the surrounding plantations, it grew into the commercial heart of the islands. It is today the country's main port, business centre, and cruise-ship destination.",
"Antigua_(island)": "Antigua is the larger of the two main islands of the country of Antigua and Barbuda, in the Leeward Islands of the eastern Caribbean. A low island of volcanic and limestone origin ringed by beaches and reefs, it was a British colony built on sugar plantations for over three centuries. Its chief town and the national capital is Saint John's.",
"Britain": "Britain, or Great Britain, is the largest island of the British Isles, off the northwestern coast of Europe, comprising England, Scotland, and Wales. The name is also used more loosely for the United Kingdom, the sovereign state that governs the island together with Northern Ireland. Once the centre of the British Empire, the largest empire in history, it has been a major political, economic, and cultural power for centuries.",
"British_Commonwealth": "The British Commonwealth, today called the Commonwealth of Nations, is a political association of states, most of them former territories of the British Empire. Formally established in the early twentieth century, it links its members through shared history, language, and institutions and is headed symbolically by the British monarch. Its members are independent and equal, cooperating on trade, culture, and development rather than through any binding political union.",
"Strategies_of_the_Warring_States": "Strategies of the Warring States (戰國策) is an ancient Chinese text collecting anecdotes, speeches, and schemes of the political advisers and strategists of the Warring States period. Compiled and edited by the Han dynasty scholar Liu Xiang from older records, it portrays the diplomacy, intrigue, and rhetoric of the rival states down to the unification by Qin. It is valued both as a historical source and as a model of persuasive prose.",
"Battle_of_Changping": "The Battle of Changping was a massive and decisive battle of the Warring States period, fought from 262 to 260 BCE between the states of Qin and Zhao. After luring the Zhao army into a trap and starving it into surrender, the Qin general Bai Qi is said to have had several hundred thousand captured Zhao soldiers put to death. The catastrophe shattered Zhao, the last state strong enough to resist Qin, and hastened the unification of China.",
"Bai_Qi": "Bai Qi was one of the greatest generals of the state of Qin during the Warring States period, renowned and feared for never losing a battle. His campaigns broke the rival states one after another, culminating in the annihilation of the Zhao army at the Battle of Changping. Having fallen out with the Qin king, he was forced to take his own life around 257 BCE.",
"Decentralization": "Decentralization is the dispersal of power, authority, or functions away from a single central body to local, regional, or subordinate units. In government it describes the delegation of administration and decision-making to provinces, municipalities, or other lower levels of the state. It is often pursued to bring decisions closer to local communities and to keep authority from concentrating in one place.",
"Han_Fei": "Han Fei was a Chinese philosopher of the Warring States period, the foremost thinker of the Legalist school. A prince of the state of Han, he argued that strong, impartial laws and the firm authority of the ruler, not moral example, were the true basis of social order. His writings deeply influenced the state of Qin, though he died in its prison, reportedly forced to take poison by the minister Li Si.",
"Society_of_Jesus": "The Society of Jesus is a religious order of the Catholic Church, whose members are known as Jesuits. Founded by Ignatius of Loyola and approved by the pope in 1540, it became renowned for its scholarship, its schools and universities, and its missionary work across the globe. Jesuit missionaries were among the first Europeans to live and work in many parts of Asia, the Americas, and Africa.",
"God": "God is the supreme being, creator, and ultimate reality worshipped in monotheistic religions such as Judaism, Christianity, and Islam. Usually conceived as eternal, all-powerful, all-knowing, and perfectly good, God is held to be the source and sustainer of the universe. Written with a capital letter, the word names this single divine being, the central object of worship and devotion in those faiths.",
"Baháʼu'lláh": "Baháʼu'lláh was the Persian founder and prophet of the Baháʼí Faith, which he proclaimed in the mid-nineteenth century. Born into a noble family, he declared himself the messianic figure foretold by the Báb and taught the oneness of God, the unity of all religions, and the unity of humankind. Exiled and imprisoned for most of his life by Persian and Ottoman authorities, he set down his teachings in numerous works regarded by his followers as scripture.",
"Báb": "The Báb was a Persian merchant who in 1844 declared himself the bearer of a new revelation from God, founding the religion of Bábism. He taught that he was a messenger preparing the way for a greater one to come, later identified by Baháʼís as Baháʼu'lláh. Seen as a dangerous heretic, he was executed by firing squad in 1850, and he is revered as a central figure of the Baháʼí Faith.",
"ʻAbdu'l-Bahá": "ʻAbdu'l-Bahá was the eldest son of Baháʼu'lláh and, after his father's death, the appointed head of the Baháʼí Faith. Freed from a lifetime of imprisonment in 1908, he travelled through Egypt, Europe, and North America to spread and explain his father's teachings. Baháʼís regard him as the perfect exemplar of their faith and the authorized interpreter of its scriptures.",
"Polytheism": "Polytheism is the belief in or worship of many gods. Common to most ancient religions, from Egypt and Mesopotamia to Greece and Rome, it typically envisions a pantheon of deities each governing particular forces of nature or spheres of life. Its gods are often organized into divine families and ranks, presided over by a chief or king of the gods.",
"Italian_Peninsula": "The Italian Peninsula is a long, boot-shaped peninsula of southern Europe extending into the Mediterranean Sea, occupied chiefly by the country of Italy. Bounded by the Adriatic, Ionian, and Tyrrhenian Seas and backed by the Alps, it runs from the mountains in the north to the island of Sicily at its toe. It was the heartland of ancient Rome and later of the Renaissance.",
"Venice": "Venice is a historic city of northeastern Italy, built on more than a hundred small islands in a lagoon of the Adriatic Sea and famous for its canals. In the Middle Ages and Renaissance it was the seat of a powerful maritime republic that dominated Mediterranean trade between Europe and the East. Renowned for its art and architecture, it remains one of the world's most celebrated cities.",
"Rome": "Rome is the capital of Italy and one of the oldest and most historically important cities in the world, set on the Tiber River in the centre of the Italian Peninsula. According to legend founded in 753 BCE, it grew into the heart of the Roman Empire, which ruled the Mediterranean world for centuries. It later became the centre of the Roman Catholic Church and surrounds the independent enclave of Vatican City.",
"Ottoman_Empire": "The Ottoman Empire was a vast Muslim empire, founded by Turkish tribes in Anatolia around 1299, that came to rule southeastern Europe, western Asia, and North Africa. At its height after the conquest of Constantinople in 1453, it was one of the most powerful states in the world, ruled by a sultan for more than six centuries. It declined gradually and was dissolved after the First World War, giving way to the modern Republic of Turkey.",
"Stalinism": "Stalinism is the system of government and ideology associated with Joseph Stalin, leader of the Soviet Union from the 1920s until 1953. It is marked by a centrally planned economy, total control by a single party, a pervasive secret police and cult of personality, and the violent suppression of opposition through purges, forced labour, and terror. The term is often used more broadly for similarly repressive forms of communist rule.",
"One-party_state": "A one-party state is a country in which a single political party holds all governing power and other parties are banned or barred from taking office. Elections, if held at all, offer no genuine alternative, and the ruling party is fused with the machinery of the state. Such systems are characteristic of communist and many other authoritarian regimes.",
"Yugoslavia": "Yugoslavia was a country in southeastern Europe, on the Balkan Peninsula, that existed for much of the twentieth century and united several South Slavic peoples in a single state. Formed after the First World War and rebuilt as a communist federation under Josip Broz Tito after the Second, it stood apart from the Soviet bloc. In the early 1990s it broke apart in a series of wars into independent nations such as Serbia, Croatia, and Bosnia.",
"Soviet_Union": "The Soviet Union, formally the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics, was a communist federation spanning much of Eurasia from 1922 to 1991, the first and largest state founded on Marxist-Leninist ideology. Centred on Russia and ruled from Moscow by the Communist Party, it became a global superpower and the chief rival of the United States during the Cold War. Strained by economic stagnation and attempts at reform, it dissolved in 1991 into fifteen independent republics.",
"Isolationism": "Isolationism is a national policy of avoiding political and military entanglement with other countries, keeping out of foreign alliances, conflicts, and commitments. It seeks to concentrate on a country's own affairs and may extend to limiting trade, immigration, and cultural contact with the outside world. Though often driven by a wish for self-reliance or to avoid foreign wars, it can leave a state cut off and unprepared for outside threats.",
"Atheism": "Atheism is the absence of belief in the existence of any god or gods, or the positive belief that none exist. It ranges from a simple lack of religious belief to a reasoned rejection of the claims of religion, and it has been expressed in many cultures throughout history. Those described as atheist may reject religion outright or simply live without reference to the divine.",
"Dictator": "A dictator is a ruler who holds absolute power over a state, typically having seized or kept it by force and exercising it without effective legal or constitutional limits. The term originated in ancient Rome, where a dictator was a magistrate granted temporary emergency powers, but it now denotes an oppressive and unaccountable ruler. Modern dictators often rule through a single party, a personality cult, and the suppression of dissent.",
"Communism": "Communism is a political and economic ideology that calls for a classless society in which property and the means of production are owned in common rather than privately. Drawing especially on the theories of Karl Marx, it envisions the abolition of private ownership and the eventual withering away of the state. In the twentieth century, communist parties established one-party states in many countries around the world.",
"North_Africa": "North Africa is the northern region of the African continent, bordering the Mediterranean Sea and including the lands along the coast and the Sahara Desert behind them. Largely Arab and Berber in population and predominantly Muslim, it has been closely tied to the Mediterranean world since antiquity, home to ancient Egypt and Carthage. It comprises countries such as Egypt, Libya, Tunisia, Algeria, and Morocco.",
"Algiers": "Algiers is the capital and largest city of Algeria, a major port on the Mediterranean coast of North Africa. Built on hills rising from the bay, its old walled citadel, the Casbah, dates from the era of Ottoman rule, when the city was a stronghold of Barbary corsairs. It is today the political, economic, and cultural centre of Algeria.",
"Sahara_Desert": "The Sahara Desert is the largest hot desert in the world, spanning much of North Africa from the Atlantic to the Red Sea. An immense expanse of sand seas, gravel plains, and barren mountains, it is one of the harshest and driest environments on Earth, yet it has long been crossed by caravan routes linking the Mediterranean with sub-Saharan Africa. It once held lakes and grasslands and grew arid only within the last several thousand years.",
"Natural_gas": "Natural gas is a naturally occurring mixture of flammable gases, chiefly methane, found underground in porous rock, often alongside petroleum. Formed over millions of years from the buried remains of living things, it is extracted by drilling and burned as a major fuel for heating, electricity, and industry. It is a fossil fuel, cleaner-burning than coal or oil but still a source of greenhouse gases.",
"Oil": "Oil is any of various thick, greasy liquids that do not mix with water, drawn from plants, animals, or minerals. The most important is petroleum, or crude oil, a fossil fuel pumped from underground and refined into fuels, lubricants, and the raw materials of plastics and chemicals. Oils have been used since antiquity for food, lighting, lubrication, and medicine.",
"Corrosion": "Corrosion is the gradual destruction of a material, especially a metal, by chemical reaction with its environment. The most familiar form is the rusting of iron and steel, in which the metal reacts with oxygen and moisture to form crumbling oxides. It weakens structures and machinery over time and is resisted by coatings, alloying, and other forms of protection.",
"Iron": "Iron is a common metallic chemical element, a hard, silvery-grey metal that is the most widely used of all metals. Abundant in the Earth's crust and core, it is extracted from ore by smelting and is the main ingredient of steel, the alloy on which modern industry depends. Valued since antiquity for tools and weapons, the mastery of it defined the Iron Age.",
"Carbon": "Carbon is a chemical element that is one of the essential building blocks of all known life, able to form an immense variety of compounds. It occurs in pure forms such as diamond and graphite and in countless substances from carbon dioxide to coal, oil, and living tissue. In metallurgy, the amount of carbon combined with iron determines whether the result is soft iron, hard steel, or brittle cast iron.",
"Metallic_bonding": "Metallic bonding is the type of chemical bonding that holds the atoms of a metal together, in which positively charged ions sit in a shared sea of freely moving electrons. This mobile cloud of electrons explains the characteristic properties of metals, such as their ability to conduct heat and electricity and to be hammered or drawn into shape. It is one of the principal kinds of chemical bond, alongside ionic and covalent bonding.",
"Chinese_script": "Chinese script is the logographic writing system used to write the Chinese languages, in which each character stands for a word or unit of meaning rather than a sound. One of the oldest writing systems in continuous use, it descends from the oracle bone script of the Shang dynasty and has grown to comprise many thousands of characters. It has also been used to write other languages, including Japanese and, historically, Korean and Vietnamese.",
"Ku_(sage_king)": "Ku (嚳), also called Diku or Emperor Ku, is a legendary ruler of ancient China, counted among the Five Emperors who reigned before the first dynasties. Tradition makes him a great-grandson of the Yellow Emperor and the father of the sage-king Yao, succeeding his kinsman Zhuanxu on the throne. Like the other Five Emperors, he belongs to legend rather than to verifiable history.",
"Changyi_(father_of_Zhuanxu)": "Changyi (昌意) is a figure of Chinese legend, a son of the Yellow Emperor and his wife Leizu. He is remembered chiefly as the father of Zhuanxu, one of the Five Emperors, forming a link in the genealogy that traced the sage-rulers back to the Yellow Emperor. He is a legendary rather than a historical figure.",
"Shamanism": "Shamanism is a range of religious practices centred on the shaman, a person believed to reach altered states of consciousness in order to interact with a spirit world. Found among many cultures across the globe, especially in tribal and hunter-gatherer societies, it typically involves healing, divination, and the guiding of souls, with the shaman serving as an intermediary between the human and spirit realms. The term originates from the Tungus peoples of Siberia but is applied broadly to similar practices elsewhere.",
"Shaman": "A shaman is a religious specialist believed to communicate with the spirit world, often by entering a trance or altered state of consciousness. Acting as an intermediary between people and spirits, a shaman may heal the sick, foretell the future, influence the weather, or guide the souls of the dead. Such figures are found in many traditional societies around the world.",
"Coal": "Coal is a combustible black or brownish-black sedimentary rock formed from the compressed remains of ancient plants buried over millions of years. Rich in carbon, it has been burned as a fuel since antiquity and became the chief energy source of the Industrial Revolution, powering steam engines, the making of steel, and the generation of electricity. Its burning is a major source of energy but also of air pollution and greenhouse gases.",
"Sima_Tan": "Sima Tan was a scholar and official of the Han dynasty who served as Grand Historian at the court of Emperor Wu. A learned student of astronomy, the calendar, and philosophy, he began the great history of China that he charged his son to finish. That son, Sima Qian, completed the work as the Records of the Grand Historian, which became the model for all later Chinese dynastic histories.",
"Xiongnu": "The Xiongnu (匈奴) were a confederation of nomadic peoples who dominated the steppes north of China from around the third century BCE. United into a powerful empire under their ruler Modu Chanyu, they were the great northern rivals of the Han dynasty, raiding its frontier and exacting tribute until decades of war pushed them back. Their confederation fragmented and declined in the early centuries CE, and their origins and identity remain much debated.",
"Central_Asia": "Central Asia is a large, mostly landlocked region at the heart of the Eurasian continent, lying between China, the Middle East, Russia, and South Asia. A land of steppes, deserts, and mountains, it was crossed by the Silk Road and was long home to nomadic peoples and to oasis cities that thrived on trade. It today comprises the nations of Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, Turkmenistan, Kyrgyzstan, and Tajikistan.",
"Korea": "Korea is a peninsula and region in East Asia, lying between China and Japan and bordered by the Yellow Sea and the Sea of Japan. Home to the Korean people and a civilization stretching back thousands of years, it developed under strong Chinese cultural influence while keeping its own distinct language and identity. Long unified under a single state, it was divided in the twentieth century into North Korea and South Korea.",
"Silk_Road": "The Silk Road was a network of trade routes that linked China with Central Asia, the Middle East, and the Mediterranean world from antiquity into the Middle Ages. Named for the lucrative Chinese silk carried westward along it, it also conveyed spices, precious metals, and countless other goods, as well as religions, technologies, and ideas between East and West. Its overland caravans and connected sea lanes made it one of history's great channels of exchange between civilizations.",
"State_doctrine": "A state doctrine is an official set of beliefs, principles, or ideology formally adopted and promoted by a government as the basis of its policy. It may be religious, political, or philosophical, and is often taught in schools, enforced by law, or privileged over rival views. Establishing one can unify a state under a common creed, but it may also serve to suppress dissent and alternative thought.",
"Ten_Wings": "The Ten Wings (十翼) are the ten classic commentaries traditionally appended to the I Ching, the ancient Chinese divination manual, explaining its symbolism and philosophy. Composed during the late Zhou and the Han dynasty and long attributed to Confucius, they transformed the I Ching from a manual of divination into a profound work of cosmology and ethics. Through them the text took its place among the Five Classics of the Confucian canon.",
"Abdication": "Abdication is the formal act by which a monarch or other ruler renounces and gives up the throne or high office, whether voluntarily or under pressure. It transfers sovereignty to a successor and is one of the recognized ways in which a reign comes to an end. In some traditions a ruler's voluntary yielding of power to a worthier person has been held up as a model of virtue.",
"Cassander": "Cassander was a king of Macedon, the son of Antipater and one of the Diadochi, the generals who warred over the empire of Alexander the Great after his death. He seized control of Macedonia and Greece, founded the city of Thessalonica, and had Alexander's widow and young son put to death to secure his power. He reigned as king from about 305 BCE until his death, and the writer Euhemerus served at his court.",
"Sacred_History_(Euhemerus)": "The Sacred History, or Hiera Anagraphe, is a lost work by the Greek writer Euhemerus, composed in the early third century BCE. In it he described a fictional voyage to an island where he claimed to have found records proving that gods such as Uranus, Cronus, and Zeus had originally been mortal kings, deified by their grateful subjects. The work gave rise to euhemerism, the theory that myths derive from real history, and survives only in quotations by later authors.",
"Ancient_Rome": "Ancient Rome was the civilization that grew from the city of Rome on the Italian Peninsula into one of the largest and most influential empires in history. Beginning traditionally with the city's founding in 753 BCE, it passed from kingdom to republic to empire, coming to rule the whole Mediterranean world along with much of Europe, North Africa, and the Near East. Its law, language, engineering, and culture profoundly shaped Western civilization long after the western empire fell in 476 CE.",
"Kabul": "Kabul is the capital and largest city of Afghanistan, lying high in a valley of the Hindu Kush mountains in the east of the country. One of the oldest continuously inhabited cities in the region, it commanded the routes through the mountains and was long a prize on the roads between Central and South Asia. It has been fought over repeatedly in modern times and remains the political and economic centre of Afghanistan.",
"Hindu_Kush": "The Hindu Kush is a great mountain range of Central and South Asia, stretching mainly through Afghanistan and into Pakistan. An extension of the wider Himalayan system, it rises to peaks over seven thousand metres and forms a formidable barrier crossed by historic passes such as the Khyber. For millennia these passes carried trade, armies, and migrations between the Iranian world, Central Asia, and the Indian subcontinent.",
"Taliban": "The Taliban are an Islamist militant and political movement in Afghanistan that follows a strict fundamentalist interpretation of Islam. Emerging in 1994 from the chaos of civil war, they ruled most of the country from 1996 to 2001, enforcing harsh religious law, before being toppled by a United States–led invasion. After a long insurgency they recaptured Kabul and returned to power in 2021.",
"Hebrew": "Hebrew is a Semitic language, the tongue of the ancient Israelites and of most of the Hebrew Bible. After ceasing to be an everyday spoken language around the start of the common era, it survived for nearly two thousand years as a language of Jewish religion, scholarship, and literature. In the modern era it was revived as a spoken language and is today an official language of Israel.",
"Arabic": "Arabic is a Semitic language spoken across the Arab world of the Middle East and North Africa by hundreds of millions of people. As the language of the Quran, it is the sacred and liturgical language of Islam and has been carried far beyond its homeland by the faith. It exists in a formal classical and standard written form alongside many regional spoken dialects.",
"Shem": "Shem is one of the three sons of Noah in the Hebrew Bible, traditionally regarded as the ancestor of the Semitic peoples. Through his line the scriptures trace the descent of the Hebrews, Arabs, and related nations, and the word Semitic itself derives from his name. He is honoured as a forefather in Judaism, Christianity, and Islam.",
"Noah": "Noah is a patriarch in the Hebrew Bible, famous as the man who, warned by God, built an ark to survive a great flood sent to destroy a corrupt world. He saved his family and pairs of every kind of animal, and from his three sons, Shem, Ham, and Japheth, the scriptures descend all the peoples of the earth. He is a revered figure in Judaism, Christianity, and Islam, in which he is counted among the prophets.",
"Book_of_Genesis": "The Book of Genesis is the first book of the Hebrew Bible and the Christian Old Testament, opening the scriptures of Judaism and Christianity. It recounts the creation of the world, the stories of Adam and Eve, Noah and the flood, and the patriarchs Abraham, Isaac, Jacob, and Joseph. Its narratives of beginnings are foundational to the Abrahamic religions.",
"Grand_Historian": "The Grand Historian (太史) was a high office of the ancient Chinese court responsible for astronomy, the calendar, divination, and the keeping of official records. Its holders observed the heavens, regulated the calendar, and maintained the archives and chronicles of the state. The post combined the duties of court astronomer and official recordkeeper and was held by learned scholars across many dynasties.",
"Twenty-Four_Histories": "The Twenty-Four Histories (二十四史) are the canon of official dynastic histories of imperial China, covering the past from earliest legendary times down to the Ming dynasty. Compiled over nearly two thousand years and sanctioned as authoritative, they record the politics, institutions, and notable figures of successive dynasties in a standard form of annals and biographies. Together they make up one of the most extensive and continuous historical records produced by any civilization.",
"Li_Ling": "Li Ling was a general of the Han dynasty, a grandson of the famed Flying General Li Guang, who led campaigns against the Xiongnu on the northern frontier. In 99 BCE his five thousand infantry were surrounded and overwhelmed by a far larger Xiongnu army, and after a desperate stand he surrendered rather than die. The Han emperor had his family executed, and he lived out his remaining years among the Xiongnu, never returning home.",
"Letter_to_Ren_An": "The Letter to Ren An (報任安書) is a celebrated letter written by the Han historian Sima Qian to his friend Ren An around 91 BCE. In it he explains, with deep feeling, why he chose to endure the disgrace of castration rather than take his own life, so that he might live to complete his great history. It is treasured as one of the masterpieces of classical Chinese prose and a rare, intensely personal testament from an ancient author.",
"Fenghao": "Fenghao (豐鎬) was the capital of the Western Zhou dynasty, a pair of neighbouring cities, Feng and Hao, on opposite banks of the Feng River near modern Xi'an. Established by the early Zhou kings, it served for some three centuries as the political and ceremonial centre of the realm. It was sacked in 771 BCE, after which the court fled east and the Western Zhou came to an end.",
"Wei_River": "The Wei River is the largest tributary of the Yellow River, flowing eastward across the Guanzhong basin of Shaanxi in north-central China. Its fertile valley was one of the cradles of Chinese civilization, the homeland of the early Zhou and Qin and the site of a long succession of capital cities. It joins the Yellow River near the great bend where that river turns sharply to the east.",
"Xi'an": "Xi'an is a city in north-central China, the capital of Shaanxi province, set in the Wei River valley of the Guanzhong basin. Under its older name Chang'an it served as the capital of a long succession of dynasties and as an eastern terminus of the Silk Road. It is renowned today for its ancient city walls and for the terracotta army buried nearby with the first Qin emperor.",
"Duke_of_Zhou": "The Duke of Zhou was a statesman of the early Western Zhou dynasty, a younger brother of King Wu who served as regent for the boy-king Cheng after the dynasty's founding. He is credited with consolidating Zhou rule, putting down a great rebellion, building the eastern capital, and shaping the rituals and institutions of the new state. Later ages, above all Confucius, revered him as a model sage and the ideal of the wise and loyal minister.",
"Qin_dynasty": "The Qin dynasty was the first imperial dynasty of China, founded in 221 BCE when the state of Qin completed its conquest of the rival kingdoms. Under its first emperor and his ministers it standardized the script, weights, measures, and coinage, built roads and a vast wall along the northern frontier, and imposed a centralized bureaucracy in place of the old feudal order. Harsh and short-lived, it collapsed in rebellion within a few years of the first emperor's death.",
"Great_Wall_of_China": "The Great Wall of China (長城) is a vast series of fortifications built and rebuilt across the northern frontier of China over many centuries to guard against raids and invasions from the steppe. Earlier rulers raised walls of pounded earth, which the first Qin emperor linked into a single barrier, while the famous stone-and-brick wall that survives today was largely the work of the Ming dynasty. Stretching thousands of miles across mountains and desert, it is one of the largest building projects ever undertaken.",
"Terracotta_Army": "The Terracotta Army (兵馬俑) is a vast collection of life-sized clay soldiers, horses, and chariots buried near the tomb of Qin Shi Huang, the first emperor of China. Made to guard the emperor in the afterlife, the figures number in the thousands and are individually modelled, arrayed in battle formation in great underground pits. Discovered by well-diggers in 1974 near modern Xi'an, it is among the most celebrated archaeological finds of the twentieth century.",
"Grand_Canal": "The Grand Canal (大運河) is the longest artificial waterway in the world, a network of canals linking the great rivers of eastern China from north to south. Sections were dug as early as the Spring and Autumn period, and the Sui dynasty joined them into a single system to carry grain and goods between the Yellow River and the Yangtze. Running for more than a thousand miles, it long served as a vital artery of trade, transport, and imperial supply.",
"Li_Si": "Li Si was the chief minister of the state and then the empire of Qin, the leading statesman behind its unification of China. A follower of Legalist principles, he promoted the centralized bureaucracy, standardized the written script, and is blamed for the burning of books that dissented from the new order. After the first emperor's death he was outmanoeuvred in a court intrigue and put to death in 208 BCE.",
"Mencius": "Mencius (孟子), also known as Mengzi, was a Confucian philosopher of the Warring States period, traditionally honoured as the greatest of the early Confucian thinkers. He taught that human nature is innately good, that benevolence can be cultivated, and that a ruler governs justly only with the welfare and consent of the people. His teachings, gathered in the book that bears his name, became a central text of the Confucian tradition.",
"Xunzi": "Xunzi (荀子) was a Confucian philosopher of the late Warring States period, one of the most rigorous thinkers of the classical age. He held that human nature is by itself crooked and selfish and must be straightened through ritual, education, and the deliberate effort of moral cultivation. His pupils included leading figures of the next generation, and his realism deeply shaped the statecraft of early imperial China.",
"Mozi": "Mozi (墨子) was a Chinese philosopher of the early Warring States period and the founder of the school of thought known as Mohism. He preached impartial care for all people equally, condemned offensive warfare and lavish display, and prized frugality, merit, and the practical benefit of the common people. A skilled craftsman and logician, he led a disciplined band of followers who put his ideals into practice, including the defence of cities under siege.",
"Shang_Yang": "Shang Yang was a statesman and reformer of the state of Qin during the Warring States period, the chief architect of its rise to power. Serving Duke Xiao, he enacted sweeping Legalist reforms that organized the population into groups of mutual responsibility, rewarded farming and soldiering, and replaced hereditary privilege with strict law and merit. His measures made Qin a formidable centralized power, though he himself fell from favour and was executed after his patron's death.",
"Sun_Tzu": "Sun Tzu (孫子) is the military strategist traditionally honoured as the author of The Art of War, the celebrated Chinese treatise on warfare. Tradition places him in the Spring and Autumn period as a general in the service of the state of Wu, though his historical existence is uncertain and much debated. Whether a real man or a later attribution, the name has become synonymous with the art of strategy.",
"The_Art_of_War": "The Art of War (孫子兵法) is an ancient Chinese treatise on military strategy, traditionally attributed to the strategist Sun Tzu. In thirteen terse chapters it sets out principles of warfare, deception, terrain, and leadership, teaching that the supreme skill is to win without fighting by foreseeing and outthinking the enemy. It is among the most influential works on strategy ever written, studied for over two thousand years in war, politics, and business.",
"Zuo_Zhuan": "The Zuo Zhuan (左傳), or Commentary of Zuo, is an ancient Chinese narrative history covering the Spring and Autumn period in rich and dramatic detail. Cast as a commentary on the terse chronicle of the state of Lu, it expands bare entries into vivid accounts of wars, diplomacy, intrigue, and moral judgement among the rival states. It is both a foundational work of Chinese historiography and a masterpiece of early Chinese prose.",
"Houyi": "Houyi (后羿) is a heroic archer of Chinese mythology, famed for saving the world when ten suns rose into the sky together and scorched the earth. Drawing his great bow, he is said to have shot down nine of the ten suns, leaving the single sun that lights the sky today. In some tales he is rewarded with an elixir of immortality, which becomes bound up with the legend of the moon.",
"Chang'e": "Chang'e (嫦娥) is the goddess of the moon in Chinese mythology, the wife of the heroic archer Houyi. According to legend she swallowed an elixir of immortality and floated up to the moon, where she has dwelt ever since, sometimes in the company of a jade rabbit. She is honoured at the Mid-Autumn Festival, when people gaze at the full moon and share round mooncakes.",
"Queen_Mother_of_the_West": "The Queen Mother of the West (西王母), or Xiwangmu, is a great goddess of Chinese mythology, a powerful female deity dwelling in a paradise amid the far western Kunlun mountains. She is the keeper of the peaches of immortality, which ripen once in thousands of years and confer eternal life on those who eat them. Worshipped from ancient times, she came to be revered in Daoism as a highest goddess and a giver of long life.",
"Jade_Emperor": "The Jade Emperor (玉皇大帝) is the supreme ruler of heaven in Chinese folk religion and Daoism, the highest of the gods who presides over the celestial bureaucracy. Pictured as an emperor enthroned in his court above the clouds, he governs the deities of heaven, earth, and the underworld much as a mortal emperor governs his officials. He hears the reports of lesser gods and weighs the deeds of mortals, dispensing reward and punishment across the cosmos.",
"Analects": "The Analects (論語) is a collection of the sayings, conversations, and teachings of Confucius, compiled by his disciples and their followers after his death. In brief, often aphoristic passages it presents his thought on virtue, ritual, learning, family, and good government, centred on the cultivation of the noble and humane person. Revered for centuries as a core classic of the Confucian canon, it shaped the moral and political ideals of much of East Asia.",
"Zhang_Qian": "Zhang Qian was an envoy and explorer of the Han dynasty, sent west by Emperor Wu to seek allies among the peoples beyond the empire's frontier. His long and perilous journeys through Central Asia brought back the first detailed Chinese knowledge of those distant lands and their kingdoms. By opening regular contact and trade between China and the west, his missions are credited with inaugurating the routes later known as the Silk Road.",
"Liu_Bei": "Liu Bei was a warlord of the late Eastern Han dynasty who became the founding emperor of Shu Han, one of the Three Kingdoms. Despite a humble background and many early defeats, he gathered loyal supporters and carved out a realm in the southwest centered on present-day Sichuan, declaring himself emperor in 221. He is portrayed in the novel Romance of the Three Kingdoms as a model of benevolent and humane rule, an image that made him widely revered in later Chinese culture.",
"Moses": "Moses is a prophet and lawgiver who is the central human figure of the Torah and a major figure in Judaism, Christianity, and Islam. According to the Book of Exodus, he was a Hebrew born in Egypt, drawn from the Nile as an infant and raised in Pharaoh's household, who later led the Israelites out of slavery. He is traditionally credited with receiving the law at Mount Sinai and guiding the people through forty years of wandering toward the land of Canaan.",
"Guqin": "The guqin (古琴) is a plucked seven-stringed Chinese zither with a long, narrow lacquered body and no movable bridges. It is played by plucking the silk or metal strings while sliding and pressing the fingers along the surface to produce glissandos and harmonics. Long associated with scholars and the literati tradition, its music was inscribed by UNESCO as a Masterpiece of the Oral and Intangible Heritage of Humanity in 2003.",
"Gautama_Buddha": "Gautama Buddha, also known as Siddhartha Gautama or Shakyamuni, was a wandering ascetic and spiritual teacher whose teachings became the foundation of Buddhism. According to tradition he was born in Lumbini in present-day Nepal and attained awakening through meditation at Bodh Gaya, after which he taught the Middle Way, the Four Noble Truths, and the Noble Eightfold Path for some forty-five years. He is most commonly dated to roughly the fifth century BCE, and his death is referred to as the parinirvana, or final passing into nirvana.",
"Classic_of_Poetry": "The Classic of Poetry (詩經), also called the Book of Songs, is the oldest existing collection of Chinese poetry, comprising 305 works that date mostly from the 11th to 7th centuries BCE. It is divided into airs of the states, court odes, and hymns, and was traditionally regarded as one of the Five Classics associated with Confucius. Generations of scholars memorized and studied it, and it remains a rich source of four-character classical idioms in modern Chinese.",
"Metaphysics": "Metaphysics is the branch of philosophy that examines the basic nature and most fundamental structure of reality. It investigates topics such as existence, being, the categories into which things divide, identity, possibility and necessity, space and time, and causation. Its questions concern what kinds of things exist and what their nature is, prior to any particular empirical inquiry.",
"Zhang_Daoling": "Zhang Daoling was a religious leader of the Eastern Han dynasty who is traditionally regarded as the founder of organized religious Daoism. He established the Way of the Celestial Masters, a movement that required adherents to donate five pecks of rice and that set up a self-governing theocratic community in the region of Sichuan. His descendants have continued to hold the hereditary title of Celestial Master into modern times.",
"Nephthys": "Nephthys is a goddess of ancient Egyptian religion and a member of the Great Ennead of Heliopolis, the daughter of Geb and Nut. Her name is usually translated as Lady of the House, and she was associated with mourning, the night, embalming, and the protection of the dead. In funerary contexts she was paired with her sister Isis as a guardian of the mummy, and she was regarded as the wife of Set.",
"Mount_Tai": "Mount Tai is a mountain in Shandong Province in eastern China, rising to about 1,545 metres at its highest peak. It is the easternmost of the Five Great Mountains and has been a site of worship for around three thousand years, serving as a major ceremonial centre where emperors performed Feng and Shan sacrifices to Heaven and Earth. It was inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1987.",
"Imperial_examination": "The imperial examination, known in Chinese as the keju, was a civil-service recruitment system in which candidates competed in written examinations to qualify for appointment to the state bureaucracy. Systematized under the Sui dynasty and expanded under the Tang and later dynasties, it tested mastery of the Confucian classics, literary composition, and policy questions through a tiered sequence of local, provincial, and metropolitan examinations. The system shaped the education and social mobility of the gentry for some thirteen centuries until it was abolished in 1905.",
"Zeus": "Zeus is the sky and thunder god of ancient Greek religion and the ruler of the gods of Mount Olympus. He is the youngest child of the Titans Cronus and Rhea, and his siblings include Hades, Poseidon, Hera, Demeter, and Hestia. He is associated with the thunderbolt, the eagle, and the oak, and presides over order, justice, and the rule of law.",
"Ban_Gu": "Ban Gu was an Eastern Han historian, poet, and official who compiled most of the Book of Han, the dynastic history of the Western Han period. He inherited the project from his father Ban Biao and worked on it for decades until his death, after which his sister Ban Zhao completed the unfinished portions. He died in prison in 92 CE following the downfall of his patron, the general Dou Xian.",
"Brahma": "Brahma is the creator god of Hinduism, associated with creation, knowledge, and the Vedas. He is traditionally depicted with four faces pointing to the cardinal directions and four arms holding sacred texts, prayer beads, a ritual ladle, and a water vessel, with the swan as his mount. Though prominent in early texts, his independent worship declined over the centuries, and his consort is the goddess Saraswati.",
"Epic_of_Gilgamesh": "The Epic of Gilgamesh is an ancient Mesopotamian poem regarded as one of the earliest surviving works of literature, recounting the adventures of Gilgamesh, king of Uruk, and his companion Enkidu. Its standard Akkadian version, compiled from older Sumerian poems, is traditionally credited to the scribe Sin-leqi-unninni, while an Old Babylonian version dates to around 1800 BCE. The latter portion of the narrative follows Gilgamesh in his grief-driven quest for immortality, which includes an account of a great flood survived by Utnapishtim.",
"Hongwu_Emperor": "The Hongwu Emperor, born Zhu Yuanzhang, was the founder and first emperor of the Ming dynasty, reigning from 1368 to 1398. Rising from a poor peasant family and a period as a Buddhist monk, he led rebel forces that drove the Mongol Yuan dynasty out of China and established his capital at Nanjing. His reign was marked by sweeping centralizing reforms, a detailed legal code, and brutal purges of officials suspected of disloyalty.",
"Nezha": "Nezha (哪吒) is a protection deity in Chinese folk religion, Taoism, and Buddhism, often titled Marshal of the Central Altar and the Third Lotus Prince. His name derives from the yaksha figure Nalakuvara of Tantric Buddhist texts, and he is most fully developed in the Ming novel Fengshen Yanyi, where he is born as a ball of flesh to the general Li Jing and reincarnated into a body of lotus. Popular legend recounts his battle against the dragon spirits of the sea, his self-sacrifice to spare his parents, and his veneration as a youthful, fiery warrior wielding fire-wheels and a sky-ribbon.",
"Thor": "Thor is a hammer-wielding god in Norse and wider Germanic mythology, associated with thunder, storms, strength, the protection of humankind, and the sanctifying of fertility. He is the son of the chief god Odin and the personified earth Jörð, the husband of the golden-haired goddess Sif, and the father of the goddess Þrúðr. His chief attribute is the hammer Mjölnir, with which he defends the gods and people against hostile jötnar.",
"Liezi": "The Liezi (列子) is a Daoist text traditionally attributed to the philosopher Lie Yukou, who is held to have lived around the 5th century BCE, and is counted among the principal classics of Daoism alongside the Daodejing and the Zhuangzi. The received text, arranged in eight chapters, was compiled much later, around the 4th century CE, and incorporates earlier material along with passages shared with other pre-Han writings. It is known for its fables, cosmological speculation, and a fatalistic, naturalistic outlook on life and death.",
"Papermaking": "Papermaking is the process of manufacturing paper from cellulose fibres, typically by suspending macerated plant or rag fibre in water, draining it on a screen to form a thin mat, and pressing and drying the resulting sheet. The product provides a cheap, lightweight, and durable surface for writing, printing, and packaging. Modern industrial papermaking uses wood pulp and powered machinery to produce paper in vast continuous rolls.",
"Wang_Anshi": "Wang Anshi was a Chinese economist, statesman, and poet of the Northern Song dynasty who served as chancellor under Emperor Shenzong. He is best known for designing and implementing the sweeping fiscal, military, and agrarian reforms known as the New Policies. His reform program provoked intense factional conflict at court, with conservatives led by Sima Guang opposing it.",
"Emperor_Taizong_of_Tang": "Emperor Taizong of Tang (唐太宗), personal name Li Shimin, was the second emperor of the Tang dynasty and is traditionally regarded as a co-founder of the dynasty for urging his father Li Yuan to rebel against the Sui. His reign, known as the Reign of Zhenguan, is celebrated as a golden age of effective governance and later studied as a model for crown princes. He greatly expanded Tang power across Central Asia, defeating the Eastern Turkic Khaganate and annexing oasis states along the Silk Road.",
"Carthage": "Carthage was an ancient city in North Africa, on the eastern side of the Lake of Tunis in what is now Tunisia, founded as a Phoenician colony according to tradition by the legendary queen Dido. It grew into a wealthy maritime trading power whose commercial network spanned the western Mediterranean. The city was destroyed by the Roman Republic in 146 BCE at the end of the Third Punic War and later rebuilt as a Roman provincial center.",
"Zhuge_Liang": "Zhuge Liang, courtesy name Kongming, was a statesman, strategist, and inventor who served as chancellor of the state of Shu Han during the Three Kingdoms period. Recruited by Liu Bei after the famous three visits to his thatched cottage, he became the principal architect of Shu policy and led several northern campaigns against Cao Wei before dying on campaign at the Wuzhang Plains. Celebrated for his ingenuity and loyalty, he became one of the most renowned figures of Chinese history and a symbol of wisdom and devotion.",
"David": "David is described in the Hebrew Bible as the second king of the united Kingdom of Israel and Judah, succeeding Saul. The narrative portrays him as a shepherd and musician who killed the Philistine giant Goliath, rose to the throne, and made Jerusalem his capital. He is venerated as an ideal ruler and an ancestor of a promised future king, and is also regarded as a prophet in Islam.",
"Guzheng": "The guzheng (古箏) is a Chinese plucked zither with movable bridges, typically strung with 21 or more strings over a long resonant soundboard of paulownia wood. Each string passes over an individual bridge that can be shifted to set the pitch, and the instrument is usually tuned to a pentatonic scale. Its earliest forms date to the Warring States period, and it became one of the most widely played instruments during the Tang dynasty.",
"Bodhidharma": "Bodhidharma was a semi-legendary Buddhist monk traditionally credited with transmitting Chan Buddhism to China and is regarded as its first Chinese patriarch. Sources place his life in the fifth or sixth century CE and describe him as coming from the Western Regions, either Central Asia or South India. Later tradition also linked him to the martial arts of the Shaolin Monastery, an association that scholars consider a much later legend.",
"Book_of_Rites": "The Book of Rites (禮記), or Liji, is a collection of texts describing the social forms, governmental system, and ceremonial rites of the Zhou dynasty as understood in the Warring States and early Han periods. The received version of 49 chapters was edited by Dai Sheng and later annotated by the Han scholar Zheng Xuan. It counts among the Five Classics and includes the chapters that became the Great Learning and the Doctrine of the Mean.",
"Epistemology": "Epistemology is the branch of philosophy that studies the nature, sources, and limits of knowledge. It analyzes concepts such as belief, truth, justification, and evidence, and asks how people come to know things and whether certainty is attainable. The field examines sources of knowledge including perception, memory, reasoning, and testimony, along with challenges raised by skepticism.",
"Way_of_the_Celestial_Masters": "The Way of the Celestial Masters (天師道) was the first enduring organized Daoist movement, founded by Zhang Daoling in 142 CE in what is now Sichuan. It administered a community through a hierarchy of priestly officials, collected donations of rice from members, and used talismans, petitions to deities, and confession of sins to cure illness and ensure good fortune. The movement gave rise to later lineages of Daoist clergy who trace their authority to its founder.",
"Khnum": "Khnum is an ancient Egyptian deity associated with creation, fertility, and the source of the Nile. He was depicted as a man with the head of a ram or as a full ram, and was believed to fashion the bodies of humans and gods from clay on a potter's wheel. His principal cult center was on the island of Elephantine near the First Cataract, where he was venerated as lord of the inundation.",
"Huashan": "Mount Hua is a mountain near the city of Huayin in Shaanxi Province, China, lying at the eastern end of the Qinling range about 120 kilometres east of Xi'an. It is the westernmost of the Five Great Mountains and one of the holiest sites of Daoism, with its highest South Peak reaching roughly 2,155 metres. The mountain is known for its steep granite peaks and narrow cliffside paths, and it has long drawn pilgrims and Daoist hermits.",
"Scholar-official": "A scholar-official, or shidafu, was a member of the educated elite who staffed the civil bureaucracy of imperial China after qualifying through study of the Confucian classics, often by passing the imperial examinations. Such officials combined the roles of administrator, scholar, and frequently poet, painter, or calligrapher, and formed the dominant social and political class for much of Chinese history. In Western writing they are often called mandarins, a term derived from the Portuguese rendering of the word for an official.",
"Hera": "Hera is the ancient Greek goddess of marriage, women, and family, and a queen among the Olympian deities. She is the daughter of the Titans Cronus and Rhea and the wife of Zeus, with whom she bore Ares, Hephaestus, Hebe, and Eileithyia. Her sacred animals include the peacock and the cow, and many myths recount her jealousy toward the lovers and children of Zeus.",
"Ban_Zhao": "Ban Zhao was an Eastern Han scholar regarded as the first known female Chinese historian, who completed the Book of Han after the death of her brother Ban Gu by supplying its missing tables and the treatise on astronomy. She served as a court librarian and tutor to Empress Deng Sui, gaining considerable influence at the imperial court. She also wrote Lessons for Women, a treatise on female conduct that remained widely read for centuries.",
"Vishnu": "Vishnu is one of the principal deities of Hinduism, revered as the preserver and protector of the cosmos. When order and righteousness are threatened, he is said to descend to earth in the form of avatars to restore balance and protect dharma. His consort is the goddess Lakshmi, and he is the supreme being for the Vaishnava traditions.",
"Gilgamesh": "Gilgamesh was a legendary ruler of the city of Uruk who appears as the hero of the Epic of Gilgamesh and several earlier Sumerian poems. The Sumerian King List places him as a king of the First Dynasty of Uruk, and he was credited with building the city's great walls. In later tradition he was deified and worshipped as a judge of the underworld, blending a possible historical figure with extensive myth.",
"Yongle_Emperor": "The Yongle Emperor, personal name Zhu Di, was the third emperor of the Ming dynasty, reigning from 1402 to 1424 after seizing the throne from his nephew in a civil war. He moved the capital from Nanjing to Beijing, where he ordered the construction of the Forbidden City, and commissioned the vast Yongle Encyclopedia. He also sponsored the great maritime expeditions of the admiral Zheng He, projecting Ming power across the Indian Ocean.",
"Erlang_Shen": "Erlang Shen (二郎神) is a warrior god in Chinese folk religion and Taoism associated with water control, demon-subduing, hunting, and justice, recognizable by a third truth-seeing eye in the middle of his forehead. He is often identified with Li Erlang, said to be the son of the Qin-dynasty hydraulic engineer Li Bing, and is accompanied by a hunting hound called Xiaotian Quan. He appears in the novel Journey to the West, where he is dispatched by the Jade Emperor to capture the Monkey King.",
"Loki": "Loki is a shape-shifting trickster figure in Norse mythology, the son of the jötunn Fárbauti and Laufey, who moves between the worlds of the gods and the giants. By the jötunn Angrboða he fathered the wolf Fenrir, the serpent Jörmungandr, and the being Hel, and in the form of a mare he bore the eight-legged horse Sleipnir. He engineers the death of the god Baldr and is bound by the gods as punishment, but is foretold to break free at Ragnarök and fight against them.",
"Yang_Zhu": "Yang Zhu (楊朱; 440–c. 360 BCE) was an early Chinese philosopher whose thought centered on self-preservation and the principle of weiwo, or acting for oneself. He held that a person should value bodily integrity and personal well-being above external gains and should neither sacrifice the self for the world nor harm others for profit. His ideas were prominent enough during the Warring States period to be singled out for attack by Mencius, though no work of his survives and his views are known mainly through later texts.",
"Woodblock_printing": "Woodblock printing is a technique for reproducing text or images by carving a design in relief on the surface of a wooden block, inking the raised areas, and pressing the block onto paper or cloth. A single carved block can yield many identical impressions before it wears out, making it an early means of mass reproduction. The method was long used for books, illustrations, and patterned textiles.",
"Sima_Guang": "Sima Guang was a Chinese historian, scholar-official, and chief councillor of the Northern Song dynasty. He directed the compilation of the Zizhi Tongjian (資治通鑑), a vast chronological history of China from 403 BCE to 959 CE intended as a guide to statecraft. He led the conservative faction that opposed Wang Anshi and rolled back the New Policies when he came to power in 1085.",
"Wu_Zetian": "Wu Zetian (武則天) was the only woman in Chinese history to rule as emperor in her own right, having risen from imperial consort to become the sole sovereign of China. After serving as a consort to Emperor Taizong and then empress to Emperor Gaozong, she wielded power as empress dowager behind her sons Emperor Zhongzong and Emperor Ruizong before declaring herself emperor in 690. Her accession founded her own Wu Zhou dynasty, which interrupted the Tang for fifteen years until a palace coup in 705 forced her to abdicate and the Tang was restored.",
"Punic_Wars": "The Punic Wars were a series of three conflicts fought between the Roman Republic and Carthage between 264 and 146 BCE. They were waged largely over control of the western Mediterranean and included Hannibal's invasion of Italy during the Second Punic War. Rome's victory ended with the destruction of Carthage and established Roman dominance across the region.",
"Guan_Yu": "Guan Yu was a general who served the warlord Liu Bei during the late Eastern Han dynasty and the founding of Shu Han. Renowned for his martial prowess and personal loyalty, he captured wide fame for feats such as defeating Yan Liang and was eventually killed after the loss of Jing Province to allied Cao Wei and Eastern Wu forces. In later centuries he was deified as a god of war and brotherhood, venerated in temples across China under titles such as Guandi.",
"Solomon": "Solomon is described in the Hebrew Bible as a king of Israel and the son and successor of David. He is portrayed as a wise and wealthy monarch who built the First Temple in Jerusalem and is traditionally credited with authorship of several biblical books. He appears as a prophet in Islam, where he is known for his wisdom and his command over animals and spirits.",
"Pipa": "The pipa (琵琶) is a four-stringed Chinese plucked instrument with a pear-shaped wooden body and frets along its neck and soundboard. It is held upright and played with the fingers of the right hand, often using rapid tremolo and strumming techniques. The pear-shaped form reached China along trade routes from Central Asia and was well established by the Tang dynasty.",
"Xuanzang": "Xuanzang was a Chinese Buddhist monk, scholar, and translator famous for a seventeen-year overland pilgrimage to the Indian subcontinent in search of Buddhist scriptures. He studied at the monastic university of Nalanda and returned with hundreds of Sanskrit texts, many of which he translated into Chinese, and he is associated with the East Asian Yogachara tradition. His travel account, the Records of the Western Regions, is a major source on seventh-century India and Central Asia and later inspired the novel Journey to the West.",
"Rites_of_Zhou": "The Rites of Zhou (周禮), originally titled Officers of Zhou, is a Chinese work on bureaucracy and organizational theory that idealizes the administrative structure of the Zhou government. It describes a system of six ministries, detailing the duties and ranks of hundreds of official posts across governance, finance, rites, the military, justice, and public works. Most scholars date its composition to around the 3rd century BCE, and it is counted among the ritual classics.",
"Ontology": "Ontology is the philosophical study of being and existence. It asks what kinds of entities exist, what features all entities share, and how they may be sorted into basic categories such as objects, properties, relations, and events. A central concern is the division between particular things and the universals they may instantiate.",
"Way_of_the_Five_Pecks_of_Rice": "The Way of the Five Pecks of Rice (五斗米道) was an early Daoist religious community founded by Zhang Daoling in 142 CE that took its name from the rice contribution required of its members. It governed a theocratic state in the Hanzhong valley, organizing followers under priestly officials and emphasizing the curing of disease through confession, talismans, and the proper balance of qi. The community was absorbed into the domain of the warlord Cao Cao in the early third century CE.",
"Sobek": "Sobek is an ancient Egyptian deity associated with the Nile crocodile, depicted as a crocodile or as a man with a crocodile head. He was linked to fertility, military prowess, and the life-giving waters of the river, and was thought to protect against the dangers of the Nile. His major cult centers were at Crocodilopolis in the Faiyum and at Kom Ombo, where crocodiles were kept and mummified in his honor.",
"Mount_Emei": "Mount Emei is a mountain in Sichuan Province, southwestern China, rising to about 3,099 metres at its summit. It is one of the Four Sacred Buddhist Mountains and is traditionally regarded as the place of enlightenment of the bodhisattva Samantabhadra. The mountain holds dozens of temples and monasteries and was inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1996.",
"Jinshi": "Jinshi was the highest and most prestigious degree awarded in the Chinese imperial examination system, conferred on candidates who passed the metropolitan and palace examinations held in the capital. Holders of the degree became eligible for the most senior posts in the bureaucracy and enjoyed great social distinction. The title was first established as an examination category under the Sui dynasty and endured until the examinations were abolished in 1905.",
"Poseidon": "Poseidon is the ancient Greek god of the sea, earthquakes, storms, and horses. He is a son of the Titans Cronus and Rhea and a brother of Zeus and Hades, with whom he divided dominion over the cosmos after the defeat of the Titans. His chief attribute is the trident, a three-pronged spear with which he was said to stir the seas and split the earth.",
"Ban_Chao": "Ban Chao was an Eastern Han general and diplomat who spent more than three decades reasserting Han control over the Western Regions of the Tarim Basin against the Xiongnu. Skillfully exploiting divisions among rival states, he brought more than fifty kingdoms into submission and was named Protector General of the Western Regions in 91 CE. In 97 CE he dispatched the envoy Gan Ying westward in an attempt to reach the Roman Empire.",
"Shiva": "Shiva is one of the principal deities of Hinduism, known as the destroyer and transformer who recycles and renews existence. He is typically depicted with a third eye on his forehead, a crescent moon in his hair, a serpent around his neck, and a trident, and is associated with both fierce and benevolent aspects. He is the supreme being of the Shaiva traditions, and his consort is the goddess Parvati.",
"Enkidu": "Enkidu is a central figure in the Epic of Gilgamesh, created by the gods as a wild man who lives among animals before being civilized through contact with humans. He becomes the close companion of Gilgamesh, joining him in adventures that include slaying the guardian Humbaba and the Bull of Heaven. His death, decreed by the gods as punishment, drives Gilgamesh into mourning and his subsequent search for eternal life.",
"Wanli_Emperor": "The Wanli Emperor, personal name Zhu Yijun, was the fourteenth emperor of the Ming dynasty and its longest-reigning ruler, holding the throne from 1572 to 1620. His early reign was guided by the able Grand Secretary Zhang Juzheng, during which state finances and administration reached a high point of efficiency. After Zhang's death the emperor gradually withdrew from active governance, leaving disputes and factional struggles that historians often link to the dynasty's later decline.",
"Guanyin": "Guanyin (觀音) is the bodhisattva of compassion in Chinese Buddhism, the East Asian form of the Sanskrit Avalokiteśvara, whose name renders the idea of perceiving the sounds or cries of the world. Introduced to China as a male figure, the bodhisattva came over the centuries to be widely depicted and worshipped in female form. Guanyin is venerated for vowing to relieve the suffering of all beings and is invoked for mercy, childbirth, and protection across folk religion, Taoism, and Buddhism.",
"Freyja": "Freyja is a goddess of the Vanir in Norse mythology, associated with love, beauty, fertility, gold, war, and the magical practice of seiðr. She owns the necklace Brísingamen, rides a chariot drawn by two cats, and possesses a falcon-feather cloak that allows flight. She rules the afterlife field Fólkvangr, where she receives half of those who die in battle, and she is the daughter of Njörðr and sister of Freyr.",
"Hui_Shi": "Hui Shi (惠施; c. 370–310 BCE) was a Chinese philosopher of the Warring States period associated with the School of Names and a chief minister of the state of Wei. He is remembered for a series of ten theses, preserved in the Zhuangzi, that explore the relativity of sameness and difference, space, time, and the unity of all things. His own writings are lost, and he appears in classical sources as a frequent interlocutor and debating partner of Zhuangzi.",
"Movable_type": "Movable type is a system of printing in which text is assembled from many small reusable pieces, each bearing a single character, letter, or symbol, locked together in a frame to print a page. After printing, the pieces can be cleaned and rearranged to compose new pages, sparing the labour of cutting a fresh surface for every text. Type has been made from materials such as fired clay, wood, and cast metal.",
"Su_Shi": "Su Shi, also known by his art name Dongpo, was a Chinese poet, essayist, calligrapher, painter, and scholar-official of the Song dynasty. He is counted among the Eight Masters of Tang and Song prose and the Four Masters of Song calligraphy, and he advanced the bold haofang style of ci poetry. His official career was repeatedly disrupted by exile during the factional struggles over Wang Anshi's reforms.",
"Emperor_Gaozong_of_Tang": "Emperor Gaozong of Tang (唐高宗), personal name Li Zhi, was the third emperor of the Tang dynasty, reigning from 649 to 683 as the ninth son and successor of Emperor Taizong. During his reign the empire reached its greatest territorial extent, as Tang armies destroyed the Western Turkic Khaganate and, in alliance with Silla, conquered the Korean kingdoms of Baekje and Goguryeo. In his later years, increasingly incapacitated by illness, he ceded much of the conduct of government to his consort Empress Wu, the future Wu Zetian, who wielded power so forcefully alongside him that the two were known as the Two Saints.",
"Hannibal": "Hannibal was a Carthaginian general regarded as one of the greatest military commanders of antiquity. During the Second Punic War he led an army with war elephants across the Alps to invade Italy, where he won a celebrated victory at the Battle of Cannae in 216 BCE. He was ultimately defeated by Roman forces at the Battle of Zama in 202 BCE.",
"Zhang_Fei": "Zhang Fei was a military general who served the warlord Liu Bei from the early days of his career through the founding of Shu Han. Celebrated for his ferocity in battle, he is famously said to have held off pursuing enemies at the Changban bridge during Liu Bei's flight from Cao Cao. He was murdered by his own subordinates on the eve of a campaign against Eastern Wu and is remembered in legend as a bold and fearsome warrior.",
"Adam": "Adam is the first man created by God in the creation narratives of Judaism, Christianity, and Islam. According to the Book of Genesis, he was formed from the dust of the ground, placed in the Garden of Eden, and given Eve as a companion. The story of his disobedience in eating forbidden fruit is central to several traditions about the human condition.",
"Erhu": "The erhu (二胡) is a two-stringed Chinese bowed instrument with a small resonator covered in python skin and a long neck without a fingerboard. The bow hair is fixed permanently between the two strings, and the player stops the strings by pressing them without pushing them against the neck. Its expressive, vocal tone makes it a leading melodic instrument in Chinese folk music and opera.",
"Faxian": "Faxian was a Chinese Buddhist monk and translator who journeyed overland to India and back by sea to obtain Buddhist texts and visit sacred sites. Setting out around 399 CE in old age, he travelled the Silk Road, spent about a decade in India, and recorded his experiences in an account known as the Record of Buddhist Kingdoms. His writings provide an important historical record of Buddhism and geography across early fifth-century Central Asia, India, and Sri Lanka.",
"Erya": "The Erya (爾雅) is the earliest surviving Chinese dictionary, a glossary that defines roughly 4,300 words across 2,094 entries. Its nineteen sections begin with chapters explaining abstract terms and then group concrete vocabulary by subject, covering kinship, buildings, astronomy, geography, plants, and animals. Compiled over the late Warring States and early Han periods, it became a standard reference and was eventually included among the Confucian classics.",
"Logic": "Logic is the study of correct reasoning and the principles that determine whether an argument's premises support its conclusion. It distinguishes deductive arguments, in which true premises guarantee a true conclusion, from inductive arguments, in which premises make a conclusion more probable. Formal logic analyzes the structure of inference using symbolic systems and rules that apply regardless of subject matter.",
"Zhengyi_Dao": "Zhengyi Dao (正一道), the Way of Orthodox Unity, is a major Daoist tradition descended from the lineage of the Celestial Masters and is one of the two dominant forms of Daoism in China today. Its priests are often married and live among the laity, performing rituals, exorcisms, and talismanic practices for their communities rather than withdrawing into monastic life. The tradition is historically centered on Mount Longhu in Jiangxi and is led by a hereditary Celestial Master claiming descent from Zhang Daoling.",
"Bastet": "Bastet is a goddess of ancient Egyptian religion who was worshipped as early as the Second Dynasty. Originally portrayed as a lioness, she came increasingly to be depicted as a domestic cat or a cat-headed woman and was associated with protection, the home, fertility, and music. Her chief cult center was at Bubastis in the Nile Delta, where large numbers of mummified cats have been discovered.",
"Mount_Wutai": "Mount Wutai is a mountain in Shanxi Province, northern China, whose northern peak reaches about 3,061 metres, the highest point in North China. It is one of the Four Sacred Buddhist Mountains and is venerated as the abode of Manjusri, the bodhisattva of wisdom. The area preserves some of China's oldest surviving timber buildings, including Tang-dynasty temple halls, and was inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2009.",
"Eunuchs_in_China": "Eunuchs in China were castrated men who served within the imperial palace, tending the inner quarters, the harem, and the person of the emperor. Their intimate access to the ruler frequently allowed individual eunuchs and eunuch factions to accumulate considerable political power, and at several points in history they dominated court affairs. They formed a distinct administrative body that persisted from antiquity through the end of the Qing dynasty in the early twentieth century.",
"Hades": "Hades is the ancient Greek god of the underworld and the realm of the dead, which also bears his name. He is a son of the Titans Cronus and Rhea and a brother of Zeus and Poseidon, receiving the underworld as his domain when the brothers divided the cosmos. He carried off Persephone to be his queen and was associated with wealth drawn from beneath the earth and with a helmet that conferred invisibility.",
"Huo_Qubing": "Huo Qubing was a Western Han cavalry general who won a series of decisive victories over the Xiongnu under Emperor Wu before dying at about the age of twenty-three. His campaigns of 121 BCE through the Hexi Corridor and his role in the 119 BCE Battle of Mobei broke Xiongnu power in the northwest and opened the route to the Western Regions. He was a nephew of the general Wei Qing and a half-brother of the statesman Huo Guang.",
"Trimurti": "The Trimurti is a concept in Hinduism in which the cosmic functions of creation, preservation, and destruction are personified by three deities. Brahma serves as the creator, Vishnu as the preserver, and Shiva as the destroyer. The grouping expresses the cyclical processes by which the universe is generated, sustained, and dissolved.",
"Anu": "Anu was the Mesopotamian god of the sky and king of the gods, regarded as an ancestor of many other deities. His authority was often largely ceremonial, with practical power exercised by gods such as Enlil, though his name remained a source of legitimacy for rulers and divinities alike. His principal cult center was the city of Uruk, where his worship was revived during the Seleucid period.",
"Chongzhen_Emperor": "The Chongzhen Emperor, personal name Zhu Youjian, was the seventeenth and last emperor of the Ming dynasty, reigning from 1627 to 1644. He inherited a state weakened by an empty treasury, factional politics, peasant rebellions, and mounting Manchu pressure on the northern frontier. When the rebel forces of Li Zicheng captured Beijing in 1644, he took his own life on a hill behind the palace, ending Ming rule in the capital.",
"Dragon_King": "The Dragon King (龍王), or Longwang, is a water and weather deity in Chinese folk religion and Taoism who commands the seas, rivers, rainfall, and all aquatic creatures. He is frequently multiplied into the Dragon Kings of the Four Seas, presiding over the eastern, southern, western, and northern waters and bearing the surname Ao. Fishermen and farmers offered sacrifices to him for safe voyages, abundant catches, and timely rains during the planting season.",
"Freyr": "Freyr is a god of the Vanir in Norse mythology, associated with kingship, fertility, peace, prosperity, fair weather, and good harvests. Among his possessions are the ship Skíðblaðnir, which always finds a favorable wind, and the golden-bristled boar Gullinbursti. He is the son of Njörðr and the brother of Freyja, and he gives away his sword to win the giantess Gerðr, a loss that leaves him fated to fall at Ragnarök.",
"Gongsun_Long": "Gongsun Long (公孫龍; c. 320–250 BCE) was a Chinese philosopher of the Warring States period and a leading figure of the School of Names. He is best known for the argument that a white horse is not a horse, which turns on distinctions between class membership and identity, and for analyses of names and reality and of hardness and whiteness. His collected work, the Gongsun Longzi, originally held fourteen essays, of which six survive.",
"Gunpowder": "Gunpowder is an explosive mixture of saltpetre, charcoal, and sulfur that burns extremely rapidly, producing a large volume of hot gas. The earliest known chemical explosive, it has been used for fireworks, signalling, blasting in mining and construction, and as the propellant in early firearms and artillery. Its adoption in weapons transformed warfare, and it remained the dominant explosive until more powerful modern compounds were developed.",
"Zhu_Xi": "Zhu Xi was a Chinese philosopher and scholar-official who became the central figure of Song Neo-Confucianism. He synthesized earlier thought into a coherent system organizing study around the Four Books, whose commentaries he wrote and which later formed the basis of the civil service examinations. His rationalist school, known as the Cheng-Zhu school, shaped orthodox thought across later imperial China.",
"Emperor_Xuanzong_of_Tang": "Emperor Xuanzong of Tang (唐玄宗), personal name Li Longji, was an emperor of the Tang dynasty who reigned from 712 to 756, the longest reign of the dynasty. During the early Kaiyuan era his able administration and merit-based governance brought the Tang to a cultural and economic zenith widely regarded as a high point of imperial China. His later infatuation with Consort Yang Guifei and neglect of government allowed corrupt ministers to dominate the court and helped precipitate the catastrophic An Lushan rebellion, which forced him to flee the capital Chang'an for Sichuan and abdicate in favor of his son, Emperor Suzong.",
"Seleucid_Empire": "The Seleucid Empire was a Hellenistic state founded by Seleucus I Nicator, one of the generals who divided the conquests of Alexander the Great after his death. At its height it stretched from the Aegean coast of Anatolia eastward through Mesopotamia, Persia, and into Central Asia. It declined under pressure from Parthia and Rome and was finally absorbed by Rome in 63 BCE.",
"Zhou_Yu": "Zhou Yu was a military general and strategist who served the warlord Sun Quan during the late Eastern Han dynasty. As chief commander of the allied forces of Sun Quan and Liu Bei, he led the campaign that defeated Cao Cao's much larger army at the Battle of Red Cliffs in 208. Admired for his refinement and skill, he died young while planning further expansion and is remembered as one of the great commanders of his age.",
"Eve": "Eve is the first woman in the creation accounts of Judaism, Christianity, and Islam, and the wife of Adam. According to the Book of Genesis, she was formed from Adam's rib and lived with him in the Garden of Eden. The narrative recounts that she was persuaded by a serpent to eat fruit from a forbidden tree, an act that led to their expulsion from the garden.",
"Dizi_(instrument)": "The dizi (笛子) is a Chinese transverse flute usually made of bamboo, with finger holes and a blowing hole bored along its length. A distinctive feature is the dimo, a thin membrane of reed glued over an extra hole, which gives the instrument a bright, buzzing timbre. It is used widely in folk music, opera accompaniment, and modern Chinese orchestras.",
"Huineng": "Huineng was a Tang dynasty Chan master traditionally honored as the Sixth Patriarch of Chan Buddhism. He is associated with the Southern school and its teaching of sudden enlightenment, and the Platform Sutra, which recounts his life and sermons, is attributed to him. Much of his traditional biography was shaped by later followers, and modern scholars regard many details of his life as legendary.",
"Shuowen_Jiezi": "The Shuowen Jiezi (說文解字) is an early Chinese dictionary compiled by the Eastern Han scholar Xu Shen and presented to the throne in 121 CE. It offered the first systematic analysis of the structure of Chinese characters, explaining how each was formed and grouping graphs under 540 shared components known as radicals. This organizing principle was a major innovation in understanding the writing system and shaped Chinese lexicography for centuries.",
"Cosmology": "Cosmology is the study of the universe as a whole, including its origin, large-scale structure, evolution, and eventual fate. In its scientific form it draws on physics and astronomy to model phenomena such as the expansion of space and the distribution of matter. The term also names philosophical and religious accounts that describe the overall order and nature of the cosmos.",
"Quanzhen_School": "The Quanzhen School (全真道), meaning Complete Perfection, is a major monastic tradition of Daoism founded in the twelfth century by Wang Chongyang in the Shandong region. It emphasizes internal cultivation through neidan, asceticism, celibacy, and meditation, and it drew on Daoist, Buddhist, and Confucian teachings in its program of self-transformation. It is one of the two principal forms of Daoism in modern China and maintains large monastic centers such as the White Cloud Temple in Beijing.",
"Khonsu": "Khonsu is an ancient Egyptian lunar deity whose name is connected to the idea of traveling or crossing the sky. He was commonly depicted as a youth wearing a sidelock of hair and a crown combining a crescent and a full lunar disc. At Thebes he formed a divine family with the god Amun and the goddess Mut, and he was credited with powers of healing and the driving out of malevolent spirits.",
"Qinling": "The Qinling is a major east-west mountain range in southern Shaanxi Province, China, with its highest peak, Mount Taibai, reaching about 3,767 metres. It marks the divide between the drainage basins of the Yellow River and the Yangtze and forms a natural boundary between North and South China. The range is ecologically rich and shelters wildlife including a population of giant pandas.",
"Three_Departments_and_Six_Ministries": "The Three Departments and Six Ministries, in Chinese sansheng liubu, was the central administrative structure of the Chinese government from the Sui dynasty onward. The three departments handled the drafting of policy, the review of policy, and the execution of policy, while the six ministries oversaw personnel, revenue, rites, war, justice, and public works. By dividing authority among separate organs, the system limited the concentration of power and provided a durable model for later imperial administration.",
"Demeter": "Demeter is the ancient Greek goddess of agriculture, grain, and the harvest. She is a daughter of the Titans Cronus and Rhea, and the mother of Persephone by Zeus. Her grief at the abduction of her daughter was said to bring barrenness to the earth, and she was a central figure of the Eleusinian Mysteries.",
"Wei_Qing": "Wei Qing was a Western Han general who rose from humble origins to become Grand General through repeated victories over the Xiongnu under Emperor Wu. A half-brother of Empress Wei Zifu and uncle of Huo Qubing, he commanded the Han forces that won the 119 BCE Battle of Mobei, driving the Xiongnu north of the Gobi Desert. He was noted by historians for remaining modest despite his great power and imperial favor.",
"Krishna": "Krishna is a major deity in Hinduism, worshipped both as the eighth avatar of Vishnu and as the supreme god in his own right. He is a central figure in the epic Mahabharata, where he serves as charioteer to the warrior Arjuna and delivers the teachings of the Bhagavad Gita on the eve of the Kurukshetra War. Stories of his childhood, his role as a divine cowherd, and his romantic and heroic exploits are central to many devotional traditions.",
"Enlil": "Enlil was a Mesopotamian deity associated with wind, air, earth, and storms who served as the chief god of the Sumerian pantheon. His main place of worship was the Ekur temple at Nippur, which was held to be the bond linking heaven and earth. He rose to prominence in the third millennium BCE and was later eclipsed by Marduk as the supreme deity following the decline of Nippur.",
"Zhang_Juzheng": "Zhang Juzheng was a Ming dynasty statesman who served as Senior Grand Secretary from 1572 to 1582, effectively governing China during the youth of the Wanli Emperor. He implemented fiscal and administrative reforms, including a nationwide land survey and the consolidation of taxes into silver payments known as the Single Whip reform. After his death his policies were largely reversed and his family was disgraced, though he was later rehabilitated as one of the dynasty's most capable administrators.",
"Yanluo_Wang": "Yanluo Wang (閻羅王) is the god of death and ruler of Diyu, the underworld of Chinese mythology, whose name transcribes the Sanskrit King Yama introduced through Buddhism. He sits in judgment over the dead, weighing their deeds to assign reward, punishment, or a future rebirth, and is conventionally portrayed as a stern, red-faced man with bulging eyes and a long beard. He presides over the Ten Kings of Hell and is attended by the guardians Ox-Head and Horse-Face, who bring the newly deceased before him.",
"Frigg": "Frigg is a goddess of the Æsir in Norse mythology, associated with marriage, motherhood, prophecy, and clairvoyance, and she is portrayed as the wife of Odin. She is the mother of the god Baldr, and she secures oaths from all things not to harm him, overlooking only the mistletoe that ultimately causes his death. She dwells in the wetland hall Fensalir and is said to know the fates of all though she speaks little of them.",
"School_of_Names": "The School of Names (名家) was a current of thought in the Warring States period concerned with the relationship between language, names, and reality. Its associated thinkers, including Deng Xi, Hui Shi, Yin Wen, and Gongsun Long, engaged in logical and linguistic analysis and produced paradoxes that probed how words correspond to things. Most of its writings were lost, surviving mainly as fragments of Gongsun Long's work and as references in texts such as the Zhuangzi.",
"Compass": "A compass is an instrument for finding direction, in its traditional form a freely pivoting magnetized needle that aligns with the Earth's magnetic field to point toward magnetic north. By giving a fixed bearing independent of landmarks, sun, or stars, it made reliable navigation possible in fog, darkness, and the open sea. Later designs include the gyrocompass and electronic compasses that do not depend on magnetism.",
"Neo-Confucianism": "Neo-Confucianism (理學; lǐxué) is a revival and reformulation of Confucian ethics, metaphysics, and social philosophy that took mature shape during the Song dynasty. It sought a rational moral cosmology centered on the concepts of li, or principle, and qi, or vital force, while drawing on and responding to Buddhist and Daoist ideas. The tradition became the dominant intellectual framework of later imperial China and influenced Korea, Japan, and Vietnam.",
"Empress_Wei_(Tang_dynasty)": "Empress Wei (韋皇后) was the wife of Emperor Zhongzong of Tang and sought to emulate Wu Zetian by taking de facto control of government during her husband's second reign. She is traditionally believed to have orchestrated Zhongzong's death by poisoning in 710, acting with her daughter Princess Anle. After becoming empress dowager she served as regent for only seventeen days before being overthrown and killed in a coup led by Li Longji and Princess Taiping.",
"Ptolemaic_Kingdom": "The Ptolemaic Kingdom was a Hellenistic state in Egypt founded by Ptolemy I Soter, a Macedonian general of Alexander the Great. Ruled from Alexandria, it blended Greek and Egyptian traditions and became a major center of Hellenistic learning and trade. The dynasty ended with the death of Cleopatra VII in 30 BCE, after which Egypt became a Roman province.",
"Sun_Ce": "Sun Ce was a warlord of the late Eastern Han dynasty who conquered much of the Jiangdong region in the lower Yangtze, laying the territorial foundation for the later state of Eastern Wu. The eldest son of Sun Jian, he built his power through a series of rapid campaigns before being mortally wounded in an ambush at a young age. He passed his domain to his brother Sun Quan, who would go on to become emperor of Wu.",
"Cain_and_Abel": "Cain and Abel are the first two sons of Adam and Eve in the Book of Genesis. Cain is portrayed as a farmer and Abel as a shepherd, and when God favored Abel's offering over Cain's, Cain killed his brother in the first murder described in the Bible. The story has been widely interpreted in Jewish, Christian, and Islamic tradition as a lesson about jealousy, violence, and divine justice.",
"Sheng_(instrument)": "The sheng (笙) is a Chinese mouth-blown free reed instrument consisting of vertical pipes set into a wind chamber, each pipe containing a metal reed. The player produces sound by exhaling or inhaling through a mouthpiece, allowing continuous tones and the playing of chords. It is one of the oldest Chinese instruments, with depictions and surviving examples reaching back to antiquity.",
"Zhiyi": "Zhiyi was a Chinese Buddhist monk regarded as the principal founder and systematizer of the Tiantai school. He organized the diverse body of Buddhist scriptures into a graded scheme of teachings and developed influential methods of meditation and doctrinal study centered on the Lotus Sutra. His synthesis of contemplative practice and scriptural analysis became foundational for much of later East Asian Buddhism.",
"Bamboo_Annals": "The Bamboo Annals (竹書紀年) are an ancient chronicle of China that recounts events from legendary antiquity down to 299 BCE, with later portions centering on the state of Wei. The text was written on bamboo slips and buried in a royal tomb, escaping the Qin book burning, before being rediscovered in 281 CE during the Western Jin dynasty. Its chronology sometimes diverges from other early histories, making it an important independent source for early Chinese dating.",
"Astronomy": "Astronomy is the scientific study of celestial objects and phenomena beyond Earth's atmosphere, such as stars, planets, comets, and galaxies. It uses observation and the laws of physics to explain the motions, composition, and evolution of these bodies. As one of the oldest natural sciences, it grew from early efforts to track the positions of the Sun, Moon, and stars.",
"Wang_Chongyang": "Wang Chongyang was a Chinese Daoist master of the Jin dynasty who founded the Quanzhen School of Daoism. He gathered a group of followers known as the Seven Perfected and taught a program of internal alchemy combined with monastic discipline and the harmonizing of Daoist, Buddhist, and Confucian ideas. His teachings shaped one of the two principal branches of later Daoism.",
"Nun_(mythology)": "Nun is the personification of the primordial watery abyss in ancient Egyptian religion, conceived as a limitless, dark, and formless expanse existing before creation. From these waters the first mound of land and the creator sun god were said to have emerged, marking the beginning of the ordered world. Nun was counted among the eight deities of the Ogdoad and was understood as the latent source from which all existence arose.",
"Kunlun_Mountains": "The Kunlun Mountains are one of the longest mountain ranges in Asia, extending more than 3,000 kilometres across western China through Xinjiang, Qinghai, and Tibet. They form the northern edge of the Tibetan Plateau, bordering the Tarim Basin to the south, and reach over 7,000 metres at their highest peaks. In Chinese mythology the Kunlun is a sacred paradise associated with the Queen Mother of the West.",
"Nine-rank_system": "The nine-rank system, in Chinese jiupin zhongzheng, was a method of recruiting and classifying officials used in China from the Cao Wei period through the Northern and Southern dynasties. Local arbiters known as rectifiers evaluated candidates on family background, moral character, and ability, assigning each to one of nine grades that determined eligibility for office. Over time the system came to favor entrenched aristocratic families, since rank increasingly reflected lineage rather than individual merit.",
"Athena": "Athena is the ancient Greek goddess of wisdom, handicraft, and strategic warfare, and the patron deity of the city of Athens. In the most widespread myth she sprang fully armed from the head of Zeus. She is associated with the owl and the olive tree and is commonly depicted with a helmet, spear, and the aegis bearing the head of the Gorgon.",
"Zhang_Heng": "Zhang Heng was an Eastern Han polymath who made notable contributions to astronomy, mathematics, mechanical engineering, and literature. He built a water-powered armillary sphere, catalogued thousands of stars, and in 132 CE constructed a bronze seismoscope capable of indicating the direction of a distant earthquake. He was also celebrated as a poet for his rhapsodies on the Han capitals.",
"Rama": "Rama is a major deity in Hinduism, regarded as the seventh avatar of Vishnu and one of the most popular. He is the central figure of the epic Ramayana, born as a prince of Ayodhya to King Dasharatha and Queen Kausalya, and is celebrated as an embodiment of dharma and the ideal man. His wife is Sita, and the narrative follows his exile, the abduction of Sita, and his war to recover her.",
"Inanna": "Inanna was the Sumerian goddess of love, war, sex, and political power, one of the most widely venerated deities of ancient Mesopotamia. Her primary temple was the Eanna at Uruk, and she was identified with the planet Venus, whose movements were linked to her mythological descent into and return from the underworld. Among the Akkadians and Babylonians she came to be known as Ishtar.",
"Yuan_Chonghuan": "Yuan Chonghuan was a Ming dynasty military commander known for defending the northeastern frontier of Liaoning against the rising Jurchen-led Later Jin state. He won renown for repelling forces under Nurhaci at the Battle of Ningyuan in 1626 and for resisting later assaults led by Hong Taiji. Despite his successes, he was arrested on charges of treason and executed by slow slicing on the orders of the Chongzhen Emperor in 1630.",
"Mount_Penglai": "Mount Penglai (蓬萊) is a legendary island paradise of Chinese mythology said to lie in the eastern sea, where immortals dwell amid palaces of gold and jade. It is grouped in early texts with the other holy isles Fangzhang and Yingzhou, and its trees were imagined to bear gems while its waters held the elixir of eternal life. Tradition holds that the First Emperor of Qin sent expeditions, including the alchemist Xu Fu, eastward in a fruitless search for the island and its deathless inhabitants.",
"Týr": "Týr is a god of the Æsir in Norse mythology, associated with war, justice, law, and the assembly. His most famous deed is the binding of the wolf Fenrir, during which he places his right hand in the wolf's mouth as a pledge of good faith and loses it when the gods refuse to release the beast. He is foretold to fight and fall against the hound Garmr at Ragnarök.",
"Zou_Yan": "Zou Yan (鄒衍; 305–240 BCE) was a Chinese thinker of the Warring States period regarded as the principal systematizer of the yin-yang and Five Phases doctrines. A scholar at the Jixia Academy in the state of Qi, he applied cyclical theories of natural forces to cosmology, geography, and the rise and fall of dynasties. His writings are lost, and his ideas are known largely through quotations in Sima Qian's Records of the Grand Historian.",
"Abacus": "An abacus is a manual calculating device consisting of rows of beads or counters that slide along rods or in grooves within a frame, each row standing for a place value. By moving the beads according to learned procedures, a skilled user can perform addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division quickly. Forms of the abacus have been used for commerce and teaching in many cultures for thousands of years.",
"Shen_Kuo": "Shen Kuo was a Chinese polymath, scientist, and statesman of the Northern Song dynasty whose interests spanned mathematics, astronomy, geology, optics, and engineering. He served as a finance official, inspector, and head of the Bureau of Astronomy. His Dream Pool Essays (夢溪筆談; Mengxi Bitan) recorded scientific observations including the magnetic compass needle and the concept of true north.",
"Princess_Taiping": "Princess Taiping (太平公主) was a daughter of Emperor Gaozong and Wu Zetian who became one of the most powerful political figures of the early eighth century. She helped carry out the 705 coup that restored Emperor Zhongzong and the 710 purge of Empress Wei's faction, and for several years acted as the real power behind the throne during Emperor Ruizong's reign. In 713 Emperor Xuanzong, convinced she was plotting against him, executed her associates and forced her to take her own life.",
"Ancient_Egypt": "Ancient Egypt was a civilization of the lower Nile valley in northeastern Africa that endured for roughly three millennia. Its agricultural prosperity depended on the annual flooding of the Nile, and it was ruled by kings known as pharaohs across periods conventionally divided into the Old, Middle, and New Kingdoms. It produced monumental architecture, hieroglyphic writing, and a complex polytheistic religion before falling under Roman rule in 30 BCE.",
"Lü_Bu": "Lü Bu was a military general and warlord of the late Eastern Han dynasty famed for his exceptional fighting ability and skill on horseback. He served and then betrayed a succession of masters, killing the tyrant Dong Zhuo before seizing territory of his own, until he was defeated and executed by Cao Cao at the Battle of Xiapi. He is depicted in later fiction as the mightiest warrior of his era but also as treacherous and unreliable.",
"Garden_of_Eden": "The Garden of Eden is the earthly paradise described in the Book of Genesis where God placed the first humans, Adam and Eve. It is depicted as a lush garden watered by a river that divides into four streams and containing the Tree of Life and the Tree of the Knowledge of Good and Evil. According to the narrative, the first humans were expelled from the garden after eating the forbidden fruit.",
"Suona": "The suona (嗩吶) is a Chinese double-reed wind instrument with a conical wooden body and a flared metal bell, producing a loud and penetrating tone. It is a central instrument in the folk music of northern China and is commonly heard at weddings, funerals, and festivals. Modern keyed versions have been developed to extend its range and allow fully chromatic playing.",
"Chan_Buddhism": "Chan Buddhism is a tradition of Mahayana Buddhism that emphasizes direct insight into the nature of mind, often through seated meditation and the guidance of a teacher. It developed in China and spread to Korea, Japan, and Vietnam, where it became known by names such as Seon, Zen, and Thiền. Its teachings stress the possibility of awakening in this life and frequently express distrust of reliance on words and conceptual reasoning alone.",
"Book_of_Han": "The Book of Han (漢書), also called the History of the Former Han, is an official history covering the Western Han dynasty from 206 BCE to the fall of Wang Mang in 23 CE. It was begun by Ban Biao, continued by his son Ban Gu, and completed with contributions from his daughter Ban Zhao around 111 CE. Organized into annals, tables, treatises, and biographies, it became the model for later dynastic histories devoted to a single dynasty.",
"Scientific_method": "The scientific method is an empirical approach to acquiring knowledge through observation, the formulation of testable hypotheses, prediction, and controlled experiment. Results are analyzed, interpreted, and subjected to independent replication and peer scrutiny before being accepted. Rather than a fixed sequence of steps, it is an iterative process of refining explanations against evidence.",
"Shangqing_School": "The Shangqing School (上清), or Highest Clarity, is a Daoist tradition that arose in the fourth century CE from revelations received by the visionary Yang Xi. It emphasizes meditation, the inner visualization of deities and celestial realms, and the recitation of scriptures over the laboratory alchemy of earlier movements. The school became especially influential among the aristocracy and reached its height during the Tang dynasty.",
"Aten": "The Aten is the visible disc of the sun in ancient Egyptian belief, worshipped as a god especially during the reign of Akhenaten in the Eighteenth Dynasty. Under Akhenaten the Aten was elevated to the position of supreme and nearly sole deity, with worship focused on the sun's rays as the giver of life. Devotion to the Aten declined sharply after Akhenaten's death, and the traditional pantheon was restored.",
"Qilian_Mountains": "The Qilian Mountains lie along the border between Gansu and Qinghai provinces in northwestern China, forming the northeastern escarpment of the Tibetan Plateau. The range stretches roughly 800 kilometres and reaches elevations above 5,800 metres, and its glaciers and meltwater rivers supply the oases of the Hexi Corridor. The mountains appear in early Chinese texts such as the Shiji in connection with the Yuezhi people.",
"Censorate": "The Censorate, in Chinese yushitai or later duchayuan, was a high government body in imperial China charged with surveillance, inspection, and the impeachment of officials. Its censors monitored the conduct of the bureaucracy, exposed corruption and maladministration, and could remonstrate even with the emperor over matters of policy. The institution existed in various forms across many dynasties and served as a principal check on the operation of the civil service.",
"Apollo": "Apollo is an ancient Greek god associated with the sun and light, music, poetry, prophecy, archery, healing, and plague. He is the son of Zeus and Leto and the twin brother of Artemis. His principal sanctuary was the oracle at Delphi, and his attributes include the lyre, the bow, and the laurel.",
"Dong_Zhongshu": "Dong Zhongshu was a Western Han Confucian scholar whose proposals to Emperor Wu helped establish Confucianism as the orthodox doctrine of the imperial state. He urged the throne to exalt Confucius, dismiss the other schools of thought, and found an imperial academy to train officials in the classics. He developed an influential cosmology linking the conduct of the ruler to omens and the resonance between Heaven and humanity.",
"Ganesha": "Ganesha is one of the best-known and most widely worshipped deities in Hinduism, readily identified by his elephant head. He is honored as the remover of obstacles, the bringer of good fortune, and the patron of beginnings, wisdom, and learning. According to Hindu texts he is the son of Shiva and Parvati.",
"Ishtar": "Ishtar was the East Semitic and Akkadian name of the Mesopotamian goddess of love, war, and fertility, who originated as the Sumerian Inanna. Her veneration spread widely through Mesopotamia, particularly after the conquests of Sargon of Akkad, and she was associated with political power and divine law. Like her Sumerian form, she was linked to the planet Venus and was among the most prominent figures in the regional pantheon.",
"Li_Zicheng": "Li Zicheng was a Chinese rebel leader of the late Ming period, known as the Dashing King, who rose to lead one of the largest peasant uprisings of the era. Promising land redistribution and tax relief, he captured Xi'an and proclaimed the short-lived Shun dynasty before entering Beijing largely unopposed in 1644, an event that precipitated the Chongzhen Emperor's suicide. His forces were soon defeated by combined Qing and Ming armies at the Battle of Shanhai Pass, and he died in flight the following year.",
"Kuafu": "Kuafu (夸父) is a giant in Chinese mythology recorded in the Classic of Mountains and Seas who resolved to chase and catch the sun. Pursuing it from east to west, he grew so thirsty that he drank dry the Yellow River and the Wei River, and when these failed to quench him he died of thirst before reaching his goal. The staff he dropped was said to grow into a vast peach forest, and his story is invoked in Chinese to describe bold but overreaching ambition.",
"Heimdall": "Heimdall is a god of the Æsir in Norse mythology who serves as the watchman of the gods, guarding the rainbow bridge Bifröst from his dwelling Himinbjörg. He possesses extraordinarily keen senses, able to see vast distances by night and to hear grass growing on the earth and wool growing on sheep. He owns the horn Gjallarhorn, which he sounds to warn of Ragnarök, where he and Loki are foretold to slay one another.",
"School_of_Naturalists": "The School of Naturalists, or yin-yang school (陰陽家), was one of the major intellectual currents of the Warring States period, devoted to explaining the cosmos through the interaction of natural forces. Its teachings combined the complementary principles of yin and yang with the Five Phases of metal, wood, water, fire, and earth, and were associated above all with the thinker Zou Yan. Its concepts later shaped Chinese cosmology, medicine, alchemy, and were absorbed into Han-era Confucianism.",
"Repeating_crossbow": "A repeating crossbow is a crossbow fitted with a mechanism that stores several bolts and loads, draws, and shoots them in quick succession through the working of a single lever. The design trades the power of an individual shot for a much higher rate of fire, allowing even an untrained user to loose many bolts rapidly. It has been used both in warfare and for the defence of homes and fortifications.",
"Yue_Fei": "Yue Fei was a Chinese military general of the Southern Song dynasty who led campaigns against the Jurchen-led Jin dynasty in an effort to recover lost northern territory. Recalled from a successful offensive, he was imprisoned on fabricated charges arranged by the chancellor Qin Hui and executed in 1142. He was later posthumously rehabilitated and is revered in Chinese culture as a model of patriotic loyalty.",
"An_Lushan_rebellion": "The An Lushan rebellion was a devastating civil war that erupted in 755 when the military governor An Lushan revolted against the Tang dynasty and proclaimed a rival Yan dynasty. Rebel forces captured the capital Chang'an, forcing the emperor to flee, and the conflict was not fully suppressed until 763. Census figures recorded a steep population decline afterward, and the war permanently weakened central authority by empowering autonomous regional military governors.",
"Hittites": "The Hittites were an Anatolian people who spoke an Indo-European language and built one of the major powers of the Late Bronze Age in West Asia. Centered on their capital at Hattusa in north-central Anatolia, their empire at its peak rivaled Egypt and Assyria and clashed with Egypt at the Battle of Kadesh. The unified state collapsed around 1200 BCE amid the wider Bronze Age upheaval.",
"Dong_Zhuo": "Dong Zhuo was a military general and warlord whose seizure of the capital Luoyang in 189 marked the beginning of the collapse of central authority in the Eastern Han dynasty. He deposed one young emperor to install the puppet Emperor Xian, burned Luoyang, and ruled through terror until a coalition of warlords rose against him. He was assassinated in a plot involving his adopted son Lü Bu and the minister Wang Yun.",
"Tower_of_Babel": "The Tower of Babel is an origin story in the Book of Genesis that explains the existence of different languages among peoples. According to the narrative, a unified humanity speaking a single language settled in the land of Shinar and began building a city with a tower meant to reach the heavens. God confounded their speech so they could no longer understand one another and scattered them across the earth, leaving the tower unfinished.",
"Yunluo": "The yunluo (云锣) is a Chinese percussion instrument made of a set of small tuned gongs suspended in a wooden frame. Each gong is struck with a mallet, and pitch is varied by the thickness of the metal rather than the diameter. The traditional form holds about ten gongs, while enlarged versions used in modern Chinese orchestras carry many more.",
"Pure_Land_Buddhism": "Pure Land Buddhism is a broad tradition of Mahayana Buddhism centered on devotion to a Buddha and aspiration to be reborn in his purified realm, or Pure Land. Practitioners commonly recite the name of the Buddha Amitabha, trusting in his vows to lead beings to a realm where enlightenment can be readily attained. It became one of the most widespread forms of devotional Buddhism across East Asia.",
"Zizhi_Tongjian": "The Zizhi Tongjian (資治通鑑), or Comprehensive Mirror in Aid of Governance, is a monumental chronicle led by the Song scholar-official Sima Guang and completed in 1084. Arranged year by year, it narrates almost 1,400 years of Chinese history from 403 BCE to 959 CE, drawing on a wide range of earlier sources. It was intended to instruct rulers through historical example and is regarded as a masterpiece of Chinese historiography.",
"Alchemy": "Alchemy was a tradition of natural philosophy and practical experimentation aimed at transforming and perfecting matter. Practitioners sought to transmute base metals into gold, to produce a philosopher's stone, and to prepare elixirs believed to confer health or long life. The pursuit combined laboratory techniques with philosophical and spiritual ideas about purification and change.",
"Tao_Hongjing": "Tao Hongjing was a Chinese polymath of the Southern dynasties active as an alchemist, pharmacologist, astronomer, and Daoist scholar. He compiled and edited the revealed scriptures of the Shangqing tradition and organized its sacred geography and pantheon, while also producing important works on medicinal substances. He spent much of his life in retreat on Mount Mao, where he advised rulers and pursued alchemical study.",
"Akhenaten": "Akhenaten was a pharaoh of the Eighteenth Dynasty of ancient Egypt who originally ruled as Amenhotep IV. He is known for promoting the worship of the sun disc Aten above other gods and for founding a new capital at Akhetaten, in the period now called the Amarna age. His religious reforms were largely reversed after his death, and his monuments and name were subsequently subjected to deliberate erasure.",
"Tian_Shan": "The Tian Shan is a large system of mountain ranges in Central Asia, spanning Kyrgyzstan, Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, and the Xinjiang region of China. Its highest peak, Jengish Chokusu, rises to 7,439 metres, and the range forms the northern rim of the Tarim Basin in China. Parts of the system have been designated UNESCO World Heritage Sites for their natural significance.",
"Grand_Secretariat": "The Grand Secretariat, in Chinese neige, was a central advisory and coordinating body that emerged under the Ming dynasty after the abolition of the office of chancellor. Its grand secretaries drafted documents, reviewed memorials to the throne, and helped formulate policy, in practice often functioning as the empire's senior administrative council. The institution continued under the Qing dynasty before being eclipsed by other organs of state.",
"Artemis": "Artemis is the ancient Greek goddess of the hunt, wilderness, wild animals, childbirth, and chastity. She is the daughter of Zeus and Leto and the twin sister of Apollo. She is typically depicted carrying a bow and quiver of arrows and accompanied by deer or hunting dogs.",
"Huo_Guang": "Huo Guang was a Western Han statesman who served as the dominant figure at court from 87 BCE until his death, acting as regent for the young Emperor Zhao. In 74 BCE he deposed the newly enthroned Prince of Changyi after twenty-seven days and installed Emperor Xuan in his place. He was a half-brother of the general Huo Qubing, and his clan was destroyed for alleged conspiracy two years after his death.",
"Hanuman": "Hanuman is a deity in Hinduism, revered as a divine vanara and a devoted companion of Rama. He is celebrated for his great strength, courage, and unwavering devotion, and plays a key role in the epic Ramayana, especially in the search for and rescue of Sita. He is traditionally regarded as the spiritual son of the wind god Vayu.",
"Shamash": "Shamash, known in Sumerian as Utu, was the Mesopotamian sun god believed to see everything that occurred in the world each day. Because of this all-seeing nature, he was regarded as the divine guardian of justice and truth, often invoked in legal and oracular contexts. His chief cult centers were Sippar and Larsa, where temples called Ebabbar were dedicated to him.",
"Wu_Sangui": "Wu Sangui was a Ming dynasty general who commanded the strategic Shanhai Pass at the eastern end of the Great Wall during the crisis of 1644. After the rebel Li Zicheng seized Beijing, he opened the pass to allow Manchu forces into China proper, enabling the Qing conquest. Decades later he turned against the Qing, leading the Revolt of the Three Feudatories from 1673 and declaring himself emperor shortly before his death in 1678.",
"Jingwei": "Jingwei (精衛) is a bird in Chinese mythology said to have been the transformed spirit of a daughter of the Flame Emperor who drowned while playing in the Eastern Sea. Described as resembling a crow with a patterned head, a white beak, and red feet, she resolved to fill in the sea that had taken her by endlessly carrying pebbles and twigs in her beak to drop into the water. The tale gives rise to the idiom about Jingwei filling the sea, a byword for dogged perseverance against impossible odds.",
"Baldr": "Baldr is a god in Norse mythology, the radiant son of Odin and Frigg, married to Nanna and father of Forseti. After he dreams of his own death, his mother secures vows from all things not to harm him except the mistletoe, and Loki guides the blind god Höðr to kill him with a shaft of that plant. His death is the first in a chain of events leading to Ragnarök, after which he is foretold to return to the renewed world.",
"Shen_Buhai": "Shen Buhai (申不害; c. 400–c. 337 BCE) was a statesman who served for some fifteen years as chancellor of the state of Han under Marquis Zhao. He is associated with the doctrine of shu, a set of administrative techniques for controlling and evaluating officials by matching their performance to their assigned duties and titles. His original writings survive only in fragments, but his emphasis on bureaucratic method became an important strand within Legalist statecraft.",
"Cast_iron": "Cast iron is a group of iron-carbon alloys with a high carbon content that melt at a relatively low temperature and are shaped by pouring the molten metal into moulds. Hard, brittle, and highly resistant to compression and wear, it suits cookware, pipes, machine bases, stoves, and ornamental work. Producing it requires furnaces hot enough to melt iron fully, and it has been made since antiquity.",
"Emperor_Taizu_of_Song": "Emperor Taizu of Song, personal name Zhao Kuangyin, was the founder and first emperor of the Song dynasty, reigning from 960 to 976. A military commander under the Later Zhou, he was proclaimed emperor by his troops during the Chenqiao mutiny and unified much of China after the fragmentation of the Five Dynasties and Ten Kingdoms period. He concentrated power in the civil bureaucracy and curbed the autonomy of regional military governors.",
"An_Lushan": "An Lushan (安祿山) was a Tang dynasty general of Sogdian and Turkic descent who rose to command vast frontier armies as a military governor before launching the rebellion that bears his name. In 756 he proclaimed himself emperor of a new Yan dynasty and his forces sacked the capital Chang'an. He was assassinated by supporters of his own son early in 757, but the revolt he began crippled the Tang state.",
"Phoenicia": "Phoenicia was an ancient maritime civilization of Semitic-speaking peoples based in coastal city-states of the eastern Mediterranean, including Tyre, Sidon, and Byblos. Renowned as traders and seafarers, the Phoenicians founded colonies across the Mediterranean and spread an alphabetic script that influenced many later writing systems. Their independence ended as their cities were absorbed by larger empires such as the Achaemenids and later Alexander the Great.",
"Yuan_Shao": "Yuan Shao was one of the most powerful warlords of the late Eastern Han dynasty, controlling a large territory across the north China plain. Born to the prominent Yuan family, he led the coalition against Dong Zhuo and later contested supremacy with Cao Cao. His decisive defeat at the Battle of Guandu in 200 broke his dominance, and his sons' infighting after his death allowed Cao Cao to absorb his lands.",
"The_Exodus": "The Exodus is the founding narrative of the Israelites recounted in the Hebrew Bible, describing their departure from slavery in Egypt. According to the account, God acting through Moses sent a series of plagues upon Egypt and led the people across a parted sea to freedom. The events are commemorated in Jewish tradition through the festival of Passover and form a central theme in later religious thought.",
"Peking_opera": "Peking opera (京劇) is a major form of Chinese theatre that combines instrumental music, stylized singing, mime, dance, acrobatics, and martial arts. Performers use codified roles, elaborate painted face makeup, and conventional gestures to convey character and narrative. It took shape in Beijing in the late 18th and 19th centuries after Anhui theatrical troupes brought their repertoire to the capital.",
"Tiantai": "Tiantai is a school of Mahayana Buddhism that developed in sixth-century China and emphasizes the Lotus Sutra as the highest expression of the Buddha's teaching. It is known for an elaborate classification of scriptures, the doctrine of the threefold truth, and integrated systems of meditation and study. The tradition spread to Korea, Japan, and Vietnam, where it strongly influenced later Buddhist thought.",
"Four_Books": "The Four Books (四書) are a group of Confucian texts comprising the Great Learning, the Doctrine of the Mean, the Analects, and the Mencius. The neo-Confucian philosopher Zhu Xi selected and grouped them in the Song dynasty as an introduction to Confucian thought. During the Ming and Qing dynasties they formed the core of the civil service examination curriculum.",
"Astrology": "Astrology is a set of divinatory practices that claim to interpret human affairs and earthly events from the apparent positions of celestial bodies. Practitioners construct charts based on the placement of the Sun, Moon, and planets at a given moment, such as a person's birth, and read meaning from signs and aspects. It has been regarded as a pseudoscience since systematic testing failed to support its predictive claims.",
"Lingbao_School": "The Lingbao School (靈寶), or Numinous Treasure, is a Daoist tradition that emerged around the early fifth century CE and is centered on a body of revealed scriptures concerned with communal ritual and salvation. It absorbed elements from the Shangqing scriptures, Celestial Masters liturgy, and Buddhist concepts such as universal salvation and rebirth, producing elaborate ceremonies for the benefit of the living and the dead. Although it did not survive as a separate organization, its ritual forms shaped later Daoist liturgy.",
"Nefertiti": "Nefertiti was a queen of ancient Egypt and the great royal wife of the pharaoh Akhenaten during the Eighteenth Dynasty. She played a prominent role in the religious reforms of the Amarna period and appears frequently in its art, often shown taking part in worship of the Aten. A painted limestone bust attributed to her, discovered at Amarna, has become one of the most recognized works of ancient Egyptian art.",
"Huai_River": "The Huai River is a major river in central China, flowing roughly 1,110 kilometres through Henan, Anhui, and Jiangsu provinces from its source in the Tongbai Mountains. It forms part of the Qinling-Huaihe Line, a conventional geographic boundary between North and South China that approximates the 0 degrees Celsius January isotherm. The river has historically been prone to severe flooding, worsened by past southward shifts of the Yellow River into its basin.",
"Tributary_system_of_China": "The tributary system of China was a network of diplomatic and commercial relations in which foreign states and peoples acknowledged the supremacy of the Chinese emperor by presenting tribute and receiving gifts and titles in return. Framed in terms of the emperor's universal authority, it regulated trade, diplomacy, and ceremonial contact between China and surrounding polities. The arrangement governed much of East and Southeast Asian interstate relations for many centuries before declining in the nineteenth century.",
"Ares": "Ares is the ancient Greek god of war, representing its violence, bloodshed, and brutality. He is a son of Zeus and Hera and was often regarded with ambivalence for his association with the destructive aspects of combat. His attributes include the spear, helmet, and shield, and he was sometimes attended by figures personifying fear and dread.",
"Yellow_Turban_Rebellion": "The Yellow Turban Rebellion was a massive peasant uprising that broke out in 184 CE against the Eastern Han government during a period of famine, corruption, and eunuch dominance. It was led by Zhang Jue and his brothers and inspired by the Way of Supreme Peace, a Taoist movement whose followers wore yellow headscarves and proclaimed the coming of a new age. Though the main revolt was suppressed within a year, the militarization it provoked accelerated the collapse of Han central authority.",
"Lakshmi": "Lakshmi is one of the principal goddesses in Hinduism, revered as the goddess of fortune, wealth, prosperity, beauty, and abundance. She is the consort of Vishnu and is venerated as his divine energy in the Vaishnava traditions. She is commonly depicted seated on a lotus and is especially honored during the festival of Diwali.",
"Sin_(mythology)": "Sin, known in Sumerian as Nanna, was the Mesopotamian god of the moon and one of the major astral deities of the region. His principal cult centers were the city of Ur in southern Mesopotamia and Harran to the north, where his temples held lasting importance. He was the father of the sun god Shamash and the goddess Inanna in many traditions.",
"Nurhaci": "Nurhaci was a Jurchen leader who unified the rival Jurchen tribes of the northeast through a series of military and diplomatic campaigns beginning in 1583. In 1616 he declared himself khan and founded the Later Jin state, and he organized his followers into the Eight Banners military and social system. His descendants renamed his people the Manchus and transformed his state into the Qing dynasty, making him its founding ancestor.",
"Azure_Dragon": "The Azure Dragon (青龍), or Qinglong, is one of the Four Symbols of the Chinese constellations, the celestial guardian of the eastern sky. Within the Five Phases system it embodies the element wood, the season of spring, and the blue-green color, and its body is mapped across a chain of seven mansions known as the Azure Dragon of the East. It is also called Seiryū in Japan, Cheongnyong in Korea, and Thanh Long in Vietnam.",
"Njörðr": "Njörðr is a god of the Vanir in Norse mythology, associated with the sea, seafaring, wind, fishing, and wealth. He is the father of the deities Freyr and Freyja, and after the war between the Æsir and the Vanir he comes to live among the Æsir and enters an unhappy marriage with the giantess Skaði. He dwells at Nóatún, a coastal hall whose name means enclosure of ships.",
"Shen_Dao": "Shen Dao (慎到; c. 350–c. 275 BCE) was a Chinese thinker of the Warring States period and a scholar at the Jixia Academy in Qi. He is known for the concept of shi, the idea that effective rule derives from a ruler's position and circumstance rather than from personal virtue or talent, and for advocating impartial standards and laws over reliance on sage individuals. Only fragments of his original essays survive, but his ideas influenced later Legalist and Huang-Lao thought.",
"Wheelbarrow": "A wheelbarrow is a small hand-propelled vehicle, usually with a single wheel at the front, designed to be pushed and steered by one person by means of two handles. By letting the wheel and the ground bear much of the weight, it lets a single labourer move heavy or bulky loads with far less effort. It is a common tool in construction, gardening, and farming.",
"Cheng_Yi_(philosopher)": "Cheng Yi was a Chinese Neo-Confucian philosopher of the Northern Song dynasty and the younger of the two Cheng brothers. With his brother Cheng Hao he developed a metaphysics centered on li, or principle, which Zhu Xi later systematized into the Cheng-Zhu school. He studied under Zhou Dunyi and stressed disciplined study and the investigation of things.",
"Yang_Guifei": "Yang Guifei (楊貴妃) was the favored consort of Emperor Xuanzong of Tang during the later years of his reign and held the highest rank among imperial consorts. Her romance with the emperor was immortalized in Bai Juyi's poem Song of Everlasting Regret and influenced literature across East Asia. During the An Lushan rebellion in 756, mutinous imperial guards at Mawei blamed her family for the crisis and compelled the emperor to order her death.",
"Charlemagne": "Charlemagne was King of the Franks and later the first emperor crowned in western Europe since the fall of the Western Roman Empire. He united much of western and central Europe through extensive military campaigns and was crowned emperor by Pope Leo III on Christmas Day in the year 800. His reign promoted administrative reform and a revival of learning sometimes called the Carolingian Renaissance.",
"Battle_of_Red_Cliffs": "The Battle of Red Cliffs was a decisive naval engagement fought in the winter of 208 along the Yangtze River during the final years of the Eastern Han dynasty. The allied forces of Sun Quan and Liu Bei, commanded chiefly by Zhou Yu, used fire to destroy the much larger fleet of the northern warlord Cao Cao. The victory halted Cao Cao's southern expansion and is regarded as a pivotal moment that paved the way for the tripartite division into the Three Kingdoms.",
"Ten_Commandments": "The Ten Commandments are a set of biblical principles relating to ethics and worship that play a fundamental role in Judaism and Christianity. According to the Book of Exodus, they were given by God to Moses on Mount Sinai and inscribed on two stone tablets. They include directives such as worshipping one God, honoring one's parents, and prohibitions against murder, theft, and bearing false witness.",
"Chinese_calligraphy": "Chinese calligraphy (書法) is the art of writing Chinese characters with brush and ink as an aesthetic practice valuing line, rhythm, and composition. It is executed with the brush, inkstick, inkstone, and paper, and developed several script styles including seal, clerical, regular, running, and cursive forms. The practice has long been esteemed among the literati and treated as a high art alongside painting and poetry.",
"Huayan": "Huayan is a school of Mahayana Buddhism that flourished in Tang dynasty China and takes the Avatamsaka Sutra, or Flower Garland Sutra, as its central scripture. Its signature teaching is the mutual interpenetration of all phenomena, the view that every thing contains and reflects all others within a single interconnected reality. The school deeply influenced East Asian Buddhist philosophy, including Chan thought.",
"Doctrine_of_the_Mean": "The Doctrine of the Mean (中庸) is a Confucian text, traditionally attributed to Confucius's grandson Zisi, that began as a chapter of the Book of Rites. It teaches the cultivation of balance, harmony, and sincerity, holding that one should avoid excess and remain steadfast in proper principle. Elevated by Zhu Xi as one of the Four Books, it became central to neo-Confucian education.",
"Eschatology": "Eschatology is the body of belief and study concerned with the end of the world, of history, or of an age. It addresses themes such as final judgment, the ultimate destiny of individuals and of the cosmos, and the events thought to bring the present order to a close. The subject appears in many religious traditions and also in scientific discussion of the long-term fate of the universe.",
"Neidan": "Neidan (內丹), or internal alchemy, is a set of Daoist meditative and physiological practices aimed at refining the body's vital energies to attain health, longevity, and spiritual transcendence. Practitioners work with the three internal treasures of essence, breath, and spirit, circulating and transmuting them through breathing, visualization, and concentration to form an immortal embryo within the body. It became the central self-cultivation method of later Daoist traditions such as Quanzhen.",
"Ramesses_II": "Ramesses II, also known as Ramesses the Great, was a pharaoh of the Nineteenth Dynasty who ruled ancient Egypt for roughly sixty-seven years. His reign was marked by extensive building projects, including the rock temples at Abu Simbel and additions to major temple complexes. He fought the Hittites at the Battle of Kadesh and later concluded one of the earliest known peace treaties with them.",
"Pearl_River_(China)": "The Pearl River is a river system in southern China that drains much of Guangdong and Guangxi before emptying into the South China Sea. Measured through its longest tributaries it is among China's longest rivers and its second largest by volume, and its estuary forms the heavily urbanised Pearl River Delta. The name is said to come from pearl-coloured shells in the riverbed near Guangzhou.",
"Corvée": "Corvée is a form of unpaid, compulsory labor that a person owes to the state or to a lord, typically for a set number of days each year. It has been used in many societies to build roads, canals, fortifications, and other public works and to maintain infrastructure without monetary wages. The obligation often fell on peasants and could be commuted into a payment in money or goods.",
"Aphrodite": "Aphrodite is the ancient Greek goddess of love, beauty, pleasure, and procreation. One tradition holds that she was born from the sea foam that arose when the severed genitals of Uranus fell into the water, while another names her as a daughter of Zeus and Dione. Her symbols include the dove, the rose, the myrtle, and the scallop shell.",
"Emperor_Gaozu_of_Han": "Emperor Gaozu, born Liu Bang, was the founder and first emperor of the Han dynasty, reigning from 202 to 195 BCE after defeating Xiang Yu in the civil war that followed the Qin collapse. He lowered taxes and corvée burdens, adopted a less harsh approach to governance than the Qin, and established his capital at Chang'an. Facing military pressure from the Xiongnu, he inaugurated the heqin policy of marriage alliances to secure the northern frontier.",
"Saraswati": "Saraswati is one of the principal goddesses in Hinduism, revered as the goddess of knowledge, learning, language, music, and the arts. She is often depicted holding a vina, seated on a white lotus or accompanied by a swan, and is associated with the river of the same name in the Vedas. She is described as the consort of Brahma and is also widely venerated as an independent goddess of wisdom.",
"Ninhursag": "Ninhursag was a Sumerian mother goddess associated with fertility, birth, and the mountains, counted among the great deities of Sumer. She was known by many names and epithets, including Ninmah, Nintu, Mami, and Belet-Ili, reflecting her wide-ranging maternal role. In mythology she is depicted shaping humanity and participating in the creation of life.",
"Hong_Taiji": "Hong Taiji was the eighth son of Nurhaci and the founding emperor of the Qing dynasty, ruling first as khan of the Later Jin from 1626 and then as emperor from 1636. He renamed the Jurchen people the Manchus and changed the dynastic name from Later Jin to Great Qing, while expanding the state's control over Inner Mongolia and Korea. He consolidated the institutions and military strength that his successors used to conquer Ming China, though he died in 1643 before that conquest was achieved.",
"Vermilion_Bird": "The Vermilion Bird (朱雀), or Zhuque, is one of the Four Symbols of the Chinese constellations, the celestial guardian of the southern sky. In the Five Phases system it represents the element fire, the season of summer, and the color red, and it is depicted as a flame-feathered bird resembling a pheasant wreathed in fire. It is associated with the sun, daylight, and renewal, and is known as Suzaku in Japan, Jujak in Korea, and Chu Tước in Vietnam.",
"Yggdrasil": "Yggdrasil is the immense sacred ash tree at the center of Norse cosmology, around which the Nine Worlds are arranged. Its three great roots reach toward separate locations, including the well Urðarbrunnr where the gods hold their assembly and the spring Hvergelmir, and the gods ride to its shade each day to give judgment. Many creatures dwell within it, among them the dragon Níðhöggr gnawing at its roots, the squirrel Ratatoskr scurrying along its trunk, and an eagle perched in its branches.",
"Guanzi_(text)": "The Guanzi (管子) is a large early Chinese text traditionally attributed to the 7th-century BCE statesman Guan Zhong but actually composed by many hands, much of it linked to the Jixia Academy and compiled into its received form in the early Han. Running to more than 130,000 characters, it gathers writings on government, economics, and political economy, including discussions of price stabilization and money, as well as Daoist self-cultivation in chapters such as the Neiye. Its blend of Legalist, Confucian, and Daoist material led later bibliographers to classify it variously as Daoist and as Legalist.",
"Porcelain": "Porcelain is a hard, white, and often translucent ceramic made by firing a refined clay body, usually rich in kaolin, at very high temperatures. The intense heat fuses the material into a dense, glassy, nonporous substance prized for its strength, fineness, and ringing tone. It is used for tableware, ornaments, sanitary fixtures, and electrical and industrial components.",
"Cheng_Hao": "Cheng Hao was a Chinese Neo-Confucian philosopher of the Northern Song dynasty and the elder of the two Cheng brothers. Together with his brother Cheng Yi he helped formulate the doctrine that universal principle, or li, is immanent within all things. The brothers are counted among the founders of Song Neo-Confucian thought.",
"Li_Linfu": "Li Linfu (李林甫) was a chancellor under Emperor Xuanzong of Tang who held office for roughly eighteen years, one of the longest tenures in Tang history. He became notorious for removing rivals through false accusations and manipulation, giving rise to the proverb about a man with honey in his mouth and a sword in his belly. Historians blame his promotion of non-Han frontier generals and suppression of capable officials for helping set the stage for the An Lushan rebellion.",
"Holy_Roman_Empire": "The Holy Roman Empire was a decentralized political entity that controlled much of central Europe from the early Middle Ages until the early nineteenth century. Headed by an elected emperor, it was a loose confederation of kingdoms, principalities, free cities, and ecclesiastical territories rather than a centralized state. It was formally dissolved in 1806 when Emperor Francis II abdicated during the Napoleonic Wars.",
"Battle_of_Guandu": "The Battle of Guandu was a major military confrontation fought in 200 between the warlords Cao Cao and Yuan Shao during the late Eastern Han dynasty. Though heavily outnumbered, Cao Cao won a decisive victory by raiding and burning Yuan Shao's supply depot at Wuchao. The triumph crippled Yuan Shao's power and allowed Cao Cao to consolidate control over northern China.",
"Torah": "The Torah is the compilation of the first five books of the Hebrew Bible and the foundational scripture of Judaism. It contains narratives of creation and the early history of the Israelites along with a body of laws and commandments. In Jewish tradition it is read in synagogues from a handwritten scroll and is central to religious teaching and practice.",
"Ink_wash_painting": "Ink wash painting (水墨畫) is a style of brush painting that uses black ink in varied dilutions to create tonal washes and gradations. It emphasizes expressive brushwork and the conveying of a subject's spirit rather than precise imitation of appearance. The style emerged in the Tang dynasty and flourished from the Song dynasty onward, often depicting landscapes, bamboo, and flowers.",
"Mahayana": "Mahayana, meaning the Great Vehicle, is one of the principal branches of Buddhism and encompasses a wide range of traditions across East and Central Asia. It emphasizes the bodhisattva path, in which practitioners aspire to attain Buddhahood for the benefit of all sentient beings, and it venerates an expanded array of Buddhas and bodhisattvas. Its teachings are preserved in a large body of sutras that elaborate doctrines such as emptiness and universal Buddha-nature.",
"Great_Learning": "The Great Learning (大學) is a short Confucian text, traditionally attributed to the disciple Zengzi, that originated as a chapter of the Book of Rites. It outlines a program of moral self-cultivation in which investigating things, extending knowledge, and rectifying the mind lead outward to ordering the family, the state, and the world. Zhu Xi made it one of the Four Books, treating it as the gateway to Confucian learning.",
"Reincarnation": "Reincarnation is the belief that the nonmaterial essence of a living being begins a new life in a different physical body after death. It is held in various forms across many religious and philosophical traditions, which differ over what is reborn and what governs the process. In several of these systems the cycle of rebirth is tied to moral conduct in previous lives.",
"Waidan": "Waidan (外丹), or external alchemy, is a branch of Chinese alchemy that sought immortality by compounding and ingesting elixirs prepared from minerals, metals, and other substances heated in crucibles. It flourished from the Han through the Tang dynasties, drawing on cosmological theory to time and arrange its operations, and its most prized ingredients included cinnabar, mercury, and lead. The practice declined as attention shifted toward the internal cultivation methods of neidan.",
"Hatshepsut": "Hatshepsut was a pharaoh of the Eighteenth Dynasty of ancient Egypt and one of the few women to rule as king in her own right. She came to power as regent for her stepson Thutmose III and later assumed the full titles and regalia of a pharaoh. Her reign is remembered for peaceful trade expeditions, notably to the land of Punt, and for her mortuary temple at Deir el-Bahari.",
"Taihu_Lake": "Lake Tai is a large freshwater lake in the Yangtze Delta of eastern China, straddling the border of southern Jiangsu and northern Zhejiang provinces. With a surface area of about 2,250 square kilometres it is one of the largest freshwater lakes in China, though it is shallow, averaging around two metres deep, and dotted with dozens of islands. Surrounded by cities such as Suzhou and Wuxi, it connects to the Grand Canal and feeds several rivers of the region.",
"Well-field_system": "The well-field system, in Chinese jingtian, was an idealized land arrangement described in early Chinese texts in which a square of farmland was divided into nine plots resembling the character for a well. The eight outer plots were cultivated by individual families, while the central plot was worked in common, with its produce going to the lord or state. Later thinkers, especially within the Confucian tradition, treated it as a model of equitable landholding, though its historical reality is debated.",
"Hephaestus": "Hephaestus is the ancient Greek god of fire, metalworking, and craftsmanship, and the divine blacksmith of the Olympian gods. He is described as a son of Zeus and Hera, or in another account as born of Hera alone, and several myths recount his lameness and his fall from Olympus. He forged weapons and wondrous objects for gods and heroes, and his symbols are the hammer, anvil, and tongs.",
"Cai_Lun": "Cai Lun was an Eastern Han eunuch official credited with refining the papermaking process around 105 CE by using tree bark, hemp, rags, and fishing nets to produce a cheap and durable writing material. His improvements enabled the large-scale manufacture and eventual worldwide spread of paper, and the product became known as Cai Hou paper. Caught up in palace intrigue, he took his own life in 121 CE when ordered to answer charges from earlier in his career.",
"Parvati": "Parvati is one of the principal goddesses in Hinduism, revered as the goddess of power, energy, love, devotion, and motherhood. She is the consort of Shiva and the mother of the deities Ganesha and Kartikeya. She is regarded as a benevolent and nurturing form of the great goddess and is worshipped under many names and aspects.",
"Dumuzid": "Dumuzid, called Tammuz by the Akkadians, was a Mesopotamian god associated with shepherds, agriculture, and fertility who served as the consort of the goddess Inanna. In the central myth he is seized by demons and dragged to the underworld as a substitute for Inanna after she returns from there. A later resolution allows him to spend half the year below and half above, an arrangement linked to the cycle of the seasons.",
"Yongzheng_Emperor": "The Yongzheng Emperor, personal name Yinzhen, was the fourth emperor of the Qing dynasty, reigning from 1722 to 1735 between the long reigns of his father and son. A diligent and centralizing ruler, he is credited with anti-corruption measures, fiscal reforms, and the creation of the Grand Council, which became the dynasty's central organ of decision-making. He also instituted a secret succession system to forestall the kind of disputed accession that had marked his own rise to power.",
"White_Tiger_(mythology)": "The White Tiger (白虎), or Baihu, is one of the Four Symbols of the Chinese constellations, the celestial guardian of the western sky. Within the Five Phases system it corresponds to the element metal, the season of autumn, and the color white, and it was anciently regarded as a god of war whose image marked banners and seals. The figure embodies righteousness, justice, and martial valor, and is known as Byakko in Japan, Baekho in Korea, and Bạch Hổ in Vietnam.",
"Asgard": "Asgard is the celestial realm of the Æsir gods in Norse mythology, often depicted as a fortified stronghold gleaming with gold. Within it stand notable halls and sites including Valhöll, where slain warriors gather, the assembly field Iðavöllr, and Odin's high seat Hlidskjálf, from which all the worlds can be surveyed. It is reached by the rainbow bridge Bifröst, which links it to the world of humans below.",
"Sun_Bin": "Sun Bin (孫臏; died 316 BCE) was a military strategist of the Warring States period who served as adviser to the general Tian Ji of Qi. Said to have been crippled by his rival Pang Juan while in Wei, he escaped to Qi and engineered victories including the ambush of Wei forces at the Battle of Maling in 342 BCE. His military treatise, long thought lost, was partially recovered in 1972 from the Yinqueshan Han bamboo slips found in Shandong.",
"Water_clock": "A water clock, or clepsydra, is a timekeeping device that measures time by the regulated flow of water into or out of a vessel, the changing water level marking the passing hours. As one of the oldest means of keeping time independently of the sun, it could measure the night and cloudy days. Elaborate versions drove pointers, moving figures, and astronomical displays through floats and gearing.",
"Zhou_Dunyi": "Zhou Dunyi was a Chinese cosmologist and philosopher of the Northern Song dynasty regarded as a foundational figure of Neo-Confucianism. His Taijitu shuo (太極圖說), an explanation of the Diagram of the Supreme Ultimate, set out a cosmology relating the supreme ultimate, yin and yang, and the five agents to human conduct. He taught the Cheng brothers and influenced later thinkers including Zhu Xi.",
"Wei_Zheng": "Wei Zheng (魏徵) was a chancellor and advisor to Emperor Taizong of Tang, renowned for offering blunt and fearless criticism to the throne. Taizong valued him so highly that he compared losing Wei to losing a mirror in which he could see his own faults. Wei also oversaw the compilation of the Book of Sui, the official history of the preceding dynasty.",
"Napoleon": "Napoleon Bonaparte was a French military and political leader who rose to prominence during the French Revolution and became Emperor of the French. He led a series of campaigns across Europe known as the Napoleonic Wars and reshaped the continent's borders and institutions, introducing reforms such as the Napoleonic Code. After defeats culminating at Waterloo in 1815, he was exiled to the island of Saint Helena, where he died.",
"Battle_of_Xiaoting": "The Battle of Xiaoting, also called the Battle of Yiling, was fought in 222 between the forces of Shu Han under Liu Bei and those of Eastern Wu commanded by Lu Xun. Liu Bei launched the campaign to avenge the death of Guan Yu and the loss of Jing Province but suffered a catastrophic defeat when Lu Xun set fire to his encampments. The disaster shattered Shu's military strength and Liu Bei died the following year.",
"Talmud": "The Talmud is a central text of Rabbinic Judaism and a primary source of Jewish law and theology. It consists of the Mishnah, a written compendium of oral tradition, and the Gemara, a later commentary that elaborates on it. It records the teachings, debates, and opinions of generations of rabbis on law, ethics, custom, and lore.",
"Seals_in_the_Sinosphere": "A seal in East Asia is a carved stamp, often of stone, used to make an inked impression that serves the function of a signature. Pressed in red cinnabar paste, seals authenticate documents and contracts and mark ownership or authorship on works of calligraphy and painting. Their carving became an art form in its own right, drawing on the same script traditions as Chinese writing.",
"Theravada": "Theravada, meaning the Doctrine of the Elders, is a major branch of Buddhism that bases its teachings on the Pali Canon. It is the dominant form of Buddhism in much of South and Southeast Asia, including Sri Lanka, Myanmar, Thailand, Laos, and Cambodia. Its practice centers on monastic discipline, meditation, and the goal of attaining liberation as an arhat.",
"Classic_of_Filial_Piety": "The Classic of Filial Piety (孝經) is a Confucian treatise on filial piety, presented as a dialogue between Confucius and his disciple Zengzi. It argues that devotion to one's parents extends naturally to loyalty toward rulers and thereby produces a harmonious society. Compact and widely taught, it became a foundational text of moral instruction and one of the Confucian classics.",
"Feudalism": "Feudalism is a term for the legal, military, and social arrangements of medieval Europe organized around the holding of land in return for service. In its classic description a lord granted a fief to a vassal, who in turn owed military and other obligations, while the lord offered protection. Modern historians debate how accurately the single label captures the varied practices it is applied to.",
"Xian_(Taoism)": "A xian (仙) is an immortal or transcendent being in Daoism and Chinese folklore who has attained a deathless, spiritually elevated state. Such figures are generally understood to have begun as humans who achieved transcendence through self-cultivation, alchemy, meditation, or moral merit, gaining powers such as flight and freedom from ordinary bodily limits. The pursuit of becoming a xian is a central aspiration in many Daoist practices.",
"Thutmose_III": "Thutmose III was a pharaoh of the Eighteenth Dynasty of ancient Egypt who became sole ruler after the death of his co-regent Hatshepsut. He led numerous military campaigns into the Levant and Nubia that greatly expanded Egyptian territory and influence. His victories, including the Battle of Megiddo, were recorded on the walls of the temple at Karnak.",
"Taklamakan_Desert": "The Taklamakan Desert is a large sandy desert occupying much of the Tarim Basin in southern Xinjiang, northwestern China. Covering about 337,000 square kilometres, it is ringed by the Kunlun, Pamir, and Tian Shan mountains and is known for its shifting dunes and extreme temperatures. Oasis towns along its rim, such as Kashgar and Khotan, were important stops on the Silk Road.",
"Equal-field_system": "The equal-field system, in Chinese juntian, was a method of land distribution under which the state allotted farmland to households according to the number and capacity of their members, with much of the land reverting to the state on the holder's death. First implemented by the Northern Wei in 485 and adopted by the Sui and early Tang, it was linked to obligations of tax, grain, cloth, and labor service. The system gradually broke down as population growth and private accumulation of land outstripped the supply available for redistribution.",
"Hermes": "Hermes is an ancient Greek god associated with trade, travelers, boundaries, eloquence, thieves, and the guiding of souls to the underworld. He is a son of Zeus and the nymph Maia and served as the messenger of the gods. He is commonly depicted with winged sandals, a winged cap, and the caduceus, a herald's staff entwined with serpents.",
"Wang_Mang": "Wang Mang was a Han consort relative who seized the throne in 9 CE and founded the short-lived Xin dynasty, dividing the Western and Eastern Han periods. He attempted sweeping reforms modeled on idealized antiquity, including nationalizing land, restricting slavery, and repeatedly overhauling the currency, but these measures provoked widespread disorder. His rule ended in 23 CE when peasant rebellions and the fall of Chang'an led to his death.",
"Durga": "Durga is a major goddess in Hinduism, especially revered in the Shakta traditions as a fierce protective form of the divine feminine. She is best known as a warrior goddess who battles demonic forces, most famously slaying the buffalo demon Mahishasura while mounted on a lion or tiger. She is typically depicted with many arms, each bearing a weapon, and is honored during the autumn festival of Durga Puja.",
"Ereshkigal": "Ereshkigal was the Mesopotamian goddess who ruled Kur, the underworld also called Irkalla. In the poem Inanna's Descent into the Underworld she appears as the elder sister who passes judgment on the visiting Inanna. Her consort was the god Nergal, with whom she came to govern the realm of the dead in later tradition.",
"Empress_Dowager_Cixi": "Empress Dowager Cixi was a Manchu noblewoman who effectively controlled the government of the Qing dynasty for nearly half a century in the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries. Beginning as a concubine of the Xianfeng Emperor and mother of his only surviving son, she seized power through a coup in 1861 and ruled as regent for the Tongzhi and Guangxu emperors. Her tenure saw cautious modernization, the suppression of the Hundred Days' Reform, and the upheavals of the Boxer Rebellion before her death in 1908.",
"Black_Turtle-Snake": "The Black Turtle-Snake (玄武), or Xuanwu, also called the Black Warrior of the North, is one of the Four Symbols of the Chinese constellations and the celestial guardian of the northern sky. It is usually depicted as a tortoise entwined with a snake, and in the Five Phases system it represents the element water, the season of winter, and the color black. Taoist tradition later venerated Xuanwu as a major deity of the northern heavens, said to have been a prince who renounced his throne to cultivate the Dao.",
"Midgard": "Midgard is the world inhabited by humans in Norse cosmology, its name meaning the middle enclosure. According to myth the gods fashion it from the body of the slain primordial being Ymir, using his flesh for the land, his blood for the seas, and his bones for the mountains, and they raise a protective wall from his eyebrows. It is encircled by a vast ocean in which the serpent Jörmungandr lies, and it is destined to be destroyed and then renewed at Ragnarök.",
"Su_Qin": "Su Qin (蘇秦; died 284 BCE) was a political strategist of the Warring States period associated with the School of Diplomacy and born in Luoyang. He is famous for promoting the hezong, or vertical alliance, a coalition meant to unite the states of Qi, Chu, Yan, Han, Zhao, and Wei against the growing power of Qin. He was executed in Qi in 284 BCE, and later silk manuscripts recovered at Mawangdui have raised questions about the traditional account of his life.",
"Armillary_sphere": "An armillary sphere is a model of the celestial sphere built from a framework of rings, each representing a great circle of the heavens such as the equator, the ecliptic, and the meridian. It served both to demonstrate the apparent motions of the sky and, fitted with sights, to measure the positions of celestial bodies. The instrument was central to astronomy and teaching for many centuries before the rise of the telescope.",
"Zhang_Zai": "Zhang Zai was a Chinese philosopher and official of the Northern Song dynasty and a leading early Neo-Confucian thinker. He built a metaphysics around qi, the primordial vital substance from which all things condense and into which they disperse. His essay the Western Inscription, expressing universal kinship within a unified cosmos, became a celebrated statement of Confucian ethics.",
"Guo_Ziyi": "Guo Ziyi (郭子儀) was a leading Tang dynasty general credited as the principal commander who suppressed the An Lushan rebellion, retaking the capital Chang'an in 757. After the war he repeatedly repelled Tibetan incursions, once dispersing an army through psychological tactics rather than battle. In 765 he secured an alliance with the Uyghurs and led the combined forces to a major victory over Tibetan troops.",
"Frankish_Empire": "The Frankish Empire, also called Francia, was the territory ruled by the Franks, a Germanic people who came to dominate much of western Europe after the collapse of Roman authority. Under the Merovingian and later Carolingian dynasties it expanded across present-day France, Germany, and neighboring lands. Following the death of its greatest ruler, it was partitioned among his heirs, giving rise to states that shaped medieval Europe.",
"Lu_Xun_(Three_Kingdoms)": "Lu Xun was a military general and statesman who served the state of Eastern Wu during the Three Kingdoms period. He rose to prominence by commanding the Wu forces that destroyed Liu Bei's invading army at the Battle of Xiaoting, and later served as a leading minister and imperial chancellor under Sun Quan. His career ended in disgrace after he became entangled in a succession dispute at the Wu court.",
"Gospel": "A gospel is an account describing the life, teachings, death, and resurrection of Jesus, a central genre of early Christian literature. The term refers especially to the four canonical texts attributed to Matthew, Mark, Luke, and John that open the New Testament. The word itself means good news, reflecting the message these writings proclaim.",
"Four_Treasures_of_the_Study": "The Four Treasures of the Study (文房四寶) are the brush, inkstick, paper, and inkstone, the essential implements of Chinese writing and painting. The brush is dipped in ink ground from a solid inkstick on a stone with water, and the strokes are laid down on absorbent paper. The grouping reflects the central role these tools play in the scholarly and artistic traditions of East Asia.",
"Bodhisattva": "A bodhisattva is a being who is on the path toward Buddhahood or who has vowed to attain it. In Mahayana Buddhism the term especially denotes one who, moved by compassion, aspires to awaken in order to help liberate all sentient beings, often postponing final enlightenment for their sake. Bodhisattvas such as the embodiments of wisdom and compassion are widely venerated and depicted in Buddhist art.",
"Journey_to_the_West": "Journey to the West (西遊記) is a Ming dynasty novel commonly attributed to Wu Cheng'en and published around 1592. It gives a fantastical account of the monk Tang Sanzang, based on the historical pilgrim Xuanzang, who travels to India to obtain Buddhist scriptures accompanied by the disciples Sun Wukong, Zhu Bajie, and Sha Wujing. Blending folklore, satire, and religious allegory, it is counted among the great classical Chinese novels.",
"Monarchy": "Monarchy is a form of government in which a single person, the monarch, holds the position of head of state, often for life and usually by inheritance. The monarch's powers may be nearly absolute or sharply limited by law and other institutions, as in a constitutional monarchy. Titles for the office include king, queen, emperor, and sultan, among others.",
"Eight_Immortals": "The Eight Immortals (八仙) are a group of legendary transcendents in Chinese mythology widely venerated in Daoism and popular culture. Each member has a distinctive personal story and an emblem associated with their powers, and together they are taken to represent good fortune, longevity, and the varied conditions of human life such as youth, age, wealth, and poverty. They appear frequently in literature, theater, and decorative art across East Asia.",
"Cleopatra": "Cleopatra VII was the last active ruler of the Ptolemaic Kingdom of Egypt, a Greek-speaking dynasty descended from a general of Alexander the Great. She formed political and personal alliances with the Roman leaders Julius Caesar and Mark Antony in an effort to preserve her realm's independence. Her death followed the defeat of her forces by Octavian, after which Egypt was annexed as a province of Rome.",
"Gobi_Desert": "The Gobi Desert is a large cold desert and steppe region covering parts of northern China and southern Mongolia, spanning roughly 1.3 million square kilometres. Much of it consists of bare rock and gravel rather than sand dunes, and it experiences extreme seasonal and daily temperature swings. The desert has expanded southward into China in recent decades through desertification.",
"Salt_and_iron_monopoly": "The salt and iron monopoly was a state policy in which the imperial Chinese government took exclusive control of the production and sale of salt and iron to generate revenue. First imposed on a large scale under Emperor Wu of the Han dynasty, it made two essential commodities a major source of state income. The merits of the monopoly were debated at the famous court discussion preserved in the text known as the Discourses on Salt and Iron.",
"Dionysus": "Dionysus is the ancient Greek god of wine, vegetation, fertility, ritual madness, and theatre. He is described as the son of Zeus and the mortal Semele, and myths recount his birth, wanderings, and the spread of his ecstatic cult. His attributes include the grapevine, ivy, the thyrsus staff, and a retinue of satyrs and frenzied female followers called maenads.",
"Emperor_Wen_of_Han": "Emperor Wen was the fifth emperor of the Han dynasty, reigning from 180 to 157 BCE in a period remembered for stability, frugality, and reduced burdens on the population. He cut land taxes to historically low rates, relaxed harsh punishments, and was influenced by Taoist ideas of restrained government. His reign and that of his son Emperor Jing are jointly celebrated by historians as the Rule of Wen and Jing.",
"Kali": "Kali is a major goddess in Hinduism, primarily associated with time, change, death, and destruction. She is depicted with dark skin, a protruding tongue, multiple arms, and a garland of severed heads or skulls, imagery that conveys her role as a fierce destroyer of evil. She is worshipped especially in the Shakta traditions, where she is also regarded as a maternal and liberating power.",
"Nergal": "Nergal was a Mesopotamian god primarily associated with war, plague, and inflicted death, often regarded as a ruler of the underworld. His main cult center was the city of Kutha, where his temple known as E-Meslam stood. In the narrative of Nergal and Ereshkigal, he becomes lord of the dead through his marriage to the underworld goddess Ereshkigal.",
"Koxinga": "Koxinga, Chinese name Zheng Chenggong, was a Southern Ming military leader who resisted the Qing conquest of China in the seventeenth century. Born in Japan to a Chinese merchant father, he received the imperial surname from the Longwu Emperor and continued the loyalist cause along the southeastern coast. In 1661 he expelled the Dutch East India Company from Taiwan and founded the Kingdom of Tungning, which his descendants held until the Qing annexed the island in 1683.",
"Kitchen_God": "The Kitchen God (灶君), commonly called Zao Jun, is a domestic deity of Chinese folk religion, Taoism, and folk Buddhism who guards the hearth and oversees the moral conduct of the household. Each year, near the close of the twelfth lunar month, he is believed to ascend to Heaven to report the family's behavior to the Jade Emperor, who rewards or punishes them accordingly. Families traditionally kept a paper image of him above the stove and smeared its lips with honey or sweets before his departure to ensure a favorable account.",
"Jötunheimr": "Jötunheimr is the land of the jötnar, the giant beings of Norse mythology, and its name means jötunn-home. It is generally located beyond the realms of gods and humans and separated from them by barriers such as rivers, forests, mountains, or fire that must be crossed by unusual means. The Eddic sources often place its prosperous lands toward the north, though the jötnar are reached from several directions.",
"Zhang_Yi_(Warring_States_period)": "Zhang Yi (張儀; died 309 BCE) was a diplomat and strategist of the Warring States period, born in Wei, who served as chancellor of Qin from around 329 BCE. He championed the lianheng, or horizontal alliance, a policy of forging east-west arrangements between Qin and individual rival states in order to break up coalitions against it. He is regarded, with Su Qin, as one of the foremost figures of the School of Diplomacy.",
"Sericulture": "Sericulture is the raising of silkworms in order to produce raw silk, the fine fibre that the larvae spin to form their cocoons. The practice involves feeding the caterpillars on suitable leaves, letting them spin their cocoons, and then unwinding the long filaments and reeling them into thread. It is the foundation of the silk textile industry and demands careful control of the insects' diet and surroundings.",
"Lu_Jiuyuan": "Lu Jiuyuan, also known as Lu Xiangshan, was a Chinese Neo-Confucian philosopher of the Southern Song dynasty who founded the School of the Mind, or Xinxue. He held that the universe and the mind are one, locating moral principle within the innate heart-mind rather than in external investigation. His ideas were debated against Zhu Xi and later inspired the Ming thinker Wang Yangming.",
"Huang_Chao": "Huang Chao (黃巢) was the leader of a massive popular uprising against the Tang dynasty between 874 and 884 that drew support from impoverished farmers, burdened merchants, and salt smugglers. In 881 his forces seized the capital Chang'an, forcing Emperor Xizong to flee, and he proclaimed himself emperor of a new Qi dynasty. The rebellion shattered what remained of Tang central authority and hastened the dynasty's collapse.",
"Inca_Empire": "The Inca Empire, known to its people as Tawantinsuyu, was the largest state in pre-Columbian America, centered in the Andes mountains of South America. Ruled from the capital at Cusco, it integrated diverse peoples through an extensive road network, knotted-cord record-keeping, and obligations of reciprocal labor. It fell to Spanish conquistadors under Francisco Pizarro in the 1530s.",
"Sima_Yi": "Sima Yi was a general and statesman of the state of Cao Wei during the Three Kingdoms period and the effective founder of the political power of the Sima clan. He gained renown for defending against the northern campaigns of the Shu chancellor Zhuge Liang and for suppressing rebellions, before seizing control of the Wei government in a coup in 249. His descendants used the dominance he established to displace the Cao family and found the Jin dynasty.",
"Muhammad": "Muhammad was an Arab religious, social, and political leader and the founder of Islam. According to Islamic belief, he received revelations from God through the angel Gabriel beginning around the age of forty, which were later compiled into the Quran. Muslims regard him as the final prophet sent to confirm the monotheistic teachings of earlier prophets, and his life and example are foundational to Islamic practice.",
"Cloisonné": "Cloisonné is a technique for decorating metalwork in which thin metal wires are affixed to a surface to form compartments that are filled with coloured enamel and fired. The wires separate the areas of glassy colour, producing bright, sharply outlined designs on objects such as vases, bowls, and censers. In China the technique reached a celebrated level of refinement during the Ming dynasty, where it is known as jingtailan after the Jingtai reign.",
"Avalokiteśvara": "Avalokiteshvara is a bodhisattva who embodies the compassion of all Buddhas and is among the most widely revered figures in Mahayana Buddhism. Devotees appeal to this bodhisattva for protection and aid, and the figure is depicted in many forms, sometimes with multiple arms or heads symbolizing the capacity to perceive and relieve suffering. In East Asia the bodhisattva came to be venerated in female form under the name Guanyin.",
"Dream_of_the_Red_Chamber": "Dream of the Red Chamber (紅樓夢) is an eighteenth-century novel by Cao Xueqin, composed in the 1740s through the early 1760s during the Qing dynasty. It traces the rise and decline of the wealthy Jia family and a love triangle among Jia Baoyu and his cousins Lin Daiyu and Xue Baochai. Admired for its psychological depth and detailed portrait of aristocratic life, it is widely regarded as the pinnacle of classical Chinese fiction.",
"Aristocracy": "Aristocracy is a form of government or social order in which power is held by a small privileged class regarded as the most qualified to rule. The term also denotes that ruling class itself, whose standing typically rests on noble birth, hereditary title, or landed wealth. In political philosophy it has been described as rule by the few in the supposed interest of the whole.",
"Daozang": "The Daozang (道藏) is the canon of Daoist scriptures, a vast collection comprising roughly fifteen hundred texts on doctrine, ritual, alchemy, meditation, and related subjects. Its contents are organized into three principal divisions known as the Three Grottoes, with later supplementary sections added to accommodate additional writings. The canon serves as the foundational textual corpus from which Daoist priests are ordained and trained.",
"Narmer": "Narmer was an ancient Egyptian ruler of the Early Dynastic Period who is widely regarded as the unifier of Upper and Lower Egypt. He is frequently identified as the founder of the First Dynasty and is sometimes equated with the figure known as Menes. The Narmer Palette, a carved ceremonial slab bearing his name, depicts him wearing the crowns of both regions and is among the earliest historical documents from Egypt.",
"Tarim_Basin": "The Tarim Basin is a large endorheic basin in Xinjiang, northwestern China, covering about 888,000 square kilometres. It is bounded by the Tian Shan to the north and the Kunlun Mountains to the south and is largely filled by the Taklamakan Desert, with oasis settlements around its edges. The basin was a crucial crossroads of the Silk Road, linking China with Central Asia and India.",
"Single_whip_law": "The single whip law, in Chinese yitiao bianfa, was a tax reform of the Ming dynasty that consolidated numerous separate land taxes, poll taxes, and labor obligations into a single payment levied in silver. Developed during the sixteenth century and promoted empire-wide by the grand secretary Zhang Juzheng around 1580, it simplified a complex fiscal code and increased the monetization of the rural economy. The reform reflected the growing role of silver in Chinese commerce and government finance.",
"Cronus": "Cronus is the youngest of the first generation of Titans in ancient Greek mythology and the ruler of the cosmos during the Golden Age. He is the son of Uranus and Gaia, and with his sister Rhea he fathered Hestia, Hades, Demeter, Poseidon, Hera, and Zeus. He castrated and overthrew his father with a sickle and later swallowed his own children, until Zeus deposed him and freed his siblings.",
"Empress_Lü_Zhi": "Lü Zhi was the empress of Emperor Gaozu and, after his death in 195 BCE, the dominant power at the Han court as empress dowager and regent until her own death in 180 BCE. Ruling through her son Emperor Hui and then two child emperors, she became the first woman to control the government of imperial China. She elevated her own kinsmen and dealt brutally with rivals, and her clan was overthrown shortly after she died.",
"Indra": "Indra is the king of the gods in Vedic and Hindu mythology, associated with the sky, lightning, thunder, storms, rain, and war. His principal weapon is the vajra, a thunderbolt, with which he is said to have slain the serpent demon Vritra to release the waters. He is a prominent deity in the Rigveda, where more hymns are addressed to him than to almost any other god.",
"Ziggurat": "A ziggurat is a massive terraced structure built in ancient Mesopotamia and neighboring regions, formed of successively receding stepped levels. These structures served as temple platforms regarded as dwelling places for patron deities, with access typically restricted to priests. Notable examples include the Great Ziggurat of Ur and the Etemenanki at Babylon.",
"Hong_Xiuquan": "Hong Xiuquan was a Chinese religious and revolutionary leader who founded and led the Taiping Heavenly Kingdom against the Qing dynasty. After failing the civil service examinations and reading Christian pamphlets, he came to believe he was the younger brother of Jesus Christ and called for the overthrow of Manchu rule. His movement captured Nanjing in 1853 and held much of southern China for over a decade until his death in 1864, shortly before the city fell.",
"The_Cowherd_and_the_Weaver_Girl": "The Cowherd and the Weaver Girl (牛郎織女) is a Chinese folktale telling of the love between the herdsman Niulang and the celestial weaver Zhinü, identified with the stars Altair and Vega. Their union is forbidden because a goddess cannot wed a mortal, and they are separated to opposite banks of the heavenly river of the Milky Way. Once a year, on the seventh night of the seventh lunar month, magpies are said to form a bridge so the two may briefly reunite, an event celebrated as the Qixi Festival.",
"Valhalla": "Valhalla is a great hall in Asgard ruled by the god Odin, whose name means hall of the slain. It houses the einherjar, warriors chosen from among those killed in battle, who feast and fight there while awaiting the end of the world. At Ragnarök the einherjar are foretold to march out from its many doors to fight alongside Odin against the jötnar.",
"School_of_Diplomacy": "The School of Diplomacy (縱橫家) was a Warring States current comprising itinerant persuaders and strategists who advised rulers on inter-state alliances and the balance of power. Its members are associated with two rival policies: the vertical alliance, hezong, by which weaker states combined against Qin, and the horizontal alliance, lianheng, by which Qin drew individual states into separate arrangements. Its best-known figures were Su Qin and Zhang Yi, and the tradition traced its origins to the teacher Guiguzi.",
"Dujiangyan": "Dujiangyan is an irrigation and flood-control system on the Min River in Sichuan, China, built around 256 BCE under the Qin official Li Bing. Rather than damming the river, it divides the flow with a constructed levee and channels, controlling seasonal floods while watering a vast agricultural plain. The system has been maintained and used continuously for over two millennia and still irrigates a large area of farmland.",
"Ouyang_Xiu": "Ouyang Xiu was a Chinese statesman, historian, essayist, and poet of the Northern Song dynasty and a leader of the Classical Prose Movement. He helped compile the New Book of Tang and wrote the New History of the Five Dynasties, the only one of the Twenty-Four Histories authored privately by a single person. He mentored and promoted many of the era's leading literary figures.",
"Li_Bai": "Li Bai (李白) was one of the most celebrated poets of the Tang dynasty and of all Chinese literature, a central figure of what is called the golden age of Chinese poetry. Around a thousand of his poems survive, marked by themes of wine, nature, friendship, and Daoist imagery, and he earned the epithet Immortal of Poetry. His verse has exerted lasting influence across East Asia and on Western writers such as Ezra Pound.",
"Aztec_Empire": "The Aztec Empire was an alliance of three city-states in the Valley of Mexico, dominated by Mexico-Tenochtitlan, that controlled much of central Mesoamerica in the fifteenth and early sixteenth centuries. It collected tribute from subject peoples and built a powerful religious and military culture centered on its lake island capital. The empire was overthrown by Spanish conquistadors under Hernán Cortés and their indigenous allies in 1521.",
"Liu_Shan": "Liu Shan was the second and last emperor of the state of Shu Han during the Three Kingdoms period, succeeding his father Liu Bei in 223. For much of his reign he relied on the regency of the chancellor Zhuge Liang and later officials, presiding over a state in the southwest until its conquest by Cao Wei in 263. After surrendering he was relocated to the Wei capital, where he is said to have lived out his days in comfort.",
"Angel": "An angel is a spiritual being understood in several religious traditions as a servant or messenger of God. Angels are commonly depicted carrying out divine errands, delivering messages to humans, and offering protection or praise. They appear prominently in Judaism, Christianity, and Islam, where they are described as created beings who obey the will of God.",
"Jade_burial_suit": "A jade burial suit is a ceremonial garment made of small plaques of jade sewn together to enclose the body of a high-ranking person for burial. The plaques were pierced at the corners and joined with thread, the metal of which signified rank, with gold reserved for emperors. Such suits were produced for royalty and aristocrats during the Han dynasty and required vast labour and expense to make.",
"Maitreya": "Maitreya is a bodhisattva regarded in Buddhist tradition as the future Buddha who will appear in the world after the teachings of the present Buddha have been forgotten. Believed to await rebirth in a heavenly realm, Maitreya is expected to attain complete enlightenment and renew the teaching of the dharma for a future age. The figure is venerated across many Buddhist traditions and depicted in numerous works of art.",
"Water_Margin": "Water Margin (水滸傳) is a classical Chinese novel, traditionally attributed to Shi Nai'an and dating to the late Yuan or early Ming period. It follows a band of 108 outlaws who gather at Mount Liang to resist a corrupt government before accepting amnesty and serving the Song court against rebels and invaders. Written in vernacular prose, it is celebrated for its vivid hero stories and is one of the great classical Chinese novels.",
"Bureaucracy": "Bureaucracy is an administrative system in which the affairs of a large institution are carried out by appointed officials working through defined offices. Its characteristic features include a hierarchy of authority, a division of labor, written rules and procedures, and selection and advancement based on qualifications. The model is applied to governments as well as to businesses and other large organizations.",
"Taipingjing": "The Taipingjing (太平經), or Scripture of Great Peace, is an early Daoist text surviving in part within the Daoist canon and associated with visions of a coming age of cosmic harmony. It addresses cosmology, morality, governance, and the cultivation of health, teaching that human conduct affects the balance of heaven and earth. Its ideas provided ideological inspiration for popular religious movements of the late Eastern Han period.",
"Narmer_Palette": "The Narmer Palette is an ancient Egyptian ceremonial slab of carved siltstone dating to around the thirty-first century BCE, discovered at Hierakonpolis. It depicts King Narmer wearing the White Crown of Upper Egypt on one side and the Red Crown of Lower Egypt on the other, and is often read as commemorating the unification of the country. It bears some of the earliest known hieroglyphic inscriptions and is a key artifact of the Early Dynastic Period.",
"Hexi_Corridor": "The Hexi Corridor, also called the Gansu Corridor, is a narrow strip of traversable land in western Gansu Province, China, running about 1,100 kilometres between the Qilian Mountains and the Mongolian Plateau. It formed a vital section of the Northern Silk Road, serving as the main route connecting China proper with Central Asia. The Han dynasty conquered the corridor around 121 BCE and established military commanderies there.",
"Baojia_system": "The baojia system was a method of community-based local administration and mutual surveillance in imperial China, in which households were grouped into units of tens and hundreds. Each unit bore collective responsibility for the conduct of its members, assisting in policing, tax collection, militia organization, and the reporting of crime. Associated especially with reforms of the Song dynasty and revived in later periods, it tied population control to neighborhood organization.",
"Rhea_(mythology)": "Rhea is a Titaness of ancient Greek mythology, daughter of the primordial deities Uranus and Gaia. She is the sister and consort of Cronus and the mother of Hestia, Hades, Demeter, Poseidon, Hera, and Zeus. When Cronus swallowed each of their children at birth, she saved the infant Zeus by giving Cronus a stone wrapped in swaddling clothes in his place.",
"Rebellion_of_the_Seven_States": "The Rebellion of the Seven States was a revolt of seven semi-autonomous Han kingdoms in 154 BCE, triggered by Emperor Jing's efforts to reduce their territories on the advice of Chao Cuo. Led by Liu Pi, the Prince of Wu, the rebels were defeated within about three months by imperial forces under the general Zhou Yafu. The suppression greatly weakened the regional kingdoms and advanced the centralization of Han imperial power.",
"Agni": "Agni is the god of fire in Vedic and Hindu tradition, and one of the most invoked deities of the Rigveda. He acts as a messenger who carries offerings from humans to the gods through the flames of the sacrifice. Fire personified by Agni remains central to many Hindu rituals, including weddings, where the couple circles the sacred flame, and cremations.",
"Babylon": "Babylon was an ancient city in central Mesopotamia that became one of the most important political and cultural centers of the region. It rose to power under Hammurabi in the eighteenth century BCE and reached a celebrated peak under the Neo-Babylonian Empire of Nebuchadnezzar II. The city was renowned for monuments such as the Ishtar Gate, the temple Esagila, and the ziggurat Etemenanki.",
"Eight_Banners": "The Eight Banners were the military and social organization of the Manchu people and the foundation of Qing dynasty armed forces. Created by Nurhaci in the early seventeenth century, the system grouped families into hereditary units identified by colored banners that served as both army divisions and administrative households. Bannermen formed a privileged hereditary caste receiving state stipends, and the institution was later expanded to include Mongol and Han Chinese banners.",
"Sun_Wukong": "Sun Wukong (孫悟空), the Monkey King, is a central figure of the sixteenth-century novel Journey to the West and a trickster god of Chinese mythology. Born from a stone egg and trained in Taoist arts, he gains immense strength, seventy-two transformations, a cloud-somersault that spans great distances, and a magic staff that he can shrink or enlarge at will. After rebelling against Heaven as the Great Sage Equal to Heaven, he is subdued by the Buddha and later escorts the monk Tang Sanzang on a pilgrimage to fetch Buddhist scriptures.",
"Valkyrie": "A valkyrie is a supernatural female figure in Norse mythology whose name means chooser of the slain. Valkyries decide which warriors die in battle and guide the souls of the chosen dead to Odin's hall Valhalla, where they then serve mead and ale to the einherjar. They appear throughout Old Norse poetry and prose, frequently depicted as armed and helmeted women who ride through the air and over the sea.",
"Agriculturalism": "Agriculturalism (農家) was a Warring States current of thought that held farming and the cultivation of the land to be the proper foundation of society and government. Drawing on the model of the legendary ruler Shennong, its adherents, of whom Xu Xing is the best documented, argued that a ruler should till the soil alongside the people and live from its yield. The school favored a form of egalitarian self-sufficiency, and most of its texts were lost during the Qin suppression of scholarship.",
"Seismometer": "A seismometer is an instrument that detects and records vibrations of the ground caused by earthquakes, explosions, and other disturbances. A suspended mass tends to stay still while the instrument's frame moves with the ground, and the relative motion is measured and traced as a seismogram. Networks of seismometers allow scientists to locate earthquakes, gauge their strength, and probe the internal structure of the Earth.",
"Bi_Sheng": "Bi Sheng was a Chinese artisan of the Northern Song dynasty credited with inventing movable type printing using individual fired-clay characters. Working between roughly 1039 and 1048, he arranged the ceramic types on an iron plate fixed with resin and wax so they could be rearranged and reused. His invention is described in Shen Kuo's Dream Pool Essays.",
"Du_Fu": "Du Fu (杜甫) was a Tang dynasty poet widely regarded, alongside Li Bai, as one of the greatest figures in Chinese poetry, with nearly fifteen hundred of his poems preserved. Called the Poet-Historian and Poet-Sage, he chronicled the suffering caused by the An Lushan rebellion in verse of unusual social and historical depth. Underappreciated in his lifetime, his reputation grew from the ninth century onward until he became a model exemplar of Confucian moral seriousness.",
"Maya_civilization": "The Maya civilization was a Mesoamerican culture known for the only fully developed writing system of the pre-Columbian Americas, as well as advances in art, architecture, mathematics, and astronomy. It was organized into numerous independent city-states across present-day southern Mexico and northern Central America. Many major cities declined during a period of collapse around the ninth century, though Maya peoples and communities persisted into the colonial era and to the present.",
"Emperor_Wu_of_Jin": "Emperor Wu of Jin, personal name Sima Yan, was the founding emperor of the Jin dynasty, which he established in 266 by accepting the abdication of the last Cao Wei emperor. In 280 his armies completed the conquest of Eastern Wu, reunifying China after the long division of the Three Kingdoms period. His later reign was marked by lavish excess and the granting of power to imperial princes, decisions that contributed to the instability following his death.",
"Gabriel": "Gabriel is an archangel who appears in the scriptures of Judaism, Christianity, and Islam as a messenger of God. In the Hebrew Bible he interprets visions for the prophet Daniel, and in the Christian Gospel of Luke he announces the births of John the Baptist and Jesus. In Islam he is identified as the angel who conveyed the revelations of the Quran to Muhammad.",
"Chinese_jade": "Chinese jade refers to the carved nephrite and later jadeite objects that have held ritual, ornamental, and symbolic value in China since the Neolithic period. Early ritual forms include the flat perforated disc known as the bi and the squared tube known as the cong, which were placed in burials of the elite. The stone has long been prized for its hardness, translucence, and associations with purity and moral virtue.",
"Amitābha": "Amitabha is a celestial Buddha associated with infinite light and life who is central to the devotional traditions of Mahayana Buddhism. According to scripture he established a purified realm, often called the Western Pure Land, through a series of vows, and beings who sincerely call upon him may be reborn there. Recitation of his name is a core practice of Pure Land Buddhism throughout East Asia.",
"Jin_Ping_Mei": "Jin Ping Mei (金瓶梅), often rendered The Plum in the Golden Vase, is a late Ming vernacular novel of manners published under the pseudonym Lanling Xiaoxiao Sheng. It centers on the rise and ruin of the wealthy merchant Ximen Qing and his household of wives and concubines, offering a detailed and often explicit portrait of domestic life. Despite its notoriety, it is admired for its narrative sophistication and realistic depiction of society.",
"Theocracy": "Theocracy is a form of government in which a deity or divine law is recognized as the supreme ruling authority. Governance is conducted by religious leaders or officials who claim to act on behalf of that authority and to administer its commands. The mere existence of an official state religion does not by itself make a state a theocracy unless its rulers derive their power from religious authority.",
"Cantong_qi": "The Cantong qi (參同契), often rendered as the Token for Joining the Three, is regarded as the earliest extant Chinese treatise on alchemy and is traditionally attributed to Wei Boyang in the second century CE. The text joins three strands of thought, drawing the symbolism of the hexagrams of the Book of Changes together with cosmology and alchemical practice to describe the formation of the elixir. It became a foundational scripture for both external and internal alchemical traditions in later Daoism.",
"Old_Kingdom_of_Egypt": "The Old Kingdom of Egypt is the period of ancient Egyptian history spanning roughly the Third through the Sixth Dynasties, conventionally dated to the third millennium BCE. It is often called the Age of the Pyramids because the largest stone pyramids, including those at Giza, were built during this time. Centralized royal authority was administered from the capital at Memphis until the era gave way to political fragmentation.",
"Ordos_Plateau": "The Ordos Plateau is an elevated region in northern China enclosed by the great northern loop of the Yellow River, spanning parts of Inner Mongolia, Shaanxi, Ningxia, Gansu, and Shanxi. It includes arid stretches such as the Mu Us and Kubuqi deserts in the north and the more fertile Hetao plains, and sits at elevations of roughly 1,000 to 1,600 metres. The area was an early centre of human occupation, with Paleolithic and Bronze Age cultures attested there.",
"Lijia": "The lijia was a system of rural administrative organization under the Ming dynasty that grouped households into units for the assessment of taxes and the assignment of labor service. A set number of households formed a jia and a larger number formed a li, with designated head households rotating responsibility for collecting dues and managing local obligations. The system underpinned the empire's registration of land and population in its earlier period.",
"Gaia": "Gaia is the personification of the Earth in ancient Greek mythology and one of the primordial deities who emerged at the beginning of the cosmos. She gave birth to Uranus, the sky, and with him produced the Titans, the Cyclopes, and the hundred-handed Hecatoncheires. She figures prominently in succession myths, aiding the overthrow of Uranus and later opposing the rule of his successors.",
"Gan_Ying": "Gan Ying was an Eastern Han envoy dispatched in 97 CE by the general Ban Chao on a mission to reach the Roman Empire. He travelled as far as the Persian Gulf or the eastern shore of a great sea before Parthian sailors discouraged him with accounts of a long and dangerous voyage, prompting him to turn back. The observations he gathered about distant western lands were recorded in the Book of the Later Han.",
"Mahabharata": "The Mahabharata is one of the two major Sanskrit epics of ancient India, traditionally attributed to the sage Vyasa. It narrates a dynastic struggle and the great Kurukshetra War between two branches of a royal family, the Pandavas and the Kauravas. One of the longest poems ever composed, it contains the philosophical dialogue known as the Bhagavad Gita.",
"Code_of_Hammurabi": "The Code of Hammurabi is a Babylonian legal text issued around 1750 BCE by Hammurabi, the sixth king of the First Dynasty of Babylon. Inscribed on a tall basalt stele discovered in 1901, it is among the longest and best-preserved legal documents from the ancient Near East. The code is widely known for applying the principle of retribution often summarized as an eye for an eye.",
"Hanlin_Academy": "The Hanlin Academy was an elite scholarly and administrative institution of imperial China, founded in the eighth century under the Tang dynasty. Its members, drawn from the highest ranks of examination graduates, performed literary, secretarial, and editorial duties for the court and helped shape interpretations of the Confucian classics. The academy remained a prestigious body through the Ming and Qing dynasties until its closure in the early twentieth century.",
"Mazu": "Mazu (媽祖) is a sea goddess of Chinese folk religion venerated as the protector of seafarers, fishermen, and sailors. She is the deified form of Lin Moniang, a shamaness from Fujian traditionally said to have lived in the tenth century, who after her death was worshipped for guarding those at sea. Imperial courts conferred rising titles on her, including Tianhou, Empress of Heaven, and belief in her was inscribed on UNESCO's list of intangible cultural heritage in 2009.",
"Ragnarök": "Ragnarök is the foretold series of events in Norse mythology that culminates in a great battle, the deaths of many gods, and the destruction of the world. Among those fated to fall are Odin, who is consumed by the wolf Fenrir, and Thor, who slays the serpent Jörmungandr but dies of its venom, while fire spreads and the earth sinks into the sea. After the cataclysm the world is foretold to rise again green and fertile, with surviving gods and the human pair Líf and Lífþrasir to repopulate it.",
"Guiguzi": "Guiguzi (鬼谷子), meaning Master of Ghost Valley, is the name of a semi-legendary teacher active in the 4th century BCE and of the text attributed to him. The figure is traditionally regarded as the founder of the School of Diplomacy and the teacher of persuaders and strategists such as Su Qin and Zhang Yi. The text, running a few thousand characters across three books, sets out techniques of rhetoric, persuasion, and psychological influence and was later absorbed into the Daoist canon.",
"Blast_furnace": "A blast furnace is a tall shaft furnace used to smelt metal from its ore, in which a continuous blast of air or oxygen is forced through a burning charge of ore, fuel, and flux. The intense, sustained heat reduces the ore to molten metal, which gathers at the bottom and is drawn off, while impurities form a floating slag. It is the principal means of producing iron from iron ore on a large scale.",
"Emperor_Huizong_of_Song": "Emperor Huizong of Song (宋徽宗), personal name Zhao Ji, reigned from 1100 to 1126 as the eighth emperor of the Song dynasty and is remembered above all as a gifted painter, calligrapher, and lavish patron of the arts who developed the distinctive Slender Gold style of calligraphy. Absorbed in aesthetic and Daoist pursuits, he largely neglected the affairs of state and left administration to ministers whose costly projects and misrule steadily weakened the dynasty. In early 1126 he abdicated in favour of his son Qinzong as Jurchen Jin armies advanced, and both were seized in the Jingkang Incident of 1127 that toppled the Northern Song, after which Huizong was taken into captivity in the north, where he died in 1135.",
"Wang_Wei_(Tang_dynasty)": "Wang Wei (王維) was a Tang dynasty poet, painter, and musician celebrated for landscape poetry in the mountains-and-streams tradition. The later writer Su Shi praised his work by saying his poems contained paintings and his paintings contained poems. He is traditionally regarded as a founder of the Southern School of Chinese landscape art and a devout Buddhist whose verse reflects quiet contemplation of nature.",
"Spartacus": "Spartacus was a Thracian gladiator who became one of the leaders of a major slave uprising against the Roman Republic. The revolt, known as the Third Servile War, began in 73 BCE and at its height fielded tens of thousands of escaped enslaved people who defeated several Roman armies. The rebellion was crushed by forces under Marcus Licinius Crassus in 71 BCE, and Spartacus is believed to have died in the final battle.",
"War_of_the_Eight_Princes": "The War of the Eight Princes was a series of civil wars fought from 291 to 306 among princes and regents of the Jin imperial Sima clan over control of the central government. The prolonged conflict devastated the Jin state, depopulated its heartland, and drained its military strength. The chaos opened the way for non-Han peoples to rise in revolt, leading to the loss of northern China and the start of the Sixteen Kingdoms period.",
"Satan": "Satan is a figure in the Abrahamic religions who personifies evil, temptation, and rebellion against God. In the Hebrew Bible the term originally denoted an accuser or adversary, while later Jewish, Christian, and Islamic traditions developed him into a powerful spiritual opponent of God and humanity. He is often portrayed as the tempter who leads people away from righteousness.",
"Ru_ware": "Ru ware (汝窯) is a rare type of Chinese stoneware produced for the imperial court during a brief period of the Northern Song dynasty. It is prized for its subtle bluish-green glaze, often likened to the colour of sky after rain, and for the fine crackle that appears across many surviving pieces. Fewer than a hundred complete examples are known, making it among the most coveted of Chinese ceramics.",
"Mañjushri": "Manjushri is a bodhisattva who embodies the transcendent wisdom of the Buddhas in Mahayana Buddhism. He is commonly depicted as a youthful figure wielding a flaming sword that cuts through ignorance and holding a scripture of perfected wisdom, and he is sometimes shown riding a lion. He is among the oldest and most important bodhisattvas in Mahayana literature.",
"Records_of_the_Three_Kingdoms": "The Records of the Three Kingdoms (三國志) is an official history compiled by Chen Shou in the late third century, covering the end of the Han dynasty and the Three Kingdoms period from about 184 to 280 CE. It is arranged into separate books for the rival states of Cao Wei, Shu Han, and Eastern Wu and is composed largely of biographies. A fifth-century commentary by Pei Songzhi added extensive supplementary material, making it a primary source for the era.",
"Oligarchy": "Oligarchy is a form of government in which power rests with a small group of people. That group may be set apart by wealth, family connection, military strength, or other forms of influence, and it tends to govern in its own interest. The concept has been used since antiquity to describe and criticize rule concentrated in the hands of a few.",
"Wei_Boyang": "Wei Boyang was a Chinese alchemist and Daoist writer of the Eastern Han dynasty traditionally credited with composing the Cantong qi. His work wove together alchemical operations, the symbolism of the Book of Changes, and Daoist ideas of non-action to describe the preparation of an elixir of immortality. He is remembered as one of the earliest named figures in the Chinese alchemical tradition.",
"Middle_Kingdom_of_Egypt": "The Middle Kingdom of Egypt is the period of ancient Egyptian history that followed the reunification of the country under the Eleventh Dynasty and continued through the Twelfth and Thirteenth Dynasties. It is regarded as a time of strong central government, expansion into Nubia, and notable achievements in literature and art. The era is conventionally placed in the early second millennium BCE.",
"Yumen_Pass": "Yumen Pass, also known as the Jade Gate, was a frontier pass northwest of Dunhuang in Gansu Province, China, named for the jade caravans that passed through it. Established under Emperor Wu of Han around 121 BCE, it guarded a key route of the Silk Road connecting Central Asia with East Asia. The fortified site was largely abandoned by the sixth century as caravans favoured more northerly routes, and it was later inscribed as part of a UNESCO World Heritage Site.",
"Fubing_system": "The fubing system was a militia organization of military households used in China from the Western Wei through the Tang dynasty, in which soldiers supported themselves by farming allotted land. In return for tax and labor exemptions, the farmer-soldiers supplied their own provisions and equipment and served in rotation at the capital and frontier, keeping the cost to the state low. The system declined in the eighth century as the land base that sustained it eroded, giving way to professional armies.",
"Uranus_(mythology)": "Uranus is the personification of the sky in ancient Greek mythology and one of the early primordial deities. He is the son and consort of Gaia, with whom he fathered the Titans, the Cyclopes, and the Hecatoncheires. He was castrated and overthrown by his son Cronus, an act from which further beings were said to have arisen.",
"Book_of_the_Later_Han": "The Book of the Later Han (後漢書) is one of the Twenty-Four Histories, covering the Eastern Han dynasty from 6 to 189 CE. It was compiled in the fifth century by Fan Ye and others during the Liu Song dynasty, drawing on earlier records written closer to the events. The work is valued for its detailed accounts of the Western Regions and of contacts with distant lands including the Roman Empire.",
"Ramayana": "The Ramayana is one of the two major Sanskrit epics of ancient India, traditionally attributed to the poet Valmiki. In nearly twenty-four thousand verses it recounts the life of Rama, including his exile from Ayodhya, the abduction of his wife Sita by the demon king Ravana, and the war to rescue her. The epic has been retold in many languages across South and Southeast Asia and is central to Hindu religious culture.",
"Ur": "Ur was a major Sumerian city-state in southern Mesopotamia, located at the modern site of Tell el-Muqayyar in present-day Iraq. Its power peaked during the Third Dynasty of Ur, when it ruled as an imperial center, and its patron deity was the moon god Nanna. The Great Ziggurat of Ur, built under Ur-Nammu in the twenty-first century BCE, remains one of its best-known monuments.",
"First_Opium_War": "The First Opium War was a conflict fought between the British Empire and Qing China from 1839 to 1842, sparked by Chinese efforts to suppress the British-led opium trade. British naval and military superiority forced a series of Qing defeats along the coast and rivers. The war ended with the Treaty of Nanking, which ceded Hong Kong Island to Britain, opened treaty ports, and imposed a large indemnity, opening the era of unequal treaties.",
"Zhong_Kui": "Zhong Kui (鍾馗) is a deity of Chinese folk religion and Taoism revered as a queller of demons and malevolent spirits. Legend holds that he was a scholar who, after failing or being denied the imperial examination, took his own life and returned as a fierce ghost-catcher, appearing in a dream of Emperor Xuanzong of Tang to drive off a demon and cure the emperor's illness. He is portrayed as a large, fierce-faced man with a curly beard wielding a sword, and his image is hung at the New Year and other times to ward off evil.",
"Jörmungandr": "Jörmungandr, also called the Midgard Serpent or World Serpent, is an enormous sea serpent in Norse mythology that lies in the ocean encircling the world of humans and grips its own tail. It is the middle child of Loki and the jötunn Angrboða, cast into the sea by Odin, where it grows large enough to surround the earth. At Ragnarök it releases its tail and rears onto the land, where Thor kills it but then dies after walking nine steps, overcome by its venom.",
"Lü_Buwei": "Lü Buwei (呂不韋; 291–235 BCE) was a wealthy merchant who rose to become chancellor of the state of Qin and a dominant figure at its court. Having helped Prince Yiren reach the throne, he served as regent during the youth of Ying Zheng, the future Qin Shi Huang, and sponsored the compilation of the encyclopedic Lüshi Chunqiu. Implicated in a court scandal in 235 BCE, he was stripped of his offices and banished, and took his own life in exile.",
"Crossbow": "A crossbow is a ranged weapon consisting of a bow mounted horizontally on a stock, with a mechanism that holds the drawn string until a trigger releases it to shoot a short arrow called a bolt or quarrel. Because the string is held mechanically rather than by the archer's muscles, a crossbow can store great force and be aimed at leisure, letting relatively untrained users shoot with accuracy. It has been employed in hunting and warfare and survives today in sport and specialized roles.",
"Jingkang_incident": "The Jingkang incident (靖康之變) was the 1127 capture of the Northern Song capital Bianjing by the Jurchen-led Jin dynasty. Jin forces seized the retired Emperor Huizong, the reigning Emperor Qinzong, and much of the imperial household, marching thousands of captives northward. The catastrophe ended the Northern Song and led survivors to reestablish the dynasty in the south under Emperor Gaozong.",
"Bai_Juyi": "Bai Juyi (白居易) was a prolific Tang dynasty poet who wrote in a deliberately accessible, plain style and left behind more than twenty-eight hundred poems. He held a series of official posts, including governor of Hangzhou and Suzhou, where he undertook public works such as repairing a lake dike. His best-known works, the Song of Everlasting Regret and the Song of the Pipa Player, became immensely popular across East Asia.",
"Crusades": "The Crusades were a series of religious wars sanctioned by the Latin Church during the medieval period, beginning in 1095. The early campaigns aimed to recover Jerusalem and the Holy Land from Muslim rule, leading to the establishment of short-lived Crusader states in the Levant. Over roughly two centuries the movement reshaped relations between Christian Europe and the Islamic and Byzantine worlds.",
"Sixteen_Kingdoms": "The Sixteen Kingdoms was a period of Chinese history from roughly 304 to 439 during which northern China fragmented into a shifting array of short-lived states, many founded by peoples of non-Han origin. The era began as the Jin dynasty lost control of the north following internal wars and uprisings, and it saw repeated rises and falls of regimes such as Han-Zhao, Later Zhao, Former Yan, and Former Qin. It ended when the Northern Wei reunified the north, opening the Northern and Southern dynasties era.",
"Messiah": "A messiah is a promised deliverer or anointed leader awaited in several religious traditions. In Judaism the term refers to a future king of the line of David who will restore Israel and bring an age of peace. In Christianity the title is applied to Jesus, whom believers identify as the awaited savior of humanity.",
"Blue_and_white_pottery": "Blue and white pottery (青花瓷) is porcelain decorated with designs painted in cobalt pigment under a clear glaze, producing blue patterns on a white ground. The cobalt was applied to the unfired body and fired with the glaze in a single high-temperature firing. The technique became widely used in China from the 14th century, centred on the kilns at Jingdezhen, and was exported across Asia and beyond.",
"Samantabhadra": "Samantabhadra is a bodhisattva associated with Buddhist practice, meditation, and the carrying out of vows in Mahayana Buddhism. He is traditionally depicted seated on a white elephant with multiple tusks and is celebrated for a set of great vows expressing the ideal conduct of one striving toward enlightenment. He is widely venerated across East Asian and Tibetan Buddhist traditions.",
"Lüshi_Chunqiu": "The Lüshi Chunqiu (呂氏春秋) is an encyclopedic Chinese text compiled around 239 BCE under the patronage of the Qin chancellor Lü Buwei. Drawing on Confucian, Legalist, Mohist, and Daoist ideas, it is organized into almanacs, examinations, and discourses treating subjects such as government, music, and agriculture. It is valued both as a synthesis of pre-imperial thought and as a well-structured early reference work.",
"Ideology": "An ideology is a system of ideas, beliefs, and values that explains how society works and prescribes how it ought to be organized. It typically offers a shared framework that guides political and social action for a group or movement. The term is used both neutrally, for any such belief system, and critically, to suggest a distorted or partisan view of reality.",
"Ge_Hong": "Ge Hong was a Chinese scholar, physician, and alchemist of the Eastern Jin dynasty best known for his treatise the Baopuzi. In that work he defended the pursuit of immortality through alchemy, the ingestion of elixirs, and moral and meditative cultivation, while also recording medical and technical knowledge. His writings on medicinal preparations, including descriptions of treatments for fevers, influenced later Chinese medicine.",
"New_Kingdom_of_Egypt": "The New Kingdom of Egypt is the period of ancient Egyptian history spanning the Eighteenth through the Twentieth Dynasties, dated to the later second millennium BCE. It was the era of Egypt's greatest territorial extent and imperial power, with rulers campaigning in the Levant and Nubia. Many of the most famous pharaohs, including Hatshepsut, Akhenaten, Tutankhamun, and Ramesses II, reigned during this time.",
"Nanjing": "Nanjing is a city in eastern China and the capital of Jiangsu Province, situated on the lower Yangtze River. It served as the capital of numerous Chinese states and dynasties, including several of the Six Dynasties, the early Ming dynasty, and the Republic of China. The city has long been a major political, cultural, and educational centre of southern China.",
"Foot_binding": "Foot binding was the practice of tightly wrapping the feet of young girls in China to alter their shape and restrict their growth, producing the small feet considered a mark of beauty and status. Begun in the imperial era and widespread among many social classes by late imperial times, it caused lifelong deformity and impaired mobility. The custom was the target of reform campaigns from the late nineteenth century and was largely eradicated in the twentieth century.",
"Titans": "The Titans are the deities of the second divine generation in ancient Greek mythology, preceding the Olympian gods. They are the children of the primordial figures Uranus and Gaia and include Cronus, Rhea, Oceanus, Hyperion, Iapetus, Themis, and Mnemosyne. After a ten-year war known as the Titanomachy, they were defeated by the Olympians led by Zeus and many were confined in Tartarus.",
"Emperor_Guangwu_of_Han": "Emperor Guangwu, born Liu Xiu, restored the Han dynasty and founded its Eastern phase, reigning from 25 to 57 CE after the collapse of Wang Mang's Xin dynasty and the ensuing civil wars. He defeated rival warlords to reunify China and moved the capital eastward from Chang'an to Luoyang. He was noted as an unusually merciful founder who spared many former opponents and rewarded loyal generals rather than executing them.",
"Bhagavad_Gita": "The Bhagavad Gita is a Hindu scripture of seven hundred verses that forms part of the epic Mahabharata. It is structured as a dialogue in which the god Krishna instructs the warrior Arjuna on duty, action, and the nature of the self on the eve of battle. It is one of the most influential texts of Hindu philosophy and devotion, and was likely composed in the centuries around the start of the Common Era.",
"Uruk": "Uruk was one of the earliest cities in human history, situated in southern Mesopotamia near the Euphrates in present-day Iraq. As the type site of the Uruk period, it played a leading role in early urbanization and reached perhaps forty thousand residents around 3100 BCE. The legendary king Gilgamesh was associated with Uruk and credited in tradition with constructing its walls.",
"Treaty_of_Nanking": "The Treaty of Nanking was the 1842 agreement between Great Britain and the Qing dynasty that ended the First Opium War. Its terms ceded Hong Kong Island to Britain, opened five treaty ports including Shanghai and Canton to foreign trade, and required China to pay a large silver indemnity. Regarded as the first of the so-called unequal treaties, it marked the beginning of expanding foreign privilege within China.",
"Tudigong": "Tudigong (土地公) is a class of tutelary earth deity in Chinese folk religion, Taoism, and folk Buddhism, each a guardian of a specific locality such as a village, field, bridge, or building. Typically depicted as a kindly old man with a long white beard, he is regarded as a modest local official of the spirit bureaucracy to whom villagers appeal in times of drought, famine, or other community need. A formal title for him is Fude Zhengshen, and small shrines dedicated to him were once found throughout rural China.",
"Fenrir": "Fenrir is a monstrous wolf in Norse mythology, the offspring of Loki and the jötunn Angrboða and a sibling of the serpent Jörmungandr and the being Hel. Fearing his strength, the gods bind him with the magical fetter Gleipnir, and in the process the god Týr loses his right hand to the wolf's jaws. At Ragnarök Fenrir breaks loose and devours Odin, after which Odin's son Víðarr avenges his father by killing the wolf.",
"Yin_Wen": "Yin Wen (尹文; c. 350–284 BCE) was a Chinese philosopher and logician of the state of Qi who was active at the Jixia Academy and served the kings Xuan and Min. He is associated with the School of Names and with a theory of the rectification of names, holding that names should correspond to realities, while also drawing on Huang-Lao ideas and favoring minimal government through non-action. His thought is preserved in the Yin Wenzi and in references by later writers.",
"Seed_drill": "A seed drill is an agricultural implement that sows seeds in straight rows at a controlled depth and spacing, covering them with soil as it is drawn across a field. By placing seed precisely below the surface rather than scattering it by hand, it reduces waste, improves germination, and eases later weeding and harvesting. The device was an important step in the mechanization of farming.",
"Emperor_Gaozong_of_Song": "Emperor Gaozong of Song (宋高宗), personal name Zhao Gou, reigned from 1127 to 1162 as the first emperor of the Southern Song, having escaped the Jurchen Jin capture of the northern capital Kaifeng in the Jingkang Incident and fled south to re-establish the dynasty with its capital at Lin'an, present-day Hangzhou. With his chancellor Qin Hui he pursued a policy of accommodation with the Jin, agreeing to the Treaty of Shaoxing in 1141 that fixed the border along the Huai River and made the Southern Song a tributary of the Jin. To clear the path to that peace he had the celebrated patriotic general Yue Fei imprisoned and put to death on fabricated charges in 1142, and he later abdicated in favor of his adopted heir Emperor Xiaozong in 1162.",
"Han_Yu": "Han Yu (韓愈) was a Tang dynasty essayist, poet, and official who led a movement promoting clear classical prose, known as guwen, over ornate parallel styles. A fervent defender of Confucianism, he attacked Buddhist and Daoist influence, most famously in a memorial protesting the veneration of a Buddha relic. Later critics ranked him first among the Eight Great Prose Masters of the Tang and Song.",
"Black_Death": "The Black Death was a devastating pandemic of plague that swept across Afro-Eurasia in the fourteenth century. It is generally attributed to the bacterium Yersinia pestis and is estimated to have killed a large share of the population of Europe, the Middle East, and North Africa between 1346 and 1353. The catastrophe brought profound demographic, economic, and social upheaval to the affected regions.",
"Battle_of_Fei_River": "The Battle of Fei River was fought in 383 between the Di-led Former Qin dynasty and the much smaller army of the Eastern Jin dynasty. The Former Qin ruler Fu Jian sought to conquer the south and reunify China, but his vast, hastily assembled host collapsed in confusion and was routed near the Huai River. The defeat secured the survival of the Eastern Jin in the south and triggered the disintegration of the Former Qin in the north.",
"Trinity": "The Trinity is the Christian doctrine that God exists as three coequal and coeternal persons: the Father, the Son, and the Holy Spirit. According to this teaching, the three persons share one divine essence while remaining three distinct persons within the one Godhead. The doctrine was articulated through the early church councils and is a defining belief of most Christian denominations.",
"Lacquerware": "Lacquerware is decorative or functional ware coated with lacquer made from the refined sap of the lacquer tree, which dries to a hard, glossy, water-resistant surface. Objects are built up through many thin layers, and in the carved technique thick accumulations of lacquer are cut into relief designs. The craft has a very long history in China, with examples surviving from Neolithic sites and elaborate carved pieces produced from the Song dynasty onward.",
"Kṣitigarbha": "Kshitigarbha is a bodhisattva who vowed to guide and protect beings through the period between the passing of the present Buddha and the coming of the future Buddha. He is especially associated with compassion for those suffering in hellish realms and is said to have resolved not to attain Buddhahood until all such realms are emptied. He is typically depicted as a monk holding a staff and a wish-fulfilling jewel.",
"Wen_Xuan": "The Wen Xuan (文選), or Selections of Refined Literature, is one of the earliest and most influential anthologies of Chinese literature, compiled around 520–530 CE by Xiao Tong, crown prince of the Liang dynasty. It gathers 761 works arranged by genre into categories such as rhapsodies, poems, and prose, spanning from the late Warring States period to the early sixth century. The anthology became essential study material for educated readers and shaped literary taste across East Asia.",
"Taboo": "A taboo is a strong social or sacred prohibition against an act, object, person, or word, breach of which is regarded as deeply offensive or dangerous. Such prohibitions are often felt to be self-evidently binding and may be tied to ideas of purity, danger, or the sacred. The concept entered wider use from a Polynesian term and has been studied across many cultures.",
"Fangshi": "Fangshi (方士) were technical and occult specialists in early China who practiced arts such as alchemy, astrology, divination, geomancy, and the search for longevity. Active especially from the late Warring States period through the early medieval era, they served rulers seeking immortality and esoteric knowledge and circulated methods for transforming substances and predicting fortune. Much of their lore was later absorbed into organized Daoism and traditional Chinese medicine.",
"Memphis,_Egypt": "Memphis was an ancient city of Egypt situated near the apex of the Nile Delta, south of modern Cairo. It served as the capital during the Old Kingdom and remained an important administrative and religious center for much of Egyptian history. The city was a major cult site of the creator god Ptah, and its associated necropolis includes the pyramid fields of Saqqara and Giza.",
"Hangzhou": "Hangzhou is a city in eastern China and the capital of Zhejiang Province, lying at the southern end of the Grand Canal near Hangzhou Bay. It was the capital of the Wuyue kingdom and later of the Southern Song dynasty, and is counted among the Eight Ancient Capitals of China. The city is renowned for the scenic West Lake, a UNESCO World Heritage Site.",
"Queue_(hairstyle)": "The queue was a hairstyle in which the front of the head was shaved and the remaining hair worn in a long braid at the back. In China it was imposed on the male population by the Qing dynasty after 1644 as a mark of submission to Manchu rule, enforced under severe penalties. The hairstyle became a charged political symbol and was widely cut off following the revolution that ended the dynasty in the early twentieth century.",
"Twelve_Olympians": "The Twelve Olympians are the principal deities of the ancient Greek pantheon, said to reside on Mount Olympus. The group is usually counted as Zeus, Hera, Poseidon, Demeter, Athena, Apollo, Artemis, Ares, Aphrodite, Hephaestus, Hermes, and either Hestia or Dionysus. They rose to power after the Olympians, led by Zeus, overthrew the Titans.",
"Chao_Cuo": "Chao Cuo was a Western Han official who advised Emperors Wen and Jing on statecraft, frontier defense, and economics, and rose to the rank of Imperial Secretary. He pressed for reducing the size of the powerful regional kingdoms to strengthen central authority, a policy that helped provoke the Rebellion of the Seven States. In 154 BCE Emperor Jing had him executed in a failed attempt to appease the rebel princes.",
"Upanishads": "The Upanishads are a collection of late Vedic Sanskrit texts that mark a shift from ritual practice toward philosophical and contemplative inquiry. They explore foundational ideas such as Brahman, the ultimate reality, and Atman, the inner self, and discuss meditation, knowledge, and liberation. They form the basis for much of later Hindu philosophy, including the various schools of Vedanta.",
"Nippur": "Nippur was an ancient Sumerian city that served as the chief seat of worship for the god Enlil and home to the Ekur temple. Although it rarely held political power of its own, control of Nippur conferred religious legitimacy on rulers from other city-states. It lay in lower Mesopotamia, roughly two hundred kilometers south of modern Baghdad, and retained its sacred status across many dynasties.",
"Second_Opium_War": "The Second Opium War was a conflict from 1856 to 1860 in which Britain and France fought the Qing dynasty to expand foreign trade and diplomatic rights in China. The allied forces captured Guangzhou and Tianjin and ultimately occupied Beijing, where they looted and burned the Old Summer Palace. The war concluded with the Convention of Peking, which legalized the opium trade, opened further ports, and ceded Kowloon to Britain.",
"Caishen": "Caishen (財神) is the god of wealth in Chinese folk religion and Taoism, whose name means God of Wealth. Rather than a single figure, he is venerated through several incarnations identified with historical and legendary persons such as Zhao Gongming, Bi Gan, and Fan Li, and these are often grouped into civil and martial forms. He is frequently depicted holding a golden rod or riding a black tiger, and his name is invoked during the Chinese New Year, when households ceremonially welcome him for prosperity in the year ahead.",
"Sleipnir": "Sleipnir is the eight-legged horse ridden by Odin in Norse mythology, described as the finest of all horses among gods and humans. He is the offspring of Loki, who in the form of a mare bore him to the stallion Svaðilfari. He is able to travel between the worlds, and he carries the messenger Hermóðr on his journey to the realm of the dead to seek the release of Baldr.",
"Deng_Xi": "Deng Xi (鄧析; c. 545–501 BCE) was a senior official of the state of Zheng and an early figure linked to the School of Names. Often called China's earliest recorded lawyer, he is credited with a privately drafted penal code and was known for skill in legal argument and for defending contradictory propositions through the practice of bian, or distinguishing categories in debate. He was executed in 501 BCE, after which the ruler of Zheng is said to have adopted his penal code.",
"Suspension_bridge": "A suspension bridge is a bridge whose deck is hung from cables or chains suspended between tall towers and anchored at each end. Because the main load is carried in tension by the cables, the form can span far greater distances than a rigid beam or arch. Modern examples use spun-steel cables to cross wide rivers, straits, and deep gorges.",
"Qin_Hui": "Qin Hui was a chancellor of the Southern Song dynasty under Emperor Gaozong who directed the policy of seeking peace with the Jurchen Jin dynasty. He negotiated the Treaty of Shaoxing and orchestrated the imprisonment and execution of the general Yue Fei on fabricated charges. He is widely condemned in traditional Chinese historiography as a traitor.",
"Liu_Zongyuan": "Liu Zongyuan (柳宗元) was a Tang dynasty writer and official who, with Han Yu, led the classical prose movement and is counted among the Eight Great Prose Masters of the Tang and Song. He excelled at biography, travel writing, and fable, often depicting the hardships of ordinary people under heavy taxation. His essays advanced the idea that a ruler's legitimacy rests on the support of the people.",
"French_Revolution": "The French Revolution was a period of political and social upheaval in France that began in 1789 and overturned the monarchy and feudal privileges. It produced the Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen, the execution of King Louis XVI, and a turbulent succession of revolutionary governments including the Reign of Terror. Its ideals of liberty, equality, and popular sovereignty had a lasting influence on modern politics.",
"Former_Qin": "Former Qin was a state of the Sixteen Kingdoms period, founded in 351 by the Di people under the Fu clan with its capital at Chang'an. Under the ruler Fu Jian and his chief minister Wang Meng it briefly unified almost all of northern China in the 370s. Its power shattered after the catastrophic defeat at the Battle of Fei River in 383, after which it fragmented and fell within a few years.",
"Ark_of_the_Covenant": "The Ark of the Covenant is a sacred chest described in the Hebrew Bible as the most holy object of the Israelites. According to the Book of Exodus it was made of acacia wood overlaid with gold and topped by a lid bearing two cherubim, and it held the stone tablets of the Ten Commandments. It was kept in the Tabernacle and later in the First Temple in Jerusalem, and its eventual fate is unknown.",
"Dougong": "Dougong (斗拱) is a system of interlocking wooden brackets used in traditional Chinese timber architecture to support the eaves and transfer the weight of the roof onto the columns. The brackets are assembled by joinery alone, fitting together without glue or nails, and their layered construction helps buildings absorb seismic forces. Over time the bracket sets became smaller and increasingly decorative, and their use was associated with structures of high status.",
"Nirvana_(Buddhism)": "In Buddhism, nirvana is the ultimate goal of the path, a state of liberation in which the fires of craving, aversion, and ignorance are extinguished. It marks the end of suffering and of the cycle of repeated birth and death, bringing release from the conditions that bind beings to rebirth. The complete nirvana attained at the death of one who has been liberated is sometimes called parinirvana.",
"The_Literary_Mind_and_the_Carving_of_Dragons": "The Literary Mind and the Carving of Dragons (文心雕龍) is a comprehensive work of literary theory and criticism written by Liu Xie in the early sixth century. Across fifty chapters it surveys the origins, genres, and craft of Chinese writing, treating literature as the expression of human feeling through ordered language. It is regarded as the most systematic and important work of literary criticism in the Chinese tradition.",
"Pilgrimage": "A pilgrimage is a journey undertaken to a place held to be sacred or otherwise significant, usually for religious or spiritual reasons. Pilgrims may travel to seek blessing, fulfill a vow, do penance, or honor a holy figure or event associated with the destination. The practice is found in many religious traditions and has shaped routes, shrines, and rituals around the world.",
"Fulu": "Fulu (符籙) are Daoist talismans, written or drawn symbols believed to carry spiritual power and to enable communication with deities and spirits. Their scripts are often deliberately stylized and difficult to read, and they are used in rituals of healing, protection, and exorcism, sometimes by burning the talisman and consuming the ashes. The practice spread beyond Daoism into Chinese Buddhist and folk religious traditions.",
"Thebes,_Egypt": "Thebes was an ancient Egyptian city on the east bank of the Nile in Upper Egypt, on the site of present-day Luxor. It rose to prominence as a royal and religious capital, especially during the Middle and New Kingdoms, and was the center of the cult of the god Amun. Its monuments include the temple complexes of Karnak and Luxor and, on the west bank, the royal tombs and mortuary temples of the Theban necropolis.",
"Kaifeng": "Kaifeng is a city in Henan Province, east-central China, on the southern bank of the Yellow River. One of the Eight Ancient Capitals of China, it is best known as the capital of the Northern Song dynasty, when it became one of the largest and most prosperous cities in the world. It was also home to one of the oldest known Jewish communities in China.",
"Concubinage": "Concubinage is an arrangement in which a person, most often a woman, lives with and has a recognized but subordinate relationship to a partner outside of full marriage. In many historical societies concubines occupied a defined status within the household, ranking below a primary spouse but above servants, and their children might hold particular rights of inheritance. The institution was bound up with property, lineage, and household hierarchy across a range of cultures.",
"Prometheus": "Prometheus is a Titan of ancient Greek mythology known as a benefactor of humanity and a figure of craft and forethought. In the most famous myth he stole fire from the gods and gave it to mortals, defying Zeus. As punishment he was bound to a rock where an eagle fed daily on his regenerating liver, until he was eventually freed.",
"Su_Wu": "Su Wu was a Western Han diplomat sent to the Xiongnu in 100 BCE who was detained when a plot involving his deputy was uncovered. Refusing to renounce his allegiance despite starvation and exile to a remote lake where he herded sheep, he remained in captivity for about nineteen years before returning home around 81 BCE. His steadfast loyalty made him an enduring symbol of fidelity in Chinese tradition.",
"Brahman": "Brahman is, in Hindu philosophy, the unchanging ultimate reality that underlies and pervades the universe. It is described as the absolute, transcendent, and eternal cosmic principle from which all existence arises, and is held to be infinite and beyond ordinary attributes or form. Many schools of Hindu thought hold that the innermost self of a being shares in or is identical with this reality.",
"Anunnaki": "The Anunnaki were a group of deities in the religions of the ancient Sumerians, Akkadians, Assyrians, and Babylonians, often associated with determining human fate. The name is thought to derive from Sumerian and to mean something like princely or royal offspring. They are attested from inscriptions of the Gudea period and the Third Dynasty of Ur onward, and appear in later works such as the Enuma Elish.",
"Tongzhi_Restoration": "The Tongzhi Restoration was a period of attempted revival and reform in the Qing dynasty during the 1860s, named after the reigning Tongzhi Emperor. Following the suppression of the Taiping Rebellion, reform-minded officials sought to stabilize the dynasty through administrative reconstruction, the adoption of Western military technology, and the strengthening of Confucian governance. Although it brought a measure of recovery, its limited modernization left many of the underlying weaknesses of the late Qing state unresolved.",
"Legend_of_the_White_Snake": "The Legend of the White Snake (白蛇傳) is a Chinese folktale, counted among the country's Four Great Folktales, centered on the love between the scholar Xu Xian and Bai Suzhen, a white snake spirit who takes human form. Aided by her companion Xiaoqing, a green snake, Bai Suzhen marries Xu Xian, but the monk Fahai seeks to expose and separate them, eventually imprisoning her beneath Leifeng Pagoda. Drawn from Song and Yuan sources and given full literary form by the Ming writer Feng Menglong, the tale has been retold across opera, fiction, and film.",
"Mjölnir": "Mjölnir is the hammer of the thunder god Thor in Norse mythology, serving both as a weapon against the gods' enemies and as an instrument of blessing. Forged by the dwarven brothers Eitri and Brokkr, it strikes with great force, never misses its mark, and returns to Thor's hand when thrown. It was also used in ritual to hallow brides, funerals, and other ceremonies, and around a thousand hammer-shaped amulets from the Viking Age have been found across northern Europe.",
"Wu_Qi": "Wu Qi (吳起; 440–381 BCE) was a general and statesman of the Warring States period who served in Lu and Wei before becoming chief minister of Chu under King Dao. As Protector of the West River in Wei and later as a reforming minister in Chu, he reorganized state administration and stressed discipline and coordinated command over individual heroism. His military treatise, the Wuzi, is counted among the Seven Military Classics, and he was killed in 381 BCE by enemies created through his reforms.",
"Pound_lock": "A pound lock is a device for raising and lowering boats between stretches of water at different levels, consisting of a watertight chamber with a gate at each end. A vessel enters the chamber, the gates close, and water is admitted or drained to float it to the level of the next reach before the far gate is opened. It lets canals and rivers climb gradients with little waste of water and became standard on inland waterways.",
"Emperor_Shenzong_of_Song": "Emperor Shenzong of Song (宋神宗), personal name Zhao Xu, was the sixth emperor of the Song dynasty, reigning from 1067 to 1085 over the Northern Song from its capital at Kaifeng. He gave his backing to the reformist chancellor Wang Anshi, whose sweeping New Policies reorganized state finances, taxation, and the military in an effort to shore up the government against fiscal strain and the military pressure of the Liao and Western Xia. These reforms divided the court into rival reformist and conservative camps and set off bitter factional strife that long outlasted his reign, and after his death in 1085 he was succeeded by his young son, Emperor Zhezong.",
"Li_Shangyin": "Li Shangyin (李商隱) was a late Tang dynasty poet known for dense, allusive, and often deliberately untitled verses that frequently take love as their theme. His work is regarded as marking a transition from Tang poetry toward the ci lyric form that flourished under the Song. Scholars have long described him as among the most ambiguous of Chinese poets, sparking centuries of debate over the meaning of his poems.",
"Seleucus_I_Nicator": "Seleucus I Nicator was a Macedonian officer of Alexander the Great who founded the Seleucid Empire after the conqueror's death. In the wars among Alexander's successors he secured control of Babylon and expanded eastward across Persia and into the Indian frontier, where he reached an accommodation with the Maurya ruler Chandragupta. He extended his realm westward into Anatolia before being assassinated in 281 BCE.",
"Northern_Wei": "Northern Wei was a dynasty founded by the Tuoba clan of the Xianbei people that ruled northern China from 386 to 535. By the late fifth century it had reunified the north, ending the Sixteen Kingdoms period and inaugurating the northern half of the Northern and Southern dynasties era. It is noted for its patronage of Buddhism, seen in the great cave temples of Yungang and Longmen, and for the sweeping sinicization reforms of Emperor Xiaowen.",
"Israelites": "The Israelites were a confederation of Semitic-speaking tribes in the ancient Near East who, according to the Hebrew Bible, descended from the patriarch Jacob. They are portrayed as worshippers of one God who settled in the land of Canaan and formed kingdoms in the region. Their history and religious traditions form the basis of later Judaism.",
"Chinese_garden": "The Chinese garden is a landscape design tradition that arranges water, rocks, plants, and architecture to evoke an idealized natural scene within an enclosed space. Pavilions, winding galleries, bridges, and framed views guide the visitor through a sequence of carefully composed scenes. Drawing on poetic and philosophical ideas about harmony between people and nature, it served as a setting for retreat, contemplation, and social gathering.",
"Saṃsāra": "Samsara is the cycle of repeated birth, death, and rebirth to which beings are bound in Indian religious thought, including Buddhism. Driven by ignorance and craving, beings wander through this cycle across various realms of existence, experiencing suffering shaped by their past actions. Liberation from samsara is the central aim of the Buddhist path.",
"Yongle_Encyclopedia": "The Yongle Encyclopedia (永樂大典) is a vast Chinese leishu reference work commissioned by the Yongle Emperor of the Ming dynasty and completed in 1408. Compiled by thousands of scholars, it collected and excerpted texts from across Chinese literature and knowledge in some 11,095 volumes. Most of its manuscript was lost over the following centuries, leaving only a small fraction of the original surviving today.",
"Prophecy": "Prophecy is a message or revelation claimed to come from a divine or supernatural source and delivered through a human intermediary called a prophet. Such messages may foretell future events, convey commands or warnings, or interpret the will of a deity. Prophecy holds an important place in many religious traditions and their sacred writings.",
"Ziran": "Ziran (自然) is a key concept in Daoist thought meaning naturalness or self-so, describing the way things arise and unfold spontaneously according to their own inherent nature. It expresses an ideal in which phenomena are not forced or contrived by external intervention but follow their own course, and it is closely linked to the principle of effortless action. The term appears prominently in foundational Daoist texts as a description of how the Dao operates.",
"Giza_pyramid_complex": "The Giza pyramid complex is a group of ancient monuments on the Giza Plateau near Cairo, built during the Fourth Dynasty of the Old Kingdom. It includes the Great Pyramid of Khufu, the pyramids of Khafre and Menkaure, several smaller satellite pyramids, and the Great Sphinx. The site served as a royal necropolis and is the most famous surviving example of monumental ancient Egyptian funerary architecture.",
"Suzhou": "Suzhou is a city in Jiangsu Province, eastern China, lying on the Grand Canal near Lake Tai. Founded in 514 BCE as a capital of the state of Wu, it grew into a major centre of trade, silk production, and culture. The city is celebrated for its classical gardens and network of canals, both recognised as UNESCO World Heritage Sites.",
"Chinese_kinship": "Chinese kinship refers to the system of family relationships and descent that organizes Chinese society, traditionally emphasizing the patrilineal line traced through fathers and sons. It is marked by a detailed vocabulary that distinguishes relatives by generation, age, and side of the family, and by the importance of the surname group and the extended household. The system shaped inheritance, marriage, residence, and ritual obligations such as the veneration of ancestors.",
"Pandora": "Pandora is the first human woman in ancient Greek mythology, fashioned on the instruction of Zeus as a punishment for humanity after Prometheus stole fire. Several deities endowed her with gifts and qualities, and she was sent to the mortal world bearing a large storage jar. When the jar was opened, the ills it contained escaped into the world, leaving only hope within.",
"Discourses_on_Salt_and_Iron": "The Discourses on Salt and Iron (鹽鐵論) is a record of a court debate held in 81 BCE on the economic policies of the Han state, especially the government monopolies on salt and iron established under Emperor Wu. It pits reform-minded Confucian scholars, who sought to abolish the monopolies, against officials who defended state intervention to fund frontier defense. The text was compiled around 60 BCE by the scholar Huan Kuan.",
"Ātman_(Hinduism)": "Atman is, in Hindu philosophy, the true and innermost self or essence of a living being, conceived as eternal and unchanging. It is understood as the spiritual core that persists across successive lifetimes and is held to be separate from the body, mind, and ego. Realizing the nature of Atman is a central aim in many Hindu schools, several of which teach that it is one with the ultimate reality.",
"Sumerian_King_List": "The Sumerian King List is an ancient literary composition written in Sumerian that records rulers of various Mesopotamian city-states and the lengths of their reigns. It was compiled between the Ur III and Old Babylonian periods and presents kingship as passing in sequence from one city to another. It is notable for attributing extraordinarily long reigns, sometimes spanning thousands of years, to its earliest legendary kings.",
"Zeng_Guofan": "Zeng Guofan was a Qing dynasty official, scholar, and military commander best known for organizing the regional Xiang Army that helped defeat the Taiping Rebellion. A devoted Confucian, he rose through the examination system and built a disciplined provincial force when the regular Qing armies proved unable to contain the rebels. He later became a leading promoter of the Self-Strengthening Movement, advocating the selective adoption of Western technology to bolster the dynasty.",
"Moon_rabbit": "The Moon rabbit (玉兔), known in Chinese as the Jade Rabbit or Yutu, is a figure of East Asian folklore said to live on the moon and to pound herbs or the elixir of immortality with a mortar and pestle. In Chinese tradition it is portrayed as a companion of the moon goddess and, in one origin story, a rabbit who selflessly offered itself in a fire to feed a disguised deity and was honored with a place on the moon. The motif recurs across Chinese, Korean, and Japanese culture and is associated with the Mid-Autumn Festival.",
"Norns": "The Norns are female beings in Norse mythology who shape the destiny of gods and humans. They are most often described as three figures named Urðr, Verðandi, and Skuld, who dwell by the well of Urðr at the base of the world tree Yggdrasil. They are said to allot the fates of newborn children and to tend the tree daily by sprinkling it with water and clay from the well so that it does not wither.",
"The_Book_of_Lord_Shang": "The Book of Lord Shang (商君書) is the earliest surviving work of Chinese Legalism, named for and partly attributed to the Qin reformer Shang Yang though compiled by him and his followers over more than a century. Its chapters argue for maintaining order through impartial laws backed by strict rewards and punishments, the promotion of agriculture and military strength, and the rejection of reliance on ancient precedent. It is an explicitly anti-Confucian text that ties social rank and wealth to the state's interest in productivity and warfare.",
"Acupuncture": "Acupuncture is a practice in which fine needles are inserted at specific points on the body, originating within traditional Chinese medicine. Practitioners describe it in terms of regulating the flow of qi along channels called meridians to address pain and a range of conditions. It has been transmitted through classical medical texts and remains widely practised, while its mechanisms and efficacy are the subject of ongoing scientific study.",
"New_Policies_(Song_dynasty)": "The New Policies (新法; xinfa) were a program of state reforms enacted by chancellor Wang Anshi under Emperor Shenzong of the Northern Song between 1069 and 1076. They included government loans to farmers, replacement of labor service with hired labor funded by taxes, and the baojia village militia system, aiming to raise revenue, strengthen the military, and ease the burden on peasants. The measures sharply divided the court into reformist and conservative factions for decades.",
"Du_Mu": "Du Mu (杜牧) was a poet of the late Tang dynasty admired for his lyrical and romantic quatrains exploring separation, impermanence, and historical reflection. He is often paired with Li Shangyin as the Little Li-Du, echoing the earlier pairing of Li Bai and Du Fu. His polished verse blends classical imagery with striking turns of phrase and remains widely anthologized.",
"Chandragupta_Maurya": "Chandragupta Maurya was the founder of the Maurya Empire in ancient India. With the guidance of his adviser Chanakya he overthrew the Nanda dynasty and built a state that came to encompass much of the Indian subcontinent. He concluded a treaty with the Seleucid ruler Seleucus I and, according to tradition, later abdicated to follow an ascetic life.",
"Emperor_Xiaowen_of_Northern_Wei": "Emperor Xiaowen of Northern Wei, born Tuoba Hong and later renamed Yuan Hong, was a ruler of the Xianbei-led Northern Wei dynasty known for his far-reaching program of cultural and administrative reform. He moved the capital from Pingcheng to Luoyang in 494 and ordered his people to adopt Han Chinese surnames, language, and dress, while implementing the equal-field land system. His sinicization policies reshaped northern society but also generated tensions that troubled the dynasty after his death.",
"Pentateuch": "The Pentateuch is a term for the first five books of the Bible: Genesis, Exodus, Leviticus, Numbers, and Deuteronomy. These books recount the creation of the world, the early ancestors of the Israelites, their deliverance from Egypt, and the giving of the law. They hold foundational authority in both Jewish and Christian scripture.",
"Qipao": "The qipao (旗袍), also called the cheongsam, is a fitted Chinese dress for women featuring a standing collar, an asymmetric front closure, and side slits. It draws on the clothing of the Manchu people and was reshaped into its close-fitting modern form in the early 20th century. It became especially fashionable in Shanghai during the 1920s and 1930s and was later adopted as a form of formal and emblematic dress.",
"Four_Noble_Truths": "The Four Noble Truths are a foundational formulation of the Buddha's teaching concerning suffering and the way to its cessation. They hold that life is marked by suffering, that suffering arises from craving, that suffering can cease, and that there is a path leading to its cessation. This path is identified with the Noble Eightfold Path, and the truths frame much of Buddhist doctrine and practice.",
"Fu_(poetry)": "Fu (賦), often translated as rhapsody or rhyme-prose, is a major form of Chinese literature that mixes passages of verse and prose. A fu describes its subject in exhaustive detail from many angles, favoring elaborate cataloging, parallelism, and rare vocabulary, and was recited or chanted rather than sung. The form flourished from the Han dynasty onward and was a prestigious genre of court and scholarly writing.",
"Soul": "The soul is, in many religious and philosophical traditions, the immaterial essence of a living being thought to give it life, consciousness, or identity. Beliefs vary widely over whether the soul is immortal, how it relates to the body, and what becomes of it after death. Debate over its existence and nature has been a longstanding theme in philosophy of mind and metaphysics.",
"Pu_(Taoism)": "Pu (樸) is a Daoist concept usually translated as the uncarved block or unworked wood, used as a metaphor for an original state of simplicity and natural wholeness. It represents a condition prior to deliberate shaping or social conditioning, valued as a model of how a person or thing can remain close to its inborn nature. The image recurs in early Daoist texts as an emblem of spontaneity and freedom from artifice.",
"Karnak": "Karnak is a vast complex of temples, chapels, and other structures near Luxor in Egypt, developed over many centuries of ancient Egyptian history. Its central precinct was dedicated to the god Amun and was expanded by successive pharaohs, making it one of the largest religious buildings ever constructed. The complex is noted for its great hypostyle hall filled with massive columns.",
"Chengdu": "Chengdu is a city in southwestern China and the capital of Sichuan Province, situated on the Chengdu Plain within the fertile Sichuan Basin. Founded by the Kingdom of Shu in the 4th century BCE, it later served as the capital of Shu Han during the Three Kingdoms period and has retained its name throughout its history. Nearby lies the ancient Dujiangyan irrigation system, a UNESCO World Heritage Site.",
"Cash_(Chinese_coin)": "The cash was a type of coin used in China for over two millennia, typically a small round disc of bronze or copper with a square central hole. The hole allowed coins to be strung together in large numbers for counting and transport, and strings of cash served as a basic medium of everyday currency. Cast rather than struck, these coins circulated from antiquity until the early twentieth century, when machine-struck coinage replaced them.",
"Heracles": "Heracles is a divine hero of ancient Greek mythology, celebrated for his extraordinary strength and numerous adventures. He is the son of Zeus and the mortal woman Alcmene and faced the persistent hostility of Hera. He is best known for the Twelve Labours, a series of seemingly impossible tasks he completed as penance, and was later worshipped as a god.",
"Li_Guang": "Li Guang was a Western Han general renowned for his archery and for decades of frontier service against the Xiongnu, who nicknamed him the Flying General. Despite his fame and skill in defending the border, he never attained the marquessate he sought. After becoming lost in the desert during the 119 BCE Battle of Mobei, he took his own life rather than face a court inquiry.",
"Moksha": "Moksha is the concept of liberation or release from the cycle of death and rebirth in the Indian religions. In Hinduism it is regarded as one of the principal aims of human life and represents freedom achieved through knowledge, devotion, or disciplined practice depending on the tradition. Its attainment is understood as a state of enduring freedom from suffering and bondage.",
"Adapa": "Adapa was a sage in Mesopotamian mythology connected with the city of Eridu and the temple of the god Ea. In the central myth he is granted great wisdom by Ea but, following his patron's advice, declines the food and drink of life when brought before the god Anu, thereby forfeiting immortality. He was later remembered as an archetype of the wise ruler and identified by some with Uanna, first of the seven apkallu sages.",
"Li_Hongzhang": "Li Hongzhang was a leading Qing dynasty statesman, general, and diplomat who played a central role in the late nineteenth-century affairs of China. He helped suppress the Taiping and Nian rebellions, built the modern Beiyang Fleet, and was a principal figure in the Self-Strengthening Movement's efforts at industrial and military modernization. He also represented the Qing court in numerous foreign negotiations, including the treaties following the First Sino-Japanese War and the Boxer Rebellion.",
"Sanxing_(deities)": "The Sanxing (三星) are three star gods of Chinese folk religion personifying Fortune, Prosperity, and Longevity, known respectively as Fu, Lu, and Shou. Each is linked to a celestial body, with Fu presiding over Jupiter, Lu over the star Mizar, and Shou over Canopus, and the three are commonly shown together as auspicious figures. Their statues appear in temples, ancestral shrines, homes, and shops, especially during the Chinese New Year, where they express wishes for blessing, status, and long life.",
"Niflheim": "Niflheim is a primordial realm of mist, ice, and cold in Norse cosmology, its name meaning home of mist. In the creation account of the Prose Edda its frozen rivers and the well Hvergelmir, the source of all rivers, meet the heat streaming from the fire realm to begin the formation of the world and the being Ymir. It is also linked to the underworld where those who die of sickness or old age are said to go.",
"The_Methods_of_the_Sima": "The Methods of the Sima (司馬法) is an early Chinese military text developed in the state of Qi in the 4th century BCE and traditionally attributed to the general Sima Rangju. According to Sima Qian, it was assembled at the order of King Wei of Qi from the most famous military writings then current in the state. One of the Seven Military Classics, it emphasizes law, organization, discipline, and the moral justification of war over detailed battlefield tactics, and survives in only five of its many original chapters.",
"Moxibustion": "Moxibustion is a therapy in traditional Chinese medicine that burns dried mugwort, called moxa, on or near the skin to warm specific points of the body. It may be applied directly to the skin or held a short distance above it, often over the same points used in needling therapies. The practice is described in classical Chinese medical literature and is used to influence what the tradition regards as the flow of vital energy.",
"Chanyuan_Treaty": "The Chanyuan Treaty (澶淵之盟) was a 1005 peace agreement between the Northern Song dynasty and the Khitan-led Liao dynasty. It established a fraternal relationship between the two courts and committed the Song to an annual payment to the Liao of 200,000 bolts of silk and 100,000 taels of silver. The settlement secured roughly a century of relative peace along the northern frontier.",
"Wang_Bo_(poet)": "Wang Bo (王勃) was an early Tang dynasty poet traditionally grouped with Luo Binwang, Lu Zhaolin, and Yang Jiong as the Four Paragons of the Early Tang. He rejected the ornamental court style inherited from earlier centuries in favor of poetry that more directly expresses the writer's mind. His parallel-prose preface to the Pavilion of the Prince of Teng remains a celebrated work studied in Chinese schools.",
"Timur": "Timur, also known as Tamerlane, was a Turco-Mongol conqueror who founded the Timurid Empire in Central Asia. From his capital at Samarkand he led campaigns that ravaged territories across Persia, the Caucasus, India, and Anatolia, defeating powers such as the Ottoman Sultanate and the Delhi Sultanate. He died in 1405 while preparing a campaign toward the east, and his descendants ruled a realm noted for its cultural achievements.",
"Liu_Yu_(emperor)": "Liu Yu was a general of the Eastern Jin dynasty who rose from humble origins to become its dominant military figure before founding the Liu Song dynasty in 420. He led successful campaigns that destroyed several northern states and temporarily recovered the old capitals of Luoyang and Chang'an. By accepting the abdication of the last Jin emperor he ended the Jin dynasty and inaugurated the Southern dynasties.",
"Original_sin": "Original sin is a Christian doctrine holding that all humans inherit a fallen and sinful nature as a consequence of the first humans' disobedience to God. It traces this condition to the act of Adam and Eve eating the forbidden fruit in the Garden of Eden. The teaching has been understood in varying ways across Christian traditions and is connected to beliefs about baptism and salvation.",
"Dragon_robe": "The dragon robe (龍袍) is a Chinese imperial garment decorated with embroidered dragons as its principal motif. The dragon symbolized the authority of the wearer, and the right to wear robes bearing such patterns was restricted by sumptuary rules. By the Qing dynasty the typical imperial example carried nine five-clawed dragons arranged across the robe.",
"Noble_Eightfold_Path": "The Noble Eightfold Path is the course of practice taught in Buddhism as the way leading to the cessation of suffering and the attainment of liberation. Its eight factors are commonly grouped into the cultivation of ethical conduct, mental discipline, and wisdom, encompassing right view, intention, speech, action, livelihood, effort, mindfulness, and concentration. It is presented as the practical realization of the fourth of the Four Noble Truths.",
"Ci_(poetry)": "Ci (詞) is a form of Classical Chinese lyric poetry written to fit fixed tonal and rhythmic patterns called cipai, which derive from melodies and produce lines of uneven length. The form drew on folk and musical traditions and emerged in the late Tang dynasty before reaching its height during the Song dynasty. It became one of the most celebrated genres of Chinese verse and is still composed today.",
"Destiny": "Destiny is the idea that events are fixed in advance and bound to unfold in a particular way, regardless of individual choice. It is often associated with a predetermined course for a person's life or for the world as a whole. The concept appears across mythology, religion, and philosophy, where it is variously linked to divine will, cosmic order, or impersonal necessity.",
"Three_Treasures_(Taoism)": "The Three Treasures (三寶) are foundational virtues set out in chapter sixty-seven of the Daodejing, commonly identified as compassion, frugality, and humility. They are presented as qualities by which a person may live in accordance with the Dao and govern wisely, with the text praising restraint and refusal to put oneself ahead of others. In later usage the same term also came to denote the three internal energies of essence, breath, and spirit cultivated in Daoist practice.",
"Sarcophagus": "A sarcophagus is a container for a corpse, usually carved from stone and intended to be displayed above ground. In ancient Egypt sarcophagi were often elaborately decorated with inscriptions and protective imagery and housed the inner coffins of high-status individuals. The word derives from a Greek term referring to a kind of stone once thought to consume the flesh of the dead.",
"Dunhuang": "Dunhuang is a city in northwestern Gansu Province, China, that stood at the junction of the main Silk Road routes during the Sui and Tang dynasties. It is famous for the nearby Mogao Caves, a complex of hundreds of Buddhist grottoes renowned for their murals, sculptures, and a celebrated cache of medieval manuscripts. The site was an important centre of trade and cultural exchange between China and the wider world.",
"Tael": "The tael was a unit of weight used across East and Southeast Asia, and by extension a monetary unit when applied to silver. In China it served as a standard measure for weighing silver bullion used in large transactions, taxation, and trade, though its exact weight varied by region and period. Silver reckoned in taels became central to Chinese commerce and government finance in the later imperial centuries.",
"Persephone": "Persephone is an ancient Greek goddess who serves as queen of the underworld and is associated with spring growth and vegetation. She is the daughter of Zeus and Demeter and was abducted by Hades to become his consort. Her annual return to and departure from the upper world was used to explain the changing of the seasons.",
"Wang_Chong": "Wang Chong was an Eastern Han philosopher known for his rationalist and skeptical outlook, which rejected superstition and supernatural explanations of natural events. In his principal work, the Lunheng (論衡), he argued that phenomena such as thunder and eclipses had physical rather than divine causes and demanded evidence-based reasoning. His ideas gained wider influence after his death as the prevailing classical orthodoxy waned.",
"Karma": "Karma is the principle, found across the Indian religions, that a person's intentions and actions shape their future. Good actions are held to produce favorable results while harmful actions produce unfavorable ones, with effects unfolding within this life and in lives to come. The doctrine is closely linked to the cycle of rebirth, in which accumulated karma influences future circumstances.",
"Hanging_Gardens_of_Babylon": "The Hanging Gardens of Babylon were one of the Seven Wonders of the Ancient World, described as an ascending series of tiered gardens planted with trees and shrubs. Tradition credits their construction to King Nebuchadnezzar II for his wife Amytis, though the gardens are the only one of the Seven Wonders whose location has not been firmly established. No Babylonian texts mention them and no definitive archaeological evidence has been found at Babylon, leading some scholars to question their existence or to propose a site at Nineveh.",
"First_Sino-Japanese_War": "The First Sino-Japanese War was a conflict fought between Qing China and the Empire of Japan from 1894 to 1895, primarily over influence in Korea. Japanese forces won a series of decisive victories on land and at sea, destroying the Qing Beiyang Fleet and exposing the limits of China's modernization efforts. The war ended with the Treaty of Shimonoseki, under which China recognized Korean independence and ceded Taiwan and other territory to Japan.",
"Muspelheim": "Muspelheim is a primordial realm of fire and heat in Norse cosmology, home to the fire jötnar and guarded by the giant Surtr with his flaming sword. In the creation account its sparks meet the ice of the mist realm, producing the Sun, Moon, and stars, while the melting of the ice forms the being Ymir. At Ragnarök the sons of Muspel ride out to take part in the destruction of the world, led by Surtr.",
"Philosopher's_stone": "The philosopher's stone is a legendary substance sought in alchemy, believed to be able to transmute base metals such as lead into gold or silver. It was also thought to yield an elixir of life granting rejuvenation, healing, and even immortality, and it stood as the central symbol of alchemical perfection. Producing it was regarded as the ultimate goal of alchemical work, sometimes called the magnum opus or Great Work.",
"Unicorn": "A unicorn is a legendary creature described since antiquity as resembling a horse or goat with a single large, pointed, often spiraling horn projecting from its forehead. In European tradition it was associated with purity, grace, and untamable wildness, and its horn was reputed to have healing powers and the ability to detect poison. Similar single-horned beasts appear in the myths and art of many cultures.",
"Chimera_(mythology)": "In Greek mythology the Chimera was a monstrous fire-breathing hybrid, usually depicted as a lion in front, a goat in the middle, and a serpent as its tail. Said to be the offspring of Typhon and Echidna, it was slain by the hero Bellerophon riding the winged horse Pegasus. From this creature comes the adjective chimerical, meaning fantastical, illusory, or made of wildly incompatible parts.",
"Deer": "Deer are hoofed ruminant mammals forming the family Cervidae, which includes species such as elk, moose, reindeer, and roe deer. Most male deer, and reindeer of both sexes, grow and annually shed branched bony antlers, a feature unique to the family. They are widely distributed across most continents and typically inhabit forests, grasslands, and mountains, feeding on vegetation such as leaves, grasses, and shoots.",
"Ox": "An ox is a large bovine trained and kept as a draft animal, most often a castrated adult male whose docility makes it easier and safer to work with. Oxen are used to pull plows and carts, haul loads, thresh grain, and power mills, providing steady strength for heavy labor. They pull heavier loads for longer periods than horses but move more slowly.",
"Horse": "The horse is a domesticated, single-toed hoofed mammal of the species Equus ferus caballus, belonging to the family Equidae. Domesticated from wild ancestors several thousand years ago, it has been bred in a wide range of sizes and types for riding, pulling loads, farm work, and transport. Horses are grazing herbivores noted for their speed, strength, and social herd behavior.",
"Goat": "The goat is a domesticated hoofed mammal of the species Capra hircus, a ruminant kept as livestock in many parts of the world. Goats are raised for their milk, meat, hair, and skins, and are valued for thriving on rough forage and varied terrain. Both sexes may bear horns and a beard, and the animals are agile climbers known for their curiosity and hardiness.",
"Dog": "The dog is a domesticated mammal of the species Canis familiaris, descended from the wolf and widely regarded as the first animal domesticated by humans. Through selective breeding it exists in hundreds of breeds varying greatly in size, shape, and temperament. Dogs have long been kept for companionship as well as for tasks such as herding, hunting, guarding, and assistance work.",
"Cosmos": "The cosmos is the universe regarded as an ordered and harmonious whole rather than as mere matter or empty space. The word derives from a Greek term for order and arrangement, and it emphasizes the systematic structure underlying existence. The cosmos is the central subject of cosmology, the scientific, philosophical, and religious study of the universe's nature, origin, and order.",
"Pacific_Ocean": "The Pacific Ocean is the largest and deepest of Earth's oceanic divisions, covering roughly a third of the planet's surface. It stretches from the Arctic in the north to the Southern Ocean in the south, bordered by Asia and Australia to the west and the Americas to the east. It contains the Challenger Deep in the Mariana Trench, the deepest known point in any ocean.",
"South_China_Sea": "The South China Sea is a marginal sea of the western Pacific Ocean covering about 3.5 million square kilometers. It is bounded by southern China to the north, the Indochinese Peninsula to the west, Taiwan and the Philippines to the east, and Borneo and Sumatra to the south. It connects to neighboring waters including the East China Sea, the Philippine Sea, the Sulu Sea, and the Gulf of Thailand.",
"ASEAN": "The Association of Southeast Asian Nations, or ASEAN, is an intergovernmental regional organization of states in Southeast Asia. It was founded on 8 August 1967 by Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, and Thailand, and later expanded to include additional Southeast Asian members. It aims to promote economic, social, and cultural development and to foster regional peace and stability through consensus-based cooperation.",
"Strait_of_Gibraltar": "The Strait of Gibraltar is a narrow strait connecting the Atlantic Ocean to the Mediterranean Sea. It separates the continents of Europe and Africa, with Spain and Gibraltar on the northern shore and Morocco and Ceuta on the southern shore. At its narrowest the two coasts lie only about 14 kilometers apart.",
"Atlantic_Ocean": "The Atlantic Ocean is the second largest of Earth's oceanic divisions, covering roughly a fifth of the planet's surface. It lies between the Americas to the west and Europe and Africa to the east, extending from the Arctic in the north to the Southern Ocean in the south. Its central Mid-Atlantic Ridge marks the boundary where tectonic plates spread apart.",
"Indus_Valley_Civilisation": "The Indus Valley Civilisation, also called the Harappan Civilisation, was a Bronze Age civilization of the northwestern regions of South Asia, flourishing chiefly between about 2600 and 1900 BCE. Centered on the Indus River and neighboring river systems, it built well-planned cities such as Mohenjo-daro and Harappa with grid layouts, brick architecture, and early urban sanitation systems. It used a standardized system of weights and an undeciphered script, and it declined and dispersed in the early second millennium BCE.",
"Iranian_Plateau": "The Iranian Plateau is a large geological and geographic region of highland terrain in western and central Asia, forming part of the Eurasian tectonic plate. It stretches roughly from the Caspian Sea in the northwest to the Sulaiman Mountains in the southeast, covering most of Iran and Afghanistan and extending into neighboring lands. Despite its name it is mountainous rather than flat, bounded by ranges such as the Zagros and enclosing deserts and basins.",
"Indo-Iranian_languages": "The Indo-Iranian languages are the largest branch of the Indo-European language family, spoken by well over a billion people. They divide into three groups: the Indo-Aryan, the Iranian, and the small Nuristani branch, all descended from a reconstructed Proto-Indo-Iranian ancestor. They are spoken mainly across South, West, and Central Asia, from the Iranian plateau to South Asia, with communities reaching into Europe and beyond.",
"Italic_languages": "The Italic languages are a branch of the Indo-European language family whose earliest known members were spoken on the Italian Peninsula in the first millennium BCE. Ancient members included Latin, Faliscan, Oscan, and Umbrian, of which Latin came to dominate as the language of Rome and spread widely. Its later forms diversified into the Romance languages, such as Spanish, French, Italian, Portuguese, and Romanian, the only Italic languages still natively spoken.",
"Balto-Slavic": "Balto-Slavic is a branch of the Indo-European language family that traditionally comprises the Baltic and Slavic languages. Its members are spoken across northern, eastern, central, and southeastern Europe and into northern Asia, with several hundred million speakers. The two groups share numerous linguistic features found in no other Indo-European branch, taken as evidence of a common Proto-Balto-Slavic ancestor.",
"Celtic": "Celtic is a branch of the Indo-European language family descended from a reconstructed Proto-Celtic language. It is divided into the extinct Continental Celtic languages and the surviving Insular Celtic languages, the latter splitting into Goidelic and Brythonic groups. Six Celtic languages are known in modern times, including Irish, Scottish Gaelic, Welsh, and Breton.",
"Latin": "Latin is an Italic language of the Indo-European family, originally spoken by the Latins of Latium in the lower Tiber region around Rome. It became the dominant language of the Roman state and later evolved into the Romance languages such as Spanish, French, Italian, Portuguese, and Romanian. It is written in the Latin alphabet and remains in use for liturgical, scholarly, scientific, and legal purposes.",
"Greek (language)": "Greek is an independent Hellenic branch of the Indo-European language family, spoken mainly in Greece and Cyprus and by diaspora communities elsewhere. It has the longest documented history of any Indo-European language, with written records spanning at least 3,400 years. Modern Greek is written in the Greek alphabet, which developed from earlier scripts including Linear B.",
"English (language)": "English is a West Germanic language of the Indo-European family that emerged in early medieval England from the dialects of Anglo-Saxon settlers. It spread worldwide through British colonial expansion and later American influence, becoming a leading language of diplomacy, science, and commerce. With roughly 1.5 billion native and non-native speakers, it functions as a global lingua franca and an official language in many countries.",
"Proto-Indo-European": "Proto-Indo-European is the reconstructed common ancestor of the Indo-European language family, rebuilt by linguists through the comparative method rather than attested in any surviving records. It is thought to have been spoken during the late Neolithic to early Bronze Age, with the Kurgan hypothesis placing its speakers on the Pontic-Caspian steppe. The reconstructed language featured complex inflection, multiple grammatical cases, and vowel alternation known as ablaut.",
"Wu (language)": "Wu is a group of Sinitic languages spoken mainly in Shanghai, Zhejiang, and southern Jiangsu, largely south of the Yangtze River. Its varieties include Shanghainese and Suzhounese and are often mutually unintelligible with one another and with other Chinese branches. Wu characteristically preserves the voiced initial consonants of medieval Chinese and a checked tone realized as a glottal stop.",
"Min": "Min is a diverse group of Sinitic languages spoken mainly in Fujian and spread to Taiwan, Hainan, other coastal areas of southern China, and Southeast Asia. Its varieties are generally not mutually intelligible with one another or with other Chinese branches and preserve features of Old Chinese lost elsewhere. Major divisions include coastal branches such as Southern Min, which contains the widely spoken Hokkien and Teochew, and inland branches such as Northern Min.",
"Hakka": "Hakka is a group of Sinitic language varieties spoken natively by the Hakka people of southern China. It is found in eastern Guangdong, western Fujian, southern Jiangxi, and western Hunan, as well as in Taiwan, Hong Kong, and overseas communities in Southeast Asia. It is not mutually intelligible with Mandarin or Cantonese and is recognized as a national language in Taiwan.",
"Xiang": "Xiang is a group of historically related Sinitic languages spoken mainly in Hunan province and neighboring areas. It is commonly divided into New Xiang, which has lost the voiced consonants of Middle Chinese, and Old Xiang, which retains them, along with several smaller subgroups. Xiang has been heavily influenced by the Mandarin dialects bordering its territory.",
"Gan": "Gan is a group of Sinitic languages spoken natively in Jiangxi province and surrounding regions of China. Additional speakers are found in parts of Hunan, Hubei, Anhui, and Fujian, and the Nanchang dialect serves as its prestige variety. Gan preserves a number of archaic expressions from classical Chinese that have disappeared from Mandarin.",
"Hong Kong": "Hong Kong is a special administrative region of China on the country's southeastern coast, comprising a peninsula and numerous islands. It was a British colony from the mid-nineteenth century until its handover to China in 1997, after which it retained separate economic and legal systems under the one country, two systems principle. It is one of the world's most densely populated territories and a leading global financial center.",
"Macau": "Macau is a special administrative region of China on the country's southern coast, situated about sixty kilometers west of Hong Kong. It was under Portuguese administration for over four centuries until its handover to China in 1999, after which it retained separate systems under the one country, two systems principle. It is renowned for its gambling and gaming industry, which is the largest in the world by revenue.",
"Himalayas": "The Himalayas are a mountain range in Asia that separates the plains of the Indian subcontinent from the Tibetan Plateau. The range spans Nepal, India, China, Bhutan, and Pakistan and includes more than a hundred peaks exceeding 7,200 meters, among them Mount Everest, the highest point on Earth. It formed from the collision of the Indian and Eurasian tectonic plates and continues to rise today.",
"Newar (language)": "Newar, also called Nepal Bhasa, is a Sino-Tibetan language of the Tibeto-Burman group spoken chiefly by the Newar people of Nepal's Kathmandu Valley. It served as the official language during the medieval Malla dynasty and has a literary tradition several centuries old. It was later suppressed under the Rana regime and is today classified as an endangered language despite modern revitalization efforts.",
"Meitei (language)": "Meitei, also called Manipuri, is a Tibeto-Burman language and the official language and lingua franca of the state of Manipur in northeastern India. It is written in its own script, the Meitei Mayek, and has historically also been recorded in the Bengali script. Recognized as a scheduled language of India, it is the most widely spoken Tibeto-Burman language in the country.",
"Demigod": "A demigod is a being that is partly divine and partly mortal, most often described as the offspring of a deity and a human. The term can also refer to a minor deity or to a mortal hero who is granted divine status, sometimes after death. The concept appears in many polytheistic mythologies and religions, where such figures may possess extraordinary powers or receive worship.",
"Tutelary_deity": "A tutelary deity is a god or spirit regarded as the guardian, patron, or protector of a particular place, feature, person, lineage, nation, culture, or occupation. Such figures are believed to watch over and safeguard those under their care and are invoked for protection and favor. The idea of a divine patron appears across many world religions and cultures, from ancient polytheistic traditions to later ones.",
"Patronage": "Patronage is the support, encouragement, protection, or financial aid that a patron, whether a person or an institution, extends to another party. Historically, wealthy rulers, nobles, and religious figures acted as patrons of artists, scholars, and causes, and the term derives from the Latin patronus, one who benefits clients. The practice spans the arts, politics, scholarship, and charity, and continues today through grants and philanthropic foundations.",
"Meridian_(astronomy)": "In astronomy, the meridian is the great circle on the celestial sphere that passes through the two celestial poles and through the zenith and nadir of an observer's location. It is perpendicular to both the celestial equator and the horizon and contains the north and south points of the horizon. A celestial object reaches its highest point in the sky, called culmination, at the moment it crosses the observer's meridian as the Earth rotates.",
"Ecliptic": "The ecliptic is the apparent path that the Sun traces across the celestial sphere over the course of a year, as seen from a planet orbiting it. It corresponds to the plane of that planet's orbit, known as the ecliptic plane, and serves as a fundamental reference plane for measuring the positions of celestial bodies. Its name derives from the fact that eclipses can occur only when the Moon crosses this path.",
"Leto": "Leto is a goddess in ancient Greek mythology, best known as the mother of the twin deities Apollo and Artemis, whom she bore to Zeus. She is the daughter of the Titans Coeus and Phoebe, and her sister Asteria was associated with the island of Delos, where Leto gave birth. She is connected in myth with motherhood and the protection of the young.",
"Astronomical_object": "An astronomical or celestial object is a naturally occurring physical entity, association, or structure that exists within the observable universe. A tightly bound, single, contiguous body such as a planet, moon, asteroid, or star is often termed a celestial body, while more loosely bound structures such as star clusters, nebulae, and galaxies are termed celestial objects. Astronomy is the study of these objects and the phenomena that arise from them.",
"Iðavöllr": "Iðavöllr is a location in Norse mythology, described as a plain that serves as a gathering place for the gods. It appears in the poem Völuspá of the Poetic Edda, where the gods assemble there early in time to raise temples and forges. It is mentioned again near the poem's end, after Ragnarök, when the surviving gods reconvene there to rebuild.",
"Hliðskjálf": "Hlidskjalf is the high seat of the god Odin in Norse mythology, from which he can see into and across all the worlds. It is located within his dwelling, and from it Odin observes the deeds of gods and mortals alike. In the Eddas the seat features in episodes where Odin and Frigg watch their foster sons, and where the god Freyr looks out and first sees the giantess Gerðr.",
"Bifröst": "Bifröst is a burning bridge in Norse mythology that connects Midgard, the world of humans, with Asgard, the realm of the gods. It is guarded by the god Heimdallr and is described in the sources as a bridge of three colours. According to prophecy it breaks during Ragnarök as the fiery forces of Muspell ride across it.",
"Ashur_(god)": "Ashur was the national god of the Assyrians in the religion of ancient Mesopotamia, closely identified with the city of Assur and with the Assyrian state itself. Unlike many other Mesopotamian deities he had little independent mythology, functioning chiefly as an embodiment of Assyrian political and military power. The king was regarded as his earthly representative, and royal conquests were attributed to his will until the Assyrians gradually converted to Christianity.",
"Nimrud": "Nimrud is an ancient Assyrian city in what is now northern Iraq, situated on the Tigris in the Nineveh Plains south of Mosul. Known in antiquity as Kalhu and in the Bible as Calah, it was made a royal capital by Ashurnasirpal II around 879 BCE and grew into one of the largest cities of its age. Extensively excavated for its palace reliefs, lamassu sculptures, and ivories, much of the exposed site was destroyed in 2015 before later reconstruction efforts began.",
"Assyrians": "The Assyrians are an ethnic group indigenous to Mesopotamia, with cultural and historical roots in ancient Assyria and the wider ancient Near East. They speak dialects of Neo-Aramaic, a Semitic language that spread across the region in antiquity, and most adhere to branches of Syriac Christianity. Today they live in their historical homeland spanning parts of Iraq, Syria, Turkey, and Iran, as well as in a widespread diaspora, and some members identify as Chaldeans or Arameans.",
"Ban_Biao": "Ban Biao was a Chinese historian and official of the Han dynasty who began the compilation of the Book of Han, a history of the Western Han. His work was left unfinished at his death and was continued by his son Ban Gu and later his daughter Ban Zhao. He also wrote the essay Treatise on the Mandate of Kings, which was preserved in the literary anthology Wen Xuan.",
"Dou_Xian": "Dou Xian was a military commander and consort kin of the Eastern Han dynasty whose family gained great influence at court after his sister became empress. He is best known for leading a decisive campaign against the Northern Xiongnu in 89 CE, a victory commemorated by the Inscription of Yanran that helped break Xiongnu power. His concentration of power ended in 92 CE when the emperor moved against him and he was forced to take his own life.",
"Deng_Sui": "Deng Sui, also known as Empress Hexi, was an empress and later regent of the Eastern Han dynasty in China. After the death of her husband, Emperor He, she governed the empire as regent for two successive child emperors from 106 until her death in 121. She is remembered as a capable ruler who cut court expenses, organized relief during floods and droughts, and patronized scholarship.",
"Lessons_for_Women": "Lessons for Women (女誡) is a didactic text on the conduct of women written by the Han dynasty scholar Ban Zhao. Composed in seven short chapters, it sets out expectations of humility, devotion, and obedience within the family and describes four womanly virtues of proper virtue, speech, manner, and merit. Originally intended for the author's daughters, it later circulated widely and became one of the influential Four Books for Women.",
"South_Asia": "South Asia is the southern subregion of Asia, occupying the Indian subcontinent and the territories bounded by the Himalayas to the north and the Indian Ocean to the south. It is home to roughly a quarter of the world's population, making it one of the most densely populated regions on Earth. Its core countries are Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan, and Sri Lanka, with Afghanistan sometimes included.",
"Bay_of_Bengal": "The Bay of Bengal is the northeastern arm of the Indian Ocean, lying between the Indian subcontinent and the Indochinese peninsula. Covering about 2.6 million square kilometres, it is bordered by India, Bangladesh, Myanmar, Thailand, Sri Lanka, and Indonesia, and receives the waters of major rivers including the Ganges and Brahmaputra. Its southern limit runs between Sri Lanka and Sumatra, and its eastern edge is marked by the Andaman and Nicobar Islands.",
"Dhaka": "Dhaka is the capital and largest city of Bangladesh, situated on the Ganges Delta and bounded by several rivers including the Buriganga. Founded as a Mughal provincial city in 1608 and once renowned for its muslin trade, it became the national capital following Bangladesh's independence. It is among the most populous and densely populated urban areas in the world and serves as the country's political and economic centre.",
"Ganges": "The Ganges is a major trans-boundary river of South Asia, flowing about 2,525 kilometres from the western Himalayas across the northern plains before emptying into the Bay of Bengal. It rises in the Indian state of Uttarakhand at the confluence of the Alaknanda and Bhagirathi and passes through India and Bangladesh, where its main branch is called the Padma. Its basin is one of the most densely populated in the world, and the river holds deep religious significance for Hindus, who venerate it as the goddess Ganga.",
"Brahmaputra_River": "The Brahmaputra is a major trans-boundary river of Asia that rises near Mount Kailash in the Himalayas, where it is known as the Yarlung Tsangpo, and flows through Tibet, India, and Bangladesh. Roughly 2,900 to 3,100 kilometres long, it carries heavy sediment loads and is prone to severe seasonal flooding, frequently shifting its course. It joins the Ganges and Meghna rivers before draining into the Bay of Bengal through a vast shared delta.",
"Imperial_China": "Imperial China refers to the roughly two-millennia era in which China was governed as a centralized empire under a succession of ruling dynasties headed by an emperor. It is conventionally dated from the unification under the Qin dynasty in 221 BCE to the fall of the Qing dynasty in 1912. Throughout the period, the ideology of the Mandate of Heaven legitimized dynastic rule, and a bureaucratic state administered the realm through officials.",
"Militia": "A militia is a military or paramilitary force made up of civilian members rather than professional, full-time soldiers. Militias are typically raised for local defence or to reinforce regular armies in times of need, and members usually serve part-time or on call. Their roles have ranged from community protection and irregular warfare to formally organized reserve forces integrated with state armies.",
"Bridgetown": "Bridgetown is the capital and largest city of Barbados, located on the southwestern coast within the parish of Saint Michael along Carlisle Bay. Established by English settlers in 1628, it takes its name from a bridge built over an inlet known as the Careenage. It serves as the island's principal financial centre, port, and commercial hub, and its historic core with its garrison is a UNESCO World Heritage Site.",
"Sugar": "Sugar is a class of sweet-tasting, soluble carbohydrates composed of carbon, hydrogen, and oxygen, ranging from simple monosaccharides such as glucose and fructose to disaccharides such as sucrose. Table sugar is sucrose, extracted commercially chiefly from sugarcane grown in tropical regions and from sugar beet grown in temperate climates. It is widely used as a sweetener and preservative in food and is metabolized by the body as a source of energy.",
"Bubastis": "Bubastis was an ancient city in the Nile Delta of Lower Egypt, near the modern town of Zagazig, known in Egyptian as Per-Bast. It was the principal cult centre of the feline goddess Bastet and drew large crowds of pilgrims to her annual festival. The city reached the height of its prominence during the Twenty-Second Dynasty, when it served as a royal residence, before declining in later periods.",
"Nile_Delta": "The Nile Delta is the fan-shaped lowland in Lower Egypt where the Nile River spreads out and drains into the Mediterranean Sea. One of the world's largest deltas, it stretches roughly 240 kilometres along the coast and splits into distributaries including the Damietta and Rosetta branches, with several coastal lakes and lagoons. Its fertile soils have supported intensive agriculture for thousands of years, and it remains home to a large share of Egypt's population.",
"Mummy": "Mummification is the preservation of a dead body's soft tissues and organs, occurring either naturally or through deliberate treatment. Natural mummies form when a body is exposed to conditions such as extreme dryness, cold, acidic bogs, or lack of air that halt decay, while intentional mummification involves chemical treatment, drying, and wrapping. The practice has arisen in numerous cultures across the world, often connected to religious beliefs about the afterlife and the memorialization of the dead.",
"Di_(Five_Barbarians)": "The Di were an ancient ethnic group of western China who inhabited areas of present-day Gansu, Qinghai, Sichuan, and Shaanxi. Culturally related to the Qiang, they farmed in river valleys and are counted among the peoples known collectively as the Five Barbarians. During the Sixteen Kingdoms era they founded several states, most notably the Former Qin, which briefly unified northern China.",
"Chang'an": "Chang'an was an ancient Chinese capital city on the site of present-day Xi'an in Shaanxi Province. It served as the seat of government for several dynasties, most notably the Western Han and the Tang, during which it grew into one of the largest cities in the world and the eastern terminus of the overland Silk Road. It was a major centre of politics, commerce, and religious and cultural exchange until its decline at the end of the Tang.",
"Fu_Jian_(337–385)": "Fu Jian was an emperor of the Former Qin state during China's Sixteen Kingdoms period, ruling from 357 to 385. Of Di ethnicity, he unified northern China with the help of his chancellor Wang Meng, but his ambition led to a catastrophic defeat by the Eastern Jin at the Battle of Fei River in 383. The loss triggered widespread rebellions, and he was captured and killed by his former subordinate Yao Chang.",
"Wang_Meng_(Former_Qin)": "Wang Meng was a Chinese statesman and general who served as chancellor of the Former Qin state under Emperor Fu Jian. Widely regarded as one of the most capable administrators in Chinese history, he reformed the government into an efficient and honest bureaucracy and helped expand Former Qin control over much of northern China. On his deathbed he warned against invading the Eastern Jin, advice that Fu Jian later disregarded to disastrous effect.",
"Eastern_Jin": "The Eastern Jin was the southern continuation of the Jin dynasty of China, established in 317 after invasions forced the court to flee south and re-establish itself at Jiankang, modern Nanjing. It endured for just over a century amid conflict with the northern states of the Sixteen Kingdoms, winning a celebrated victory over the Former Qin at the Battle of Fei River in 383. Its politics were dominated by powerful émigré clans, and it fell in 420 when the general Liu Yu founded the Liu Song dynasty.",
"Wuchao": "Wuchao was the site of a supply depot in present-day Yanjin County, Henan, that stored the food reserves of the warlord Yuan Shao during the Battle of Guandu in 200 CE. Acting on intelligence from a defector, the rival warlord Cao Cao led a picked force to raid and burn the depot, destroying its stores. The loss of provisions shattered the morale of Yuan Shao's army and proved a decisive turning point in the battle.",
"List_of_national_founders": "A founding father is a person credited with a leading role in establishing a nation, institution, or movement. Such figures are often recognized for shaping systems of governance, drafting constitutions, or leading struggles for independence that create a sovereign state. Which individuals are honoured with the title varies by country and historical tradition.",
"Religious_text": "A religious text, or scripture, is a written work that a religious tradition regards as sacred or authoritative. Such texts commonly set out beliefs, rituals, moral commandments, and accounts of the divine, and serve as sources of guidance and communal identity for their adherents. Traditions differ in which texts they treat as canonical, and some transmit their sacred teachings through oral means rather than writing.",
"Savanna": "A savanna is a mixed woodland-grassland biome in which trees are spaced widely enough that their canopies do not close, leaving a continuous layer of grasses below. Savannas typically occur in warm climates with strongly seasonal rainfall concentrated in a single wet season. They cover roughly a fifth of the Earth's land surface and often form transitional zones between forests and drier grasslands or deserts.",
"Xu_Xing_(philosopher)": "Xu Xing (許行) was a Chinese thinker of the Warring States period and a leading advocate of Agriculturalism, a school holding that rulers and subjects alike should work the land and live by their own labour. He gathered followers around a doctrine of self-sufficiency and egalitarian farming, and around 315 BCE settled in the state of Teng to put these ideals into practice. His teachings are known chiefly through a recorded debate in which one of his disciples argued his positions against the Confucian philosopher Mencius.",
"Amarna": "Amarna, known in antiquity as Akhetaten, was an ancient Egyptian city founded by the pharaoh Akhenaten as a new capital dedicated to the sun disc Aten. Built rapidly in mudbrick on the east bank of the Nile beginning around 1346 BCE, it was largely abandoned soon after Akhenaten's death and left uninhabited for centuries. Because it was not built over, the site preserves an unusually complete plan of an Egyptian city, making it an important source for archaeology of the period.",
"Amarna_Period": "The Amarna Period was a phase of ancient Egyptian history during the later Eighteenth Dynasty, centred on the reign of the pharaoh Akhenaten and the elevation of the sun disc Aten to supreme worship. It saw the royal court move from Thebes to the new capital Akhetaten and produced a distinctive, highly stylised art depicting the royal family in naturalistic and elongated forms. After Akhenaten's death traditional religion was restored and later rulers sought to erase the period from official records.",
"Afroasiatic_languages": "The Afroasiatic languages are a large language family of around 400 languages spoken across North Africa, the Horn of Africa, the Sahel, and much of West Asia. The family is usually divided into six branches: Berber, Chadic, Cushitic, Egyptian, Omotic, and Semitic, with Arabic, Hausa, Amharic, Oromo, and Somali among its most widely spoken members. Its Egyptian branch has the longest recorded written history of any language, spanning several thousand years.",
"Nuclear_transmutation": "Transmutation is the conversion of one chemical element or isotope into another, occurring when the number of protons or neutrons in an atomic nucleus changes. The idea originated in alchemy, whose practitioners long sought to turn base metals such as lead into gold, an aim later shown to be impossible by ordinary chemical means. In modern physics transmutation is achieved through radioactive decay or by bombarding nuclei with particles, and it was first observed scientifically in the early twentieth century.",
"Elixir": "An elixir is a liquid preparation, typically sweetened and often containing alcohol, intended to be taken by mouth for medicinal purposes. In alchemical and folk traditions the word also named substances believed to cure all ills or to grant long life, the so-called elixir of life. The term derives through Medieval Latin from the Arabic al-iksir, itself borrowed from a Greek word for a medicinal powder.",
"Methane": "Methane is a chemical compound with the formula CH4, consisting of one carbon atom bonded to four hydrogen atoms, and is the simplest alkane. A colourless, odourless, flammable gas, it is the main component of natural gas and is produced by both geological processes and microbial activity in wetlands, livestock, and sediments. Methane is widely burned as a fuel and is also a potent greenhouse gas whose atmospheric concentration has risen sharply since industrialisation.",
"Petroleum": "Petroleum, or crude oil, is a naturally occurring flammable liquid consisting mainly of hydrocarbons found in geological formations beneath the Earth's surface. It forms over millions of years from the buried remains of ancient marine organisms subjected to heat and pressure, and is extracted by drilling into underground reservoirs. Refined petroleum yields fuels such as gasoline, diesel, and jet fuel, as well as feedstocks for plastics, fertilisers, and many other chemical products.",
"Fossil_fuel": "A fossil fuel is a carbon-rich material formed naturally in the Earth's crust from the buried remains of prehistoric organisms over millions of years. The main types are coal, petroleum, and natural gas, which are burned to power engines, generate electricity, and supply raw materials for industry. Because they take geological ages to form they are considered non-renewable, and their combustion releases carbon dioxide and other pollutants that drive climate change.",
"Greenhouse_gas": "A greenhouse gas is an atmospheric gas that absorbs and re-emits infrared radiation, trapping heat near a planet's surface in what is called the greenhouse effect. The principal greenhouse gases in Earth's atmosphere include water vapour, carbon dioxide, methane, nitrous oxide, and ozone. Without them Earth's average surface temperature would be far below freezing, but human activity has raised their concentrations and intensified global warming.",
"Casbah_of_Algiers": "The Casbah of Algiers is the old fortified quarter, or medina, of Algiers, rising on a steep slope above the Mediterranean and centred on a former citadel. Founded in 944 on the site of the earlier settlement of Icosium, it grew into the political and commercial heart of the region during the Regency of Algiers and later became a stronghold during the Algerian War of Independence. It was inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1992 for its dense maze of alleys, houses, mosques, and palaces of traditional Maghrebi design.",
"Barbary_Coast": "The Barbary Coast is a historical name for the coastal regions of North Africa, roughly the Maghreb, encompassing parts of present-day Morocco, Algeria, Tunisia, and Libya. From the sixteenth to the nineteenth centuries the area was divided among the Moroccan sultanate and the regencies of Algiers, Tunis, and Tripoli, several of them nominally under Ottoman authority. The coast became notorious for the Barbary corsairs, who raided Mediterranean and Atlantic shipping and coastlines for plunder and captives.",
"Constantinople": "Constantinople was a city on the Bosporus founded by the Roman emperor Constantine I in 330 on the site of the earlier Greek colony of Byzantium. It served as capital of the Roman and then Byzantine Empire for over a thousand years and, for much of the medieval era, was among the largest and wealthiest cities in Europe, famed for monuments such as the Hagia Sophia and the Theodosian Walls. Conquered by the Ottomans in 1453, it remained their capital until the early twentieth century and was formally renamed Istanbul in 1930.",
"Sultan": "A sultan is a title of sovereign authority used by Muslim rulers, derived from an Arabic word meaning strength or authority. It came into use around the late tenth century to designate rulers who governed with practically independent power, in theory holding authority delegated by the caliph. The title was borne by monarchs of many Islamic states over the centuries and is still used today by the rulers of Brunei and Oman.",
"World_War_I": "World War I was a global conflict fought from 1914 to 1918 between the Allied Powers, including France, the United Kingdom, Russia, Italy, and later the United States, and the Central Powers of Germany, Austria-Hungary, the Ottoman Empire, and Bulgaria. Marked by trench warfare, industrial-scale artillery, and battles across Europe, the Middle East, Africa, and beyond, it was one of the deadliest conflicts in history, causing an estimated 15 to 22 million deaths. It ended with the armistice of 11 November 1918 and a peace settlement that redrew borders, dissolved empires, and established the League of Nations.",
"Turkic_peoples": "The Turkic peoples are a collection of ethnic groups across West, Central, East, and North Asia and parts of Eastern Europe who speak languages of the Turkic family. Numbering over 170 million speakers, they include the Turks, Azerbaijanis, Uzbeks, Kazakhs, Uyghurs, Kyrgyz, Turkmens, and Tatars, among others. Their Proto-Turkic language is thought to have originated in Central-East Asia, and the first state to bear the name Turk was the Göktürk Khaganate of the sixth to eighth centuries.",
"Chemical_bond": "A chemical bond is a lasting attraction between atoms or ions that allows them to form molecules, crystals, and other structures. Bonds arise from electrostatic forces and the sharing or transfer of electrons, and they largely determine the structure and properties of matter. The main types are covalent bonds, in which atoms share electrons, ionic bonds, in which electrons are transferred to create oppositely charged ions, and metallic bonds, in which electrons are delocalised across a lattice of atoms.",
"Ion": "An ion is an atom or molecule that carries a net electrical charge because it has an unequal number of electrons and protons. A positively charged ion, having lost one or more electrons, is called a cation, while a negatively charged ion, having gained electrons, is called an anion. Ions form when atoms gain or lose electrons and can combine through electrostatic attraction to build ionic compounds such as common salt.",
"Electron": "An electron is a subatomic particle carrying a negative electric charge of one elementary charge. It is one of the fundamental constituents of ordinary matter and occupies regions around an atomic nucleus called orbitals. The arrangement of electrons determines an atom's chemical behaviour, and moving electrons give rise to electricity and magnetism.",
"Ionic_bonding": "Ionic bonding is a type of chemical bond formed by the electrostatic attraction between oppositely charged ions. It typically arises when an atom of low ionization energy transfers one or more electrons to an atom of high electron affinity, producing a positive cation and a negative anion. The resulting ions arrange themselves into a crystalline lattice held together by these electrostatic forces.",
"Covalent_bond": "A covalent bond is a chemical bond in which atoms share one or more pairs of electrons. The shared electron pairs, called bonding pairs, allow each participating atom to attain a more stable electron configuration. Covalent bonding produces discrete molecules and network structures and is central to the chemistry of many compounds.",
"Buddhahood": "Buddhahood is the condition or state of being a buddha, one who has attained complete spiritual awakening in Buddhism. A buddha is understood as an awakened being who has fully realized the nature of reality and freed the mind of craving, aversion, and ignorance. Different Buddhist traditions describe the qualities and number of buddhas in varying ways, from a supremely enlightened teacher to transcendent beings of boundless wisdom.",
"Sukhavati": "Sukhavati is the pure land, or buddha-field, associated with the Buddha Amitābha in Mahāyāna Buddhism, its Sanskrit name meaning the Land of Bliss. It is also called the Western Pure Land and is described as a realm of great beauty free from suffering, aging, and death. In Pure Land practice, devotees aspire to be reborn there, where conditions are held to be ideal for attaining enlightenment.",
"Sogdia": "Sogdia was an ancient Iranian civilization in Central Asia centred on the region between the Amu Darya and Syr Darya rivers, with major cities including Samarkand and Bukhara. Its people, the Sogdians, spoke an Eastern Iranian language and were organized into city-states rather than a single unified realm. They became renowned merchants who dominated much of the Silk Road trade, serving as middlemen linking distant commercial networks.",
"Yan_(An–Shi)": "Yan, also called Great Yan, was a short-lived dynastic state proclaimed in 756 by the rebel general An Lushan during his revolt against the Tang dynasty. Its forces captured the eastern capital Luoyang and much of northern China before internal strife and Tang counteroffensives brought about its collapse. The regime came to an end in 763 with the death of its last claimant, Shi Chaoyi.",
"Civil_war": "A civil war is an armed conflict between organized groups within the same state or country. The competing factions typically seek to take control of the government, gain independence for a region, or force a change in government policy. Such conflicts are usually high-intensity and sustained, often causing heavy loss of life and great economic damage.",
"Disciple": "A disciple is a follower and student of a teacher, mentor, or other figure. Discipleship traditionally involves close personal attachment in which the disciple seeks to learn and imitate not only the teachings but also the way of life of the master. The concept appears in many philosophical and religious traditions across the ancient world.",
"Aphorism": "An aphorism is a concise, memorable expression of a general truth or principle. Aphorisms are typically terse and self-contained, often inviting interpretation rather than stating a self-evident fact. They are commonly passed down as distilled observations drawn from experience and reflection.",
"Western_Asia": "Western Asia is the westernmost region of the Asian continent, also known as West Asia or Southwest Asia. It commonly encompasses Anatolia, the Arabian Peninsula, Iran, Mesopotamia, the Armenian highlands, the Levant, the Sinai Peninsula, and the South Caucasus. The region is bounded by the Mediterranean, Black, Caspian, and Arabian seas and lies at the meeting point of Asia, Europe, and Africa.",
"Aegean_Sea": "The Aegean Sea is an elongated arm of the Mediterranean Sea lying between the Balkan and Anatolian peninsulas. It connects northward to the Sea of Marmara and the Black Sea through the Dardanelles and Bosphorus straits. The sea contains numerous islands and reaches depths of over two and a half kilometres.",
"Sea_of_Marmara": "The Sea of Marmara is a small inland sea that links the Black Sea and the Aegean Sea through the Bosphorus and Dardanelles straits. It separates the European and Asian portions of Turkey and is among the smallest seas in the world. Roughly 280 kilometres long, it reaches a maximum depth of over a thousand metres.",
"Byzantine_Empire": "The Byzantine Empire was the continuation of the Roman Empire centred on Constantinople during late antiquity and the Middle Ages. Its inhabitants regarded themselves as Romans and maintained Roman legal, administrative, and, from late antiquity, Christian traditions. The state endured for roughly a thousand years until Constantinople fell to the Ottoman Empire in 1453.",
"Nile": "The Nile is a major north-flowing river in northeastern Africa, generally regarded as the longest river in the world. It gathers waters from the highlands of East and Central Africa and flows through eleven countries before emptying into the Mediterranean Sea through a large delta. Its annual flooding deposited fertile silt along its banks, sustaining agriculture and settlement in an otherwise arid landscape.",
"Nile_Valley": "The Nile Valley is the fertile lowland corridor of cultivable land that follows the course of the Nile through northeastern Africa. Bordered by desert, its soil was enriched by silt deposited during the river's annual flood, making the narrow strip far more productive than the surrounding land. This ribbon of farmland supported dense settlement and the growth of early civilizations along the river.",
"Pharaoh": "Pharaoh was the title given to the monarch of ancient Egypt, derived from an Egyptian term meaning great house that originally referred to the royal palace. The pharaoh served as both civil ruler and religious leader, holding authority over the land, laws, taxation, and military. Egyptian kingship often held the ruler to be a divine or semi-divine figure responsible for maintaining cosmic order.",
"Egyptian_hieroglyphs": "Egyptian hieroglyphs were the formal writing system used in ancient Egypt for monumental, religious, and royal inscriptions. The script combined logograms that stand for whole words, phonograms that represent sounds, and determinatives that clarify a word's meaning, drawing on more than seven hundred distinct signs. Developed by around 3200 BCE, the system remained in use for over three thousand years before being deciphered in the early nineteenth century with the aid of the Rosetta Stone.",
"Republic": "A republic is a form of government in which political power ultimately rests with the citizen body rather than with a hereditary monarch. Public offices are typically held by elected or appointed representatives, and the state is treated as a public matter rather than the private property of a ruler. The concept takes its name from the Latin res publica, meaning public affair, and has taken many forms across history.",
"Pyrenees": "The Pyrenees are a mountain range in southwestern Europe that stretches roughly 500 kilometres and forms much of the boundary between France and Spain. The range reaches its highest point at Aneto, about 3,404 metres, and encloses the small state of Andorra along its central crest. Formed largely during the Cretaceous period, the mountains support alpine flora, glaciated peaks, and are a popular destination for skiing and mountaineering.",
"Andorra_la_Vella": "Andorra la Vella is the capital and largest town of Andorra, located high in the eastern Pyrenees at an elevation of about 1,023 metres. It sits at the confluence of two mountain streams that join to form the Gran Valira river, and it has served as the principality's principal settlement since the thirteenth century. Its economy rests largely on tourism, retail, and the country's low-tax status.",
"Principality": "A principality is a monarchical state or territory whose ruler holds the title of prince or an equivalent rank below that of king. It may be a fully sovereign state or a constituent part of a larger political entity, and the term is often applied to small monarchies. Sovereign principalities that survive today include Liechtenstein, Monaco, and Andorra.",
"Microstate": "A microstate is a sovereign state that is exceptionally small in land area, population, and economic resources. Because no single agreed threshold defines the category, examples are identified by their very limited size, and many depend on larger powers for defence and economic viability. Commonly cited microstates include Andorra, Liechtenstein, Monaco, San Marino, and Vatican City, along with several small Pacific island nations.",
"President_of_France": "The President of France is the head of state of the French Republic and commander-in-chief of its armed forces, holding the highest office in the country. Under the Fifth Republic, established in 1958, the president is directly elected and shares executive power with a prime minister in a semi-presidential system. The office carries wide authority, particularly over national security and foreign policy.",
"Roman_Catholic_Diocese_of_Urgell": "The Diocese of Urgell is a Catholic diocese seated at La Seu d'Urgell in Catalonia, Spain, whose territory also covers the whole of Andorra. Its bishop holds, ex officio, the role of co-prince of Andorra, ruling the microstate jointly with the president of France. This makes the bishop of Urgell the world's only remaining prince-bishop, a status the diocese has held since Andorra was ceded to it in the twelfth century.",
"Luanda": "Luanda is the capital and largest city of Angola, lying on the country's northern Atlantic coast. Founded in 1576 as a Portuguese settlement, it grew into a major colonial port and a centre of the transatlantic slave trade before becoming the administrative and economic heart of independent Angola. Today it is a major seaport and industrial hub and one of the most populous Portuguese-speaking cities in the world.",
"Cabinda_Province": "Cabinda is a province of Angola that forms a coastal exclave, separated from the rest of the country by a narrow strip of the Democratic Republic of the Congo along the lower Congo River. It became a Portuguese protectorate in 1885 and was incorporated into Angola around the time of independence in 1975, a status contested by local separatist movements. The territory is rich in offshore oil, which makes it economically significant to Angola.",
"Uruk_period": "The Uruk period was an era of the Chalcolithic to Early Bronze Age in Mesopotamia, lasting roughly from 4000 to 3100 BCE. It is marked by the emergence of the first cities, monumental temple architecture, full-time bureaucracy, and the earliest writing, developments most visible at the southern Mesopotamian site of Uruk. By its close, Uruk may have been the largest urban settlement in the world.",
"Urbanization": "Urbanization is the process by which an increasing share of a population comes to live in cities and towns rather than in rural areas. It involves the growth and formation of urban settlements and the accompanying changes in economy, society, and culture as people concentrate in denser environments. The term usually refers to the proportion of a population classified as urban rather than the absolute number of city dwellers.",
"Religion": "Religion is a system of beliefs, practices, and institutions that relate people to what they regard as sacred, transcendent, or supernatural. It commonly includes shared rituals, moral codes, sacred texts or narratives, holy places, and forms of communal worship or devotion. Scholars have not agreed on a single definition, but religion is generally distinguished from purely private belief by its organized and public dimensions.",
"Gudea": "Gudea was a ruler of the Mesopotamian city-state of Lagash who governed around 2144 to 2124 BCE during the era of Gutian dominance following the fall of the Akkadian Empire. Taking the title ensi, or governor, rather than the grander lugal, he presided over a period of prosperity and artistic revival in Lagash. He is especially remembered for extensive temple building and for the many surviving inscribed statues that depict him in prayer.",
"Nebuchadnezzar_I": "Nebuchadnezzar I was a king of Babylon who reigned around 1121 to 1100 BCE as the most prominent ruler of the Second Dynasty of Isin. He is best known for a decisive campaign against Elam in which he defeated its king and recovered the cult statue of the god Marduk that the Elamites had carried off. His reign is remembered as a period of Babylonian resurgence, and he is unrelated to the later, more famous king of the same name.",
"Nebuchadnezzar_II": "Nebuchadnezzar II was the second king of the Neo-Babylonian Empire, reigning from 605 to 562 BCE and its longest-ruling and most celebrated monarch. He extended Babylonian power across the Levant, defeated Egypt at Carchemish, and in 587 BCE destroyed Jerusalem and deported much of the population of Judah in the event known as the Babylonian captivity. He is also remembered as a great builder who adorned his capital with the Ishtar Gate, the ziggurat Etemenanki, and other monuments.",
"Dione_(Titaness)": "Dione is an oracular goddess in Greek mythology, variously described as an Oceanid daughter of Oceanus and Tethys or a Titaness born of Gaia and Uranus. She is most often named as the mother of the goddess Aphrodite, whom she comforts and tends after Aphrodite is wounded in Book V of Homer's Iliad. Her chief cult was at the sanctuary of Dodona, where she was worshipped as a consort of Zeus alongside his oracle.",
"Scallop": "A scallop is a marine bivalve mollusc of the family Pectinidae, found in oceans around the world. Its two hinged shell valves typically bear radiating ribs and a pair of flat ear-like projections beside a toothless hinge, and it swims by rapidly clapping the valves together. Scallops are filter feeders and possess a ring of numerous small eyes along the edge of the mantle, an unusual feature among bivalves.",
"Myrtus": "Myrtus, commonly called myrtle, is a genus of evergreen shrubs or small trees in the family Myrtaceae native to the Mediterranean region and parts of western Asia. The plants bear small glossy aromatic leaves rich in essential oils and produce star-shaped white flowers with five petals and many stamens. After flowering they form rounded berries, usually blue-black, that are eaten and dispersed by birds.",
"Dove": "Dove is a common name for many birds of the family Columbidae, which also includes the pigeons and is the only family in the order Columbiformes. These stout-bodied birds have small heads, short necks, and slender bills, and feed largely on seeds, fruit, and other plant matter. Doves occur nearly worldwide and have long served as symbols of peace and love in art and religion.",
"Pythia": "The Pythia was the high priestess of the temple of Apollo at Delphi in ancient Greece, who served as the oracle through which the god was believed to speak. Chosen from local women, she delivered prophecies while seated on a tripod in the temple's inner sanctum, reportedly entering an altered state before pronouncing her answers. Her responses, sought by individuals and city-states alike, made the Delphic oracle one of the most influential religious institutions of the classical world.",
"Delphi": "Delphi was an ancient sacred precinct on the southwestern slope of Mount Parnassus in central Greece, regarded by the ancient Greeks as the centre of the world and marked by the Omphalos stone. Its sanctuary of Apollo housed the famous oracle, whose priestess the Pythia delivered prophecies to visitors from across the Greek world. The site also hosted the Pythian Games, a panhellenic festival of athletic and musical contests held every four years.",
"Lyre": "The lyre is a stringed musical instrument in which strings are stretched from a crossbar, or yoke, held between two arms down to a bridge over a hollow resonating body. It is played by strumming or plucking the strings, often with a plectrum, while damping unwanted strings with the free hand. One of the oldest known chordophones, the lyre was widely used to accompany song and poetry across ancient Mediterranean and Near Eastern cultures.",
"Laurus_nobilis": "Laurus nobilis, commonly known as laurel or bay laurel, is an aromatic evergreen tree or large shrub in the family Lauraceae native to the Mediterranean region. It has glossy, smooth-edged leaves, small pale yellow-green flowers, and small black berry-like fruits. Its dried leaves are used as the culinary bay leaf, and wreaths woven from its foliage have long been used as emblems of honour and victory.",
"Personification": "Personification is the representation of a thing, place, being, or abstract idea as a person or with human form and qualities. As a literary and artistic device it gives human traits such as speech, emotion, or bodily shape to concepts like death, justice, the seasons, cities, or nations. In many religions and mythologies it appears as deities who embody natural forces or abstractions, endowing intangible ideas with character and agency.",
"Middle_East": "The Middle East is a geopolitical region generally understood to encompass Egypt and much of West Asia, including the Arabian Peninsula, the Levant, Mesopotamia, Anatolia, and the Iranian plateau. It contains part of the Fertile Crescent, where some of the earliest civilizations and writing systems arose, and it is the birthplace of the Abrahamic religions. In modern times the region has held major strategic and economic importance, in large part because of its extensive petroleum reserves.",
"Liturgy": "Liturgy is the customary form of public worship or ritual carried out by a religious community, through which participants collectively express praise, thanksgiving, remembrance, supplication, or repentance. It consists of prescribed words, actions, and ceremonies understood by the worshippers as an act performed in relation to the sacred. The term derives from a Greek word meaning work or service on behalf of the people, and set liturgies are found across many faith traditions.",
"Achaemenid_Empire": "The Achaemenid Empire was the first Persian empire, founded by Cyrus the Great around 550 BCE and lasting until its conquest by Alexander the Great in 330 BCE. At its height it stretched from southeastern Europe and Egypt across the Iranian plateau to the Indus Valley, making it one of the largest empires of the ancient world. It became known for its centralized administration, network of provinces and royal roads, and a policy of relative tolerance toward the many peoples and religions it ruled.",
"Artifact_(archaeology)": "An artefact, in archaeology, is an object made, modified, or used by humans, such as a tool, weapon, ornament, or piece of pottery. Artefacts are studied as physical evidence of past human activity and are recovered from sites through excavation and survey. They are set apart from naturally occurring materials by bearing traces of deliberate human manufacture or use.",
"Architecture": "Architecture is the art and practice of designing and constructing buildings and other physical structures. It combines technical and engineering knowledge with aesthetic and functional considerations, spanning the process from conception and planning through to the finished work. Beyond providing shelter, architecture expresses cultural values and has served as a lasting record of the societies that produced it.",
"Ambivalence": "Ambivalence is a state of holding simultaneous conflicting feelings, beliefs, or attitudes toward a single object, person, or situation. Rather than cancelling one another out, the positive and negative reactions coexist, often producing internal tension, uncertainty, or difficulty in deciding. Because of this uncertainty, ambivalent attitudes tend to be weaker predictors of behaviour than clearly one-sided ones.",
"Buenos_Aires": "Buenos Aires is the capital and largest city of Argentina, situated on the southwestern shore of the Río de la Plata estuary. Federalized in 1880 and governed as an autonomous city, it anchors a metropolitan area that is among the most populous in South America. It is noted for its eclectic European-influenced architecture and for a population shaped by successive waves of immigration.",
"Andes": "The Andes are the longest continental mountain range in the world, running roughly 8,900 kilometres along the western edge of South America. They pass through seven countries, from Venezuela and Colombia in the north through Ecuador, Peru, Bolivia, Chile, and Argentina in the south. The range includes numerous high peaks, with Aconcagua the tallest at about 6,961 metres, as well as high plateaus such as the Altiplano.",
"Pampas": "The Pampas are fertile lowland grasslands in southern South America, spanning parts of Argentina, Uruguay, and southernmost Brazil. Covering more than a million square kilometres of largely treeless plains, they support prairie and steppe vegetation across a temperate climate. Their deep soils have made the region a major area for agriculture and cattle ranching.",
"Patagonia": "Patagonia is a geographical region at the southern end of South America, spanning parts of Argentina and Chile. Its terrain is strikingly varied, with arid steppes, tablelands, and deserts to the east and the Andes, lakes, fjords, glaciers, and temperate rainforests to the west. Sparsely populated and bounded by the Atlantic and Pacific Oceans, it is joined to the mainland's tip by waterways including the Strait of Magellan.",
"Tango": "Tango is a partner dance and accompanying style of music that originated in the 1880s along the Río de la Plata on the border between Argentina and Uruguay. It developed from a blend of earlier dance and music traditions and is performed by a leader and follower moving in a close embrace with improvised steps. UNESCO added tango to its list of Intangible Cultural Heritage in 2009.",
"Association_football": "Association football, commonly called football or soccer, is a team sport played between two sides of eleven players who use their feet to move a spherical ball toward the opposing goal. The objective is to score by sending the ball into the goal, with only the goalkeeper permitted to handle it inside the penalty area. A standard match lasts ninety minutes divided into two halves, and the sport is played and watched by hundreds of millions of people worldwide.",
"Nobility": "Nobility is a privileged social class ranked below royalty that has existed in many societies with an aristocracy. Its status is typically conferred and formally recognized, often hereditary, and has historically carried privileges such as tax exemptions, land rights, and preferential access to office. In most modern states these legal privileges have been abolished, leaving nobility as a largely honorary distinction.",
"Political_philosophy": "Political philosophy is the branch of philosophy that studies the theoretical and conceptual foundations of politics, government, and social organization. It examines questions of justice, authority, legitimacy, liberty, rights, and the proper form and limits of political power. Rather than describing how governments actually operate, it evaluates the norms and values by which they should be judged.",
"Book_of_Exodus": "The Book of Exodus is the second book of the Torah and the Hebrew Bible, narrating the enslavement of the Israelites in Egypt and their deliverance under the leadership of Moses. It recounts the ten plagues, the departure from Egypt, the crossing of the sea, and the covenant made at Mount Sinai, including the giving of the Ten Commandments. Most scholars date its composition to the first millennium BCE from earlier oral and written traditions.",
"Acacia": "Acacia is a large genus of shrubs and trees in the pea family Fabaceae, comprising over a thousand species. Its members often bear finely divided bipinnate leaves or flattened leaf-like phyllodes and clusters of small golden to cream-coloured flowers, followed by seed pods. Acacias grow across a wide range of habitats including grasslands, woodlands, and deserts, with the great majority of species native to Australia.",
"Cherub": "Cherubim are a class of winged celestial beings that serve God in Jewish, Christian, and Islamic tradition, and are the most frequently named heavenly creatures in the Hebrew Bible. They act as guardians and bearers of the divine throne, appearing at the entrance to the Garden of Eden and over the Ark of the Covenant. Descriptions range from the multi-faced, many-winged figures of Ezekiel's visions to the plump winged infants of later Western art.",
"Tabernacle": "The Tabernacle was a portable sanctuary described in the Hebrew Bible as the dwelling place of God among the Israelites during their journey through the wilderness. Built to instructions given at Mount Sinai, it consisted of an outer courtyard, a Holy Place with a lampstand, incense altar, and table, and an inner Holy of Holies housing the Ark of the Covenant. It served as the Israelites' central place of worship until it was replaced by the Temple in Jerusalem.",
"Solomon's_Temple": "Solomon's Temple, also called the First Temple, was the temple in Jerusalem described in the Hebrew Bible as built by King Solomon around the tenth century BCE. It housed the Ark of the Covenant in an inner Holy of Holies and served as the central sanctuary of ancient Israelite worship. According to biblical account it was destroyed by the Babylonians under Nebuchadnezzar II in 587 or 586 BCE.",
"Jerusalem": "Jerusalem is a city on a plateau in the Judaean Mountains between the Mediterranean and the Dead Sea, and one of the oldest cities in the world. It is regarded as holy by Judaism, Christianity, and Islam, and its Old City contains sites such as the Western Wall, the Dome of the Rock, the Al-Aqsa Mosque, and the Church of the Holy Sepulchre. Its political status is disputed, with both Israel and Palestine claiming the city as their capital.",
"Caucasus": "The Caucasus is a geographical region between the Black Sea and the Caspian Sea, spanning parts of Eastern Europe and Western Asia. It is dominated by the Caucasus Mountains, whose Greater Caucasus range includes Mount Elbrus, and is often taken as a boundary between Europe and Asia. The region contains Russia's southern territories along with Georgia, Armenia, and Azerbaijan, and is noted for its exceptional ethnic and linguistic diversity.",
"Yerevan": "Yerevan is the capital and largest city of Armenia, situated along the Hrazdan River in the South Caucasus. Among the world's oldest continuously inhabited cities, it traces its origin to the Urartian fortress of Erebuni founded in 782 BCE. It became the capital of the Republic of Armenia in 1918 and was extensively rebuilt in the twentieth century according to Alexander Tamanian's urban plan.",
"Chastity": "Chastity is a virtue associated with temperance in which a person refrains from sexual activity regarded as immoral or, in some contexts, from sexual activity altogether according to their state of life. Its precise expectations vary by religious and cultural framework, often meaning abstinence for the unmarried and fidelity within marriage. The term derives from the Latin castus, meaning pure.",
"Pseudoscience": "Pseudoscience consists of statements, beliefs, or practices that claim to be scientific but do not adhere to the scientific method. It is typically marked by contradictory, exaggerated, or unfalsifiable claims, reliance on confirmation bias, and resistance to independent testing and peer review. Because it presents itself with the appearance of science while lacking its rigor, distinguishing it from genuine science is a central concern of the philosophy of science.",
"Galaxy": "A galaxy is a gravitationally bound system of stars, stellar remnants, interstellar gas, dust, and dark matter. Galaxies range from dwarfs with fewer than a thousand stars to giants with many trillions, and are commonly classified by shape as elliptical, spiral, or irregular. The observable universe is estimated to contain hundreds of billions of galaxies, typically separated by millions of light-years.",
"Comet": "A comet is an icy small body of the Solar System that releases gas and dust when it approaches the Sun, forming a glowing coma and often one or more tails. Its solid nucleus is composed of rock, dust, water ice, and frozen gases such as carbon dioxide and methane, and is generally only a few kilometres across. Comets follow highly elliptical orbits, with short-period comets originating in the Kuiper Belt and long-period comets in the distant Oort cloud.",
"Washington,_D.C.": "Washington, D.C., officially the District of Columbia, is the capital city and federal district of the United States, located on the north bank of the Potomac River and bordered by Maryland and Virginia. It is not part of any state and operates under the ultimate jurisdiction of Congress, with a locally elected mayor and council under home rule. The city houses the principal institutions of the federal government, including the White House, the Capitol, and the Supreme Court.",
"New_York_City": "New York City is the most populous city in the United States, located at the southern tip of New York State on one of the world's largest natural harbours. It is made up of five boroughs — Manhattan, Brooklyn, Queens, the Bronx, and Staten Island — each coextensive with a county, and has a population of roughly eight and a half million. It is a leading global centre of finance, commerce, culture, and media, and hosts the headquarters of the United Nations.",
"Pantheon_(religion)": "A pantheon is the collective set of gods and goddesses belonging to a particular religion, mythology, or cultural tradition. The word derives from Greek elements meaning all and god, and such a body of deities often reflects a culture's values and view of the world. By extension the term can also denote a temple dedicated to all gods or a group of especially celebrated or revered figures.",
"Athens": "Athens is the capital and largest city of Greece, located in the Attica region on a plain ringed by mountains near the Aegean coast. It is one of the world's oldest cities, with a recorded history spanning more than three thousand years. In classical antiquity it was among the most powerful Greek city-states and an early center of democracy, philosophy, and the arts.",
"Aegis": "The aegis is a protective device in Greek mythology carried by the deities Zeus and Athena, described variously as a shield or an animal skin. It is often depicted bearing the head of a Gorgon at its center and bordered by serpents or golden tassels. Shaking it was said to inspire terror and produce storms, and the word survives in the expression to act under someone's aegis, meaning under their protection or sponsorship.",
"Gorgons": "In Greek mythology the Gorgons are three monstrous sisters, Stheno, Euryale, and Medusa, typically portrayed with living snakes for hair and a fearsome gaze. Their look could turn onlookers to stone, and of the three only Medusa was mortal, eventually slain by the hero Perseus. Their image, called a gorgoneion, was widely placed on shields, temples, and coins as a protective emblem.",
"Id,_ego_and_superego": "The ego is a concept in psychoanalytic theory naming the part of the mind that mediates between instinctual drives, moral standards, and external reality. In the structural model of the psyche it operates by the reality principle, weighing consequences and organizing thought, perception, and action. In everyday usage the word also refers more loosely to a person's sense of self-esteem or self-importance.",
"Jötunn": "A jötunn is a type of being in Norse and wider Germanic mythology, often rendered in English as a giant though not necessarily large in size. According to myth all jötnar descend from the primordial being Ymir, and they typically dwell in wild regions such as Jötunheimr across boundaries from gods and humans. Their relationship to the gods is complex, since several major deities including Odin, Thor, and Loki have jötunn ancestry.",
"Rime_ice": "Rime is a white, opaque coating of ice that forms when supercooled water droplets in fog or cloud freeze on contact with a cold surface. Soft rime develops in calm, humid conditions and appears feathery and fragile, while hard rime forms in wind and builds denser, comb-like deposits aligned with the wind direction. Because it can accumulate on structures, trees, and aircraft, rime is a recognized hazard in cold weather and aviation.",
"Southern_Hemisphere": "The Southern Hemisphere is the half of Earth lying south of the Equator. It is dominated by ocean, holding roughly a third of the planet's land, and contains all or part of the continents of Antarctica, Australia, South America, Africa, and Asia. Its seasons are reversed relative to the Northern Hemisphere, with summer falling around December to February and winter around June to August.",
"Tasmania": "Tasmania is an island state of Australia lying about 240 kilometres south of the mainland, separated from it by the Bass Strait. It comprises a main island, the twenty-sixth largest in the world, together with around a thousand smaller islands, and its capital is Hobart. It is Australia's smallest and least populous state, with a cool temperate climate and extensive forests and protected reserves.",
"Canberra": "Canberra is the capital city of Australia, located inland within the Australian Capital Territory between Sydney and Melbourne. It is a planned city, chosen as a compromise between those two rival cities and designed by the architects Walter Burley Griffin and Marion Mahony Griffin, with formal naming in 1913. It houses the country's major federal institutions, including Parliament House and the High Court.",
"Sydney": "Sydney is the capital of the Australian state of New South Wales and the country's most populous city, situated on the east coast around Sydney Harbour. Founded as a British penal colony on 26 January 1788, it grew into a major economic and cultural center with a metropolitan population of several million. It is known for landmarks such as the Sydney Opera House and the Sydney Harbour Bridge.",
"Melbourne": "Melbourne is the capital of the Australian state of Victoria and the country's second most populous city, set on Port Phillip Bay in the southeast. Established in 1835 and named after the British prime minister Viscount Melbourne, it expanded rapidly during the Victorian gold rush of the 1850s to become one of the era's wealthiest cities. It is a leading financial and cultural center and the birthplace of Australian rules football.",
"Aboriginal_Australians": "Aboriginal Australians are the Indigenous peoples of mainland Australia, Tasmania, and many nearby islands, forming one of the world's oldest continuous cultures. Their ancestors are thought to have reached the continent tens of thousands of years ago, and at the time of European contact they were divided into hundreds of distinct language and territorial groups. Their populations declined sharply after colonization before recovering in the twentieth century.",
"Landlocked_country": "A landlocked country is a state that has no coastline on the world ocean and is entirely surrounded by land. Such countries must rely on neighbours for access to seaports, which can raise the cost of trade and shape their economic development. A doubly landlocked country is one surrounded only by other landlocked countries, of which there are just two in the world.",
"Vienna": "Vienna is the capital and largest city of Austria, situated on the Danube River in the northeast of the country. Founded on the site of the Roman camp of Vindobona, it long served as the residence of the House of Habsburg and a leading German-speaking metropolis. It is renowned as a center of classical music and hosts major international organizations, with its historic center inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site.",
"Alps": "The Alps are a major mountain range system in Europe, extending roughly 1,200 kilometres in an arc across Monaco, France, Switzerland, Italy, Liechtenstein, Germany, Austria, and Slovenia. They were formed over tens of millions of years by the collision of the African and Eurasian tectonic plates and contain more than eighty peaks above 4,000 metres, the highest being Mont Blanc. The range strongly influences the climate and water supply of surrounding regions and draws large numbers of visitors.",
"Habsburg_monarchy": "The Habsburg monarchy was the collection of kingdoms, duchies, and other territories ruled by the House of Habsburg, centered on Austria and usually governed from Vienna. It existed from the late thirteenth century until 1918, over time incorporating Bohemia, Hungary, and many other lands into a large multi-ethnic composite state. In its final phase it was known as the Austrian Empire and then Austria-Hungary before dissolving after the First World War.",
"European_Union": "The European Union is a supranational political and economic union of member states located primarily in Europe. It was established when the Maastricht Treaty took effect in 1993, building on earlier integration efforts, and maintains a single market allowing free movement of people, goods, services, and capital. Many of its members share a common currency, the euro, and most participate in the passport-free Schengen Area.",
"Caspian_Sea": "The Caspian Sea is the world's largest inland body of water, an endorheic basin lying between Europe and Asia with no natural outflow to the ocean. Its surface sits about 27 metres below sea level, its water is mildly saline at roughly a third of ocean salinity, and it is bordered by Kazakhstan, Russia, Azerbaijan, Iran, and Turkmenistan. It is fed largely by the Volga River and holds several times more water than all of the Great Lakes combined.",
"Baku": "Baku is the capital and largest city of Azerbaijan, located on the western shore of the Caspian Sea on the Absheron Peninsula. Lying about 28 metres below sea level, it is the lowest-lying national capital in the world and the largest city on the Caspian. It is the scientific, cultural, and industrial heart of the country, long noted for its petroleum industry, and its walled Old City is a UNESCO World Heritage Site.",
"Gas": "Gas is one of the fundamental states of matter, having neither a fixed shape nor a fixed volume. Its particles are widely separated and move freely in random motion, so a gas expands to fill any container and can be compressed far more readily than a liquid or solid. A gas may consist of individual atoms, single molecules, or a mixture of different chemical species.",
"Valley_of_Mexico": "The Valley of Mexico is a large highland basin in central Mexico, ringed by mountains and volcanoes and lying more than 2,200 metres above sea level. It once held a system of five interconnected lakes, the largest being Lake Texcoco, most of which have since been drained. The basin was home to major pre-Columbian settlements and is today occupied by the sprawling metropolis of Mexico City.",
"Tenochtitlan": "Tenochtitlan was the capital of the Aztec Empire, built on an island in Lake Texcoco in the Valley of Mexico. Founded in 1325 by the Mexica, it grew into one of the largest cities in the world, with causeways, canals, marketplaces, and the great temple precinct of the Templo Mayor. The city was besieged and destroyed in 1521 by a Spanish expedition and its indigenous allies, and Mexico City was later built over its ruins.",
"Mesoamerica": "Mesoamerica is a historical and cultural region extending from central Mexico through much of Central America. The peoples who lived there shared distinctive traits, including maize agriculture, pyramid architecture, base-20 mathematics, dual calendars, and independently developed writing systems. It was one of the few regions in the world where complex civilization and writing arose without outside influence, giving rise to societies such as the Olmec, Maya, and Aztec.",
"Tribute": "Tribute is wealth or goods that one party gives to another as a sign of submission, allegiance, or respect. It differs from ordinary taxation in that it explicitly acknowledges the political subordination of the payer to a more powerful ruler or state. Throughout history dominant powers used tribute to extract resources from conquered or dependent territories while leaving local structures partly intact.",
"Hernán_Cortés": "Hernán Cortés was a Spanish conquistador who led the expedition that brought about the fall of the Aztec Empire in the early sixteenth century. Landing on the Mexican coast in 1519, he advanced to the Aztec capital of Tenochtitlan and, with indigenous allies, captured and destroyed it by 1521. He afterward served as governor of the newly established colony of New Spain before returning to Spain, where he died in 1547.",
"Bábism": "Bábism is a religious movement founded in 1844 by the Báb, a merchant of Shiraz in Qajar-era Persia. Its followers held that the Báb was a divine messenger who inaugurated a new era of revelation and foretold a still greater figure to come. The movement spread rapidly across Iran and met severe persecution, and after the Báb's execution in 1850 most of its adherents eventually followed the Bahá'í Faith.",
"Ishtar_Gate": "The Ishtar Gate was the eighth gate of the inner city wall of Babylon, built around 569 BCE under King Nebuchadnezzar II. It was faced with deep-blue glazed bricks and adorned with rows of relief animals, including dragons, bulls, and lions associated with major deities. Dedicated to the goddess Ishtar, it formed part of a grand processional way leading into the city.",
"Esagila": "Esagila was the principal temple of the god Marduk in the city of Babylon, its name meaning the temple whose top is lofty. The complex housed the cult statue of Marduk and other sacred images within a series of courts and a central shrine. Rebuilt and embellished by rulers such as Esarhaddon and Nebuchadnezzar II, it stood near the ziggurat Etemenanki and remained a religious center of Babylon for centuries.",
"Etemenanki": "Etemenanki was a great ziggurat in the city of Babylon dedicated to the god Marduk, its Sumerian name meaning the temple of the foundation of heaven and earth. The most famous version was a towering multi-tiered structure rebuilt during the Neo-Babylonian period, notably under Nabopolassar and Nebuchadnezzar II. Many scholars regard it as a likely inspiration for the biblical account of the Tower of Babel, and it fell into ruin after the campaigns of Alexander the Great.",
"Great_Ziggurat_of_Ur": "The Great Ziggurat of Ur is a massive stepped temple platform in the ancient Sumerian city of Ur, in what is now southern Iraq. It was built in the twenty-first century BCE by King Ur-Nammu of the Third Dynasty of Ur and completed by his son Shulgi, as a shrine to the moon god Nanna. Originally a structure of several tiers, it was later restored and expanded, and its lowest stage survives today.",
"Amorites": "The Amorites were an ancient Northwest Semitic-speaking people of the Bronze Age Near East, whose homeland is thought to have centered on the region of central Syria. From roughly the twenty-first century BCE onward they spread across Mesopotamia and the Levant, founding numerous city-states and kingdoms, including Babylon under Hammurabi and the kingdom of Mari. Their language is known mainly from personal names and loanwords preserved in Akkadian records.",
"Cyrus_the_Great": "Cyrus the Great was the founder of the Achaemenid Persian Empire, reigning from about 559 to 530 BCE. Through a series of conquests he absorbed the Median, Lydian, and Neo-Babylonian realms, building the largest empire the world had yet seen. He is remembered for his administrative system of provinces and for policies of religious tolerance, including permitting exiled Jews to return to their homeland.",
"Abbasid_Caliphate": "The Abbasid Caliphate was the third major Islamic caliphate, ruled by a dynasty descended from Abbas ibn Abd al-Muttalib, an uncle of Muhammad. Founded in 750 after the overthrow of the Umayyads, it made Baghdad its capital and presided over a flourishing of science, culture, and learning often called the Islamic Golden Age. Its central power waned over subsequent centuries, and the line at Baghdad ended when Mongol forces sacked the city in 1258.",
"Caliph": "A caliph is the title given to the head of a caliphate, regarded as a successor to the Islamic prophet Muhammad and a leader of the Muslim community. The word derives from an Arabic term meaning successor or deputy, and the office combined political and religious authority. Different Islamic traditions held differing views on how a caliph should be chosen, and historic caliphates included the Rashidun, Umayyad, Abbasid, and Ottoman.",
"Al-Mansur": "Al-Mansur was the second caliph of the Abbasid Caliphate, reigning from 754 to 775 CE. He founded the city of Baghdad in 762 as a new round-walled capital on the Tigris, which became a major center of administration and learning. He consolidated Abbasid rule by suppressing rivals and building a centralized bureaucracy influenced by Persian administrative traditions.",
"Islamic_Golden_Age": "The Islamic Golden Age was a period of cultural, economic, and scientific flourishing in the history of Islam, conventionally dated from the 8th to the 14th century. It is often traced from the establishment of the House of Wisdom in Baghdad and the Abbasid translation movement, which rendered Greek, Persian, and Sanskrit works into Arabic. Scholars of the era made lasting advances in mathematics, astronomy, medicine, optics, and philosophy.",
"House_of_Wisdom": "The House of Wisdom was a major Abbasid-era intellectual center and library in Baghdad during the Islamic Golden Age. It served as a hub of the Greco-Arabic translation movement, where scholars translated texts from Greek, Persian, Syriac, and Sanskrit into Arabic and conducted original research. It flourished under caliphs such as Harun al-Rashid and al-Ma'mun until Baghdad was sacked in 1258.",
"Al-Khwarizmi": "Al-Khwarizmi was a Persian mathematician, astronomer, and geographer active at the House of Wisdom in Baghdad during the 9th century. His treatise on al-jabr set out systematic methods for solving linear and quadratic equations and gave rise to the word algebra, while the Latinized form of his name became the word algorithm. He also popularized the Hindu-Arabic decimal numeral system, whose transmission reshaped later mathematics.",
"Bahrain_Island": "Bahrain Island, also called Awal, is the largest island of the archipelago that makes up the Kingdom of Bahrain in the Persian Gulf. Covering about 604 square kilometers, it holds most of the country's population and its capital, Manama, on the northeastern coast. The low-lying, largely desert island is linked to nearby islands and to the Saudi Arabian mainland by causeways.",
"King_Fahd_Causeway": "The King Fahd Causeway is a series of bridges and embankments spanning about 25 kilometers across the Gulf of Bahrain. It connects Bahrain with the eastern coast of Saudi Arabia and was officially opened in 1986. The crossing includes an artificial island, sometimes called Passport Island, that houses the border and customs facilities between the two countries.",
"Manama": "Manama is the capital and largest city of Bahrain, situated on the northeastern coast of Bahrain Island along the Persian Gulf. It has developed from a modest trading port into a regional financial center hosting numerous banks and institutions. The city is the political and economic heart of the country and served as the 2012 Arab Capital of Culture.",
"House_of_Khalifa": "The House of Khalifa is the ruling royal family of Bahrain, a Sunni Muslim dynasty descended from the Utub tribal alliance of the Arabian Peninsula. The family took control of the Bahrain archipelago in 1783 and has governed it ever since, with the head of state bearing the title of king since 2002. Members of the dynasty hold many senior government and cabinet positions.",
"Constitutional_monarchy": "A constitutional monarchy is a form of government in which a monarch serves as head of state within the limits of a constitution. The sovereign's powers are constrained by law rather than absolute, and many functions are exercised only on the advice of elected ministers or a legislature. The monarch may hold largely ceremonial duties or retain certain formal authorities, depending on the system.",
"Chang_hen_ge_(poem)": "Chang hen ge is a long narrative poem written by the Tang poet Bai Juyi in 809, whose title is often rendered as the Song of Everlasting Regret or Song of Everlasting Sorrow. It recounts the love of Emperor Xuanzong of Tang for his consort Yang Yuhuan and her death during the An Lushan rebellion. The work became one of the most celebrated poems in Chinese literature and inspired many later retellings.",
"Pipa_xing": "Pipa xing is a narrative poem composed by the Tang poet Bai Juyi in 816, its title often translated as the Song of the Pipa Player or Ballad of the Lute. Written after Bai Juyi was exiled from court, it describes a chance evening encounter with a pipa player near the Yangtze whose fading fortunes mirror the poet's own. The poem is admired for the vivid imagery with which it renders the sound of the instrument in words.",
"Nanna_(Norse_deity)": "Nanna is a goddess in Norse mythology, the wife of the god Baldr and mother of Forseti. According to the Prose Edda, she dies of grief at Baldr's death and is placed on his funeral ship, where the two are burned together and later reunited in the underworld of Hel. Her name appears in medieval Icelandic sources, though its precise meaning is debated.",
"Forseti": "Forseti is a god of justice and reconciliation in Norse mythology, described as the son of Baldr and Nanna. He presides over a hall called Glitnir, said to have pillars of gold and a roof of silver, where disputes among gods and people are settled. He is attested chiefly in the Prose Edda and the poem Grimnismal.",
"Mistletoe": "Mistletoe is a common name for a group of hemiparasitic plants that grow attached to the branches of trees and shrubs. They anchor to a host through a structure called a haustorium, drawing water and nutrients from it while still carrying out some photosynthesis, and typically bear evergreen leaves and waxy berries. Many species exist worldwide, and some serve as important food and nesting resources for wildlife.",
"Höðr": "Höðr is a blind god in Norse mythology, a son of Odin. In the best-known account he is deceived and guided by Loki into throwing a shaft of mistletoe that kills the otherwise invulnerable Baldr. In vengeance, Odin fathers Vali, who grows to adulthood swiftly and slays Höðr.",
"Bamboo_and_wooden_slips": "Bamboo and wooden slips were the main writing medium of ancient China before the spread of paper. Each slip was a long, narrow strip holding a column of brush-written characters, and multiple slips were bound together with cord to form rolls or books. They were in use from at least the Warring States period through the Han dynasty before being largely replaced by paper.",
"Western_Jin": "The Western Jin was the first phase of the Jin dynasty, ruling China from 266 to 316 CE. It was founded by Sima Yan, known posthumously as Emperor Wu of Jin, who in 280 conquered Eastern Wu and reunified China after the Three Kingdoms period. Weakened by the War of the Eight Princes and invasions by nomadic peoples, it collapsed with the loss of Luoyang and Chang'an in the early 4th century.",
"Protectorate_of_the_Western_Regions": "The Protectorate of the Western Regions was a Han dynasty administration overseeing territories in Central Asia, especially the oasis states of the Tarim Basin west of the Yumen Pass. First established around 60 BCE, it was headed by a protector-general who commanded garrisons and supervised the region's numerous vassal states along the Silk Road. It operated intermittently through the Eastern Han and was revived at times in later periods.",
"Northern_Hemisphere": "The Northern Hemisphere is the half of a planet that lies north of its equator. On Earth it contains the great majority of the world's land and human population, including all of North America and mainland Eurasia. Because of the planet's axial tilt, its seasons are the reverse of those in the Southern Hemisphere, with winter around the December solstice and summer around the June solstice.",
"Mammal": "A mammal is a vertebrate animal of the class Mammalia, characterized by mammary glands that in females produce milk to nourish their young. Other distinguishing features include hair or fur, three middle ear bones, and a neocortex region of the brain, and most species regulate their own body temperature. Mammals occupy nearly every habitat on Earth and range from tiny shrews and bats to whales, elephants, and humans.",
"Omnivore": "An omnivore is an animal that eats and can obtain energy and nutrients from both plant and animal matter. The term derives from the Latin omnis, meaning all, and vorare, meaning to devour, and such animals often have digestive systems and teeth suited to a varied diet. This dietary flexibility allows omnivores to exploit many food sources and survive in changing or unpredictable environments.",
"Totemism": "Totemism is a system of belief in which people hold a spiritual or symbolic relationship with a totem, typically an animal, plant, or natural object regarded as an emblem of a group such as a family, clan, or tribe. The totem often marks group identity and may be linked to rules about kinship, marriage, and ritual behavior toward the associated being. Practices classified as totemic vary widely across cultures, and anthropologists have debated whether they form a single coherent phenomenon.",
"Forbidden_City": "The Forbidden City (紫禁城) is a vast imperial palace complex in the center of Beijing, built between 1406 and 1420 under the Yongle Emperor of the Ming dynasty. It served as the residence of emperors and the ceremonial and political center of the Chinese state for the Ming and Qing dynasties until 1924, housing 24 rulers across roughly five centuries. The complex, now home to the Palace Museum, contains hundreds of buildings arranged around outer ceremonial courts and inner residential quarters.",
"Minsk": "Minsk is the capital and largest city of Belarus, situated on the Svislach and the now largely subterranean Nyamiha rivers in the center of the country. First mentioned in chronicles in 1067, it passed through the Grand Duchy of Lithuania, the Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth, and the Russian Empire before becoming capital of the Byelorussian Soviet Socialist Republic and later of independent Belarus. It is the nation's principal political, economic, and cultural center, with a population of around two million.",
"North_Sea": "The North Sea is a marginal sea of the Atlantic Ocean lying between Great Britain to the west and the northern European mainland to the east and south, bordered by Norway, Denmark, Germany, the Netherlands, Belgium, and France. It connects to the Atlantic through the Straits of Dover and the English Channel in the southwest and opens to the Norwegian Sea in the north, while narrow straits link it to the Baltic Sea in the east. Largely shallow and resting on the continental shelf, it is an important region for fishing, shipping, and offshore oil and gas.",
"NATO": "NATO is an intergovernmental military alliance of countries in North America and Europe, established on 4 April 1949 by the North Atlantic Treaty. Its founding principle of collective defense, set out in Article 5, holds that an armed attack against one member is considered an attack against all. Headquartered in Brussels, the alliance was created after the Second World War and grew over time to comprise dozens of member states.",
"Dutch_language": "Dutch is a West Germanic language of the Indo-European family, spoken as a first language by roughly 25 million people. It is the native language of the Netherlands and of the Flanders region of Belgium, and is also spoken in Suriname and several Caribbean territories. Belonging to the Low Franconian branch of West Germanic, it developed the closely related daughter language Afrikaans in southern Africa.",
"Flanders": "Flanders is the Dutch-speaking northern region of Belgium, functioning both as the Flemish Region and as the Flemish Community within the country's federal structure. It emerged from the medieval County of Flanders, once among Europe's richest and most urbanized areas, and its major cities today include Antwerp, Ghent, and Bruges. Home to roughly 6.8 million people, it is highly urbanized and one of the more economically prosperous parts of Belgium.",
"French_language": "French is a Romance language of the Indo-European family, descended from the Vulgar Latin of Roman Gaul and shaped by Celtic and Germanic influences. It is spoken natively in France, the Wallonia region of Belgium, western Switzerland, Monaco, Luxembourg, and parts of Canada, and holds official status in many countries across Africa, the Caribbean, and beyond. With hundreds of millions of speakers worldwide, it is a working language of numerous international organizations, including the United Nations.",
"Wallonia": "Wallonia is the predominantly French-speaking southern region of Belgium, making up the majority of the country's territory but a minority of its population. Its capital is Namur, and its main cities include Charleroi, Liège, and Mons; German is also an official language in some eastern cantons. Historically it was the first fully industrialized area of continental Europe, built on coal mining and steelmaking along the Sambre-Meuse valley, though heavy industry has since declined.",
"Central_America": "Central America is a subregion of the Americas forming a tapering isthmus that connects North and South America, bounded by Mexico to the north and Colombia to the southeast. It faces the Caribbean Sea to the east and the Pacific Ocean to the west, and comprises seven countries: Belize, Guatemala, Honduras, El Salvador, Nicaragua, Costa Rica, and Panama. Marked by mountainous highlands and abundant volcanic activity, it serves as an important land bridge for biological diversity between the two continents.",
"Belmopan": "Belmopan is the capital city of Belize, located inland in the Cayo District at an elevation that protects it from coastal storm surge. It was established as a planned city and became the seat of government in 1970, after Hurricane Hattie devastated the former coastal capital in 1961. With around 20,000 residents, it is one of the smallest national capitals in the Americas by population.",
"Belize_City": "Belize City is the largest city in Belize, situated on the Caribbean coast at the mouth of Haulover Creek, a distributary of the Belize River. It served as the capital of British Honduras and then of Belize until the government relocated to Belmopan in 1970 following hurricane damage. It remains the country's principal port and its main financial, commercial, and industrial center.",
"Barrier_reef": "A barrier reef is a coral reef that runs roughly parallel to a coastline and is separated from the land by a lagoon or a deep channel of water. The intervening lagoon can be several kilometres wide and tens of metres deep, and the reef's outer edge rises steeply from deeper open water. Such reefs typically take a very long time to form and are relatively rare among reef types.",
"Gulf_of_Guinea": "The Gulf of Guinea is the northeasternmost part of the tropical Atlantic Ocean, lying off the coasts of West and Central Africa. It is bordered by numerous countries, including Liberia, Ghana, Nigeria, Cameroon, Equatorial Guinea, and Gabon, and receives the waters of major rivers such as the Niger. The point where the Equator and the Prime Meridian intersect, at zero latitude and longitude, lies within the gulf.",
"Porto-Novo": "Porto-Novo is the official capital and second-largest city of Benin, lying in the country's southeast on a lagoon a short distance from the Atlantic Ocean. It grew from a settlement of the Yoruba and Gun peoples into a Portuguese trading port and later became the capital of the French colony of Dahomey. Although it is the constitutional capital and seat of the legislature, most government institutions, including the presidency, are based in the larger city of Cotonou.",
"Cotonou": "Cotonou is the largest city of Benin and its de facto seat of government, situated on the southeastern coast between the Atlantic Ocean and Lake Nokoué. Although Porto-Novo is the official capital, most government institutions, the presidency, and foreign embassies are located in Cotonou, making it the country's economic and administrative hub. Its autonomous port is one of the largest in West Africa, handling trade for Benin and several neighboring inland countries.",
"Dahomey": "Dahomey was a West African kingdom that existed from about 1600 to 1904 in the area of present-day Benin, centered on the city of Abomey among the Fon people. It was a centralized monarchy known for its professional army, which included an elite all-female regiment, and for its extensive participation in the Atlantic slave trade. Following two wars with France in the 1890s, it was conquered and absorbed into the French colonial empire.",
"Bölþorn": "Bölþorn is a jötunn, or giant, in Norse mythology, known chiefly from the Poetic Edda and the Prose Edda. He is the father of the giantess Bestla, making him the maternal grandfather of the gods Odin, Vili, and Vé. He is also said to have a son, sometimes identified with Mímir, who taught Odin nine powerful magic incantations.",
"Skald": "A skald was a poet who composed and recited skaldic verse, one of the two main forms of Old Norse poetry, associated with the courts of Scandinavian and Icelandic rulers during the Viking Age. Skaldic poems were typically eulogistic and historical, praising a lord's deeds in intricate alliterative meters such as the dróttkvætt stanza. The verse is dense with kennings, fixed metaphorical phrases that supply stock images to fit the strict metrical requirements.",
"Mímir": "Mímir is a figure in Norse mythology renowned for his knowledge and wisdom, whose name is linked to memory. According to the myths, the Aesir sent him to the Vanir as a hostage after their war, but he was beheaded and his head returned to the Aesir. Odin preserved the severed head with herbs and consulted it for counsel and hidden knowledge, and a well of wisdom beneath the world tree Yggdrasil is associated with his name.",
"Arjuna": "Arjuna is one of the central heroes of the ancient Hindu epic Mahabharata and the third of the five Pandava brothers, celebrated as a peerless archer and warrior. Born to Kunti and the god Indra, he plays a decisive role in the war between the Pandavas and their cousins the Kauravas at Kurukshetra. In the Bhagavad Gita he receives spiritual instruction from his charioteer Krishna, an avatar of Vishnu, when he despairs at the prospect of fighting his own kinsmen.",
"Common_Era": "Common Era, abbreviated CE, is a secular designation for the calendar year-numbering system that is numerically identical to the Anno Domini era, with the years before it labeled Before Common Era, or BCE. The scheme counts forward from the year 1 CE and backward as 1 BCE, with no year zero between them. The notation became widespread in academic and scientific writing during the later twentieth century as a religiously neutral alternative to AD and BC.",
"Thimphu": "Thimphu is the capital and largest city of Bhutan, situated in a valley of the western part of the country along the Wang Chhu river. It replaced Punakha as the seat of government in the mid-twentieth century and was formally declared the capital in 1961. Lying at an elevation of roughly 2,300 to 2,600 metres, it is one of the highest capital cities in the world.",
"Gross_National_Happiness": "Gross National Happiness is a development philosophy and measurement framework that gauges a population's collective well-being rather than economic output alone. The concept originated in Bhutan, whose government adopted it as a guiding goal enshrined in the country's constitution, and it assesses domains such as psychological well-being, health, education, governance, and ecological resilience. Its index was developed with academic researchers to inform policy toward holistic societal welfare.",
"Gross_domestic_product": "Gross domestic product is a monetary measure of the total market value of all final goods and services produced within a territory over a given period, usually a quarter or a year. It can be calculated by the production, expenditure, or income approach, and its main components are consumption, investment, government spending, and net exports. When adjusted for inflation it is called real GDP, and it is a widely used indicator of economic activity though not a direct measure of living standards or distribution.",
"Wangchuck_dynasty": "The Wangchuck dynasty is the ruling house of Bhutan, holding the hereditary title of Druk Gyalpo, or Dragon King, since 1907. It was founded when Ugyen Wangchuck was elected the first king by an assembly of clergy, officials, and nobles, ending a long-standing dual system of government and unifying the country. Under its rule Bhutan secured its independence through treaties and later moved toward a constitutional monarchy.",
"Northern_Song": "The Northern Song was the first phase of the Song dynasty, beginning when Zhao Kuangyin reunified much of China and established his capital at Bianjing, present-day Kaifeng. This period saw remarkable growth in commerce, agriculture, and the arts, including the flowering of monumental landscape painting and the issuing of the world's first government paper money. It ended when Jurchen forces of the Jin captured the capital and the imperial family in the Jingkang Incident, forcing the court to flee south.",
"Southern_Song": "The Southern Song was the later phase of the Song dynasty, beginning after the loss of northern China to the Jurchen-led Jin dynasty forced the court to retreat south of the Yangtze. The regrouped state under Emperor Gaozong established its capital at Lin'an, present-day Hangzhou, which grew into one of the most populous cities in the world. Despite reduced territory the period remained economically and culturally vibrant until the dynasty fell to the Mongol Yuan in 1279.",
"Resin": "Resin is a viscous organic substance, either secreted by plants or produced synthetically, that is typically capable of hardening into a solid. Natural plant resins are mixtures of organic compounds, predominantly terpenes and resin acids, that many trees exude in response to injury as protection against insects and pathogens. The term also covers many synthetic polymers such as epoxies, polyesters, and acrylics, which cure from a fluid state into rigid materials.",
"Dream_Pool_Essays": "The Dream Pool Essays (夢溪筆談) is an encyclopedic work written by the polymath and statesman Shen Kuo, completed in 1088 during the Song dynasty. Composed of hundreds of notes across dozens of categories, it ranges over astronomy, mathematics, geology, cartography, medicine, and many other subjects. It contains some of the earliest known descriptions of the magnetic compass used for navigation, movable-type printing, and the formation of fossils.",
"Afro-Eurasia": "Afro-Eurasia is the combined landmass of Africa, Asia, and Europe, together with adjacent islands, forming the largest and most populous contiguous landmass on Earth. It covers roughly 57 percent of the world's land area and is home to the great majority of the global population. In geopolitical thought it has been termed the World Island, connected across history by extensive overland and maritime trade networks.",
"Yersinia_pestis": "Yersinia pestis is a gram-negative, rod-shaped bacterium that causes plague, taking bubonic, septicemic, and pneumonic forms. It is typically transmitted to humans through the bite of infected fleas that live on rodents, and the pneumonic form can spread between people through respiratory droplets. The organism was identified in 1894 by Alexandre Yersin and is regarded as the agent behind historic pandemics including the Plague of Justinian and the Black Death.",
"Bacteria": "Bacteria are microscopic, mostly single-celled organisms classified as prokaryotes, meaning their cells lack a membrane-bound nucleus and other membrane-enclosed organelles. They occur in an enormous variety of shapes, including spheres, rods, and spirals, and inhabit nearly every environment on Earth, from soil and water to the bodies of other organisms. Most reproduce by binary fission, and while many are harmless or beneficial, some cause disease.",
"Bosporus": "The Bosporus is a narrow natural strait that connects the Black Sea to the Sea of Marmara and, by extension, links to the Mediterranean. Running through the city of Istanbul, it forms part of the conventional continental boundary between Europe and Asia. Only a few hundred metres wide at its narrowest, it is one of the world's most strategically important and heavily trafficked waterways for shipping.",
"Dardanelles": "The Dardanelles is a narrow natural strait in northwestern Turkey that connects the Aegean Sea to the Sea of Marmara. One of the two Turkish Straits marking part of the continental boundary between Europe and Asia, it helps link the Mediterranean to the Black Sea. Known in antiquity as the Hellespont, it has been a strategic crossing since ancient times, traversed by armies such as those of Xerxes I and Alexander the Great.",
"Danube": "The Danube is a major river of Europe and the second-longest on the continent, flowing for roughly 2,850 kilometres from the Black Forest of Germany to the Black Sea. It runs generally southeastward through Central and Southeastern Europe, passing through or bordering ten countries and several national capitals including Vienna, Bratislava, Budapest, and Belgrade. It has long served as a vital route for trade, transport, and settlement.",
"Slag": "Slag is a stony by-product formed during the smelting or refining of metal ores, consisting mainly of metal oxides and silicon dioxide together with compounds of calcium, magnesium, aluminium, and iron. It separates from the molten metal because it is less dense and does not mix with it, floating on top so that it can be drawn off. Once cooled and solidified, slag can be discarded as waste or reused in applications such as cement, road aggregate, and ballast.",
"Cobalt": "Cobalt is a hard, lustrous, silvery-grey metallic element with the chemical symbol Co and atomic number 27, classed as a transition metal. It is ferromagnetic and in nature occurs almost exclusively in chemically combined form, often alongside nickel in ore deposits. Its compounds have long been used to give a deep blue colour to glass and ceramics, and the metal is used in high-strength alloys, rechargeable batteries, and as the core of vitamin B12.",
"Jingdezhen": "Jingdezhen is a city in the eastern part of Jiangxi province in China, long known as the porcelain capital for its ceramics industry. It was renamed in 1004 CE after the reign era of a Song emperor, when its kilns rose to prominence, and by the fourteenth century it had become the leading centre of Chinese porcelain production. Its success drew on nearby deposits of kaolin and petuntse and on the imperial kilns that supplied fine wares to the court.",
"Shaolin_Monastery": "Shaolin Monastery (少林寺) is a Chan Buddhist temple at the foot of Mount Song in Henan province, China, traditionally founded in 495 CE during the Northern Wei dynasty. It is regarded as a cradle of Chan Buddhism, associated with the monk Bodhidharma, and as the birthplace of the Shaolin martial arts practised by its warrior monks. The temple complex was inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2010.",
"Sucre": "Sucre is the constitutional capital of Bolivia and the seat of its supreme court, located in the south-central highlands within the Chuquisaca Department. Founded by Spanish colonists in 1538 and later renamed after the independence leader Antonio José de Sucre, it was an early centre of the South American independence movement. Its well-preserved colonial centre was designated a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1991.",
"La_Paz": "La Paz is the seat of government of Bolivia and one of its largest cities, set in a canyon in the west of the country at roughly 3,650 metres above sea level, making it the highest administrative capital in the world. It was founded by Spanish colonists in 1548 on the site of an earlier Andean settlement. The city is Bolivia's principal administrative and financial centre and hosts the country's foreign embassies.",
"Salar_de_Uyuni": "The Salar de Uyuni is the world's largest salt flat, covering roughly 10,000 square kilometres of the Altiplano in southwestern Bolivia at about 3,656 metres elevation. It formed from the desiccation of a series of prehistoric lakes, leaving a thick crust of salt over a brine that is exceptionally rich in lithium. Its extreme flatness makes it useful for calibrating satellites, and in the wet season a thin layer of water turns its surface into a vast mirror.",
"Lake_Titicaca": "Lake Titicaca is a large freshwater lake in the Andes on the border between Bolivia and Peru, sitting at about 3,812 metres above sea level. It is South America's largest lake by volume and is often described as the highest navigable lake in the world, dotted with dozens of islands. The lake holds deep cultural significance for the region's Indigenous peoples and supports many endemic species.",
"Confucian_canon": "The Confucian canon, also called the Thirteen Classics (十三經), is the body of texts venerated in the Confucian tradition and used as the basis of study and civil examination in imperial China. The collection took shape over centuries and by the Song dynasty comprised thirteen works, including the classics of Changes, Documents, and Poetry, the ritual texts, commentaries on the Spring and Autumn Annals, the Analects, and the Mencius. Mastery of these writings was long central to scholarly and official life in East Asia.",
"Prose": "Prose is a form of language that follows the ordinary grammatical structure and natural flow of speech, organised into sentences and paragraphs. It is written or spoken without the regular metrical rhythm and line breaks that mark verse. Prose is the usual medium of novels, essays, journalism, conversation, and most everyday writing.",
"Dai_Sheng": "Dai Sheng was a ritual scholar of the Western Han dynasty in China, active in the first century BCE. He is best known for editing a compilation of ritual texts into the version of the Book of Rites (禮記) that survives today, a work sometimes called the Smaller Dai's Book of Rites to distinguish it from the larger recension attributed to his uncle Dai De. He was a figure in the New Text school of Confucian learning of his era.",
"Zheng_Xuan": "Zheng Xuan was a Confucian scholar and commentator of the late Eastern Han dynasty in China. Drawing on both the Old Text and New Text traditions of learning, he produced influential commentaries on many of the Confucian classics that shaped their interpretation for centuries. Although his teachings were never officially adopted by the government, they became the mainstream reading of the canon.",
"Fan_Ye_(historian)": "Fan Ye was a Chinese historian and official who lived under the Liu Song dynasty during the Northern and Southern dynasties period. He is remembered as the principal compiler of the Book of the Later Han (後漢書), one of the Twenty-Four Histories, which chronicles the Eastern Han dynasty. He was executed in 446 CE on charges of involvement in a plot against the throne.",
"Liu_Song_dynasty": "The Liu Song dynasty was an imperial Chinese dynasty that ruled southern China from 420 to 479 CE, the first of the four Southern dynasties of the Northern and Southern dynasties period. It was founded by Liu Yu, posthumously known as Emperor Wu, with its capital at Jiankang, present-day Nanjing. The reign of Emperor Wen is regarded as one of the relative golden ages of the Southern dynasties.",
"Roman_Empire": "The Roman Empire was the post-Republican Roman state, ruled by emperors, that dominated the lands around the Mediterranean Sea as well as much of Europe, Western Asia, and North Africa. It is conventionally dated from 27 BCE, when the Senate granted Octavian the title Augustus, and reached its greatest territorial extent under the emperor Trajan in the early second century CE. Its western half fell in 476 CE, while the eastern half, centred on Constantinople, endured until 1453.",
"Sarajevo": "Sarajevo is the capital and largest city of Bosnia and Herzegovina, lying in a valley of the Dinaric Alps along the Miljacka River. Founded as an Ottoman stronghold in the fifteenth century, it later passed to Austria-Hungary, and in 1914 the assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand there helped trigger the First World War. During the Bosnian War of the 1990s it endured a siege of nearly four years, one of the longest in modern history.",
"Federation_of_Bosnia_and_Herzegovina": "The Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina is one of the two political entities that make up the country of Bosnia and Herzegovina. It was established by the Washington Agreement of 1994 to end fighting between Bosniaks and Croats, and its status was confirmed by the Dayton Agreement of 1995. Divided into ten autonomous cantons and largely inhabited by Bosniaks and Croats, it covers roughly half of the country's territory.",
"Republika_Srpska": "Republika Srpska is one of the two political entities that make up the country of Bosnia and Herzegovina, occupying much of its northern and eastern territory. Proclaimed in 1992 at the outbreak of the Bosnian War, it was recognised as part of Bosnia and Herzegovina under the Dayton Agreement of 1995, with Banja Luka serving as its main administrative centre. Its population is predominantly Serb.",
"Bosnian_War": "The Bosnian War was an armed conflict in Bosnia and Herzegovina that followed the breakup of Yugoslavia, fought mainly among Bosniak, Serb, and Croat forces. It began after Bosnia and Herzegovina declared independence in 1992 and involved widespread ethnic cleansing, sieges, and mass killings, causing around 100,000 deaths and displacing more than two million people. The war ended in 1995 with the Dayton Agreement, which preserved the country as a single state divided into two entities.",
"Dayton_Agreement": "The Dayton Agreement, formally the General Framework Agreement for Peace in Bosnia and Herzegovina, is the peace treaty that ended the Bosnian War. It was negotiated at Wright-Patterson Air Force Base near Dayton, Ohio, initialed on 21 November 1995, and formally signed in Paris on 14 December 1995. The accord kept Bosnia and Herzegovina as a single state made up of the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina and Republika Srpska, and set up a rotating three-member presidency and international oversight.",
"Gaborone": "Gaborone is the capital and largest city of Botswana, located in the southeast of the country near the border with South Africa. It was established in 1964 as a planned capital ahead of Botswana's independence in 1966, chosen for its water supply, rail access, and central position. The city serves as the nation's political and economic centre and hosts the headquarters of the Southern African Development Community.",
"Kalahari_Desert": "The Kalahari Desert is a large semiarid sandy savanna in Southern Africa, covering much of Botswana and parts of Namibia and South Africa. Characterised by expanses of red sand and a lack of permanent surface water, it is drained by dry valleys, seasonal pans, and salt flats such as the Makgadikgadi and Etosha pans. Despite its aridity it receives enough seasonal rainfall to support more vegetation and wildlife than a true desert.",
"Okavango_Delta": "The Okavango Delta is a vast inland delta in northern Botswana where the Okavango River spreads across a tectonic trough instead of flowing to the sea. Water originating in the Angolan highlands travels roughly 1,200 kilometres before fanning out over floodplains, with nearly all of it lost to evapotranspiration or seepage into aquifers. The seasonally flooded wetland supports rich biodiversity and was inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2014.",
"Diamond": "A diamond is a solid form of the element carbon in which the atoms are arranged in a rigid tetrahedral crystal lattice. This structure makes it the hardest known natural material and gives it the highest thermal conductivity of any bulk substance, along with a high refractive index that produces brilliance in cut stones. Diamonds form deep within the Earth's mantle over long periods and are carried toward the surface by volcanic activity, and they are used both as gemstones and as abrasives for cutting and grinding.",
"First_Dynasty_of_Egypt": "The First Dynasty of Egypt was the earliest line of pharaohs, ruling from roughly 3100 to 2890 BCE at the start of the Early Dynastic Period. It followed the unification of Upper and Lower Egypt and governed from the city of Thinis in the south. Its rulers included Narmer, often identified with the unifier Menes, and Den, the first king shown wearing the double crown of the two lands.",
"Second_Dynasty_of_Egypt": "The Second Dynasty of Egypt ruled from about 2890 to 2686 BCE during the Early Dynastic Period, a phase that remains among the most obscure in Egyptian history. Its kings oversaw institutional and economic developments that laid the groundwork for the Old Kingdom. Its final and most famous ruler, Khasekhemwy, was an early master builder credited with reuniting the country after a period of internal conflict.",
"Third_Dynasty_of_Egypt": "The Third Dynasty of Egypt ruled from roughly 2686 to 2613 BCE and is regarded as the first dynasty of the Old Kingdom. Its most notable king, Djoser, commissioned his vizier Imhotep to build the Step Pyramid at Saqqara, the earliest surviving Egyptian pyramid. This achievement marked a major advance in monumental stone architecture and royal funerary practice.",
"Fourth_Dynasty_of_Egypt": "The Fourth Dynasty of Egypt ruled from about 2613 to 2498 BCE and is often called the golden age of the Old Kingdom. It is best known as the age of the great pyramid builders, with Sneferu erecting the Red and Bent Pyramids and Khufu building the Great Pyramid of Giza. His successors Khafre and Menkaure added the other two major Giza pyramids, and Khafre is also associated with the Great Sphinx.",
"Fifth_Dynasty_of_Egypt": "The Fifth Dynasty of Egypt ruled from roughly 2498 to 2345 BCE during the Old Kingdom, founded by Userkaf and ending with Unas. Its kings gave growing prominence to the sun god Ra, building dedicated sun temples alongside their pyramids. The reign of Unas produced the Pyramid Texts, the earliest known corpus of royal funerary prayers inscribed on tomb walls.",
"Sixth_Dynasty_of_Egypt": "The Sixth Dynasty of Egypt ruled from about 2345 to 2181 BCE and was the last dynasty of the Old Kingdom. Its kings, including Teti and Pepi I, mounted trading and mining expeditions to Sinai, Nubia, and beyond while provincial governors steadily grew more powerful. The exceptionally long reign attributed to Pepi II coincided with the weakening of central authority that led to the Old Kingdom's collapse.",
"Seventh_Dynasty_of_Egypt": "The Seventh Dynasty of Egypt is a shadowy line placed around 2181 BCE at the opening of the First Intermediate Period. It is known almost solely from the historian Manetho, who described seventy kings ruling in seventy days, a phrase usually read as a symbol of chaos rather than literal record. Most Egyptologists regard the dynasty as spurious, though a few have argued that some kings later assigned to the Eighth Dynasty may belong to it.",
"Eighth_Dynasty_of_Egypt": "The Eighth Dynasty of Egypt ruled from about 2181 to 2160 BCE at the transition from the Old Kingdom into the First Intermediate Period. Based at Memphis, its kings held only weak central authority as provincial nomarchs increasingly governed their own regions. Its best-attested ruler, Qakare Ibi, built a small pyramid at Saqqara inscribed with Pyramid Texts before the dynasty fell to rivals from Heracleopolis.",
"Ninth_Dynasty_of_Egypt": "The Ninth Dynasty of Egypt ruled from roughly 2160 to 2130 BCE during the First Intermediate Period, when the country was politically fragmented. It was based at Heracleopolis Magna in Middle Egypt after seizing power from the preceding dynasty. Its founder, Meryibre Khety, is identified with the ruler Manetho called Achthoes and described as a harsh and violent king.",
"Tenth_Dynasty_of_Egypt": "The Tenth Dynasty of Egypt ruled from about 2130 to 2040 BCE during the First Intermediate Period, continuing the Heracleopolitan line based in Middle Egypt. It governed the north while the rival Eleventh Dynasty rose at Thebes in the south. Its ruler Merykare was a chief opponent of the Theban king Mentuhotep II, and the dynasty ended when Thebes reunified the country.",
"Eleventh_Dynasty_of_Egypt": "The Eleventh Dynasty of Egypt ruled from roughly 2150 to 1991 BCE, governing from Thebes in Upper Egypt. Under Mentuhotep II it defeated the Heracleopolitan rulers of the north and reunified the country around his thirty-ninth regnal year. This victory ended the fragmented First Intermediate Period and began the Middle Kingdom.",
"Twelfth_Dynasty_of_Egypt": "The Twelfth Dynasty of Egypt ruled from about 1991 to 1802 BCE and is often regarded as the apex of the Middle Kingdom. Founded by Amenemhat I, who established a new capital at Itjtawy near the Faiyum, it was a stable and well-documented period of expansion and administrative reform. Its notable kings included the warrior Senusret III, who campaigned in Nubia, and Amenemhat III, remembered for his mortuary complex at Hawara.",
"Thirteenth_Dynasty_of_Egypt": "The Thirteenth Dynasty of Egypt ruled from roughly 1802 to 1649 BCE, spanning the end of the Middle Kingdom and the onset of the Second Intermediate Period. It was marked by a long succession of kings with brief reigns and a gradual loss of control over the country, with the capital shifting from Itjtawy toward Thebes. Its stronger rulers included Neferhotep I and Sobekhotep IV, and the dynasty declined as power fragmented across Egypt.",
"Fourteenth_Dynasty_of_Egypt": "The Fourteenth Dynasty of Egypt ruled during the Second Intermediate Period, from about 1725 to 1650 BCE, over the eastern Nile Delta. It was a local line of Canaanite or Semitic rulers based at the city of Avaris, whose kings bore West Semitic names such as Yakbim and Yaqub-Har. Its best-attested king was Nehesy, whose name means the Nubian and who left inscriptions at Avaris.",
"Fifteenth_Dynasty_of_Egypt": "The Fifteenth Dynasty of Egypt ruled from about 1650 to 1550 BCE during the Second Intermediate Period and was the dynasty of the Hyksos, foreign rulers of Asiatic origin. Based at Avaris in the Nile Delta, they controlled Lower Egypt and traded widely with Canaan and Cyprus while contending with the Theban kingdoms to the south. Among its most prominent kings was Apophis, also called Apepi, who reigned for more than forty years.",
"Sixteenth_Dynasty_of_Egypt": "The Sixteenth Dynasty of Egypt ruled the Theban region of Upper Egypt from about 1649 to 1582 BCE during the Second Intermediate Period. This native Egyptian line governed from Thebes at the same time as the Hyksos Fifteenth Dynasty dominated Lower Egypt from Avaris. Its territory shrank under repeated Hyksos pressure, and the dynasty ended when Hyksos armies conquered Thebes itself.",
"Seventeenth_Dynasty_of_Egypt": "The Seventeenth Dynasty was a line of ancient Egyptian rulers based at Thebes during the late Second Intermediate Period, reigning roughly from about 1580 to 1550 BC. It governed Upper Egypt while the Hyksos held the north, and its last kings, Seqenenre Tao and Kamose, launched the wars to expel the Hyksos. Their campaigns set the stage for reunification under Ahmose I, who founded the New Kingdom.",
"Eighteenth_Dynasty_of_Egypt": "The Eighteenth Dynasty was the first dynasty of the New Kingdom of Egypt, ruling from about 1550 to 1292 BC after Ahmose I completed the expulsion of the Hyksos. It presided over the height of Egyptian power, with extensive expansion into Nubia and the Near East. Its rulers included Hatshepsut, the conqueror Thutmose III, the reformer Akhenaten, and the famous Tutankhamun.",
"Nineteenth_Dynasty_of_Egypt": "The Nineteenth Dynasty was the second dynasty of the New Kingdom of Egypt, reigning from about 1292 to 1189 BC and founded by the vizier Ramesses I. It is part of the Ramesside era and reached its zenith under Seti I and the long-reigning Ramesses II, who fought the Hittites and later concluded one of the earliest recorded peace treaties. The dynasty ended amid succession disputes and the brief reign of Queen Twosret.",
"Twentieth_Dynasty_of_Egypt": "The Twentieth Dynasty was the third and last dynasty of the New Kingdom of Egypt, ruling from about 1189 to 1077 BC during the wider Bronze Age collapse. Its most notable king, Ramesses III, repelled the Sea Peoples but presided over economic strain that produced the first recorded labor strike at Deir el-Medina. Under the later Ramesside kings royal authority weakened as the High Priests of Amun gained control of Upper Egypt.",
"Twenty-first_Dynasty_of_Egypt": "The Twenty-first Dynasty was the first dynasty of the Third Intermediate Period of ancient Egypt, reigning from about 1077 to 943 BC from a capital at Tanis in the Delta. Its kings, beginning with Smendes, effectively controlled only Lower Egypt while the High Priests of Amun at Thebes governed the south. The dynasty is remembered for the intact royal burials at Tanis, including the gold funerary mask of Psusennes I.",
"Twenty-second_Dynasty_of_Egypt": "The Twenty-second Dynasty was a line of ancient Egyptian rulers of Libyan Meshwesh origin during the Third Intermediate Period, reigning from about 943 to 716 BC. It was founded by Shoshenq I, sometimes identified with the biblical Shishak, and is also called the Bubastite Dynasty after its early seat at Bubastis. Its later years saw the kingdom fragment into rival centers of power across the Delta and beyond.",
"Twenty-third_Dynasty_of_Egypt": "The Twenty-third Dynasty was a group of ancient Egyptian rulers of Libyan origin during the Third Intermediate Period, reigning from about 837 to 728 BC. It ruled contemporaneously with other lines rather than over a unified country, part of a fragmented era with competing power centers in the Delta and Upper Egypt. The reconstruction of its kings remains debated, and the period ended as the Kushite ruler Piye asserted control over Egypt.",
"Twenty-fourth_Dynasty_of_Egypt": "The Twenty-fourth Dynasty was a short-lived line of ancient Egyptian rulers based at Sais in the western Delta during the Third Intermediate Period, reigning from about 732 to 720 BC. It comprised the kings Tefnakht and Bakenranef, who briefly extended their authority over much of Lower Egypt including Memphis. The dynasty ended when the Kushite Twenty-fifth Dynasty conquered Sais.",
"Twenty-fifth_Dynasty_of_Egypt": "The Twenty-fifth Dynasty was a line of Kushite rulers from the Kingdom of Kush in present-day Sudan who governed Egypt during the late Third Intermediate Period, reigning from about 744 to 656 BC. Beginning with Piye and reaching its height under Taharqa, it reunited Egypt and Kush into the largest realm since the New Kingdom and revived earlier religious and architectural traditions. Assyrian invasions eventually drove the Kushite kings back to Nubia.",
"Twenty-sixth_Dynasty_of_Egypt": "The Twenty-sixth Dynasty, also called the Saite Dynasty after its capital at Sais, ruled ancient Egypt from 664 to 525 BC and marks the beginning of the Late Period. Its founder Psamtik I reunified the country and ended Kushite control, and his successor Necho II campaigned against the Neo-Babylonian Empire. It was the last native dynasty before the Achaemenid Persian conquest of 525 BC.",
"Twenty-seventh_Dynasty_of_Egypt": "The Twenty-seventh Dynasty represents the first period of Achaemenid Persian rule over Egypt, when the country was a satrapy of the Persian Empire from 525 to 404 BC. It began when Cambyses II defeated Psamtik III at the Battle of Pelusium and was crowned pharaoh, and continued under Darius I, who codified Egyptian law and completed a canal linking the Nile to the Red Sea. Persian control ended when Amyrtaeus led a successful revolt around 404 BC.",
"Twenty-eighth_Dynasty_of_Egypt": "The Twenty-eighth Dynasty of ancient Egypt consisted of a single ruler, Amyrtaeus of Sais, who reigned from about 404 to 398 BC during the Late Period. He led a revolt that expelled the Achaemenid Persians and proclaimed himself pharaoh, briefly restoring native independence. His reign left almost no monuments and ended when he was overthrown and executed by Nepherites I, founder of the following dynasty.",
"Twenty-ninth_Dynasty_of_Egypt": "The Twenty-ninth Dynasty was a native Egyptian line of the Late Period based at Mendes in the Delta, reigning from about 398 to 380 BC. It was founded by Nepherites I after he defeated Amyrtaeus, and its strongest king, Hakor, resisted Persian attempts to reconquer Egypt with support from Athens and Cyprus. The dynasty lasted only about eighteen years before it was overthrown.",
"Thirtieth_Dynasty_of_Egypt": "The Thirtieth Dynasty was the last dynasty of native Egyptian pharaohs, reigning from 380 to 343 BC during the Late Period from a capital at Sebennytos. Its founder Nectanebo I and his grandson Nectanebo II defended Egypt against Persia and sponsored extensive temple building, while the middle king Teos was undermined by heavy taxation. Nectanebo II, regarded as the last native pharaoh, was defeated by the Persians and fled south.",
"Thirty-first_Dynasty_of_Egypt": "The Thirty-first Dynasty was the second period of Achaemenid Persian rule over Egypt, lasting from 343 to 332 BC after Artaxerxes III defeated Nectanebo II near Pelusium. Persian kings, ending with Darius III, governed Egypt as a satrapy under heavy taxation intended to prevent further revolt. Persian control ended in 332 BC when the satrap Mazaces surrendered the country to Alexander the Great without a fight.",
"First_Dynasty_of_Uruk": "The First Dynasty of Uruk is the earliest sequence of rulers assigned to the Mesopotamian city of Uruk in the Sumerian King List, said to have received kingship after the fall of Kish. Its listed kings include the legendary figures Meshkiangasher, Enmerkar, Lugalbanda, Dumuzid the Fisherman, and Gilgamesh, several of whom appear as heroes in later Sumerian epic literature. It is conventionally associated with the Early Dynastic period of the early third millennium BCE, though most of its rulers lack independent archaeological confirmation.",
"Second_Dynasty_of_Uruk": "The Second Dynasty of Uruk is a line of three rulers recorded at Uruk in the Sumerian King List, credited with receiving kingship after a dynasty of Ur. Its kings are given as Enshakushanna, Lugal-kinishe-dudu, and Argandea, with Enshakushanna and Lugal-kinishe-dudu also attested in contemporary inscriptions as figures who claimed authority over parts of Sumer. It is placed in the mid-third millennium BCE, and the King List states that Uruk was afterward defeated and kingship passed on.",
"Third_Dynasty_of_Uruk": "The Third Dynasty of Uruk is a single-king entry in the Sumerian King List consisting of Lugal-zage-si, who is credited with a reign of twenty-five years. Lugal-zage-si is historically attested as a ruler who conquered Lagash and brought several Sumerian city-states under his control before the rise of the Akkadian Empire. The King List records that he was defeated and that kingship then passed to Akkad, marking the end of this brief dynasty.",
"Fourth_Dynasty_of_Uruk": "The Fourth Dynasty of Uruk is a line of rulers placed in the Sumerian King List after the Akkadian Empire, comprising kings such as Ur-nigin, Ur-gigir, Kuda, Puzur-ili, and a final ruler whose name is given variously. Ur-nigin and Ur-gigir are attested in contemporary inscriptions, lending the dynasty partial historical support during the period of Akkadian decline. The King List states that Uruk was afterward defeated and kingship taken by the Gutians.",
"Fifth_Dynasty_of_Uruk": "The Fifth Dynasty of Uruk in the Sumerian King List consists of the single ruler Utu-hengal, credited with ending the period of Gutian domination over southern Mesopotamia. Utu-hengal is historically attested and is remembered for defeating the Gutians and for appointing the governor who would found the Third Dynasty of Ur. The King List assigns him widely varying reign lengths across its manuscripts, reflecting the uncertain transmission of the text.",
"Mummification": "Mummification is the preservation of a body after death, whether by deliberate treatment or by natural conditions, so that its soft tissues and form are retained rather than decaying away. Deliberate methods typically involve removing or drying the internal organs and treating the body with salts, resins, or other substances that resist decay, after which it is wrapped or sealed. It has been practised by a number of cultures around the world, often in connection with beliefs about the afterlife.",
"Wu_Chinese": "Wu is a major group of Sinitic languages spoken in the lower Yangtze region of eastern China, including Shanghai, southern Jiangsu, and much of Zhejiang. Its best-known variety is Shanghainese, and the group is noted for preserving voiced consonants that many other Chinese varieties have lost. It is among the most widely spoken Sinitic languages after Mandarin.",
"Song_of_Everlasting_Regret": "The Song of Everlasting Regret (長恨歌) is a long narrative poem written by the Tang dynasty poet Bai Juyi in 806. It recounts the love of Emperor Xuanzong of Tang for his consort Yang Guifei and the sorrow that followed her death during the An Lushan rebellion. One of the most celebrated poems in Chinese literature, it has inspired plays, operas, and retellings across East Asia.",
"Indian_Ocean": "The Indian Ocean is the third largest of the world's oceanic divisions, occupying much of the region between Africa, Asia, and Australia. It stretches from the shores of East Africa and the Arabian Peninsula in the west to the Indonesian archipelago and Australia in the east, and southward to the Southern Ocean. Its warm waters and seasonal monsoon winds have shaped maritime trade and travel around its rim for thousands of years.",
"Infrared": "Infrared is a form of electromagnetic radiation with wavelengths longer than those of visible red light but shorter than microwaves. It is emitted by all objects that have a temperature and is felt by the skin as radiant heat. It is put to use in thermal imaging, remote controls, night vision, heating, and a wide range of scientific and communication applications.",
"Numerology": "Numerology is the belief in a mystical or divine relationship between numbers and events, objects, or living things. Its practitioners assign meanings to particular numbers and use them to interpret character, foretell the future, or find hidden significance in names and dates. Regarded as a pseudoscience, it has appeared in many cultures and is often bound up with divination and the occult.",
"Knotted-cord_record-keeping": "Knotted-cord record-keeping is the practice of recording information, counts, or messages by tying knots in cords or strings, whose number, position, colour, and type carry meaning. Employed by various peoples before or alongside writing, it served to keep tallies, accounts, calendars, and even narratives. Elaborate knotted-cord systems are known from several cultures around the world.",
"Stele": "A stele is an upright stone slab or pillar, usually taller than it is wide, erected as a monument and typically bearing an inscription, a relief carving, or both. Steles have been raised since antiquity to mark graves and boundaries, commemorate events and rulers, record laws and treaties, and serve religious purposes. Many survive as important historical sources, preserving texts and images from cultures across the world.",
"Heredity": "Heredity is the passing of traits, characteristics, or status from parents to their offspring and from one generation to the next. In biology it refers to the transmission of physical and behavioural features through genes, the basis of the science of genetics. The word is also used more broadly for anything handed down by descent, such as a hereditary title, office, or right.",
"Suiren": "Suiren (燧人) is a legendary culture hero of ancient Chinese mythology, honoured as the inventor of fire-making. Tradition credits him with teaching people to produce fire by drilling wood, and so to cook their food and drive off cold and wild beasts. He is counted in some accounts among the earliest sovereigns of high antiquity, before the age of the first dynasties.",
"Genealogy": "Genealogy is the study and tracing of family descent, recording the lines of ancestry and the relationships between successive generations. Genealogists gather evidence from records such as births, marriages, and deaths and set out their findings in family trees and pedigrees. Long important for inheritance, rank, and identity, it is today pursued both as a scholarly discipline and as a popular hobby.",
"Xia–Shang–Zhou_Chronology_Project": "The Xia–Shang–Zhou Chronology Project was a large multidisciplinary research effort sponsored by the Chinese state to establish a firm chronology for the Xia, Shang, and Zhou dynasties. Running from 1996 to 2000 and involving some two hundred scholars, it combined textual study, archaeology, radiocarbon dating, and astronomical analysis to assign dates to the early dynasties. Among its results was the dating of the Zhou conquest of the Shang to around 1046 BCE, though several of its conclusions remain debated.",
"Pharmacopoeia": "A pharmacopoeia is an official or authoritative book listing medicinal drugs along with their descriptions, their standards of strength and purity, and directions for preparing and using them. Issued by governments or professional bodies, it sets the recognized standards that medicines must meet within a country or region. Such compilations have a long history, evolving from early collections of remedies into the strict regulatory reference works of modern medicine.",
"Sexagenary_cycle": "The sexagenary cycle (干支), or ganzhi, is a traditional Chinese cycle of sixty terms used to count days and years. Each term pairs one of the ten Heavenly Stems with one of the twelve Earthly Branches, the two sequences turning together to give sixty unique combinations before repeating. Attested in the oracle-bone records of the Shang for numbering days, it was later applied to years and remains part of the traditional calendar.",
"Silkworm": "A silkworm is the caterpillar, or larva, of a silk moth, above all the domesticated moth Bombyx mori, whose cocoon is the source of most commercial silk. The larva feeds voraciously on leaves, chiefly those of the mulberry, and then spins its cocoon from a single long filament of silk. Reared in captivity for thousands of years, the domesticated silkworm depends entirely on human care and no longer lives in the wild.",
"Orthodoxy": "Orthodoxy is adherence to accepted, correct, or established beliefs, especially in religion, and the body of doctrine regarded as authoritative within a tradition. More broadly the word denotes conformity to any officially approved or conventional set of views, whether in faith, politics, or scholarship. Departures from the accepted standard are commonly labelled heresy or heterodoxy.",
"Eastern_Orthodox_Church": "The Eastern Orthodox Church is one of the largest branches of Christianity, a communion of self-governing churches that share the same faith, sacraments, and liturgical tradition. It traces its origins to the early Christian communities of the eastern Mediterranean and developed within the Byzantine world, becoming a separate body after its break with the Church of Rome in 1054. Led by bishops, with the Patriarch of Constantinople holding a place of honour, it is especially prominent in Greece, Eastern Europe, and Russia.",
"Mythography": "Mythography is the recording, compiling, and systematic study of myths. It embraces both the ancient authors who gathered and retold the myths of their peoples and the modern scholarly analysis of mythic narratives and their meanings. A mythographer collects, organizes, and interprets myths, preserving stories that might otherwise be lost.",
"Chronicle": "A chronicle is a historical account that sets down events in the order in which they happened, usually year by year. It records events plainly and in sequence, often compiled by contemporaries or drawn from earlier annals, with little of the analysis of a fuller narrative history. Chronicles have been kept in many civilizations and are valued as primary sources for the periods they cover.",
"Four_Barbarians": "The Four Barbarians (四夷) is a traditional Chinese term for the peoples living beyond the frontiers of the Central Plains, in the four cardinal directions. Classical texts named them the Yi to the east, the Man to the south, the Rong to the west, and the Di to the north, the peoples surrounding the Huaxia of the centre. The expression reflected an old worldview that placed the Chinese cultural sphere at the middle of the world, ringed by less civilized outsiders.",
"Confederation": "A confederation is a union of states, communities, or groups that join together for common purposes while each retains a large measure of independence. Its members typically cooperate on matters such as defence, trade, or foreign policy through a central body whose powers they agree to grant. Looser than a fully unified state, it leaves ultimate authority largely with its constituent parts.",
"Progenitor": "A progenitor is an ancestor or forebear, especially the founder from whom a family, line, people, or group is descended. The word is also used more broadly for the originator or first source of something, such as an idea, a style, or a biological lineage. In genealogy a progenitor stands at the head of a line of descent, the common ancestor from whom later generations spring.",
"Sovereign_(ruler)": "A sovereign is a supreme ruler, especially a monarch such as a king, queen, or emperor, who holds the highest authority in a state. The sovereign is the person or body in whom ultimate power resides and who is subject to no higher earthly authority. The title has been held under many forms of rule, from absolute monarchs to constitutional heads of state whose powers are limited by law.",
"Sovereignty": "Sovereignty is the supreme authority to govern a state or territory, free from outside control. It includes the power to make and enforce laws, to command allegiance within a territory's borders, and to act independently in dealings with other states. In modern political thought sovereignty may rest with a monarch, a government, or the people themselves, and it is a foundational principle of international law and the system of states.",
"Hundun": "Hundun (混沌) is the primordial, formless chaos of Chinese cosmology, representing the undifferentiated state of the universe before heaven and earth were separated. The name is often glossed as muddled confusion, and Hundun is sometimes personified as a featureless being lacking the usual openings of the face. A well-known parable in the Zhuangzi tells how two emperors bored seven holes into their faceless friend Hundun to give him senses, and on the seventh day he died.",
"Wuji_(philosophy)": "Wuji (無極) is a term in Chinese philosophy denoting the limitless or ultimateless, an undifferentiated primordial state without boundary or distinction. In Daoist thought it names an infinite condition to which cultivated beings may return, and it appears in the Daodejing as a state of primal wholeness. In Neo-Confucian cosmology, especially the diagram of the Song thinker Zhou Dunyi, wuji is depicted as an empty circle from which the Supreme Ultimate and the manifest world arise.",
"Taiji_(philosophy)": "Taiji (太極), often translated as the Supreme Ultimate, is a concept in Chinese cosmology denoting the highest principle from which existence unfolds. It is understood as the source that generates the complementary forces of yin and yang through alternating motion and stillness, which in turn give rise to the Five Phases and all things. The Song dynasty philosopher Zhou Dunyi elaborated it in his Explanation of the Diagram of the Supreme Ultimate, making it foundational to Neo-Confucian metaphysics, and it is symbolized by the interlocking dark and light swirls of the taijitu.",
"Trailokya": "Trailokya is a Sanskrit term meaning the three worlds, a cosmological framework describing three planes or realms of existence found in Hindu, Buddhist, and Jain traditions. The three realms are variously identified, such as heaven, the mortal earth, and an underworld, or in Buddhist thought the worlds of desire, form, and formlessness, through which beings pass in the cycle of rebirth. The concept spread across East Asia, where it is expressed by the term rendered as Sanjie in Chinese, denoting a layered structure of celestial, human, and infernal spheres.",
"Diyu": "Diyu (地獄), literally earth prison, is the realm of the dead or hell in Chinese mythology and folk religion, drawing on Buddhist, Daoist, and traditional beliefs. It is commonly conceived as a purgatory where the souls of the dead are judged and made to atone for wrongdoing before being sent on to reincarnation, often organized into ten courts or eighteen levels each with its own punishments. Presided over by the judges known as the Yama Kings, it functions as a place of moral reckoning within the cycle of rebirth.",
"Meng_Po": "Meng Po (孟婆), rendered as Old Lady Meng or the Lady of Forgetfulness, is a deity of the Chinese underworld associated with the erasure of memory before rebirth. She is said to await departed souls at the Bridge of Forgetfulness, also called the Naihe Bridge, within Diyu. There she serves a broth known as Meng Po soup, which causes souls to forget their past lives so that they may be reincarnated without the burden of former memories.",
"Ox-Head_and_Horse-Face": "Ox-Head (牛頭) and Horse-Face (馬面) are two guardians of the underworld in Chinese mythology, each having the body of a man topped with the head of an ox or a horse respectively. They serve the underworld king Yanluo Wang, acting as messengers and as the beings who capture the souls of the newly dead and escort them into Diyu for judgment. In many stories they are the first figures a soul meets upon entering the realm of the dead.",
"Heibai_Wuchang": "Heibai Wuchang (黑白無常), the Black and White Impermanence, are a pair of deities in Chinese folk religion tasked with escorting the spirits of the dead to the underworld. They are conventionally identified as the White Guard, Xie Bi'an, and the Black Guard, Fan Wujiu, and are often shown wearing tall hats and carrying tokens or shackles for the souls they collect. They appear frequently in City God temples and are also venerated as bringers of fortune, embodying the idea that reward and punishment await in the afterlife.",
"Jiangshi": "A jiangshi (殭屍) is a reanimated corpse in Chinese legend and folklore, said to arise from improper burial, spirit possession, or the retention of vital energy after death. In traditional accounts it is a ferocious being of great strength that preys on the living to absorb their qi, though the most powerful specimens were sometimes said to fly. Popular culture depicts the jiangshi moving with stiff, hopping motions and outstretched arms, an image often linked to the historical practice of transporting corpses upright on bamboo poles.",
"City_God_(China)": "The City God, or Chenghuangshen (城隍神), is a tutelary deity in Chinese folk religion charged with protecting a particular town or city and overseeing the fate of its dead. The name combines the words for city wall and moat, reflecting the deity's origin as a guardian of a settlement's physical defenses. City Gods were traditionally understood to be the spirits of deceased worthies or officials appointed to administer the local spiritual realm, and their birthdays are marked by temple festivals with processions, theatrical performances, and incense.",
"Yaoguai": "Yaoguai (妖怪) are a broad class of supernatural creatures in Chinese folklore marked by strange, weird, or unnatural qualities and possessing magical powers. They are often said to arise from animals, plants, or objects that absorb natural energy or undergo long cultivation, and many can shapeshift into human form, with fox, snake, and tiger spirits among the common types. Though generally regarded as dangerous, yaoguai are morally ambivalent beings that can feel emotion and form relationships, and they feature prominently as antagonists in works such as Journey to the West and Strange Stories from a Chinese Studio.",
"Four_Symbols": "The Four Symbols (四象), or Sixiang, are four mythological creatures in Chinese astronomy that appear among the constellations along the ecliptic and serve as guardians of the four cardinal directions. They are the Azure Dragon of the East, the Vermilion Bird of the South, the White Tiger of the West, and the Black Tortoise of the North, each formed from a cluster of seven lunar mansions. In Chinese cosmology each of the four is also associated with a season, a color, and one of the classical phases, making them a framework linking the heavens to the ordered structure of the world.",
"King_Father_of_the_East": "The King Father of the East, or Dongwanggong (東王公), is a deity in Taoist theology regarded as the patron and ruler of the male immortals. He embodies the yang principle and presides over the eastern quarter, and is traditionally paired with the Queen Mother of the West as his female counterpart. Some accounts describe him with a bird's face and a tiger's tail, and his image appears alongside the Queen Mother on Han-dynasty bronze mirrors as an emblem of prosperity and long life.",
"Peaches_of_immortality": "The peaches of immortality (蟠桃), or pantao, are a mythical fruit in Chinese tradition said to grant longevity or eternal life to those who eat them. They grow in an orchard belonging to Xi Wangmu, the Queen Mother of the West, on a tree that in legend blossoms and bears fruit only once every several thousand years. The immortals were said to gather at her Feast of Peaches to partake of them, and the fruit became a lasting symbol of long life in Chinese art and birthday celebrations.",
"Three_Sovereigns_and_Five_Emperors": "The Three Sovereigns and Five Emperors (三皇五帝), or Sanhuang Wudi, are a group of legendary sage-rulers who in traditional Chinese historiography reigned before the Xia dynasty. The Three Sovereigns are portrayed as demigods or culture heroes who used their powers to introduce fundamental arts such as fire, agriculture, and family life, while the Five Emperors are depicted as morally exemplary rulers of a golden age. They are credited in myth with inventions including writing, silk, medicine, and the calendar, and were long venerated as divine ancestors, though the membership of each list varies among ancient sources.",
"Youchao": "Youchao (有巢) is a legendary figure in ancient Chinese mythology traditionally credited with teaching people to build wooden houses and dwellings. According to accounts such as the Han Feizi, his innovation allowed early humans to shelter themselves and avoid harm from wild animals, and he is counted among the legendary rulers or clans of high antiquity. He is sometimes grouped with figures like Suiren, Fuxi, and Shennong in the sequence of culture-bringing sovereigns.",
"Xingtian": "Xingtian (刑天) is a figure in Chinese mythology who symbolizes indomitable defiance and continued resistance in the face of defeat. In the account preserved in the Classic of Mountains and Seas, he served the Yan Emperor and challenged the supreme god Huangdi for power, and after being beheaded and his head buried on a mountain he refused to yield. His nipples became eyes and his navel a mouth, and he went on brandishing a shield and battle-axe in an endless dance of struggle.",
"Shaohao": "Shaohao (少昊) is a legendary Chinese sovereign usually identified as a son of the Yellow Emperor and counted among the Five Emperors of high antiquity. He is traditionally said to have ruled the Dongyi peoples of eastern China for many years from a capital at Qufu, with legends describing a court whose offices were named after birds. Modern scholarship regards him as a mythological or reconstructed figure, and his tomb site is traditionally located near Qufu in Shandong.",
"Yellow_Dragon": "The Yellow Dragon (黄龙, Huanglong) is, in Chinese religion and mythology, the zoomorphic incarnation of the Yellow Emperor and the ruler of the center of the cosmos. Within the Wuxing system it embodies the element earth and the central direction, and it completes the set of the Four Symbols as a fifth emblem representing the middle. Legend holds that the Yellow Emperor took the form of the Yellow Dragon at the end of his life to ascend to heaven, reinforcing the dragon's later use as a symbol of imperial power.",
"Xihe_(deity)": "Xihe (羲和) is a solar deity in Chinese mythology, described as a wife of the god Di Jun and the mother of ten suns that took the form of three-legged crows dwelling in the mulberry tree Fusang. She also serves as the charioteer of the sun, driving one of the sun birds across the sky each day in her carriage. In the associated myth all ten suns once rose together and scorched the world, until the archer Houyi shot down all but one.",
"Zhu_Bajie": "Zhu Bajie (豬八戒) is one of the three disciples who accompany the monk Tang Sanzang in the sixteenth-century novel Journey to the West. Formerly the heavenly Marshal Tianpeng, he was banished from heaven and reborn as a part-human, part-pig creature after misbehaving, and was later recruited to the pilgrimage by the bodhisattva Guanyin. He is portrayed as gluttonous, lazy, and lustful yet loyal, and at the journey's end is appointed Cleanser of the Altars rather than attaining Buddhahood.",
"Wu_Gang": "Wu Gang (吳剛) is a figure in Chinese folklore who is condemned to endlessly chop down a self-healing tree on the Moon. According to legends dating to at least the Tang dynasty, he sought immortality but was punished for his errors, and each cut he makes into the great cassia or osmanthus tree closes up instantly so that his labour never ends. His story gives rise to the Chinese expression describing futile, ceaseless toil.",
"Pixiu": "Pixiu (貔貅) is a winged hybrid creature of Chinese mythology, typically depicted with the head of a dragon and the body of a lion. It is regarded as an auspicious guardian that draws in wealth from all directions and, because it is said to have no anus, retains everything it consumes, making it a symbol of accumulated fortune. Two forms are distinguished in tradition, the single-horned Tianlu (天祿) and the double-horned Bixie (辟邪), and the creature is widely used as a protective and prosperity emblem.",
"Huli_jing": "The huli jing (狐狸精), or fox spirit, is a shapeshifting creature of Chinese mythology and folklore. Foxes are said to gain magical powers with age, eventually taking human form, often that of a beautiful woman, and the most powerful is the nine-tailed fox that appears in the Classic of Mountains and Seas. Fox spirits hold an ambiguous reputation, appearing at times as auspicious omens and at other times as dangerous, seductive, or man-eating beings.",
"Leigong": "Leigong (雷公), meaning Lord of Thunder, is the god of thunder in Chinese folk religion, mythology, and Taoism. He is depicted as a fearsome figure with claws, bat wings, and a blue bird-beaked face, carrying a drum and mallet to produce thunderclaps and a chisel with which he punishes the guilty and evil spirits when so ordered by heaven. He is often paired with Dianmu, the goddess of lightning, who illuminates his targets so that he strikes only the deserving.",
"Dianmu": "Dianmu (電母), meaning Mother of Lightning, is the goddess of lightning in Chinese mythology and folk religion. She is said to flash a pair of mirrors to send bolts of light across the sky, illuminating the earth so that the thunder god can see his intended targets and spare the innocent. She is regarded as the wife of the thunder god Leigong, with whom she works to produce storms.",
"Danzhu": "Danzhu (丹朱) was, in Chinese legend, the eldest son of the sage-king Yao. According to tradition he was considered unworthy or unruly, so Yao passed over him and chose the virtuous Shun as his successor rather than allow the throne to descend to his own son. He was later granted territory to maintain ancestral sacrifices, and some early texts associate him with the invention or early play of the board game Go.",
"Xiangshuishen": "Xiangshuishen (湘水神) are the goddesses of the Xiang River in Chinese mythology, most often identified as the sisters Ehuang and Nüying, daughters of the sage-king Yao and wives of the sage-king Shun. According to legend, when Shun died the sisters wept along the riverbank, and their tears are said to have permanently stained the local bamboo, giving rise to the spotted variety known as mottled bamboo. They appear in early literature including the Nine Songs of the Chuci anthology, where they are invoked as river deities.",
"Xirang": "Xirang (息壤) is a magical self-expanding soil in Chinese mythology that grows and multiplies on its own without diminishing. In the Great Flood myth it is used to dam and hold back the floodwaters, and one tradition holds that Gun stole it from the supreme deity to fight the flood, an act for which he was executed. Later accounts describe Yu the Great receiving the soil as a divine gift and using it to seal the springs that fed the waters.",
"Xiangliu": "Xiangliu (相柳) is a venomous nine-headed serpent monster of Chinese mythology described in the Classic of Mountains and Seas as a minister of the water deity Gonggong. Its nine heads fed simultaneously from nine mountains, and wherever it rested or was killed the ground turned into foul, poisonous marsh where crops could not grow. Accounts credit its slaying to Yu the Great, who repeatedly dammed the tainted ground until it could be reclaimed.",
"Hebo": "Hebo (河伯), whose name means Lord of the River, is the god of the Yellow River in Chinese mythology and religion. He is often depicted with a human face and the body or tail of a fish, sometimes riding a chariot drawn by dragons, and evidence of his worship appears as early as the Shang dynasty oracle bones. Historical records describe a practice of offering young women as brides to Hebo, a custom that the official Ximen Bao is said to have abolished at Ye during the Warring States period.",
"Wuzhiqi": "Wuzhiqi (無支祁) is a supernatural being of Chinese mythology usually portrayed as a monkey-like water demon dwelling in the Huai River. In the best-known myth he is subdued by Yu the Great during the taming of the floods and imprisoned in chains beneath a mountain to keep the waters calm. The earliest written accounts date to the Tang dynasty, and some scholars have suggested he was an inspiration for the monkey Sun Wukong of Journey to the West.",
"Four_Perils": "The Four Perils (四凶) are four malevolent beings of Chinese mythology, traditionally named as Hundun, Qiongqi, Taowu, and Taotie. According to the Zuo Zhuan they were banished to the four remote corners of the land by the sage-king Shun to ward off evil spirits and hostile powers. Different texts treat them variously as monstrous beasts embodying vices such as chaos and gluttony or as wicked historical persons of noble descent.",
"Taotie": "The Taotie (饕餮) is a mythological creature of ancient China best known as a zoomorphic mask motif on ritual bronze vessels of the Shang and Zhou dynasties. The design is typically a frontally symmetrical face with prominent eyes, horns, and often no lower jaw, appearing frequently on ding cauldrons and other bronzes. The name is associated with gluttony in early texts such as the Zuo Zhuan, and the Taotie is counted among the Four Perils of Chinese mythology.",
"Qiongqi": "Qiongqi (窮奇) is a monstrous creature of Chinese mythology recorded in the Classic of Mountains and Seas and counted among the Four Perils. One description gives it the form of a winged tiger that devours people, while another depicts it as an ox-like beast with coarse, hedgehog-like fur. It is characterized as a perverse being that attacks the honest and loyal while rewarding wrongdoers, embodying moral inversion.",
"Taowu": "Taowu (檮杌) is a monster of Chinese mythology numbered among the Four Perils and described as having a human face, a tiger's legs, a boar's tusks, and a very long tail. It is associated with stubbornness and wild recklessness, and Sima Qian linked the name to an unruly, incorrigible son of the legendary ruler Zhuanxu. The word also came to name an ancient chronicle of the state of Chu, later applied to other historical records as well.",
"Jiaolong": "Jiaolong (蛟龍) is a serpentine dragon of Chinese mythology, often defined as a scaled and sometimes hornless creature associated with rivers, floods, and aquatic realms. Early sources such as the Shuowen Jiezi classify the jiao as a kind of dragon that hatches from eggs, and medieval texts describe it as a large water reptile capable of swallowing a person. It is frequently linked to the waters of southern China and to the Yue peoples of the region.",
"Bashe": "Bashe (巴蛇) is a giant python-like serpent of Chinese mythology said to be large enough to swallow an elephant whole and to expel the bones only after three years. It is mentioned in early classics such as the Chuci and the Classic of Mountains and Seas, where it appears among the marvels of distant lands. In traditional Chinese materia medica its regurgitated elephant bones were credited with medicinal value against ailments of the heart and abdomen.",
"Three_Pure_Ones": "The Three Pure Ones (三清) are the three highest deities of the Taoist pantheon, comprising Yuanshi Tianzun, Lingbao Tianzun, and Daode Tianzun. They are understood as manifestations of the Tao and of primordial cosmic energy, each presiding over one of three celestial heavens known as Jade Purity, Upper Purity, and Grand Purity. In art they are commonly shown as elderly robed figures holding objects such as a pearl, a ruyi scepter, and a fan that signify their roles in creation and cosmic order.",
"Yuanshi_Tianzun": "Yuanshi Tianzun (元始天尊), the Celestial Venerable of the Primordial Beginning, is the foremost of the Three Pure Ones and among the highest deities in Taoism. He is said to have existed from the very origin of the universe as the purest breath, forming Heaven and Earth and presiding over the heaven of Jade Purity. In the vernacular novel Investiture of the Gods he is portrayed as a master dwelling in the Kunlun Mountains who directs the disciple Jiang Ziya.",
"Lingbao_Tianzun": "Lingbao Tianzun (靈寶天尊), the Heavenly Lord of Numinous Treasure, is one of the Three Pure Ones, the supreme trinity of deities in Taoism. He is associated with the Shangqing heaven and is said to govern the present age, mediating between the primordial source and the manifest world. He is frequently invoked in Taoist ritual, including funerary rites in which an emanation known as Taiyi Jiuku Tianzun guides souls toward salvation.",
"Daode_Tianzun": "Daode Tianzun (道德天尊), the Heavenly Lord of the Way and its Virtue, is one of the Three Pure Ones, the highest trinity of deities in Taoism. He is commonly identified with the deified Laozi, the sage traditionally credited with composing the Tao Te Ching, and is also titled Taishang Laojun. Taoist tradition holds that he manifested in many incarnations across the ages to teach living beings and transmit the Way.",
"Lü_Dongbin": "Lü Dongbin (呂洞賓) is among the most widely venerated of the Eight Immortals of Taoism, remembered as a scholar and poet traditionally placed in the Tang dynasty. He is regarded as an early master of neidan, or internal alchemy, and is a patron figure of the Quanzhen school. In art he is typically shown dressed as a scholar and carrying a sword used to dispel evil spirits.",
"Li_Tieguai": "Li Tieguai (李鐵拐), meaning Iron-Crutch Li, is one of the Eight Immortals of Taoism and is associated with medicine and the healing of the sick and needy. He is depicted as an ugly, lame old man leaning on an iron crutch and carrying a calabash gourd that dispenses magical medicine. Legend holds that his spirit once left his body to travel to Heaven, and finding his own corpse destroyed on his return, he entered the body of a dead beggar, which explains his ragged appearance.",
"Sha_Wujing": "Sha Wujing (沙悟淨) is one of the three disciples of the monk Tang Sanzang in the sixteenth-century novel Journey to the West. Once a celestial general, he was banished from Heaven and became a monster dwelling in the Flowing Sands River before the bodhisattva Guanyin recruited him for the pilgrimage. Also called Monk Sha, he serves as the third disciple, carrying the luggage and providing steady, reliable strength on the journey westward.",
"Yue_Lao": "Yue Lao (月下老人), the Old Man under the Moon, is the god of marriage and love in Chinese mythology, portrayed as an elderly matchmaker. He is said to bind predestined couples together with a red silken cord, after which their eventual union cannot be prevented. He is traditionally described as dwelling in the moon or in obscure celestial regions, and his name gives rise to the enduring motif of the red thread of fate.",
"Zhongli_Quan": "Zhongli Quan (鍾離權) is one of the Eight Immortals of Taoism and is often regarded as the eldest and leader among them. He is commonly depicted as a stout, bare-bellied figure wielding a large feather fan said to revive the dead and to transmute stone into silver or gold. He is also known as Han Zhongli because he was traditionally said to have been born during the Han dynasty.",
"Rhine": "The Rhine is one of the major rivers of Europe, rising in the Swiss Alps and flowing generally northward for about 1,230 kilometres before entering the North Sea in the Netherlands. It passes through or along Switzerland, Liechtenstein, Austria, Germany, France, and the Netherlands, forming part of several international borders. Historically it served as a frontier of the Roman Empire and remains one of the busiest inland waterways in the world for freight transport.",
"Zambezi": "The Zambezi is the fourth-longest river in Africa, running about 2,574 kilometres from its source in northwestern Zambia to its mouth on the Indian Ocean in Mozambique. It flows through or along Zambia, Angola, Namibia, Botswana, Zimbabwe, and Mozambique, and its most famous feature is Victoria Falls. The river is dammed at Kariba and Cahora Bassa, providing hydroelectric power to the surrounding region.",
"Mekong": "The Mekong is the longest river in Southeast Asia, flowing roughly 4,900 kilometres from the Tibetan Plateau through China, Myanmar, Laos, Thailand, Cambodia, and Vietnam before reaching the South China Sea. It supports one of the world's most productive inland fisheries and its delta is a major rice-growing region. The river's flow is heavily influenced by monsoon seasons and by a growing number of hydroelectric dams along its course.",
"Irrawaddy_River": "The Irrawaddy is the principal river of Myanmar, formed by the confluence of the N'mai and Mali rivers in the north and flowing about 2,170 kilometres southward to the Andaman Sea. Its drainage basin covers a large majority of the country, and its fertile delta is a central rice-producing region. The river has served as the country's main commercial waterway and transport artery for many centuries.",
"Amazon_River": "The Amazon is the largest river in the world by discharge of water, carrying more flow than the next several largest rivers combined and accounting for roughly a fifth of global river discharge into the oceans. It rises in the Andes of Peru and flows generally eastward through Peru, Colombia, and Brazil before emptying into the Atlantic Ocean. Its vast basin contains the Amazon rainforest, the largest tropical forest on Earth.",
"Río_de_la_Plata": "The Río de la Plata is a wide estuary on the southeastern coast of South America, formed where the Paraná and Uruguay rivers meet and flow into the Atlantic Ocean. It forms part of the border between Argentina and Uruguay and reaches a maximum width of about 220 kilometres, making it among the widest such waterways in the world. Its shores are home to the major port cities of Buenos Aires and Montevideo.",
"Red_Sea": "The Red Sea is a narrow inlet of the Indian Ocean lying between northeastern Africa and the Arabian Peninsula. It connects to the Mediterranean Sea in the north through the Suez Canal and to the Gulf of Aden in the south through the strait of Bab-el-Mandeb, making it a vital shipping route between Europe and Asia. The sea is known for its warm, highly saline waters and its extensive coral reefs.",
"Baltic_Sea": "The Baltic Sea is a shallow, brackish arm of the Atlantic Ocean in Northern Europe, nearly enclosed by land and connected to the North Sea through the Danish straits. It is bordered by Denmark, Germany, Poland, Lithuania, Latvia, Estonia, Russia, Finland, and Sweden. Its low salinity results from heavy freshwater inflow from surrounding rivers and limited exchange with the open ocean.",
"Arabian_Sea": "The Arabian Sea is a region of the northern Indian Ocean bounded by the Arabian Peninsula to the west, the Horn of Africa to the southwest, Pakistan and Iran to the north, and India to the east. It contains important shipping lanes linking India and East Asia with Europe through the Gulf of Aden and the Red Sea. Major inlets include the Gulf of Oman and the Gulf of Aden, and it receives the outflow of the Indus River.",
"Gulf_of_Aden": "The Gulf of Aden is an arm of the Indian Ocean lying between Yemen on the Arabian Peninsula to the north and Somalia and the Horn of Africa to the south. It connects to the Red Sea in the west through the strait of Bab-el-Mandeb and opens into the Arabian Sea to the east. As part of the route between the Mediterranean and the Indian Ocean, it is one of the world's busiest and most strategic shipping corridors.",
"Gulf_of_Oman": "The Gulf of Oman is a strait-like arm of the Arabian Sea that connects it to the Strait of Hormuz and the Persian Gulf to the northwest. It lies between Oman and the United Arab Emirates on its southern shore and Iran and Pakistan on its northern shore. The gulf is a critical passage for the transport of oil from the Persian Gulf to the wider Indian Ocean.",
"Gulf_of_Mexico": "The Gulf of Mexico is a large oceanic basin and marginal sea of the Atlantic Ocean, bordered by the United States, Mexico, and Cuba. It connects to the Atlantic through the Straits of Florida and to the Caribbean Sea through the Yucatán Channel. The gulf receives the outflow of many rivers, most notably the Mississippi, and holds significant offshore petroleum and fishery resources.",
"Mozambique_Channel": "The Mozambique Channel is a stretch of the Indian Ocean separating the island of Madagascar from mainland Africa, bordered chiefly by Mozambique to the west. It is roughly 1,700 kilometres long and around 400 kilometres wide at its narrowest, and it carries the warm southward-flowing Mozambique Current. The channel has long served as a maritime route along the East African coast.",
"Strait_of_Malacca": "The Strait of Malacca is a narrow waterway between the Malay Peninsula and the Indonesian island of Sumatra, linking the Andaman Sea of the Indian Ocean with the South China Sea of the Pacific. Roughly 900 kilometres long, it is the main shipping channel between the Indian and Pacific oceans and one of the busiest straits in the world. Its narrowness makes it a strategic maritime chokepoint through which a large share of global trade passes.",
"Drake_Passage": "The Drake Passage is the body of water between Cape Horn at the southern tip of South America and the South Shetland Islands off Antarctica, connecting the Atlantic and Pacific oceans. It is the narrowest gap around the Antarctic continent, and the Antarctic Circumpolar Current flows through it unimpeded by any land. The passage is notorious for extremely rough seas and powerful winds.",
"Deccan_Plateau": "The Deccan Plateau is a large elevated region occupying much of southern and central India, lying between the Eastern and Western Ghats mountain ranges. Much of it is formed of ancient volcanic basalt known as the Deccan Traps, and it is drained by major eastward-flowing rivers such as the Godavari and Krishna. The plateau has been home to a succession of powerful kingdoms and empires throughout Indian history.",
"Maghreb": "The Maghreb is the western region of North Africa, generally comprising Morocco, Algeria, Tunisia, Libya, Mauritania, and the disputed territory of Western Sahara. It lies between the Mediterranean Sea to the north, the Atlantic Ocean to the west, and the Sahara Desert to the south, with the Atlas Mountains crossing its northern portion. The name derives from an Arabic word meaning the place of sunset or the west.",
"Iberian_Peninsula": "The Iberian Peninsula is a landmass in the southwestern corner of Europe, separated from the rest of the continent by the Pyrenees mountains and bordered by the Atlantic Ocean and the Mediterranean Sea. It is occupied chiefly by Spain and Portugal, along with Andorra, Gibraltar, and a small part of France. Its southern tip is separated from Africa by the narrow Strait of Gibraltar.",
"Arabian_Peninsula": "The Arabian Peninsula is a large peninsula in Western Asia, bordered by the Red Sea, the Arabian Sea, the Gulf of Aden, the Gulf of Oman, and the Persian Gulf. It contains Saudi Arabia, Yemen, Oman, the United Arab Emirates, Qatar, Bahrain, and Kuwait, and is dominated by vast deserts including the Rub' al Khali. The region holds a substantial share of the world's petroleum reserves and is the birthplace of Islam.",
"Horn_of_Africa": "The Horn of Africa is a large peninsula and geopolitical region in the easternmost part of mainland Africa, extending into the Arabian Sea and the Gulf of Aden. It comprises Ethiopia, Eritrea, Djibouti, and Somalia, and is also known as the Somali Peninsula. Its position along major maritime routes near the Red Sea and the Bab-el-Mandeb strait has long made it strategically important for trade and navigation.",
"Sahel": "The Sahel is a semi-arid transitional belt of savanna and grassland stretching across Africa between the Sahara to the north and the wetter tropical savannas to the south. It runs roughly from the Atlantic Ocean to the Red Sea, crossing parts of countries including Senegal, Mauritania, Mali, Niger, Chad, and Sudan. Its name comes from an Arabic word meaning shore or coast, evoking the southern edge of the desert.",
"Western_Sahara": "Western Sahara is a sparsely populated territory of desert and coastline in northwestern Africa, bordered by Morocco, Algeria, Mauritania, and the Atlantic Ocean. Formerly a Spanish colony until 1975, it is a disputed territory whose sovereignty is contested between Morocco, which controls most of it, and the Polisario Front, which proclaims the Sahrawi Arab Democratic Republic. The United Nations lists it as a non-self-governing territory, and a promised referendum on its status has never taken place.",
"South_Caucasus": "The South Caucasus, also called Transcaucasia, is a region straddling the southern Caucasus Mountains between the Black Sea and the Caspian Sea. It is generally understood to comprise Armenia, Azerbaijan, and Georgia, lying at the crossroads of Eastern Europe and Western Asia. The area has historically been contested by the Persian, Ottoman, and Russian empires, and its modern states gained independence after the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991.",
"Southern_Cone": "The Southern Cone is a geographical and cultural subregion of South America made up of the southernmost areas of the continent, mostly south of the Tropic of Capricorn. It is traditionally understood to include Argentina, Chile, and Uruguay, and is sometimes extended to Paraguay and southern Brazil. The region is bounded by the Pacific Ocean to the west and the Atlantic Ocean to the east and narrows toward the tip of the continent.",
"Melanesia": "Melanesia is a subregion of Oceania in the southwestern Pacific Ocean, extending from New Guinea eastward to Fiji. It includes the countries of Papua New Guinea, the Solomon Islands, Vanuatu, and Fiji, along with the French territory of New Caledonia and other islands. The name derives from Greek words meaning black islands, historically applied by Europeans in reference to the appearance of the region's inhabitants.",
"Polynesia": "Polynesia is a large grouping of over a thousand islands scattered across the central and southern Pacific Ocean, forming a subregion of Oceania. Its outer boundaries are often described as a triangle whose corners are Hawaii, New Zealand, and Easter Island, encompassing peoples such as the Hawaiians, Maori, Samoans, Tahitians, and Tongans. The name comes from Greek words meaning many islands, and the region shares closely related Austronesian languages and seafaring traditions.",
"Oceania": "Oceania is a geographic region comprising Australia, New Guinea, New Zealand, and the many island groups of the tropical Pacific Ocean. It is commonly divided into the subregions of Australasia, Melanesia, Micronesia, and Polynesia, spanning a vast area of ocean with a relatively small total land area. It is often treated as one of the world's continental regions and contains a wide diversity of peoples, languages, and environments.",
"Micronesia": "Micronesia is a subregion of Oceania made up of thousands of small islands in the western Pacific Ocean, north of the equator and Melanesia. It includes the Federated States of Micronesia, Palau, the Marshall Islands, Kiribati, Nauru, and Guam and the Northern Mariana Islands. The name derives from Greek words meaning small islands, reflecting the tiny size of most of its coral atolls and volcanic islands.",
"Siberia": "Siberia is a vast region of northern Asia extending from the Ural Mountains eastward to the Pacific Ocean and southward from the Arctic Ocean to the borders of Kazakhstan, Mongolia, and China. It makes up the greater part of Russia's territory and is known for its harsh, cold climate, extensive forests known as taiga, and sparse population. Rich in natural resources such as timber, oil, gas, and minerals, it was gradually incorporated into the Russian state from the late sixteenth century onward.",
"Crimea": "Crimea is a peninsula on the northern coast of the Black Sea, connected to the mainland by the narrow Isthmus of Perekop and nearly enclosing the Sea of Azov. Historically home to Greeks, Scythians, Tatars, and others, it was long part of the Crimean Khanate before annexation by the Russian Empire in 1783. In 2014 it was annexed by Russia from Ukraine, an act that most of the international community does not recognize.",
"West_Indies": "The West Indies is a region of the North Atlantic Ocean comprising the islands of the Caribbean, including the Greater Antilles, the Lesser Antilles, and the Lucayan Archipelago. It stretches in an arc from near Florida and the Gulf of Mexico toward the coast of northern South America, separating the Caribbean Sea from the open Atlantic. The name arose from the European belief on first contact that these islands lay near the Indies of Asia.",
"African_Great_Lakes": "The African Great Lakes are a series of large lakes lying within and around the East African Rift, in the eastern part of the continent. They include Lake Victoria, the largest tropical lake in the world, along with Lake Tanganyika, Lake Malawi, and several others, together holding a substantial share of the planet's surface fresh water. The surrounding region is densely populated and includes parts of countries such as Tanzania, Uganda, Kenya, Rwanda, Burundi, and the Democratic Republic of the Congo.",
"Bengal": "Bengal is a geographical and ethnolinguistic region in South Asia lying north of the Bay of Bengal and covering much of the Ganges-Brahmaputra delta. Today it is divided between the independent nation of Bangladesh in the east and the Indian state of West Bengal in the west. Defined largely by the Bengali language and a shared cultural heritage, it has historically been a center of trade, learning, literature, and the arts.",
"Punjab": "Punjab is a geographical and cultural region in the northwestern part of the Indian subcontinent, named for its five rivers, tributaries of the Indus. Following the partition of British India in 1947, it was divided between Pakistan, which holds the larger western Punjab province, and India, whose eastern portion forms the state of Punjab and neighboring areas. The region is known for its fertile plains, intensive agriculture, and the Punjabi language and Sikh, Muslim, and Hindu communities.",
"Kashmir": "Kashmir is a mountainous region in the northwestern part of the Indian subcontinent, encompassing the Kashmir Valley, surrounding Himalayan ranges, and neighboring highlands. Since the partition of British India in 1947 it has been divided and disputed among India, Pakistan, and China, each of which administers part of the territory. The region is known for its lakes, alpine scenery, and a long history as a center of learning and of Hindu, Buddhist, and Islamic culture.",
"Great_Rift_Valley": "The Great Rift Valley is a series of connected geological trenches and faults running roughly north to south for thousands of kilometers, from the Middle East through East Africa. Formed by the tectonic pulling apart of the Earth's crust, it contains volcanoes, deep lakes, and escarpments and is associated with numerous fossil discoveries of early humans and their ancestors. In Africa it splits into eastern and western branches around Lake Victoria and holds many of the African Great Lakes.",
"Namib_Desert": "The Namib is a coastal desert in southern Africa stretching along the Atlantic coastline, chiefly through Namibia and into Angola and South Africa. Considered one of the oldest deserts in the world, it is known for its towering red sand dunes, gravel plains, and frequent coastal fog that sustains specialized plants and animals. The country of Namibia takes its name from this desert, whose name means vast place in the Khoekhoe language.",
"Hispaniola": "Hispaniola is an island in the Greater Antilles of the Caribbean Sea, the second largest island in the West Indies after Cuba. It is divided between two sovereign countries, the Dominican Republic occupying the eastern portion and Haiti the western. First reached by Christopher Columbus in 1492, it became an early center of Spanish colonization in the Americas and later saw French control of its western part.",
"Borneo": "Borneo is the third-largest island in the world, located in Southeast Asia and surrounded by the seas of the western Pacific and eastern Indian Oceans. It is divided politically among three countries: Malaysia and Brunei in the north, and Indonesia, which controls the majority of the island as Kalimantan, in the south. The island is covered by extensive tropical rainforest and is home to great biodiversity, including orangutans and the Rafflesia flower.",
"New_Guinea": "New Guinea is the world's second-largest island, situated in the southwestern Pacific Ocean just north of Australia. It is divided along a north-south line between Indonesia, which governs the western half as the provinces of Papua, and the independent nation of Papua New Guinea in the east. The island is known for its rugged mountainous interior, dense rainforest, and exceptional cultural and linguistic diversity, with hundreds of distinct languages spoken.",
"Canary_Islands": "The Canary Islands are a Spanish archipelago in the Atlantic Ocean off the northwestern coast of Africa. Composed of eight main volcanic islands including Tenerife and Gran Canaria, they form an autonomous community of Spain and one of its outermost regions. The islands have a mild subtropical climate and their highest point is Mount Teide, a volcano that is the tallest peak in all of Spain.",
"Easter_Island": "Easter Island is a remote volcanic island in the southeastern Pacific Ocean, forming a special territory of Chile. It is famous for its nearly 900 monumental stone statues called moai, carved by the Rapa Nui people between roughly the 13th and 16th centuries. Lying more than 3,500 kilometres from the coast of South America, it is one of the most isolated inhabited places on Earth.",
"Kuril_Islands": "The Kuril Islands are a volcanic archipelago of 56 islands stretching about 1,300 kilometres between Japan's Hokkaido and Russia's Kamchatka Peninsula. They separate the Sea of Okhotsk from the Pacific Ocean and are administered by Russia as part of Sakhalin Oblast. Japan claims the four southernmost islands, which it calls the Northern Territories, and this territorial dispute has kept the two countries from signing a formal peace treaty after World War II.",
"Cape_of_Good_Hope": "The Cape of Good Hope is a rocky headland on the Atlantic coast of the Cape Peninsula in South Africa. First rounded by Portuguese navigator Bartolomeu Dias in 1488, it became a key landmark on the sea route from Europe to Asia around the southern tip of Africa. Though often popularly regarded as the meeting point of the Atlantic and Indian Oceans, the southernmost point of the African continent is actually Cape Agulhas to its southeast.",
"Chagos_Archipelago": "The Chagos Archipelago is a group of seven atolls comprising more than sixty islands in the central Indian Ocean, south of the Maldives. Administered by the United Kingdom as the British Indian Ocean Territory, its sovereignty is claimed by Mauritius, and international courts have found the UK administration unlawful. Its largest island, Diego Garcia, hosts a major joint UK-US military base, and the original Chagossian inhabitants were forcibly removed between 1967 and 1973.",
"Bantu_peoples": "The Bantu peoples are a large grouping of several hundred Indigenous African ethnic groups who speak Bantu languages, a branch of the Niger-Congo family. They inhabit a vast region covering much of Central, East, and Southern Africa, and number in the hundreds of millions. Their present distribution resulted from the Bantu expansion, a series of migrations that began several thousand years ago from the Cameroon-Nigeria region and spread across the southern half of the continent.",
"Fula_people": "The Fula are one of the largest ethnic groups in the Sahel and West Africa, dispersed across a wide belt from Senegal and Guinea to Sudan and beyond. Traditionally a pastoralist and trading people, many Fula historically herded cattle across the savanna, while others settled in towns as scholars and traders. They played a major role in spreading Islam in West Africa and founded several states and jihadist caliphates, including the Sokoto Caliphate in the 19th century.",
"Yoruba_people": "The Yoruba are an ethnic group native to southwestern Nigeria and parts of Benin and Togo in West Africa. They speak the Yoruba language, a member of the Niger-Congo family, and number well over forty million people. Their history includes powerful city-states and kingdoms such as Ife and Oyo, a rich tradition of art and bronze casting, and a religion whose deities, the orishas, spread widely to the Americas through the Atlantic slave trade.",
"Zulu_people": "The Zulu are a Bantu ethnic group of Southern Africa and the largest ethnic group in South Africa, concentrated in the province of KwaZulu-Natal. They speak isiZulu, a Bantu language, and number roughly twelve million people. Under the leadership of Shaka in the early 19th century they built a powerful and militarily organized kingdom, which later fought the Anglo-Zulu War against the British Empire in 1879.",
"Akan_people": "The Akan are an ethnic group living primarily in Ghana and parts of Ivory Coast in West Africa, speaking languages of the Tano branch of the Niger-Congo family. They are organized around a matrilineal clan system and include subgroups such as the Asante, Fante, and Akyem. Over the centuries the Akan founded a number of states and empires, most notably the Asante Empire, which became a dominant power in the region during the 18th and 19th centuries.",
"Boer": "The Boers are descendants of Dutch, German, and French Huguenot colonists who settled at the Cape of Good Hope from the 17th century onward, and their name comes from the Dutch word for farmer. They developed a distinct frontier culture centred on cattle farming and a Calvinist Protestant faith, and their language evolved into Afrikaans. In the 1830s many undertook the Great Trek into the interior to escape British rule, establishing independent republics such as the Transvaal and the Orange Free State.",
"Rajput": "The Rajputs are a large patrilineal community and caste grouping from northern and western India, historically associated with warfare, land ownership, and princely rule. Emerging as a prominent martial class from around the 6th to 12th centuries, they governed numerous kingdoms and princely states, especially in the region of Rajasthan. They are noted for their codes of honour, their fortified palaces and citadels, and their long resistance to and eventual accommodation with later Muslim and British powers.",
"Manchu_people": "The Manchu are an ethnic group from Manchuria in northeastern Asia, originally a Tungusic-speaking people descended from the earlier Jurchens. Under the leadership of Nurhaci and his successors in the early 17th century they were unified and organized into the Eight Banners military system. In 1644 they conquered China and established the Qing dynasty, ruling the empire until its fall in 1912, after which many assimilated into the surrounding Han population.",
"Khmer_people": "The Khmer are the majority ethnic group of Cambodia, also present in adjacent parts of Thailand and Vietnam, and they speak the Khmer language, an Austroasiatic tongue. Their civilization reached its height under the medieval Khmer Empire, which built the vast temple complex of Angkor. Predominantly Theravada Buddhist, the Khmer have a rich heritage of art, dance, and monumental architecture rooted in that classical period.",
"Malays_(ethnic_group)": "The Malays are an Austronesian ethnic group native to the Malay Peninsula, eastern Sumatra, and coastal Borneo in Southeast Asia. They speak the Malay language and are predominantly Muslim, with a maritime and trading heritage shaped by centuries of contact across the region. Historically organized into sultanates such as Malacca, they form the majority population of Malaysia and Brunei and a significant part of Indonesia and Singapore.",
"Swahili_people": "The Swahili are a Bantu ethnic group inhabiting the coast of East Africa, from southern Somalia through Kenya and Tanzania to northern Mozambique, as well as offshore islands such as Zanzibar. They speak the Swahili language and their culture emerged from centuries of trade linking the African interior with the wider Indian Ocean world of Arabia, Persia, and India. Predominantly Muslim, they built a string of prosperous coastal city-states and trading towns during the medieval period.",
"Mughal_Empire": "The Mughal Empire was an early modern empire that ruled much of the Indian subcontinent from the 16th to the 19th centuries. It was founded in 1526 by Babur, a Central Asian prince of Turco-Mongol descent, who defeated the Delhi Sultanate at the First Battle of Panipat. Reaching its cultural and territorial peak under emperors such as Akbar, Shah Jahan, and Aurangzeb, it fused Persian and Indian traditions and left monuments such as the Taj Mahal before declining and being abolished by the British in 1857.",
"Maratha_Empire": "The Maratha Empire was an early modern Indian state that rose in the western Deccan under the Maratha warrior Shivaji, who was crowned sovereign in 1674. After his death it evolved into a decentralized confederacy of powerful chiefs led by the Peshwa, a hereditary prime minister, and expanded across much of the Indian subcontinent during the eighteenth century. Its power waned after defeats by Afghan and later British forces, and it was dissolved following the Third Anglo-Maratha War in 1818.",
"Vijayanagara_Empire": "The Vijayanagara Empire was a South Indian state founded in 1336 that governed the Deccan and peninsular south from its capital at Vijayanagara on the Tungabhadra River. It became a major regional power, patronizing Hindu temple architecture, literature, and long-distance trade, and its ruins at Hampi are a UNESCO World Heritage Site. Weakened by a coalition of Deccan sultanates that defeated it at the Battle of Talikota in 1565, the empire declined and fragmented over the following century.",
"Bahmani_Kingdom": "The Bahmani Kingdom was a Persianate Muslim state founded in 1347 that ruled the Deccan Plateau of India from capitals at Gulbarga and later Bidar. It was the first independent Islamic sultanate in the Deccan and became known for its Indo-Islamic architecture, Persian cultural influence, and long rivalry with the neighbouring Vijayanagara Empire. During the late fifteenth and early sixteenth centuries it fragmented into five successor states collectively known as the Deccan sultanates, and it formally dissolved in 1527.",
"Kingdom_of_Mysore": "The Kingdom of Mysore was a state in southern India ruled for most of its history by the Wodeyar dynasty, traditionally dated from 1399 and centred on the city of Mysore. In the later eighteenth century it grew into a formidable power under the military commanders Hyder Ali and his son Tipu Sultan, who fought a series of wars against the British East India Company. After Tipu Sultan's defeat in 1799 the Wodeyars were restored as rulers under British suzerainty, and the state persisted until it was integrated into independent India in 1947.",
"Toungoo_dynasty": "The Toungoo dynasty was a ruling house of Burma founded at the town of Taungoo in 1510 that went on to unify much of the region under a single crown. At its height in the sixteenth century it built one of the largest empires in the history of Southeast Asia, extending its authority over neighbouring kingdoms and peoples. Weakened by rebellions and warfare, the dynasty was overthrown when its capital fell in 1752.",
"Ayutthaya_Kingdom": "The Ayutthaya Kingdom was a Thai state founded in 1351 and centred on the island city of Ayutthaya in the Chao Phraya valley of present-day Thailand. Known to foreign traders as Siam, it became a wealthy cosmopolitan power that controlled much of mainland Southeast Asia and maintained commercial and diplomatic ties with Europe, China, Japan, and Persia. The kingdom endured for more than four centuries before its capital was destroyed by Burmese armies in 1767.",
"Khmer_Empire": "The Khmer Empire was a powerful state in mainland Southeast Asia that dominated much of the region from the early ninth century, with its heartland in present-day Cambodia. Centred on the city of Angkor, it built vast temple complexes such as Angkor Wat and Angkor Thom and developed extensive irrigation and hydraulic systems to support a large population. The empire gradually declined through internal strain and external pressure, and its capital was abandoned as a royal centre in the fifteenth century.",
"Mali_Empire": "The Mali Empire was a West African state that rose in the thirteenth century in the upper Niger region and grew into one of the largest and wealthiest empires of medieval Africa. Its economy rested on control of trans-Saharan trade in gold, salt, and other goods, and its ruler Mansa Musa became famous for a lavish pilgrimage to Mecca. Cities such as Timbuktu flourished as centres of Islamic learning and commerce before the empire fragmented and declined in the later medieval period.",
"Kilwa_Sultanate": "The Kilwa Sultanate was a medieval Swahili state centred on the island of Kilwa Kisiwani off the coast of present-day Tanzania. From around the tenth century it grew wealthy by controlling Indian Ocean trade in gold, ivory, and other goods, extending its influence over numerous coastal towns as far south as Sofala. Its prosperity declined after the arrival of the Portuguese in the early sixteenth century, who seized and weakened the port.",
"Sokoto_Caliphate": "The Sokoto Caliphate was a large Islamic state in West Africa founded in 1804 by the scholar and reformer Usman dan Fodio through a religious and military movement against the Hausa kingdoms. Organized as a federation of emirates under a central caliph based at Sokoto, it became one of the most populous and powerful states in nineteenth-century Africa, spanning parts of present-day Nigeria, Niger, and Cameroon. The caliphate was conquered and absorbed by European colonial powers, chiefly Britain, by 1903.",
"Merina_Kingdom": "The Merina Kingdom was a state in the central highlands of Madagascar that expanded from the late eighteenth century to control most of the island. Under King Andrianampoinimerina and his successors it built a centralized administration from its capital at Antananarivo and unified much of Madagascar under a single monarchy. The kingdom was conquered by France, which abolished the monarchy and made the island a colony in the 1890s.",
"Congo_Free_State": "The Congo Free State was a large state in Central Africa that existed from 1885 to 1908 as the private domain of King Leopold II of Belgium rather than a colony of the Belgian state. Administered to extract rubber and ivory, it became notorious for a brutal system of forced labour that caused mass suffering and a severe decline in the region's population. International outcry over these atrocities led Belgium to annex the territory in 1908, replacing it with the Belgian Congo.",
"Kingdom_of_the_Two_Sicilies": "The Kingdom of the Two Sicilies was a state in southern Italy formed in 1816 by the union of the kingdoms of Naples and Sicily under the House of Bourbon. Covering the Italian mainland south of the Papal States as well as the island of Sicily, it was the most populous of the pre-unification Italian states. It was conquered during the Italian unification movement and annexed into the emerging Kingdom of Italy in 1861.",
"Crown_of_Aragon": "The Crown of Aragon was a composite monarchy in the western Mediterranean that arose in the twelfth century from the dynastic union of the Kingdom of Aragon and the County of Barcelona. Under a shared sovereign it came to include territories such as Valencia, the Balearic Islands, Sardinia, Sicily, and Naples, and its merchants dominated Mediterranean trade. It was joined to the Crown of Castile through the marriage of Ferdinand and Isabella, and its separate institutions were abolished in the early eighteenth century.",
"Hanseatic_League": "The Hanseatic League was a commercial and defensive confederation of merchant guilds and market towns across northern Europe that flourished from the late medieval period. Centred on cities such as Lübeck, Hamburg, and Bremen, it dominated trade around the Baltic and North Seas, maintaining trading posts and privileges from London to Novgorod. The league gradually lost influence from the sixteenth century as rising territorial states and shifting trade routes eroded its power.",
"Old_Swiss_Confederacy": "The Old Swiss Confederacy was a loose alliance of self-governing cantons in the Alpine region that grew from a defensive pact traditionally dated to 1291. Over the following centuries it expanded through further alliances and military victories, gaining effective independence from the Holy Roman Empire while remaining a decentralized union of city and rural states. It endured until it was overrun by French forces and reorganized into the centralized Helvetic Republic in 1798.",
"German_Confederation": "The German Confederation was an association of German-speaking states established in 1815 by the Congress of Vienna to replace the dissolved Holy Roman Empire. It linked dozens of sovereign kingdoms, duchies, and free cities in a loose union led by Austria, with a federal assembly meeting at Frankfurt, but it had little central authority. Rivalry between Austria and Prussia culminated in a war in 1866, after which the confederation was dissolved and replaced by Prussian-led German unification.",
"Prussia": "Prussia was a German state that grew from the Duchy of Prussia and the Margraviate of Brandenburg into a major European power ruled by the Hohenzollern dynasty. Proclaimed a kingdom in 1701 and expanded through the military and administrative reforms of rulers such as Frederick the Great, it became the dominant force behind the unification of Germany in 1871. After the First World War it continued as the largest state within Germany until it was formally abolished in 1947.",
"Dutch_Republic": "The Dutch Republic was a confederal state in the northern Low Countries that emerged from the revolt of seven provinces against Spanish Habsburg rule in the late sixteenth century. Governed by provincial assemblies and a central States General rather than a monarch, it became a leading maritime, commercial, and financial power during its seventeenth-century Golden Age, with a global trading network run through chartered companies. The republic ended when it was overrun by French revolutionary armies and replaced by the Batavian Republic in 1795.",
"Papal_States": "The Papal States were a group of territories in central Italy under the direct sovereign rule of the pope from the 8th century until 1870. At their height they covered much of Lazio, Umbria, the Marche, and Romagna, governed from Rome as a temporal monarchy alongside the pope's spiritual authority. They were absorbed into the newly unified Kingdom of Italy after Italian forces captured Rome in 1870, ending papal temporal power until the creation of Vatican City in 1929.",
"Safavid_Iran": "Safavid Iran was a Persian empire founded in 1501 by Shah Ismail I, who established Twelver Shia Islam as the state religion across his realm. At its peak it ruled all of present-day Iran along with parts of the Caucasus, Mesopotamia, and Central Asia, governing from capitals at Tabriz, Qazvin, and later Isfahan. The dynasty declined in the early 18th century and effectively ended in the 1720s–1730s amid Afghan invasion and the rise of Nader Shah.",
"House_of_Bourbon": "The House of Bourbon is a European royal dynasty that branched from the Capetian line and first took the French throne with Henry IV in 1589. Its members ruled France until the Revolution and again during the Restoration, and branches came to reign in Spain, Naples, Sicily, Parma, and Luxembourg. Bourbon monarchs continue to reign in Spain and Luxembourg today.",
"House_of_Habsburg": "The House of Habsburg was one of the most prominent royal dynasties of Europe, taking its name from Habsburg Castle in present-day Switzerland and centring its power on Vienna. Its members held the Holy Roman Empire almost continuously from 1440 to 1806 and ruled Austria, Bohemia, Hungary, Spain, and extensive overseas possessions. The dynasty split into Spanish and Austrian branches, the latter continuing as Habsburg-Lorraine until the fall of the monarchy in 1918.",
"House_of_Savoy": "The House of Savoy is a dynasty founded around 1003 in the Alpine region of Savoy between France and Italy. Over the centuries it advanced from counts and dukes of Savoy to kings of Sardinia, expanding its lands in northwestern Italy. Its rulers led the unification of Italy and reigned as kings of the united country from 1861 until a 1946 referendum established the Italian Republic.",
"House_of_Medici": "The House of Medici was an Italian banking family and political dynasty that rose to dominance in Florence during the 15th century. Enriched by the Medici Bank, its members effectively ruled the Florentine republic and later held the title of Grand Duke of Tuscany, while becoming celebrated patrons of Renaissance art and learning. The family produced four popes and two queens of France before dying out in the male line in 1737.",
"Asante_Empire": "The Asante Empire was a West African state founded around 1701 by the Akan-speaking Asante people in the forest region of present-day Ghana. Centred on its capital Kumasi and unified by the symbol of the Golden Stool, it grew into a powerful and wealthy kingdom that expanded into parts of modern Ivory Coast and Togo. After a series of wars with Britain it was annexed to the Gold Coast colony in 1902, though the Asante kingship survives as a traditional institution within Ghana.",
"Zulu_Kingdom": "The Zulu Kingdom was a southern African state established in the 1810s by Shaka kaSenzangakhona, who unified numerous chiefdoms in the region of present-day KwaZulu-Natal, South Africa. It became a formidable military power through reorganized age-regiment armies and new tactics, extending along the Indian Ocean coast between the Tugela and Pongola rivers. The kingdom was defeated by Britain in the Anglo-Zulu War of 1879 and subsequently absorbed into colonial rule.",
"Cape_Colony": "The Cape Colony was a settlement and later colony at the southern tip of Africa, in the region of present-day South Africa. It was founded in 1652 by the Dutch East India Company as a resupply station at the Cape of Good Hope and passed permanently into British hands in the early 19th century. It expanded inland over the following decades and in 1910 became the Cape Province of the newly formed Union of South Africa.",
"Congress_of_Vienna": "The Congress of Vienna was a conference of European powers held in the Austrian capital in 1814 and 1815 to settle affairs after the defeat of Napoleon. Guided by figures such as the Austrian statesman Metternich, it redrew the map of Europe, restored many former ruling houses, and sought to establish a durable balance of power. Its settlement shaped European diplomacy for much of the 19th century and inaugurated the Concert of Europe.",
"War_of_the_Spanish_Succession": "The War of the Spanish Succession was a major European conflict fought from 1701 to 1714 over who would inherit the throne of Spain after the childless Charles II. A coalition led by Austria, Britain, and the Dutch Republic opposed the accession of a Bourbon claimant backed by France, fearing a union of the French and Spanish crowns. The war ended with the Peace of Utrecht and related treaties, which confirmed a Bourbon on the Spanish throne while barring a merger of the two kingdoms and redistributing Spanish territories.",
"Acts_of_Union_1707": "The Acts of Union 1707 were two parallel acts passed by the parliaments of England and Scotland that merged the two kingdoms into a single state, the Kingdom of Great Britain. Taking effect on 1 May 1707, they created a shared parliament at Westminster while preserving Scotland's separate legal system and established church. The two countries had shared a monarch since 1603, but this union combined them into one political entity.",
"League_of_Nations": "The League of Nations was an international organization founded in 1920 in the aftermath of the First World War to promote collective security and prevent future conflicts. Headquartered in Geneva, it provided a forum for arbitration, oversaw mandated territories, and coordinated cooperation on health, labour, and other issues. Weakened by the absence of major powers and its failure to halt aggression in the 1930s, it was formally dissolved in 1946, its role passing to the newly founded United Nations.",
"United_Nations": "The United Nations is an intergovernmental organization founded in 1945 to maintain international peace and security, foster cooperation among states, and uphold human rights. Established by its founding charter after the Second World War, it includes nearly every sovereign state and is headquartered in New York City. Its principal organs include the General Assembly, the Security Council, and the Secretariat led by the Secretary-General.",
"Napoleonic_Wars": "The Napoleonic Wars were a series of conflicts fought between 1803 and 1815 that pitted the French Empire under Napoleon Bonaparte against shifting coalitions of European powers. French armies achieved sweeping victories and dominated much of continental Europe before disastrous campaigns, notably the 1812 invasion of Russia, reversed their fortunes. The wars ended with Napoleon's final defeat at Waterloo in 1815 and reshaped the borders and politics of Europe.",
"Peace_of_Westphalia": "The Peace of Westphalia was a series of treaties signed in 1648 in the German cities of Osnabrück and Münster that ended the Thirty Years' War and the Eighty Years' War. It recognized the independence of the Dutch Republic and the Swiss Confederation, granted greater autonomy to the states of the Holy Roman Empire, and settled religious disputes among Catholics, Lutherans, and Calvinists. It is often cited as a foundational moment in the development of the modern system of sovereign states.",
"Seven_Years'_War": "The Seven Years' War was a global conflict fought from 1756 to 1763 involving most of the great powers of Europe and their colonial empires. It ranged across Europe, the Americas, West Africa, India, and the seas, pitting an alliance around Britain and Prussia against one around France, Austria, and Russia. The war ended with the Treaty of Paris and the Treaty of Hubertusburg, greatly expanding British colonial dominance, especially in North America and India.",
"American_Revolutionary_War": "The American Revolutionary War was fought from 1775 to 1783 between Great Britain and thirteen of its North American colonies, which declared their independence as the United States in 1776. France, Spain, and the Dutch Republic later entered on the American side, widening the conflict into an international war. It ended with the Treaty of Paris in 1783, in which Britain recognized the independence of the United States.",
"Bourbon_Reforms": "The Bourbon Reforms were a series of administrative, economic, and military changes enacted by the Spanish crown under the House of Bourbon during the 18th century, most extensively under King Charles III. They aimed to centralize authority, increase revenue, and tighten control over the empire by reducing the influence of colonial-born elites in favour of officials sent from Spain. Applied across both Spain and its American territories, the reforms boosted trade and mining output but also stirred resentment that later fed independence movements in Spanish America.",
"Meiji_Restoration": "The Meiji Restoration was the 1868 political transformation in Japan that ended the rule of the Tokugawa shogunate and restored practical governing power to the emperor. It abolished the feudal domain system and the samurai class, centralized the state, and launched rapid industrialization and adoption of Western technology and institutions. The changes turned Japan into a modern nation-state and an emerging imperial power within a few decades.",
"World_War_II": "World War II was a global conflict fought from 1939 to 1945 between the Axis powers, chiefly Germany, Italy, and Japan, and the Allied powers, including the Soviet Union, the United States, the United Kingdom, and China. It was the deadliest war in history, causing tens of millions of deaths, the Holocaust, and the destruction of cities across Europe and Asia. The war ended with the defeat of the Axis, the emergence of the United States and the Soviet Union as superpowers, and the founding of the United Nations.",
"East_India_Company": "The East India Company was an English, later British, joint-stock company chartered in 1600 to trade with South and Southeast Asia. Over time it evolved from a commercial enterprise into a territorial power, ruling large parts of the Indian subcontinent through its own presidency armies and administration. Following the Indian Rebellion of 1857 its Indian possessions were transferred to the British Crown, and the company was formally dissolved in 1874.",
"Scramble_for_Africa": "The Scramble for Africa was the rapid invasion, conquest, and colonization of most of the African continent by European powers in the late 19th and early 20th centuries. Belgium, France, Germany, Italy, Portugal, Spain, and the United Kingdom competed to claim territory, partitioning Africa with little regard for existing societies. The Berlin Conference of 1884 to 1885 set rules for these claims, requiring effective occupation and shaping borders that in many cases persist today.",
"Colombo": "Colombo is the largest city and the executive and judicial capital of Sri Lanka, situated on the island's west coast beside the Indian Ocean. A natural harbour, it was successively controlled by the Portuguese, Dutch, and British, who developed it into the colonial capital of Ceylon. It remains the country's commercial and financial hub, though some administrative functions moved to nearby Sri Jayawardenepura Kotte in the late 20th century.",
"Feng_shui": "Feng shui (風水), literally wind-water, is a traditional Chinese practice of geomancy that seeks to arrange buildings, tombs, cities, and objects in harmony with the flow of qi and the surrounding landscape. Practitioners draw on the principles of yin and yang and the five phases, and site or orient a place by reading the forms of mountains, rivers, and other features along with directional calculations. A central instrument is the luopan, a magnetic compass ringed with concentric bands of cosmological and directional formulas used to align a structure with auspicious currents of energy.",
"Tu_Di_Po": "Tu Di Po (土地婆) is a grandmotherly female earth deity of Chinese folk religion, the wife of the local earth god Tudigong, with whom she is enshrined and venerated at neighborhood earth-god shrines. Depicted as an elderly woman and often titled the Grandmother of the Soil, she is regarded in some accounts as a just and benevolent figure on the same rank as her husband, and in others as a grudging one who holds back the blessings and wealth he would otherwise bestow. Folklore holds that the Jade Emperor assigned her to oversee how many blessings Tudigong distributes so that he would not give them out too freely, a belief that leaves some worshippers reluctant to honor her, though in parts of Taiwan she is separately revered as a goddess of fertility and childbirth.",
"Ghost_Festival": "The Ghost Festival (中元節) is a traditional East Asian observance held on the fifteenth night of the seventh lunar month, known in Taoism as the Zhongyuan Festival and in Buddhism as the Yulanpen or Ullambana Festival. It falls within the seventh lunar month, regarded as the Ghost Month, when the spirits of the dead are believed to leave the lower realm and roam among the living. Families make offerings of food, incense, and joss paper to honour their ancestors and to appease wandering hungry ghosts, and the festival is widely observed across Chinese and other East Asian communities.",
"Bohai_Sea": "The Bohai Sea (渤海) is a shallow, semi-enclosed gulf off the coast of northeastern China, forming the northwestern and innermost extension of the Yellow Sea. It is bounded by the Liaodong Peninsula to the north and the Shandong Peninsula to the south, and connects to the wider Yellow Sea through the Bohai Strait between them, while receiving the waters of the Yellow, Hai, and Liao rivers. Its bays support major fishing grounds that serve as spawning and feeding areas for species such as small yellow croaker and prawn, and its seabed holds large offshore oil and gas reserves.",
"Xu_Fu": "Xu Fu (徐福) was a court sorcerer and alchemist, or fangshi, who served the First Emperor Qin Shi Huang of the Qin dynasty. Around 219 BCE he petitioned the emperor to sail eastward across the sea in search of the elixir of immortality held by the immortals on mythical isles such as Penglai, and he departed with a large company that included thousands of young boys and girls. He undertook a second voyage around 210 BCE and never returned, later legend holding that he reached Japan.",
"Penglai_Pavilion": "Penglai Pavilion (蓬萊閣) is a historic pavilion and temple complex built in 1061 during the Northern Song dynasty on the cliffs of Danya Mountain at Penglai, on the northern coast of Shandong Province in China. Overlooking the point where the Bohai and Yellow Seas meet, it is counted among the Four Great Towers of China and is renowned for the sea mirages, a form of Fata Morgana, that occasionally appear off its shores. In legend it is tied to the Eight Immortals, who are said to have crossed the sea from this place, and its name evokes the fabled paradise island of Penglai.",
"Zhurong_Peak": "Zhurong Peak (祝融峰) is the highest summit of Mount Heng in Hunan Province, the southern mountain of China's Five Great Mountains, rising to about 1,300 metres above sea level. It takes its name from Zhurong, the fire god of Chinese mythology, and is crowned by a small stone temple dedicated to him. The summit is a destination for pilgrims and visitors, who climb to it to worship at the temple and to watch the sunrise over the surrounding landscape.",
"Mount_Heng_(Hunan)": "Mount Heng (衡山), also called Nanyue or the Southern Great Mountain, is a sacred mountain in Hunan province of south-central China and the southern of the Five Great Mountains of Chinese tradition. Its highest summit is Zhurong Peak, rising about 1,300 metres above sea level and named after Zhurong, the god of fire. Long revered in both Taoism and Buddhism, the mountain is a major pilgrimage destination dotted with temples and monasteries, including the large Grand Temple of Mount Heng at its foot.",
"Zhurong_rover": "The Zhurong rover (祝融号) was China's first Mars rover, a solar-powered six-wheeled robotic vehicle carried to the planet as part of the Tianwen-1 mission of the China National Space Administration. It is named after Zhurong, the god of fire in Chinese mythology, a choice meant to evoke the igniting of interstellar exploration. Landing on the plain of Utopia Planitia in May 2021 and rolling onto the surface days later, it made China the second nation to operate a rover on the Martian surface after the United States.",
"Prefecture": "A prefecture is an administrative jurisdiction or district headed by an official known as a prefect, the term deriving from the Latin praefectura. It has been applied to units of regional and local government in many countries and historical empires, ranging from major territorial divisions to smaller local subdivisions. The size, powers, and rank of a prefecture within a governing hierarchy vary widely from one system to another.",
"Joss_paper": "Joss paper (紙錢), also called spirit money or ghost money, is a kind of paper burned as an offering in Chinese ancestral veneration and folk religious rituals. Made to represent money, clothing, houses, and other goods, it is set alight so that ancestors and spirits may receive and use these things in the afterlife. It is offered at funerals, at gravesites, and during festivals honouring the dead, and is widely used across Chinese and other East Asian communities.",
"Black_Tortoise": "The Black Tortoise (玄武), or Xuanwu, is one of the Four Symbols of the Chinese constellations, the celestial guardian of the northern sky. Within the Five Phases system it corresponds to the element water, the season of winter, and the color black, and it is depicted as a tortoise entwined with a snake. It is associated with longevity and endurance, and is known as Genbu in Japan, Hyeonmu in Korea, and Huyền Vũ in Vietnam.",
"Wudang_Mountains": "The Wudang Mountains (武当山) are a mountain range in northwestern Hubei province, China, long revered as one of the most sacred sites of Taoism. Home to an extensive complex of temples, palaces, and monasteries built on a grand scale under the Ming dynasty in the early 15th century, they are dedicated especially to the god Xuanwu, the Dark Warrior of the North, and were recognized as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1994. The mountains are also celebrated as a cradle of the internal Chinese martial arts, the Wudang styles traditionally traced to the legendary Taoist sage Zhang Sanfeng.",
"UNESCO": "UNESCO, the United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization, is a specialized agency of the United Nations founded in 1945 to promote international cooperation in education, science, culture, and communication. Headquartered in Paris, it works to advance literacy, protect cultural and natural heritage, support scientific programmes, and defend freedom of expression among its member states. It is best known to the wider public for designating World Heritage Sites, places judged to be of outstanding value to humanity.",
"World_Heritage_Site": "A World Heritage Site is a landmark or area with legal protection under an international treaty administered by UNESCO, recognized for its cultural, historical, scientific, or other outstanding value to humanity. Sites are inscribed on the World Heritage List under the World Heritage Convention adopted in 1972, and may be cultural, natural, or mixed in character. Once designated, a site is intended to be preserved for future generations, with the host country undertaking to protect and conserve it, sometimes with international assistance.",
"Zhang_Sanfeng": "Zhang Sanfeng (張三丰) is a legendary and semi-historical Taoist priest traditionally revered as a founder of Taijiquan and the internal (neijia) martial arts of the Wudang Mountains. His life is placed variously across the Song, Yuan, and Ming dynasties, with traditional accounts crediting him with an extraordinarily long lifespan and the attainment of immortality as a Taoist adept. He is associated with Taoist alchemy and longevity practices, and his historical existence remains uncertain, as no reliable contemporary Song or Yuan sources confirm him.",
"White_Snake": "The White Snake (白蛇) is Bai Suzhen (白素貞), a benevolent white-serpent yaoguai who through a thousand years of Taoist cultivation gains the power to take the form of a beautiful woman. She is the protagonist of the Legend of the White Snake, in which she loves the scholar Xu Xian and is opposed by the monk Fahai. Portrayed as kindhearted and devoted despite her demonic origin, she is remembered in Chinese culture as an emblem of true love and self-sacrifice.",
"White_Bone_Spirit": "The White Bone Spirit (白骨精) is a shapeshifting skeleton demoness who appears as an episode-villain in the novel Journey to the West, her true form being a pile of bleached bones. Seeking to devour the monk Tang Sanzang in the belief that his flesh grants immortality, she disguises herself in succession as a young village girl, an old woman, and an old man to deceive the pilgrims. Sun Wukong sees through each human form and finally destroys her on the third attempt, an episode known as the Three Strikes of the White Bone Demon.",
"Pu_Songling": "Pu Songling (蒲松齡) was a Chinese writer of the Qing dynasty, best known as the author of the classical-Chinese short-story collection Strange Tales from a Chinese Studio (Liaozhai Zhiyi), a compilation of supernatural and fantastical tales he gathered and refined over much of his life. Having earned a licentiate degree in his youth, he repeatedly failed the higher provincial examinations and spent most of his career working as a private tutor, only receiving an honorary senior-licentiate rank late in life. His stories, many of them centred on encounters between struggling scholars and ghosts, fox spirits, and other otherworldly beings, circulated in manuscript during his lifetime and were published posthumously to become one of the most celebrated works of Chinese fiction.",
"Strange_Tales_from_a_Chinese_Studio": "Strange Tales from a Chinese Studio (聊齋誌異) is a collection of nearly five hundred short tales of the strange written in classical Chinese by Pu Songling over roughly four decades of his life. Its stories are populated by ghosts, fox spirits, and other yaoguai, many of them tales of love or encounter between such beings and mortal scholars. Circulated in manuscript during Pu Songling's lifetime and first printed in 1766 in Hangzhou, the collection frequently uses its supernatural material to carry social and moral satire.",
"Yokai": "Yokai (妖怪) are a broad class of supernatural beings, spirits, and monsters in Japanese folklore, ranging from malevolent and dangerous to mischievous or even bringers of good fortune. They include such types as oni, tengu, kappa, and shapeshifting animal spirits such as foxes and raccoon dogs. Yokai are frequently associated with the uncanny and with otherwise unexplained natural phenomena, disasters, and illnesses.",
"Yogachara": "Yogachara is an influential school of Mahayana Buddhist philosophy and psychology, its Sanskrit name meaning the practice of yoga, also known as Vijnanavada, the doctrine of consciousness, and Cittamatra, the teaching of mind-only or consciousness-only. It holds that the reality experienced by beings is ultimately a transformation or construction of consciousness rather than an external world existing independently of it. Founded in India in the first centuries of the common era and systematized by the brothers Asanga and Vasubandhu around the 4th to 5th century, it is known for the concept of the storehouse consciousness, or alaya-vijnana, a deep layer of mind that retains the karmic seeds shaping perception.",
"Prefect": "A prefect is a senior administrative or magisterial official placed in charge of a district, department, or institution, often the prefecture that the office governs. The word derives from the Latin praefectus, the past participle of praeficere, to place in charge, formed from prae, before, and facere, to make or do. The office has taken many forms across states and eras, from the praefectus of ancient Rome and the chief state officer of a French department to a senior pupil granted authority in some schools.",
"Bamboo": "Bamboo is a group of tall, fast-growing woody plants of the grass family Poaceae, distinguished by hollow, jointed stems called culms. Various species are native to warm-temperate and tropical regions across Asia, the Americas, Africa, and Oceania, and some rank among the fastest-growing plants on Earth, capable of extending as much as several dozen centimetres in a single day. Its strong, lightweight culms are widely used for building, furniture, paper, and tools, while the tender young shoots of many species are harvested as food.",
"Ji_Yun": "Ji Yun (紀昀) was a scholar-official of the Qing dynasty who rose through the imperial examinations to hold high posts at the Qianlong court, eventually becoming Minister of Rites and a Grand Academician. He served as the chief editor of the Siku Quanshu, the imperial Complete Library of the Four Treasuries, the largest compilation of texts in Chinese history. In his later years he wrote the collection of supernatural anecdotes and reflections known as the Yuewei Caotang Biji, or Notes of the Thatched Abode of Close Observations.",
"Notes_of_the_Thatched_Abode": "The Notes of the Thatched Abode (閱微草堂筆記), or Yuewei Caotang Biji, is a collection of supernatural anecdotes, strange tales, and reflections compiled by the scholar-official Ji Yun across five volumes written from 1789 to 1798. Composed in a terse classical Chinese in the zhiguai and biji traditions, it gathers hundreds of accounts of ghosts, fox spirits, and other uncanny happenings, most of them related to Ji Yun by colleagues and friends among the educated elite. Its stories are frequently paired with didactic, skeptical, or moralizing commentary that questions the reality of the marvels it records.",
"Mr._Vampire": "Mr. Vampire (殭屍先生) is a 1985 Hong Kong horror-comedy film directed by Ricky Lau and produced by Sammo Hung. It stars Lam Ching-ying as a Taoist priest who battles a reanimated jiangshi, blending martial-arts action, slapstick comedy, and supernatural folklore. Its commercial success popularized the jiangshi in cinema and set off a wave of similar hopping-corpse films in Hong Kong during the late 1980s.",
"Xu_Xian": "Xu Xian (許仙) is the human male protagonist of the Legend of the White Snake, portrayed as a gentle but timid young man who is depicted in various versions as a scholar or a physician. In the tale he meets and marries the white-snake spirit Bai Suzhen without knowing her true nature, the two having fallen in love after he lends her his umbrella in the rain by West Lake. His devotion is tested when the monk Fahai reveals that his wife is a serpent, an exposure that drives the story toward its tragic separation and Xu Xian's long efforts to reunite with her.",
"Fahai": "Fahai (法海) is the Buddhist monk who serves as the antagonist of the Legend of the White Snake, an abbot of Jinshan Temple in Zhenjiang who possesses spiritual powers and regards the white-snake spirit Bai Suzhen as a dangerous demon, working to expose her and separate her from her husband Xu Xian. He advises Xu Xian to make his wife drink realgar wine during the Dragon Boat Festival so that she reverts to her serpent form, and after she floods his temple in a failed attempt to rescue Xu Xian, he defeats her and imprisons her beneath Leifeng Pagoda. The figure is loosely derived from a historical eminent monk of the Tang dynasty associated with Jinshan Temple in Zhenjiang, though he is remembered in the folktale as its stern adversary.",
"Three_Strikes_of_the_White_Bone_Demon": "The Three Strikes of the White Bone Demon (三打白骨精) is a celebrated episode from Chapter 27 of the novel Journey to the West, in which the shapeshifting White Bone Spirit disguises herself in three successive human forms, a young woman, an old woman, and an old man, in an attempt to seize and devour the monk Tang Sanzang. Each time, Sun Wukong perceives the demon behind the disguise and strikes the form down with his staff, until the third blow finally kills her and exposes a pile of white bones. Because Tang Sanzang cannot see through the illusions and takes the three killings for the murder of innocents, he berates Sun Wukong and briefly banishes him from the pilgrimage.",
"Bestiary": "A bestiary is a compendium or catalogue of beasts, taking its name from the Latin bestiarium, meaning a collection of animals. In its classic form it is an illustrated volume of the European Middle Ages that describes the appearance and habits of creatures both real and imaginary and draws a moral or religious lesson from each. More broadly, the term names any descriptive collection or reference work devoted to real or mythical creatures.",
"Talisman": "A talisman is an object, such as a stone, ring, or inscribed charm, believed to hold magical or protective power that brings good fortune to its bearer or wards off evil, illness, and misfortune. Objects treated as talismans appear across many cultures and historical periods, ranging from engraved gems and metal seals to written verses and worn ornaments. The word entered English in the 1630s from French talisman, by way of Arabic tilsam, from the Byzantine and ancient Greek telesma, meaning a completion, consecration, or religious rite, itself from telein, to perform a rite or bring to completion.",
"Antares": "Antares is a red supergiant star with the Bayer designation Alpha Scorpii, the brightest star in the constellation Scorpius and one of the brightest in the night sky. It marks the heart of the scorpion and ranks among the largest stars visible to the naked eye, displaying a strongly reddish colour. Its name comes from the Ancient Greek for rival of Ares, the god identified with the planet Mars, chosen for the star's Mars-like ruddy hue.",
"Spica": "Spica is the brightest star in the constellation Virgo and one of the twenty brightest stars in the night sky, appearing to the eye as a single blue-white point of light about 250 light-years from the Sun. It is in fact a close binary system whose two hot, massive stars orbit their common centre of gravity in roughly four days, so near to each other that their mutual gravity distorts them into egg shapes. Its name is Latin for ear of grain, and it traditionally marks the sheaf of wheat held in the hand of the maiden depicted by Virgo.",
"Dragon_Raising_its_Head": "Dragon Raising its Head (龍抬頭) is a traditional Chinese festival held on the second day of the second lunar month, marking the awakening of the dragon that governs rain and the beginning of the spring ploughing season. Its name derives from the moment in early spring when the horn stars of the Azure Dragon, the eastern celestial guardian, first rise above the eastern horizon, as if the sky-dragon were lifting its head. Customary observances include getting a haircut for good fortune, eating foods named for the dragon such as dumplings called dragon ears and noodles called dragon beards, and praying to the Dragon King for rain and an abundant harvest.",
"Seiryu": "Seiryū (青龍) is the azure, or blue-green, dragon of Japanese tradition, one of the four guardian gods known as the Shijin who watch over the cardinal directions. As the tutelary deity of the east, it is associated with the season of spring and the element wood, and it embodies the eastern quarter of the heavens formed by seven of the lunar mansions. In Japanese belief it guards the eastern side of a city, and it is venerated in this role at the eastern edge of the old capital Kyoto, notably at the Kiyomizu-dera temple in the Higashiyama district.",
"Cheongnyong": "Cheongnyong (청룡, 靑龍) is an azure dragon of Korean tradition, one of the Sasin, the Four Guardian Deities that protect the four cardinal directions. It presides over the east, and in the correlative symbolism of directions, seasons, colours, and elements it is associated with spring, the blue-green colour, and the wood phase. The dragon appears prominently in the mural paintings of Goguryeo tombs, where it was painted on the eastern wall of the burial chamber to guard the deceased against threats from that quarter.",
"Fenghuang": "The fenghuang (鳳凰) is a mythical bird of Chinese tradition, often called the Chinese phoenix, said to reign over all other birds and to embody virtue, grace, peace, and prosperity. It was believed to appear only in eras blessed with peace and good government, so its presence served as an auspicious sign of a virtuous ruler and harmonious rule. It became an emblem of the empress and of feminine grace, and is commonly depicted amid flowers and clouds in art, textiles, and decoration.",
"Pheasant": "A pheasant is any of numerous large, long-tailed, ground-dwelling birds of the family Phasianidae, native across parts of Asia and Europe and naturalized in many other regions. The group shows strong sexual dimorphism: males are typically brilliantly coloured with iridescent plumage, wattles, and long ornate tails, while females are a drab mottled brown that provides camouflage while nesting on the ground. Pheasants are widely raised, released, and hunted as game birds, and several species have been introduced far beyond their original range for that purpose.",
"Snake": "A snake is an elongated, limbless, carnivorous reptile of the suborder Serpentes, with a highly flexible body covered in overlapping scales. Many species have skulls with numerous mobile joints and loosely connected jaws that allow them to swallow prey much larger than their heads, sometimes whole. Snakes live on every continent except Antarctica and on many smaller landmasses, and while most are harmless to humans, some kinds are venomous.",
"Pleiades": "The Pleiades is a prominent open star cluster in the constellation Taurus, among the nearest such clusters to Earth and one of the most obvious to the naked eye. Its light is dominated by hot, luminous blue stars that formed within roughly the last hundred million years. Popularly known as the Seven Sisters, it takes its name from Greek mythology, in which the seven daughters of the Titan Atlas and the sea nymph Pleione were placed among the stars.",
"Orion's_Belt": "Orion's Belt is an asterism formed by three bright stars, Alnitak, Alnilam, and Mintaka, arranged in a nearly straight, evenly spaced line across the middle of the constellation Orion. Representing the belt of the mythological hunter for which the constellation is named, it is one of the most recognizable and easily identified star patterns in the night sky. The asterism is prominent in the evening sky through the northern winter months and has long served as a marker for locating other stars and celestial features.",
"Lunar_mansion": "A lunar mansion is one of a series of divisions of the sky along the path the Moon traces against the stars, each marking roughly where the Moon lies on successive nights across its monthly cycle. Because a sidereal month lasts about twenty-seven and one-third days, such schemes group the stars into twenty-seven or twenty-eight sectors, each associated with the constellations or bright stars near it. Systems of lunar mansions arose independently in several traditions, including the twenty-eight mansions of Chinese astronomy, the nakshatras of Indian astronomy, and the manazil of Arabic astronomy.",
"Kyoto": "Kyoto (京都) is a major city in the Kansai region of Japan, founded in 794 as Heian-kyo when Emperor Kanmu moved the imperial court there. It served as the seat of the Japanese emperor and the political and cultural heart of the country for over a thousand years, until the imperial court was transferred to Tokyo in 1869. The city is renowned for its many classical Buddhist temples, Shinto shrines, imperial palaces, and gardens, several of which are collectively designated a UNESCO World Heritage Site.",
"Suzaku_Gate": "The Suzaku Gate (朱雀門) was the great main southern gate of the palace enclosure in the ancient Japanese capitals of Heijo-kyo (Nara) and Heian-kyo (Kyoto), and earlier Fujiwara-kyo. Standing at the northern end of the central Suzaku Avenue, it served as the ceremonial front entrance to the imperial palace grounds and the site where foreign envoys were received. It took its name from Suzaku, the vermilion bird guardian of the south in the traditional scheme of directional animals.",
"Suzaku_Avenue": "Suzaku Avenue (朱雀大路) was the broad central boulevard that ran north to south through the grid-planned ancient Japanese capitals of Heijō-kyō and Heian-kyō, dividing the city into eastern and western halves. As the widest and principal ceremonial thoroughfare, it connected the Suzakumon, the main southern gate of the palace enclosure, to the Rajōmon gate at the southern edge of the city. Its name honors Suzaku, the vermilion bird revered as the guardian deity of the south.",
"Li_Shimin": "Li Shimin (李世民) was a prince and general of the Tang dynasty who helped his father, the founding Emperor Gaozu, overthrow the Sui and establish the new dynasty, and who then reigned as its second emperor under the name Taizong. He came to the throne after the Xuanwu Gate Incident of 626, a palace coup in which he killed his rival brothers Li Jiancheng and Li Yuanji and soon after received the throne from his father. His reign, known as the Zhenguan era, was long celebrated as a model of capable and just government, and he is widely regarded as one of the greatest emperors in Chinese history.",
"Corpse_driving": "Corpse-driving (趕屍) is a folk practice and legend of western Hunan, in the Xiangxi region of China, in which the bodies of people who died far from home were said to be conveyed back to their native villages for burial. According to the tradition, Taoist priests could make the corpses hop along in single file, usually travelling by night and heralded by a bell, an appearance often explained by bodies tied upright to flexing bamboo poles carried on the shoulders. The custom is bound up with the folklore of the jiangshi, the reanimated hopping corpse of Chinese legend.",
"Qianlong_Emperor": "The Qianlong Emperor (乾隆) was a ruler of the Qing dynasty whose long reign is often regarded as the peak of the dynasty's power, prosperity, and territorial expansion. A prolific patron of the arts and scholarship, he ordered the compilation of the Siku Quanshu, an immense imperial anthology gathering thousands of works of Chinese literature, philosophy, history, and science. He formally abdicated the throne in 1796 after sixty years of rule so that he would not reign longer than his grandfather, the Kangxi Emperor, though he continued to hold effective power until his death.",
"Minister_of_Rites": "The Minister of Rites (禮部尚書) was the head of the Ministry of Rites, one of the Six Ministries of the central imperial Chinese government alongside the ministries of Personnel, Revenue, War, Justice, and Works. The office directed state ceremonies, ritual sacrifices, court protocol and etiquette, the reception of foreign envoys, and the administration of the imperial examinations. It endured from the Tang period through the Ming and Qing dynasties until the Six Ministries were dissolved in the late-Qing reforms preceding the 1911 revolution.",
"Grand_Academician": "Grand Academician (大學士) was a senior scholar-official title of the Ming and Qing dynasties, borne by the leading members of the Grand Secretariat who served as close advisors to the emperor. Its holders scrutinized memorials submitted to the throne and drafted the suggested rescripts pasted to them for imperial approval, a process that made the Grand Secretariat a central organ of state policy and its senior members among the most influential figures at court. The post was reserved for eminent scholars, typically drawn from the Hanlin Academy after rising through the imperial examinations.",
"Siku_Quanshu": "The Siku Quanshu (四庫全書), or Complete Library of the Four Treasuries, is an imperial manuscript compendium commissioned by the Qianlong Emperor of the Qing dynasty in 1772 and completed in 1782, the largest collection of books assembled in imperial Chinese history. It gathered thousands of works into the four traditional bibliographic divisions of classics, histories, masters, and collections, copied by hand into seven complete sets deposited in libraries across the empire. The same undertaking served as an instrument of control, since many texts submitted for inclusion were censored, edited, or destroyed for containing sentiments the Qing court judged objectionable.",
"Suzaku": "Suzaku (朱雀), also read Sujaku, is the vermilion bird of Japanese tradition and one of the four guardian gods known as the Shijin, serving as the tutelary deity of the south. It is associated with summer and with the element fire, and guards the southern quarter of the heavens as a great red, phoenix-like bird. Its name was given to the Suzakumon, the great southern gate of the ancient capitals of Fujiwara-kyo, Heijo-kyo, and Heian-kyo, and to Suzaku Avenue, the central north-south thoroughfare running south from that gate.",
"Jujak": "In Korean tradition, Jujak (주작, 朱雀) is the vermilion bird, one of the Sasin, the four guardian deities that watch over the cardinal directions. As the guardian of the south, it is associated with summer, the element fire, and the colour red, and it is often depicted as a phoenix-like bird wreathed in flame. Jujak appears famously in the wall murals of Goguryeo tombs, painted on the southern wall of the burial chamber in the position corresponding to its direction.",
"Byakko": "In Japanese tradition Byakko (白虎) is the celestial white tiger, one of the four guardian gods known as the Shijin, and the tutelary deity of the west. It is associated with the season of autumn and the Five-Phase element metal, and it is envisioned as spanning seven of the twenty-eight lunar mansions across the western quarter of the night sky. As a directional guardian Byakko watches over and protects the western reaches, and the four guardian gods were invoked to orient the siting of ancient Japanese capitals such as Heijō-kyō and Heian-kyō.",
"Baekho": "Baekho (백호, 白虎) is the white tiger of Korean tradition, one of the Sasin, the four guardian deities that preside over the cardinal directions. As guardian of the west, it is associated with autumn, the metal phase of the five elements, and the colour white. It appears painted on the western wall in the tomb murals of Goguryeo, where each of the four guardians occupies the wall of its direction.",
"Genbu": "Genbu (玄武) is the black tortoise of Japanese tradition, one of the four guardian gods known as the Shijin. He is the tutelary deity of the north, associated with the season of winter and the Five-Phase element water. Genbu is usually depicted as a tortoise entwined with a snake, and he guards the northern quarter.",
"Hyeonmu": "Hyeonmu (현무, 玄武) is the black tortoise of Korean tradition, depicted as a tortoise entwined with a serpent, and is one of the Sasin, the four guardian deities of the cardinal directions. It serves as the guardian of the north and is associated with winter, water, and the colour black. Hyeonmu appears painted on the northern wall in the tomb murals of the Goguryeo kingdom, where the intertwined tortoise and serpent were rendered with increasing refinement over the centuries.",
"Horn_mansion": "The Horn mansion (角, Jiao) is the first of the twenty-eight lunar mansions of traditional Chinese astronomy and belongs to the Azure Dragon of the east. Its determinative star is Spica (Alpha Virginis), and the mansion lies in the modern constellation Virgo. Named for the horns of the celestial dragon, it marks the creature's head and is associated with the coming of spring in the seasonal reckoning tied to the mansions.",
"Neck_mansion": "The Neck mansion (亢, Kang) is one of the twenty-eight lunar mansions of traditional Chinese astronomy, the second of the seven mansions belonging to the Azure Dragon of the east. Its determinative star is Kappa Virginis, and the mansion lies within the modern constellation Virgo. The name refers to the neck of the Azure Dragon, and its small asterism is formed from stars in the region including Kappa, Iota, Phi, and Lambda Virginis.",
"Root_mansion": "Root mansion (氐, Di) is the third of the twenty-eight lunar mansions in traditional Chinese astronomy and one of the seven mansions of the Azure Dragon of the east. Its determinative star is Alpha Librae, known in the West as Zubenelgenubi, which lies in the modern constellation Libra. The mansion's name refers to the base or root of the dragon, and its asterism gathers several stars of Libra, with Alpha Librae designated 氐宿一, the first star of Root.",
"Room_mansion": "The Room mansion (房, Fang) is the fourth of the twenty-eight lunar mansions in traditional Chinese astronomy and belongs to the Azure Dragon of the eastern quadrant, representing the dragon's belly or chest. Its determinative star is Pi Scorpii, known in Chinese as Fang Xiu yi, which lies in the modern constellation Scorpius in the region of the scorpion's claws just west of Antares. The name means room or chamber, and the asterism was identified with the Mingtang, the bright ceremonial hall from which the Son of Heaven was said to conduct government and observe the seasons.",
"Heart_mansion": "The Heart mansion (心, Xin) is the fifth of the twenty-eight lunar mansions in traditional Chinese astronomy and the fifth of the seven mansions of the Azure Dragon of the east. Its determinative star is Antares (心宿二, Alpha Scorpii), and the mansion lies within the modern constellation Scorpius, where its three stars — Antares together with Sigma and Tau Scorpii — form an asterism representing the dragon's heart. Antares, a red supergiant known anciently as the Great Fire (大火, Dahuo), was watched at dawn and dusk as a seasonal marker for the calendar.",
"Tail_mansion": "The Tail mansion (尾, Wei) is the sixth of the twenty-eight lunar mansions and belongs to the Azure Dragon of the east, forming the dragon's tail. Its determinative star is Mu Scorpii, and the mansion lies within the modern constellation Scorpius. The curving hook of stars running from Epsilon Scorpii out to Lambda and Upsilon Scorpii corresponds to the tail and stinger of the Scorpion in the Western tradition.",
"Winnowing_Basket_mansion": "The Winnowing Basket mansion (箕, Ji) is the seventh of the twenty-eight lunar mansions in traditional Chinese astronomy and the last of the seven mansions belonging to the Azure Dragon of the east. Its determinative star is Gamma Sagittarii, and the mansion lies within the modern constellation Sagittarius. Its four principal stars, Gamma, Delta, Epsilon, and Eta Sagittarii, form a quadrilateral asterism representing a winnowing basket used to separate grain from chaff.",
"Dipper_mansion": "The Dipper mansion (斗, Dou) is the first of the seven lunar mansions belonging to the Black Tortoise of the north, among the twenty-eight mansions of traditional Chinese astronomy. Its determinative star is Phi Sagittarii, and the mansion lies in the modern constellation Sagittarius. Its six principal stars form the asterism known as the Southern Dipper, a ladle-shaped grouping whose name evokes a measuring vessel for grain or liquid.",
"Ox_mansion": "The Ox mansion (牛, Niu) is one of the twenty-eight lunar mansions of traditional Chinese astronomy, belonging to the Black Tortoise of the north. Its determinative star is Beta Capricorni, the star known in the West as Dabih, which lies in the modern constellation Capricornus. The mansion's principal asterism represents a sacrificial ox and sits within a region of the sky rich in pastoral and agricultural imagery, near the Weaving Girl and Celestial Farmland asterisms.",
"Girl_mansion": "The Girl mansion (女, Nü) is the tenth of the twenty-eight lunar mansions of traditional Chinese astronomy and the third of the seven mansions belonging to the Black Tortoise of the north. Its determinative star is Epsilon Aquarii, known as Albali, which lies in the modern constellation Aquarius. The name refers to a maidservant or weaving girl, and the mansion's asterism is formed by Epsilon, Mu, 4, and 3 Aquarii near the border with Aquila.",
"Emptiness_mansion": "The Emptiness mansion (虛, Xu) is one of the twenty-eight lunar mansions of traditional Chinese astronomy, and it is the fourth of the seven mansions belonging to the Black Tortoise of the north. Its determinative star is Beta Aquarii, known in the West as Sadalsuud, which lies in the modern constellation Aquarius. The mansion pairs Beta Aquarii with Alpha Equulei to form a small asterism, and its name, meaning emptiness or a ruined mound, carried associations with desolation, death, and funerary matters in Chinese astrological tradition.",
"Rooftop_mansion": "Rooftop mansion (危, Wei) is one of the twenty-eight lunar mansions of traditional Chinese astronomy, the fifth of the seven mansions belonging to the Black Tortoise of the north. Its determinative star is Alpha Aquarii, known as Sadalmelik, which lies in the modern constellation Aquarius. The name refers to the ridge or apex of a rooftop, and the mansion is drawn as a three-star asterism whose members span into neighbouring Pegasus, together tracing the peaked shape of a roof.",
"Encampment_mansion": "The Encampment mansion (室, Shi) is the thirteenth of the twenty-eight lunar mansions in traditional Chinese astronomy and one of the seven mansions of the Black Tortoise of the north. Its determinative star is Alpha Pegasi, known as Markab, which lies in the modern constellation Pegasus. Together with Beta Pegasi it forms an asterism representing a walled palace or military encampment, and its evening culmination in late autumn traditionally marked the season for building and construction work.",
"Wall_mansion": "The Wall mansion (壁, Bi) is one of the twenty-eight lunar mansions of traditional Chinese astronomy, the seventh and final mansion of the Black Tortoise of the north. Its determinative star is Gamma Pegasi, also called Algenib, which lies in the modern constellation of Pegasus, while the mansion's principal asterism is completed by Alpheratz in neighbouring Andromeda. Its name refers to a wall, and it was associated with the eastern wall of an imperial library or archive, so the mansion came to be linked with books, scholarship, and literary learning.",
"Legs_mansion": "The Legs mansion (奎, Kui) is the first of the seven lunar mansions of the White Tiger of the West, one of the twenty-eight mansions into which traditional Chinese astronomy divides the sky along the ecliptic and celestial equator. Its determinative star is Eta Andromedae, and the asterism spans the modern constellations of Andromeda and Pisces. Often interpreted as the rear legs or feet of the White Tiger and sometimes as a wild boar, it is associated in East Asian culture with wisdom, scholarship, and literature, and was known in an older tradition as Tianshi, the Celestial Pig.",
"Bond_mansion": "The Bond mansion (婁, Lóu) is the sixteenth of the twenty-eight lunar mansions of traditional Chinese astronomy and the second of the seven mansions of the White Tiger of the West. Its determinative star is Beta Arietis, known as Sheratan, which lies in the modern constellation Aries. Its name is usually rendered as Bond, and its asterism is the short crooked line formed by the stars Alpha, Beta, and Gamma Arietis, which mark the horns of the ram.",
"Stomach_mansion": "The Stomach mansion (胃, Wei) is the seventeenth of the twenty-eight lunar mansions of traditional Chinese astronomy and the third of the seven mansions forming the White Tiger of the West. Its determinative star is 35 Arietis, and the mansion lies within the modern constellation Aries. Its principal asterism is composed of 35, 39, and 41 Arietis, and its name was anciently associated with the storage of grain, so that bright stars here were read as an omen of a bountiful harvest.",
"Hairy_Head_mansion": "The Hairy Head mansion (昴, Mao) is one of the twenty-eight lunar mansions of traditional Chinese astronomy, ranking among the seven mansions of the White Tiger of the west. Its determinative star is 17 Tauri, also called Electra, which lies within the constellation Taurus. The mansion corresponds to the Pleiades open star cluster, whose tight grouping of naked-eye stars was likened to a tuft or head of hair, giving the mansion its name.",
"Net_mansion": "The Net mansion (畢, Bi) is the fifth of the seven lunar mansions of the White Tiger of the west, one of the twenty-eight mansions of traditional Chinese astronomy. Its determinative star is Epsilon Tauri, also called Ain, a member of the Hyades open cluster in the modern constellation Taurus. The name evokes a long-handled hunting net, and the mansion is identified with the V-shaped Hyades, whose stars form the asterism from which the mansion takes its name.",
"Turtle_Beak_mansion": "The Turtle Beak mansion (觜, Zi) is one of the twenty-eight lunar mansions of traditional Chinese astronomy, the twentieth of the twenty-eight and the sixth of the seven mansions belonging to the White Tiger of the West. Its determinative star is Lambda Orionis, also known as Meissa, which lies in the modern constellation of Orion. Named for a beak or snout, the mansion forms a compact triangle of three stars, Meissa together with Phi-1 and Phi-2 Orionis in the head of Orion, spanning only about two degrees and making it the smallest of the twenty-eight mansions.",
"Three_Stars_mansion": "The Three Stars mansion (參, Shen) is one of the twenty-eight lunar mansions of traditional Chinese astronomy, the seventh and last of the seven mansions belonging to the White Tiger of the west. Its determinative star is Zeta Orionis, also called Alnitak, and the mansion lies within the modern constellation of Orion. The name refers to the three closely spaced belt stars of Orion, and the mansion also encompasses the surrounding bright stars of the figure, including Betelgeuse and Rigel.",
"Well_mansion": "The Well mansion (井, Jing), sometimes called the Eastern Well, is one of the twenty-eight lunar mansions of traditional Chinese astronomy and the first of the seven mansions of the Vermilion Bird of the south. Its determinative star is Mu Geminorum, and the mansion lies within the modern constellation Gemini. The name derives from its eight principal stars, which form an asterism resembling the Chinese character for a water well, and it is the widest of the twenty-eight mansions in celestial extent.",
"Ghost_mansion": "The Ghost mansion (鬼, Gui) is one of the twenty-eight lunar mansions of traditional Chinese astronomy, the second of the seven mansions belonging to the Vermilion Bird of the south. Its determinative star is Theta Cancri, lying in the modern constellation Cancer. The mansion is formed by a quadrilateral of four stars surrounding the open star cluster Praesepe, known in the West as the Beehive Cluster, whose hazy glow was perceived as a ghostly vapour and gave the mansion its name referring to the spirits of the dead.",
"Willow_mansion": "The Willow mansion (柳, Liu) is one of the twenty-eight lunar mansions of traditional Chinese astronomy, ranking among the seven mansions of the Vermilion Bird of the south. Its determinative star is Delta Hydrae, and the asterism lies within the modern constellation Hydra. The mansion is made up of eight stars that trace the head of the celestial Hydra, their curving arrangement evoking the drooping fronds of a willow tree, from which the name derives.",
"Star_mansion": "The Star mansion (星, Xing) is one of the twenty-eight lunar mansions of traditional Chinese astronomy and the fourth of the seven mansions of the Vermilion Bird of the south. Its determinative star is Alphard (Alpha Hydrae), an orange giant lying in the modern constellation Hydra. Also known as the Seven Stars, the mansion is formed of an asterism of seven stars along the body of Hydra and represents the neck of the Vermilion Bird.",
"Extended_Net_mansion": "The Extended Net mansion (張, Zhang) is the fifth of the seven lunar mansions belonging to the Vermilion Bird of the south, one of the Four Symbols within the twenty-eight mansions of traditional Chinese astronomy. Its determinative star is Upsilon-1 Hydrae, and the mansion lies in the modern constellation Hydra. Named for an outstretched net, it is envisioned as the crop or gizzard of the Vermilion Bird and forms an asterism of six stars including Upsilon-1, Lambda, Mu, Kappa, and Phi-1 Hydrae.",
"Wings_mansion": "The Wings mansion (翼, Yi) is one of the twenty-eight lunar mansions of traditional Chinese astronomy, the sixth of the seven mansions that form the Vermilion Bird of the south. Its determinative star is Alkes, Alpha Crateris, an orange giant known in Chinese as 翼宿一 that lies in the modern constellation Crater. Envisioned as the wings of the celestial bird, the mansion forms a large, sprawling asterism of stars drawn mainly from Crater and Hydra.",
"Chariot_mansion": "The Chariot mansion (軫, Zhen) is the last of the twenty-eight lunar mansions of traditional Chinese astronomy and the seventh and final mansion of the Vermilion Bird of the south. Its determinative star is Gamma Corvi, also called Gienah, lying in the modern constellation Corvus. Its name refers to the crossbar at the rear of a chariot, and its principal asterism, formed by the four brightest stars of Corvus, depicts a chariot associated with wind, transport, and the carriage of tribute.",
"Han_Chinese": "The Han Chinese are an East Asian ethnic group native to China and the largest ethnic group in the world, numbering over 1.4 billion, roughly a sixth of all humanity. They make up about nine-tenths of the population of China and the great majority on Taiwan, and form large communities across Southeast Asia and beyond. Named after the Han dynasty, they share the Chinese written script and a common cultural heritage, though they remain internally diverse, speaking many varieties of Chinese.",
"Motif": "A motif is a recurring element — an image, symbol, idea, or narrative unit — that appears repeatedly within a single work or across many works, helping to develop and reinforce its themes. In literature, visual art, and music it is a distinct, repeatable component whose recurrence lends structure and meaning, such as a phrase, a color, a shape, or a short musical figure. In folklore and mythology a motif is a standard, widely diffused story element, for example a great flood, a trickster, or a magical helper, and the term derives from the French motif, meaning a dominant idea or theme.",
"Hanzi": "Hanzi (漢字) are the logographic characters used to write the Chinese language, and historically Japanese, Korean, and Vietnamese as well, each character generally standing for a meaningful syllable or morpheme rather than for a sound alone. They number in the tens of thousands, with more than a hundred thousand distinct forms identified overall, though only a few thousand are needed for everyday literacy. Among the writing systems independently invented in human history, they are the only one to have remained in continuous use.",
"Chinese_language": "Chinese (漢語) is a group of Sinitic language varieties forming the largest branch of the Sino-Tibetan language family, spoken natively by the Han Chinese majority and many minority peoples. Its varieties, including Mandarin, Cantonese, and Wu, share a common written form yet are frequently mutually unintelligible in speech. The language is typically tonal, using pitch contours to distinguish words, and it has the largest number of native speakers of any language.",
"Austronesia": "Austronesia is the vast region of the world settled by Austronesian-speaking peoples, extending from Taiwan and Maritime Southeast Asia across the islands of the Pacific to Madagascar in the west, Easter Island in the east, and New Zealand in the south. Its inhabitants spread through a series of seafaring migrations over several thousand years, beginning with expansions out of Taiwan around 3000 BCE and reaching the remotest Pacific islands only in the past millennium. The peoples of this region carry the Austronesian languages, one of the largest and most geographically widespread language families on Earth.",
"Tibetan_language": "Tibetan (བོད་སྐད་) is a Tibeto-Burman language of the Sino-Tibetan family spoken by the Tibetan people across the Tibetan Plateau and neighbouring Himalayan regions of Asia. It exists in a wide range of dialects and is written in the Tibetan script, an abugida of Indic origin dating from around the seventh century. Its classical written form carries a rich literary tradition and serves above all as the language of Tibetan Buddhist scripture.",
"Danya_Mountain": "Danya Mountain (丹崖山), whose name means cinnabar cliff after the reddish-brown hue of its rock, is a low seaside cliff-hill on the northern coast of the Shandong Peninsula at Penglai in Shandong Province. Rising only about fifty metres yet ending in a sheer wall that drops abruptly to the sea, it forms a steep headland above the water. It is best known as the elevated site on which the Penglai Pavilion was built.",
"Four_Great_Towers_of_China": "The Four Great Towers of China (四大名樓) are a traditional grouping of celebrated historic multi-storey towers and pavilions long renowned in classical Chinese poetry and painting. Three members are consistently listed: the Yellow Crane Tower at Wuhan in Hubei, the Yueyang Tower at Yueyang in Hunan, and the Pavilion of Prince Teng at Nanchang in Jiangxi. The fourth place is assigned variously, most often to the Penglai Pavilion in Shandong or the Guanque Tower in Shanxi.",
"Fata_Morgana": "A Fata Morgana is a complex form of superior mirage seen in a narrow band just above the horizon, in which distant objects such as ships, coastlines, or cliffs appear stacked, stretched, and transformed into shifting, castle-like shapes. It arises when rays of light passing through atmospheric layers of sharply different temperatures are bent, producing several inverted and upright images piled on top of one another. The name comes from the Italian for Morgan le Fay, the Arthurian sorceress once thought to conjure such illusions as false castles or land in the air to lure sailors astray.",
"Fanghu": "Fanghu (方壺), also called Fangzhang, is one of the mythical mountain-isles of the immortals said to lie in the Bohai Sea in Chinese mythology. It is imagined as a paradise where immortals dwell and where the trees of the isles bear fruits that grant immortality and everlasting youth to those who eat them, its terraces described as made of gold, jade, and onyx. Named alongside Penglai and Yingzhou among the sacred isles sought by rulers and seekers of the elixir of life, including the envoys sent by Qin Shi Huang, it is described in the Liezi as an ethereal mountain adrift on the waves.",
"Yingzhou": "Yingzhou (瀛洲) is one of the fabled isles of the immortals said to lie in the sea east of China, a mountainous paradise where deathless beings dwell amid palaces of jade and gold. It is named in early texts alongside Penglai and Fangzhang, and its slopes are described as bearing sweet springs and the divine herbs that confer immortality. Belief in these islands prompted Chinese emperors to dispatch seaborne expeditions in search of them and of the elixir of eternal life.",
"Lie_Yukou": "Lie Yukou (列禦寇), also honored as Liezi, was a semi-legendary Daoist philosopher traditionally placed in the fifth century BCE, during the Warring States period. He is credited as the author of the Liezi, a Daoist classic of parables and dialogues that bears his name, and in legend he was said to be able to ride upon the wind. Very little can be reliably established about his life, and some scholars have argued that he was a purely literary figure rather than a historical person.",
"Jasper": "Jasper is an opaque, fine-grained variety of silica, classed as an impure form of chalcedony or microcrystalline quartz. Iron oxides and other mineral impurities color it red, yellow, brown, or green, and in some specimens produce banded, spotted, or picture-like patterns. Valued as a gemstone and ornamental stone since antiquity, it has been carved into beads, seals, vessels, amulets, and inlays by many cultures.",
"Weak_River": "The Weak River (弱水), or Weak Water, is a mythical river of Chinese legend whose current was said to be so weak and insubstantial that nothing could float upon it, not even a feather. It flowed near the paradise of Kunlun, the mountain home of the immortals presided over by the Queen Mother of the West, and served in myth as an impassable barrier guarding that realm from the unworthy. The river appears throughout classical Chinese poetry and prose, including as an obstacle the pilgrims must cross in the novel Journey to the West.",
"Sumeru": "Sumeru, also called Mount Meru, is the sacred mountain that stands at the centre of the universe in the cosmologies of Hinduism, Buddhism, and Jainism, and is often described as golden. Rising to an immense height and encircled by concentric seas and mountain ranges, it forms the axis around which the sun, moon, planets, and surrounding continents are arranged. Its slopes and summit are the dwelling places of various gods, with the heaven of the devas said to lie at its peak.",
"Qinghai": "Qinghai (青海) is a large, sparsely populated province in northwestern China that occupies much of the northeastern Tibetan Plateau. It takes its name from Qinghai Lake, the largest saltwater lake in the country, and contains the source regions of the Yellow, Yangtze, and Mekong rivers. Its population includes Tibetan, Han, Hui, Mongol, Tu, Salar, and other peoples.",
"Fengjian": "Fengjian (封建) was the decentralized system of governance of the Zhou dynasty, under which the king granted territories to royal kinsmen, allied clans, and meritorious followers who ruled them as hereditary regional lords, the zhuhou. These lords owed the crown homage, tribute, attendance at court, military service in wartime, and ritual allegiance to the Son of Heaven, binding a kin-based network of vassal states to the royal house. The term is commonly rendered into English as feudalism, though the arrangement rested chiefly on lineage bonds and ritual obligation rather than on codified law, and lordships were in principle revocable and reappointed by the crown even as they generally passed to heirs.",
"Ritual_vessel": "A ritual vessel is a container made and used for religious or ceremonial purposes rather than for everyday domestic tasks. Such vessels serve to hold food, wine, water, incense, or other offerings during rites of worship, sacrifice, and libation, and their forms are often shaped by the specific ceremonies they support. Fashioned across many cultures from materials such as bronze, gold, ceramic, jade, or stone, they are frequently richly decorated and treated as sacred or prestigious objects.",
"Gonghe_regency": "The Gonghe regency (共和) was a fourteen-year period of the Western Zhou dynasty during which government was carried on by regents after King Li was driven into exile by a popular uprising. It ended when his son took the throne as King Xuan of Zhou. Its first year, 841 BCE, is traditionally regarded as the start of continuously and precisely dated Chinese history.",
"Quanrong": "The Quanrong (犬戎), whose name is sometimes rendered as the Dog Rong, were a nomadic people of the northwestern frontier of ancient China, reckoned among the Rong tribes. In 771 BCE they joined the Marquess of Shen in an attack on the Western Zhou capital of Haojing, killing King You and sacking the city. This assault forced the Zhou court to flee eastward, bringing the Western Zhou period to an end.",
"Marquess": "A marquess is a hereditary title of nobility that in several European systems ranks below a duke and above a count or earl. The rank was historically associated with the government of a march, a border territory or frontier district whose defence demanded a lord of high standing. Western writers have also used the word to render comparable grades of nobility in other societies, and the title reached English from Old French, ultimately from the notion of a march or frontier.",
"Emperor_Hui_of_Han": "Emperor Hui of Han (漢惠帝), personal name Liu Ying, was the second emperor of the Western Han dynasty, reigning from 195 to 188 BCE from the capital at Chang'an. The son of the dynasty's founder Emperor Gaozu of Han and Empress Lü, he came to the throne as a teenager, and real power was held throughout his reign by his mother, who ruled as Empress Dowager Lü. Recorded as gentle-natured but overwhelmed by governance and by his mother's dominance and cruelty toward rivals, he withdrew from state affairs and died young in 188 BCE.",
"Emperor_Qianshao_of_Han": "Emperor Qianshao of Han (漢前少帝) was a boy ruler of the Western Han dynasty who reigned from 188 to 184 BCE as a puppet controlled by his grandmother, the regent Grand Empress Dowager Lü Zhi. A son of Emperor Hui of Han by a concubine, he was placed on the throne as a child after his father's death and raised as the son of Empress Zhang Yan, exercising no real authority while the Lü clan governed. He was deposed, secretly imprisoned, and put to death after he learned that his birth mother had been killed and rashly declared that he would take revenge when he grew up, and later historians commonly omit him from the official list of Han emperors.",
"Emperor_Houshao_of_Han": "Emperor Houshao of Han (漢後少帝), personal name Liu Hong, was a child emperor of the Western Han dynasty who reigned from 184 to 180 BCE as a son of Emperor Hui of Han and grandson of the Grand Empress Dowager Lü. He was installed on the throne after his elder brother Emperor Qianshao of Han was deposed, and throughout his reign real power lay entirely with the Grand Empress Dowager Lü, who governed as regent and made him a mere figurehead. After her death in 180 BCE, officials led by Chen Ping and Zhou Bo purged the Lü clan, deposed Houshao on the assertion that he was no true son of Emperor Hui of Han, and had him killed, clearing the way for his uncle to take the throne as Emperor Wen of Han.",
"Emperor_Jing_of_Han": "Emperor Jing of Han (漢景帝) was the sixth emperor of the Western Han dynasty of China, reigning from 157 to 141 BCE as the son and successor of Emperor Wen of Han. Together their reigns are remembered as the Rule of Wen and Jing, a prosperous period marked by low taxes, light punishments, and the accumulation of state reserves. He suppressed the Rebellion of the Seven States in 154 BCE and afterward curbed the autonomy of the semi-independent princely kingdoms, strengthening the authority of the central government.",
"Emperor_Zhao_of_Han": "Emperor Zhao of Han (漢昭帝), personal name Liu Fuling, was an emperor of the Western Han dynasty who reigned from 87 to 74 BCE. The youngest son of Emperor Wu of Han, he came to the throne as a child of about eight and ruled under the regency of the powerful minister Huo Guang. During this period the state recovered from the fiscal and social strains of Emperor Wu of Han's long military campaigns through lowered taxes and reduced government spending, and a court debate in 81 BCE over the monopolies on salt, iron, and wine led to the abolition of the wine monopoly.",
"Liu_He_(Marquis_of_Haihun)": "Liu He (劉賀) was a grandson of Emperor Wu of the Western Han dynasty who was briefly enthroned as emperor in 74 BCE, following the death of the childless Emperor Zhao of Han. After a reign of only 27 days he was deposed by the powerful regent Huo Guang, who charged him with numerous acts of misconduct and impropriety during the mourning period, and he was later demoted to Marquis of Haihun with a fief in what is now Jiangxi. His richly furnished tomb, containing tonnes of coins, gold, jade, and other artifacts, was discovered in 2011 and has become one of the most significant Han-era archaeological finds.",
"Emperor_Xuan_of_Han": "Emperor Xuan of Han (漢宣帝) was the tenth emperor of the Western Han dynasty, a great-grandson of Emperor Wu of Han who reigned from 74 to 48 BCE from the capital at Chang'an. Born after his branch of the imperial family was purged, he grew up among commoners outside the palace before being placed on the throne by the regent Huo Guang, an unusual background that gave him firsthand knowledge of ordinary people's hardships. His reign is conventionally regarded as a high point of Western Han good government, marked by administrative competence, economic recovery, and frontier success, including the submission of the Xiongnu and the extension of Han authority into the Western Regions.",
"Emperor_Yuan_of_Han": "Emperor Yuan of Han (漢元帝) was the eleventh emperor of the Western Han dynasty, reigning from 48 to 33 BCE as the son and successor of Emperor Xuan of Han and the father of Emperor Cheng of Han. A devoted student of Confucian learning, he elevated classical scholars to high office and promoted Confucianism as the guiding creed of government. His reign nonetheless saw the growing sway of consort clans, notably the Wang family of his empress Wang Zhengjun, together with powerful eunuchs, a factional dominance that gradually weakened the dynasty.",
"Emperor_Cheng_of_Han": "Emperor Cheng of Han (漢成帝), personal name Liu Ao, was an emperor of the Western Han dynasty who reigned from 33 to 7 BCE as the successor to his father Emperor Yuan of Han. During his reign the affairs of government fell increasingly into the hands of the family of his mother, the powerful Empress Dowager Wang, whose brothers and kinsmen were made marquesses and took successive command of the administration as regents. This concentration of authority in the Wang clan, culminating in the rise of his cousin Wang Mang, opened the way for the dynasty's later decline and the eventual usurpation that founded the Xin interregnum.",
"Emperor_Ai_of_Han": "Emperor Ai of Han (漢哀帝), personal name Liu Xin, was an emperor of the Western Han dynasty who reigned from 7 to 1 BCE, having been chosen as heir by his childless uncle Emperor Cheng of Han. He died in his mid-twenties without an heir of his own and was succeeded by his young cousin, who reigned as Emperor Ping of Han. He is best remembered in later anecdote for his devotion to his favourite Dong Xian, an attachment that gave rise to the phrase the passion of the cut sleeve, from the story that Ai cut off his own sleeve rather than wake the sleeping Dong Xian.",
"Emperor_Ping_of_Han": "Emperor Ping of Han (漢平帝), personal name Liu Kan, was an emperor of the Western Han dynasty who reigned from 1 BCE until his death in 6 CE. Having come to the throne as a child of about eight, he ruled only in name, with all real power held by the regent Wang Mang, his father-in-law, who governed the empire throughout his reign. Tradition holds that Wang Mang had the young emperor poisoned, and Wang Mang went on to usurp the throne and found the short-lived Xin dynasty.",
"Ruzi_Ying": "Ruzi Ying (孺子嬰), personal name Liu Ying, was the last ruler of the Western Han dynasty, designated as heir in 6 CE while Wang Mang governed as acting emperor after the death of the childless Emperor Ping of Han. An infant of about one year when chosen, he was given the title of heir apparent but was never formally enthroned, and Wang Mang wielded actual power throughout the period. When Wang Mang founded the Xin dynasty in 9 CE he set Ruzi Ying aside, demoting him to a ducal rank and keeping him in confinement.",
"Gengshi_Emperor": "the Gengshi Emperor (更始帝), personal name Liu Xuan, was a member of the Han imperial clan descended from Emperor Jing of the Western Han, and he reigned from 23 to 25 CE as the ruler of a short-lived Han restoration. He was proclaimed emperor by the Lülin rebels who had risen against and overthrown Wang Mang, whose Xin dynasty had displaced the Han, and he took the reign name Gengshi, meaning new beginning. Regarded as a weak sovereign who left affairs to relatives and favourites, he was defeated by the Red Eyebrows rebels, who deposed and strangled him in 25 CE, after which his kinsman Liu Xiu founded the Eastern Han.",
"Emperor_Ming_of_Han": "Emperor Ming of Han (漢明帝) was the second emperor of the Eastern Han dynasty, ruling from 57 to 75 CE as the son and successor of the dynasty's founder, Emperor Guangwu of Han. He consolidated the restored Han state through firm administration, tighter control over the imperial clan and officials, and campaigns that reasserted Han influence over the Western Regions. Tradition dates the first official introduction of Buddhism to China to his reign, holding that a dream of a golden figure prompted him to dispatch envoys westward, an account later linked to the founding of the White Horse Temple at the capital, Luoyang.",
"Emperor_Zhang_of_Han": "Emperor Zhang of Han (漢章帝), personal name Liu Da, was the third emperor of the Eastern Han dynasty, reigning from 75 to 88 CE as the son and successor of Emperor Ming of Han. His reign, marked by lowered taxes, a lenient penal policy, and the promotion of Confucian scholarship, is remembered together with that of his father as the flourishing Rule of Ming and Zhang, regarded as a golden age of the Eastern Han. In 79 CE he convened the White Tiger Hall conference, a gathering of scholars summoned to debate and settle divergent interpretations of the Confucian classics, whose proceedings were later compiled by Ban Gu into the treatise known as the Baihu tong.",
"Emperor_He_of_Han": "Emperor He of Han (漢和帝), personal name Liu Zhao, was the fourth emperor of the Eastern Han dynasty and a son of Emperor Zhang of Han, reigning from 88 to 106 CE. Having come to the throne as a boy of about nine, he ruled at first under the regency of his adoptive mother, Empress Dowager Dou, until in 92 he broke the power of her family with the help of the eunuch Zheng Zhong and took direct control of the government. Often regarded as the last vigorous ruler of the Eastern Han before its long decline, his reign nonetheless entrenched the political influence of palace eunuchs, whose growing dominance would trouble the dynasty in the generations that followed.",
"Emperor_Shang_of_Han": "Emperor Shang of Han (漢殤帝), personal name Liu Long, was the fifth emperor of the Eastern Han dynasty, the son and successor of Emperor He of Han, who was placed on the throne while still an infant with real power held by the regent Empress Dowager Deng Sui. Proclaimed ruler when barely one hundred days old, he reigned nominally for a matter of months in 106 CE before dying that September, still short of his first birthday. He is remembered as the shortest-lived of the Han emperors and among the youngest to accede in Chinese history, and little is recorded of his brief reign beyond the dominance of the Deng consort clan.",
"Emperor_An_of_Han": "Emperor An of Han (漢安帝) was the sixth emperor of the Eastern Han dynasty, a grandson of Emperor Zhang of Han who reigned from 106 to 125 CE from the capital at Luoyang. Enthroned as a child, he ruled at first only in name under the regency of Empress Dowager Deng, who retained real authority until her death in 121 CE. His era was marked by frequent natural disasters, persistent frontier troubles with the Qiang and Xianbei peoples, and deepening corruption at court, where he came to rely heavily on eunuchs and the family of his consort.",
"Marquess_of_Beixiang": "the Marquess of Beixiang (北鄉侯), personal name Liu Yi, was a child ruler of the Eastern Han dynasty raised to the imperial throne in 125 CE by the Empress Dowager Yan and her faction after the sudden death of Emperor An of Han. His nominal reign lasted only about seven months, from roughly May to December of that year, before he fell ill and died, whereupon eunuchs led by Sun Cheng overthrew the Yan clan and enthroned Emperor Shun of Han. Because his brief tenure was regarded as short and of questionable legitimacy, he received no temple name or reign era and is often omitted from the standard list of the dynasty's emperors.",
"Emperor_Shun_of_Han": "Emperor Shun of Han (漢順帝), personal name Liu Bao (劉保), was an emperor of the Eastern Han dynasty who reigned from 125 to 144 CE and was the only son of Emperor An of Han. He came to the throne as a boy after eunuchs loyal to him, led by Sun Cheng, staged a palace coup against Empress Dowager Yan, who had placed a rival on the throne following Emperor An of Han's death. His reign saw the further entrenchment of both eunuch power, as eunuch-marquesses were permitted to pass their fiefs to adopted sons, and consort-clan dominance, as government was largely entrusted to the family of his empress Liang Na, notably Liang Shang and the corrupt Liang Ji.",
"Emperor_Chong_of_Han": "Emperor Chong of Han (漢沖帝), personal name Liu Bing, was the ninth emperor of the Eastern Han dynasty and the only son of Emperor Shun of Han, born to a low-ranking concubine known as Beautiful Lady Yu and placed on the throne as an infant in 144 CE upon his father's death. His nominal reign, lasting only from his accession in the autumn of 144 CE until his death in early 145 CE, was conducted under the regency of the empress dowager Liang Na and her powerful brother Liang Ji, who controlled the court through the Liang consort clan. Because he was around one year old at his accession and died at about the age of two, no acts of his own governance are recorded, and his brief reign is remembered chiefly as an episode of consort-clan domination of the Eastern Han court.",
"Emperor_Zhi_of_Han": "Emperor Zhi of Han (漢質帝), personal name Liu Zuan, was an emperor of the Eastern Han dynasty who reigned from 145 to 146 CE, installed as a child of about seven by the powerful consort clan of Empress Dowager Liang. Real authority lay with the empress dowager's brother, the general Liang Ji, who dominated the court and effectively ruled in the boy emperor's name. Perceptive despite his youth, Emperor Zhi of Han is recorded to have openly called Liang Ji an arrogant general, and in 146 the offended Liang Ji had him poisoned, ending his reign after little more than a year.",
"Emperor_Huan_of_Han": "Emperor Huan of Han (漢桓帝), personal name Liu Zhi, was the twenty-seventh emperor of the Han dynasty, reigning over the Eastern Han from 146 to 168 CE. Placed on the throne as a boy under the regency dominated by the general Liang Ji and the Liang consort clan, in 159 he destroyed the overmighty Liang family with the help of palace eunuchs, whom he then permitted to dominate the government. Under his rule the first of the Partisan Prohibitions was imposed in 166, when reformist scholar-officials and university students who criticized eunuch power were labeled factionalists and barred from office.",
"Emperor_Ling_of_Han": "Emperor Ling of Han (漢靈帝) was an emperor of the Eastern Han dynasty who reigned from 168 to 189 CE, having been placed on the throne as a boy following the death of the childless Emperor Huan of Han. Indifferent to governing, he left power largely in the hands of favoured eunuchs and consort-clan officials while indulging in luxury, and to meet fiscal shortfalls he instituted the open sale of government offices and ranks for cash from around 178 CE. This misgovernment, the resulting corruption, and heavy popular hardship helped provoke the Yellow Turban Rebellion of 184 CE, and the strife following his death in 189 hastened the disintegration of Han central authority.",
"Emperor_Shao_of_Han": "Emperor Shao of Han (漢少帝), personal name Liu Bian, was an emperor of the Eastern Han dynasty who was enthroned in 189 CE as a young teenager following the death of his father, Emperor Ling of Han. His brief reign lasted only a few months amid the court turmoil that erupted after the massacre of the palace eunuchs, during which the warlord Dong Zhuo seized control of the capital Luoyang. Dong Zhuo deposed him later that same year and installed his younger half-brother Liu Xie as Emperor Xian of Han, and the deposed boy was forced to commit suicide by poison early in the following year.",
"Cao_Rui": "Cao Rui (曹叡) was the second emperor of the state of Cao Wei during the Three Kingdoms period, reigning from 226 to 239 CE as the son and successor of Cao Pi and being posthumously honoured as Emperor Ming of Wei. During his reign his frontier generals repeatedly held off the northern campaigns of Zhuge Liang's Shu Han as well as incursions by Eastern Wu, keeping the Wei realm intact along its southern and western borders. He also devoted lavish resources to grand palace building that strained the treasury, and dying without a surviving natural heir he left the adopted child Cao Fang on the throne under the regents Cao Shuang and Sima Yi.",
"Cao_Fang": "Cao Fang (曹芳) was the third emperor of the state of Cao Wei during the Three Kingdoms period, reigning from 239 to 254 CE with his capital at Luoyang. Adopted as heir by the second Wei emperor Cao Rui, he came to the throne as a young boy and ruled under the joint regency of Cao Shuang and Sima Yi, after whose deaths real power passed to Sima Yi's son Sima Shi. In 254 he was deposed by Sima Shi as the Sima clan tightened its grip on the Wei court, was reduced to the rank of a prince, and lived out his remaining years without political power.",
"Cao_Mao": "Cao Mao (曹髦) was the fourth emperor of the state of Cao Wei during the Three Kingdoms period, reigning from 254 to 260 CE after the regent Sima Shi deposed his predecessor Cao Fang and enthroned him as a boy of about thirteen. Remembered as intelligent and studious, he chafed under the domination of the Sima clan, whose control of the government left him a largely powerless figurehead. In 260 CE he personally led a small band of retainers in a desperate attempt to overthrow the regent Sima Zhao, and was struck down and killed during the failed coup, an act of regicide that further exposed the Sima family's grip on the throne.",
"Cao_Huan": "Cao Huan (曹奐) was the fifth and last emperor of the state of Cao Wei during China's Three Kingdoms period, placed on the throne in 260 CE after the regent Sima Zhao's forces killed his predecessor Cao Mao. Throughout his reign he was a powerless figurehead under the domination of the Sima family, who held real authority at the Wei capital. In 266 CE he abdicated in favour of Sima Zhao's son Sima Yan, ending the Wei regime and bringing the Jin dynasty into being, after which he was granted the title Prince of Chenliu and was posthumously honoured as Emperor Yuan of Wei.",
"Sun_Liang": "Sun Liang (孫亮) was the second emperor of Eastern Wu during the Three Kingdoms period, reigning from 252 to 258 CE as the youngest son of the state's founder, Sun Quan. Enthroned as a child upon his father's death, he ruled under a succession of contending regents, beginning with Zhuge Ke and passing to Sun Jun and then Sun Chen amid recurring coups and executions at court. After Sun Liang attempted to break free of Sun Chen's control, the regent deposed him in 258 and installed his elder brother Sun Xiu, and Sun Liang died two years later.",
"Sun_Xiu": "Sun Xiu (孫休) was the third emperor of Eastern Wu, one of the three contending states of the Three Kingdoms period, reigning from 258 to 264 CE. A son of the dynasty's founder Sun Quan, he came to the throne after his younger brother Sun Liang was deposed by the regent Sun Chen, whom Sun Xiu subsequently overthrew and had executed. Known posthumously as Emperor Jing of Wu, he was noted for his studiousness and promotion of classical learning, founding an imperial academy during his brief reign.",
"Sun_Hao": "Sun Hao (孫皓) was the fourth and last emperor of Eastern Wu, one of the three states of the Three Kingdoms period, reigning from 264 to 280 CE after succeeding his uncle Sun Xiu, who is known posthumously as Emperor Jing of Wu. Chinese historiography remembers him as a cruel and extravagant tyrant whose superstition, heavy drinking, and mismanagement hastened the decline of his state. When the Jin dynasty launched a multi-pronged invasion down the Yangtze, Sun Hao surrendered in 280, an event that ended Eastern Wu and reunified China under Jin.",
"Castration": "Castration is the removal or permanent deactivation of the testicles in males, or of the ovaries in females, which halts the production of sex hormones and ends the capacity to reproduce. It has been performed on humans and animals since antiquity for a range of purposes, including livestock management, judicial punishment, the creation of certain religious or social roles, and medical treatment. When carried out on males before puberty it prevents many secondary sexual characteristics, such as a deepened voice and facial hair, from developing.",
"Eunuch": "A eunuch is a man who has been castrated, especially one formerly employed in a royal or noble household. Across many civilizations eunuchs served as guardians of harems and women's quarters, palace attendants, and trusted officials, and some rose to considerable power as administrators, generals, or advisers to rulers. Because they could father no heirs and so were unlikely to establish a rival dynasty, they were often regarded as uniquely loyal servants and were granted access and influence denied to other courtiers.",
"Sexual_dimorphism": "Sexual dimorphism is the condition in which the two sexes of a species differ systematically in characteristics beyond their reproductive organs, such as body size, colouration, ornamentation, or overall form. It occurs widely across the animal kingdom and arises largely through sexual selection and the differing ecological roles of the sexes, as competition for mates favours conspicuous traits in one sex. A common pattern appears in many birds, where males display bright plumage that attracts mates while females remain drab to stay camouflaged while nesting.",
"Iridescence": "Iridescence is the property of certain surfaces that appear to change colour as the angle of view or illumination shifts, producing gleaming, rainbow-like hues. It is a form of structural colour, arising not from pigments but from microscopic surface structures that split and interfere with light waves rather than absorbing particular wavelengths. It is seen in soap bubbles and oil films, in seashells, beetle shells, and butterfly wings, and in the feathers of many birds.",
"Wattle_(anatomy)": "A wattle is a fleshy, often brightly coloured fold or lobe of skin that hangs from the head or neck of certain birds, including chickens, turkeys, and some pheasants. Usually larger and more vivid in males, the wattle functions in visual display and courtship, its rich blood supply flushing it with colour to signal health and vigour to potential mates. Because it is highly vascular, a wattle also aids thermoregulation by radiating away excess body heat, and comparable fleshy growths appear in a few mammals such as some goats and pig breeds.",
"Leopard": "The leopard (Panthera pardus) is a large wild cat native to much of Africa and Asia, recognized by its tawny to golden coat patterned with dark, rosette-shaped spots that serve as camouflage. A powerful, stealthy, and adaptable solitary predator, it is an accomplished climber that often hauls its kills into trees to keep them from scavengers, and it thrives across habitats ranging from rainforest and savanna to desert and mountain. It has the widest distribution of any wild cat, ranging across more than seventy countries.",
"Kunlun": "Kunlun (崑崙山) is a sacred mountain of Chinese mythology, envisioned as a towering paradise at the western edge of the world that serves as a pillar linking earth to the heavens and as a dwelling of immortals, where the herbs and fruits of deathlessness grow. It is the mountain palace of the Queen Mother of the West, and it is ringed by the Weak River, whose waters are so insubstantial that nothing can float upon them, barring all but the worthy from ascending. The name also belongs to a real and immense mountain range that stretches for more than three thousand kilometres across western China, forming the northern rim of the Tibetan Plateau.",
"Jasper_Pool": "The Jasper Pool (瑤池), also rendered as the Jade Pool, is a fabled lake beside the palace of the Queen Mother of the West atop Mount Kunlun in Chinese mythology. There the goddess hosts the Feast of Peaches, a lavish banquet at which the assembled immortals gather to celebrate and are served the peaches of immortality that ripen only after long ages. Its waters are themselves linked to immortality and divine vitality, and the pool ranks among the most storied features of her western paradise.",
"Peach_Banquet": "The Peach Banquet (蟠桃會) is a legendary feast in Chinese mythology hosted by the Queen Mother of the West, at which the immortals gather in her palace to eat the peaches of immortality, marvellous fruit that blossoms and ripens only once in several thousand years. The gathering is famed from the novel Journey to the West, where the Monkey King Sun Wukong, appointed guardian of the peach orchard, throws the celebration into chaos by devouring the sacred peaches and the elixirs of immortality before the guests arrive. Having consumed them, he gains lasting immortality and enhanced powers, and his rampage brings the wrath of Heaven down upon him.",
"Classic_of_the_Divine_and_the_Strange": "The Classic of the Divine and the Strange (神異經), or Shenyijing, is an early Chinese text describing marvellous creatures, strange peoples, and wondrous lands at the edges of the known world. Traditionally attributed to the Han-dynasty courtier Dongfang Shuo, it is generally regarded by scholars as a later compilation of the Southern Dynasties period, and it survives only in fragments preserved in quotations. Arranged by the cardinal directions, it catalogues fantastic beings such as giants, monsters, and spirits said to dwell in remote regions.",
"Black_bear": "A black bear is either of two dark-coated bear species, chiefly the American black bear (Ursus americanus) of North America and the Asian black bear (Ursus thibetanus) of the forests and mountains of Asia. Medium-sized and usually black-furred, though the colour can vary, they are omnivorous and agile climbers that feed on fruit, nuts, insects, and small animals. The Asian black bear has a distinctive pale crescent across its chest, from which it takes the popular name moon bear.",
"Carpenter's_square": "A carpenter's square is an L-shaped tool with two straight arms meeting at a right angle, used to mark and check square corners and straight lines in woodworking and construction. It is usually made of metal or wood, the arms are marked with a scale of measurements, and the longer arm is called the blade while the shorter is the tongue. It has served builders and carpenters since antiquity to lay out right angles and to test that surfaces are true.",
"Matriarchy": "Matriarchy is a form of social organization in which women, and mothers in particular, hold the central roles of political leadership, moral authority, and control of property. In such a system descent, inheritance, or residence may be reckoned through the female line, so that name, kinship, and the transmission of goods pass from mother to daughter. Anthropologists debate whether fully matriarchal societies have existed on a large scale, though many cultures display matrilineal features, where lineage is traced through mothers, or matrifocal ones, where women occupy the emotional and organizational core of family life.",
"Sea_turtle": "A sea turtle is any of several large marine reptiles equipped with a streamlined shell, non-retractable head and limbs, and long paddle-like flippers that make them powerful ocean swimmers. They spend almost their entire lives at sea and are strong navigators, with females coming ashore only to bury clutches of eggs on sandy beaches and some species migrating thousands of kilometres across ocean basins between feeding and nesting grounds. Long-lived and very slow to reach maturity, sea turtles are represented by seven living species, most of which are classified as threatened or endangered.",
"Bixi": "Bixi (贔屭) is a creature of Chinese mythology, reckoned among the nine sons of the dragon and depicted as a powerful dragon-headed tortoise. It is renowned for bearing immense weights on its back, most famously the great stone stelae and memorial tablets that rest upon carved Bixi plinths at temples, tombs, and palaces. As an image it embodies strength, endurance, and longevity, and its stele-bearing form became especially widespread during the Ming and Qing dynasties.",
"Plough": "A plough is a farming implement used to cut, lift, and turn over the topsoil in preparation for sowing seed, breaking up the ground while burying weeds and crop residue so that fresh soil is brought to the surface. Its working part is a share or blade that slices the earth and a curved mouldboard that rolls the loosened soil aside to form a long trench called a furrow. Drawn in early forms by oxen and other draught animals and later by tractors, it is among the oldest and most important agricultural tools.",
"Agriculture": "Agriculture is the practice of cultivating the soil to grow crops and of raising animals for food, fibre, and other products, encompassing the plants that are grown, the livestock that are herded, and the tools, techniques, and knowledge used to work the land. It developed gradually from foraging beginning around eleven thousand years ago, as people domesticated wild plants and animals in several regions of the world. By producing food surpluses, it allowed communities to settle in one place and gave rise to the first villages, towns, and civilizations.",
"Fire_drill": "A fire-drill is a friction device for kindling fire, in which a pointed wooden spindle is spun rapidly against a wooden baseboard so that the heat of friction chars the wood and produces a glowing ember. The ember, formed from hot wood dust that collects in a notch cut in the baseboard, is transferred to a bundle of dry tinder and blown into flame. The spindle is turned by hand, by a bow that draws a cord back and forth, or by a pump mechanism, making it one of the oldest fire-making methods and one used by peoples across the world.",
"Suiming": "The Country of Suiming (燧明國) is a far-off land in ancient Chinese legend where the four seasons and the alternation of day and night were unknown, its people never died, and a great fire-tree grew whose canopy spread over ten thousand acres. A sage who journeyed there saw a bird pecking at the tree and striking bright sparks from its wood, and from this he learned to make fire by drilling small branches together, becoming the culture hero Suiren. The tale is preserved in the Shiyiji, a fourth-century collection of marvels compiled by Wang Jia during the Eastern Jin dynasty.",
"Silk_reel": "A silk reel is a device used to unwind the long, fine filaments from softened silkworm cocoons and wind several of them together into a single continuous thread of raw silk. In its traditional form it consists of a rotating reel, turned by hand or by a foot treadle, that draws the filaments from cocoons floating in a basin of warm water, which softens the natural gum binding each cocoon so its thread can be found and pulled free. Because a single filament is too fine to use on its own, the ends from several cocoons are gathered and drawn off together, adhering into one strand as they are wound onto the reel.",
"Loom": "A loom is a frame or machine used for weaving, holding a set of lengthwise threads called the warp under tension so that crosswise threads called the weft can be interlaced through them to form cloth. Most looms open a gap in the warp called a shed, into which the weft is passed and then beaten firmly into place, building up the fabric row by row. Ranging from simple handworked frames to large power-driven industrial machines, the loom is among the oldest and most important tools of textile making, with examples attested since the Neolithic period.",
"Tea": "Tea is an aromatic beverage prepared by steeping the cured leaves of the evergreen shrub Camellia sinensis in hot water, and it is one of the most widely consumed drinks in the world. The plant is native to the borderlands of East Asia, and its leaves are processed by controlling their oxidation to yield types such as green, black, and oolong tea. Most tea contains caffeine, and it is drunk both plain and with additions such as milk, sugar, or spices across many cultures.",
"Cangjie_input_method": "The Cangjie input method (倉頡輸入法) is a system for typing Chinese characters on a standard keyboard by decomposing each character into a sequence of graphical root shapes, roughly two dozen of which are assigned to the letter keys, so that characters are entered according to their visual structure rather than their pronunciation. Devised in 1976 by the engineer Chu Bong-Foo and named after Cangjie, the legendary inventor of Chinese writing, it was the first such method built around the QWERTY keyboard. It is designed primarily for entering traditional characters and remains in wide use, particularly in Hong Kong and Taiwan.",
"Cangjiepian": "The Cangjiepian 倉頡篇 is an early Chinese primer for learning to write, compiled around 220 BCE during the Qin dynasty as part of the standardization of the script and traditionally credited to the chancellor Li Si. It presented characters in the unified small-seal forms and arranged them in rhyming four-character lines so that students and scribes could memorize and recite them. Its title honors Cangjie, the legendary inventor of Chinese writing, and though the original work is lost, portions survive through later fragments and commentaries.",
"Zuo_Qiuming": "Zuo Qiuming (左丘明) was a historian and official of the state of Lu during the Spring and Autumn period, remembered as a near-contemporary of Confucius. He is traditionally credited as the author of the Zuo Zhuan, the great narrative commentary on the Spring and Autumn Annals, and of the Guoyu, an account of history arranged state by state, an attribution first advanced by Sima Qian. Little is reliably known of his life, and later and modern scholars have disputed both his authorship of these works and even his exact name, some treating Zuo as an office rather than a surname.",
"Taijitu": "The taijitu (太極圖), meaning diagram of the supreme ultimate, is the well-known Chinese symbol in which a circle is divided by an S-shaped curve into a dark half and a light half, each containing a small dot of the opposite colour. It represents yin and yang as complementary forces that arise from a single source and continually flow into, contain, and balance each other, so that neither exists without the seed of the other. This swirling two-dot form was simplified by the Ming-period scholar Lai Zhide from an earlier layered diagram whose foundational explanation, the Taijitu shuo, was written by the Song-dynasty Neo-Confucian philosopher Zhou Dunyi.",
"Joseph_Needham": "Joseph Needham was a British biochemist, historian of science, and sinologist whose work as head of a British scientific mission to China in the 1940s turned his career toward documenting the nation's scientific and technological past. He initiated and largely wrote Science and Civilisation in China, a monumental multi-volume study cataloguing Chinese contributions to fields such as astronomy, medicine, and engineering, including the invention of paper, printing, gunpowder, and the magnetic compass. His name is attached to the Needham Question, the influential historical problem of why modern science arose in Europe rather than in China despite China's long lead in technology.",
"Jade_Mountain": "The Jade Mountain (玉山) is a peak of Chinese mythology set among the western mountains, named in the Classic of Mountains and Seas as the dwelling place of the goddess Queen Mother of the West. That text describes it as abounding in jade and its resident goddess as a human-bodied figure with a leopard's tail and tiger's fangs who presides over cosmic catastrophes. Later tradition associated the mountain with the Kunlun range, and the name reflects a common Chinese usage in which a jade mountain evokes a gleaming, snow-capped summit.",
"Qu_Yuan": "Qu Yuan (屈原) was a poet and statesman of the state of Chu during the Warring States period, celebrated as one of the earliest and greatest of Chinese poets and traditionally regarded as a foundational author of the Chuci. After his loyal counsel was rejected and he was sent into exile, he is said to have drowned himself in the Miluo River in despair at the decline of his state. His death is commemorated annually by the Dragon Boat Festival, whose boat races recall the search for his body in the water.",
"Naraka": "Naraka, from the Sanskrit naraka, is a hell or purgatorial realm in the cosmologies of Indian religions such as Hinduism, Buddhism, and Jainism, into which a being is reborn to suffer the painful consequences of its bad deeds. Entry and departure are governed by karma rather than divine sentence, and in Hindu accounts the dead are judged and assigned their torments by Yama, the god of death and justice. It is a temporary station within the cycle of rebirth rather than eternal damnation, and once the accumulated negative karma is exhausted the being passes out of it to be reborn elsewhere.",
"Yellow_Springs": "The Yellow Springs (黃泉) are an ancient Chinese conception of the underworld, imagined as a shadowy subterranean realm of springs deep beneath the earth to which the souls of the dead descend. The name joins the character for yellow, the colour associated with the earth, to the character for spring, and it served in early texts as a poetic byword for death and the world below. It appears in the Zuo Zhuan in the oath of Duke Zhuang of Zheng, who swore not to meet his mother again until they reached the Yellow Springs, a vow he satisfied by having a tunnel dug into the earth until it struck spring water, so the two could be reconciled underground.",
"Ten_Courts_of_Hell": "The Ten Courts of Hell (十殿) are the ten successive tribunals of the Chinese underworld Diyu, through which the souls of the dead pass in turn to be judged and made to atone for the wrongs they committed in life before they are sent onward to reincarnation. Each court is presided over by one of the Ten Kings, who examines the offences brought before his hall and metes out the punishments appropriate to them. The tenth and final court determines the form each soul will take in its next life and dispatches it to be reborn.",
"Ten_Kings_of_Hell": "The Ten Kings of Hell (十王) are the ten judge-kings who each preside over one of the ten courts of Diyu, the Chinese underworld, pronouncing judgement on the souls of the dead. They weigh a soul's deeds and assign it rewards or torments in the hells under their authority, and the tenth king, the Wheel-Turning King, determines the form of its next rebirth by reincarnation. Named as a set in the ninth-century Scripture of the Ten Kings, they became central to popular ideas of the afterlife across Chinese Buddhism, Daoism, and folk religion.",
"Bridge_of_Helplessness": "The Bridge of Helplessness (奈何橋), also called the Naihe Bridge, is a bridge in the Chinese underworld of Diyu that the souls of the dead must cross on their path toward reincarnation. As a soul crosses, the old goddess Meng Po serves it a broth of forgetfulness that erases all memory of its past lives and its time in the underworld before it is reborn. Its name is commonly explained as evoking the phrase wu ke nai he, an expression of helpless resignation, though it is also linked to the underworld Nai River over which the bridge is said to stand.",
"Jade_Record": "The Jade Record (玉歷), also called the Yuli, is a Chinese religious and moral tract, presented as a divine revelation, that describes the ten courts of the underworld Diyu and the punishments inflicted there for various sins. It vividly catalogues the tortures awaiting wrongdoers in each court, with the aim of frightening the living into virtuous conduct. Blending folk-Buddhist ideas of karmic retribution with the Daoist notion of a celestial bureaucracy, it circulated widely in the nineteenth century as an illustrated devotional booklet.",
"Fengdu": "In Chinese folk religion Fengdu (酆都) is the capital of the underworld, a shadowy city of the dead governed by an infernal bureaucracy of judges, magistrates, and demon-officers who process the souls of the deceased. The name also belongs to a real town on the northern bank of the Yangtze River in Chongqing, whose Ming Mountain has been linked to the legend since at least the Song dynasty and is home to a temple complex nicknamed the Ghost City. There pilgrims pass through structures such as the Ghost Gate and the Naihe Bridge, where Meng Po serves her broth, and view statues and murals depicting the courts of Diyu and the torments awaiting sinners.",
"Jianwen_Emperor": "The Jianwen Emperor (建文), personal name Zhu Yunwen, was the second emperor of the Ming dynasty, reigning from 1398 to 1402 as the grandson and chosen successor of the founding Hongwu Emperor. Soon after his accession he moved to curb the power of his princely uncles, prompting the Prince of Yan to rise in a rebellion known as the Jingnan campaign. In 1402 the rebel forces captured the capital at Nanjing and the Prince of Yan seized the throne as the Yongle Emperor, after which the young Jianwen Emperor disappeared and his ultimate fate remained unknown.",
"Hongxi_Emperor": "The Hongxi Emperor (洪熙), personal name Zhu Gaochi, was the fourth emperor of the Ming dynasty and the eldest son of the Yongle Emperor, ascending the throne on his father's death in 1424. He reigned for under a year, dying in mid-1425, yet his brief rule is remembered for a decisive turn toward benevolent and frugal government, including halting the costly maritime expeditions and other extravagant projects of the preceding reign. He rehabilitated many officials who had been punished or disgraced under his father and restructured the administration around trusted advisors, a course continued by his son the Xuande Emperor.",
"Xuande_Emperor": "The Xuande Emperor (宣德), personal name Zhu Zhanji, was the fifth emperor of the Ming dynasty, reigning from 1425 to 1435 as the successor to his father, the Hongxi Emperor. Together, the reigns of these two rulers are remembered as a stable and prosperous era in which the dynasty consolidated its institutions and enjoyed relative peace. A cultivated patron of the arts and an accomplished painter in his own right, the Xuande Emperor presided over a reign celebrated for its refined blue-and-white porcelain and other imperial workshops.",
"Zhengtong_Emperor": "The Zhengtong Emperor (正統), personal name Zhu Qizhen, was the sixth emperor of the Ming dynasty, reigning from 1435 to 1449 as the eldest son and successor of the Xuande Emperor. In 1449 he personally led a campaign against the Oirat Mongol leader Esen and was captured at the disastrous Battle of Tumu, an event known as the Tumu Crisis, after which the court enthroned his brother as the Jingtai Emperor. Held in captivity and later placed under house arrest following his release, he regained the throne through a palace coup in 1457 and ruled a second time until 1464 under the new era name Tianshun (天順).",
"Jingtai_Emperor": "The Jingtai Emperor (景泰), personal name Zhu Qiyu, was the seventh emperor of the Ming dynasty, reigning from 1449 to 1457. He was raised to the throne in 1449 after his elder brother the Zhengtong Emperor was captured by the Mongols under Esen Taishi at the Battle of Tumu, and his government under the minister of war Yu Qian oversaw the successful defence of Beijing against the ensuing Mongol advance. When his brother returned from captivity, the Jingtai Emperor kept him under house arrest, but in 1457 a palace coup restored the former ruler, deposing Zhu Qiyu, who died shortly afterward.",
"Chenghua_Emperor": "The Chenghua Emperor (成化), personal name Zhu Jianshen, was the ninth emperor of the Ming dynasty, reigning from 1464 to 1487. His reign saw the growing power of palace eunuchs, including Wang Zhi, who headed the Western Depot secret police, and the corrupt Liang Fang, who came to dominate the court. He was also known for his lifelong devotion to his consort Lady Wan, a woman roughly seventeen years his senior who wielded considerable influence and was accused of forcing abortions on other palace women and eliminating potential rival heirs.",
"Hongzhi_Emperor": "The Hongzhi Emperor (弘治), personal name Zhu Youcheng, was the tenth emperor of the Ming dynasty, reigning from 1487 to 1505. He is remembered as a diligent, frugal, and conscientious ruler who reduced taxes and government spending, appointed capable ministers, and curbed the influence of court eunuchs. His reign brought a period of capable and comparatively clean government, marked by unusually harmonious cooperation between the emperor and his officials.",
"Zhengde_Emperor": "The Zhengde Emperor (正德), personal name Zhu Houzhao, was the eleventh emperor of the Ming dynasty, reigning from 1505 to 1521 after succeeding his father the Hongzhi Emperor. Coming to the throne as a teenager, he was an impulsive and pleasure-loving ruler who neglected the routine business of government, leaving much administration to eunuchs and favourites while he indulged in revelry and elaborate military play-acting, even styling himself a general under an invented name. He died in 1521 at about twenty-nine, leaving no heir, and the succession passed to a cousin who became the Jiajing Emperor.",
"Jiajing_Emperor": "The Jiajing Emperor (嘉靖), personal name Zhu Houcong, was the twelfth emperor of the Ming dynasty, reigning from 1521 to 1567 after being chosen to succeed his heirless cousin the Zhengde Emperor. His long reign became dominated by an obsession with Daoist alchemy and the search for immortality, leading him to withdraw from the Forbidden City and leave the running of the state to his grand secretaries. He survived a plot in 1542 in which a group of palace women attempted to strangle him in his sleep, while wokou pirate raids escalated and harried the southeastern coast throughout the middle decades of his rule.",
"Longqing_Emperor": "The Longqing Emperor (隆慶) was the thirteenth emperor of the Ming dynasty, reigning from 1567 to 1572, and was born Zhu Zaiji as the son of the Jiajing Emperor whom he succeeded. Early in his reign the Ming lifted its long-standing Haijin ban on private maritime trade, legalizing licensed overseas commerce through the Fujian port of Yuegang and drawing large inflows of foreign silver into the empire. In 1571 his court concluded a peace settlement with the Mongol leader Altan Khan, granting him the title Prince of Shunyi and opening regulated border markets, which eased raiding along the northern frontier.",
"Taichang_Emperor": "The Taichang Emperor (泰昌), personal name Zhu Changluo, was the fifteenth emperor of the Ming dynasty and the eldest son and successor of the Wanli Emperor. Enthroned in August 1620 after decades of succession disputes at court, he began appointing reform-minded officials but reigned for only about a month before dying suddenly on 26 September 1620. His abrupt death, following his ingestion of medicinal red pills, became the focus of the palace intrigue known as the Case of the Red Pills, in which court factions traded accusations of poisoning and malpractice.",
"Tianqi_Emperor": "The Tianqi Emperor (天啟), personal name Zhu Youjiao, was the sixteenth emperor of the Ming dynasty, reigning from 1620 to 1627 after ascending the throne at the age of fifteen upon the sudden death of his father, the Taichang Emperor. He took little interest in the affairs of state and was far more absorbed in carpentry and woodworking, at which he was reputedly highly skilled, than in the business of ruling. As a result the government fell into the hands of the powerful court eunuch Wei Zhongxian, who together with the emperor's wet nurse Madame Ke dominated the court, purged the Donglin faction, and wielded near-absolute power until the emperor's death.",
"Shunzhi_Emperor": "The Shunzhi Emperor (順治), personal name Fulin, was the second emperor of the Qing dynasty and the first to reign over China proper following the Manchu conquest of 1644. He came to the throne as a young child in 1643 after the death of his father Hong Taiji, and for the early years of his reign real power lay with his uncle Dorgon, who served as prince regent until his death at the end of 1650. After Dorgon died the Shunzhi Emperor began to rule personally, and he died of smallpox in 1661 while still in his early twenties, succeeded by his son the Kangxi Emperor.",
"Kangxi_Emperor": "The Kangxi Emperor (康熙), personal name Xuanye, was the third emperor of the Qing dynasty, reigning from 1661 to 1722. His reign of sixty-one years is the longest of any emperor in Chinese history, during which he consolidated Manchu rule over China, crushed the Revolt of the Three Feudatories, and greatly expanded the empire's frontiers. He also sponsored major scholarly compilations, including the Kangxi Dictionary of the Chinese language.",
"Jiaqing_Emperor": "The Jiaqing Emperor (嘉慶), personal name Yongyan, was the sixth emperor of the Qing dynasty, reigning from 1796 to 1820 as the successor to his father the Qianlong Emperor. Though he took the throne in 1796, he wielded little real authority until Qianlong's death in 1799, after which he swiftly moved against the vastly corrupt court favourite Heshen, stripping him of his titles, confiscating his enormous fortune, and ordering him to commit suicide. His reign was consumed by the protracted and costly White Lotus Rebellion and marked the first clear signs of dynastic decline through fiscal strain, official corruption, and mounting social unrest.",
"Daoguang_Emperor": "The Daoguang Emperor (道光) was the seventh emperor of the Qing dynasty, whose personal name was Minning and who reigned from 1820 to 1850 as successor to his father, the Jiaqing Emperor. During his reign the escalating influx of British opium prompted him to appoint the commissioner Lin Zexu to suppress the trade, a confrontation that triggered the First Opium War against Britain. China's defeat led to the 1842 Treaty of Nanjing, which ceded Hong Kong Island to Britain and opened several treaty ports, marking the beginning of the era known in China as the century of humiliation.",
"Xianfeng_Emperor": "The Xianfeng Emperor (咸豐), personal name Yizhu, was the eighth emperor of the Qing dynasty, reigning from 1850 until his death in 1861 as the last Qing monarch to wield sole imperial power. His reign was consumed by the vast Taiping Rebellion, which seized much of southern China and captured Nanjing in 1853, alongside the concurrent Second Opium War against Britain and France. As Anglo-French forces advanced on Beijing in 1860 he fled north to the mountain resort at Rehe, where he died the following year, while the invading troops sacked and burned the Old Summer Palace.",
"Tongzhi_Emperor": "The Tongzhi Emperor (同治), personal name Zaichun, was the ninth emperor of the Qing dynasty, reigning from 1861 until his death in 1875 as the successor to his father, the Xianfeng Emperor. Having come to the throne as a young boy, he ruled under a regency dominated by his mother, the Empress Dowager Cixi, alongside the Empress Dowager Ci'an, and the period saw an attempted revival of the dynasty known as the Tongzhi Restoration, associated with the reform efforts of the Self-Strengthening Movement. He died in his late teens without leaving a son, after which his young cousin Zaitian was chosen as heir and became the Guangxu Emperor.",
"Guangxu_Emperor": "The Guangxu Emperor (光緒), personal name Zaitian, was the tenth emperor of the Qing dynasty, reigning from 1875 until his death in 1908 after acceding to the throne as a child under the regency of his aunt, the Empress Dowager Cixi. In 1898 he launched the reformist Hundred Days movement, a sweeping program of political, educational, and institutional modernization pursued with progressive advisers such as Kang Youwei. The reforms provoked a conservative backlash led by Cixi, who mounted a coup that stripped the emperor of power and held him under virtual house arrest for the rest of his life, leaving him a nominal ruler until he died a day before Cixi in November 1908.",
"Xuantong_Emperor": "The Xuantong Emperor (宣統) was the last emperor of China, reigning as the final ruler of the Qing dynasty from 1908 until the fall of the monarchy in 1912. Personally named Puyi, he came to the throne as a small child at not yet three years of age after the death of the Guangxu Emperor, and the government was conducted by regents until his abdication was proclaimed on his behalf in February 1912 during the revolution that ended imperial rule. Decades later he was installed by Japan as the puppet ruler of the state of Manchukuo in the Japanese-occupied northeast, a position he held until the collapse of that regime in 1945.",
"Carp": "Carp are any of various freshwater fish of the family Cyprinidae, typically stout-bodied and large-scaled, with toothless jaws, pharyngeal teeth, and often one or two pairs of barbels flanking the mouth. Native to Europe and Asia and widely introduced elsewhere, they are hardy, omnivorous fish that thrive in slow-moving or still waters such as lakes, ponds, and sluggish rivers. Long raised in aquaculture as a food source, carp have also been selectively bred into brightly coloured ornamental varieties kept in decorative ponds and gardens.",
"Eagle": "An eagle is a large bird of prey with a powerful hooked beak, strong feet tipped with sharp talons, and exceptionally keen eyesight, belonging to several genera within the family Accipitridae. Eagles are found on every continent except Antarctica and inhabit environments ranging from coasts and wetlands to mountains, forests, and open plains. Hunting by day, they take fish, mammals, and other birds, and many species rank as apex predators of their habitats.",
"Camel": "A camel is a large, long-necked, humped mammal of the genus Camelus, adapted to arid deserts and semi-deserts and comprising the one-humped dromedary and the two-humped Bactrian camel. Fat-storing humps, a marked tolerance of dehydration, and broad, padded feet allow it to travel long distances across sand with little food or water. Camels have long been kept by desert- and steppe-dwelling peoples for transport and riding as well as for their milk, meat, and wool.",
"Son_of_Heaven": "The Son of Heaven (天子, Tianzi) is the traditional title of the sovereign in Chinese political thought, designating the emperor as the supreme earthly ruler who governs all under heaven by virtue of the Mandate of Heaven. First attested in Zhou-dynasty bronze inscriptions, the title cast the monarch as the intermediary linking heaven, earth, and humanity, responsible for maintaining cosmic and social harmony through just rule. Misrule, corruption, or natural calamity was interpreted as a sign of heaven's displeasure, and persistent failure was believed to forfeit the mandate and the ruler's legitimacy.",
"Sisyphus": "In Greek mythology, Sisyphus was a cunning and deceitful king of Ephyra, later called Corinth, who twice outwitted death, once by binding Thanatos in chains and again by tricking his way back from the underworld to the world of the living. For his hubris the gods condemned him to an eternal punishment: to roll a huge boulder up a hill, only for it to roll back down each time it neared the summit, leaving his labour endless and futile. His name gives the adjective Sisyphean, describing a task that is laborious, repetitive, and doomed never to be completed.",
"Youyang_Zazu": "The Youyang Zazu 酉陽雜俎 is a miscellany compiled by the scholar Duan Chengshi during the Tang dynasty, gathering more than a thousand entries of anecdotes, marvels, folklore, natural curiosities, and reports of foreign lands. It draws on what its compiler read, heard, and personally observed, and is valued as a rich store of medieval beliefs, legends, and lore ranging from the fantastical to the everyday. It is especially noted for preserving the tale of Ye Xian, one of the earliest known written versions of the Cinderella story.",
"zhang_(unit)": "A zhang (丈) is a traditional Chinese unit of length equal to ten chi, or roughly three and a third metres. Because it was defined in terms of the chi, whose length was reset by successive dynasties, its exact value varied considerably over time before being standardized in the twentieth century. It was commonly used to express the heights of walls and buildings, the depth of water, and the length of cloth and rope.",
"Rabbit": "A rabbit is a small, long-eared, plant-eating mammal of the family Leporidae, with soft fur, a short tail, and powerful hind legs adapted for a hopping gait. Rabbits shelter in underground burrows or in shallow surface nests called forms, feed chiefly on grasses and other vegetation, and breed prolifically through short pregnancies and frequent litters. Found in the wild across parts of the Americas, Europe, Africa, and Asia, they have also been widely domesticated and are kept as livestock and as pets.",
"Mid-Autumn_Festival": "The Mid-Autumn Festival (中秋節) is a traditional Chinese harvest celebration held on the fifteenth day of the eighth month of the lunisolar calendar, when the full moon is at its roundest and brightest. Families gather to reunite, view the moon, light and carry lanterns, and eat round mooncakes, whose shape echoes the fullness of the moon and the ideal of family unity. The festival is bound up with lunar legend, above all the goddess Chang'e, who is said to dwell on the moon and to whom offerings are made on this night.",
"Mao_Zedong": "Mao Zedong (毛澤東; 1893–1976) was a Chinese revolutionary and political theorist who led the Chinese Communist Party to victory in the Chinese Civil War and proclaimed the People's Republic of China in 1949, ruling it as its paramount leader until his death. Governing under communism, he pursued sweeping and often catastrophic mass campaigns, including the Great Leap Forward and the Cultural Revolution, which caused tens of millions of deaths and vast social upheaval. His distinctive body of thought, emphasizing peasant-based revolution and continuous class struggle, became known as Maoism and influenced insurgent movements worldwide.",
"Osmanthus": "Osmanthus is a genus of about thirty species of evergreen flowering shrubs and small trees in the olive family, native mainly to the woodlands of eastern and southeastern Asia. Its blossoms are small, borne in clusters, and range from white to yellow or deep orange, and in several species they release an intense sweet fragrance often likened to ripe apricots or peaches. The scented flowers are harvested to perfume and flavour tea, to season foods and confections, and to produce fragrances.",
"Cleanser_of_the_Altars": "The Cleanser of the Altars (淨壇使者) is the Buddhist title bestowed on Zhu Bajie, the pig-like disciple, at the close of the novel Journey to the West as a reward for helping the pilgrimage retrieve the sacred scriptures. Because his gluttony and lust left him too attached to worldly desires to attain full buddhahood alongside his companions, he was instead appointed to this humble rank. The office entitled him to consume the surplus food offerings left upon altars, a duty that suited his voracious appetite.",
"Lunar_New_Year": "Lunar New Year is the festival marking the beginning of the year in a traditional lunisolar calendar, generally falling on the second new moon after the winter solstice and so shifting between late January and mid-February each year. It is observed across many East and Southeast Asian cultures, taking forms such as the Chinese Spring Festival, the Vietnamese Tet, and the Korean Seollal. The occasion is typically kept with family reunions, feasting, and rites intended to welcome good fortune for the coming year.",
"Zhao_Gongming": "Zhao Gongming (趙公明) is a deity of Chinese folk religion and Taoism, revered as a martial god of wealth as well as a fearsome queller of plague, and is commonly depicted riding a black tiger and wielding an iron whip. Originally cast as a demon associated with disease, he was later transformed into a bringer of prosperity and given the title Xuantan Zhenjun, Lord of the Dark Altar. He figures prominently in the Ming novel Investiture of the Gods, in which he is slain in battle and posthumously deified, and he is among the martial figures venerated as Caishen, the god of wealth.",
"Predynastic_Zhou": "The Predynastic Zhou (先周) is the Zhou people and their state in the centuries before their conquest of the Shang dynasty, when the Ji-clan rulers held the Guanzhong region on the western frontier in what is now central Shaanxi and grew into a farming and cattle-raising power owing nominal allegiance to the Shang. Their traditional line of chieftains descended from the millet-farming ancestor Hou Ji (后稷) through Gong Liu, who led the people to settle at Bin, and the Old Duke Danfu (古公亶父), who migrated the clan to the plain of Zhouyuan beneath Mount Qi. From this base the rulers Ji Li, King Wen, and King Wu accumulated the strength that let the Zhou overthrow the Shang around 1046 BCE and found the Zhou dynasty.",
"Gong_Liu": "Gong Liu (公劉), also called Duke Liu, was an early leader of the predynastic Zhou people, remembered as the ancestor who revived the clan's fortunes after his forebears had abandoned the cultivation for which their ancestor Hou Ji was honoured. According to traditional accounts preserved in the Shiji, he led his people from Tai to settle at Bin (豳), where he restored agriculture, drew on resources gathered from across the Wei River to build up stores, and grew the community into a flourishing settlement that attracted followers. His labours at Bin are celebrated in a hymn among the Major Odes of the Classic of Poetry, and the house he strengthened there became the seat from which the later Zhou royal line arose.",
"Zhouyuan": "Zhouyuan (周原), the Plain of Zhou, is a fertile plateau at the foot of Mount Qi in what is now Shaanxi province, straddling the modern counties of Qishan and Fufeng north of the Wei River. It was the ancestral homeland and early ceremonial centre of the Zhou people after the Old Duke Danfu led his clan there from Bin, and it remained a major cult and administrative hub through the Western Zhou period. As one of the most important archaeological sites of early China, it has yielded extensive rammed-earth palace and temple foundations, large caches of inscribed oracle bones, and hoards of ritual bronzes bearing dated inscriptions that are central to the study of Zhou history.",
"Wu_Taibo": "Wu Taibo (太伯), also written 泰伯, was the eldest son of the Old Duke Danfu, leader of the Zhou people, and had two younger brothers, Zhongyong and Jili. Understanding that his father wished the succession to pass to Jili and thence to Jili's son, the future King Wen of Zhou, Taibo yielded his claim and traveled far to the southeast, where tradition holds that he founded the state of Wu (吳) and, dying without an heir, passed his rule to his brother Zhongyong. Confucius praised him in the Analects as a man of the highest virtue for thrice declining the throne, and he is venerated as the ancestor of those bearing the surname Wu.",
"Jiang_Ziya": "Jiang Ziya (姜子牙), also known as Lü Shang, Taigong Wang, and Jiang Taigong, was a sage strategist whom tradition holds was discovered fishing in old age with a barbless hook and recognized as the promised counsellor of Zhou. He became the chief military adviser to King Wen of Zhou and King Wu of Zhou, planning the campaign that overthrew the Shang dynasty at the Battle of Muye. For this service he was enfeoffed with the eastern lands in present-day Shandong that became the state of Qi, of which he is honoured as the founding lord.",
"Rebellion_of_the_Three_Guards": "The Rebellion of the Three Guards (三監之亂) was a revolt early in the Western Zhou in which three of King Wu of Zhou's younger brothers, whom he had stationed to oversee the conquered Shang lands, joined the surviving Shang prince Wu Geng (武庚) in rising against the regency of the Duke of Zhou over the young King Cheng of Zhou. Conventionally dated to around 1042 to 1039 BCE, it drew in Shang loyalists and eastern peoples who resented Zhou rule and rejected the legitimacy of the regency. The Duke of Zhou suppressed the uprising in a hard three-year eastern campaign that killed or dispossessed its leaders, after which he expanded Zhou authority across the eastern plain and reorganized the conquered territories under a network of enfeoffed states.",
"Duke_of_Shao": "The Duke of Shao (召公), personal name Shi (奭), was a leading statesman of the early Western Zhou who held the office of Grand Guardian (太保) and stood as one of the twin pillars of the regency and administration under King Cheng of Zhou. Working alongside the Duke of Zhou, he governed the western portion of the realm from the primary capital while the eastern lands were overseen from the newly built eastern seat, and his benevolent conduct is celebrated in the Book of Songs poem Gantang (甘棠). He was enfeoffed with the northeastern state of Yan and sent his eldest son to rule there in his stead, so that his lineage became its founding ruling house.",
"Chinese_ritual_bronzes": "Chinese ritual bronzes (青銅禮器) are cast bronze vessels and bells made in ancient China to hold food and wine offerings in ancestral sacrifices and ceremonial feasts. Their standardized types, chief among them the tripod food cauldron ding (鼎) and the round food tureen gui (簋), were owned and used in prescribed numbers that signified an aristocrat's rank and legitimated his authority. Produced in great quantity under the Shang and Zhou dynasties, they are prized for their intricate cast decoration and for the commemorative inscriptions cast into many of them, which record grants, campaigns, and appointments and serve as primary evidence for early Chinese history.",
"Chinese_bronze_inscriptions": "Chinese bronze inscriptions (金文, jinwen) are texts cast, or less often engraved, into ancient Chinese ritual bronze vessels and bells, recording such matters as royal charges, ceremonial gifts, official appointments, land and legal agreements, and commemorations of ancestors. Made chiefly during the Late Shang dynasty (c. 1250–1046 BCE) and above all the Western Zhou dynasty (c. 1046–771 BCE), they range from a single clan or ancestor name to formal narratives of several hundred characters, the longest being the roughly 500-character Mao Gong ding. Because they were produced by the very people and institutions they describe, these inscriptions rank among the most important primary sources for the political history and the written script of early China.",
"Bo_Qin": "Bo Qin (伯禽) was the eldest son of the Duke of Zhou and, in the early Western Zhou period, was enfeoffed by King Cheng of Zhou as the first ruler of the state of Lu, whose seat lay at Qufu. Because his father remained at the royal court to assist the young king, Bo Qin was sent in his stead to take up the domain and govern it. There he instituted the Zhou ritual and musical order, and Lu accordingly became renowned for preserving that tradition more faithfully than any other feudal state.",
"Shu_Yu_of_Tang": "Shu Yu of Tang (唐叔虞), personal name Ji Yu (姬虞), was a younger son of King Wu of Zhou and a younger brother of King Cheng of Zhou, who enfeoffed him with the newly conquered territory of Tang (唐) in what is now southern Shanxi. His son and successor Xie moved the seat of the fief nearer the Jin River and renamed the domain Jin (晉), so that Shu Yu is remembered as the progenitor of the ruling house of the state of Jin. Later tradition surrounds his enfeoffment with the anecdote of the paulownia leaf, in which a joking promise by the boy-king Cheng was held to be binding and duly fulfilled.",
"Yan_(state)": "Yan (燕) was one of the regional states of the Zhou realm, enfeoffed in the far north around present-day Beijing to the line of the Duke of Shao, a leading statesman of the early Zhou court. Its capital was eventually established at Ji (薊), within modern Beijing, and it ruled the northeasternmost reaches of the Chinese world through the Spring and Autumn and Warring States periods. As one of the seven great powers of the Warring States era, Yan resisted the advance of Qin until its final conquest in 222 BCE, on the eve of Qin's unification of China.",
"Kang_Shu": "Kang Shu (康叔), personal name Feng (封), was a son of King Wen of Zhou and a younger brother of King Wu of Zhou and the Duke of Zhou. After the Duke of Zhou suppressed the Rebellion of the Three Guards, Kang Shu was enfeoffed with the former Shang heartland around the old capital of Zhaoge and set over its remnant Shang population, becoming the founding ruler of the state of Wey. The Duke of Zhou is recorded as having instructed him at length on governing the conquered Shang people, admonitions preserved in the Kang Gao (康誥) chapter of the Book of Documents.",
"Wey_(state)": "Wey (衞) was a state of the Zhou dynasty founded around 1040 BCE by Kang Shu, a younger brother of King Wu of Zhou, on the former Shang heartland around Zhaoge after the Rebellion of the Three Guards. Its rulers were charged with governing the remnant Shang population and the lands that had been the center of that revolt. Reduced to a minor state through the Spring and Autumn and Warring States periods, Wey outlasted every other state enfeoffed by the Zhou except Qin, surviving even Qin's conquest of the major kingdoms until its ruling line was extinguished by Qin Er Shi around 209 BCE.",
"Song_(state)": "Song (宋) was a state of the Western Zhou period granted to Weizi (微子), the eldest son of the Shang king Di Yi and a half-brother of the last Shang king Di Xin, so that the Shang royal house might continue offering sacrifices to its ancestors after the fall of the Shang dynasty. Centred on Shangqiu in what is now eastern Henan, it was enfeoffed following the suppression of the Rebellion of the Three Guards and was ruled by the Shang lineage as dukes who preserved older Shang ritual and cultural traditions. Song endured as a middling power through the Spring and Autumn and Warring States periods, briefly aspiring to hegemony under Duke Xiang before it was conquered and partitioned by Qi in 286 BCE.",
"Da_Yu_ding": "The Da Yu ding (大盂鼎) is a large bronze ritual cauldron of the Western Zhou, cast during the reign of King Kang of Zhou and excavated in 1849 in Qishan County, Shaanxi. Its interior bears an inscription of 291 characters in nineteen lines in which the king, invoking the fall of the Shang dynasty as a warning against drunkenness, charges a noble named Yu with office and grants him sacrificial wine, robes, chariots, horses, and more than a thousand subjects. Prized as one of the finest examples of early Zhou bronze-inscription calligraphy, it is held in the National Museum of China in Beijing.",
"Tale_of_King_Mu": "The Tale of King Mu, Son of Heaven (穆天子傳) is an early, semi-legendary Chinese narrative recounting the far-western travels of King Mu of Zhou, who journeys by chariot drawn by his team of eight fine horses to distant lands and is famously feasted by the goddess Queen Mother of the West (西王母) upon Mount Kunlun. Blending a sober, diary-like itinerary with myth, the text belongs to the Warring States period and could not have been composed later than 296 BCE, the death year of King Xiang of Wei, in whose tomb it was buried. Written on bamboo slips, it was recovered in 281 CE among the cache of texts unearthed at Jixian and transcribed by Jin-dynasty scholars, making it one of the most celebrated of China's rediscovered ancient works.",
"Feizi": "Feizi (非子) was a horse-breeder of the Ying (嬴) clan who, according to the Records of the Grand Historian, won the favour of King Xiao of Zhou through his skill in raising and training horses for the royal army. In reward the king granted him a small fief at Qin (秦) in the western borderlands, in present-day Gansu, along with charge of the royal herds. From Feizi the later marquises, dukes, and kings of the state of Qin traced their descent, making him the reputed founder of that lineage.",
"Mao_Gong_ding": "The Mao Gong ding (毛公鼎) is a Western Zhou bronze ritual cauldron whose interior bears an inscription of roughly five hundred characters, the longest known cast into any ancient Chinese bronze. In its text King Xuan of Zhou charges the Duke of Mao with broad authority over affairs of state and admonishes him to govern honestly and serve the throne loyally. Excavated in Qishan County, Shaanxi in 1843 and now held by the National Palace Museum in Taipei, it is prized both as a historical record of late Western Zhou governance and as a masterwork of early bronze-script calligraphy.",
"Da_Ke_ding": "The Da Ke ding (大克鼎) is a large Western Zhou bronze ritual cauldron cast for a court steward named Ke (克), who held the office of shanfu (膳夫) in charge of the royal kitchen. Its inscription of 290 characters in 28 lines records a royal charge from King Xiao of Zhou appointing Ke to office together with grants of land and people, and it opens with praise of Ke's grandfather Shi Huafu (師華父). Unearthed in 1890 in Fufeng County, Shaanxi, and now held in the Shanghai Museum, it is admired as one of the finest surviving Zhou bronzes and is counted among the Three Treasures alongside the Da Yu ding and the Mao Gong ding.",
"Bao_Si": "Bao Si (褒姒) was the favored consort of King You of Zhou, the final ruler of the Western Zhou. Traditional histories relate that the melancholic Bao Si rarely smiled, and that to delight her the king repeatedly ordered the frontier beacon fires lit to summon his vassal lords under false alarm, until the lords ceased to trust the signal. When the Quanrong later attacked in earnest around 771 BCE the summoned lords did not come, King You was killed, and Bao Si was captured, an episode long blamed for the fall of the Western Zhou though modern scholars regard the beacon-fire tale as a later fabrication.",
"Shen_(state)": "Shen (申) was a Zhou vassal state ruled by the Jiang clan, centered in the region of present-day Nanyang in Henan and serving as a southern gateway of the royal domain. Its marquess was the father of the queen whom King You of Zhou deposed in favor of the consort Bao Si, along with her son the crown prince Yijiu. Enraged at this treatment of his daughter and grandson, the Marquess of Shen allied with the state of Zeng and the Quanrong to attack the Zhou capital in 771 BCE, an assault that killed King You and ended the Western Zhou.",
"Chaos": "In cosmology and myth, chaos is the formless, disordered state imagined to exist before the creation or ordering of the universe, the raw condition out of which an ordered cosmos is said to emerge. The concept recurs across many creation traditions, which often open with a primordial void, watery abyss, or undifferentiated mass that is later separated, shaped, or set in order, and the word itself derives from the ancient Greek khaos, meaning a gap, chasm, or yawning void. In modern general usage the word has broadened to mean any state of complete confusion and disorder.",
"Hen": "A hen is an adult female chicken, and by extension the term is applied to the female of certain other birds such as the pheasant or turkey. Kept widely as domestic poultry, hens are raised chiefly for their eggs and their meat. They are noted for going broody to incubate a clutch of eggs and for brooding, guiding, and protecting their young once the chicks have hatched.",
"Cognate": "In linguistics, a cognate is a word that descends, together with a word in another language, from a common ancestral word in a shared parent language, so the two are related by direct etymological inheritance. Because they trace back to the same source, cognates often resemble one another in form and meaning, as with English mother and German Mutter, both inherited from Proto-Germanic and ultimately from Proto-Indo-European. The word is also used more broadly for anything related to something else by common origin or descent.",
"Sinology": "Sinology is the academic study of China, encompassing its language, literature, history, philosophy, and broader civilization. The term was coined around 1838 from the Late Latin Sina, meaning China, and the Greek -logia, meaning study, and it traditionally denoted the scholarship of researchers outside China, being long equated with the philological study of the Chinese classics. From the early nineteenth century the field developed into an institutional discipline, marked by the 1814 establishment of a chair of Chinese at the Collège de France, and it has since widened toward the interdisciplinary work also called China studies.",
"Frog": "A frog is a tailless amphibian of the order Anura, a diverse group of cold-blooded vertebrates found on every continent except Antarctica. It typically has a short, squat body, protruding eyes, moist smooth skin, webbed feet, and long, muscular hind legs that power its characteristic leaping and swimming. Most frogs begin life as an aquatic, gilled larva called a tadpole, which develops lungs and limbs and absorbs its tail during metamorphosis into the terrestrial or semi-aquatic adult.",
"Anthropology": "Anthropology is the scientific study of humanity, encompassing human societies, cultures, biology, and languages across both the past and the present. Its name derives from the Greek anthrōpos, meaning human being, joined with -logia, the study of a subject. The discipline is commonly divided into four subfields — cultural anthropology, linguistic anthropology, archaeology, and biological anthropology — which together examine the full range of the human condition.",
"Censorship": "Censorship is the suppression or restriction of speech, writing, images, or other information that a governing authority or institution deems objectionable, harmful, or sensitive. It may be exercised by governments, religious bodies, corporations, or other powerful groups, applied either before material is produced or afterward to remove or ban it, and when creators restrain their own expression to avoid sanction it is called self-censorship. Common justifications include national security, public morality, the protection of children, and the promotion or suppression of particular political or religious views, and the practice is widely debated for its tension with freedom of expression.",
"Hegemony": "Hegemony is the political, economic, or military dominance of one state, group, or social class over others, often exercised through a combination of coercion and the shaping of prevailing norms rather than direct force alone. A state, group, or class that holds such a position is called a hegemon, and the word hegemony derives from the ancient Greek hegemonia, meaning leadership or supremacy, originally the authority exercised by one city-state over others. The concept is central to international relations and political theory, where it describes both the ascendancy of a leading state in the global order and, in the sense developed by Antonio Gramsci, the cultural and ideological predominance of a ruling class.",
"Chariot": "A chariot is a light, usually two-wheeled vehicle drawn by horses and driven by a standing rider, made fast and maneuverable by the invention of the spoked wheel. First appearing among the Sintashta culture of the Eurasian steppe around 2000 BCE, it spread across many ancient civilizations, serving in warfare, hunting, racing, and ceremonial procession. On the battlefield it acted as a mobile platform for archers and spearmen until it gave way to cavalry, after which it survived chiefly in racing and pageantry.",
"Golden_Rule": "The Golden Rule is an ethical principle, also known as the ethic of reciprocity, holding that one should treat others as one would wish to be treated oneself. It appears in a positive form, urging people to do to others what they would want done to them, and a negative form, sometimes called the Silver Rule, counselling against doing to others what one would not want done to oneself. Versions of the maxim arise across many of the world's religious and philosophical traditions, including the teachings of Confucius, the Jewish sage Hillel, and Jesus in the Sermon on the Mount, making it one of the most widely shared moral precepts.",
"Eurasia": "Eurasia is the combined continental landmass of Europe and Asia, the largest on Earth, covering roughly 55 million square kilometres, or about 36 percent of the planet's land area. It is home to well over five billion people, approximately 70 percent of the world's population. Across its expanse arose many of history's major civilizations, and the boundary conventionally drawn between Europe and Asia is regarded as a cultural and historical distinction rather than a physical divide.",
"East_Africa": "East Africa is the eastern region of the African continent, generally taken to include countries such as Kenya, Tanzania, Uganda, Ethiopia, and Somalia. Much of it is traversed by the East African Rift, a system of tectonic valleys where the continent is slowly splitting apart, giving rise to the Great Lakes, towering volcanic peaks, and sites that have yielded some of the earliest known hominin fossils. Its long Indian Ocean coastline was for centuries a hub of maritime commerce, home to the Swahili city-states that exported goods such as gold, ivory, and hardwoods to Arabia, India, and lands farther east.",
"Americas": "The Americas are the lands of the Western Hemisphere, comprising the continents of North America and South America along with their associated islands, and are also known as the New World. Stretching from the Arctic in the north to Cape Horn in the south, they encompass an enormous range of environments, including tundra, prairie, tropical rainforest, desert, and the Andean and Rocky mountain systems. The region was home to diverse indigenous peoples and civilizations, such as the Maya, Aztec, and Inca, for many thousands of years before sustained European contact began in the late 15th century and gave rise to widespread colonization, with the name honoring the explorer Amerigo Vespucci.",
"Utopia_Planitia": "Utopia Planitia is a vast, smooth plain in the northern hemisphere of Mars, lying within Utopia, the largest recognized impact basin on the planet at an estimated 3,300 kilometres across; its Latin name means the Plain of Utopia. Substantial water ice lies beneath its surface, and its flat, relatively hazard-free terrain has made it a favoured landing region for spacecraft. Missions that have touched down there include NASA's Viking 2 lander in 1976 and China's Zhurong rover, part of the Tianwen-1 mission, in 2021.",
"Yarrow": "Yarrow is a hardy perennial flowering plant of the genus Achillea, especially Achillea millefolium, in the daisy family Asteraceae, distinguished by its finely divided, feathery leaves and flat-topped clusters of small white or pink flowers. Native across the temperate regions of the Northern Hemisphere from Europe and Asia to North America, it grows readily in meadows, grasslands, and disturbed ground, and has a long history in traditional medicine, valued in particular for staunching bleeding and treating wounds. Its dried stalks have also been used in divination, notably in the yarrow-stalk method for consulting the I Ching.",
"Kaolin": "Kaolin is a soft, fine-grained white clay composed chiefly of the mineral kaolinite, a hydrous aluminium silicate. It is an essential raw material of porcelain and other fine ceramics, and it also serves as a coating and filler in paper, an extender in paint, and an ingredient in rubber, cosmetics, and medicine. Its name derives from Gaoling, a hill near Jingdezhen in southeastern China where the clay was quarried, from which the term passed into European use in the early eighteenth century.",
"Go_(game)": "Go is a two-player abstract strategy board game in which the players alternately place black and white stones on the intersections of a gridded board, most commonly a 19x19 grid of 361 points, aiming to surround more territory than the opponent. Stones or connected groups that become completely surrounded by the opposing colour are captured and removed, and at the end each side's score is the enclosed territory added to captured stones. Believed to have originated in China more than two thousand years ago, it is among the oldest board games still played today and is celebrated for pairing very simple rules with extraordinary strategic depth.",
"Science_and_Civilisation_in_China": "Science and Civilisation in China is a monumental multi-volume study of the history of science, technology, and medicine in Chinese civilization, published by Cambridge University Press. It was initiated and edited by the British biochemist and sinologist Joseph Needham, who published the first volume in 1954, drew on a vast range of Chinese primary sources, and worked with an international team of collaborators. The work transformed Western understanding of China's scientific and technological achievements and has continued in successive volumes beyond Needham's death in 1995.",
"Needham_Question": "The Needham Question, named for the British biochemist and sinologist Joseph Needham, is the historical problem of why modern science and the Industrial Revolution arose in Europe rather than in China, even though China had led the world in technological invention for many centuries. Needham gave the question its enduring form in his 1969 essay collection The Grand Titration and pursued it through his vast survey Science and Civilisation in China, arguing that China's practical mastery of nature never crystallized into the mathematized, experimental method of the European scientific revolution. The question has since prompted wide debate over the economic, social, political, and intellectual conditions that fostered or hindered scientific development.",
"Taijitu_shuo": "The Taijitu shuo 太極圖說, or Explanation of the Diagram of the Supreme Ultimate, is a brief cosmological text written by the eleventh-century Chinese philosopher Zhou Dunyi (1017–1073). Pairing a diagram with a short commentary of roughly 250 characters, it describes how the myriad things arise from the Supreme Ultimate through the alternation of yin and yang and the generation of the five phases—water, fire, wood, metal, and earth. The work became a foundational text of Neo-Confucianism, placed at the head of the anthology Reflections on Things at Hand compiled by Zhu Xi and Lü Zuqian in 1175.",
"Tai_chi": "Tai chi (太極拳), or taijiquan, is a Chinese internal martial art practised for both self-defence and health, marked by slow, flowing, circular movements performed with a relaxed body and continuous motion. Rooted in Daoist philosophy and the interplay of yin and yang, it emphasises balance, breath, and the cultivation of internal energy, training the practitioner to yield to and redirect an opponent's force rather than meet it with hard resistance. The art's origins are traditionally traced in legend to the Daoist Zhang Sanfeng, and it is now practised worldwide, most commonly as a gentle, low-impact form of exercise.",
"Wuji_stance": "The wuji stance (無極) is the foundational standing posture of tai chi and related Chinese internal martial arts, in which the practitioner stands upright and relaxed with the feet about shoulder-width apart, the knees softly bent, and the body still. Its name comes from wuji, the undifferentiated void or limitless state of Chinese cosmology from which the Supreme Ultimate and the polarity of yin and yang are said to emerge. Practitioners hold the posture to quiet the mind, settle the breath, and centre the body before beginning movement.",
"Four_images": "The four images (四象, sixiang) are the four two-line figures obtained by pairing yin and yang lines, named greater yang, lesser yin, lesser yang, and greater yin. In the cosmology set out in the Book of Changes, they mark an intermediate stage in a generative sequence in which yin and yang give rise to the four images, and the four images in turn give rise to the eight trigrams. Each image stacks two lines one above the other, so that greater yang is two yang lines, greater yin is two yin lines, and the two lesser images each combine one line of each kind.",
"Sixty-four_hexagrams": "The sixty-four hexagrams (六十四卦) are the set of six-line figures at the core of the I Ching, or Book of Changes, each built from six stacked horizontal lines that are individually either broken (yin) or unbroken (yang). They are generated by combining the eight trigrams of the bagua in every possible pair, an upper trigram over a lower one, which yields exactly sixty-four distinct arrangements. Each hexagram carries a name and an associated image along with judgments and line statements used in divination and reflection, so that the full set forms a complete symbolic map of the situations and changes of the world.",
"Lai_Zhide": "Lai Zhide (來知德) was a Ming-dynasty Confucian scholar who withdrew into decades of mountain seclusion in Sichuan to devote himself to the study of the Book of Changes. His major work, the Zhouyi jizhu (Collected Commentary on the Book of Changes), completed after some twenty-nine years of study, reorganized the interpretation of the hexagrams around their inverted and laterally paired forms as well as the nuclear hexagrams formed by their inner lines. He is also credited with an influential diagram of the Supreme Ultimate that bears his name, the Lai-style taijitu.",
"Earlier_Heaven": "The Earlier Heaven arrangement (先天) is one of the two classic orderings of the eight trigrams of the bagua, traditionally attributed to the legendary sage Fuxi. In this layout the eight trigrams are placed symmetrically around a circle so that each sits directly across from its complement, the trigram with every line reversed, with Qian (Heaven) at the top facing Kun (Earth) at the bottom and Li (Fire) balancing Kan (Water) along the horizontal axis. It is understood as an idealized, primal cosmic order depicting the natural forces the trigrams symbolize in a state of perfect, static balance.",
"Later_Heaven": "The Later Heaven arrangement (後天) is one of the two classic orderings of the eight trigrams of the bagua, its sequence traditionally attributed to King Wen of Zhou. It maps the trigrams onto the compass directions, the cycle of the seasons, and the workings of the phenomenal world, presenting them as a dynamic progression through natural processes. It is applied in feng shui, where it underlies the Luo Pan compass, as well as in traditional Chinese medicine.",
"Junzi": "A junzi (君子) is the Confucian moral ideal of the cultivated person, rendered variously as gentleman, superior person, or exemplary person. The term originally designated a nobleman by birth, literally a ruler's son, but Confucius redefined it to mean one who is noble in character through the practice of virtue, ritual propriety, and benevolence, irrespective of hereditary rank. A junzi thus stands as a model of ethical self-cultivation, embodying moral integrity and right conduct as an aspiration open to anyone willing to develop it.",
"Luopan": "A luopan (羅盤) is a Chinese magnetic compass used in feng shui to assess the orientation and energetic qualities of a site. Its needle sits at the centre of a plate bearing numerous concentric rings inscribed with the cardinal directions, the eight trigrams of the bagua, the twenty-four directional mountains, the Heavenly Stems and Earthly Branches of the sexagenary cycle, and further cosmological formulas. A practitioner aligns the needle and reads these rings to position buildings, doorways, and graves in an auspicious relationship to the surrounding landscape.",
"Baguazhang": "Baguazhang 八卦掌, the eight-trigram palm, is an internal Chinese martial art characterized by continuous circle-walking and fluid, spiralling, evasive palm techniques. Its theory draws on the eight trigrams of the Book of Changes and their principle of ceaseless change, so that its movements are meant to flow and transform without settling into fixed lines. Formalized in nineteenth-century China and traditionally attributed to Dong Haichuan, it is practised both as a system of combat and as an exercise for health.",
"Tianwen-1": "Tianwen-1 (天問一號) is China's first independent interplanetary mission to Mars, launched on 23 July 2020 by the China National Space Administration and comprising an orbiter, a lander, and the Zhurong rover. After entering Martian orbit in February 2021, its lander touched down that May and released the Zhurong rover, making China the second nation to land and operate a rover on the planet. Its name, meaning Questions to Heaven, is drawn from a classical poem attributed to the ancient poet Qu Yuan.",
"China_National_Space_Administration": "The China National Space Administration (國家航天局) is the government agency responsible for the civil space programme of China, overseeing its satellites, launch vehicles, and lunar and planetary probes. Established in 1993, it plans and coordinates space projects and international cooperation, while the design and manufacture of rockets and spacecraft are carried out by affiliated state-owned contractors. It has directed missions including the Chang'e lunar programme, whose landers and sample-return craft have explored the Moon, and the Tianwen-1 mission that placed an orbiter, lander, and rover at Mars.",
"Zhoufang": "Zhoufang (周方) was the name by which the late Shang court referred, in its oracle-bone divinations, to the Predynastic Zhou as a fang (方), a frontier polity lying to the west of the Shang heartland. In these inscriptions the Zhoufang figures at times as a subordinate vassal whose hunts and soldiers the Shang king inquired after, and at other times as an adversary against whom military campaigns were divined. From this position on the Shang frontier it steadily expanded until it became the dominant power in the west, the polity that under its later leaders would overthrow the Shang.",
"Ji_clan": "Ji clan (姬) was the royal clan and ancestral surname of the Zhou dynasty, the name borne by its kings and by many of the feudal lords enfeoffed to rule its subordinate states. Its lineage was traditionally traced back to Hou Ji, the ancestor credited with pioneering millet cultivation, and it ranks among the oldest recorded Chinese surnames. Because descendants of the clan commonly adopted the names of their fiefs and states as new surnames, Ji itself became comparatively rare in later China.",
"Hou_Ji": "Hou Ji (后稷), a title meaning Lord of Millet, is a culture hero of Chinese mythology worshipped as a god of agriculture and grain and honoured as the ancestral founder of the Zhou people. Tradition holds that his mother Jiang Yuan conceived him after stepping into the footprint of a deity and, reading the birth as an ill omen, abandoned the infant she named Qi, the discarded one, three times, only for oxen, sheep, and birds to shelter and preserve him. Said to have loved farming from childhood, he taught the people to sow and cultivate grain, above all millet, and legend credits him with service under the sage-kings Yao and Shun, the latter appointing him to the office of Hou Ji.",
"Mount_Qi": "Mount Qi (岐山) is a mountain in present-day Shaanxi province, at whose southern foot spreads the fertile plain of the Zhouyuan. In late Shang times the Old Duke Danfu led the Zhou people from Bin to settle beneath it, and the mountain and its plain became the heartland from which the predynastic Zhou grew into a power. It held enduring sanctity in Zhou tradition, in which a phoenix was said to have sung upon the mountain as an auspicious omen heralding the rise of the house of Zhou.",
"Rong": "Rong (戎) is a collective name that the ancient Chinese applied to various non-Huaxia peoples along their western and northwestern frontier, functioning less as a precise ethnic label than as a broad term for outsiders regarded as pastoral and warlike. The groups so named ranged across the highlands and river valleys of what are now Gansu, Qinghai, Shaanxi, and Ningxia, where they herded livestock and raided along the margins between settled farmland and the steppe. Recorded as adversaries from the Shang dynasty onward, the various Rong were frequently campaigned against by the early Chinese states, and one of their branches, the Quanrong, overran the Western Zhou capital and brought that period to an end in 771 BCE.",
"Di_(people)": "Di (狄), also called the Beidi (北狄, Northern Di), was a general name applied by the ancient Chinese to various non-Huaxia peoples of the northern frontier during the Zhou dynasty. Chinese sources divided them into groups such as the Red Di (赤狄), White Di (白狄), and Tall Di (長狄), and describe a mixed pastoral, agricultural, and hunting economy that included walled settlements. Frequently in conflict with the Zhou and with northern states such as Jin, the Di were gradually conquered or absorbed, their last kingdom, Zhongshan, falling to Zhao in 295 BCE.",
"Bin": "Bin (豳) was an early homeland of the predynastic Zhou, traditionally located in the Jing River valley of present-day Shaanxi Province. According to accounts in the Records of the Grand Historian and the Classic of Poetry, the ancestor Gong Liu led his people to settle at Bin, where they opened farmland, built lasting dwellings, and revived agriculture. The Zhou clan remained based at Bin for generations before migrating southwest to Zhouyuan, at the foot of Mount Qi in the Wei River valley.",
"Zhongyong": "Zhongyong (仲雍) was the second son of the Old Duke Danfu (King Tai) and the younger brother of Wu Taibo, a figure of the predynastic Zhou traditionally placed in the twelfth century BCE. According to tradition, he and Taibo left the Zhou heartland so that the succession could pass to their youngest brother Jili, and the two settled among the peoples of the lower Yangtze, where they are said to have founded the state of Wu at Meili. After Taibo died without an heir, Zhongyong inherited the rule of Wu, and the later kings of that state were reckoned as his descendants.",
"Tairen": "Tairen (太任) was a noblewoman of the Ren clan from the state of Zhi who became the wife of King Ji of Zhou and the mother of King Wen of Zhou near the end of the Shang dynasty. Confucian tradition, drawing especially on Liu Xiang's Biographies of Exemplary Women, honours her as a paragon of feminine virtue and the archetypal practitioner of taijiao (胎教), or fetal instruction, recounting that while pregnant she looked upon no evil sights, listened to no lewd sounds, and uttered no arrogant words in order to shape the character of her unborn child. Through this example she became a lasting model of prenatal moral influence in China, and the wisdom of her son was traditionally credited to the discipline she maintained while carrying him.",
"King_Wen_Ding_of_Shang": "King Wen Ding of Shang (文丁) was a ruler of the late Shang dynasty and the grandfather of Di Xin (King Zhou of Shang), the dynasty's final king. Traditional accounts hold that he grew wary of the rising power of the Predynastic Zhou and had their leader King Ji of Zhou put to death, luring him with honours before confining him in a storehouse and starving him there. This killing is remembered as an act that deepened Zhou resentment toward the Shang and helped set in motion the eventual Zhou conquest.",
"Youli": "Youli (羑里) was an ancient site in present-day Tangyin County, Henan Province, remembered as the place where King Wen of Zhou was held captive by the Shang king Di Xin. According to tradition King Wen was confined there for seven years, during which he is said to have devoted himself to the eight trigrams and elaborated them into the sixty-four hexagrams of the I Ching. It is traditionally regarded as the earliest recorded state prison in China, and a memorial complex commemorating King Wen's imprisonment now stands at the site.",
"King_Helü_of_Wu": "King Helü of Wu (闔閭) was a ruler of the state of Wu during the Spring and Autumn period who seized the throne in 514 BCE after arranging the assassination of his predecessor, King Liao. Aided by the strategists Wu Zixu and Sun Tzu, the author of The Art of War, he reorganized Wu's army and administration and forged the state into a formidable military power. In 506 BCE his forces won a series of victories over the much larger state of Chu and captured its capital Ying, though he was later fatally wounded during a campaign against the state of Yue and died in 496 BCE.",
"King_Fuchai_of_Wu": "King Fuchai of Wu (夫差) was the last king of the state of Wu, a power in the lower Yangtze region during the Spring and Autumn period. The son of King Helü, he avenged his father's death by crushing the state of Yue and reducing its king Goujian to submission, but chose to spare Yue rather than annex it outright. Goujian eventually rebuilt his strength and overran Wu in 473 BCE, upon which Fuchai took his own life, bringing the state of Wu to an end.",
"Shi_Qiang_pan": "Shi Qiang pan (史牆盤) is a bronze ritual water basin of the Western Zhou, cast by a court scribe named Qiang of the Wei lineage during the reign of King Gong in the late tenth century BCE. Its interior bears a long inscription of 284 characters in eighteen lines, whose first part recounts the deeds of the early Zhou kings and whose second part records the achievements of the scribe's own ancestors, culminating with the scribe himself. Unearthed in 1976 from a hoard of more than one hundred family vessels at Fufeng in Shaanxi and now held in the Baoji Bronzeware Museum, it is often described as the first conscious attempt in China to write history.",
"Rule_of_Cheng_and_Kang": "Rule of Cheng and Kang (成康之治) is the traditional Chinese name for a period early in the Western Zhou spanning the reigns of King Cheng of Zhou and his son King Kang of Zhou, conventionally dated to roughly the second half of the eleventh century BCE. Chinese historiography remembers it as a golden age of peace, prosperity, and orderly government, when the young dynasty consolidated the order established after the conquest of the Shang dynasty. According to the Records of the Grand Historian, the realm was so secure during these two reigns that punishments were set aside and went unused for more than forty years.",
"Fengchu_complex": "The Fengchu complex (鳳雛) is a large rammed-earth building foundation excavated in 1976 at Fengchu village within Zhouyuan and dated to the early Western Zhou period. Laid out symmetrically along a north-south axis, it comprises a screen wall, a gate chamber, flanking wing rooms, a front hall, rear chambers, and front and rear courtyards, and is widely regarded as one of the earliest and most complete Chinese courtyard-house compounds known. A storage pit in one of its side rooms yielded more than seventeen thousand oracle bones and fragments, a few hundred of them inscribed, making it one of the most important archaeological finds of the early Zhou period.",
"Shu_(region)": "Shu (蜀) is a historical name for the western Sichuan Basin in southwestern China, centered on the fertile Chengdu Plain, an expanse of rich rice and grain farmland ringed by steep mountains that long made it prosperous and easily defended. It is also known as Ba-Shu, a compound name that joins it with the adjacent region of Ba to the east around present-day Chongqing. During the Three Kingdoms period the region formed the heartland of the state of Shu Han, which had its capital at Chengdu.",
"Yi_Province": "Yi Province (益州) was one of the administrative provinces of imperial China, formed under the Han dynasty in the late second century BCE to cover the Sichuan basin and its neighbouring uplands. Centred on the city of Chengdu, at its greatest extent it spanned present-day central and eastern Sichuan, Chongqing, southern Shaanxi, and parts of Yunnan and Guizhou, and was subdivided into commanderies such as Hanzhong, Ba, Shu, and Jianwei. During the collapse of the Eastern Han, the warlord Liu Bei wrested the region from its governor Liu Zhang between 211 and 214 and made it the territorial base of the state of Shu Han.",
"Baidicheng": "Baidicheng (白帝城), or White Emperor City, is a fortified hilltop town overlooking the Yangtze River at the western mouth of the Three Gorges, near present-day Fengjie in Chongqing. Its name derives from Gongsun Shu, a warlord of the early first century CE who proclaimed himself the White Emperor and raised a stronghold on the site. The town became famous in Chinese tradition as the refuge where Liu Bei withdrew after his defeat at the Battle of Xiaoting and died in 223, entrusting his heir to Zhuge Liang.",
"Deng_Ai": "Deng Ai (鄧艾, courtesy name Shizai, c. 197–264) was a general and statesman of the state of Cao Wei during the Three Kingdoms period. In 263 he led an army along treacherous, lightly guarded mountain tracks through the rugged Yinping wilderness to emerge behind the defences of Shu Han and march on its capital, Chengdu. His sudden arrival forced the surrender of the Shu emperor Liu Shan and brought about the fall of Shu Han, though within months Deng Ai was arrested on charges of insubordination and killed while being escorted toward Luoyang.",
"Yang_Liang": "Yang Liang 楊諒 (575–605) was the youngest son of Emperor Wen, the founder of the Sui dynasty, and held the title Prince of Han while governing the fifty-two provinces north of the Yellow River from his base at Bing Province, near modern Taiyuan. In 604, after his father's death placed his brother on the throne as Emperor Yang, Yang Liang rose in armed rebellion with the support of some nineteen provinces and the generals Wang Kui and Xiao Mohe. The revolt was swiftly crushed by the general Yang Su, and Yang Liang was spared execution but stripped of rank, reduced to commoner status, and held in imprisonment until his death.",
"Jing_Province": "Jing Province (荊州), also romanized as Jingzhou, was a large administrative division of imperial China established under Emperor Wu of the Western Han that encompassed the middle reaches of the Yangtze River, roughly corresponding to the modern provinces of Hubei and Hunan. Its fertile Jianghan Plain, defensible mountain-ringed terrain, and command of the Yangtze and Han rivers made it a strategically vital region during the late Eastern Han and Three Kingdoms period. After the death of the provincial governor Liu Biao and the pivotal Battle of Red Cliffs in 208, it was bitterly contested among Cao Cao, Sun Quan, and Liu Bei, and was ultimately partitioned between the states of Cao Wei and Eastern Wu.",
"Longzhong_Plan": "The Longzhong Plan (隆中對) was the grand strategy that the adviser Zhuge Liang set out for the warlord Liu Bei during their meeting at Longzhong, near present-day Xiangyang in Hubei, around 207 CE. It urged Liu Bei to seize Jing Province and Yi Province as a secure territorial base, to form an alliance with the eastern warlord Sun Quan, and together to resist the dominant northern warlord Cao Cao before contending for control of the empire. The plan foresaw a threefold division of China and became the strategic foundation on which Liu Bei established the state of Shu Han.",
"Peach_Garden_oath": "The Peach Garden oath (桃園結義) is a fictional episode near the opening of the fourteenth-century Chinese novel Romance of the Three Kingdoms, in which Liu Bei, Guan Yu, and Zhang Fei swear an oath of brotherhood in a blossoming peach orchard. Pledging to seek not birth on the same day but death on the same day, the three vow to join forces to aid the endangered and restore order to the Han realm amid the upheaval of the Yellow Turban Rebellion. The scene does not appear in Chen Shou's historical Records of the Three Kingdoms and developed from earlier folk tales, becoming an enduring emblem of sworn fraternal loyalty commemorated in temples dedicated to the three men.",
"Zhao_Kuangyin": "Zhao Kuangyin 趙匡胤 was a military general of the Later Zhou who in 960 seized the throne and founded the Song dynasty, reigning until his death as its first emperor under the temple name Taizu. In the Chenqiao Mutiny his troops proclaimed him emperor and forced the abdication of the child ruler of the Later Zhou, after which he campaigned to reunify most of China proper by absorbing the southern states left fragmented during the Five Dynasties and Ten Kingdoms period. To forestall the recurrence of the coups that had toppled a succession of short-lived regimes, he curtailed the authority of the regional military governors, brought the armies under central command, and elevated a civil bureaucracy to administer the realm.",
"Five_Dynasties": "The Five Dynasties (五代) were a succession of five short-lived regimes—Later Liang, Later Tang, Later Jin, Later Han, and Later Zhou—that ruled the North China Plain between the collapse of the Tang dynasty in 907 and the founding of the Song dynasty in 960. The sequence began when the warlord Zhu Wen deposed the last Tang emperor and proclaimed the Later Liang from Kaifeng, and it closed when the Later Zhou general Zhao Kuangyin seized power and established the Song in 960. Because none of the five controlled more than the northern heartland, the period is conventionally paired with the Ten Kingdoms, a set of largely southern states that existed alongside them, together forming the Five Dynasties and Ten Kingdoms era of division.",
"Khitans": "The Khitans 契丹 were a nomadic, Para-Mongolic-speaking people who arose on the eastern steppe across Manchuria and Mongolia. In 916 they founded the Liao dynasty, which for roughly two centuries ruled Manchuria, much of Mongolia, and part of northern China before falling to the Jurchen in 1125. Their name passed westward as the root of Cathay, an early European designation for China, and surviving groups afterward established the Qara Khitai in Central Asia.",
"Liao_dynasty": "The Liao dynasty (遼) was an imperial dynasty founded in 916 by the Khitan leader Yelü Abaoji, ruling a vast realm across Manchuria, the Mongolian Plateau, and part of northern China until 1125. Governed by the Yelü clan, it maintained a dual administration that separated its nomadic steppe subjects under a tribal northern government from its settled Chinese population under a southern government modeled on Tang institutions. It fell to the Jurchen-led Jin dynasty in 1125, after which surviving loyalists led by Yelü Dashi established the Western Liao, also called Qara Khitai, in Central Asia.",
"Jurchens": "The Jurchens (女真) were a Tungusic-speaking people of the forests and river valleys of Manchuria in northeastern Asia. The chieftain Wanyan Aguda united the Jurchen tribes and in 1115 founded the Jin dynasty, which by 1127 had overrun northern China and seized the Song capital at Kaifeng, capturing its emperor. After the Jin dynasty fell in 1234, the Jurchen population of Manchuria was reorganized in the early seventeenth century under Nurhaci and his son Hong Taiji, who renamed the people the Manchus and went on to establish the Qing dynasty.",
"Jin_dynasty_(Jurchen)": "The Jin dynasty (金), founded in 1115 by the Jurchen leader Wanyan Aguda, was an imperial dynasty ruled by the Wanyan clan that governed Manchuria and much of northern China. Having overthrown the Liao dynasty by 1125, it seized the North China Plain from the Song, capturing the Song capital and driving the Song court to relocate south of the Yangtze. The Jin ruled its northern territory until 1234, when it was conquered by the Mongols.",
"Tanguts": "The Tanguts (党項) were a people of Tibeto-Burman origin, belonging to the Qiangic branch, who settled in the arid northwest of what is now China, across the modern regions of Ningxia, Gansu, and the Ordos. They founded and ruled the Western Xia state, a multiethnic realm that also incorporated Han Chinese, Tibetan, and Uyghur populations, from 1038 until its conquest by the Mongol Empire in 1227. The Tanguts spoke their own Qiangic language and devised a distinctive logographic script of roughly 6,000 characters, which remained in use for centuries after the state fell.",
"Western_Xia": "The Western Xia (西夏), also called the Tangut Empire, was a state founded in 1038 by the Tangut leader Li Yuanhao that ruled the northwestern lands of the Ordos region and the Gansu corridor. Centred on its capital at Xingqing, the site of modern Yinchuan, it controlled stretches of the Silk Road trade routes and developed a distinctive logographic script for the Tangut language. The dynasty endured for nearly two centuries until it was overrun by the Mongols under Genghis Khan in 1227.",
"Mongols": "The Mongols (蒙古) are a nomadic pastoral people of the eastern steppe, traditionally organized into herding clans across the grasslands of present-day Mongolia and neighboring regions of Inner Asia. United in 1206 under Genghis Khan, they built through mounted conquest the largest contiguous land empire in history, extending from the Pacific coast to Eastern Europe. Under his grandson Kublai Khan they ruled all of China as the Yuan dynasty from 1271 to 1368, after which their power there gave way to the Ming.",
"Genghis_Khan": "Genghis Khan (成吉思汗), born Temüjin around 1162, was the founder and first Great Khan of the Mongol Empire. At a kurultai held at the source of the Onon River in 1206 he was proclaimed supreme ruler of the united Mongol tribes of the steppe, after which he directed sweeping military campaigns across Central Asia and northern China. By his death in 1227 his conquests had laid the foundation of the largest contiguous land empire in history, which his sons and grandsons continued to expand.",
"Mongol_Empire": "The Mongol Empire was the largest contiguous land empire in history, founded in 1206 when Temujin was proclaimed Genghis Khan and unified the nomadic tribes of the Mongolian steppe under a single ruler. Under Genghis Khan and his successors its armies expanded rapidly across much of Eurasia, conquering territories that stretched from Korea and northern China to Persia, Russia, and the frontiers of Eastern Europe. At its thirteenth-century height it covered roughly 23 million square kilometres before fragmenting into several khanates, among them the Yuan dynasty in China and the Golden Horde on the western steppe.",
"Kublai_Khan": "Kublai Khan 忽必烈 (1215–1294) was a grandson of Genghis Khan who became Great Khan of the Mongol Empire in 1260 and founded the Yuan dynasty of China. He proclaimed the dynastic name Great Yuan in 1271 and completed the Mongol conquest of China by subjugating the Song dynasty in 1279, ruling from a new capital at Dadu, on the site of present-day Beijing. Honored posthumously with the temple name Emperor Shizu of Yuan, he presided over an empire that opened direct contact between East Asia and Europe and whose court was famously described by the traveler Marco Polo.",
"Great_Khan": "The Great Khan (大汗), also rendered as khagan, was the supreme ruler of the Mongol Empire, the paramount sovereign to whom the lesser khans of the realm owed allegiance. Temüjin assumed the title at a kurultai in 1206 as Genghis Khan, and the office passed among his descendants through election at these assemblies, with his son Ögedei formally adopting the fuller style khagan. Kublai Khan was proclaimed Great Khan in 1260 and went on to found the Yuan dynasty, after which the empire fractured and the title's authority over the western khanates became largely nominal.",
"Dadu": "Dadu (大都, meaning Grand Capital) was the principal capital of the Yuan dynasty, laid out on a grand rectangular plan by Kublai Khan on the site of present-day Beijing, with construction beginning in the 1260s, the city proclaimed capital in 1272, and building work completed around 1293. Known in Mongolian and Turkic as Khanbaliq, meaning City of the Khan, and reported to Europeans by Marco Polo as Cambaluc, it stood as the eastern seat of the Mongol realm and a cosmopolitan center of trade and many religions. The city fell to Ming forces in 1368, after which its palaces were razed and it was renamed Beiping, later rebuilt to form the core of modern Beijing.",
"Semu": "The Semu (色目) were a legally defined social class in the Yuan dynasty of Mongol-ruled China, comprising a diverse array of non-Han, non-Mongol peoples drawn largely from Central and Western Asia, including Turkic, Persian, Tangut, and Tibetan groups. Within the dynasty's tiered four-class hierarchy they were placed below the ruling Mongols but above the Han Chinese, and the name itself denoted an assortment of varied categories of people rather than a single unified ethnicity. Many Semu served the Mongol court as officials, tax supervisors, financial managers, and merchants, functioning as a privileged administrative and commercial intermediary across the empire.",
"Pax_Mongolica": "The Pax Mongolica, Latin for Mongol Peace, refers to the period of relative stability and security across Eurasia during the 13th and 14th centuries, when the vast conquests of the Mongol Empire brought a single political order to territories stretching from Eastern Europe to East Asia. With the trade routes of the Silk Road unified under Mongol control and protected by administrative measures such as the yam relay postal system and safe-conduct passes for merchants, overland commerce across the continent flourished with comparatively little disruption. This secured connection fostered an extensive exchange of goods, people, technologies, and ideas among the civilizations of Europe, the Islamic world, and Asia, and it is generally regarded as ending amid the fragmentation of the khanates and the spread of the Black Death in the mid-14th century.",
"Marco_Polo": "Marco Polo (c. 1254–1324) was a Venetian merchant and traveller who journeyed across Asia along the Silk Road, reaching the China of the Yuan dynasty around 1275. He spent roughly seventeen years in the service of the Mongol emperor Kublai Khan, undertaking missions to distant parts of the realm before returning to Venice near the close of the thirteenth century. His account of these journeys, later known as The Travels of Marco Polo or Il Milione, introduced medieval Europe to the geography, wealth, and customs of the East and remained one of the most widely read descriptions of Asia for generations.",
"Zaju": "Zaju 雜劇 is a form of classical Chinese musical theatre that unites sung arias, spoken dialogue, and stylized dance and mime. A typical play is organized into four acts, each built on a suite of songs in a single musical mode and rhyme, with the singing delivered by one leading male or female role. The genre reached its height under the Yuan dynasty, an era often regarded as a golden age of Chinese drama and associated with playwrights such as Guan Hanqing and works including Wang Shifu's The Story of the Western Wing.",
"Jiaozi": "Jiaozi (交子) were promissory notes issued in the Sichuan region during the Northern Song dynasty and are widely regarded as the earliest paper money in the world. They arose because Sichuan circulated cumbersome iron coins, prompting merchant houses in Chengdu to issue deposit receipts redeemable for coin, a practice the government later took over and regulated through a state paper-notes office established in 1023. As printed certificates standing in for metal currency, jiaozi could be exchanged for a fixed value of cash and served as a convenient medium for commerce.",
"Champa_rice": "Champa rice is a fast-ripening, drought-resistant strain of rice that takes its name from the kingdom of Champa in what is now central Vietnam, from which it spread across maritime and mainland Asia. Reaching China by the early eleventh century and actively promoted by the Song court under Emperor Zhenzong, who around 1012 had seed grain distributed to drought-prone regions, it matured in roughly a hundred days and could be grown on higher, less reliably watered ground. Its short growing season permitted two harvests a year across much of the Yangzi basin and southern China, contributing to a substantial expansion of food production and a surge in population.",
"Tibetan_Buddhism": "Tibetan Buddhism is a form of Vajrayana Buddhism that developed in Tibet and the surrounding Himalayan region, combining the Mahayana and tantric traditions of Indian Buddhism with indigenous ritual and cultural elements. It is organized into several schools, among them the Nyingma, Kagyu, Sakya, and Gelug, whose teachings pass through lineages of lamas and emphasize esoteric practices such as deity yoga, mantra recitation, and meditation directed toward the attainment of Buddhahood. Established in Tibet from the seventh century onward and elaborated over the following centuries, it later received extensive patronage from the Mongol Yuan and Manchu Qing courts and spread across Mongolia, the Himalayas, and parts of Central and East Asia.",
"Eight_Ancient_Capitals_of_China": "The Eight Ancient Capitals of China (八大古都) are a traditional grouping of the eight cities that served as the seat of government for major Chinese dynasties, namely Xian, Luoyang, Nanjing, Beijing, Kaifeng, Hangzhou, Anyang, and Zhengzhou. The list took shape gradually over the twentieth century, beginning with four capitals recognized in the 1920s and growing as the China Ancient Capital Society added Anyang as the seventh in 1988 and Zhengzhou as the eighth in 2004. Four of the eight cities lie in Henan province, and collectively the group spans more than three thousand years of dynastic history, from the Shang capital at Anyang to Beijing under the Ming dynasty and the Qing dynasty.",
"Han_state": "The state of Han (韓) was one of the seven major powers of the Warring States period, created in 403 BCE when the noble houses of Han, Zhao, and Wei partitioned the state of Jin and won recognition as marquises from the Zhou court. Occupying a compact and strategically exposed territory on the central plain in what is now Shanxi and Henan, it ranked among the smallest of the seven states, yet it was the home of the Legalist philosopher Han Fei. In 230 BCE it became the first of the seven states to fall to the state of Qin, an early step in Qin's conquest and unification of China.",
"Legalism": "Legalism (法家) was a school of political thought that emerged during the Warring States period, holding that social order is best secured through strict written laws, severe punishments, and the concentration of authority in the ruler. Its leading thinkers included Shang Yang, Han Fei, and Li Si, who argued that clearly defined rewards and penalties applied uniformly to all subjects provided a dependable basis for governing the state. The doctrine became the guiding ideology of the state of Qin, whose adoption of Legalist administrative and military reforms enabled it to overcome its rivals and establish China's first unified empire in 221 BCE.",
"Shu_Han": "Shu Han (蜀漢) was one of the three states of the Three Kingdoms period, founded in 221 by the warlord Liu Bei in the Sichuan region with its capital at Chengdu. Its rulers took the dynastic name Han and presented themselves as the legitimate continuation of the fallen Han dynasty. The state was ruled after Liu Bei's death by his son Liu Shan and administered for years by the chancellor Zhuge Liang, until it was conquered by the rival state of Cao Wei in 263.",
"Red_Turban_Rebellion": "The Red Turban Rebellion (紅巾起義) was a series of mid-14th-century popular uprisings, beginning in 1351, against the Mongol-led Yuan dynasty of China, whose fighters identified themselves by wearing red turbans. Its leaders drew on the millenarian teachings of the White Lotus movement, which prophesied the advent of the Maitreya Buddha, and rallied peasants embittered by famine, heavy taxation, and the devastating flooding of the Yellow River. From among its competing factions Zhu Yuanzhang rose to defeat his rivals and expel the Yuan, proclaiming himself the Hongwu Emperor and founding the Ming dynasty in 1368.",
"Zheng_He": "Zheng He 鄭和 (c. 1371–1433) was a Muslim eunuch admiral and diplomat of the early Ming dynasty, born Ma He and later granted the surname Zheng by the Yongle Emperor after distinguished military service. Between 1405 and 1433 he commanded seven large maritime expeditions across the South China Sea and Indian Ocean, sailing under the commission of the Yongle Emperor and then the Xuande Emperor. His fleets, which included enormous treasure ships, reached Southeast Asia, India, Arabia, and the east coast of Africa, projecting Ming diplomatic and commercial influence far across the maritime world.",
"Eight-legged_essay": "The eight-legged essay 八股文 was a rigidly prescribed style of prose composition required of candidates in the Chinese imperial examinations under the Ming and Qing dynasties. It took its name from its eight balanced sections of parallel argument, within which the writer expounded a brief passage from the Confucian Four Books or Five Classics, adhering strictly to orthodox interpretations and to a fixed length of several hundred characters. Standardized in the mid-Ming and later condemned by reformers as a constraint on original thought, it dominated examination writing until it was dropped from the civil examinations in 1901, a few years before the imperial examination system was abolished altogether in 1905.",
"Unequal_treaties": "The unequal treaties (不平等條約) were a series of agreements imposed on Qing China by Western powers and Japan during the 19th and early 20th centuries, following Chinese defeats in conflicts such as the Opium Wars and the First Sino-Japanese War. Beginning with the Treaty of Nanking in 1842 and extending through the Boxer Protocol of 1901, they forced open treaty ports to foreign trade, ceded territory including Hong Kong, granted foreign nationals extraterritoriality from Chinese jurisdiction, fixed low tariffs that stripped China of tariff autonomy, and levied heavy indemnities. Their terms placed obligations almost entirely on China, and the phrase became a rallying point for Chinese nationalists in the early twentieth century who campaigned to abolish the treaties and recover full sovereignty.",
"Century_of_Humiliation": "The Century of Humiliation (百年國恥) is a term in Chinese national memory for the period running from the First Opium War of 1839 to the founding of the People's Republic of China in 1949. Across this era the ruling Qing dynasty and the succeeding Republic of China were repeatedly defeated by Western powers, Russia, and Japan and forced to accept unequal treaties that ceded territory such as Hong Kong, opened treaty ports, and granted foreigners sweeping legal and economic privileges. Popularized in the early twentieth century and later emphasized by the Chinese Communist Party, the narrative of foreign aggression and eventual national recovery remains a central element of Chinese identity and political discourse.",
"Taiping_Rebellion": "The Taiping Rebellion (太平天國) was a massive civil war fought in Qing China from 1850 to 1864 between the ruling Qing dynasty and the rebel Taiping Heavenly Kingdom. It was led by Hong Xiuquan, a failed examination candidate who, after visions he interpreted as divine, declared himself the younger brother of Jesus Christ and in 1851 founded a heterodox Christian theocracy aimed at toppling the Manchu Qing and building a Heavenly Kingdom of Great Peace. Combining fervent religion with radical social and land reforms, the movement was finally crushed when Qing and provincial armies retook its capital at Nanjing in 1864, by which point warfare, famine, and disease had killed an estimated twenty to thirty million people, making it one of the deadliest conflicts in history.",
"Boxer_Rebellion": "The Boxer Rebellion (義和團運動) was an anti-foreign, anti-Christian uprising in northern China from 1899 to 1901, driven by a martial-arts movement known in the West as the Boxers and rallying under the slogan support the Qing, destroy the foreigners. In the summer of 1900 the Boxers, with backing from the Qing court, besieged the foreign legation quarter in Beijing for fifty-five days while attacking missionaries and Chinese Christians across the north. An eight-nation alliance of foreign troops relieved the siege and captured Beijing, and the resulting Boxer Protocol of 1901 stationed foreign soldiers in the capital and imposed a heavy indemnity on the Qing government.",
"King_Ping_of_Zhou": "King Ping of Zhou was the king who in 770 BCE moved the royal capital eastward to Luoyi, inaugurating the Eastern Zhou. His relocation followed the fall of his father King You and the sack of the old western capital by Quanrong tribesmen and rebels. From his reign onward the Zhou kings retained only nominal authority while the great states rose, opening the Spring and Autumn period.",
"King_Wu_of_Zhou": "King Wu of Zhou was the founder of the Zhou dynasty, who overthrew the last Shang king and won mastery over the Chinese heartland. The son of King Wen, he led an alliance of states to victory over the Shang at the Battle of Muye around 1046 BCE, an event later seen as the transfer of the Mandate of Heaven. He died only a few years into his reign, after which his brother the Duke of Zhou governed as regent.",
"King_Jing_Gui_of_Zhou": "King Jing of Zhou (周景王), personal name Gui, was a king of the Chinese Zhou dynasty who reigned from 544 to 520 BCE during the Eastern Zhou and the Spring and Autumn period, when the Zhou kings held little real power beyond their capital at Luoyi. He succeeded King Ling of Zhou, and the traditional record notes that his court was in financial difficulty, at times having to obtain supplies from neighbouring states. His death in 520 BCE was followed by a violent succession struggle among his sons, in which his heir briefly reigned as King Dao before the throne was contested between Prince Chao and Prince Gai, the latter eventually prevailing as King Jing of Zhou.",
"King_Wen_of_Zhou": "King Wen of Zhou (周文王), born Ji Chang, was a pre-dynastic Zhou leader who ruled the Zhou state as Count of the West under the Shang until his death around 1050 BCE, and he is revered as the founding king of the Zhou dynasty, honored with that title posthumously. He is remembered in Chinese tradition as an ideal sage-ruler who received the Mandate of Heaven and laid the foundation for the conquest of the Shang, which his son King Wu completed after his death. Tradition also credits him with arranging the sixty-four hexagrams of the I Ching and composing the judgements upon them.",
"King_Cheng_of_Zhou": "King Cheng of Zhou (周成王) was the second king of the Chinese Zhou dynasty, reigning during the early Western Zhou period from about 1042 to 1021 BCE. Having come to the throne as a child, he ruled at first under the regency of his paternal uncle the Duke of Zhou, who suppressed the Rebellion of the Three Guards and consolidated the newly founded dynasty. His reign together with that of his successor and son King Kang was later remembered as the Rule of Cheng and Kang, a golden age of stability and consolidation.",
"King_Kang_of_Zhou": "King Kang of Zhou (周康王) was the third king of the Chinese Zhou dynasty, reigning during the Western Zhou period as the son and successor of King Cheng of Zhou. His reign continued the peace and stability that his father had established, and traditional histories group the two together as the Cheng-Kang era. This period was praised by later chroniclers as a golden age of good order, said to have lasted more than forty years during which punishments went unused.",
"King_Zhao_of_Zhou": "King Zhao of Zhou (周昭王) was the fourth king of the Zhou dynasty of ancient China, reigning during the Western Zhou period from around 977 to 957 BCE. He is remembered chiefly for leading a series of military campaigns southward against the state of Chu and the polities of the Han River valley, seeking to extend Zhou control over the middle Yangtze region. His final expedition ended in catastrophe, with his army destroyed and the king himself dying on campaign, traditionally said to have drowned in the Han River.",
"King_Mu_of_Zhou": "King Mu of Zhou (周穆王) was the fifth king of the Chinese Zhou dynasty, reigning during the Western Zhou for roughly half a century from about 976 to 922 BCE. His long rule was marked by military campaigns, notably a westward expedition against the Quanrong, and by an interest in law that tradition credits with an early systematic penal code preserved in the Book of Documents as the Punishments of Lü, a graduated schedule of penalties framed by his minister the Marquis of Lü. He is best remembered in later legend for extraordinary far-western travels aboard a chariot drawn by eight fine horses, during which he is said to have journeyed to the Kunlun mountains and met the Queen Mother of the West.",
"King_Gong_of_Zhou": "King Gong of Zhou (周共王) was the sixth king of the Chinese Zhou dynasty, ruling during the Western Zhou period conventionally from about 922 to 900 BCE and succeeding his father King Mu of Zhou. His reign is sparsely documented, but he is chiefly remembered for a campaign against the small state of Mi, recounted in the Records of the Grand Historian. According to that received tradition, King Gong demanded that the lord of Mi hand over three beautiful women, and when the lord kept them for himself the king invaded Mi and destroyed the state.",
"King_Yi_Jian_of_Zhou": "King Yi of Zhou (周懿王), whose personal name was Ji Jian, was the seventh king of the Chinese Zhou dynasty, reigning during the Western Zhou period from about 899 to 892 BCE, with the first year of his reign conventionally fixed by a solar eclipse recorded for 21 April 899 BCE. His reign is poorly documented, but tradition remembers it as a time of declining Zhou fortunes, and Sima Qian noted that poets composed verses satirizing the age. The Bamboo Annals record that the king moved the capital from Zongzhou to a locality called Huaili, which some read as a sign that he had been removed from power by his uncle, though the matter is uncertain.",
"King_Xiao_of_Zhou": "King Xiao of Zhou (周孝王) was the eighth king of the Chinese Zhou dynasty, conventionally reigning around 891 to 886 BCE during the Western Zhou period. A son of King Mu and younger brother of King Gong, he came to the throne out of the direct line of succession, taking power after his nephew King Yi rather than passing it to that king's own heirs. He is best remembered for granting Feizi, the ancestor of the Qin ruling house, a fief at Qin along with the charge of breeding and raising horses for the Zhou, an appointment traditionally regarded as the origin of the state of Qin.",
"King_Yi_Xie_of_Zhou": "King Yi of Zhou (周夷王), personal name Ji Xie, was the ninth king of the Western Zhou dynasty, conventionally reigning c. 885-878 BCE. His reign is traditionally associated with a decline in royal authority, as regional rulers grew less inclined to pay homage to the Zhou court. According to tradition he sided with the Marquis of Ji in a dispute and had Duke Ai of Qi boiled alive in a cauldron, afterward installing the duke's half-brother as ruler of Qi.",
"King_Li_of_Zhou": "King Li of Zhou (周厲王) was the tenth king of the Chinese Zhou dynasty, reigning during the Western Zhou period from c. 877 to 841 BCE. He is remembered as a tyrant who seized state monopolies over the profits of communal forests and lakes and who imposed a brutal law that put to death anyone who dared criticize him, silencing dissent so thoroughly that people reportedly communicated only with their eyes. His exactions and repression provoked a popular uprising in 841 BCE that drove him into exile at Zhi, inaugurating the Gonghe regency that governed in his absence until his death around 828 BCE.",
"King_Xuan_of_Zhou": "King Xuan of Zhou (周宣王) was the eleventh king of the Chinese Zhou dynasty and the penultimate ruler of the Western Zhou, reigning from 827 to 782 BCE. He came to the throne after the fourteen-year Gonghe regency that had followed the exile of his father King Li, and he led a partial restoration of Zhou authority through military campaigns against the Xianyun and other neighbouring peoples. His later years, however, were marked by military reversals, including a defeat at the Battle of Qianmu, and a decline in royal control over the regional lords.",
"King_You_of_Zhou": "King You of Zhou (周幽王) was the twelfth and last king of the Western Zhou dynasty, conventionally reigning from 781 to 771 BCE. Enamoured of his concubine Baosi, he deposed his queen and their son the crown prince Yijiu in favour of Baosi and her son Bofu, provoking the outrage of his father-in-law the Marquess of Shen. The Marquess allied with the Quanrong, whose forces sacked the capital of Haojing and killed King You at the foot of Mount Li in 771 BCE, ending Western Zhou rule.",
"King_Huan_of_Zhou": "King Huan of Zhou (周桓王) was the fourteenth king of the Zhou dynasty and the second king of the Eastern Zhou, reigning from 719 to 697 BCE after succeeding his grandfather King Ping, whose son and heir Crown Prince Xiefu had predeceased him. Seeking to reassert royal authority over the increasingly independent regional states, King Huan led a coalition against the state of Zheng but was defeated at the Battle of Xuge in 707 BCE, where he was wounded in the shoulder by an arrow shot by Zheng forces under Duke Zhuang. This humiliating defeat shattered the prestige of the Zhou court and openly exposed the collapse of royal power at the outset of the Spring and Autumn period.",
"King_Zhuang_of_Zhou": "King Zhuang of Zhou (周莊王), personal name Ji Tuo, was the fifteenth king of the Chinese Zhou dynasty, conventionally reigning from 696 to 682 BCE. He succeeded his father, King Huan of Zhou, and ruled from Luoyi during the early Spring and Autumn period of the Eastern Zhou, when the king's authority continued to wane as regional states grew increasingly autonomous. Little of substance is recorded of his fourteen-year reign, which is remembered chiefly for this continued decline of royal power rather than for any notable events or accomplishments.",
"King_Xi_of_Zhou": "King Xi of Zhou (周釐王) was the fourth king of the Eastern Zhou, reigning from 681 to 677 BCE during the Spring and Autumn period, when the Zhou kings had become largely ceremonial figures while regional states held real power. The son of King Zhuang of Zhou and father of King Hui of Zhou, he ruled from the eastern capital at Luoyi over a realm in which the feudal lords increasingly acted independently of the royal house. It was during his reign that Duke Huan of Qi rose to preeminence and came to be recognized as the first of the hegemons who dominated interstate politics in the place of the enfeebled Zhou throne.",
"King_Hui_of_Zhou": "King Hui of Zhou (周惠王) was the seventeenth king of the Chinese Zhou dynasty, reigning during the Spring and Autumn period of the Eastern Zhou. He ruled from 676 to 652 BCE, succeeding his father King Xi and preceding his son King Xiang. Early in his reign a revolt led by his uncle Prince Tui, backed by disaffected nobles, briefly drove him from the royal capital, and he was restored to the throne with the military support of the states of Zheng and Guo, whose lords killed the usurper.",
"King_Xiang_of_Zhou": "King Xiang of Zhou (周襄王), personal name Ji Zheng, was the sixth king of the Eastern Zhou period, reigning conventionally from 651 to 619 BCE during the Spring and Autumn period as a successor to his father King Hui. In 635 BCE he was driven from the royal capital at Luoyi by his younger brother, Prince Dai, and was restored to the throne by the Jin ruler Duke Wen. In gratitude for this support King Xiang granted Duke Wen several counties of the royal domain in the Nanyang region, and he later formally acknowledged Duke Wen as hegemon among the regional lords.",
"King_Qing_of_Zhou": "King Qing of Zhou (周頃王) was a king of the Eastern Zhou dynasty who reigned from 618 to 613 BCE during the Spring and Autumn period, succeeding his father King Xiang of Zhou. By his time the Zhou kings held little real power, functioning as ceremonial figureheads while the regional states dominated affairs. Little of substance is recorded of his brief reign, and he was succeeded by his son King Kuang of Zhou.",
"King_Kuang_of_Zhou": "King Kuang of Zhou (周匡王), personal name Ji Ban, was the eighth king of the Eastern Zhou dynasty, reigning from 612 to 607 BCE during the Spring and Autumn period. He was a son of King Qing of Zhou, whom he succeeded, and after his death the throne passed to his brother, who ruled as King Ding of Zhou. Little is recorded of his brief reign, as by this time the Zhou kings had become largely ceremonial figures while the great regional states held the real power.",
"King_Ding_of_Zhou": "King Ding of Zhou (周定王) was a king of the Eastern Zhou dynasty during the Spring and Autumn period, conventionally reigning from 606 to 586 BCE as a son of King Qing of Zhou and the successor of his elder brother King Kuang of Zhou. His reign fell in an age when the Zhou kings retained ritual prestige but wielded little real power, which had passed to the great regional states. According to traditional accounts, it was in 606 BCE during his reign that the ambitious King Zhuang of Chu, having marched his army near the royal capital, inquired about the size and weight of the royal nine tripod cauldrons in a gesture widely understood as a challenge to Zhou legitimacy, and the Zhou envoy Wangsun Man rebuffed him by declaring that sovereignty rested on virtue rather than on the cauldrons themselves.",
"King_Jian_of_Zhou": "King Jian of Zhou (周簡王) was the twenty-second king of the Chinese Zhou dynasty and a ruler of the Eastern Zhou during the Spring and Autumn period, conventionally reigning from 585 to 572 BCE as the son and successor of King Ding of Zhou. Little is recorded of his reign, during which the Zhou royal house retained only nominal authority and functioned largely as a ceremonial figurehead. His years on the throne coincided with the prolonged struggle between the powerful states of Jin and Chu for supremacy over the other Chinese states.",
"King_Ling_of_Zhou": "King Ling of Zhou (周靈王) was the twenty-third king of the Chinese Zhou dynasty and the eleventh of the Eastern Zhou, reigning conventionally from 571 to 545 BCE during the Spring and Autumn period, when the Zhou kings had become largely ceremonial figureheads. He succeeded his father King Jian of Zhou and was in turn succeeded by his son King Jing of Zhou. Little of note is recorded of his reign in the surviving sources, which chiefly remark that the philosopher Confucius was born during it.",
"King_Dao_of_Zhou": "King Dao of Zhou (周悼王), personal name Ji Meng, was a king of the Eastern Zhou dynasty during the Spring and Autumn period, reigning briefly in 520 BCE after the death of his father, King Jing of Zhou. His short reign was consumed by a violent dispute over the succession, in which his brother Prince Zhao contested the throne. He was killed within the year during the struggle with Prince Zhao, and the throne passed to another of his brothers, Prince Gai, who reigned as King Jing of Zhou.",
"King_Jing_Gai_of_Zhou": "King Jing of Zhou (周敬王), personal name Ji Gai, was a king of the Eastern Zhou dynasty who reigned from 519 to 477 BCE during the late Spring and Autumn period. He came to the throne only after a succession war, in which his brother Prince Zhao seized power on the death of their father King Jing (Gui) and was ousted when the state of Jin intervened militarily to install Gai, though conflict between the brothers persisted for years and the court was moved eastward to a new seat at Chengzhou. His long reign of more than four decades spanned the closing years of the Spring and Autumn era, by which time the Zhou king held little real authority and the great regional states dominated affairs.",
"King_Yuan_of_Zhou": "King Yuan of Zhou (周元王) was a king of the Eastern Zhou dynasty who reigned from 475 to 469 BCE, ruling from the capital at Luoyi. He was a son of King Jing of Zhou, whom he succeeded, and he was in turn succeeded by his own son, King Zhending of Zhou. His accession is conventionally taken, following the chronology of the historian Sima Qian, to mark the transition from the Spring and Autumn period to the Warring States period, though little of substance is recorded of his reign, by which time the Zhou kings had become largely ceremonial figureheads.",
"King_Zhending_of_Zhou": "King Zhending of Zhou (周貞定王), personal name Ji Jie, was a king of the Chinese Zhou dynasty who ruled during the Eastern Zhou period, conventionally reigning from 468 to 441 BCE. His reign spanned the transition from the Spring and Autumn period into the Warring States period, by which time the Zhou kings had become largely ceremonial figureheads while real power rested with the regional states. During his rule the de facto partition of the powerful state of Jin among its ministerial families of Han, Zhao, and Wei was underway, following the destruction of the rival Zhi clan at the Battle of Jinyang in 453 BCE.",
"King_Ai_of_Zhou": "King Ai of Zhou (周哀王), personal name Ji Quji, was a king of the Zhou dynasty during the Warring States period of the Eastern Zhou, ruling from the royal seat at Luoyi. The eldest son of King Zhending, he succeeded his father in 441 BCE, by which time the Zhou kings retained only ceremonial authority while power lay with the regional states. His reign lasted only about three months before he was killed by his younger brother Shuxi, who briefly took the throne as King Si of Zhou.",
"King_Si_of_Zhou": "King Si of Zhou (周思王), personal name Ji Shuxi, was a king of the Eastern Zhou dynasty who reigned briefly in 441 BCE. He seized the throne in that year by killing his elder brother King Ai of Zhou, who had himself ruled for only a few months. King Si then reigned for about five months before he too was killed, slain by his younger brother, who succeeded him as King Kao of Zhou.",
"King_Kao_of_Zhou": "King Kao of Zhou (周考王) was a king of the Zhou dynasty of ancient China who reigned during the Eastern Zhou period, in the early years of the Warring States era. His conventional reign is given as 440 to 426 BCE, following his father King Zhending and preceding his son King Weilie. During his reign he enfeoffed his younger brother, later known as Duke Huan of Western Zhou, within the greatly diminished royal domain around the capital in present-day Henan, creating the small polity of Western Zhou that would in time further fragment.",
"King_Weilie_of_Zhou": "King Weilie of Zhou (周威烈王) was a sovereign of the Eastern Zhou dynasty who reigned from 425 to 402 BCE, a period in which the Zhou kings retained ceremonial authority while real power lay with the contending regional states. In 403 BCE he formally recognized the rulers of Han, Zhao, and Wei as marquesses following their partition of the state of Jin. This royal sanction of the partition of Jin is conventionally taken by historians to mark the beginning of the Warring States period.",
"King_An_of_Zhou": "King An of Zhou (周安王), personal name Ji Jiao, was a king of the Eastern Zhou dynasty who conventionally reigned from 401 to 376 BCE during the Warring States period. He succeeded his father King Weilie of Zhou and was in turn succeeded by his son King Lie of Zhou. Little is recorded of his reign, during which he held only nominal authority as a ceremonial figurehead while the major warring states contended for power.",
"King_Lie_of_Zhou": "King Lie of Zhou (周烈王) was a monarch of the Eastern Zhou dynasty who reigned from 375 to 369 BCE during the Warring States period, succeeding his father King An of Zhou. He held little real authority, as the Zhou royal domain had shrunk to a small territory around Luoyi while power lay with the contending regional states. Little is recorded of his brief reign, which is remembered mainly for events in neighboring states, such as Duke Xian of Qin moving the Qin capital to Yueyang.",
"King_Xian_of_Zhou": "King Xian of Zhou (周顯王), personal name Ji Bian, was a king of the Eastern Zhou dynasty who reigned from 368 to 321 BCE during the Warring States period, by which time the Zhou monarch had become a largely ceremonial figure while power rested with the contending regional states. Little is recorded of his own actions, though it was during his long reign that the western state of Qin rose to preeminence through the sweeping legalist reforms of the statesman Shang Yang, which strengthened Qin's administration, agriculture, and military. Late in his reign the rulers of the major states began proclaiming themselves kings in their own right, ceasing even to acknowledge the king of Zhou as their nominal overlord.",
"King_Shenjing_of_Zhou": "King Shenjing of Zhou (周慎靚王) was the penultimate king of the Zhou dynasty, reigning during the Eastern Zhou in the Warring States period from around 320 to 315 BCE. He was a son of King Xian of Zhou and was succeeded by his own son, King Nan of Zhou. Little is recorded of his brief reign, as the Zhou king held only nominal authority while the warring states manoeuvred through shifting alliances and the major regional powers determined the era's events.",
"King_Nan_of_Zhou": "King Nan of Zhou (周赧王) was the last king of the Zhou dynasty, reigning during the Warring States period from 314 to 256 BCE, a span of some fifty-nine years that is the longest recorded reign of any pre-imperial Chinese ruler. By his time the Zhou kings held little more than ceremonial authority, and the royal domain around Luoyi had shrunk and fractured, leaving him dependent on the rival lords of the small West Zhou and East Zhou states. In 256 BCE the state of Qin overran the tiny royal territory and King Nan submitted to Qin, dying soon afterward and bringing the roughly eight-century Zhou dynasty to an end.",
"King_Tai_of_Zhou": "The Old Duke Danfu (古公亶父), an early leader of the Zhou people who was posthumously honoured as King Tai (太王), guided his followers away from the Bin region to escape raids by neighbouring tribes and settled them on the plain of Zhouyuan at the foot of Mount Qi in the Wei River valley. There he laid out walled towns, ancestral temples, and ordered fields, transforming a migrant people into a settled polity and founding the enduring base of the Zhou state. He was the grandfather of King Wen of Zhou, through whom the line that would overthrow the Shang dynasty descended.",
"King_Ji_of_Zhou": "King Ji of Zhou (季歷), whose personal name was Ji Li, was a leader of the predynastic Zhou, the son of the Old Duke Danfu and the father of King Wen of Zhou. He strengthened the Zhou through a series of military campaigns against neighbouring Rong peoples, expanding its territory and prestige while serving nominally as a vassal of the Shang dynasty. Wary of this growing power, the Shang king Wen Ding had him imprisoned and put to death, and he was later honoured with the posthumous title King Ji.",
"Emperor_Wu_of_Han": "Emperor Wu of Han was the seventh emperor of the Han dynasty, whose long reign marked one of the high points of Chinese imperial power. He greatly expanded the empire through campaigns against the Xiongnu nomads and into Central Asia, the south, and Korea, opening the trade routes later called the Silk Road. He also made Confucianism the official state doctrine and centralized the government, shaping the imperial system for centuries.",
"Emperor_Xian_of_Han": "The last emperor of the Han dynasty, who reigned from 189 to 220 as a powerless figurehead under the control of Cao Cao. In 220 he was forced to abdicate to Cao Cao's son Cao Pi, an act that formally ended the Han and ushered in the Three Kingdoms. He lived out his remaining years as the Duke of Shanyang and died in 234.",
"Qian_trigram": "The Qian trigram (乾), pinyin Qián, is the first of the eight trigrams of the bagua, formed of three unbroken yang lines. In the symbolism of the Book of Changes it takes heaven or the sky as its natural image and the Creative, strong and active and ceaselessly initiating, as its chief attribute. Within the family scheme it stands for the father, is assigned the northwest in the Later Heaven arrangement, and is correlated with the phase metal.",
"Kun_trigram": "The Kun trigram (坤), Kūn, is one of the eight trigrams of the bagua, composed of three broken yin lines stacked one above another. Its natural image is the earth, and its chief attribute is the Receptive, a yielding and nurturing power that sustains and gives form to what has been initiated. In the symbolic family scheme of the Book of Changes it is read as the mother, and it is assigned the direction southwest and the phase earth.",
"Zhen_trigram": "The Zhen trigram (震), pronounced Zhèn, is one of the eight trigrams (bagua) of the Book of Changes, composed of a single unbroken yang line below two broken yin lines. Its natural image is thunder, and its chief attribute is the Arousing, the sudden movement, shock, and awakening produced by an energetic impulse rising from beneath. In the symbolic family scheme it is read as the eldest son, and it is associated with the direction east, the phase wood, and the season of spring.",
"Kan_trigram": "The Kan trigram (坎, Kǎn) is one of the eight trigrams of the bagua, composed of a single unbroken (yang) line set between two broken (yin) lines (☵). Its natural image is water, and its chief attribute is danger, the plunging depth of the Abysmal into which things flow and sink. In the symbolic scheme read as a family it stands for the middle son, and it is aligned with the north, the phase water, the moon, and the season of winter.",
"Gen_trigram": "The Gen trigram (艮), pinyin Gen, is one of the eight trigrams (bagua) of the Book of Changes, composed of a single unbroken yang line resting above two broken yin lines. Its natural image is the mountain, and its chief attribute is Keeping Still, expressing stillness, stopping, and the point at which movement comes to rest. In the symbolic family scheme it represents the youngest son, and it is correlated with the northeast direction and the phase earth.",
"Xun_trigram": "The Xun trigram (巽), pinyin Xùn, is one of the eight trigrams (bagua) of the Book of Changes, formed by a single broken yin line beneath two unbroken yang lines. Its natural image is wind and wood, and its chief attribute is the Gentle, a soft influence that penetrates and pervades everything, as wind slips through the smallest openings or roots work quietly into the earth. In the symbolic scheme it stands for the eldest daughter, corresponds to the direction southeast, and is associated with the phase wood.",
"Li_trigram": "The Li trigram (離), pronounced lí, is one of the eight trigrams of the bagua whose paired combinations form the sixty-four hexagrams of the Book of Changes, and it is composed of a single broken yin line held between two unbroken yang lines. Its natural image is fire, and its chief attribute is the Clinging, expressing brightness, clarity, and radiant illumination. In the symbolic scheme it is identified with the middle daughter among the family of trigrams, the direction south, the phase fire, the sun, and the season of summer.",
"Dui_trigram": "The Dui trigram (兌), pronounced Duì, is one of the eight trigrams (bagua) of the Book of Changes, formed of a single broken yin line resting above two unbroken yang lines. Its natural image is the lake or marsh, and its chief attribute is the Joyous, expressing pleasure, satisfaction, and open-hearted receptiveness. In the symbolic family scheme it represents the youngest daughter, and it is aligned with the direction west, the phase metal, and the season of autumn.",
"Jin_dynasty_(266-420)": "The Jin dynasty (晉) was a Chinese imperial dynasty founded in 266 by Sima Yan, who seized the throne from Cao Wei and in 280 conquered Eastern Wu to reunify China after the Three Kingdoms period. Its first phase, the Western Jin, ruled from Luoyang but disintegrated amid the War of the Eight Princes and invasions by northern peoples, losing the north when Chang'an fell in 316. Members of the imperial house then re-established the dynasty as the Eastern Jin, which governed southern China from Jiankang until 420, when the general Liu Yu overthrew it to found the Liu Song dynasty.",
"Northern_and_Southern_dynasties": "The Northern and Southern dynasties (南北朝) were an era of political division in China lasting from 420 to 589, during which rival dynasties ruled the north while a separate line of courts governed the south from Jiankang. The period began when Liu Yu founded the Liu Song dynasty in the south, and the north was long dominated by the Northern Wei and the successor states into which it fractured. Marked by frequent warfare between the rival courts, it was nonetheless a time of cultural flowering and the rapid spread of Buddhism, and it ended when the Sui dynasty reunified the country in 589.",
"Ten_Kingdoms": "The Ten Kingdoms (十國) were roughly ten regional states that governed mainly southern and western China during the tenth century, most of them clustered in the Yangtze valley and farther south. They emerged from the fragmentation that followed the fall of the Tang dynasty in 907, ruling their territories while a rapid succession of Five Dynasties held the north. Conventionally dated from 907 to 979, the period ended as the Song dynasty absorbed the southern states one by one and conquered the last holdout, the Northern Han, in 979.",
"Wu_Zhou": "The Wu Zhou (武周) was a short-lived Chinese imperial dynasty proclaimed in 690 by Wu Zetian, who deposed her own son and assumed the sovereign title of huangdi, naming her new state Zhou after the ancient royal house of that name. Reigning in her own right until 705, she was the only woman in the history of China to hold the office of emperor. In 705 the elderly Wu Zetian was compelled to abdicate, her dynasty came to an end, and the Tang dynasty it had interrupted was restored.",
"Liu_Song": "The Liu Song dynasty (劉宋) was a Chinese imperial dynasty that ruled southern China from 420 to 479, established when the general Liu Yu forced the abdication of the last Eastern Jin emperor and took the throne as Emperor Wu. Governing from the capital at Jiankang, it was the first and largest of the four Southern dynasties, holding the Yangtze River valley and the lands to its south. Its later reigns were consumed by court intrigue and dynastic bloodshed, and in 479 the general Xiao Daocheng seized power to found the Southern Qi, bringing the dynasty to an end.",
"Southern_Qi": "The Southern Qi dynasty (南齊) was the second of the four Southern dynasties, founded in 479 when Xiao Daocheng seized the throne from the Liu Song and ruled the Chinese south from its capital at Jiankang. Its founder took the throne as Emperor Gao, and the regime passed through seven emperors across only twenty-three years. In 502 the general Xiao Yan forced the abdication of the last Qi emperor and established the Liang dynasty, bringing Southern Qi to an end.",
"Liang_dynasty": "The Liang dynasty (梁) was the third of the four Southern dynasties, founded in 502 when the general Xiao Yan seized the throne and ruled as Emperor Wu of Liang from the capital at Jiankang. His reign of nearly half a century brought a flourishing of literature, calligraphy, and Buddhism, which he patronized fervently through temple-building, monastic donations, and personal devotion. The dynasty was ruined by the devastating Hou Jing rebellion that began in 548 and sacked Jiankang, and it collapsed in 557 when it was replaced by the Chen dynasty.",
"Chen_dynasty": "The Chen dynasty (陳) was the fourth and last of the four Southern dynasties, established in 557 by the general Chen Baxian and ruling southern China from its capital at Jiankang. The smallest of the Southern dynasties in territory and resources, it nonetheless worked to restore the economy and culture of the south after decades of warfare and rebellion. In 589 its capital fell to the armies of the Sui dynasty, ending the Chen and reunifying China under a single ruler for the first time in centuries.",
"Eastern_Wei": "The Eastern Wei (東魏) was a northern Chinese dynasty of 534 to 550 that arose from the division of the Northern Wei, ruling the eastern portion of northern China from its capital at Ye. It was a puppet regime dominated by the warlord Gao Huan, who installed the child Yuan Shanjian as Emperor Xiaojing while wielding actual power from his own base at Jinyang. In 550 Gao Huan's son Gao Yang forced Emperor Xiaojing to abdicate, ending the Eastern Wei and founding the Northern Qi.",
"Western_Wei": "The Western Wei 西魏 was a northern Chinese dynasty that ruled the western part of northern China from 535 to 557, emerging after the Northern Wei fractured into rival eastern and western regimes. Governed from the capital at Chang'an, it was nominally headed by emperors of the Yuan house beginning with Emperor Wen (Yuan Baoju), while real authority rested with the Xianbei general Yuwen Tai, who installed the throne's occupants as figureheads. In 557 Yuwen Tai's nephew Yuwen Hu deposed the last ruler, Emperor Gong, and enthroned Yuwen Tai's son to found the Northern Zhou, bringing the Western Wei to an end.",
"Northern_Qi": "The Northern Qi dynasty (北齊) was a dynasty of northern China that ruled from 550 to 577, founded by Gao Yang, who forced the last emperor of the Eastern Wei to cede the throne to him. Ruling the fertile eastern plain of the north from its capital at Ye, it succeeded the Eastern Wei, one of the two states into which the Northern Wei had earlier split. A line of Gao Yang's sons and kinsmen held the throne until the state was conquered by the Northern Zhou in 577.",
"Northern_Zhou": "The Northern Zhou (北周) was a dynasty that ruled northern China from 557 to 581, established by the Xianbei Yuwen clan after Yuwen Jue accepted the abdication of the Western Wei's final emperor. Real authority in its early years lay with the regent Yuwen Hu, and in 577 the dynasty conquered the Northern Qi to bring all of northern China under a single government. In 581 the regent Yang Jian compelled the young emperor to yield the throne, ending the Northern Zhou and inaugurating the Sui dynasty.",
"Emperor_Gaozu_of_Tang": "Emperor Gaozu of Tang (唐高祖), personal name Li Yuan, was the founder of the Tang dynasty, a Sui aristocrat and military governor who rose in rebellion amid the collapse of the Sui and proclaimed himself emperor in 618. He reigned from 618 to 626, consolidating Tang authority over a fragmented China while much of the campaigning fell to his sons. In 626 his son Li Shimin killed his brothers in the Xuanwu Gate Incident, after which Gaozu abdicated in favor of Li Shimin, who became Emperor Taizong.",
"Emperor_Zhongzong_of_Tang": "Emperor Zhongzong of Tang (唐中宗), personal name Li Xian, was a Tang emperor and a son of Emperor Gaozong and the empress Wu Zetian. He first took the throne in 684 but was deposed within weeks by his mother, who later founded her own Wu Zhou dynasty, and he was restored to the Tang throne after her fall in 705, reigning until 710. He is traditionally said to have been poisoned in 710 by his wife, Empress Wei, who together with their daughter Princess Anle sought to seize power at court.",
"Emperor_Ruizong_of_Tang": "Emperor Ruizong of Tang (唐睿宗), personal name Li Dan, was an emperor of the Tang dynasty and a son of Emperor Gaozong and the future Empress Wu Zetian. He held the throne twice, from 684 to 690 and again from 710 to 712, ruling on both occasions as a largely powerless figure while true authority rested with his mother during the first period and with his sister Princess Taiping and his son Li Longji during the second. In 712 he abdicated in favour of that capable son, who became Emperor Xuanzong, and lived on as a retired emperor until his death in 716.",
"Emperor_Suzong_of_Tang": "Emperor Suzong of Tang (唐肅宗), personal name Li Heng, was the third son of Emperor Xuanzong and reigned over the Tang dynasty from 756 to 762. He came to the throne at Lingwu in 756 after the An Lushan rebellion drove his father to flee toward Sichuan, whereupon the army there proclaimed him emperor. Aided by loyal generals such as Guo Ziyi and Li Guangbi and by allied Uyghur cavalry, he began the long campaign to recover the Tang capitals, retaking Chang'an and Luoyang in 757.",
"Emperor_Daizong_of_Tang": "Emperor Daizong of Tang (唐代宗), personal name Li Yu, reigned from 762 to 779 as the son and successor of Emperor Suzong. He came to the throne in the final years of the An Lushan rebellion, which was at last suppressed in 763 with the death of the rebel leader Shi Chaoyi. Peace was secured only by granting amnesty to the surrendered rebel commanders and appointing them as regional military governors, leaving powerful semi-autonomous warlords entrenched across the empire for the rest of the dynasty.",
"Emperor_Dezong_of_Tang": "Emperor Dezong of Tang (唐德宗), personal name Li Kuo, was the ninth emperor of the Tang dynasty, reigning from 779 to 805 as the son and successor of Emperor Daizong. Early in his reign he tried to curb the autonomous provincial military governors, but these efforts provoked a wave of revolts, including the Jingyuan Mutiny of 783, that briefly drove him from the capital Chang'an. After returning he abandoned confrontation with the warlords and relied increasingly on palace eunuchs, whom he placed in command of the imperial armies.",
"Emperor_Shunzong_of_Tang": "Emperor Shunzong of Tang (唐順宗), personal name Li Song, was an emperor of the Tang dynasty who succeeded his father Emperor Dezong and reigned for only about six months in 805. Having suffered a stroke that left him partially paralyzed and unable to speak, he backed the Yongzhen Reform, an effort led by officials such as Wang Shuwen and Wang Pi to curb the power of eunuchs and regional warlords. The reform collapsed within months, and eunuch-backed pressure forced him to abdicate in favor of his son Emperor Xianzong, after which he died the following year in 806.",
"Emperor_Xianzong_of_Tang": "Emperor Xianzong of Tang (唐憲宗), personal name Li Chun, reigned from 805 to 820 as the eldest son of Emperor Shunzong of the Tang dynasty. His reign, later celebrated as the Yuanhe Restoration, saw a vigorous revival of central authority, as he waged largely successful campaigns that brought several defiant provincial military governors back under imperial control by 817. He died suddenly in 820, reportedly murdered by the eunuch Chen Hongzhi.",
"Emperor_Muzong_of_Tang": "Emperor Muzong of Tang (唐穆宗), personal name Li Heng, was an emperor of the Tang dynasty who reigned from 820 to 824 after succeeding his father, Emperor Xianzong. He gave himself over to feasting, drinking, and pleasure while neglecting the business of government, and the authority his father had reasserted over the regional military governors rapidly slipped away. The three circuits north of the Yellow River that Xianzong had subdued reverted to de facto independence during his short reign, which is commonly regarded as the beginning of the Tang dynasty's long decline.",
"Emperor_Jingzong_of_Tang": "Emperor Jingzong of Tang (唐敬宗), personal name Li Zhan, was the eldest son of Emperor Muzong and ruled the Tang dynasty from 824 to 827, having ascended the throne while still a teenager. Devoted to polo, wrestling, feasting, and nocturnal revelry, he neglected the affairs of government and left real power in the hands of the court eunuchs who dominated the palace. After a reign of less than three years he was murdered by a group of eunuchs and palace guards, and the throne passed to his younger brother, who became Emperor Wenzong.",
"Emperor_Wenzong_of_Tang": "Emperor Wenzong of Tang (唐文宗), personal name Li Ang, was an emperor of the Tang dynasty who reigned from 827 to 840, having been raised to the throne by palace eunuchs after his elder brother Emperor Jingzong was assassinated. Resentful of eunuch domination of the court, he conspired with the officials Li Xun and Zheng Zhu to lure the leading eunuchs to their deaths, but the scheme collapsed in the Sweet Dew Incident of 835, when the eunuchs uncovered the plot and slaughtered the conspirators along with many court officials. For the remainder of his reign Wenzong was kept a virtual prisoner of the eunuchs, and he died in 840 with his authority effectively broken.",
"Emperor_Wuzong_of_Tang": "Emperor Wuzong of Tang (唐武宗), born Li Chan and later renamed Li Yan, was an emperor of the Tang dynasty who reigned from 840 to 846, taking the throne after his elder brother Emperor Wenzong died and court eunuchs installed him in place of the designated heir. A zealous patron of Daoism, he is remembered above all for the Huichang persecution, the great anti-Buddhist campaign that culminated in 845 with the destruction of thousands of monasteries and the forced return of some 260,000 monks and nuns to lay life. He died in 846, probably poisoned by the alchemical elixirs of immortality he had consumed in his pursuit of longevity.",
"Emperor_Xuanzong_II_of_Tang": "Emperor Xuanzong of Tang (唐宣宗), personal name Li Chen, was an emperor of the Tang dynasty who reigned from 846 to 859. A diligent and frugal ruler who modeled his governance on the earlier Emperor Taizong and the celebrated Zhenguan era, he presided over a modest revival of stable administration under the Dazhong era name and was later nicknamed Little Taizong (小太宗). During his reign the Tang recovered the Hexi Corridor from the Tibetan Empire after the general Zhang Yichao submitted to the dynasty in 851, though Xuanzong himself died in 859 from ingesting cinnabar-based elixirs meant to confer immortality.",
"Emperor_Yizong_of_Tang": "Emperor Yizong of Tang (唐懿宗), personal name Li Cui, was an emperor of the Tang dynasty who reigned from 859 to 873 as the son and successor of Emperor Xuanzong. A pleasure-loving ruler who neglected government in favor of lavish entertainment, he presided over deepening official corruption and heavy spending that provoked widespread unrest across the empire. The most serious of these disturbances was the mutiny led by Pang Xun from 868 to 869, which devastated the Huai River region and hastened the decline of the Tang dynasty.",
"Emperor_Xizong_of_Tang": "Emperor Xizong of Tang (唐僖宗), personal name Li Xuan, was a son of Emperor Yizong who ruled the Tang dynasty from 873 to 888 after ascending the throne as a young boy under the domination of powerful court eunuchs such as Tian Lingzi. During his reign the massive Huang Chao rebellion swept across the empire and captured the capital Chang'an, forcing him to flee to Chengdu in Sichuan in 881. Although the rebellion was finally crushed in 884, it shattered what remained of central Tang authority, leaving the dynasty carved up among regional warlords for its last decades until its collapse in 907.",
"Emperor_Zhaozong_of_Tang": "Emperor Zhaozong of Tang (唐昭宗), personal name Li Ye, was the penultimate emperor of the Tang dynasty, reigning from 888 to 904. Intelligent and reform-minded but left with almost no real authority, he struggled as a nearly powerless figure among contending warlords who had reduced the imperial court to a prize to be fought over. In 904 he was seized and murdered on the orders of the warlord Zhu Wen, who three years later formally ended the Tang dynasty by founding the Later Liang.",
"Emperor_Ai_of_Tang": "Emperor Ai of Tang (唐哀帝), personal name Li Zhu, was the last emperor of the Tang dynasty, reigning from 904 to 907. He was enthroned as a child of about eleven after the warlord Zhu Wen had his father, Emperor Zhaozong, assassinated, and he ruled only as a powerless puppet under Zhu Wen's control. In 907 Zhu Wen forced him to abdicate and founded the Later Liang dynasty, bringing the roughly three-century Tang to an end.",
"Emperor_Taizong_of_Song": "Emperor Taizong of Song (宋太宗), personal name Zhao Kuangyi, was the second emperor of the Northern Song dynasty, reigning from 976 to 997 as the younger brother and successor of the founding emperor Zhao Kuangyin. He completed the reunification of China proper by pressuring the last southern holdouts of Wuyue and Qingyuan into submission in 978 and conquering the Northern Han in 979. His two campaigns to recover the Sixteen Prefectures from the Khitan Liao dynasty both failed, ending in defeat at the Battle of Gaoliang River in 979 and in the Yongxi Northern Expedition of 986.",
"Emperor_Zhenzong_of_Song": "Emperor Zhenzong of Song (宋真宗) was the third emperor of the Song dynasty, reigning from 997 to 1022 as the son and successor of Emperor Taizong. After the Khitan Liao invaded Song territory in 1004, he concluded the Chanyuan Treaty in early 1005, ending the war and securing a lasting peace in exchange for an annual Song payment of 100,000 taels of silver and 200,000 bolts of silk. In his later years he presided over an elaborate cult of Heavenly Texts and performed the grand Feng and Shan sacrifices at Mount Tai in 1008 to bolster the legitimacy of his rule.",
"Emperor_Renzong_of_Song": "Emperor Renzong of Song (宋仁宗), personal name Zhao Zhen, was the fourth emperor of the Northern Song dynasty and reigned from 1022 to 1063, the longest tenure of any Song ruler. His decades on the throne, governed from the capital at Kaifeng, are remembered as a cultural and economic high point that produced celebrated statesmen and men of letters such as Fan Zhongyan and Ouyang Xiu. In 1043 he sanctioned the Qingli reforms, a program of administrative, fiscal, and military changes led by Fan Zhongyan that was abandoned within about two years amid entrenched opposition at court.",
"Emperor_Yingzong_of_Song": "Emperor Yingzong of Song (宋英宗), personal name Zhao Shu, was the fifth emperor of the Northern Song dynasty and reigned from 1063 to 1067 after the childless Emperor Renzong adopted him as heir. Frequently incapacitated by illness that left Empress Dowager Cao acting as regent early in his reign, his short rule was dominated by the Puyi Dispute, a protracted court controversy over the ceremonial honours owed to his biological father, Zhao Yunrang, the Prince of Pu. He died in January 1067 after fewer than four years on the throne and was succeeded by his son, Emperor Shenzong.",
"Emperor_Zhezong_of_Song": "Emperor Zhezong of Song (宋哲宗), personal name Zhao Xu, was the seventh ruler of the Song dynasty, reigning from 1085 to 1100 after succeeding his father Emperor Shenzong at the age of nine. During his minority his grandmother, Empress Dowager Gao, governed as regent and installed conservative ministers such as Sima Guang, who reversed the New Policies reforms of Wang Anshi. After Empress Dowager Gao died in 1093 Zhezong assumed personal rule, reinstated the reforms under the chancellor Zhang Dun, and revived a bitter factional struggle between the reformist and conservative parties that lasted until his death in 1100.",
"Emperor_Qinzong_of_Song": "Emperor Qinzong of Song (宋欽宗), personal name Zhao Huan, was the ninth emperor of the Song dynasty and the last ruler of the Northern Song, taking the throne in early 1126 after his father Emperor Huizong abdicated as Jurchen Jin armies advanced on the capital Kaifeng. During his brief reign he tried to buy off the invaders with tribute and territorial concessions, but the Jin renewed their siege and sacked Kaifeng in the Jingkang Incident of 1127. He and Huizong were carried off into captivity in the Jin heartland, where Qinzong was stripped of his imperial rank and died in 1156.",
"Emperor_Xiaozong_of_Song": "Emperor Xiaozong of Song (宋孝宗) was the second emperor of the Southern Song dynasty, reigning from 1162 to 1189 after Emperor Gaozong abdicated the throne in his favour. He is generally regarded as a capable and diligent ruler who presided over a period of stable government and relative prosperity, posthumously rehabilitating the general Yue Fei and purging the remnants of Qin Hui's faction from the court. In 1189 he abdicated in favour of his son, who reigned as Emperor Guangzong, and he died in 1194.",
"Emperor_Guangzong_of_Song": "Emperor Guangzong of Song (宋光宗), personal name Zhao Dun, was the twelfth emperor of the Song dynasty and the third of the Southern Song, reigning from 1189 to 1194 after his father Emperor Xiaozong abdicated the throne to him. Mentally unstable and increasingly withdrawn, he was dominated by his forceful wife Empress Li Fengniang, who wielded much of the real power at court and worked to keep him estranged from his father. When Xiaozong died in 1194 and Guangzong refused to perform the mourning rites, court officials and the Grand Empress Dowager Wu forced him to abdicate in favor of his son, who became Emperor Ningzong.",
"Emperor_Ningzong_of_Song": "Emperor Ningzong of Song (宋寧宗), personal name Zhao Kuo, was the thirteenth emperor of the Song dynasty and ruled the Southern Song from 1194 to 1224 after succeeding his father Emperor Guangzong. Throughout his reign actual authority rested with his chief councillors, first Han Tuozhou and later Shi Miyuan, rather than with the emperor himself. Under Han Tuozhou the court launched the Kaixi expedition against the Jurchen Jin in 1206, a campaign that failed badly and led to Han's killing in 1207 and a humiliating peace in 1208 that raised the Song's annual tribute payments to the Jin.",
"Emperor_Lizong_of_Song": "Emperor Lizong of Song (宋理宗) was the fifth emperor of the Southern Song dynasty, reigning from 1224 to 1264 after the chancellor Shi Miyuan placed him on the throne in place of the previously designated heir. During his long reign the Song allied with the rising Mongol Empire, and their combined forces destroyed the Jurchen-led Jin dynasty in 1234, but the subsequent Song campaign to reoccupy the former northern capitals provoked the Mongols into a protracted invasion of the south. Inclined toward personal pleasure and neo-Confucian study rather than active governance, he left much of the administration to his chancellors, and upon his death in 1264 he was succeeded by his nephew Emperor Duzong.",
"Emperor_Duzong_of_Song": "Emperor Duzong of Song (宋度宗), personal name Zhao Qi, was the fifteenth Song emperor and the sixth ruler of the Southern Song, reigning from 1264 to 1274 with his capital at Hangzhou. A dissolute ruler given to drink and pleasure, he left the conduct of government to his chief councillor Jia Sidao, who dominated the court and hid the mounting military disasters from the throne. During his reign the Mongol Yuan pressed a long siege of the strategic fortress city of Xiangyang, which fell in 1273 and opened the Yangtze heartland to conquest, leaving the dynasty near collapse when he died in 1274.",
"Emperor_Gong_of_Song": "Emperor Gong of Song (宋恭帝), personal name Zhao Xian, was a Southern Song emperor who came to the throne in 1274 as a small child following the death of his father Emperor Duzong. With his grandmother, Grand Empress Dowager Xie, acting as regent, his brief reign coincided with the final Mongol advance, and in 1276 the Song court surrendered the capital Hangzhou to the Yuan general Bayan. He was taken north and granted a noble title by Kublai Khan, while loyalists fled south to enthrone his elder brother as Emperor Duanzong and prolong resistance until the dynasty fell in 1279.",
"Emperor_Duanzong_of_Song": "Emperor Duanzong of Song (宋端宗), personal name Zhao Shi, was a boy emperor of the Southern Song dynasty who was enthroned at Fuzhou in 1276 by loyalist ministers after the Yuan Mongols captured the capital Lin'an and his younger brother Emperor Gong surrendered. His court operated as a government-in-exile that fled ever southward along the coasts of Fujian and Guangdong, its affairs directed by ministers such as Zhang Shijie and Lu Xiufu as Mongol forces pursued them. While fleeing by sea he nearly drowned after falling from his boat during a storm, and he died of illness in 1278 at the age of seven, leaving the throne to his younger brother Zhao Bing, under whom the dynasty fell to the Mongols the following year.",
"Emperor_Bing_of_Song": "Emperor Bing of Song (宋帝昺), personal name Zhao Bing, was the last emperor of the Song dynasty, a young child placed on the throne in 1278 as the court fled the advancing Mongol armies of the Yuan dynasty. After the Song fleet was annihilated at the naval Battle of Yamen in 1279, the chancellor Lu Xiufu, seeing no hope of escape, took the boy emperor in his arms and leapt into the sea, drowning them both. His death brought the three-century Song dynasty to a close and left all of China under Mongol rule.",
"Emperor_Wen_of_Sui": "Emperor Wen of Sui (隋文帝), personal name Yang Jian, founded the Sui dynasty in 581 after seizing the throne from the Northern Zhou, whose court he had come to dominate as regent. In 589 his armies conquered the southern Chen dynasty, reunifying China after centuries of political division. During his reign, which ended with his death in 604, he reorganized the central bureaucracy, promulgated a new legal code, and restored strong centralized rule before being succeeded by his son Yang Guang.",
"Emperor_Yang_of_Sui": "Emperor Yang of Sui (隋煬帝), personal name Yang Guang, was the second emperor of the Sui dynasty, reigning from 604 to 618 after succeeding his father Emperor Wen. His reign completed the Grand Canal linking the Yellow and Yangtze river systems and undertook other vast projects such as rebuilding the eastern capital at Luoyang and repairing the Great Wall, all achieved through the exhausting conscription of millions of labourers. His three costly and unsuccessful invasions of Goguryeo between 612 and 614, along with the strain of these works, provoked widespread rebellions that culminated in his assassination at Jiangdu in 618 and the collapse of the dynasty.",
"Emperor_Gong_of_Sui": "Emperor Gong of Sui (隋恭帝), personal name Yang You (楊侑), was a grandson of Emperor Yang of Sui who was placed on the throne in 617 as a puppet ruler of the collapsing Sui dynasty. After the rebel general Li Yuan seized the Sui capital of Chang'an late in 617, he installed the young Yang You as emperor while keeping real authority for himself. In the summer of 618 Li Yuan compelled Yang You to abdicate in his favour, whereupon Li founded the Tang dynasty as its Emperor Gaozu, effectively ending the Sui.",
"Emperor_Chengzong_of_Yuan": "Emperor Chengzong of Yuan (元成宗), whose Mongol name was Temür, reigned from 1294 to 1307 as the second emperor of the Mongol-led Yuan dynasty and the grandson and successor of its founder Kublai Khan. Largely maintaining his grandfather's policies, he presided over a period of relative internal stability and showed respect for Confucianism while abandoning further costly invasions of Japan and Đại Việt. Around 1304 he brokered a peace with the western Mongol khanates that acknowledged him as their nominal suzerain, helping to end the decades-long Kaidu war, though he died in 1307 without a surviving heir.",
"Emperor_Wuzong_of_Yuan": "Emperor Wuzong of Yuan (元武宗), whose Mongol name was Khayishan and who bore the title Külüg Khan, was an emperor of the Mongol Yuan dynasty who reigned from 1307 to 1311. Having gained the throne on the death of his uncle Temür Khan with the backing of the army, he rewarded the imperial princes and aristocrats who had supported him with lavish gifts and a flood of noble and official titles that drained the treasury. His heavy spending and the over-issue of a new paper currency, the zhida notes, drove severe inflation, and after a reign of less than four years he died in early 1311 and was succeeded by his younger brother Ayurbarwada.",
"Emperor_Renzong_of_Yuan": "Emperor Renzong of Yuan (元仁宗), whose given name was Ayurbarwada, was the fourth emperor of the Mongol-led Yuan dynasty, reigning from 1311 to 1320 after peacefully succeeding his elder brother Khayishan. A Confucian-educated ruler tutored by the scholar Li Meng, he actively patronized Han Chinese learning and had Chinese classics translated for the Mongol court. He reinstated the imperial civil service examinations, dormant since the Mongol conquest, with the first sitting held in 1315 and based on Neo-Confucian texts while reserving a quota of degrees for Mongols and other non-Han candidates.",
"Emperor_Yingzong_of_Yuan": "Emperor Yingzong of Yuan (元英宗), personal name Shidibala and known in Mongolian as Gegeen Khan, succeeded his father Emperor Renzong in 1320 and ruled the Mongol-led Yuan dynasty as a young man of about eighteen. Advised by his Confucian-educated grand councillor Baiju, he pursued reform along Confucian principles, recruiting Chinese scholar-officials and issuing the comprehensive legal code known as the Da Yuan Tong Zhi. In 1323 he and Baiju were assassinated while traveling from the summer capital Shangdu toward the capital Dadu, in a coup led by the official Tegshi that is remembered as the Nanpo Incident, after which Yesün Temür took the throne.",
"Emperor_Taiding_of_Yuan": "Emperor Taiding of Yuan (泰定帝), whose Mongol name was Yesün Temür, was an emperor of the Mongol-led Yuan dynasty and a great-grandson of Kublai Khan who reigned from 1323 to 1328. He was enthroned in 1323 near the Kherlen River after the Nanpo Incident, a coup in which his predecessor Emperor Yingzong was assassinated and the conspirators offered Yesün Temür the imperial seal. After he died at Shangdu in 1328, his son Ragibagh was installed there while a rival faction proclaimed Tugh Temür at Khanbaliq, igniting the War of the Two Capitals.",
"Emperor_Wenzong_of_Yuan": "Emperor Wenzong of Yuan (元文宗), Mongol name Tugh Temür, was an emperor of the Mongol Yuan dynasty who reigned from 1328 to 1329 and again from 1329 to 1332. He first won the throne by prevailing in the War of the Two Capitals, a succession conflict that erupted after the death of Yesün Temür, then ceded power to his elder brother Kusala, Emperor Mingzong, before resuming the throne when Kusala died within months of his accession. A cultivated ruler who was himself a poet, painter, and calligrapher, he founded the Academy of the Pavilion of the Star of Literature in 1329 to promote Confucian scholarship and Chinese arts and sponsored the compilation of the encyclopedic Jingshi Dadian.",
"Emperor_Mingzong_of_Yuan": "Emperor Mingzong of Yuan (元明宗), whose Mongol name was Khutughtu Khan Kusala, was a son of Emperor Wuzong who was enthroned north of Karakorum on 27 February 1329 as ruler of the Mongol-led Yuan dynasty of China. His younger brother Tugh Temür, who had briefly held the throne, abdicated in his favor and was named heir apparent, but Kusala died suddenly on 30 August 1329, only four days after a banquet with him. His death after a reign of roughly six months was widely believed to have been a poisoning arranged by the powerful minister El Temür, who then restored Tugh Temür as Emperor Wenzong.",
"Emperor_Ningzong_of_Yuan": "Emperor Ningzong of Yuan (元寧宗), whose Mongol name was Rinchinbal, was a son of Emperor Mingzong who was placed on the Yuan throne in 1332 at the age of six. He was enthroned on 23 October 1332 through the backing of the empress dowager Budashiri and the councilor El Temür following the death of Emperor Wenzong, but he died less than two months later on 14 December of that year. His reign of roughly fifty-two days made him one of the shortest-reigning monarchs in Chinese and Mongol history, and he was eventually succeeded by his elder brother Toghon Temür, the final emperor of the Yuan dynasty.",
"Toghon_Temür": "Toghon Temür (元順帝) was the last emperor of the Yuan dynasty of China, reigning from 1333 to 1368 and known by the Chinese temple name Huizong and by the posthumous title Shundi that the founding Ming emperor conferred. During his long reign, misgovernment, court factionalism, ruinous floods and famines along the Yellow River, and mounting fiscal crisis eroded Mongol authority, culminating in the Red Turban Rebellion that erupted in 1351. When the armies of the newly founded Ming dynasty captured the capital Dadu, present-day Beijing, in 1368, Toghon Temür fled north onto the Mongolian steppe, ending Yuan rule over China and beginning the rump Northern Yuan regime.",
"Emperor_Taizu_of_Liao": "Emperor Taizu of Liao (遼太祖), personal name Yelü Abaoji, was the Khitan chieftain who became supreme khagan of the Khitan tribes in 907 and the founding emperor of the Liao dynasty. He united the Khitan tribes under his sole rule, proclaimed himself emperor in 916 with a Chinese-style era name, and built a steppe empire spanning Manchuria and Mongolia. In 926 he conquered the neighbouring kingdom of Balhae to the east, but died later that year, leaving behind a dynasty that would endure until 1125.",
"Emperor_Taizong_of_Liao": "Emperor Taizong of Liao (遼太宗), personal name Yelü Deguang (耶律德光), was the second ruler of the Khitan-led Liao dynasty, reigning from 927 to 947. In 938 he took possession of the strategically vital Sixteen Prefectures of Yan and Yun, a band of northern border territory that Shi Jingtang had agreed to cede to the Khitans in exchange for the military aid that helped him found the Later Jin dynasty. He destroyed the Later Jin in 947, entering its capital at Kaifeng and briefly occupying the Central Plains, but mounting Chinese resistance soon forced a withdrawal during which he fell ill and died.",
"Emperor_Shizong_of_Liao": "Emperor Shizong of Liao (遼世宗), personal name Yelü Ruan, was the third ruler of the Khitan-led Liao dynasty of northern China. He was proclaimed emperor in 947 by the army after the sudden death of his uncle Emperor Taizong, overcoming a rival bid by the empress dowager to enthrone her son Yelü Lihu, though his short reign was troubled by persistent instability among the Khitan nobility. In 951 he was assassinated by the noble Yelü Chage during a coup amid the succession struggles of the imperial clan, ending his rule after only four years.",
"Emperor_Muzong_of_Liao": "Emperor Muzong of Liao (遼穆宗), personal name Yelü Jing, was the fourth emperor of the Khitan-led Liao dynasty, taking the throne in 951 after his cousin Emperor Shizong was assassinated. He is remembered as a dissolute and negligent ruler who drank heavily, slept through much of the day, and left the affairs of government largely unattended, while dealing savagely with the plots that troubled his reign and inflicting notorious cruelties on his personal attendants. In 969 he was murdered by six of his own attendants, among them his cook, ending an eighteen-year reign.",
"Emperor_Jingzong_of_Liao": "Emperor Jingzong of Liao (遼景宗), personal name Yelü Xian, was the fifth ruler of the Khitan-led Liao dynasty, reigning from 969 to 982 after taking the throne when his predecessor Emperor Muzong was murdered by his own servants during a hunting trip. He restored order following years of misrule by appointing capable officials of both Khitan and Han background, curbing corruption, and improving the efficiency of government, while also waging war against the Northern Song dynasty. Frequently ill, he relied heavily on his able empress Xiao Yanyan, who took an active part in state and military affairs and, after his death in 982, served as regent for their young son Emperor Shengzong.",
"Emperor_Shengzong_of_Liao": "Emperor Shengzong of Liao (遼聖宗), personal name Yelü Longxu, was the sixth ruler of the Khitan Liao dynasty, whose reign from 982 to 1031 was the longest in the dynasty's history and coincided with the height of Liao power. He acceded to the throne as a boy of about twelve under the regency of his mother, Empress Dowager Xiao Yanyan, whose forceful military and administrative leadership guided the empire until her death in 1009. In 1005 his forces concluded the Chanyuan Treaty with the Northern Song, which fixed annual payments of silver and silk to the Liao and inaugurated a long era of peace between the two states.",
"Emperor_Xingzong_of_Liao": "Emperor Xingzong of Liao (遼興宗), personal name Yelü Zongzhen, was the seventh ruler of the Khitan-led Liao dynasty, reigning from 1031 to 1055 after succeeding his father Emperor Shengzong. In 1042 he exploited the war between the Northern Song and the Western Xia to pressure the Song court into raising its annual payments to 200,000 taels of silver and 300,000 bolts of silk. He launched a major invasion of the Western Xia in 1044 that won early success but ended in a costly defeat, and on his death he was succeeded by his son Emperor Daozong.",
"Emperor_Daozong_of_Liao": "Emperor Daozong of Liao (遼道宗), personal name Yelü Hongji, was the eighth ruler of the Khitan-led Liao dynasty, reigning from 1055 to 1101. A devout Buddhist who sponsored the completion of a Liao edition of the Buddhist canon and lavish temple construction, he presided over a court riven by corruption and factional intrigue centred on the chancellor Yelü Yixin, who in 1075 fabricated charges of adultery that drove Empress Xiao Guanyin to suicide. Yixin then implicated the crown prince Yelü Jun in a false coup plot, leading Daozong to demote and imprison his own heir, who died in 1077, and the emperor was ultimately succeeded by Jun's son, Emperor Tianzuo.",
"Emperor_Tianzuo_of_Liao": "Emperor Tianzuo of Liao (遼天祚帝), personal name Yelü Yanxi, was the ninth and last emperor of the Khitan-led Liao dynasty, succeeding his grandfather Emperor Daozong in 1101. During his reign the Jurchen leader Wanyan Aguda founded the Jin dynasty in 1115 and, allied with the Northern Song, seized the Liao capitals one after another and drove Tianzuo into flight across the northern frontier. He was captured by the Jin in 1125, bringing the Liao dynasty to an end, though his kinsman Yelü Dashi led a remnant westward into Central Asia to found the Western Liao.",
"Emperor_Taizu_of_Jin": "Emperor Taizu of Jin (金太祖), personal name Wanyan Aguda (完顏阿骨打), was the founder and first emperor of the Jurchen-led Jin dynasty, reigning from 1115 to 1123. Originally chieftain of the Wanyan tribe, whose Jurchen people were subjects of the Khitan Liao dynasty, he united the Jurchen tribes and rose in revolt against the Liao in 1114, proclaiming the Jin dynasty and declaring himself emperor the following year. He formed the Alliance Conducted at Sea with the Northern Song against the Liao and, by the time of his death in 1123, had conquered most of the Liao empire's territory and made the Jin a major power in northern China.",
"Emperor_Taizong_of_Jin": "Emperor Taizong of Jin (金太宗), personal name Wanyan Sheng, was the second emperor of the Jurchen-led Jin dynasty, reigning from 1123 to 1135 after succeeding his elder brother, the dynasty's founder Emperor Taizu. During his reign the Jin completed the destruction of the Khitan-led Liao dynasty in 1125 with the capture of its last ruler, the Tianzuo Emperor, and then launched full-scale war against the Northern Song. In the Jingkang Incident of 1127 his armies besieged and sacked the Song capital of Bianjing and carried off the retired Emperor Huizong and the reigning Emperor Qinzong, ending the Northern Song and extending Jin rule over most of northern China.",
"Emperor_Xizong_of_Jin": "Emperor Xizong of Jin (金熙宗), personal name Wanyan Dan, was the third ruler of the Jurchen-led Jin dynasty, reigning from 1135 to 1150. A keen admirer of Han Chinese culture, he reorganized the Jin government along Chinese lines, establishing a Three Departments administrative system in 1136 and drawing talented Han officials into his court. His later years were marred by heavy drinking and increasingly violent conduct, and in 1150 he was assassinated in a coup led by his cousin Digunai, who seized the throne as Wanyan Liang.",
"Wanyan_Liang": "Wanyan Liang (海陵王), remembered by the demoted princely title Prince of Hailing, was the fourth ruler of the Jurchen-led Jin dynasty, who seized the throne in 1150 by assassinating his cousin Emperor Xizong in a palace coup. He pursued an aggressive program of sinicization and centralization, most famously relocating the Jin capital from Shangjing in the far northeast to Yanjing, the site of modern Beijing. In 1161 he launched a massive invasion of the Southern Song aimed at unifying China under Jin rule, but after his fleet was destroyed at the Battle of Caishi his own officers mutinied and killed him, and the new emperor posthumously stripped him of imperial rank and reduced him to the title by which he is known.",
"Emperor_Shizong_of_Jin": "Emperor Shizong of Jin (金世宗), personal name Wanyan Yong, was the fifth ruler of the Jurchen-led Jin dynasty, reigning from 1161 to 1189. He came to the throne amid the upheaval of Wanyan Liang's disastrous invasion of the Southern Song, being proclaimed emperor as that campaign collapsed and its author was killed by his own officers, after which Shizong secured a lasting peace with the Song and consolidated Jin rule over northern China. His long reign, marked by frugality, careful government, land redistribution to Jurchen settlers, and a revival of Jurchen language and learning, was remembered as a golden age of the dynasty and earned him the epithet the Little Yao and Shun, after the legendary sage-kings.",
"Emperor_Zhangzong_of_Jin": "Emperor Zhangzong of Jin (金章宗), sinicized name Wanyan Jing, was the sixth emperor of the Jurchen-led Jin dynasty and reigned from 1189 to 1208. A cultivated ruler and devoted patron of arts, literature, and Confucian learning, he presided over the cultural high point of the dynasty, founding Confucian temples across the north and ordering the construction of the artificial Taiye Lake in his capital at Zhongdu. His later years were burdened by fiscal strain, a war with the Southern Song that the Song had initiated but were compelled to end with the unfavorable peace settlement of 1208, and the rise of a unified Mongol power to the north under Genghis Khan that would soon threaten the dynasty's survival.",
"Wanyan_Yongji": "Wanyan Yongji (衛紹王) was the seventh emperor of the Jurchen-led Jin dynasty of China, reigning from 1208 until 1213 after succeeding Emperor Zhangzong, who had died without a male heir. In 1211 Genghis Khan launched a full-scale Mongol invasion of the Jin, and the Jin armies suffered heavy defeats that exposed northern China to Mongol devastation. In 1213 the general Heshilie Zhizhong, also known as Hushahu, rebelled and had him assassinated, and he was subsequently stripped of imperial honours and remembered instead by the demoted princely title Prince Shao of Wei.",
"Emperor_Xuanzong_of_Jin": "Emperor Xuanzong of Jin (金宣宗), personal name Wanyan Xun, was the eighth ruler of the Jurchen-led Jin dynasty, placed on the throne in 1213 by the general Heshilie Zhizhong after the murder of his predecessor Wanyan Yongji. Under relentless pressure from Genghis Khan's Mongols, he abandoned the northern capital of Zhongdu and moved the court south to Bianjing, modern Kaifeng, in 1214, and Zhongdu fell to the Mongols the following year. He also opened a ruinous war against the Southern Song dynasty, leaving the Jin fighting on several fronts at once, and on his death in 1224 he was succeeded by his son Emperor Aizong.",
"Emperor_Aizong_of_Jin": "Emperor Aizong of Jin (金哀宗), personal name Wanyan Shouxu, was the penultimate emperor of the Jurchen-led Jin dynasty, reigning from 1224 after succeeding his father Emperor Xuanzong. He ended the draining wars against the Southern Song to concentrate the Jin's dwindling resources on resisting the Mongol invasion, but after the Mongols besieged the capital Bianjing in 1232 he fled across the Yellow River and eventually took refuge in the walled town of Caizhou. When allied Mongol and Southern Song armies stormed Caizhou in 1234, he abdicated in favour of the general Wanyan Chenglin and then hanged himself as the city fell, ending the Jin dynasty.",
"Emperor_Mo_of_Jin": "Emperor Mo of Jin (金末帝), personal name Wanyan Chenglin (完顏承麟), was the last emperor of the Jurchen-led Jin dynasty, a general whom the besieged Emperor Aizong enthroned on 9 February 1234 because Aizong, too heavy to ride into battle, hoped the fit young Chenglin might escape and carry on the imperial line. He reigned for only a few hours, the shortest reign recorded in Chinese history, as the city of Caizhou fell that same day to the allied armies of the Mongol Empire and the Southern Song. When the walls were breached Aizong hanged himself while Chenglin rallied his soldiers into the street fighting, where he was killed, bringing the Jin dynasty to an end.",
"King_Qi_of_Xia": "King Qi of Xia (啟) was, in traditional Chinese historiography, the son of the dynasty's founder Yu the Great and the second ruler of the Xia. He is remembered chiefly for coming to the throne by heredity rather than the earlier practice of merit-based abdication, a transition that later historians treated as the origin of dynastic hereditary succession in China. Traditional accounts preserve little detail of the substance of his reign beyond this event, and he was succeeded by his son Tai Kang.",
"King_Tai_Kang_of_Xia": "King Tai Kang of Xia (太康) was, by tradition, the third ruler of the semi-legendary Xia dynasty and the son of King Qi, grandson of the dynasty's founder Yu the Great. According to later accounts such as the Records of the Grand Historian and the Bamboo Annals, he was a pleasure-loving king who neglected government for hunting, and while he was away beyond the Luo River the archer-lord Hou Yi of the Youqiong seized his capital, an episode remembered as Tai Kang losing the state. He never regained power and was succeeded by his younger brother Zhong Kang, though the traditional length of his reign is reported inconsistently in the sources.",
"King_Zhong_Kang_of_Xia": "King Zhong Kang of Xia (仲康) is traditionally listed as the fourth king of the semi-legendary Xia dynasty, a son of Qi and the younger brother of his predecessor Tai Kang. According to later accounts he came to the throne after his brother had lost effective control of the Xia realm to the archer-lord Hou Yi, who had seized the capital while Tai Kang was away hunting. Little is reliably recorded of Zhong Kang's own reign, and he was succeeded by his son Xiang.",
"King_Xiang_of_Xia": "King Xiang of Xia (相) was a ruler of the semi-legendary Xia dynasty, traditionally counted as its fifth king and named as the son of his predecessor Zhong Kang. According to later sources such as the Records of the Grand Historian and the Bamboo Annals, his reign fell during a period of turmoil in which he was driven from power and eventually killed by the usurper Han Zhuo. His death interrupted the Xia royal line, which was later restored by his posthumous son Shao Kang.",
"King_Zhu_of_Xia": "King Zhu of Xia (杼) was traditionally the seventh king of the semi-legendary Xia dynasty and the son of King Shao Kang, whose restoration of Xia rule he is said to have consolidated. Later sources such as the Bamboo Annals credit him with extending Xia power eastward toward the sea and set his reign within a prosperous period of the dynasty, though these notices are brief and their historicity is uncertain. He was succeeded by his son Huai, and beyond such traditional accounts little detail of his reign is preserved.",
"King_Huai_of_Xia": "King Huai of Xia (槐) is traditionally listed as the eighth ruler of the semi-legendary Xia dynasty, the first dynasty in traditional Chinese historiography. He is recorded as the son of the preceding king Zhu and as the father of his successor Mang, placing him within the royal genealogy preserved in later sources such as the Records of the Grand Historian and the Bamboo Annals. Little is reliably recorded of his reign beyond this position in the king list, and even its length is uncertain, so like most Xia kings he survives essentially as a name in the traditional sequence.",
"King_Mang_of_Xia": "King Mang of Xia (芒) was, according to the traditional king list preserved in later works such as the Records of the Grand Historian and the Bamboo Annals, the ninth ruler of the semi-legendary Xia dynasty of ancient China. He is recorded as the son of his predecessor King Huai and the father of his successor King Xie, placing him in the middle of the traditional Xia royal line. Almost nothing is reliably known of his reign, though the Bamboo Annals record that on his accession he presented a dark jade tablet to the Yellow River.",
"King_Xie_of_Xia": "King Xie of Xia (泄) was, according to the traditional king list preserved in later sources, the tenth ruler of the semi-legendary Xia dynasty and the son and successor of King Mang. Little is recorded of his reign, and he is remembered chiefly as a name in the dynastic sequence, being followed on the throne by his son Bu Jiang. The Bamboo Annals add only sparse annalistic notes, such as eastern Yi peoples being granted titles at his court, and no securely dated reign survives for him.",
"King_Bu_Jiang_of_Xia": "King Bu Jiang of Xia (不降) was, by traditional reckoning, the eleventh ruler of the semi-legendary Xia dynasty and a son of his predecessor, King Xie. He is known chiefly from later sources such as the Records of the Grand Historian and the Bamboo Annals, the latter assigning him a long reign of fifty-nine years before the throne passed to his younger brother Jiong, while his own son Kong Jia came to rule only later. Beyond his place in this succession, little else is reliably recorded of his reign.",
"King_Jiong_of_Xia": "King Jiong of Xia (扃) was, by traditional reckoning, the twelfth ruler of the semi-legendary Xia dynasty, the first dynasty in later Chinese historiography. According to later king lists such as those in the Records of the Grand Historian and the Bamboo Annals, he was a son of King Xie and came to the throne after his elder brother Bu Jiang, and was in turn succeeded by his own son Jin. Like most Xia kings he survives as little more than a name in these sequences, and virtually nothing is recorded of the events of his reign.",
"King_Jin_of_Xia": "King Jin of Xia (廑), also known as Yinjia (胤甲), appears in the traditional king lists as the thirteenth ruler of the semi-legendary Xia dynasty. He is recorded as the son and successor of King Jiong of Xia and was in turn followed by Kong Jia. Little of substance is preserved about his own reign, and he survives chiefly as a name in later sources such as the Records of the Grand Historian and the Bamboo Annals.",
"King_Kong_Jia_of_Xia": "King Kong Jia of Xia (孔甲) is traditionally listed as the fourteenth ruler of the Xia dynasty, a son of the earlier king Bu Jiang who came to the throne only after the intervening reigns of his uncle Jiong and his cousin Jin. Later sources such as the Records of the Grand Historian remember him as a superstitious and dissolute ruler under whom the authority of the Xia is said to have begun to weaken as its vassals grew stronger. Beyond such traditional characterizations little of substance is recorded of his reign, and he was succeeded by his son Gao.",
"King_Gao_of_Xia": "King Gao of Xia (皋) was, according to the traditional king list preserved in later sources such as the Records of the Grand Historian and the Bamboo Annals, the fifteenth ruler of the semi-legendary Xia dynasty. He is recorded as the son of the preceding king Kong Jia (孔甲) and as the father of his successor Fa (发). Like most Xia monarchs he survives essentially as a name in these later king lists, and almost nothing is reliably recorded of his reign.",
"King_Fa_of_Xia": "King Fa of Xia (發), also recorded under the given name Houjing (后敬), was traditionally the sixteenth ruler of the semi-legendary Xia dynasty and the son of the preceding king, Gao. He was the father of Jie, who succeeded him as the seventeenth and final ruler of the dynasty. Fa survives in the later king lists such as the Records of the Grand Historian and the Bamboo Annals as little more than a name, and almost nothing is reliably recorded of the events of his reign.",
"King_Wai_Bing_of_Shang": "King Wai Bing of Shang (外丙) is traditionally listed as the second king of the Shang dynasty, a son of its founder Tang who came to the throne after the early death of his elder brother, the crown prince Tai Ding. Very little is recorded of his reign, which traditional texts describe as brief, and he was succeeded by his younger brother Zhong Ren. Oracle-bone inscriptions unearthed at Yinxu record him under the name Bu Bing (卜丙) and place him differently within the royal genealogy, so his exact position in the succession remains uncertain.",
"King_Zhong_Ren_of_Shang": "King Zhong Ren of Shang (中壬) was, according to the traditional king list recorded in Sima Qian's Records of the Grand Historian, an early ruler of the Shang dynasty and a son of its founder, Tang. He is said to have come to the throne after his elder brother Wai Bing and to have been succeeded by his nephew Tai Jia, the son of Tang's heir apparent Tai Ding. Little is recorded of his short reign, and he is among the early Shang kings named in later texts but not attested in the surviving oracle-bone inscriptions.",
"King_Tai_Jia_of_Shang": "King Tai Jia of Shang (太甲) was an early king of the Shang dynasty, a grandson of its founder Tang and the son of Tang's eldest son Tai Ding, traditionally counted as the fourth Shang king after his uncles Wai Bing and Zhong Ren. According to traditional accounts, chiefly Sima Qian's Records of the Grand Historian, he ruled unjustly early in his reign and was exiled by the minister Yi Yin to the vicinity of Tang's tomb to repent, with Yi Yin governing as regent until the king reformed and was restored to the throne. He was succeeded by his son Wo Ding, and little else is recorded of his reign beyond this account of his exile and restoration.",
"King_Wo_Ding_of_Shang": "King Wo Ding of Shang (沃丁) was a ruler of the Shang dynasty of ancient China, traditionally listed as the fifth Shang king and named as the son and successor of Tai Jia. He was in turn succeeded by his brother Tai Geng. Little is recorded of his reign, and because he does not appear among the kings named in the oracle-bone inscriptions unearthed at Yinxu, some scholars have questioned whether he was a historical figure.",
"King_Tai_Geng_of_Shang": "King Tai Geng of Shang (太庚), a son of the earlier king Tai Jia, was a ruler of the Shang dynasty of ancient China. In the traditional king list preserved by Sima Qian he appears as the sixth Shang king, following his brother Wo Ding and preceding his own son Xiao Jia, though oracle-bone records instead place him fifth in the sequence. Little is recorded of his reign, and he is known chiefly from his position in the king list and the oracle-bone inscriptions, which preserve almost no detail of his rule.",
"King_Xiao_Jia_of_Shang": "King Xiao Jia of Shang (小甲), whose given name was Zi Gao, was a king of the Shang dynasty listed in the traditional royal genealogy as the seventh ruler and a son of his predecessor Tai Geng. Oracle-bone inscriptions instead record him as the sixth Shang king who came to the throne after his brother Da Geng, a discrepancy that reflects the uncertain state of early Shang succession and chronology. Little is recorded of his reign, and in the received king list he was followed on the throne by Yong Ji.",
"King_Yong_Ji_of_Shang": "King Yong Ji of Shang (雍己) was a ruler of the early Shang dynasty of China, traditionally counted as the eighth king in the dynastic king list preserved by the Han historian Sima Qian. He was a son of King Tai Geng, and in that traditional account he came to the throne after his brother Xiao Jia and was in turn succeeded by another brother, Tai Wu. Little is recorded of his reign beyond his place in the succession, and later tradition associates his time with a weakening of the dynasty's fortunes.",
"King_Tai_Wu_of_Shang": "King Tai Wu of Shang (太戊), also recorded as Da Wu, was in the traditional Shang king list the ninth ruler of the dynasty, a son of King Tai Geng who came to the throne after his brother Yong Ji. He is traditionally remembered for a long reign and a revival of Shang fortunes, said to have been guided by the ministers Yi Zhi and Wu Xian, though little of substance about his actual rule survives beyond such later accounts and his appearance in the oracle-bone records. According to the same tradition he was succeeded by his son Zhong Ding.",
"King_Zhong_Ding_of_Shang": "King Zhong Ding of Shang (仲丁) was, in the traditional Shang king list recorded by Sima Qian, the tenth king of the dynasty and a son of King Tai Wu (太戊), and he was succeeded on the throne by his younger brother Wai Ren (外壬). He is traditionally said to have moved the Shang capital from Bo (亳) to Ao (隞), and his reign is regarded as the beginning of a long period of disputed succession later known as the Chaos of the Nine Reigns (九世之亂). Little else is reliably recorded of his reign, which is known chiefly through the traditional king list and the oracle-bone records rather than through any detailed account of events.",
"King_Wai_Ren_of_Shang": "King Wai Ren of Shang (外壬) was a ruler of the Shang dynasty of ancient China, named in the traditional king list as a son of King Tai Wu and counted the eleventh Shang king in the Records of the Grand Historian, though oracle-bone inscriptions instead place him tenth. He came to the throne after his brother Zhong Ding and was in turn succeeded by his son He Dan Jia. Known chiefly from the traditional king list and the oracle-bone records, little is reliably recorded of his reign beyond his place in the royal succession.",
"King_He_Dan_Jia_of_Shang": "King He Dan Jia of Shang (河亶甲) was a ruler of the Chinese Shang dynasty, listed in the Records of the Grand Historian as its twelfth king and the son of his predecessor Wai Ren. Traditional accounts credit him with relocating the Shang capital to Xiang, but little else about his reign is reliably recorded. He was succeeded by his son Zu Yi.",
"King_Zu_Yi_of_Shang": "King Zu Yi of Shang (祖乙) was a king of the Chinese Shang dynasty, ranked the thirteenth Shang ruler in the traditional king list of Sima Qian's Records of the Grand Historian, though oracle-bone inscriptions place him twelfth. Traditional accounts make him the son and successor of King He Dan Jia, while the oracle-bone records instead treat him as a son of the earlier king Zhong Ding, and he was in turn succeeded by his own son Zu Xin. He is traditionally credited with relocating the Shang capital and leading a revival of the dynasty after a period of weakness, but little firm detail of his reign survives.",
"King_Zu_Xin_of_Shang": "King Zu Xin of Shang (祖辛), personal name Zi Dan, was a king of the Shang dynasty of ancient China, listed in Sima Qian's Records of the Grand Historian as the fourteenth Shang ruler. He succeeded his father Zu Yi and was in turn succeeded by his younger brother Wo Jia, who is also known as Qiang Jia. He is known chiefly from the traditional king list and the oracle-bone records, and little of his reign is recorded.",
"King_Wo_Jia_of_Shang": "King Wo Jia of Shang (沃甲), also recorded by the temple name Qiang Jia (羌甲), was a king of the Shang dynasty of ancient China, a son of King Zu Yi who came to the throne after his brother Zu Xin. He is placed as the fifteenth Shang king in the Records of the Grand Historian, though oracle-bone inscriptions from Yinxu suggest he was the fourteenth, and he was succeeded by his nephew Zu Ding. Little is recorded of his reign, and he is known chiefly from the traditional king list and the oracle-bone records rather than from any documented events.",
"King_Zu_Ding_of_Shang": "King Zu Ding of Shang (祖丁) was a ruler of the Chinese Shang dynasty and a son of the earlier king Zu Xin. According to Sima Qian's Records of the Grand Historian he was the sixteenth Shang king, coming to the throne after his uncle Wo Jia and being succeeded by his cousin Nan Geng, though oracle-bone inscriptions instead place him fifteenth in the royal line. Like many Shang kings he is known chiefly from the traditional king list and the oracle-bone records, and little of the events of his reign has been preserved.",
"King_Nan_Geng_of_Shang": "King Nan Geng of Shang (南庚), whose given name was Zi Geng, was a ruler of the Shang dynasty of ancient China, counted in the traditional king list as either the sixteenth or seventeenth Shang king. He was a son of the earlier king Wo Jia, also called Qiang Jia, and he came to the throne after his cousin Zu Ding before being succeeded by his cousin's son Yang Jia. Beyond his place in the royal genealogy and his appearance in later dynastic records and oracle-bone inscriptions, little is reliably recorded of his reign, and no securely dated events survive from it.",
"King_Yang_Jia_of_Shang": "King Yang Jia of Shang (陽甲) was a king of the early Chinese Shang dynasty, counted as its seventeenth or eighteenth ruler, the son of King Zu Ding and the successor of Nan Geng, his father's cousin. His reign is placed in a period of dynastic decline shortly before the Shang capital was moved to Yin under his younger brother and successor, Pan Geng. Known chiefly from the traditional king list and the oracle-bone records, little else about his reign is reliably preserved.",
"King_Xiao_Xin_of_Shang": "King Xiao Xin of Shang (小辛), personal name Zi Song, was a ruler of the Shang dynasty of ancient China, a son of King Zu Ding who came to the throne after his elder brother Pan Geng. He is known chiefly from the traditional king list and the oracle-bone inscriptions, which record his place in the royal succession but preserve little about the events of his reign. He was in turn succeeded by his younger brother Xiao Yi, and the traditional sources credit him with only a short rule.",
"King_Xiao_Yi_of_Shang": "King Xiao Yi of Shang (小乙) was a king of the Shang dynasty of ancient China, traditionally counted as the twenty-first ruler of the line, a son of King Zu Ding and a younger brother of the kings Pan Geng and Xiao Xin. He came to the throne after his brother Xiao Xin and ruled from the capital at Yin, but he is known chiefly from the traditional king list and the oracle-bone records, and little is preserved of the events of his own reign. He was the father and predecessor of Wu Ding, who is remembered as one of the greatest and most powerful of the Shang kings.",
"King_Zu_Geng_of_Shang": "King Zu Geng of Shang (祖庚), personal name Zi Yue, was a king of the Shang dynasty of ancient China and a son of King Wu Ding. He succeeded his father to the throne and was in turn followed by his younger brother Zu Jia. Like many Shang rulers he is known chiefly from the traditional king list and the oracle-bone inscriptions, and little of his reign is securely recorded.",
"King_Zu_Jia_of_Shang": "King Zu Jia of Shang (祖甲) was a king of the Chinese Shang dynasty, a son of Wu Ding who came to the throne after his elder brother Zu Geng. He is associated in the oracle-bone record with a reform of the schedule of ancestral sacrifices, and traditional accounts name Lin Xin or Geng Ding as his successor. Beyond his place in the royal succession and this ritual association little is recorded of his reign, which is known chiefly from the traditional king list and the oracle inscriptions.",
"King_Lin_Xin_of_Shang": "King Lin Xin of Shang (廩辛), also known as Feng Xin, was a king of the Shang dynasty and a son of his predecessor King Zu Jia. He reigned in the later part of the dynasty and was succeeded by his brother Geng Ding. Little is recorded of his reign, and he is known chiefly from the traditional king list preserved in later histories.",
"King_Kang_Ding_of_Shang": "King Kang Ding of Shang (康丁), also recorded as Geng Ding (庚丁), was a king of the late Shang dynasty of ancient China. According to the traditional king list he was a son of King Zu Jia, came to the throne after his brother Lin Xin, and was succeeded by his own son Wu Yi. Little is recorded of his reign, and he is known chiefly from the traditional royal genealogy and the oracle-bone records of the period.",
"King_Wu_Yi_of_Shang": "King Wu Yi of Shang (武乙) was a king of the late Shang dynasty of ancient China, a son of the preceding king Geng Ding and the father of his successor Wen Ding. In traditional accounts he is remembered chiefly for impiety toward the gods, the Records of the Grand Historian describing how he had an effigy made to represent the god of Heaven and shot arrows at a blood-filled leather bag hung aloft in mockery of the divine. He is said to have died when he was struck by lightning while hunting between the Yellow and Wei Rivers, though little else of his reign is securely recorded and much of his story survives only through later tradition.",
"King_Di_Yi_of_Shang": "King Di Yi of Shang (帝乙) was the penultimate king of the Shang dynasty of ancient China, the son and successor of Wen Ding and the father of Di Xin, the dynasty's final ruler. He is known chiefly from the traditional king list and from oracle-bone inscriptions, which record sacrificial rituals and military campaigns during his reign, among them a war against the Yufang. Little else is securely recorded of him, and the dates of his reign are not firmly established.",
"Six_Secret_Teachings": "The Six Secret Teachings (六韜, Liutao) is a treatise on civil and military strategy framed as dialogues in which the adviser Jiang Ziya, known as Taigong, counsels King Wen and King Wu of Zhou on statecraft and warfare. Tradition credits Jiang Ziya himself with the work, but modern scholars date its composition to the Warring States period. Its six sections, the Civil, Military, Dragon, Tiger, Leopard, and Dog Secret Teachings, treat subjects ranging from winning the people and organizing the state to selecting officers, battlefield tactics, and training troops, and the text is counted among the Seven Military Classics.",
"Investiture_of_the_Gods": "Investiture of the Gods (封神演義, Fengshen Yanyi) is a vernacular novel of gods and demons in one hundred chapters, written in the sixteenth century during the Ming dynasty and most commonly attributed to Xu Zhonglin, though its authorship remains debated. Set during the overthrow of Di Xin, the tyrannical last Shang king who is bewitched by the fox-spirit concubine Daji, it interweaves the rise of King Wu of Zhou with battles among immortals, demons, and magically armed warriors. At its close the strategist Jiang Ziya reads out a divine register that invests the spirits of the fallen as gods, an episode that left a lasting mark on Chinese popular religion and mythology.",
"Speech_at_Mu": "The Speech at Mu (牧誓, Mushi) is a chapter of the Book of Documents presenting the address King Wu of Zhou delivered to his assembled troops and allies before the Battle of Muye, fought around 1046 BCE. In it the king denounces Di Xin, the last Shang king, for following the words of his consort, neglecting the ancestral sacrifices, casting aside his kinsmen, and giving office to criminals, and he then issues instructions for the coming attack. The speech also names eight allied peoples marching with the Zhou host: the Yong, Shu, Qiang, Mao, Wei, Lu, Peng, and Pu.",
"Revolt_of_the_Three_Feudatories": "The Revolt of the Three Feudatories (三藩之亂) was a rebellion of 1673–1681 against the Qing dynasty, begun by Wu Sangui, the feudatory prince ruling Yunnan and Guizhou, and joined by Geng Jingzhong in Fujian and Shang Zhixin in Guangdong, after the young Kangxi Emperor moved to abolish their vast southern fiefdoms. At its height the rising controlled much of southern China, and in 1678 Wu Sangui proclaimed a rival dynasty of his own, naming it Zhou, only to die later that year. Qing forces crushed the remaining rebels by 1681, when Wu Shifan, the grandson of Wu Sangui, killed himself at Kunming, and the victory consolidated Qing control over southern China.",
"Kangxi_Dictionary": "The Kangxi Dictionary (康熙字典) is a dictionary of Chinese characters compiled by imperial order of the Kangxi Emperor, commissioned in 1710 and published in 1716. Prepared by a board of scholars whose chief editors were Zhang Yushu and Chen Tingjing, it records more than 47,000 characters, arranged under the set of 214 radicals that came to be known as the Kangxi radicals. It served as the most authoritative reference for written Chinese from its publication until the early twentieth century, and its title helped make zidian the standard Chinese word for dictionary.",
"Divine_right_of_kings": "The divine right of kings is a political and theological doctrine holding that a monarch receives authority directly from God rather than from any earthly power or from the consent of the governed. Because the sovereign is answerable to God alone, the doctrine treats resistance or rebellion against the crown as a sin as well as a crime. It flourished in early modern Europe, expounded by James VI and I of Scotland and England and reflected in the absolutism of Louis XIV of France, before constitutionalism and the revolutions of the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries eroded it.",
"Jiang_Yuan": "Jiang Yuan (姜嫄) is the legendary mother of Hou Ji, the millet lord revered as the ancestor of the Zhou royal house, and later accounts such as the Records of the Grand Historian name her a consort of Emperor Ku. According to the Shengmin hymn in the Classic of Poetry, she conceived Hou Ji miraculously after stepping into a footprint left by the supreme god Shangdi, and the infant, abandoned in a narrow lane, in a forest, and on cold ice, survived under the protection of oxen, sheep, and birds. Honoured in Zhou ancestral ritual as the ancestress of the royal line, she is worshipped as a goddess in Chinese popular religion.",
"Sheji": "Sheji (社稷) denotes the paired altars of soil and grain at which Chinese rulers offered regular sacrifices, the she honouring the spirits of the soil and the ji the spirits of the grains. From Zhou times onward every royal or imperial capital, and the seat of each regional lord, maintained such altars, and because their upkeep was bound to a ruling house's legitimacy the term became a standard metonym for the state itself. The sacrifices continued into the Qing dynasty, whose emperors performed them at the Shejitan altar in Beijing, just west of the imperial palace.",
"Muye": "Muye (牧野), a name traditionally rendered as wild pasture, was an open stretch of country in northern Henan near present-day Xinxiang, on the southern approaches to the last Shang capital. It was the site of the Battle of Muye around 1046 BCE, in which King Wu of Zhou defeated the army of the last Shang king, Di Xin, opening the way for the Zhou conquest of the Shang. The exact battlefield has never been fixed by excavation, but the name survives in the Muye District of Xinxiang, and in later texts the place stood as a byword for the fall of the Shang.",
"Si_River": "The Si River 泗水, known today as the Sihe 泗河, rises in the foothills of the Mengshan range in southern Shandong province and flows past Sishui County, Qufu, and Yanzhou before emptying into Lake Nanyang. In ancient times it continued southward through present-day Jiangsu to join the Huai River, but after 1194 the Yellow River repeatedly shifted its course to the south and took over the lower channels of both rivers, severing the old connection. It flows past Qufu, capital of the ancient state of Lu and homeland of Confucius, where tradition places his tomb on the river's northern bank and where the paired names of the Zhu and Si rivers made Zhu-Si a byname for his teaching.",
"Regency": "A regency is an arrangement in which royal authority is exercised on behalf of a monarch who is unable to reign, most often because the sovereign is a child, absent from the realm, or incapacitated by illness. The person who governs in the sovereign's name is called a regent, and the role may be filled by a single individual, frequently a close royal relative such as a queen mother or an uncle, or by a council of regency. Regencies have arisen in monarchies across the world throughout history, and they could also be declared when a throne stood vacant or the rightful successor was disputed.",
"Vassal": "A vassal is a person or state bound to a lord or superior power by reciprocal obligations, typically owing homage, military service, counsel, or tribute in return for protection and the grant of land or office. In medieval Europe the bond was sealed by a ceremony of homage and fealty, after which the vassal commonly held a fief from the lord as a tenant. Comparable relationships of subordination existed in many societies, and a vassal state is a polity that keeps its internal autonomy while acknowledging the overlordship of a stronger power, often by paying tribute.",
"Millet": "Millets are a varied group of small-seeded grasses cultivated since prehistory as cereal grains for human food and animal fodder, including foxtail, broomcorn or proso, pearl, and finger millet. Hardy, quick to mature, and tolerant of drought, heat, and poor soils, they are among the oldest domesticated crops, with broomcorn and foxtail millet brought into cultivation in East Asia by roughly eight thousand years ago and pearl and finger millet domesticated in Africa. Millets remain staple foods across large parts of Africa and Asia, where they are eaten as porridge and flatbread and are also brewed into beer.",
"She_altar": "The she 社 was the altar and cult of the god of the soil in ancient Chinese religion, typically an open-air mound of raised earth at which sacrifices were offered for the fertility of the land. Altars of the soil were maintained at every level of society, from the royal capital and the courts of regional lords down to villages, and the right to sacrifice at a state's she expressed rulership over its territory. The word forms part of the compound sheji 社稷, the paired altars of soil and grain, which became a classical metonym for the state itself.",
"Ji_altar": "The ji 稷 was the altar and cult of the god of grain in ancient Chinese religion, at which rulers offered sacrifice for a successful harvest. The character originally named millet, the staple grain of ancient north China, and Zhou tradition identified the grain god with Hou Ji, the Lord of Millet revered as the first ancestor of the Zhou royal house. It forms part of the compound sheji 社稷, the paired altars of soil and grain whose worship was a prerogative of rulers and which came to stand for the state itself.",
"Loess_Plateau": "The Loess Plateau 黃土高原 is a highland region of some 635,000 square kilometres in north-central China, spanning the middle reaches of the Yellow River across Shanxi, Shaanxi, Gansu, and neighbouring provinces. It is mantled in loess, a fine yellowish silt blown in from the deserts to the north and west over the Quaternary period, which accumulates in places to depths of two hundred metres or more and forms a soil that is easily worked and fertile but severely prone to erosion, supplying most of the sediment that gives the Yellow River its colour and its name. Farmed since Neolithic times, when millet cultivation supported some of the earliest agricultural communities in East Asia, the plateau is regarded as a cradle of early Chinese agriculture and civilization.",
"Anhui": "Anhui (安徽) is a province of eastern China crossed by both the Yangtze and Huai rivers, its name formed from the cities of Anqing and Huizhou. In its south rises Mount Huang, or Huangshan, a granite range of pines and mist-wrapped peaks long celebrated in Chinese landscape painting. The province's historic Huizhou merchants ranked among the wealthiest traders of Ming and Qing times, and its workshops have long produced famed scholarly materials such as Hui ink and Xuan paper.",
"Guizhou": "Guizhou (貴州) is a mountainous province of southwestern China, occupying a rugged stretch of the Yunnan-Guizhou Plateau where level ground is famously scarce. Its karst landscape of limestone peaks, gorges, and caverns includes Huangguoshu Waterfall, one of the largest waterfalls in China. The province is home to many ethnic groups, among them the Miao, Buyi, and Dong, and its city of Zunyi hosted the 1935 conference at which Mao Zedong rose to leadership of the Chinese Communist Party during the Long March.",
"Hainan": "Hainan (海南) is China's southernmost province, an island in the South China Sea separated from the Leizhou Peninsula by the Qiongzhou Strait. It has a tropical climate, with forested mountains in its interior that are the homeland of the indigenous Li people. For centuries the remote island served as a place of exile for disgraced officials, among them the Song poet Su Shi, and it was governed as part of Guangdong until becoming a separate province in 1988.",
"Heilongjiang": "Heilongjiang (黑龍江) is the northeasternmost province of China, named for the Amur River, known in Chinese as the Black Dragon River, which forms its long border with Russia. Part of historical Manchuria, it is a land of plains, forests, and fertile black soil, with some of the harshest winters in the country. Opened to large-scale Han settlement late in the Qing dynasty, it has become one of China's foremost grain-producing regions, with its capital at Harbin.",
"Jilin": "Jilin (吉林) is a province of northeastern China lying between Heilongjiang and Liaoning, its name derived from a Manchu phrase meaning along the river. The Changbai Mountains rise along its southeastern border with North Korea, crowned by the volcanic crater lake known as Heaven Lake. Historically part of Manchuria, the region was a homeland of the Manchus and earlier of the kingdoms of Goguryeo and Balhae, whose heritage includes the Goguryeo capital sites and tombs preserved at Ji'an.",
"Yunnan": "Yunnan (雲南) is a highland province of southwestern China bordering Myanmar, Laos, and Vietnam, with its capital at Kunming. Its terrain falls from glaciated peaks on the edge of the Tibetan Plateau in the northwest to tropical river valleys in the south, and it is home to some twenty-five recognized ethnic minority groups, more than any other Chinese province, including the Yi, Bai, Hani, and Dai. In antiquity the region was ruled by the Dian kingdom, and later by the kingdoms of Nanzhao and Dali, which dominated it until the Mongol conquest of the thirteenth century.",
"Inner_Mongolia": "Inner Mongolia (內蒙古) is a vast autonomous region of northern China, stretching in a great arc along most of the border with Mongolia and touching Russia in the northeast. Its landscape ranges from steppe grasslands in the east to the Gobi Desert in the west, high open country long given over to pastoral herding. Established in 1947, the region holds the largest Mongol population in the world, and sections of the Great Wall run near its southern margins, marking the old frontier between agrarian China and the nomads of the steppe.",
"Ningxia": "Ningxia (寧夏) is a small autonomous region of northwestern China, officially the Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region, lying on the upper Yellow River at the edge of the Loess Plateau. Sheltered by the Helan Mountains, its riverside plain has been irrigated by canals since ancient times, forming a band of farmland amid arid country. The region was the heartland of the Western Xia state founded by the Tanguts in the eleventh century, whose capital stood at modern Yinchuan, and it is today home to a large Hui Muslim population.",
"Chongqing": "Chongqing (重慶) is a direct-administered municipality of southwestern China, a vast city-region on the upper Yangtze at its confluence with the Jialing River, separated from Sichuan in 1997. Built across steep ridges at the eastern edge of the Sichuan Basin, it is known as the mountain city, and the Yangtze flows east from it through the celebrated Three Gorges. The area was home to the ancient state of Ba, and from 1937 to 1946 the city served as the wartime capital of the Republic of China, enduring heavy Japanese bombing during the Second Sino-Japanese War.",
"Hong_Kong": "Hong Kong (香港) is a special administrative region of China on the eastern side of the Pearl River estuary, comprising Hong Kong Island, the Kowloon Peninsula, and the New Territories with their many outlying islands. Its deep natural harbour amid hilly coastal terrain made it one of the world's great ports, and it grew into a leading international financial centre. Hong Kong Island was ceded to Britain in 1842 by the Treaty of Nanking after the First Opium War, the territory was later enlarged by the addition of Kowloon and a lease of the New Territories, and it was returned to China in 1997 under the principle of one country, two systems."
};

